<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-BBA-YANKS-REDSOX-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STRAWBERRY, PETTITTE SILENCE FANS AS YANKEES DOWN RED SOX 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds.: Repeats to add art note. The following story is an added
starter on The New York Times front page) (ART ADV: Photos are being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(rk) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The New York Yankees were here on the day before the
July 31 trade deadline, when Joe Torre told George Steinbrenner on
a conference call that he wanted to keep Andy Pettitte, rather than
trade him to Philadelphia. Torre cited Pettitte's penchant for
winning big games.
</P>
<P>
   Steinbrenner went along with the recommendation of Torre and
general manager Brian Cashman, making it clear they would be held
responsible if Pettitte floundered. But Sunday night, Torre and
Cashman have the right to smugly offer I-told-you-so's, after
Pettitte and the Yankees beat the Boston Red Sox, 9-2, in Game 4 of
the American League Championship Series. The Yankees, who blew open
a tense game with six runs in the ninth, lead by 3-1 in the
best-of-7 series.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees do not want this series to reach a seventh game;
they do not want Pedro Martinez _ against whom they have five hits
and 35 strikeouts in their last 61 at-bats _ to get another chance
to pitch, in what would be the deciding game.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees now have two opportunities to clinch this series
before a seventh game: Orlando Hernandez, their best pitcher, will
face Boston's Kent Mercker Monday in Game 5, and if the Red Sox win
and extend the series, then David Cone would throw against Ramon
Martinez in Game 6 on Wednesday at Yankee Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees led, 3-2, in the eighth, and blew a great scoring
chance in the top half of the inning: They had second and third and
nobody out and could not push across a run. But Boston couldn't
score in the bottom of the eighth, and in the top of the ninth, the
Red Sox made two of their four errors and Ricky Ledee bashed a
pinch-hit grand slam off Rod Beck, and the Yankees could breathe
easy. Pettitte surrendered two runs on eight hits in 7 1-3 innings.
</P>
<P>
   In the bottom of the ninth, the game was delayed for about five
minutes because of disruptive fans. When the teams returned to the
field, the Yankees closed out the game. The fans were upset about
two contested calls in consecutive innings that had gone against
the Red Sox.
</P>
<P>
   Steinbrenner, the Yankees' principal owner, sternly moved around
his team's clubhouse after Game 3s blow-out loss, and then again
before Sunday night's game, a living reminder of consequences. A
phone rang in the press room while Torre spoke with the media after
Game 3, and Torre asked if the phone was for him, adding, ``You
never know'' _ and everybody laughed, knowing what he meant.
Steinbrenner is omnipresent, especially in defeat.
</P>
<P>
   But Torre felt his team was relaxed, confident and fully aware
of the importance of Game 4. Torre shook up his lineup a bit,
replacing left fielder Ricky Ledee with Chad Curtis, and inserting
Darryl Strawberry as his designated hitter.
</P>
<P>
   When Strawberry came to bat for the first time, the Fenway Park
fans offered a new and different chorus for the slugger with the
history of drugs and alcohol abuse _ ``Just Say No,'' they cried.
``Just Say No,'' the mournful chant, louder and louder. Boston's
Bret Saberhagen threw a high fastball and Strawberry rattled a high
drive two-thirds of the way up the right field foul pole, a solo
home run. It was the last time the hearty singers serenaded
Strawberry on this evening.
</P>
<P>
   The sensitive Pettitte, too, was hearing it _ Andy, Andy, they
called _ and the Red Sox tied the game in the bottom of the second.
Butch Huskey slamming a double into the left-field corner, but
appeared to pull a leg muscle as he came out of the box. When Troy
O'Leary singled to Bernie Williams in center field, however,
Huskey's slogging limp did not deter Wendell Kim, the Boston third
base coach, from waving Huskey around third in a direct challenge
of Williams' weak throwing arm. Huskey scored easily.
</P>
<P>
   That success may have led to a poor decision by Kim in the next
inning, when the Red Sox assumed a 2-1 lead but lost an opportunity
for more. Damon Buford singled, stole second and scored when Jose
Offerman rolled a base hit through the middle.
</P>
<P>
   John Valentin smacked a long drive to left, where Curtis _ who
started, in part, because of his defensive familiarity with
Fenway's 37-foot high left-field wall _ misjudged the flight of
Valentin's shot. He was too close to the wall when the ball hit,
and it ricocheted off Curtis and behind him. Williams moved to back
up the play, and Boston's third base coach waved frantically,
beckoning Offerman around third base, sending him home.
</P>
<P>
   It was a serious miscalculation. Williams made a quick and short
throw to the shortstop Derek Jeter, and with his powerful arm,
Jeter relayed a rocket to catcher Joe Girardi; the ball arrived at
the plate in plenty of time for Girardi to reach and slap a tag on
Offerman _ the second out of the inning, with Nomar Garciaparra,
Boston's best hitter, due to bat.
</P>
<P>
   Boston made more mistakes in the top of the fourth, and it cost
the Red Sox their lead. One out into the bottom of the fourth,
Bernie Williams rolled a grounder to the right of Garciaparra, and
the Boston shortstop hurried, gloved the ball, fired sidearm _ and
high, the ball sailing well over the outstretched mitt of the first
baseman Mike Stanley and into the Red Sox dugout. Williams was
allowed to take second on the fourth error of the series by
Garciaparra, who is one short of the AL championship series record.
</P>
<P>
   Saberhagen fell behind in the count by three balls and no
strikes to Tino Martinez, fought back to 3-2, then threw a pitch
right over the heart of the plate; Martinez whacked it, the ball
short-hopping off the base of the low wall in right-center field.
Williams trotted home with the tying run, Martinez pulled into
second base with a double.
</P>
<P>
   Saberhagen intentionally walked Strawberry _ just say no, as far
as Saberhagen was concerned _ then struck out Scott Brosius and
appeared to be out of the inning when Chad Curtis hit a sharp
grounder toward Stanley.
</P>
<P>
   The Boston first baseman backed up to glove the ball, and
Saberhagen quickly moved to cover first base, Curtis running hard
down the line but well behind Saberhagen. Stanley's throw, however,
reached Saberhagen about thigh high, so that the pitcher had to
draw up his hands awkwardly to attempt the catch. The ball fell out
of his mitt and rolled away, and Jose Cardenal, the Yankees' first
base coach, whirled and waved his right arm frantically, signaling
to Martinez to keep running, keep going home, and Martinez crossed
the plate standing. Yankees 3, Boston 2, and Steinbrenner, sitting
adjacent to his team's dugout, was laughing openly and appeared to
be jockeying playfully with Red Sox fans sitting nearby.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
