<P>
   (NYT16) WASHINGTON -- Oct. 17, 1999 -- MCCONNELL-PROFILE, 10-17
-- Sen. Mitch McConnell is an outspoken critic of campaign finance
regulation. McConnell, 57, a Republican first elected to the Senate
in 1984, has been ``the point man on this issue for our side since
the late 1980s,'' as he puts it, and intellectually engaged for
longer than that. Not surprisingly, he presents himself as the
defender of the First Amendment, not of corrupt, big money
politics. (Shana Raab/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) NEW YORK -- Oct. 17, 1999 -- SCI-ASTHMA-3, 10-17 --
Ann-Nancy Murphy, a nurse practitioner from Mount Sinai Medical
Center who works at the Bilingual Bicultural Mini School in East
Harlem, has a cabinet filled with inhalers that she keeps for
younger asthmatic students to use. She also keeps two nebulizers -
machines that administer emergency breathing treatments - at the
ready becuase, she says, sometimes two children have emergencies at
once. (Jeffery A. Salter/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) WASHINGTON -- Oct. 17, 1999 -- SCI-ASTHMA-2, 10-17 --
John Thompson, 8, inhaling steroids to relax his swollen airways at
Children's National Medical Center in Washington. The rapid rise of
asthma, in this country and in developed nations around the world,
is one of the biggest mysteries in modern medicine. (Scott
Robinson/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) WASHINGTON -- Oct. 17, 1999 -- SCI-ASTHMA-1, 10-17 --
Some members of the Cunningham family, from left, Cassie, Kearea,
Carolyn, Kahlah, Mrs. Ollie Cunningham, Artez, and Kimberly. At 45,
Mrs. Cunningham is the mother of nine children, ages 4 through 22.
Seven have asthma. The family, which lives in an immaculate
three-bedroom house, has no health insurance. Mrs. Cunningham's
husband, Anthony, is a maintenance man and earns too much to
qualify for Medicaid. (Scott Robinson/New York Times Photo)
</P>
