<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-18 00:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0017 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a BC-BULLFIGHTS-AZR &LR;      10-18 0864
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BULLFIGHTS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BULLFIGHTS IN NOGALES DISMAY ANIMAL ACTIVISTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK SHAFFER  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NOGALES, Sonora _ Mario de la Fuente knows that many Americans
abhor blood sports, so he suggests they stay home when bullfighting
returns to this border city next month.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am very respectful of the American culture and I ask the
same respect when people come to my country,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, ``we'll sell the bulls' bodies to a local butcher
shop,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They will make good hamburgers the next day.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; De la Fuente is banking on Americans filling most of the 5,000
seats in his new round, very red arena with aluminum siding and
clear acrylic top.
</P>
<P>
   On Nov. 14, he will bring bullfighting back to Nogales after a
nearly 30-year absence, with events twice a month.
</P>
<P>
   Bullfighting enjoyed its heyday in Nogales in the 1950s and
early '60s, when such celebrities as John Wayne, Gary Cooper and
Sonny Liston regularly attended Sunday afternoon ``corridas'' at an
outdoor stadium decorated with matador frescos.
</P>
<P>
   De la Fuente got his start in the business there; his family
owned the stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``About 90 percent of our customers came from Arizona,'' he
said. ``We would have 400 to 500 people come down from Phoenix for
our events.''
</P>
<P>
   The old stadium, which closed in 1973, fell into disrepair and
was condemned by the city, so de la Fuente built anew.
</P>
<P>
   He thinks matadors will find his domed venue very attractive,
because there will be no wind to interfere with cape movements.
</P>
<P>
   But the dome isn't the only amenity. There will be box seats at
ground level, where patrons can come almost eye to eye with the
bulls. Concession stands will sell mixed drinks along with beer,
tacos and hot dogs.
</P>
<P>
   De la Fuente envisions other sporting events held at his grand
arena. He said he has talked with cockfight promoters about staging
fights in Nogales, now that Arizona has banned their livelihood.
</P>
<P>
   Television exposure is guaranteed. De la Fuente said he owns 18
cable companies in northwestern Mexico and will broadcast his blood
sports in the Nogales market.
</P>
<P>
   He also plans to stage concerts, boxing and wrestling matches at
the arena, near the industrial district of Nogales, about three
miles south of the U.S. border.
</P>
<P>
   ``I call this my own little BOB (Bank One Ballpark),'' said de
la Fuente, who owns a minority interest in the Arizona
Diamondbacks.
</P>
<P>
   Animal-rights activists call it a den of cruelty.
</P>
<P>
   ``Legally, there's not a damn thing we can do about this,'' said
Kim Hicks, spokeswoman for the Arizona Humane Society. ``But we are
terribly disappointed that they are going to be making money at the
expense of the animals.
</P>
<P>
   ``I find it hard to believe that, as we approach the new
millennium, . . . people act like it's still medieval times. But we
hope that people in Nogales will just drive right by that place.''
</P>
<P>
   Stephanie Nichols-Young, a Phoenix attorney active in animal
protection causes, also is sorry to hear that ``cruel blood sports
which should be long gone'' are being resurrected in Nogales.
</P>
<P>
   ``But there is an animal-rights movement beginning in Latin
America,'' she said. ``It will be interesting to see what happens
with this.''
</P>
<P>
   Hicks said sensibilities have changed since the last time
fighting bulls died in Nogales.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look what happened when we rescued six Jersey bulls from the
back of a car,'' she said. ``This community went berserk. Our
donations went way up. That strikes me as the mentality which is in
the Valley now.''
</P>
<P>
   But De La Fuente said they shouldn't impose their values on
their neighbors south of the border.
</P>
<P>
   ``If people try to pull any shenanigans, I must warn them that
the Nogales police can be very tough,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; In recent years, however, bullfighting has surged in popularity
in Tijuana, Juarez and other border cities. Noting that, de la
Fuente broke ground on his domed arena last year.
</P>
<P>
   At first, de la Fuente intended to offer a hybrid sport in which
matadors would simply tease bulls with their capes, followed by
bull wrestlers on horseback. But that didn't sit well with
bullfighting purists in Mexico, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The association of matadors and picadors said that we would
have to comply with their regulations or they wouldn't work with
us,'' de la Fuente said.
</P>
<P>
   Hence, the traditional bullfighting.
</P>
<P>
   De la Fuente has an abundance of bulls to choose from. One of
the largest ranches in Mexico for production of purebred Iberian
fighting bulls is near Trincheras, Sonora, 80 miles south of
Nogales. De la Fuente said he will buy all the bulls that the ranch
produces.
</P>
<P>
   Four animals will likely be ready for the butcher shop after
each Nogales bullfight, which will last about three hours. Tickets
will cost $16 to $25 for the events.
</P>
<P>
   De la Fuente said ground also will be broken next year for a
2,000-seat outdoor bullfighting ring in Puerto Penasco, Sonora.
</P>
<P>
   ``The market definitely is there and we are going to put on an
entertaining product,'' he said. &QL; 
Mark Shaffer can be reached at (602) 444-8057 or at
mark.shaffer(at)pni.com. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
