<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-18 00:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0019 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a BC-LEARN-AZR &LR;      10-18 1101
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEARN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIGHER EDUCATION SHIFTS FOCUS: TEACHERS NOW `GUIDE ON THE SIDE' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BEVERLY MEDLYN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ A University of Arizona junior learns biology and
psychology by talking to a parrot.
</P>
<P>
   An Arizona State University student masters English composition,
not from a book, but from teaching disadvantaged kids.
</P>
<P>
   Seniors at Northern Arizona University learn business by
advising a Flagstaff music store on marketing strategies.
</P>
<P>
   They're all part of a trend sweeping higher education called
learner-centered education _ a shift from passive learning in
lecture halls to active learning through independent discovery.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a fundamental change in the role of the faculty. They
are increasingly the guide on the side rather than the sage on the
stage,'' said Peter Likins, president of the University of Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   The switch, Likens said, is the most profound change he has seen
in 35 years as a professor.
</P>
<P>
   The concept is filtering through all levels of the state's three
universities, and has become the central focus of a yearlong
examination by the Arizona Board of Regents.
</P>
<P>
   Alan Guskin, former president of Antioch University and a
national expert on learner-centered education, said institutions
across the country are grappling with the topic.
</P>
<P>
   ``My sense about Arizona is there is a lot of exciting ferment,
a lot of interesting ideas going on,'' Guskin said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it's a very big jump to go from teacher-centered learning
to student-centered,'' he added, ``in which students learn in many
different venues, the classroom being but one.''
</P>
<P>
   That's true of Robert Sandefer, a University of Arizona junior
majoring in biology and psychology.
</P>
<P>
   He's among 140 students in the UA's undergraduate biology
research program, designed to teach students science by involving
them in projects that once were done only by graduate students. &QL; 
`INTENSIVE' LEARNING &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a very intensive, very personalized way of learning for
the student,'' said Carol Bender, program director.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are learning how to apply everything from their past
experience to a problem that has not yet been solved.''
</P>
<P>
   On any given afternoon, Sandefer conducts experiments on
cognition with an African grey parrot named Alex, who is presented
with two stacking cups.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pick up the yellow cup,'' Sandefer says.
</P>
<P>
   On a good day, Alex walks over the table and picks up the yellow
cup. He is rewarded by a nut that lies beneath.
</P>
<P>
   When Alex makes the right choice 16 out of 20 times, Sandefer
puts out a new cup in an unfamiliar color next to the yellow cup,
and instructs: ``Pick up the cup.''
</P>
<P>
   Sandefer is waiting for the moment Alex turns and asks: ``What
color?''
</P>
<P>
   Alex will then prove he knows he needs more information, and is
therefore self-aware.
</P>
<P>
   Some techniques derived from such research have been applied to
developmentally delayed children, Sandefer said. Other findings
could help neurologically impaired people use alternate structures
in their brains to learn tasks. &QL; 
LEARNING BY TUTORING &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ASU's Meghan Ederle is learning English composition by tutoring
kids at the Salvation Army's South Mountain Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``The experiences I have at this site I reflect back on paper,''
Ederle said. South Phoenix's cultural diversity and economic
challenges are fodder for essays that earn her English course
credit.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 2,000 ASU students have participated in the tutoring
program, which has helped 7,679 children in the Valley.
</P>
<P>
   Students like ASU education major Kristy Kay Stover get to
observe youngsters learn rather than simply read textbooks about
how kids process information.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've learned what kids know and what their troubles are,''
Stover said. &QL; 
HELP BUSINESSES &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In Flagstaff, students in Northern Arizona University's Small
Business Institute and Students In Free Enterprise program are
gaining knowledge by helping small businesses with real-world
problems.
</P>
<P>
   Ivan Ochsner and Martha Memmer, owners of Cedar Music, turned to
NAU students for help. Within a year, they had a 200-page report
packed with ideas for improving the bottom line, plus a $25,000
loan.
</P>
<P>
   Lisa Borstadt, an NAU finance professor, said the students ``are
developing leadership, teamwork and communication skills.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Those are the soft skills employers are really after,''
Borstadt said.
</P>
<P>
   The same skills are honed through Students in Free Enterprise, a
national organization. NAU's chapter has completed 64
entrepreneurial projects and 378 presentations, Borstadt said, as
well as working with K-12 students in 38 schools and 38 businesses
in northern Arizona. &QL; 
PROCESS LESS EFFICIENT &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Adapting to individual student learning styles is the faculty's
focus, Likins said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Learning through discovery, as opposed to learning through
authority is a less efficient process,'' he said. ``It may take you
longer to get to the truth because there is an element of trial and
error. But it produces a deeper, more enduring kind of learning.''
</P>
<P>
   Book-learning and lectures are still part of the process. But so
are conducting independent research, working in teams, learning
from colleagues, and scouring the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Judy Gignac, immediate past president of the regents, said the
movement is ``catching fire'' and could lead to profound changes in
higher education.
</P>
<P>
   Focusing on the student calls the current system of
degree-preparation into question, she said. Rather than have
everyone complete a set number of credit hours for a degree, should
individual programs be crafted, based on each student's knowledge
base?
</P>
<P>
   The cost effectiveness of learner-centered education has yet to
be quantified. Charles Bantz, senior vice provost at ASU, noted
that there will be additional short-term costs for training,
developing materials and other needs.
</P>
<P>
   Are the payoffs worth it? Small-scale studies indicate students
learn more.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's time now for the board and the universities to define
more clearly what we view as measurable outcomes,'' ASU President
Lattie Coor said.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is where the board will turn _ how to define it and
measure it.''
</P>
<P>
   Gignac said the issues also will be aired before the Governor's
Higher Education Task Force and at a town hall scheduled for May in
Prescott.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there's enough enthusiasm generated for this kind of
change, do what you love and the money will follow,'' she said.
``That may be the case with this. Who knows?'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Beverly Medlyn can be reached at bev.medlyn(at)pni.com. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-18-99 0013EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
