<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-18 00:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0020 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBN-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT     10-18 0872
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: TORRE TURNS A HUNCH INTO A SURE THING 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By HARVEY ARATON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Joe Torre had nothing to go on, choosing Darryl
Strawberry over Chili Davis. As far as he knew, Strawberry had
never batted against Bret Saberhagen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chili's struggling right now,'' Torre said. ``The one thing
Darryl gives you is the threat of a home run, and we may need a
boom here tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   Strawberry came to bat in the second inning on Sunday night, the
Yankees already trailing the Red Sox by a run. The Fenway Park fans
_ many of whom would later disgrace themselves by making the
Yankees live, fleeing targets of their anger and frustration _
chanted ``just say no.'' The count went to 2-2. Strawberry just
said boom, homering off the screen of the fair pole in right.
</P>
<P>
   ``No rhyme or reason,'' said Torre, the untouchable. ``Just a
feel thing.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a feel-better night for Torre, for the Yankees, after
Saturday's brief derailment along the way to another World Series.
Torre was right on Strawberry, who also walked in the middle of a
two-run fourth inning that gave the Yankees two unearned runs and
the lead for good. He was on the money with Andy Pettitte,
left-hander on the loose in a park known to devour them.
</P>
<P>
   Pettitte rewarded Torre for his faith with seven and one-third
gritty innings. Torre pulled more ninth-inning strings and the
Yankees ran away from the Sox to win Game 4 by 9-2 and take a
three-games-to-one lead in the American League Championship Series.
</P>
<P>
   Gone, in all likelihood, is the Game 7 sword over the Yankees'
heads known as Pedro Martinez. Torre had said he was never worried,
anyway, after 21 Red Sox hits in Game 3. There was, he would have
said, no reason to consider rearranging his pitching plans because
of the Roger Clemens fiasco, to overreact too soon. With the Yankee
bats sickly all series, he stuck with light-hitting Joe Girardi on
Sunday night, and refused to move the ailing and slumping Paul
O'Neill down in the order. On cue, the Red Sox helped out with
pitiful infield play and four badly timed errors, and also ran
themselves out of a potential big inning in the third.
</P>
<P>
   Some things don't change. Torre, as usual, came up smelling
roses. After the Yanks broke it open, he didn't have to sweat out
the ninth inning, or any more ground balls to Chuck Knoblauch. Only
the sight of sad-sack fans heaving plastic soda bottles and debris
on the field, briefly halting the game two outs from its
conclusion.
</P>
<P>
   That ugliness aside, Torre continued to enjoy life in pinstripes
in a way few men have before.
</P>
<P>
   ``The more you do this, the more fun it is,'' he said. ``For
sure last year, after winning 114 games, you felt sort of obligated
to have to go to the World Series and win. Otherwise people would
have downplayed what you accomplished. This is more fun, and maybe
I have approaching it that way because where I was six months ago
and knowing what was going on in my body and my life.''
</P>
<P>
   At a time when baseball hysteria rules, Torre is the calm,
paternal face of New York sports. That has always been his nature,
and has been his approach since he took managerial control of a
team long fueled by panic and fear. Now he works a few months
removed from believing he had been handed ``a death sentence'' upon
learning he had prostate cancer last spring. He operates in his
fourth Yankee season with the capital of two World Series
championships, the perfect steward for a team that has won with
style and class.
</P>
<P>
   At the height of the season of second-guessing, Torre floats
above the jerking knees, not having every decision analyzed like a
nuclear arms treaty. Everyone else is always one move away from
facing the tribunal of baseball geniuses. Bobby Valentine's woes
have been well documented. What a winter Bobby Cox will be in for
should the Braves ever lose to the Mets.
</P>
<P>
   If it had been Valentine _ who invites second guesses the way
politicians do soft money _ who had sent an anxious Clemens into
Fenway for such disastrous results Saturday, he would surely have
been subjected to 24 hours of hell. Fair or not, this is how it is.
</P>
<P>
   Torre shrugged it off, and even seem to enjoy a rare Yankees'
moment of doubt.
</P>
<P>
   ``That for me?'' he said when a cell phone rang during his
post-game news conferecnce. Assured it was not, he said: ``You
never know.''
</P>
<P>
   The Yankee manager knows how many native New Yorkers and a
certain Ohio-born Floridian react when the other team gets noisy
and palms get sweaty in the midst of a baseball playoff series.
Vinny from Queens and Mike from Montclair and George from Tampa
start dialing respective outlets, making a show of their
displeasure.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees' owner, in fact, planted himself in a box seat
alongside the dugout, ducking out in the ninth only when the game
was safe, and the playing field wasn't.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a very compassionate man when you do lose,'' Torre said.
``I think he's a tougher taskmaster when you're winning, to keep
you from taking your eye off the finish line. When you lose, he's
there to support you.''
</P>
<P>
   Only Torre could believe this. But then, based on the results,
we always believe Torre, too.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-18-99 0014EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
