<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    'Curse of Bambino' looms large as Yankees take game 4 of ALCS
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The light is dimming in New England, the Curse ever
more apocalyptic.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Yankees pushed Boston to within a game of ALCS
elimination Sunday night, blowing apart a tense evening with a
disputed umpire's call and a pinch-hit grand slam by Ricky Ledee in
a 9-2 runaway that put the Red Sox down three games to one.
</P>
<P>
   Boston, which had averaged 15 runs a game in three postseason
dates at Fenway Park, was blanked over the final six innings by
starter Andy Pettitte (7 1/3 innings, one earned run) and closer
Mariano Rivera.
</P>
<P>
   Just for a little Bambino Curse spicing, Boston's Jose Offerman
was called out by umpire Tim Tschida in a disputed play for running
out of the base line during an inning-ending double play in the
eighth. On cue, New York put up six runs in the ninth.
</P>
<P>
   After a close call against Boston brought a shower of debris in
the bottom of the ninth inning, umpires cleared the field for eight
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The sellout crowd of 33,586 already was angry, having seen
second-base umpire Tim Tschida call out Jose Offerman in the eighth
inning _ replays indicated second baseman Chuck Knoblauch missed
the tag.
</P>
<P>
   Then, after pinch-hitter Ricky Ledee's grand slam in the top of
the ninth broke it open and gave the Yankees a 9-2 lead, the real
trouble began.
</P>
<P>
   Nomar Garciaparra opened the bottom half with a grounder to
third baseman Scott Brosius and was called out by first-base umpire
Dale Scott.
</P>
<P>
   Red Sox manager Jimy Williams ran on the field to argue and
threw his hat. Williams was ejected, and the fans went crazy.
</P>
<P>
   At first, a few plastic water bottles were thrown on the field.
Glass bottles followed, with several of them barely missing Scott's
head.
</P>
<P>
   With security personnel rushing on the field, first baseman Tino
Martinez and other Yankees also had to duck flying objects as they
went scurrying for cover in the third-base dugout. New York
relievers also ran out of the right-field bullpen as umpires waved
them off the field.
</P>
<P>
   The crowd continued to chant profanities, and the public-address
announcer was forced to urge fans to halt, saying the Red Sox might
be forced to forfeit the game.
</P>
<P>
   After the Yankees waited safely in their dugout, order was
restored and the game resumed.
</P>
<P>
   A home run by Darryl Strawberry and error by Boston pitcher Bret
Saberhagen had given the Yankees a 3-2 advantage.
</P>
<P>
   As in the series' first three games, Boston posted an early
lead, Jose Offerman breaking up a 1-1 tie in the third inning with
an RBI single bringing in Damon Buford. The lead might have been
two runs, but Offerman was thrown out on Derek Jeter's relay home
when he attempted to score from first on John Valentin's double off
the left-field wall.
</P>
<P>
   That play became important in the fourth, when Boston gave away
its 2-1 lead. An error by Nomar Garciaparra and a more painful
bobble by Saberhagen opened the way, Garciaparra first allowing
Bernie Williams to reach second on a wild throw. Williams came
around to tie it 2-2 on Tino Martinez's double.
</P>
<P>
   Two batters later with two out, Saberhagen appeared to be out of
it when Chad Curtis grounded to first. But Mike Stanley's potential
inning-ending throw to first base was low and Saberhagen dropped
it, allowing Martinez to score, giving the Yankees the lead.
</P>
<P>
   Boston tied it 1-1 in the second, despite Butch Huskey's balky
knee. The Red Sox DH was able to leg out a double running with a
heavy limp but barely scored on Troy O'Leary's bloop single.
</P>
<P>
   New York manager Joe Torre played a hunch with his choice of
starting Strawberry as his DH, saying, ``To me, Darryl is a force.
The one thing Darryl gives you is the threat of a home run ...''
</P>
<P>
   Strawberry needed only one at-bat to fulfill that trust with a
drive off the right-field foul pole in the second inning for a 1-0
lead.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Stinson writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga. The Associated Press contributed to this report.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
