<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-BRAVES-ART-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METS STAY ALIVE WITH A STUNNING 4-3 VICTORY OVER ATLANTA 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs for rewriting throughout) (ART ADV: Photos are being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(sw) 
 By JUDY BATTISTA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Robin Ventura was waving his hand wildly, pushing his
long ball back as he neared first base and, with it, pushing the
National League Championship Series into pandemonium and a return
to Atlanta. Ventura's ball cleared the right-field wall, but he
never made it around for his grand slam. Ventura was mobbed by his
teammates near second base, his shot having driven in the winning
run in the bottom of the 15th inning for a stunning 4-3 Mets
victory over the Atlanta Braves in Game 5 of the NLCS.
</P>
<P>
   The victory cut the Braves' lead in the four-of-seven-game
series to 3-2, and forced the series back to Atlanta, where Game 6
will be played Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   The longest game in post-season history, at 5 hours 46 minutes,
and one that continued the life of the Mets' season came down to a
player who was just 1 for 18 in the series when he came to the
plate with one out and the bases loaded.
</P>
<P>
   After Ventura sent the ball sailing over the wall against the
Atlanta reliever Kevin McGlinchy, he rounded first and saw his
teammates running across the field at him. Ventura was mobbed
before he reached second base, but by that time Matt Franco had
scored the winning run. Although the ball cleared the fence,
Ventura was credited with a single and only one run scored.
</P>
<P>
   The long single completed an extraordinary inning and continued
an increasingly improbable run in the post-season.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets are only the second team _ the Braves were the first
last year _ to come back from a 0-3 deficit to win two games in a
seven-game series, but now they must try to accomplish a much more
unlikely feat: becoming the first team to come back from 0-3 to
win. And after what took place at Shea Stadium on Sunday night _ it
was reminiscent of the Mets' 7-6 victory in 16 innings over the
Astros in the NLCS in 1986 _ only someone who had not paid
attention for the last month could doubt that the World Series was
still beyond their reach.
</P>
<P>
   As they had so many times this season, the Mets looked finished
in the top half of the 15th. The teams had played to a 2-2 tie by
the fourth inning and then had stayed there, squandering
opportunities, shuffling players, stretching the patience and
endurance of the rain-soaked fans. The Braves alone stranded 19
runners on base.
</P>
<P>
   But finally, with the Mets' ninth pitcher of the game, the
rookie Octavio Dotel, on the mound _ only Al Leiter, the Game 6
starter, and Rick Reed, who pitched Game 4, were left _ Walt Weiss
led off the 15th with a single. Dotel got the next two batters out,
but when Keith Lockhart smashed a triple to right center to score
Weiss and give Atlanta a 3-2 lead, Dotel was devastated.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves were on the brink of going to their fifth World
Series of the 1990s and the Mets were on the verge of a devastating
end to a remarkable month. Dotel struck out the dangerous Brian
Jordan to escape the inning, and when he went to the dugout, he was
met by a group of his teammates.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a tough situation for a kid to come in when we're down to
the last game,'' Darryl Hamilton said. ``We said, `Kid, we're going
to get a run and you're going to be in this game and you're going
to win this game.'''
</P>
<P>
   And of course, Hamilton was right. Shawon Dunston led off the
bottom of the 15th with a remarkable at-bat: nine minutes, 12
pitches, six pitches fouled off after the count reached 3-2.
Finally, he singled up the middle. Matt Franco pinch-hit for Dotel,
meaning that if the game had continued, Manager Bobby Valentine
would have nearly needed volunteers from the crowd to take the
mound.
</P>
<P>
   Franco set a major league record this season by drawing 19 walks
as a pinch-hitter and so, naturally, after Dunston had already
stolen second, Franco drew another walk. Edgardo Alfonzo sacrificed
the two runners ahead, and McGlinchy, the Braves' sixth pitcher,
intentionally walked John Olerud, who had hit a home run in the
first inning to score the Mets' first two runs.
</P>
<P>
   With the bases loaded, Roger Cedeno, who had been held out with
back spasms, came in to run for Franco, and Todd Pratt came to the
plate. He had replaced Mike Piazza as catcher in the 14th inning,
after Piazza strained his left forearm.
</P>
<P>
   All the pressure was on the young reliever and he wasn't
throwing strikes. The count went to 3-0 and Pratt faked the bunt.
``I was trying to put another tool into the mix,'' Pratt explained.
</P>
<P>
   But Pratt took ball four to walk home the tying run and bring
Ventura to bat. Ventura, hampered by a bad knee, had seemed
terribly uncomfortable at the plate during this series and he, in
particular, had struggled all season against the Braves. But he
knew well that McGlinchy was in trouble.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's different when the bases are loaded and the guy has
already walked a guy,'' Ventura said. ``He can't really fool around
and throw a bunch of pitches in the dirt. So I'm just trying to get
a ball in the air so the guy can score.''
</P>
<P>
   He did more than that. He took the count to 2-1 and then
launched the ball in the air. Valentine did not know if it would
clear the fence, and it hardly mattered, since even a sacrifice fly
would win the game. ``He scalded that ball,'' Pratt said. ``I knew
we had won the game just the way the ball came off the bat. It was
just classic for him to come through.''
</P>
<P>
   The other comebacks that had brought the Mets to this point had
seemed improbable. This one was insane. The series now moves to
Atlanta, where the Mets have won just once in eight tries this
season. Of course, for the Mets, that's probably the good news.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just seems like this team responds to dire situations,''
Ventura said. ``We just play another day. It seems like we've been
saying that for about a month and a half now. We can't lose another
game. We're happy to just be playing.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
