<SLUG> BC-GEN-KEISSER-COLUMN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS WORLD OUT OF ORBIT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB KEISSER  
 c.1999 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Today's oversaturated edition of The Sporting Muse:
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it's the millennium, maybe it's aftershocks. Whatever the
cause, the sports world is seriously out of whack at the moment.
</P>
<P>
   The Rams are the only unbeaten team in the NFL. The World
Wildlife Association has just placed quarterbacks on the endangered
species list. The Pac-10 may send an unranked team to the Rose
Bowl. The Hokies may play for the national title. New York baseball
fans are calling their team with a $65 million payroll a
``miracle.'' The Red Sox are still playing, and the first BCS poll,
a sure sign of armageddon, is due next Monday.
</P>
<P>
   It's Y2Krazy. ...
</P>
<P>
   So what are the chances of the Los Angeles Rams -- I've
reclaimed them on the behalf of our chagrined citizenry --
finishing the season unbeaten?
</P>
<P>
   Not bad, especially since the 49er era has officially ended.
After next week's win against Cleveland, the Rams play at Tennessee
and Detroit. If they're 8-0 at that point, they'll have
home-and-homes left with Carolina and New Orleans and a game at San
Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Thereafter, their biggest challenge will be staying awake with
season ending games against the Giants, Bears and Eagles. Here's
hoping Georgia Frontiere lets the Super Bowl Trophy spend a weekend
in L.A. ...
</P>
<P>
   The Los Angeles Raiders -- I've reclaimed them on behalf of the
six people who send me letters calling for their return -- are 3-3
after six tough weeks, and they have home games coming up against
the Jets and Dolphins.
</P>
<P>
   But if they can stay upright, they could steal a playoff berth.
They'll have six games left against AFC West rivals, including two
versus the Chargers, whom they own, and games against Tennessee and
Tampa.
</P>
<P>
   With the Broncos and Jets demised and the Jags struggling, the
AFC is a raffle. Picking any one team to survive at this point is
foolish conjecture. Why not the Raiders?
</P>
<P>
   And the real advantage for L.A. Raider fans with frequent flier
miles is that plenty of good seats are available in the Oakland
Mausoleum. ...
</P>
<P>
   Here's the latest installment of ``They're Killing the Great
Quarterbacks of the NFL,'' a thrilling breakdown of all the bad
breaks at the most important position:
</P>
<P>
   Teams forced to change QBs Sunday due to injuries: Arizona (Jake
Plummer), Detroit (Charlie Batch), Jacksonville (Mark Brunell),
Miami (Dan Marino).
</P>
<P>
   Teams previously forced to change QBs due to injuries: Atlanta
(Chris Chandler), Chicago (Shane Matthews), New York Jets (Vinny
Testaverde), San Diego (Jim Harbaugh), San Francisco (Steve Young),
Tennessee (Steve McNair).
</P>
<P>
   Teams changing QBs Sunday, coach's decision: Minnesota (Jeff
George for Randall Cunningham), New Orleans (Billie Joe Tolliver
for Billie Joe Hobert), New York Jets (Ray Lucas for Rick Mirer).
</P>
<P>
   Teams previously changing QBs in 1999, coach's decision:
Cincinnati, Denver, Philadelphia, New York Giants.
</P>
<P>
   Teams starting rookies: Cincinnati (Akili Smith), Chicago (Cade
McNown), Cleveland (Tim Couch).
</P>
<P>
   Teams starting sophomores: Denver (Brian Griese), Detroit
(Charlie Batch), Indianapolis (Peyton Manning).
</P>
<P>
   Teams with first-year starters, non-rookies: Baltimore (Stoney
Case), Philadelphia (Doug Pederson), St. Louis (Kurt Warner), San
Francisco (Jeff Garcia).
</P>
<P>
   Teams starting '98 reserves: Carolina (Steve Beuerlein), New
Orleans (Billie Joe Whoever), Oakland (Rich Gannon), San Diego
(Harbaugh/Erik Kramer), Tennessee (Neil O'Donnell).
</P>
<P>
   Teams starting ex-CFL stars: Buffalo (Doug Flutie).
</P>
<P>
   Teams whose fans want a change at QB: Pittsburgh (Kordell
Stewart), Tampa Bay (Trent Dilfer).
</P>
<P>
   QBs who should buy more insurance: Troy Aikman, Drew Bledsoe,
Brett Favre, Elvis Grbac and Brad Johnson. ...
</P>
<P>
   Considering the shape of the Pac-10 this season, let's answer
this question before anyone asks: No, there's never been a Pac-10
champ with three conference losses.
</P>
<P>
   But as recently as 1983, the Pac-10 sent an unranked team to the
Rose Bowl. The Bruins started 0-3-1 but rallied under quarterback
Rick Neuheisel to go 6-1-1 in the conference and win the Rose Bowl
invitation. And once there, they routed No. 4 Illinois, 45-9. ...
</P>
<P>
   The Pac-10's play this year is indefensible, but I refuse to
believe there are seven Big Ten teams better than any one Pac-10
team, which is the case poll-wise. In the current coach's poll, 42
different teams received at least one vote, and only two were from
the Pac-10 (Arizona and Stanford).
</P>
<P>
   That's taking things a bit far. Oregon lost to Michigan State by
a touchdown. Any single loss isn't as bad as Wisconsin losing to
Cincinnati (other than Arizona State losing to New Mexico State).
And Minnesota and several other Top 25 teams have played the
football equivalent of Grenada. ...
</P>
<P>
   My greatest desire is to see three or more teams finish the
season unbeaten and throw the BCS into chaos.
</P>
<P>
   Florida State is 7-0 and No. 1, but three of the 'Noles four
remaining games are on the road -- at Clemson, where Poppa Bowden
meets Sonny Bowden Saturday; at Virginia, where the Seminoles lost
their first ACC game ever; and at Florida and Steve Spurrier,
Bowden's nemesis.
</P>
<P>
   Penn State is 7-0 and No. 2, but they still have road games left
at Purdue and Michigan State, plus a home date against Michigan. If
the Big Ten is as good as the pollsters would lead you to believe,
no one will go unbeaten.
</P>
<P>
   Nebraska is 6-0 and No. 3, but the four toughest games of their
1999 schedule lie ahead, at Texas, Texas A&AMP;M, Kansas State and at
Colorado, plus the Big XII title game.
</P>
<P>
   Virginia Tech is 6-0, ranked No. 4, and plays cheese wiz the
rest of the season -- Pitt, West Virginia, Miami, Temple and Boston
College. The Hokies thus have the best chance of playing their way
into the title game, assuming it isn't vanquished by a computer
virus. ...
</P>
<P>
   Marshall of the Mid-American Conference is also unbeaten and has
played its toughest games already, but it would take severals Acts
of God to get them into the BCS picture. Kansas State and
Mississippi State are also unbeaten but longshots to run the table.
...
</P>
<P>
   The best possible prognosis for USC and UCLA is a trip for two
to Hawaii.
</P>
<P>
   That's where a bowl doubleheader will be played Christmas Day.
But the 3-4 Bruins need to win three of their last four games to
qualify, and they still have Arizona, Washington and USC left.
</P>
<P>
   USC, 3-3, needs to win four of their remaining six, since the
bowls require at least six Division 1-A wins and a winning record.
In this case, the scheduling of a 12th game can work against the
Trojans.
</P>
<P>
   As poorly as USC has played lately, I wouldn't call anyone on
their remaining schedule unbeatable: Stanford, Cal, Arizona State,
Washington State, UCLA and Louisiana Tech. ...
</P>
<P>
   Only New York could throw words like ``miracle'' around a team
that won 95 regular season games and has a $65 million payroll.
</P>
<P>
   Bobby Valentine horribly over manages his team. Any manager who
uses seven pitchers in a 2-2 game through nine innings, and who
puts a shortstop in center field deserves to lose.
</P>
<P>
   The only reason the Mets are still alive is because Braves
manager Bobby Cox is a notorious overmanager himself, especially
when it comes to selecting his relievers. ...
</P>
<P>
   Separated at birth: Raider fan, Met fan.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-18-99 0033EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
