<HEADER>
A0034 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BBN-NLCS-HNS &LR;      10-18 0804
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-NLCS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CARLTON THOMPSON  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
NEW YORK _ A rules technicality robbed Robin Ventura of what should
have gone down as one of the greatest home runs in playoff history.
But nothing could stop the New York Mets from stealing a victory
that appeared safely tucked into the Atlanta Braves' back pockets.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ventura's game-winning hit _ a grand slam that was ruled a
single because he didn't circle the bases _ capped the longest
playoff game (by time) in major-league history and lifted the
resilient Mets to a 15-inning 4-3 victory in Game 5 of the National
League Championship Series on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   For the second day in a row, the Mets staved off elimination in
the best-of-seven series. Game 6 is set for Tuesday at Atlanta's
Turner Field, and after playing for five hours and 46 minutes, both
teams could use the day off.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was playoff baseball at its best,'' said Braves starter
Greg Maddux, who pitched the first seven innings. ``That's probably
as good a game as anyone has seen since (Game 6 of the 1986 NLCS
when the Mets eliminated the Astros in 16 innings). This was a heck
of a game.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the fourth time in two weeks the Mets won a game that
would have ended their season had they lost.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guys were thinking, they were pulling, they were believing
the whole time,'' Mets manager Bobby Valentine said. ``They came up
big. When players come up big and do the right things, you're able
to play a great team like Atlanta tough as long as we played them
until they cracked.''
</P>
<P>
   A playoff-record 45 players were used in the game, and the Mets
used nine of their 11 pitchers. Al Leiter, who will start Tuesday's
game for the Mets, was warming up along with Game 4 starter Rick
Reed when the game ended.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, Braves manager Bobby Cox, who has shown a
willingness to use his starters in relief when the game is on the
line, kept his biggest guns in the holster, apparently saving them
for a non-rainy day.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Cox put his team's fate in the hands of seldom-used
rookie reliever Kevin McGlinchy, who created the 15th-inning mess
by allowing a single and three walks (one intentional) before
serving up Ventura's bullet over the right-field wall.
</P>
<P>
   The loss was demoralizing, to say the least, for the Braves, who
had taken the lead in the top of the 15th on Keith Lockhart's RBI
triple. Within a matter of minutes, McGlinchy gave it back. The
question on almost everyone's mind was why Cox didn't use Kevin
Millwood.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't going to use Millwood in that stuff,'' Cox said in
reference to the wet and muddy conditions. ``(McGlinchy) is a
big-leaguer. He should be able to throw strikes and get them out.
We thought he would.''
</P>
<P>
   That turned out to be wishful thinking.
</P>
<P>
   Ventura, who was 1-for-19 in the series before Sunday's heroic
at-bat, rewrote the script with one swing. As he rounded first
base, his teammates poured from the bench and created a mob scene
in the middle of the diamond. That's as close as Ventura would get
to home plate, thus the odd ruling.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw it go over (the fence), and then I ran to first,''
Ventura said. ``As long as I touched first base, we won, so that's
fine with me.''
</P>
<P>
   That was the thrill of victory; the agony of defeat rested in
the gut of a rookie pitcher down the hall.
</P>
<P>
   ``I took it right on the chin,'' McGlinchy said. ``That's pretty
tough to take. That situation was about as pressure-filled as it
gets, but my job is to go out there in pressure situations. I
really wanted the ball, and I really wanted to get guys out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I kept getting behind in the count, and it's tough to pitch
from behind. At some point, the game was going to end; I just hated
being the guy who had to walk off the mound when it was over like
that. It's very discouraging.''
</P>
<P>
   There was action in the beginning and major drama at the end,
but not much in between. For about 10 innings, home plate might as
well have been under quarantine. The Braves left 19 runners on
base, and the Mets stranded 12, or one more than the Braves left in
scoring position.
</P>
<P>
   ``We missed way too many opportunities,'' Cox said. ``We should
have scored many more runs. We had a few more chances than they did
and swung at a lot of bad balls. It was not an easy way to lose a
ballgame, but in Kevin's defense, the mound was tough.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was tough to throw strikes off that mound, and your shoes
were stacking up with clay underneath them. I don't care who you
would have brought in, they probably would have walked them, too.''
</P>
<P>
   John Olerud's two-run homer put the Mets on the board in the
first inning. The Braves tied the score at 2 in the fourth on Brian
Jordan's RBI single, which followed doubles by Bret Boone and
Chipper Jones.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
