<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-IRL-MALL.COM500-TEX </SLUG>
 
Texan Ray claims IRL title at home 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM REEVES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
FORT WORTH, Texas _ In the moment after he took the checkered flag
Sunday as the new champion of the Pep Boys Indy Racing League, Greg
Ray said his thoughts turned immediately to donuts.
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``I hadn't had the chance to do donuts in this car this year,''
said Ray, referring to the celebratory spins that have become
commonplace by race winners. ``I was looking for a place big enough
to do it. I'm going to have to practice that.''
</P>
<P>
   Let the record show that Plano resident Ray executed two crisp
donuts at both ends of the front-stretch dogleg at Texas Motor
Speedway, in a salute to his team, his Lone Star fans and
ultimately to himself. On a damp and long day that began with three
drivers in contention for the 1999 driver's championship, Mark
Dismore emerged as a first-time IRL winner at the conclusion of the
Mall.com 500.
</P>
<P>
   And Ray emerged as a first-time IRL champion, who can spend the
off-season refining his donut delivery.
</P>
<P>
   ``It won't sink in for a while,'' said Ray, whose third-place
finish behind Dismore and Davey Hamilton was enough to hold off
title-contenders Kenny Brack and Sam Schmidt for a $1 million
championship bonus. ``I know when I did my first Indy 500 it didn't
sink in for months after that. To win the championship and win it
here, that's big. That's going to be real big.''
</P>
<P>
   Ray finished one lap down to Dismore in the 208-lap event around
TMS' 1.5-mile quadoval. On other race days this season, that would
have been unacceptable for the aggressive Ray and team-owner John
Menard. Sunday, pole-sitter Ray raced safely and smartly on a track
where ambient temperatures in the mid-50s at the start of the race
and track temperatures only in the 60s made traction-control a key
element of the game plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``The championship, of course, is more important than winning
one race,'' said Ray, 33, who was making his 24th IRL start. ``It
doesn't matter what your game plan is. It's a game of technology
and dealing with what is in front of you. We thought we could win
the race and the championship here in Texas. We would have liked to
have won here, almost as much as Indy. But the championship was the
focus.''
</P>
<P>
   Ray began the race _ which rolled off 3 hours, 55 minutes past
its scheduled 1 p.m. start time because of rain _ with a 16-point
lead over Brack. And Ray was 33 points up on Schmidt, winner of the
previous race at Las Vegas Motor Speedway on Sept. 26 and the only
other title contender.
</P>
<P>
   Schmidt's shot at the title ended when he and Scott Sharp
collided on a restart down the frontstretch on Lap 126. The crash
punted Schmidt into the outside retaining wall, causing heavy
front-end damage to a car he was fighting to keep in eighth place.
</P>
<P>
   Ray said that as concerned as he was for Schmidt, his friend and
weekend houseguest, he had to refocus on Brack, who was leading the
race. Ray was running second at that point, with Dismore in third.
When the race went back to green on Lap 140, Brack, Ray and Dismore
held their positions as the only drivers on the lead lap until
Sharp's blown engine brought out the day's fifth yellow flag.
</P>
<P>
   On Lap 154, Brack pitted for tires and fuel and handed the lead
to Ray. Dismore made his final stop on Lap 161, allowing Brack to
recycle his way into second behind Ray. The Texan was working on a
1.333-second lead on Lap 182 when Brack's car, owned by four-time
Indy 500 champion A.J. Foyt of Houston, slowed dramatically down
the backstretch.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all over for us,'' Foyt said as his crew hustled to
replace a broken right rear wheel bearing. ``Hopefully, we can
salvage a second in the points.''
</P>
<P>
   With both his championship contenders disabled, Ray turned his
attention to a front nose section damaged by debris from Schmidt's
crash. Ray pitted for tires and fuel and the reassurance from
Menard that the flapping carbon fiber would hold up.
</P>
<P>
   Ray went down a lap during that stop, allowing Dismore and
Hamilton to move past him. Ray's fourth victory of the season was
not going to happen here. But his championship celebration was
about to begin. The title also was the second in three seasons for
Team Menard, which won with driver Tony Stewart in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   At that point in his IRL career, Ray and underfunded team-owner
Thomas Knapp were wondering if they ever would get the chance to
run with the IRL's big boys.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be a part of this team and win a championship here at my
home track is a dream come true,'' said Ray, who signed on as
driver of the No. 2 Glidden-Menards Dallara/Aurora in October 1998.
``I questioned why we didn't win the championship last year and
also the Indy 500 this year. You just have to be patient and work
hard and give it your all. You have to make sacrifices to reach a
goal.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-18-99 0034EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
