A0037 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a BC-GEN-CSUNOTE-LADN-(SLA     10-18 0502
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEN-CSUNOTE-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIGH HOPES FOR RETURNEES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHRIS BRANAM  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The Cal State Northridge basketball teams, both of
which have realistic goals of winning the Big Sky Conference this
season, officially started fall practice on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The men worked for three hours, then gave the court to the
women, who are the defending conference champions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not a more exciting day than the first day of practice,'' said
men's head coach Bobby Braswell, who enters his fourth season with
a team picked to finish second or third in the Big Sky in most
preseason publications.
</P>
<P>
   Frozena Jerro, who took the Matadors women to the NCAA playoffs
as the interim head coach in March, said it was easy to see the
difference between last year's opening day and this one.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have eight veterans that went to the NCAA Tournament,'' she
said. ``They made it, I wouldn't say easier, but smoother. It was a
good day. I was anxious.''
</P>
<P>
   Braswell emphasized defense through most of his practice. Even
though the Matadors return four starters, more than any team in the
conference, CSUN got bounced from the Big Sky Tournament by Montana
State in a 91-90 loss.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to be one of the best defensive teams in the
country,'' Braswell said. ``In the past, our guys have had the
mentality, `If we don't stop them, we can still score.' ''
</P>
<P>
   The Matadors, who were 17-12 last year and 9-8 in the Big Sky,
recruited three quality guards: Lionel Benjamin, Craig Calloway and
Marco McCain. Calloway, a freshman, and McCain, a junior, were
teammates at Jordan High in Long Beach.
</P>
<P>
   Jerro spent most of the first practice on offensive drills. CSUN
(21-8 last season, including 13-3 in Big Sky) had the conference's
best offense last year, but Jerro wants more.
</P>
<P>
   ``Defense is going to be our mainstay,'' Jerro said.
``Eventually, it's going to be an issue for us, being able to
execute offensively.''
</P>
<P>
   __ On the rise: Despite a recent slump that includes a
disappointing 3-2 loss at Pepperdine, the women's soccer team is on
pace to set a school record for victories. The Matadors haven't
finished above .500 in their five-year history, and they've gone
8-29 the last two seasons. Sophomore forward Erin Broadwell (La
Canada High) has eight goals, setting a single-season school
record.
</P>
<P>
   __ It's a hit: CSUN athletics' home page, www.gomatadors.com, is
getting more hits than usual when the radio broadcast of a football
road game is accessible on the site.The home page averages 350 hits
on those days, and the normal rate is 220 per day.
</P>
<P>
   __ Rare opportunity: Tickets are available for the men's
basketball ``tipoff banquet'' on Nov. 1. John Wooden, who recently
turned 89, is the guest speaker.
</P>
<P>
   The cost for the 6:30 p.m. banquet, which is in the grand salon
in the student union, is $100 per person, $1,000 to reserve a
nine-person table. Information: Mike Johnson, (818) 677-3994.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
