<SLUG> BC-LAUSD-BELMONT-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIDDEN BILLS ADD MILLIONS TO BELMONT PRICE TAG
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY BETH BARRETT AND GREG GITTRICH  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
Los Angeles _ The Belmont Learning Center _ the nation's most
expensive public high school _ has racked up at least $33.5 million
in encumbrances above the costs previously disclosed by Los Angeles
Unified School District officials.
<TEXT>
<P>
   According to invoices and other public documents that school
administrators attempted to keep secret, the district owes the
additional millions to contractors, consultants and investigators
working on the public works fiasco.
</P>
<P>
   The hidden bills bring the ``official'' cost of the Belmont
project to $159 million, about twice the district's original
guaranteed maximum price. The school, which is slightly more than
half-completed, sits downtown atop an oil field plagued by
potentially deadly and explosive gases.
</P>
<P>
   The final price tag will likely surpass $200 million when
environmental mitigation costs, construction delays and additional
consultant fees are factored in.
</P>
<P>
   For the last two months, district officials had reported the
cost of the complex at $126 million.
</P>
<P>
   The new figure comes amid an investigation into the finances of
the environmentally troubled project by LAUSD auditor Don Mullinax
and three weeks after a Los Angeles Daily News investigation
revealed the ``guaranteed maximum price'' of the complex was a
sham.
</P>
<P>
   Assembly Speaker Antonio Villaraigosa, D-Los Angeles, has told a
panel of civic leaders weighing the fate of the school that the
district will not receive any state money to offset the exorbitant
costs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The state is not going to put one penny into Belmont,''
Villaraigosa told the Belmont Commission last week.
</P>
<P>
   The speaker stopped short of telling the commission to recommend
abandoning the project. Villaraigosa said he believed the public
would support completing construction if costs to mitigate methane
and hydrogen sulfide gases at the site could be held to under $15
million.
</P>
<P>
   The speaker, however, said he has no faith in the district's
ability to operate a mitigation system and believes an independent
panel would have to be set up to handle that crucial task.
</P>
<P>
   Following Villaraigosa's comments, a district-hired
environmental consultant presented four potential mitigation
systems to the Belmont Commission. The least expensive would cost
the district between $14.1 million and $20.4 million. The price for
the most expensive system with the most safety precautions would be
$35.2 million to $50.8 million.
</P>
<P>
   Those mitigation costs, however, have been disputed by lawyers
representing O'Melveny &AMP; Myers, the law firm Los Angeles Unified is
suing for malpractice over advice it doled out with regard to
Belmont.
</P>
<P>
   Mitigation specialists hired by Gibson, Dunn &AMP; Crutcher contend
even the most elaborate system, as described by the LAUSD
consultants, would cost $13.7 million, about one-third of the price
quoted to the Belmont Commission.
</P>
<P>
   The commission is scheduled to conclude its 60-day evaluation of
the project Wednesday. The panel will meet three more times,
beginning Monday, to hash out a recommendation for the school
board. All the proceedings will be held in public, with the
exception of a short session Monday morning.
</P>
<P>
   If the project is scrapped, the district has pledged to expedite
construction of a high school in the neighborhood to relieve
overcrowding. If the school board signs off on finishing Belmont,
the school is expected to open in three to four years with a
mitigation system in place.
</P>
<P>
   After initially refusing to comply with a Daily News public
records request for a list of bills the district owes on Belmont,
school officials backed down last week.
</P>
<P>
   The $33.5 million in encumbered costs is distributed among 21
parties and includes $350,000 approved by the school board for the
Belmont Commission's review.
</P>
<P>
   The bulk, $29.2 million, is owed to the developer, Temple
Beaudry Partners, a consortium led by Kajima Urban Development. The
payment has been approved by the board; however, the district and
developer are in negotiations over how much of the bill will be
paid if the complex isn't completed, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The $29 million is a reservation of funds for the unexpended
portion of the guaranteed maximum price contract,'' said LAUSD
spokesman Erik Nasarenko.
</P>
<P>
   Amid criticism from the Belmont Commission, investigators and
the press about the district's consistent practice of withholding
public documents and mismarking material as ``confidential'' or
``privileged,'' officials vowed to be more forthcoming in the
future.
</P>
<P>
   The district complied with the Daily News' records act request
for the encumbered costs after consulting with Ward Benshoof, a
lead partner from the firm McClintock, Weston, Benshoof, Rochefort,
Rubalcava &AMP; MacCuish.
</P>
<P>
   Benshoof, whose firm has been handling negotiations between the
district and Temple Beaudry Partners, said there should have been
no delay in releasing the information to the public.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is nothing (in the Daily News request) that is anything
other than the district's normal accounting records, which are open
to the public,'' Benshoof said. ``Releasing that information does
not hurt our negotiations.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We will re-emphasize (to LAUSD bureaucrats) that
confidentiality is important to us and our negotiations with Temple
Beaudry Partners, but it should not be overdrawn,'' he said. `What
should be public is public. What should be confidential is
confidential.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
