<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-CHARGERS-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOUTHERN CALIFORNIA'S (ONLY) TEAM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PAUL OBERJUERGE  
 c.1999 San Bernardino County Sun  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO _ The San Diego Chargers, L.A.'s team?
</P>
<P>
   If they're not, who is? See anybody else within 300 miles?
</P>
<P>
   The National Football League is not coming to the Los Angeles
Basin; Houston won the expansion chase, and the league may not add
another franchise in our lifetimes.
</P>
<P>
   No existing team is going to come to L.A., Orange County of the
Inland Empire until a stadium is built, and that's about as likely
as snow at Chavez Ravine.
</P>
<P>
   The only team in all of Southern California, the only NFL
franchise within commuting distance of the Southland ... is right
here at Qualcomm Stadium. The Chargers. The Bolts. Which makes them
ours, too, by default.
</P>
<P>
   At least the timing is felicitous.
</P>
<P>
   The Chargers have stunk it up in recent years, when Angelenos
still entertained the fantasy of getting their own team. Stunk it
up to the tune of 8-8, 4-12, 5-11 since 1995, the last year they
made the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Not only have the Chargers been bad, they've been boring, and
that's a deadly combination in the L.A. market; good thing we
weren't paying attention.
</P>
<P>
   The Chargers are no longer awful, but they're still tedious. All
defense and special teams, and incomplete passes and 2-yard runs by
Natrone Means. They entered Sunday's game with Seattle with the
NFL's 29th-best offense. In a 31-team league.
</P>
<P>
   But they're winning. Somehow. They defeated the Seahawks 13-10
Sunday on a 41-yard field goal on the last play of the game to
improve to 4-1 and (true story) take the lead in the AFC West.
</P>
<P>
   John Carney's decisive field goal had hardly split the goal
posts when the announcer at Qualcomm intoned, ``We'll see you back
here next week when the first-place San Diego Chargers take on the
Green Bay Packers.''
</P>
<P>
   Heady stuff. A Super Bowl preview?
</P>
<P>
   Means, the beefy running back, concedes these Chargers won't be
confused with the Air Coryell team of Dan Fouts, Charlie Joyner and
Kellen Winslow. Or even the Bobby Ross/Stan Humphries team that
reached Super Bowl XXIX.
</P>
<P>
   ``This wasn't a great game,'' Means said. ``If I was watching it
at home, maybe I'd be bored.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we'll take first place any time.''
</P>
<P>
   These Chargers actually are a team a fan might come to admire.
Yes, they're faceless once you get past linebacker Junior Seau, but
they play with enthusiasm. Their defense keeps them in games. Coach
Mike Riley is a low-key, friendly guy.
</P>
<P>
   If the Chargers can scrape up a couple of touchdowns every week,
they could be playing in January.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest problem here is the quarterback situation. Ryan Leaf
was supposed to solve that, but you know what happened to him. Can
you say, ``major bust?''
</P>
<P>
   That leaves the Chargers with a quarterback controversy pitting
career mediocrities Erik Kramer and Jim Harbaugh. Throwing to as
undistinguished a receiver corps as exists in the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's victory was a good example of what the 1999 Chargers
are about. Staying close, hanging around until the offense stumbles
into some points.
</P>
<P>
   Interceptions set up a touchdown for each team, then the
Chargers won it in the final five minutes by forcing Seattle's
seventh and eighth punts and patching together two 45-yard drives
to Carney field goals.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are games that we are going to win that aren't pretty,''
Kramer said. ``But there will be games coming up that are going to
be pretty.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe. What's most attractive about the Chargers to L.A. fans is
that they play in the NFL. Makes them pretty unique.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-18-99 0046EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
