A0041 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-CAR-LEBRETON-COLUMN-T     10-18 0733
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-LEBRETON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
 
Dismore got more than a win at TMS 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GIL LEBRETON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
FORT WORTH, Texas _ In addition to a trophy that was, by rough
guess, the approximate weight of Idaho, driver Mark Dismore finally
got his say Sunday.
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``He hasn't got anything to blame me for,'' Dismore offered.
</P>
<P>
   The ``he'' in question happened to be the same ``he'' who, at
that very moment, was being toasted as the man of the hour.
</P>
<P>
   Plano's Greg Ray was crowned the 1999 Indy Racing League
champion Sunday, despite finishing a comfortable third in the
Mall.com 500. The championship comes with a bonus check for $1
million.
</P>
<P>
   But it apparently won't come with anything from Mark Dismore.
</P>
<P>
   With his mind on his ailing father and his right foot pressed,
at long last, on an IRL victory, Dismore rode smartly, patiently to
his first series checkered flag Sunday. On the IRL's longest day,
it seemed fitting that the 75-pound stone trophy went to the driver
who had waited the longest.
</P>
<P>
   Dismore provided the lightning, while Ray stole the thunder.
</P>
<P>
   But after 29 career starts, the second-longest vigil for a first
victory in IRL history, Dismore wasn't about to downplay anything.
</P>
<P>
   In Victory Lane, his tears flowed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just thinking about things,'' explained Dismore, who
turned 43 last week. ``My dad has cancer, and it's been on my mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I don't need that reason to win a race. I've been ready
for a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   In his three years on the IRL circuit, Dismore had never
finished higher than third. At the Colorado Indy 200 at Pikes Peak
in August, Dismore had led the field heading into the final 19
laps.
</P>
<P>
   He was passed by Ray, of all people.
</P>
<P>
   Ray and Dismore. Dismore and Ray. The two names, like their Indy
cars, kept bumping into one another during this IRL season.
</P>
<P>
   An incident on pit row between the two cars knocked Ray out of
the Indianapolis 500. The two brushed again on lap 105 at Las Vegas
last month, after which Ray disparaged Dismore's driving pedigree
on national television.
</P>
<P>
   ``He got pretty brutal on me in the media, I thought,'' Dismore
said after Sunday's win. ``At Indy he ran up the side of me at a
point where I had been running well, and it just broke my heart and
shut my mouth.
</P>
<P>
   ``For Greg to come back and unload on me in Vegas was uncalled
for. I thought it was pretty stupid for him to go where you
couldn't fit a go-kart, let alone an Indy car. I think Greg has to
take some responsibility for that, for where he put his car.''
</P>
<P>
   The incidents, both drivers say, are over. Ironically, Ray could
have clinched the IRL season championship a month ago, if the two
cars hadn't bumped in Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like Greg,'' Dismore said. ``I think he respects me. We get
along fine. It's all behind me.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet, Dismore gave a spirited description of the two incidents
and the fallout that resulted.
</P>
<P>
   ``He hasn't got anything to blame me for,'' he repeated. ``In
fairness, he did apologize. But he hasn't gone out of his way to
make that very public.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no point in calling people names or saying stupid
things. You've got to think about things like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Dismore and Ray. Ray and Dismore.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't the same Sunday as, say, Foyt-vs.-Luyendyk, 1997, but
it added a touch of spice to a day when two drivers were named
winners.
</P>
<P>
   Dismore admits he is emotional and driven. Team owner Tom Kelley
of Kelley Racing calls Dismore and teammate Scott Sharp,
``caffeinated and decaffeinated,'' respectively.
</P>
<P>
   Somehow, though, Dismore had the patience to work his way back
from serious injuries suffered in 1991 at Indy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I doubted myself after that accident,'' he admitted.
</P>
<P>
   The legendary Dan Gurney said the next spring that he would give
Dismore a chance if he was healthy enough to drive at Daytona.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went down there to talk to him on crutches, but I left the
crutches in the car,'' Dismore said. ``I got in the car and cried.
I had this burning desire to drive that car as fast as I could
drive it.''
</P>
<P>
   His career started over that year. And Sunday, thinking about
his dad, Emerson, who is fighting prostate cancer, Dismore cried
again.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm pretty emotional, I guess,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   On the IRL's longest day, he had been the one who got the
checkered flag.
</P>
<P>
   He wasn't going to apologize for anything. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-18-99 0050EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
