<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-CHRGS2-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SETTING THEMSELVES UP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PAUL OBERJUERGE  
 c.1999 San Bernardino County Sun  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR;  SAN DIEGO _ Junior Seau isn't claiming the San Diego Chargers
are world-beaters just yet. But he likes where they're at after
five games.
</P>
<P>
   ``First place,'' the veteran linebacker said Sunday. ``I can't
emphasize how big that is. We haven't won anything yet, but we're
setting ourselves up for some big games down the line.''
</P>
<P>
   John Carney kicked a 41-yard field goal as time expired to give
San Diego a 13-10 victory over the Seattle Seahawks on Sunday
before 59,432 at Qualcomm Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   At 4-1, the Chargers are alone atop the AFC West standings, a
game ahead of Seattle and Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know this is a special team,'' said Mike Riley, the Chagers'
first-year coach. ``We've got some high standards here set by
people like Junior. It's very early, but I wouldn't trade places
with anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   The Chargers survived four interceptions of quarterback Erik
Kramer by blunting the Seattle offense; the Seahawks managed only
201 yards, 54 in the second half.
</P>
<P>
   Kramer came through with some key completions in the final five
minutes, when the Chargers twice drove 45 yards to set up Carney
field goals.
</P>
<P>
   ``I give Erik Kramer a lot of credit, because a less tough guy
could've folded,'' said Riley, who conceded he thought of benching
his quarterback. ``He just stayed with it and made plays.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the biggest was a 41-yard pass to Jeff Graham to set up
the tying field goal. Moments later, Kramer completed four
consecutive passes before the decisive field goal.
</P>
<P>
   Kramer, an 11-year veteran out of North Carolina State, said age
and experience allowed him to avoid mental meltdown.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was younger, I wouldn't have had the patience to
overcome'' the four interceptions, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
