<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LAUSD-ANGEL-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEVELOPER PROPOSES USING BELMONT SITE FOR $3.6 BILLION PARK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY GRET GITTRICH  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
Los Angeles _ The Los Angeles Unified School District could be
saved by an angel _ but it needs to have a little faith.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Nearly three months ago, the district received a confidential
proposal from the developer of a curious angelic monument to buy
the tainted Belmont Learning Center property downtown.
</P>
<P>
   The school board dismissed the idea in private without taking a
vote and has not notified an advisory commission weighing the fate
of the public works fiasco.
</P>
<P>
   But the developer says the offer still stands.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Angel City project is expanding, and I'm extremely
interested in the Belmont Center if it can't be completed as a
school,'' said developer Brett-Livingstone Strong, an
Australian-born sculptor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am indeed interested in acquiring it for use as park land,
which my project needs,'' Strong said.
</P>
<P>
   Belmont, the nation's costliest high school, sits atop an oil
field plagued by potentially deadly and explosive gases. State
toxics officials are investigating whether the half-completed
complex can ever be used safely as a school.
</P>
<P>
   Backed by funding from the Bank of New York and CNB Capital,
Strong has been snatching up land all around the stalled high
school to build a tower topped by a bronze, sword-wielding angel.
The Gothic celestial figure would be about twice the size of the
Statue of Liberty.
</P>
<P>
   While skeptics smirk at the idea, Strong has financing in place
to purchase more than 80 acres for the tower, park land, art
galleries, restaurants, hotels and a museum for the city's
entertainment industries.
</P>
<P>
   In an Aug. 12 letter to school officials, Strong's lawyer
detailed the financial backing behind the $3.6 billion Angel City
project and offered to buy the Belmont site.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Strong wishes to acquire the site of the Belmont Learning
Center so that the site may be used primarily for park and open
space in conjunction with the Angel City project,'' wrote attorney
Timothy Lappen from the law firm of Jeffer, Mangels, Butler &AMP;
Marmaro.
</P>
<P>
   `EVERYONE JUST LAUGHED'
</P>
<P>
   Key players in the preliminary negotiations said that board
member Julie Korenstein presented the proposal to her colleagues in
August but couldn't get them to seriously consider the idea.
</P>
<P>
   ``Korenstein was verbally beaten up for even suggesting the
board talk to the guy,'' said a school official who asked not to be
named. ``Everyone just laughed at her.''
</P>
<P>
   In an interview Saturday, Korenstein said she was stunned that
the board had no interest in investigating the proposal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted the board to consider every option, including selling
the property if it couldn't be used as a school or administrative
offices because of the environmental problems,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were and still are at a very critical point in the
decision-making process. It was a very logical proposal. I wouldn't
want it to go away without serious discussion. That would be an
enormous mistake.''
</P>
<P>
   Valerie Fields was the only other board member who responded to
questions for this story.
</P>
<P>
   Fields said she hasn't seen a proposal from the developer.
``There is nothing in writing that I've seen that indicates there
is a serious interest to buy the land,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, the confidential letter from Angel City to Chief
Administrative Officer David Koch explicitly offers to buy the
Belmont site.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Strong requests that the district obtain the necessary
consents to sell the Belmont site to him with an escrow period of
nine months, during which time Mr. Strong would complete all due
diligence,'' Lappen wrote.
</P>
<P>
   ``I understand that the district is not yet in a position to
discuss the possible price of the site but will be able to do so
once the appropriate parties have reviewed the letter. We welcome
that discussion when the district is ready.''
</P>
<P>
   Early last week, Erik Nasarenko, a spokesman for the district's
facilities division, said Koch and other LAUSD administrators only
had one meeting with representatives from Angel City.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was exploratory and informal in nature,'' Nasarenko said.
``Until the Board of Education determines the disposition of the
site, any consideration of alternative proposals is premature.''
</P>
<P>
   Strong, however, said his offer came after several meetings
between school officials and his advisers. Strong added he
personally spoke with LAUSD Superintendent Ruben Zacarias on one
occasion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't believe I've heard from the school district since
August,'' Strong said.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, others have been taking him seriously. Angel
City has approximately $180 million of property adjacent to Belmont
under contract, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The developer also has received letters of support from Mayor
Richard Riordan and the City Council.
</P>
<P>
   KEPT IN THE DARK
</P>
<P>
   A panel of civic leaders appointed by the school board is
scheduled to conclude its 60-day review of the Belmont debacle
Wednesday. Led by former District Attorney Ira Reiner, the Belmont
Commission will advise the school board to either complete or
abandon the construction project.
</P>
<P>
   While the commission was asked to weigh the environmental, legal
and financial ramifications of completing or abandoning the
complex, it has not been notified that Strong wants to buy Belmont,
Reiner said.
</P>
<P>
   Strong said he'd be willing to speak to the commissioners this
week before they hand over a recommendation to the school board.
</P>
<P>
   ``I look at L.A. and compare it with other cities around the
world _ Sydney, Tokyo, Chicago and New York,'' Strong said. ``All
those cities have beautiful large parks downtown. L.A. doesn't have
that.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to be the person who stops a much-needed school
for the neighborhood. But if they can't go forward, I want to buy
the property. Here's a chance for Los Angeles to have many acres of
park land right downtown. It would be spectacular.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-18-99 0053EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991018.0025 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-18 00:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0045 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r v BC--LADN     10-18 0405
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE>
CHASEN'S AUCTIONS OFF ITS HOLLYWOOD HISTORY
</HEADLINE>
 BC- -LADN (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DOMINIC BERBEO  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   West Hollywood _ &UR;  &LR; About 300 people paid $300 each for the
opportunity to scoop up a piece of history at Sunday's
everything-must-go auction at the historic Chasen's restaurant in
West Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   Buyers, some motivated by personal nostalgia and others by
collector's savvy, paid from $10 to thousands for furniture,
photos, and dinnerware at the restaurant that served as a haunt for
movie stars for decades before closing in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Collector Dennis Vacca, who owns Authentic Autographs and
Photos, called the auction ``one of the most important of the
year'' for his business.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to walk out of here today with as many of these
priceless things as I can,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Others were at the auction to pick up items out of pure
nostalgia, including former 20th Century Fox President Harris
Katleman, who said some of the photos had sentimental value for
him.
</P>
<P>
   Out of dozens of photos and letters framed in the historic
restaurant, some fared better than others at the auction block.
</P>
<P>
   A 14-by-17-inch autographed photo of Clark Gable drew $825,
while others went for as low as $10.
</P>
<P>
   Other items for sale included the favorite booths of such actors
as Jimmy Stewart, Humphrey Bogart, Jack Nicholson, Alfred
Hitchcock, Anthony Quinn and Ronald Reagan.
</P>
<P>
   In the Ronald Reagan booth, which was set aside for his
presidential library in Simi Valley, the former president and film
actor reportedly proposed to his wife Nancy.
</P>
<P>
   The restaurant was a hot spot since 1936, when vaudeville comic
Dave Chasen opened a chili stand on Beverly Boulevard at the corner
of Doheny Drive. When Chasen died, his wife, Maude, kept the
restaurant going until its closure.
</P>
<P>
   Demolition of the restaurant will start next month, but part of
the restaurant will be preserved within the Bristol Farms market
going up in its place.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Esbrant, a longtime waiter at the restaurant took one last
look around Sunday during the auction.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hate to see the place close,'' he said, recalling the times
he served Jimmy Stewart, Jack Nicholson and Madonna.
</P>
<P>
   The place was so popular, he said, there was even a documentary
made during the three months before it closed in 1995 called ``Off
the Menu: the Final Days of Chasen's.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
