<SLUG> BC-BBN-VECSEY-COLUMN-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: THE METS TEND TO WIN THESE CLASSIC GAMES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs for rewriting throughout) (sw) 
 By GEORGE VECSEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ By the 10th inning, Mookie Wilson started having
flashbacks, that strange feeling that sometime in another life he
had witnessed a wild game like this.
</P>
<P>
   It is not very often that one classic ball game induces memories
of another classic ball game, but Mookie was onto something, and he
was not about to give up his train of thought.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were different, but they were the same,'' the Mets' first
base coach, a hero of an October 13 years ago, would decide later,
in the delirium of the Mets' 4-3 victory in 15 innings that
prolonged the National League Championship Series by at least
another game.
</P>
<P>
   The common denominator was that the Mets won. They also won on
Oct. 15, 1986, when they beat Houston, 8-7, to avoid an encounter
with their nemesis, Mike Scott, in a seventh game that never
happened. And they won on Sunday, to send the series back to
Atlanta and all those yawning seats. The seats were not empty in
Shea Stadium on Sunday. With all of New York holding on to their
Metrocards in anticipation of a Subway Series, the Mets fought for
their lives in a persistent drizzle. They held off disaster time
and again, but then again, this has been their style over this
exciting but turbulent season.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, the Mets limped into extra innings in a 2-2 tie.
Their catcher, Mike Piazza, and their third baseman, Robin Ventura,
were walking wounded. But Mookie had his memory of 1986, when the
Mets scored three times in the ninth inning just to get into
overtime.
</P>
<P>
   ``Somebody mentioned it on the bench,'' he said, but most of the
Mets are too young to have any framework for the cumulative
mystique that now sends the Mets soaring to Atlanta on their own
personal tail wind.
</P>
<P>
   He has been there. In the Astrodome in 1986, he and Lenny
Dykstra wound up playing the outfield at the same time as the Mets
scored in the 14th and the Astros scored in the 14th, and the Mets
scored three in the 16th and the Astros scored two before Jesse
Orosco (under a death threat by Keith Hernandez to throw his best
pitch) finally shut down the Astros.
</P>
<P>
   ``They scored, we scored, they scored, we scored, they scored,
we scored,'' Mookie recalled. ``This game had more pitching.
Different but the same.''
</P>
<P>
   He is too gracious to inject his own unforgettable at-bat in the
sixth game of the 1986 World Series when he managed to levitate
above a wild pitch as one run scored, and then tapped the grounder
through Bill Buckner's gnarled ankles that won the game.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe there is no connection from one decade to another, but
there is a gathering fascination to the way the Mets have endured
the intrigues and psychodramas of the Bobby Valentine regime and
came back from a seven-game slump in the final two weeks of the
season. Valentine added to his own troubles by volunteering the
observation that if the Mets did not get into the playoffs that he
``probably should not be back.'' It has been ``Perils of Pauline''
all along.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday was more of the same. With the season getting away,
Valentine called in Orel Hershiser, who 11 years ago terrorized the
Mets in the 1988 league series. His manager at the time, Tommy
Lasorda, loved to introduce Hershiser to the press as the Bulldog,
because of Hershiser's 1950s hall-monitor smile that belied the
existence of an inner bulldog.
</P>
<P>
   Hershiser, now 41, had a bulldog moment in the sixth when he had
to guard the plate as Ryan Klesko steamed home in a rundown. The
willowy senior citizen caught the toss from Ventura as Klesko came
in standing up, throwing an elbow sideways, not dirty, but hard.
Hershiser planted the ball in his glove, braced both hands
together, and made the tag. The Bulldog held on. The Mets went on.
Something was happening on this damp day in Flushing. Mookie had
seen things like this 13 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   So did the fanatics who stayed for all of this long, wet
evening. Many of them had witnessed the 1969 miracle and the 1986
comeback.
</P>
<P>
   Ask Shawon Dunston about that. He's from Brooklyn, and he
understands the psyche of the Shea Stadium crowd.
</P>
<P>
   Dunston had not been able to catch a triple by Keith Lockhart
that put the Braves ahead in the top of the 15th.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I came running in after the inning, the fans were
screaming positive things,'' Dunston said. ``It was great.''
</P>
<P>
   Dunston promptly produced one of the great at-bats since Mookie
stood in against Bob Stanley in the desperate moments of 1986.
Dunston worked Kevin McGlinchy until he could slap a single up the
middle. Then he stole second, setting in motion the bases-loaded
walk to Todd Pratt and the wallop over the wall by the hobbling
Ventura that won the game.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets mobbed Ventura between first and second, so he lost a
grand slam and three runs batted in.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had enough,'' Ventura would decide.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets have not had enough. They now go to Atlanta for a sixth
game. Mookie has seen a couple of them in his time.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been playing like this for two weeks,'' Mookie said in
the frantic clubhouse. ``This is what we've been doing. I see no
reason why it can't continue.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
