<SLUG> BC-BBA-ALCS-TEX </SLUG>
 
Red Sox's blunder aids Yankees 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
BOSTON _ It might be February before Boston's Bret Saberhagen
covers first base again, and it will be a winter of torment for the
35-year-old pitcher should the Red Sox lose this American League
Championship Series. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Saberhagen and Mike Stanley butchered one of baseball's
fundamental plays involving the pitcher and first baseman on a
ground ball hit to the right side of the infield, and the New York
Yankees escaped Fenway Park with a 9-2 victory during Game 4 of
this best-of-seven series. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The outcome leaves the Yankees one victory shy of their 36th
World Series appearance and the Red Sox on the brink of elimination
after unraveling defensively during the fourth and ninth innings. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Controversial calls during the final two innings by second-base
umpire Tim Tschida and first-base umpire Dale Scott _ both of which
went against the Red Sox _ sent spectators at Fenway Park into an
uproar. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Spectators littered the field with objects thrown from the
stands after Scott ejected Red Sox manager Jimy Williams, who
argued that shortstop Nomar Garciaparra reached safely on a
ninth-inning ground ball. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's inexcusable,'' Yankees manager Joe Torre said of
the spectators' actions. ``To have people throw stuff on the field,
that's disgraceful. I know it's not an indication of Boston,
Massachusetts. Tonight was a bad mark against a very good team.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Crew chief Rick Reed stopped play at 11:16 p.m. ET and removed
both teams from the field. The hooliganism forced an eight-minute
delay before play resumed, and Yankees closer Mariano Rivera
recorded the final two outs to put an end to an ugly sight. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Williams and his players refused to attend the postgame media
conference, and the Red Sox manager issued only a one-sentence
statement that read: ``It's the first one to win four, and it's not
over yet.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Tschida blew a call with the Red Sox trailing, 3-2, with one out
during the eighth inning, but Boston's Jose Offerman reached on a
one-out single. Red Sox third baseman John Valentin then hit a
ground ball to Yankees second baseman Chuck Knoblauch, who
attempted to tag Offerman between first and second before throwing
to first to complete a double play. Replays, though, revealed that
Knoblauch never tagged Offerman. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I got the best position I could on that play,'' Tschida said.
``It's very difficult to get the angle you want without getting in
the way of the play.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Tschida's position forced him to ``look through the runner'' and
make his call based on the players' reactions, he said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``It appeared to me that he got him,'' Tschida said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Tschida saw a replay afterward, though, and said, ``No, I didn't
make the right call.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Boston took a 2-1 lead into the fourth inning on the strength of
a run-scoring, third-inning single by second baseman Offerman, but
it would be the only advantage the Red Sox experienced before
imploding in the field. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Yankees center fielder Bernie Williams reached safely on a
one-out infield single and advanced to second on the throwing error
by shortstop Nomar Garciaparra. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   First baseman Tino Martinez delivered a game-tying double on the
next at-bat and scored what proved to be the winning run minutes
later. Saberhagen issued an intentional walk to the
left-handed-hitting Darryl Strawberry with first base open before
retiring third baseman Scott Brosius on strikes for the inning's
second out. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Saberhagen then induced what appeared to be an inning-ending
ground ball from left fielder Chad Curtis. Stanley fielded the ball
cleanly, but Saberhagen could not handle the first baseman's
knee-high throw at first. Martinez scored from second on the play
with the second of two unearned runs during the inning. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees erupted again during the ninth after Offerman failed
to start what appeared to be an inning-ending, double-play ground
ball. The Yankees took advantage of Offerman's throwing error and
parlayed it into a six-run inning. Pinch-hitter Ricky Ledee
finished the carnage with his one-out grand slam off right-hander
Rod Beck. &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
