<HEADER>
A0051 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-FBN--COWBOYS-HNS &LR;      10-18 0605
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN--COWBOYS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JODY GOLDSTEIN  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ The New York Giants are glad they won't see
Dallas receiver Michael Irvin tonight. But they probably would be
more pleased if running back Emmitt Smith were out of the lineup.
<TEXT>
<P>
   By all indications, Smith will have a big night when the Giants
and Cowboys meet on Monday Night Football. That Irvin is out
indefinitely with a spine injury only makes Smith's job that much
more important. And he thrives under pressure.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants learned that last year. Smith carried the ball 29
times for 163 yards the last time the teams met. It was Smith's
best rushing performance in his last 60 regular-season games,
leading the Cowboys to a 16-6 victory at Texas Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're still good,'' Giants defensive end Michael Strahan
said. ``They're better with Michael Irvin, don't get me wrong. But
without him, they are still a good offense. The key is stopping the
running game, and with Dallas that means Emmitt.''
</P>
<P>
   That's something teams have been unable to do this season. The
Cowboys (3-1) have the NFC's No. 1 ground attack, thanks to Smith's
three 100-yard performances in the Cowboys' four games. Smith needs
only 25 yards to rush for 13,000 in his career. Barring injury, he
should hit that milestone in the first half tonight, becoming only
the fourth NFL player to reach that mark.
</P>
<P>
   Of Smith's 12,975 rushing yards, 1,541 have come against the
Giants, including seven 100-yard games. Not surprisingly, the
Giants (2-3) will try to stop the run first, then take their
chances with quarterback Troy Aikman's arm.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're not one-dimensional,'' safety Percy Ellsworth said.
``We can hold Emmitt to 60-some-odd yards and still lose because
Troy can throw for 300. But we have to at least get them to the
point where we know they will pass and then see how we match up.
We're a solid group in the secondary, so if we can stop the run and
force them to pass, we should have some success.''
</P>
<P>
   Particularly without Irvin. The Cowboys are confident Ernie
Mills, Wane McGarity and Jeff Ogden can fill in adequately during
Irvin's absence. But clearly, a Rocket Ismail-Mills tandem doesn't
instill in defenses the same respect Ismail-Irvin brought.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have confidence in the guys that are going to be in there,''
Cowboys coach Chan Gailey said. ``But at the same time, any time
you lose a player of Michael's stature you lose something off your
football team. It will have an impact. How much of an impact
remains to be seen.''
</P>
<P>
   Just as important will be how the Dallas defense fares against
the woeful New York offense. The Cowboys have surrendered only
three touchdowns in their last 13 quarters (plus overtime of the
Washington game) and have allowed only one touchdown per game in
their last three contests.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants have scored only six offensive touchdowns in five
games. Their biggest problem has come on third down, where they
rank 29th after converting only 18 of 70 opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   The defense has kept the Giants in games, only to end up losing
because the offense can't find the end zone. It has been enough to
reportedly cause problems between the offensive and defensive
players.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's tough,'' defensive tackle Keith Hamilton said. ``I don't
coach the offense, so I don't know what the solution is. I know
something has to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   The stats say it won't happen tonight. The Cowboys have
dominated the series, 46 wins to the Giants' 25 (with two ties).
The Cowboys are 6-0 against the Giants on Monday Night Football. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-18-99 0108EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991018.0030 </DOCNO>
