<HEADER>
A0055 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BBN--ROBERTSON-HNS &LR;      10-18 0820
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN--ROBERTSON-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
DaleRobertson
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
NEW YORK _ The Braves and the Mets are no strangers to games such
as these, and both had a track record for winning them.
</P>
<P>
   Just ask the Astros.
</P>
<P>
   But something had to give, and ultimately it would be both kids.
The Mets' star of tomorrow, Octavio Dotel, who found himself on the
spot Sunday, blinked first. Then Atlanta's alleged next great arm,
Kevin McGlinchy, blinked worse.
</P>
<P>
   Dotel, 23, surrendered the would-be losing run in the top of the
15th inning of the longest postseason game _ 5 hours, 46 minutes _
in baseball's very long history. But McGlinchy, 22, subsequently
walked home the tying run in the bottom of the 15th, then
surrendered the longest game-winning single in baseball's very long
history to Robin Ventura.
</P>
<P>
   Ventura's shot cleared the fence in right field, but because he
never bothered to finish running around the bases with all hell
breaking loose, what he did went into the scorebook as a single.
</P>
<P>
   It was that kind of game, one that went on and on and on in an
irritating drizzle and one that neither side appeared to want to
win, given what was either one of the greatest playoff pitching
displays on record or the sorriest example of clutch hitting
imaginable. The Mets' 4-3 (7-3) win has been certified a classic,
but that's more for its quantity than its quality.
</P>
<P>
   In a word, the affair was exhausting. Way more exhausting even
than Game 6 of the 1986 NLCS, when the Mets needed 4 hours, 42
minutes to eliminate the Astros in 16 innings 7-6.
</P>
<P>
   Game 4 of the ALCS in Boston, which started 3{ hours later, was
in the seventh inning by the time Roger Cedeno danced across the
plate to put the Mets on a chartered flight back to Dixie for Game
6 on Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Shawon Dunston, who had walked leading off for the Mets after
fouling off five full-count pitches and clearly flustered young
McGlinchy, must be allowed to share the hero's honors with Ventura,
heretofore a complete bust in the NLCS. After going 0-for-16, he
was Robin as in stealin' the Mets money.
</P>
<P>
   But, likewise, McGlinchy must not be made to stand alone in the
fall-guy department. That old codger in the dugout, the most
experienced postseason manager ever, deserves co-goat honors for
leaving McGlinchy in a situation he wasn't up to handling.
</P>
<P>
   Bobby Cox's only viable defense for not yanking McGlinchy was
Atlanta's obvious sense of urgency. The Braves, who once led the
series 3-0 and still lead it 3-2, have two more second chances. Cox
had not hesitated to pitch his fabled starters in relief, so why
wasn't Kevin Millwood, warming up, called upon to save the day?
</P>
<P>
   Guess Cox was trying to assure his boss, Ted Turner, of an extra
home gate.
</P>
<P>
   But in light of the Braves' history of blowing up this time of
year, Cox would have been better served to drive a stake through
the Mets' huge hearts right here and right now. If anybody can
become the first club in baseball's very long history to cough up a
3-0 lead, you suspect it might be the Atlantans.
</P>
<P>
   Cox's beleaguered counterpart, the ever-popular Bobby Valentine,
called New York's victory, and particularly Ventura's surprising
role in same, ``poetic justice,'' although he probably had no idea
how accurate an assessment that was.
</P>
<P>
   Remember how Cox won the 12-inning Division Series Game 3 beauty
against the Astros, an instant classic in its own right? Sure you
do. The Astros had the bases loaded in the 10th with one out and
Tony Eusebio at bat. Cox inexplicably pulled in his middle infield
instead of playing for the inning-ending double play, which put
Walt Weiss in the right spot to snare a shot and get the forceout
at home.
</P>
<P>
   Cox, then, deserved exactly what he got from the Amazins, whose
season has had several ``endings'' wiped from its script. When a
Todd Pratt keeps coming up big, you suspect a higher force at work.
</P>
<P>
   Pratt, a journeyman catcher who has been in organized ball for
15 years with just 610 major-league at-bats to show for his
patience, beat Arizona in extra innings with a home run. This
night, it was his walk that forced in Dunston and set the stage for
Ventura to finally _ well, awrighty then _ act like an ace.
</P>
<P>
   If you are the Braves, though, you can argue that it should not
have come down to a boy-wonder pitcher being in the wrong place at
the wrong time. From Brian Jordan's tying RBI single in the fourth,
which scored Chipper Jones after he had doubled in Bret Boone _
through Keith Lockhart's triple in the 15th that plated Weiss,
Atlanta went an embarrassing 0-for-14 with men in scoring position.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves would leave 19 stranded. They would botch decent to
excellent chances to break the stubborn deadlock in the sixth,
seventh, eighth, 10th, 11th and 13th innings.
</P>
<P>
   But of course. They are the Braves, and, yes, it is October.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
