<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-18 01:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0057 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBN-RHODEN-COLUMN-1ST     10-18 0771
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-RHODEN-COLUMN-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: FOR A HURTING PIAZZA, WINNING'S THE ONLY THING
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs for rewriting throughout)   (sw) 
 By WILLIAM C. RHODEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It was well into the evening after the longest game
in post-season history, and Mike Piazza was the last Met to come
out of training room and join the interviews. Shawon Dunston had a
cluster on the other side talking about his great at-bat in the
15th inning. Robin Ventura, who like Piazza had had a woeful series
until the 15th, was now mobbed by cameras and talking about his
miraculous game-winning run batted in.
</P>
<P>
   Finally Piazza emerged. The Mets' battered catcher, in a span of
48 hours, had been bowled over, run over, hit on a backswing by two
different batters on the same spot on two different days. He came
to his stall not quite oblivious to the swirl of excitement in the
Mets clubhouse but with arms, legs and torso ensconced in a world
of pain that seems peculiar to catchers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest thing for me are my hands,'' he said. ``When I'm
constantly getting injuries to fingers wrists and forearms, it
comes to a point when you hit the throttle and there's nothing
there. But the bottom line is to do anything I can to help this
ball club win. We're finding ways to do it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're all beat up, not just me. There's a lot of guys who are
sore, but we go out and give it all we have. Guys have 90 percent
and they're giving 100 percent. We keep pushing the dirt off us;
everyone's trying to put us under.''
</P>
<P>
   Piazza said he had jokingly told the trainer to ``give me some
heart tablets'' for the excitement.
</P>
<P>
   In the 15th inning, Piazza said he was praying. ``That's what
it's come to,'' he said. ``You should pray all the time, but now
it's like, do You have a win up there for us?''
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday night there was a miracle, though Piazza was on the
fringes of it. Piazza was forced to leave Game 5 in the 14th inning
with a strained left forearm. He was injured on a play at the plate
in the 13th inning, when he tagged out the 170-pound Keith Lockhart
trying to score from first on a double by Chipper Jones. Piazza
applied the tag but paid the price when Lockhart collided with him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chipper hit the ball hard _ Larry, Chipper, not sure what to
call him,'' Piazza said. ``When I saw that third base coach waving
him in, I knew he was coming.''
</P>
<P>
   He stayed in the game for the bottom half of the inning, when he
struck out against John Rocker, and then left the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I took the last swing and I just told Bobby I couldn't go,''
Piazza said, referring to his manager, Bobby Valentine. ``There
comes a line that you cross where your heart wants to go out there,
but you might be a detriment to the team if you do. We have so many
capable guys coming off the bench and doing the job, and everybody
feels a part of this team.''
</P>
<P>
   The forearm was the latest. Piazza missed the last two games of
the division series against Arizona with a sprained and swollen
left thumb. In Game 3 of the current series on Friday, Piazza
sustained a mild concussion in a collision when he tagged out Bret
Boone bearing down on home plate attempting to score.
</P>
<P>
   Al Leiter, whose dressing stall is next to Piazza's, has watched
in amazement at the punishment the 31-year-old catcher has taken.
``There's some little part of you that feels sorry for the guy,''
he said. ``He gets banged up every game. He's not a guy who takes
days off during the year.''
</P>
<P>
   Someone brought up Piazza's $91 million package the Mets
rewarded him with during the off season. ``I don't feel that sorry
for him,'' Leiter said, smiling. ``He's still doing all right and
he's got a pretty good living.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mets have a pretty good living, too. Living for another game
in Georgia, with their tank of a catcher, Piazza, emboldened for
more. ``No matter what happens from here on out it's a great
feeling knowing we were down 3-0 and now we have a chance to tie
the series,'' Piazza said. ``Those guys have been through the wars
before, but now maybe there's a little bit of pressure on them.''
</P>
<P>
   The larger issue for another day is how long the Mets can afford
to keep Piazza behind the plate, taking the pounding, the abuse,
the wear and tear that eventually might diminish the offensive
capacity that made the Mets pay so many millions for his services.
For the next week, at least, that's irrelevant.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now we're pulling out all the stops,'' Piazza said.
``We're just flying by the seats of out pants, and it doesn't
matter whose doing it just so long that someone's doing it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
