<HEADLINE>
GALAXY TAKES SERIES LEAD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED J. ROBLEDO  
 c.1999 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ With his arms wrapped tight at the end of the
Los Angeles Galaxy bench, the frustrated glare on Sigi Schmid's
face was understandable, considering the situation in which his
team found itself.
</P>
<P>
   With the home team up 1-0 early over Colorado, midfielder Simon
Elliot drew his second caution of the game in the 18th minute,
sending him off the pitch and forcing his team to play more than
half the match with a man down.
</P>
<P>
   But as Elliot worked in the weight room to vent his frustration,
the Galaxy outhustled and outplayed Colorado with its best
collective effort of the season, walking away with a 3-0 victory in
front of 16,307 at the Rose Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   The shutout extended the Rapid's scoreless streak to 589 minutes
and gave Los Angeles a 1-0 lead in the best-of-three Western
Conference semifinal series. Game 2 is set for Sunday at Mile High
Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Elliot, who watched the rest of the match on a 13-inch
television, stood at the end of the tunnel as his team walked off.
He received a hug from defender Paul Caligiuri and another from
Robert Fraser. Then came Schmid, who locked his arms around the
Canadian International as well.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the team felt for Elliot, whose penalty for an
innocent-looking tackle on Colorado's Marcelo Balboa seemed more
like a Balboa con job than a cautionable offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm the happiest man at the moment because I thought I let
everyone down,'' said an emotional Elliot, who will miss Game 2
because of the ejection. ``I think the referee should have realized
it wasn't a foul at all. But it was brilliant the way the boys
responded.''
</P>
<P>
   Schmid, who has done his share of arguing with the officials,
refrained from getting involved.
</P>
<P>
   ``I reserve all comments on the referee tonight,'' Schmid said.
``Normally when a person gets red-carded, I'm usually upset with
that player because it's usually a dumb foul.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I can't be upset with Simon. There were other fouls on the
field that were comparable to the one he's committed.''
</P>
<P>
   Second-half goals from Cobi Jones and Greg Vanney sealed the
victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``That s lot of hard work, to play with 10 men for seventy
minutes,'' Schmid said. ``So I couldn't be prouder than I was
tonight. The effort they put in, especially the second half, was
flat-out superb.''
</P>
<P>
   Midfield playmaker Mauricio Cienfuegos played a brilliant ball
wide to defender Ezra Hendrickson in the eighth minute. Two steps
into the penalty area, Hendrickson beat Colorado goalkeeper Ian
Feuer to the far left for a 1-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Vanney gave the Galaxy a 2-0 lead on a penalty kick in the 52nd
minute. Jones, scoring the first postseaon goal of his career, gave
the Galaxy the 3-0 cushion in the 57th minute.
</P>
<P>
   ``What a total team effort,'' said defender Danny Pena. ``It
looked like it would be a rough time after Simon got ejected, but
we came out in the second half and told ourselves it would take
everything we had and to leave it on the field. I can't tell you
how proud I am of these guys. This was a guts-win. This is what
it's all about in the playoffs.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-18-99 0123EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991018.0036 </DOCNO>
