<HEADER>
A0065 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-DOLPHINS     10-18 1130
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-DOLPHINS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOLPHINS EDGE PATRIOTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ Drew Bledsoe sat on the bench near his
locker, his head buried in his hands, devastated by yet another
late-game loss. In many ways this one, Sunday's 31-30 defeat to the
Miami Dolphins, hurt much more. This was one of those divisional
matchups, an arm-wrestling match if you will, for supremacy in the
AFC East. And the Dolphins had played without Dan Marino (right
trapezius spasms) for the final 3 1/2 quarters.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Bledsoe's ``electric'' offense was on the field for
only 19:53. The Patriots made only 14 first downs, converted only 2
of 11 third-down conversions, ran for only 46 yards, and did not
complete a pass to Terry Glenn. Their fatigued defense, which spent
40:07 on the field (and scored two touchdowns), watched almost
helplessly as backup quarterback Damon Huard picked them apart with
a 59-yard drive on 14 plays in the final 2:10. When backup fullback
Stanley Pritchett caught a 5-yard touchdown pass on the left side
away from Larry Whigham, the Patriots were sent into shock.
</P>
<P>
   A quiet crowd of 60,006 _ five more than Marino has career
passing yards _ was even more stunned. The Patriots, who were
heading to 5-1, now find themselves 4-2, in a second-place tie with
Buffalo.
</P>
<P>
   ``When your defense scores twice, there's no way you should lose
a ballgame,'' said Bledsoe. ``They came out and spotted us 14
points and then offensively we can't put up enough, or hold the
ball long enough, to come away with a victory. And that never
should have happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Never.
</P>
<P>
   Like there's no mistaking his hits, there was no mistaking
Lawyer Milloy's anger after the game, fingering his teammates and
the fans for a lackluster effort.
</P>
<P>
   ``Toward the end of the game I look on our sidelines and all the
people on the bench on offense, special teams players, and even
defensive guys in the huddle, just looked like they were going
through the motions. Our fans weren't into it. It was pretty dead
out there,'' Milloy said. ``The whole atmosphere wasn't a
championship-caliber atmosphere all around. It really made me sick
to my stomach. Other teams aren't supposed to be able to make
checks at the line. Our fans are noted as some of the craziest
fans. Maybe they were upset because of the way we were playing.''
</P>
<P>
   Willie McGinest had led a defensive assault against Huard that
produced nine sacks, one short of the Patriots' record and the most
sacks ever recorded against the Dolphins. Yet McGinest said the end
of the game made him ``sick to my stomach.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what to say. I need to get better, make more
plays, cause more turnovers,'' he said. ``I'm not going to go bitch
at the offense for what they're doing over there. It's not their
fault. We win as a team and lose as a team. We have to look at what
we do individually. Are you doing your job? Are you creating
pressure? Are you stopping the run? We need to look at each other
and say, `Pick it up, start fast, and finish strong.' What's
frustrating is we lose two games by 2 points. The good teams, the
championship teams, the ones that go to the Super Bowls and win
divisions, they finish games. They do what they're supposed to
do.''
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots lost for a number of other reasons besides lack of
offense. For one, losing six players to injuries on special teams
caused huge field position problems that enabled Miami kicker
Olindo Mare to boot six field goals.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots were playing what some Dolphin players considered a
very intricate version of a zone blitz defense on third down,
making it difficult for the Dolphins to read. But for some reason
on the final drive, the Patriots went to four down linemen and
changed their defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were bringing guys into different gaps and different
angles and it was very difficult to have to make a read in a split
second,'' said Dolphins right guard Kevin Donnalley. ``You think
you're making the right read and all of a sudden your guy drops
back and someone else is rushing at you and you have no time to
pick him up. On the last drive we saw a lot of four-man line. When
they do that, everything becomes clearer. It's as if the clouds
part.''
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots got two great interception returns for touchdowns
in the first quarter. At 12:06, Milloy stormed in and hit Marino as
he threw a dying quail into the middle of the field that rookie
linebacker Andy Katzenmoyer picked off and ran 57 yards for a
touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   Two series later, on Huard's first pass, more pressure forced a
bad throw intended for Tony Martin that Ty Law picked off. He
returned it 27 yards for a 14-0 lead at 8:04.
</P>
<P>
   But the Patriots couldn't stand prosperity, allowing the
Dolphins a couple of Mare field goals and a 69-yard touchdown pass
from Huard to Martin. As Huard scrambled, Martin put a huge fake on
Chris Carter and got wide open to make it 14-13 at 7:48 of the
second.
</P>
<P>
   Huard, who completed 24 of 42 passes for 240 yards and two TDs,
impressed all with his scrambling ability (6 carries, 54 yards).
</P>
<P>
   Milloy, who played with Huard at the University of Washington,
said, ``I was surprised he was as mobile as he was, because in
college he wasn't. He showed a tremendous amount of poise. I played
with him two or three years and I never saw him move around like
that.''
</P>
<P>
   After Adam Vinatieri and Mare exchanged field goals, the
Patriots opened up a 24-16 lead on Bledsoe's 29-yard touchdown pass
to Tony Simmons with 23 seconds to play in the half. The young
receiver did just enough pushing off not to get caught and create
enough separation from corner Sam Madison. The 80-yard drive
featured throws to Shawn Jefferson and Vincent Brisby down the
field.
</P>
<P>
   A delay penalty, a short kickoff in a strong wind to the 24, and
a 19-yard return by J.J. Johnson got Miami started at the 43. After
Huard scrambled 25 yards to the Patriots' 27, Mare hit a 45-yard
field goal to make it 25-19 at the half.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots extended their lead to 8 points twice, 27-19 and
then 30-22, but couldn't do what good teams do at the end: work on
the clock.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots' three-and-out offense enabled Mare to hit a
53-yarder to make it 30-25 with 2:45 remaining. But even at that
point, the Patriots couldn't keep the ball.
</P>
<P>
   On a third and 9 from their 21, Bledsoe threw it to Ben Coates,
who dropped it. After Lee Johnson's punt, Miami moved the ball with
short passes to Pritchett _ six of them during the drive _
including the winner.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots got the ball back with 23 seconds left, and after a
21-yard pass to Jefferson, the Patriots simply ran out of time.
</P>
<P>
   Ending with Bledsoe's face buried in his hands.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
