<SLUG> BC-SOC-GALNOTE-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HERMOSILLO SITS, WILL BE READY NEXT WEEK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED J. ROBLEDO  
 c.1999 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ Los Angeles Galaxy striker Carlos Hermosillo
sat in the press box in street clothes during the Galaxy's 3-0
victory over Colorado on Sunday at the Rose Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   The 35-year-old warrior bruised his left knee in the season
finale at Kansas City last week, but a week of treatment wasn't
enough to convince Galaxy coach Sigi Schmid to give him the start.
</P>
<P>
   ``His knee responded fairly well, but there is still some
swelling that gave us a concern,'' Schmid said of Hermosillo. ``We
expect him to be able to play by next weekend, that was the reason
for not playing him tonight. If we tried to play him tonight, he
would have been less effective next week.''
</P>
<P>
   With Hermosillo back, Clint Mathis will move from up front to
right midfield. He will replace Simon Elliott, who received a red
card in the 18th minute for a tackle on Colorado's Marcelo Balboa.
League rules mandate Elliott must sit out the next game.
</P>
<P>
   __ Hartman shines: Schmid wanted to make sure goalkeeper Kevin
Hartman's performance wasn't overlooked. Hartman, who led the MLS
in nearly every statistical category, made two acrobatic one-on-one
saves in the first half.
</P>
<P>
   Colorado's Jorge Del Valdes broke free, but his shot to the far
post from 10 yards out was knocked away by Hartman. And midfielder
Paul Bravo sneaked behind two Galaxy defenders, but again Hartman
came up with the big save.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our theme tonight was faith and patience and it was tested on
a lot of fronts,'' Schmid said. ``Hartman said he wants no more
faith games, but what he does is more than just faith.
</P>
<P>
   ``Playing in this league, teams are going to get chances and
Colorado got a couple that could have turned the game. But Hartman
showed why he is one of the best in this league. He made some
brilliant saves when we absolutely needed them.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Columbus wins opener: Stern John scored two goals in a
seven-minute span and host Columbus beat Tampa Bay 2-0 in the first
game of the best-of-three MLS Eastern Conference semifinals.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
