u s BC-FBN-MCDONOUGHCOLUMN-B     10-18 0908
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-MCDONOUGH </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MIAMI HAD WIND BENEATH WINGS 
</HEADLINE>
 COLUMN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILL MCDONOUGH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ This happened before Sunday's game ever
started.
</P>
<P>
   Jimmy Johnson walked to the middle of the Dolphins' locker room
and delivered his state-of-the-moment address.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are going to win this game in the fourth quarter. Hang in
there. No matter what, we're going to have the wind in the fourth
quarter and that's when we're going after it,'' the Miami coach
said.
</P>
<P>
   Three hours later, Johnson was a prophet. His team, against
great odds, stunned the Patriots, 31-30, with a remarkable display
of courage and tenacity.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been telling people for two years that this (Damon) Huard
kid is a good quarterback. They didn't believe me. He showed today
what he can do,'' Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   Huard, kicker Olindo Mare, and the Miami defense comprised the
trifecta the Patriots, in the end, could not deal with Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Huard, battered and belted around the field by the Patriots'
aggressive defense, ran an offense that kept the ball for an
incredible 86 offensive plays, and 40:07 on the clock.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Dolphin defense gave up just 16 points, and did
something no one else has been able to do this year, shut out Terry
Glenn, the NFL's leading receiver.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sam Madison did the job for us on Glenn,'' said Johnson later.
``Whenever we could, Sam took his man. If Glenn went to the slot,
then we gave Sam some help, but it was mostly Sam.''
</P>
<P>
   During the week, Dan Marino came up with a sore trapezius. He
couldn't throw in practice Thursday or Friday. He received a shot
before the game, trying to relax the muscle that was in spasm.
Marino warmed up poorly. He had a hard time throwing the ball 15
yards. But he decided to give it a try.
</P>
<P>
   The Dolphins had the wind in the first period, and got the ball
first. On Marino's second pass, with Lawyer Milloy blitzing off the
corner, he tried to throw the ball away and couldn't. Marino didn't
have enough arm strength to get it out of bounds, and Andy
Katzenmoyer had a gift touchdown via a 57-yard interception return.
</P>
<P>
   ``After the second series, Dan came out and told Jimmy he was a
liability,'' said Dolphin line coach Paul Boudreau. ``Dan didn't
make the throws and he was concerned going into the wind in the
second period he wouldn't be effective.''
</P>
<P>
   Enter Huard, who threw an interception on his first throw for
another New England touchdown, this time by Ty Law, to fall behind,
14-0, at 8:04 of the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just stuck with what we wanted to do,'' said Johnson,
indicating that his team wasn't about to panic. ``We were confident
in what we wanted to do. I told our guys if we stopped turning the
ball over, we could come back to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Huard was in a tough spot. The Dolphins were missing their two
best offensive linemen, Mark Dixon and Richmond Webb, for most of
the game. Their starting fullback, Rob Konrad, went out early with
a leg injury.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots' defense turned up the heat. ``We knew they would
start blitzing every chance they could,'' said Boudreau. ``They
wouldn't try that with Dan because they know how fast he can get
rid of the ball, but with this kid they knew they had a chance to
get him.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dolphins had given up just two sacks in the four previous
games. They gave up nine in this one, and Huard was knocked down
another dozen times.
</P>
<P>
   Huard had a total of 23 third- and fourth-down situations, and
converted 11 of them into first downs to keep the clock, and the
chains, moving. Conversely, Drew Bledsoe and the Patriots offense
converted just 2 of 11 third-down situations. When it was over, the
Dolphins had the ball for two out of every three minutes in the
game.
</P>
<P>
   Mare, the Miami kicker, was magnificent. He converted all six of
his field goals, in a windy stadium. Without him, the Dolphins
didn't have a chance.
</P>
<P>
   But Huard was the man of the hour. He was in a very hostile
environment. He had a hard time changing plays because of the crowd
noise, and the rookie backs behind him who wouldn't know how to
make the adjustments.
</P>
<P>
   He had to stand there and take the heat when the Patriots
brought it, and he burned them in the end with a final touchdown
drive. Four times he had third-down, must-make situations, and he
made them, including the final touchdown toss to fullback Stanley
Pritchett.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson explained the play: ``We went into the shotgun.
Pritchett came in motion across the formation (right to left). We
had a slot to the left with two receivers, and at the snap, both of
them went straight downfield. Pritchett kept on coming and went
right into the flat. It was difficult for someone (Larry Whigham)
to cover him from the end side.''
</P>
<P>
   When the ball was snapped, and the two Miami wideouts to that
side went straight downfield, Whigham got caught up in traffic, and
Pritchett came wide open in the left flat to make the catch.
</P>
<P>
   After the game, Johnson gave the ball to Boudreau, who was New
England's offensive line coach the previous two years. He was fired
last year as a fall guy for the Patriots' failures, and Johnson
hired him two days later.
</P>
<P>
   ``Paul's a great coach. I'm really happy he's with us,'' Johnson
said.
</P>
<P>
   Boudreau gave the game ball to his wife, Joan.
</P>
<P>
   ``She went through a lot when I got fired,'' said Boudreau, ``so
this is going to her.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-18-99 0127EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
