u s BC-HKN-BRUINS-BOS &LR;      10-18 1103
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRUINS ON THIN ICE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY MARRAPESE-BURRELL  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SCOTTSDALE, Ariz. _ Ugh.
</P>
<P>
   As in ug-ly.
</P>
<P>
   That's what the Bruins' first eight games have been. The club,
which had Sunday off, is off to its worst start in 35 years with a
record of 0-5-3. The morale, which before Saturday's 2-1 loss to
the Phoenix Coyotes had been pretty upbeat, has taken a decided
turn for the worse.
</P>
<P>
   The team chemistry is off, the execution is spotty, the
performances have been inconsistent (or in some cases nonexistent)
and there's a lack of desperation.
</P>
<P>
   There have been players-only meetings, players meetings with
coaches, one-on-one meetings between players and coach Pat Burns.
</P>
<P>
   When the bus arrived at the team hotel after the loss to
Phoenix, Bruins captain Ray Bourque, looking very unhappy, kept his
teammates for several minutes and addressed them. So far, no amount
of talking off the ice has translated to better play on the ice.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, when things have gone this badly, changes have been
made. There's been plenty of speculation president/general manager
Harry Sinden, who has been off hunting in Canada with Edmonton GM
Glen Sather, could be returning with more than a pelt or some
venison. It's possible Sinden could be returning to Boston with the
rights to disgruntled Oilers forward Bill Guerin, who is sitting
out in a contract dispute.
</P>
<P>
   Whether Sinden would part with unsigned, and equally unhappy,
goalie Byron Dafoe as part of a package remains to be seen, but
often when the Bruins have been in turmoil, the perceived problem
children have been shipped to Edmonton.
</P>
<P>
   Guerin, a Massachusetts native and Boston College product, has
asked to be traded. He is reportedly asking for $3.5 million a
year, but would agree to $3 million.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, back in Mudville, the Arizona sunshine belied the
fact the Bruins are living under a dark cloud. Ironically, the
goaltending, which everyone feared would be a disaster without
Dafoe, has been the steadiest part of the club's game. John Grahame
has been the better of the two netminders, though Rob Tallas
certainly hasn't played badly.
</P>
<P>
   The forwards are another story. Center Jason Allison, who is
nursing a sore right wrist, has been the team's best player
recently along with Joe Thornton and defenseman Kyle McLaren. Dave
Andreychuk has played well despite having to switch to the right
side from the left, where he's played his whole career. The
defensive line of P.J. Axelsson, Sean Pronger, and Rob DiMaio has
been the team's best combination. The defensive corps has been, if
not great, adequate.
</P>
<P>
   That leaves players such as Sergei Samsonov, Steve Heinze, and
Anson Carter _ all of whom have been subpar in all categories. No
Bruins were naming names after Saturday night's loss but all were
bitterly disappointed at the lack of team effort.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing is working for us,'' said McLaren, who was limping
Sunday as a result of a bruised knee. ``We have to go out there and
perform and if we're not performing, something has to be changed or
looked at. Certainly it's not the way we're being coached. Our
coaching is great, so that's not an issue at all. The effort is
there most nights. I don't think Pat's going to question that, but
it's the mental mistakes that are costing us right now. Coaches can
only do so much. It's us. We have to pick it up more, it comes from
inside. This game has a lot to do with your heart. You have to have
a big heart to play the game and mental toughness and if you don't
have that, you can't play here.''
</P>
<P>
   When the Bruins began the season, it was obvious the lack of
Dmitri Khristich's goal production would be missed and would only
be made up if each forward helped. So far, only a handful are
pitching in points.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to be going every night, every guy,'' said Allison.
</P>
<P>
   Allison said he expected there would be desperation with the
team still searching for a victory, but he said not enough of it
has been there.
</P>
<P>
   ``I certainly thought there was and (Saturday) it seemed like,
two games in two nights you're tired, but that's no excuse,'' said
Allison. ``That's garbage. You have to play better than that to win
games. Some guys were going, some weren't.''
</P>
<P>
   Allison said he expects to shoulder a good amount of the load,
but he said the rest of the forwards are needed as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who took the brunt of the blame when we weren't scoring last
year? Me and (Dmitri),'' he said. ``Those were the only two guys
who ever took it. And that's not the case on any team, especially
ours. We have a lot of guys who should be 20-goal scorers. If you
looked at the beginning of the year, you'd say, `We don't need
Dmitri because we've got these guys.' Well, these guys have
pressure on them now, they can't have nights off. It's easy to
point guys out like me or Dmitri if we had a bad game last year,
but wait until you're in those shoes and then you see it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a good team. We have lots of depth scoring-wise, but
we're not putting it together every night, every guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Allison said he wouldn't put any of the blame for the lack of
success on the fact Khristich is not here. He said that was a road
best not taken.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every paper in the country said that even though he had 30
goals, we're not going to miss a guy like that,'' said Allison.
``I'm not by any means going to use his being gone as an excuse as
to why we're not winning. That's not fair to anybody. We're not
going good. The guys who have to step it up aren't every night. He
was our go-to winger. (Andreychuk) has come in and played great.
Obviously if we had both, it would've been a better situation, but
that's management's decision. We can't sulk about it. We still have
a good club without him. It's hard for me to say we miss him
because it sounds like an excuse.''
</P>
<P>
   In the first few games, Allison was hampered by his ailing arm.
He's playing well now although he thinks he can be better, as can
everyone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not saying I'm playing my best either,'' he said. ``It's a
team game and the better I play, the better the team is going to
play, and the better the team plays, the better you're going to
play.
</P>
<P>
   ``I started slow and they stuck with me until I got going. There
were a lot of nights at the beginning where I wasn't playing well.
Now I've found my game and I'm playing a little bit better, but we
have to put it all together every night, every guy. It's not going
to happen every night with every guy but it's got to be close and
we're not close right now.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
