<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-ANALYSIS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DON'T PUT YOUR TRUST IN PATRIOTS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients) 
By RON BORGES 
c.1999 The Boston Globe 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ If you believe in the philosophy that you
are who you are and you're the Patriots, who you are is not a
comforting feeling this morning.
</P>
<P>
   Who these Patriots are is who they have been for more than two
years now. They are not unlike so many of those Red Sox teams that
have broken New England's hearts for generations. They are
magnificently talented but tragically flawed.
</P>
<P>
   They can pass the ball better than nearly any team in
Christendom, but they can't run through an empty lot. They can do
crushing things on defense, but when they need a stop, all systems
are go.
</P>
<P>
   They beat the teams they should beat, but not by as much as they
should. Thus they occasionally lose to them, usually at the worst
of times, which makes life difficult for them every January.
</P>
<P>
   They struggle with the teams who are nearly their equal or
better, and all too often lose to them, as they did again Sunday to
Miami, 31-30, after blowing a 14-point first-quarter lead that was
provided by their defense.
</P>
<P>
   They say they do not yet know who they are, but Sunday they
again showed you who they are if you care to look. They are a
two-games-above-.500 team capable of finishing one game better than
that or two games worse. They are who they are. They are a team
that is not to be trusted.
</P>
<P>
   They were 4-0 in September again this year, as they have been so
often lately. But when the leaves begin to disappear, so do these
Patriots. That has been as constant in New England as a
change-of-season cold.
</P>
<P>
   Their record might have been 4-0 but they were never truly a 4-0
team, as some people tried to warn you, because they were never
dominant when they should have been. Not once.
</P>
<P>
   They are the worker who does enough to get by, but not the one
who discovers the vaccine at 2 a.m. They are the worker who never
shows up late, but never stays late either. They are the lawyer who
gets all his paper work in on time, but never finds the flaw in his
opponent's legal argument at dawn.
</P>
<P>
   They are who they are. They are 4-2 and on their way to Lord
knows where because certainly they don't know. All they know is
that they've walked this way before and it is a road that doesn't
lead to Atlanta, where Super Bowl XXXIV will be played in January.
It is a road that leads to frustration and anger and occasional
moments of great elation and overconfidence instead.
</P>
<P>
   But to Atlanta? Not on the road they're on now.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've played three or four complete games since I've been
here,'' said a bitterly disappointed Lawyer Milloy after his
dog-tired defense allowed the Dolphins to beat them with a 5-yard
touchdown pass with only 23 seconds left to play Sunday. ``That's
why we haven't won a championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even giving our offense a 14-point lead without stepping on
the field (by returning two interceptions for touchdowns in the
first quarter) I never felt like we were in control. I never felt
like we were on top of them.''
</P>
<P>
   On top of the Dolphins they should have been, but Milloy was
right. These Patriots may be in the lead a lot, but they are never
on top of anybody. Not at the moment at least. Certainly not last
week against Kansas City, not Sunday against Miami, and seldom in
the four games they won before those two losses.
</P>
<P>
   The reasons why are obvious to point out, but apparently
difficult to fathom. They are like this because when they need to
play offense, they can't. And when they need to play defense, they
can't because they haven't been playing offense long enough all day
to give their defense a chance to hold on at the end.
</P>
<P>
   The last two weeks one of the NFL's allegedly best offenses has
scored an average of 15 points a game. Over the last month, that
same offense has averaged 16.2 points a game. Not once in those
games has it run the ball with even moderate efficiency, and as the
weather gets colder and wetter and windier that will not improve.
But the passing game that has gotten them those two touchdowns a
game will not be as efficient, as it was not Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Because of those problems, the defense has been on the field for
75 minutes and 44 seconds the last two Sundays. This is simply too
much to ask of the 1985 Bears and trust me, this defense is not the
1985 Bears.
</P>
<P>
   Predictably that defense let down late in each game, Sunday
allowing Miami backup quarterback Damon Huard to move his team 59
yards in 107 seconds to beat them with a 5-yard touchdown. It was a
pass he was able to throw only because tired defensive linemen
weren't quite able to throw him on the ground one more time.
</P>
<P>
   Nine sacks, two defensive touchdowns, two turnovers, and the
removal of Dan Marino before the first quarter was over should be
enough of a day's work for any defense, but Sunday it was not. A
week ago, holding the Kansas City Chiefs to 16 points was not
either.
</P>
<P>
   Conversely, on days the offense scored 31 and 30 points it was
barely enough to beat the New York Jets without their starting
quarterback or the Indianapolis Colts earlier in this odd season.
</P>
<P>
   So exactly who are these 4-2 Patriots? Exactly who they have
shown themselves to be for more than two years now.
</P>
<P>
   A team that can't be trusted.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
