<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-BOSTON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EAGLES' PENDULUM ON UPSWING 
</HEADLINE>
 COLLEGE-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL VEGA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Boston College coach Tom O'Brien was only half-kidding
when he joked Sunday, ``The easy part of the schedule is coming
up.''
</P>
<P>
   The comment came a day after his Eagles (5-1 overall, 2-1 Big
East) took a stirring 20-16 victory over Pittsburgh at Alumni
Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   BC's football team will now embark on the most perilous part of
its schedule, beginning Saturday with a visit from No. 23 Miami
(2-3, 0-0), which is vastly better than its record indicates. The
Hurricanes were off this weekend after postponing their contest
with Temple until Dec. 4 because of Hurricane Irene.
</P>
<P>
   The Eagles will wrap up the month by traveling to Syracuse Oct.
30. BC then concludes the season by hosting West Virginia (Nov.
13), and going to Notre Dame (Nov. 20), and (gulp) No. 4 Virginia
Tech (Nov. 26), which was a more-than-convincing 62-0 winner over
Syracuse.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the hard part of the schedule is over,'' O'Brien said,
before explaining why. ``To take this young football team and to
take them through the expectations that were put upon them _
everyone talking about them being 6-0 or 5-1 _ it was tough on this
football team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now we enter a phase where nobody gives us a chance to do
anything, and so we have nothing to lose and everything to gain.
All we have to do is just go out there and play relaxed football.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I know is that we're 5-1 and at this point we have a
chance to have a winning season. Hopefully, somewhere along the
way, we're going to knock somebody off and get that sixth
victory.''
</P>
<P>
   Although he tried to downplay it, BC's fifth victory was
significant for O'Brien. Not only did it mark BC's best start since
going 4-0-1 in 1992, it also ensured the coach that his team would
finish with an improved record over the 4-7 campaigns of the past
two seasons.
</P>
<P>
   So what did the Eagles show him this weekend?
</P>
<P>
   ``They showed tremendous heart and tremendous emotion in the
fact that they could play for 60 minutes,'' O'Brien said. ``It took
59 minutes to beat these guys, until we got the ball back there at
the end. But they were of the mindset that they were going to
refuse to lose the football game.''
</P>
<P>
   Tim Hasselbeck was held back for precautionary reasons because
of a mild right shoulder separation suffered in the 24-14 loss at
Temple Oct. 9. But the junior quarterback came off the bench with
10:17 remaining in the third quarter when starter Brian St. Pierre
was knocked out of the game.
</P>
<P>
   Hasselbeck completed 13 of 24 passes for 202 yards and twice
connected with wideout Dedrick Dewalt on touchdowns, including a
game-winning 36-yard strike with 1:48 left in the game.
</P>
<P>
   Suffice to say, Hasselbeck's wing was no worse for the wear.
``He still has to see the trainers,'' O'Brien said. ``But he came
out fine and he's going to be ready to go (against Miami). He'll be
fine.''
</P>
<P>
   St. Pierre, however, was another story. The redshirt freshman
from Danvers was taken to a local hospital, and later released,
after he suffered a concussion in a brutal helmet-to-helmet
collision with Pitt linebacker Amir Purifoy.
</P>
<P>
   ``(St. Pierre) watched practice today,'' O'Brien said. ``As he
said, his head cleared up and he feels pretty good, but he'll be
out until Wednesday's practice until we try to do anything with
him.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Brien reported junior running back Cedric Washington (sprained
right ankle) was still sore but is expected to be ready to play.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond that, O'Brien was buoyed by the team's overall play,
especially the defense that held Pittsburgh to 45 yards rushing. In
five red zone opportunities, the Eagles allowed only a touchdown,
three field goals, and blocked a field goal (by Jonathan Ordway).
</P>
<P>
   ``We got back basically to the way we were in the first couple
of games of the year,'' O'Brien said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
