<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-18 01:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0071 &Cx1f; tta-z
u s BC-BBA-YANKS-REDSOX-ART-     10-18 1327
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-REDSOX-ART-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEMPERS BOIL AS YANKEES DOWN RED SOX, 9-2
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs for rewriting throughout)   (ART ADV: Photos are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(sw) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The Yankees were within a couple of outs of wrapping up
a satisfying 9-2 victory over the Red Sox in Game 4 of the American
League Championship Series on Sunday night, when the heated rivalry
between the two sides boiled over.
</P>
<P>
   There was a domino effect. The frustrated Red Sox Manager Jimy
Williams vociferously argued a close call in the bottom of the
ninth, and after Williams was ejected, Fenway Park fans began
throwing bottles and other items on the field _ and the umpires
ordered the Yankees off the field for their own protection.
</P>
<P>
   But when they returned to their dugout, a security official
began screaming at them _ ``no show of class whatsover,'' Yankees
Manager Joe Torre said _ sparking a confrontation with the reliever
Jeff Nelson.
</P>
<P>
   After a delay of eight minutes, the Yankees returned to the
field and finished off the Red Sox, to take a 3-1 lead in the
four-of-seven-game series. Afterward, some Yankees were furious
with the fans, with Williams and with the entire episode.
</P>
<P>
   Orlando Hernandez will pitch Game 5 for the Yankees here Monday,
with a chance to close out the series against the Red Sox.
</P>
<P>
   ``They better lose tomorrow,'' said Nelson, referring to the Red
Sox, before ominously mentioning the prospect of the series
returning to Yankee Stadium. ``I think 56,000, 57,000 will
appreciate what they'' _ the Red Sox fans _ ``did to us today.''
</P>
<P>
   Andy Pettitte had pitched seven and one-third innings for the
Yankees, and two Boston errors allowed the Yankees to take a 3-2
lead into the eighth inning. Darryl Strawberry had slugged a home
run in the second inning, and Tino Martinez and Bernie Williams
scored the tying and go-ahead runs in the fourth.
</P>
<P>
   A controversial call that went against the Red Sox in the bottom
of the eighth _ second-base umpire Tim Tschida ruled Jose Offerman
was tagged out by the Yankees' Chuck Knoblauch, but replays showed
clearly that the Yankee did not tag him _ infuriated the Boston
manager and fans. Tschida admitted after the game that he had blown
the call, the second time in this series that an umpire admitted he
had made a wrong call that favored the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox made two more errors in the top of the ninth, as the
Yankees scored six runs, the last coming on Ricky Ledee's grand
slam. Mariano Rivera, who entered the game in the eighth, came out
to pitch the bottom of the ninth.
</P>
<P>
   But after Nomar Garciaparra was called out at first on what
appeared to be another poor call, the Red Sox manager, his team and
the fans went over the edge. The Red Sox manager threw his hat and
was ejected, and fans began throwing bottles at the players. Al
Clark, the home-plate umpire and crew chief, waved the Yankees off
the field.
</P>
<P>
   As the Yankees returned to their dugout, however, under a shower
of plastic bottles, a member of Red Sox security _ whose identity
was not immediately clear _ began shouting at the Yankees' players.
Nelson yelled back, and for a moment it appeared the incident would
escalate.
</P>
<P>
   But after eight minutes, the Yankees returned to the field. When
Paul O'Neill, the Yankees' right fielder, went to retrieve a hit in
the corner, a fan threw a bottle at him, and O'Neill went back
after the play was over to point out the fan.
</P>
<P>
   After the final out, the Yankees quickly shook hands and hustled
off the field, in control of this series and upset with fans they
thought out of control. George Steinbrenner, the Yankees' owner,
said he had always thought of Williams as manager of the year, but
added, ``He incited this.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Nelson: ``New York fans don't even do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Torre: ``Everywhere I've walked in the city these past
couple of days, people have been genuinely nice. But to have people
throw stuff, that's disgraceful. It really is. I know it's not an
indication of Boston, Massachusetts, because I mean, I've been
around the city now for four years, and it's shown a lot of class
to me. But tonight was a bad mark against a very good team.''
</P>
<P>
   Managers from both teams usually speak to reporters en masse
after each game, but Williams refused to meet them. He issued a
one-sentence statement. ``It's the first one to win four,''
Williams said, ``and it's not over yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Torre added that he felt the ugliness of the last inning greatly
detracted from the Yankees victory. Said Steinbrenner: ``It was a
long day and everybody was uptight.''
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees do not want this series to reach a seventh game;
they do not want Pedro Martinez, against whom they have five hits
and 35 strikeouts in their last 61 at-bats, to get another chance
to pitch, in what would be the deciding game. The Yankees now have
two opportunities to clinch this series before a seventh game:
Hernandez, their best pitcher, will face Boston's Kent Mercker
Monday in Game 5, and if the Red Sox win and extend the series,
then David Cone would throw against Ramon Martinez in Game 6
Wednesday, at Yankee Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Steinbrenner, the Yankees' principal owner, sternly moved around
his team's clubhouse after Game 3's blow-out loss, and then again
before Sunday night's game, a living reminder of consequences. A
phone rang in the press room while Torre spoke with reporters after
Game 3, and Torre asked if the phone was for him, adding, ``You
never know'' - and everybody laughed, knowing what he meant.
Steinbrenner is omnipresent, especially in defeat.
</P>
<P>
   But Torre felt his team was relaxed, confident, and fully aware
of the importance of Game 4. Torre shook up his lineup a bit,
replacing Ricky Ledee in left field with Chad Curtis, and inserting
Darryl Strawberry as his designated hitter.
</P>
<P>
   When Strawberry came to bat for the first time, the Fenway Park
fans offered a new and different chorus for the slugger with the
history of drugs and alcohol _ ``Just Say No.'' Boston's Bret
Saberhagen threw a high fastball and Strawberry rattled a high
drive two-thirds of the way up the right field foul pole fora home
run. It was the last time the hearty singers serenaded Strawberry
on this evening.
</P>
<P>
   The sensitive Pettitte, too, was hearing it _ ``Andy, Andy,'' _
and the Red Sox tied the score in the bottom of the second. Butch
Huskey slammed a double into the left field corner, but appeared to
pull a leg muscle as he came out of the box. When Troy O'Leary
singled to center field, to Bernie Williams, however, Huskey's
slogging limp did not deter Wendell Kim, Boston's third-base coach,
from waving Huskey around third in a direct challenge of Williams's
weak throwing arm; Huskey scored easily.
</P>
<P>
   That success may have led to a poor decision by Kim in the next
inning, when the Red Sox assumed a 2-1 lead but lost an opportunity
for more. Damon Buford singled, stole second and scored when
Offerman rolled a base hit through the middle.
</P>
<P>
   John Valentin smacked a long drive to left, where Curtis _ who
started, in part, because of his defensive familiarity with
Fenway's 37-foot high left field wall _ misjudged the flight of
Valentin's shot. He was too close to the wall when the ball hit,
and it ricocheted off Curtis and went behind him. Williams moved to
back up the play, and Boston's third-base coach waved Offerman
around third base.
</P>
<P>
   It was a serious miscalculation. Williams made a quick and short
throw to the shortstop Derek Jeter, who relayed a rocket to the
catcher Joe Girardi; the ball arrived at the plate in plenty of
time for Girardi to reach and slap a tag on Offerman _ the second
out of the inning, with Garciaparra, Boston's best hitter, due to
bat.
</P>
<P>
   Boston made more mistakes in the top of the fourth, and it cost
the Red Sox their lead. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-18-99 0134EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
