<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-NOTEBOOK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOKIES' STRENGTH IS A SURPRISE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL VEGA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Did you feel the seismic tremors? They rippled across
the college football landscape Saturday. From Tallahassee to State
College, Pa., to West Lafayette, Ind., to Oxford, Miss., to South
Bend, Ind., and all the way out to Stanford, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   But, perhaps, the biggest shock was registered in Blacksburg,
Va., where Virginia Tech obliterated 16th-ranked Syracuse, 62-0, in
a triumphant homecoming at Lane Stadium/Worsham Field.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, you read that right. Sixty-two to nuthin'.
</P>
<P>
   Holy smokes. Or, should we say, Holy sm-hokies.
</P>
<P>
   Sixty-two points. Does that register as a 6.2 on the Richter
scale?
</P>
<P>
   The victory was huge in so many respects for the Hokies, and the
Big East as well. Since its inception, the Big East has not had a
representative in the national championship game.
</P>
<P>
   But Virginia Tech's impressive victory _ which tied Rutgers'
62-0 romp over Temple Oct. 2, 1993, as the most lopsided game in
conference history _ left at least one Orangeman in the crowd,
senior tackle Mark Baniewicz, believing, ``Virginia Tech might
bring this thing, a national championship, to the Big East.''
</P>
<P>
   That, of course, is the fervent hope of everyone in the
conference home office in Providence, where it is believed the
Hokies possess all the ingredients _ a potent offense, a savage
defense, and opportunistic specials teams _ to earn a bid to the
Bowl Championship Series title game in New Orleans.
</P>
<P>
   While Virginia Tech's weaker strength of schedule could prove
troublesome in the final tabulation of the BCS's byzantine formulas
and myriad polls and power rankings, the No. 4 Hokies (6-0 overall,
2-0 Big East) remained on track for a Sugar Bowl berth by simply
taking care of business on the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've got a real good get-after-you defense, with a lot of
talent and some real high-emotion guys,'' said Syracuse tackle Jeff
Pilon, saluting a Hokies defense that held the Orangemen to 120
yards total offense and rang up 12 points.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never been on a team that's been beaten this bad.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A week after celebrating the biggest win of their season, a
34-31 triumph over Michigan, the fifth-ranked Michigan State
Spartans suffered a classic case of the letdowns _ along with a
deadly overdose of Drew Brees _ in a devastating 52-28 loss at
Purdue. Brees, the Purdue QB who revived his Heisman Trophy hopes,
beat Michigan State (6-1, 3-1 Big Ten) by completing 40 of 57
passes for a gaudy 509 yards and five touchdowns. As a result, the
Boilermakers climbed from No. 20 to No. 17 in the AP Top 25.
</P>
<P>
   As painful as it was to Michigan State, Purdue's victory proved
beneficial to No. 2 Penn State, which remained undefeated (7-0,
3-0) after its 23-10 triumph over No. 18 Ohio State. Now the
Nittany Lions have to hope Brees doesn't deep-six their
championship hopes when the Boilermakers (5-2, 2-2) host Penn State
this week.
</P>
<P>
   Rest assured, folks in Blacksburg, Va., will be jumping aboard
the Brees Bandwagon in the hope he eliminates another contender
from the title picture.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Alabama running back Shaun Alexander remained in contention to
become his school's first Heisman Trophy winner after he ran for
214 yards and three touchdowns in a 30-24 victory at No. 22
Mississippi . . . Georgia Tech quarterback Joe Hamilton fashioned
his sixth game-saving drive in the last 13 games when he rallied
the No. 8 Yellow Jackets in a 38-31 victory at Duke. Hamilton, who
completed 23 of 34 passes for 324 yards and three touchdowns,
guided Georgia Tech on a 70-yard scoring march with 2:56 to play .
. . Wisconsin's Ron Dayne ran for 167 yards, giving him 1,020 yards
for the season, in a 59-0 romp over Indiana in which the Badgers
amassed a school-record 705 yards total offense.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Florida State coach Bobby Bowden will have mixed emotions this
week when he goes for career victory No. 300 against Clemson, which
is coached by his son, Tommy. Call it a Bowden Family Feud? Or
Family Affair? Whatever the case, it will be a much anticipated
family reunion. After recording his 299th career victory in Florida
State's 33-10 triumph over Wake Forest, Bowden admitted the matchup
between his top-ranked Seminoles (7-0, 5-0 Atlantic Coast
Conference) and his son's emerging Clemson squad (3-3, 3-1) gave
him reason for some trepidation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't feel too good coming off the field,'' Bowden said.
``Tommy's going to have a plan, and it'll be tough.''
</P>
<P>
   Just when it appeared that the season had gone flat, Notre Dame
showed it still had a pulse in rallying from a 21-0 first-half
deficit to score a 25-24 victory over Southern California. The
Fighting Irish (4-3) need three victories in their last five games
_ against Navy, Tennessee, Pittsburgh, Boston College, and Stanford
_ to reach the seven-win plateau, which might be enough to steal a
bowl spot from a Big East team . . . After surviving a 21-17
victory over Oregon State, Stanford's whole season could be
determined in the next three weeks when the Cardinal face a tough
stretch of three consecutive Pac-10 road games, beginning Saturday
with a date at USC. Stanford then travels to Washington (Oct. 30),
and Arizona State (Nov. 13) before returning home to host archrival
Cal (Nov. 20). By then, Stanford could be 5-5 and playing for its
season when the Cardinal host Notre Dame (Nov. 27) . . . And while
he may never approach the NCAA record for consecutive victories set
Saturday by Division 3 Mount Union, which won its 48th in a row in
a 44-20 triumph over Otterbein, NCAA president Cedric Dempsey kept
his own streak of sorts intact when he presided over Boston
College's 20-16 victory over Pittsburgh. In his travels as NCAA
president, no home team has ever lost a football game that Dempsey
has attended.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
