<SLUG> BC-BKN-CELTICS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PITINO'S CAMPERS HAPPY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER MAY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WALTHAM, Mass. _ Kenny Anderson noticed a difference almost from
the start. There was time this year for teaching. The players were
in shape. The coach was _ dare we say it _ mellowing?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm feeling much better than last year, when it was a real
rush,'' he said recently. ``You can see Coach and the staff are
more relaxed because they have more time to put things in.''
</P>
<P>
   It translates into an atmosphere much more conducive to
learning. Rick Pitino may not have turned into Bob Newhart
overnight, but he, too, is more comfortable with what he sees and
what he's doing. He has a beautiful new practice facility that runs
on his watch and he has, for now, an attentive group of
eager-beaver campers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the best chemistry we've had since I've been here,''
Pitino said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first year was all new, everybody going in 100 different
directions. Last year was no camp (because of the lockout). This is
the best year getting to know each other.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just think it's fun teaching and focusing on little things
and the repetition of it. I'm enjoying the coaching aspect of it.
This is as good a group as I've worked with, college or pro.''
</P>
<P>
   This is Pitino's third season in Boston. He already has put
pressure on himself and the team: It will make the playoffs. But
while Larry Bird might think a coach's influence wanes after three
years, Pitino, who started from scratch and has been tinkering all
along, thinks he finally has his pieces in place.
</P>
<P>
   That's one undeniable comfort element. There are 14 players in
camp and every one will make the team. (There will be a couple of
players on the injured list to comply with league rules.) Two years
ago, in a camp best remembered for the liberal use of intravenous
lines, the roster was volatile. Chris Mills and Tony Massenburg,
both Pitino-signed free agents in the summer, were traded during
camp.
</P>
<P>
   While acknowledging that his words might come back to haunt him,
Pitino said he is not interested now in making any moves.
</P>
<P>
   General manager Chris Wallace has taken the phone off the hook,
at least to talk about prospective trades.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel very comfortable that this is our team,'' Pitino said.
``It's going to be our team. We're intact. We're not looking to do
anything.''
</P>
<P>
   The players see that, too. Dana Barros is one of two Celtics _
Antoine Walker is the other _ who has been a wire-to-wire
participant in all three Pitino training camps with the Celtics.
(The only others remaining from the team he took over, Pervis
Ellison and Greg Minor, have each missed a camp.) He was there for
the craziness of Year 1, the utter insanity of Year 2, and the
tranquillity, so to speak, of Year 3.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's still intense. It's still grinding,'' Barros said. ``But
(Pitino) is a lot more relaxed for some reason. Maybe it's because
he has the team that he wants. He's definitely a lot more relaxed.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the guys who've been here, I think we've adjusted to him.
Whether he's as intense as he was his first year, or the way he is
now, we've come to expect whatever. We know that he wants us to be
in the best shape we've been in, every year. We're more
comfortable. He's more comfortable.''
</P>
<P>
   And with the players in shape, there's more time for basketball.
Pitino stopped two-a-days a week into camp because he saw that the
need for conditioning wasn't as acute as he thought it might be.
</P>
<P>
   ``He sees everyone in shape, working hard, and he rewards us for
that,'' Walter McCarty said.
</P>
<P>
   Barros said, ``We're into the details of things rather than just
the basics. It's a lot more fun for us because we can play a lot
more and not have to stop every two minutes.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, all this is subject to change. The results are what
really matter and they won't start appearing for another fortnight.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Item for nonbelievers: Anderson for All-Defensive Team? ``I
never thought I'd see the day where he'd concentrate so much on
defense,'' Pitino said of his offense-oriented, defense-challenged
point guard. ``That's wonderful.'' Pitino said Anderson had 13
deflections in the first two games _ eight would be a lot, the
coach said _ and dived on the floor 11 times for loose balls . . .
The Celtics play the Hornets Tuesday night in the first of a
four-game exhibition swing through Dixie . . . The team drew about
3,000 to an open practice Sunday &UR;  &LR; night at the Cumberland County
Civic Center in Portland, Maine. Pitino had the players run through
several drills and then had a scrimmage. Eric Williams rolled his
right ankle, but the injury is not believed to be serious.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
