<HEADLINE>
BRUCE SPRINGSTEEN OPENS $400 MILLION ARENA IN LOS ANGELES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY FRED SHUSTER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
Los Angeles _ Ron Weeks came all the way from Montreal, Canada, to
hear the Boss call out his famous countdown: ``1-2-3-4!''
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was a double kickoff Sunday, marking the opening night of
four highly anticipated sold-out dates featuring the reunion of
Bruce Springsteen and the E Street Band, the ensemble that backed
the Boss on most of his journey from Freehold, N.J., to the stages
of the world's stadiums.
</P>
<P>
   And it was the inauguration of Staples Center, Los Angeles' new
$400 million, 20,000-seat entertainment and sports arena.
</P>
<P>
   Weeks, 30, spent three and a half days on a Greyhound bus and
bought a scalped $200 ticket at the sparkling new arena hours
before Springsteen hit the stage.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not playing in Canada until next year,'' said Weeks, who
has seen Springsteen five times previously. ``I wanted to see the
most special night of the tour, and how much more special can you
get than the opening of Staples Center with Bruce Springsteen?
</P>
<P>
   ``This reunion is what all the fans have been waiting for for 10
years. It's the magic of Bruce and the E Street band together
again.''
</P>
<P>
   Forty minutes after the scheduled 8 p.m. start time,
Springsteen, who turned 50 last month, and the band lumbered on
stage one-by-one, greeted with roars from the packed audience.
</P>
<P>
   Wearing black jeans, a button-down shirt and a black vest,
Springsteen kicked off a rousing gospel-tinged intro to one of his
more obscure songs, ``My Love Will Not Let You Down,'' going
straight into one of his biggest hits, ``Prove It All Night.''
</P>
<P>
   The tour, which opened six months ago in Barcelona, Spain, and
moved to the U.S. in July, has become the hottest ticket in the
country as Springsteen fever spreads.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, fans of all ages mingled outside the venue waiting for
doors to open at the arena, home to three major league sports
franchises and the upcoming host of the 2000 Democratic National
Convention.
</P>
<P>
   One teen from San Luis Obispo stood holding a sign that read
``Our Glory Days,'' referring to the popular Springsteen song.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is our favorite song, and it portrays our zest for
life,'' said Brittany Gonyer, 16. ``He sings about everyday life,
and feelings and experiences that mean something.''
</P>
<P>
   Bruce and the E Street Band played their final Los Angeles dates
at the Coliseum as part of the 1988 Amnesty International tour,
just before he dissolved the group in order to play with other
musicians and tour on his own.
</P>
<P>
   But after 10 years of experimenting, he reformed the group,
featuring not only original guitarist Steve Van Zandt, who had left
the unit just as Springsteen was reaching his biggest success, but
his replacement, Nils Lofgren.
</P>
<P>
   Original members also include drummer Max Weinberg, bassist
Garry W. Tallent, keyboardists Roy Bittan and Danny Federici, and
Bruce's main foil on stage, saxophonist Clarence ``Big Man''
Clemons.
</P>
<P>
   With the addition of Springsteen's wife, Patti Scialfa on vocals
and guitar, there were eight E Street members on stage Sunday. The
run continues tonight, Thursday and Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The messages in his lyrics apply to regular working people,''
said Tricia Righetti, 18, also of San Luis Obispo. ``He's kind of a
hero to me.''
</P>
<P>
   In the circular lobby, souvenir stands did a brisk business,
selling Springsteen shirts ranging from $20 to $45, coffee mugs at
$15 and beach towels for $50, among other items.
</P>
<P>
   Just before Springsteen took the stage, an announcer advised
audience members to turn off their cell phones and asked patrons in
the premium annual boxes to ``turn off your lights and
televisions.'' Premium boxes, which contain a wood-paneled bar
area, TV screens and luxury seating, go for up to $300,000 per
year.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
