<SLUG> BC-FBN-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXCEPT FOR SEAU, HAIR'S DIFFERENCE IN FINAL OUTCOME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO _ Hard to believe Sunday's matchup for the AFC West
division lead came down to who had the worst hair.
</P>
<P>
   But when resolution is undetermined until the game's final
second, little things mattered.
</P>
<P>
   Since Junior Seau was having a bad hair day for the ages, the
edge went to the San Diego Chargers over the Seattle Seahawks.
</P>
<P>
   ``To go in there with this kind of hair,'' said the Chargers'
rainbow warrior, ``you've got to show up.''
</P>
<P>
   Seau's coif was a color not found in nature _ ``I think it's
called Irish gold, or something,'' he said _ the result of losing a
bet on Saturday's Notre Dame-USC game with kicker John Carney. When
the Trojans lost 28-27, USC grad Seau paid off his rival from Notre
Dame with a dye job that was not to die for.
</P>
<P>
   As a guy who normally plays in a gear reserved for locomotives
on caffeine, it's hard to know how much more he could ratchet up
his game. But if fashion embarrassment created even a smidgen more
hostility, the Chargers were happy for his personal humiliation.
</P>
<P>
   It was needed. There was about a hair's difference between the
Chargers and Seahawks.
</P>
<P>
   As Seahawk defensive lineman Sam Adams put it, ``No one
dominated the game in any way.''
</P>
<P>
   That is, outside of Seau, whose hand in 11 tackles and presence
in the general mayhem (including two offensive plays as an H-back),
shut down the Seahawks to the point of whimpering.
</P>
<P>
   While the Seahawks defenders were scarcely less domineering,
they were on the field when Carney's 41-yard field goal sailed over
their heads, beyond the crossbar and down in front of the
scoreboard game clock that read 00:00.
</P>
<P>
   The 13-10 defeat on the game's last play might have been galling
had the Seahawks not won two earlier games on missed field goals in
the last seconds. Instead, a slip from the late-game precipice was
merely annoying, and hardly cruel.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've said all along that this division was going to come down
to the wire,'' said running back Ricky Watters. ``We better get
used to it.''
</P>
<P>
   The evidence for Watters' warning is ample. No team in the West
_ hey, no team in the AFC _ appears dominant. The Seahawks have
been in all their games except the opener, and a play here or there
has been the difference-maker, except for the freakish rout of
Pittsburgh.
</P>
<P>
   In four of the past five meetings between the Chargers and
Seahawks, outcomes were seven points or less, suggesting that this
portion of the AFC West will continue to be unpleasant for stomach
linings.
</P>
<P>
   The universal refrain in the Seahawk quarters sounded a lot like
the words around the Washington Huskies these days: Work in
progress.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be a process that takes more than five games,''
said coach Mike Holmgren. ``We lost a tough game, but this is not
an overnight thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Teams are searching for identity.''
</P>
<P>
   After 201 yards of total offense, the Seahawks are looking for
the identity of folks who can get the ball down the field. The
Seahawks' longest run was seven yards, the longest pass 25 yards.
</P>
<P>
   For most of the game, the Seahawks settled too easily for the
dink-a-thon passing game favored in the West Coast offense. Only 8
of quarterback Jon Kitna's 17 completions in 29 attempts went to
wide receivers, the longest for 13 yards.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, there was a reason for some of the conservatism: The
guy with the insulted follicles.
</P>
<P>
   Seau is the sort of disrupter that bends game plans. The
Seahawks seemed to have scripted the game to accommodate his
talents, avoiding any chance that Kitna would be in the pocket more
than two heartbeats.
</P>
<P>
   Kitna did all right, with only one interception and three sacks.
But in nearly every possession, Seau or one of his mates would make
a well-timed breakthrough to create a loss. The Seahawks, absent a
vertical game, almost never recovered from a negative yardage play.
</P>
<P>
   A good example came late in the third quarter, when the Seahawks
had just acquired their second of four consecutive interceptions
that ended Charger possessions in the second half.
</P>
<P>
   With a first down at the San Diego 31, Reggie Brown had two
yards off-tackle, Kitna missed on a pass to tight end Christian
Fauria, and then Seau dropped Watters for a five-yard loss on a
busted trap play.
</P>
<P>
   That put the Seahawks just beyond field goal range, and forced a
punt. Had Watters even reached the line of scrimmage, kicker Todd
Peterson would have had a decent shot at a 48-yarder.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Seau is doing it right, he's tough to stop,'' said
Holmgren. ``He creates a lot of problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Hook him up with Dennis Rodman's hairdresser, and maybe the AFC
West won't go down to the wire, after all.
</P>
<P>
   P-I columnist Art Thiel can be reached at 206-448-8135
</P>
<P>
   or artthiel &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
