u f BC-MOVIES-BOXOFFICE-LADN     10-18 1020
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-BOXOFFICE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`JEOPARDY' SCORES TKO IN THEATERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DAVE MCNARY  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
Los Angeles _ Moviegoers chose revenge over romance and mayhem as
``Double Jeopardy'' edged ``The Story of Us'' and ``Fight Club''
for the nation's top box office spot with an estimated $10.5
million at 2,936 theaters during a moderate Friday-Sunday period,
studio sources said Sunday.
<TEXT>
<P>
   However, any of the trio could wind up on top today when final
weekend totals are tabulated. In one of the closest races in
several years, ``The Story of Us'' performed as expected with $10.4
million at 2,136 theaters in its opening weekend while the
much-discussed debut of violence-laden ``Fight Club'' finished well
under forecasts with $10.3 million at 1,936 sites.
</P>
<P>
   If ``Double Jeopardy'' wins, it will mark its fourth consecutive
victory _ a feat achieved only by ``The Matrix'' and ``The Sixth
Sense'' this year. Paramount's Ashley Judd thriller lost only 22
percent from the previous weekend and has grossed an impressive
$80.6 million in 24 days.
</P>
<P>
   The ongoing strength of ``Double Jeopardy'' may have hampered
Universal's ``The Story of Us,'' starring Bruce Willis and Michelle
Pfeiffer as a couple in a disintegrating marriage, and 20th Century
Fox's ``Fight Club,'' with Brad Pitt as a psychotic mastermind
provoking brawls and terrorism.
</P>
<P>
   The new entries drew mixed reviews, and a number of critics
bashed Fox and director David Fincher over what they perceived as
the gratuitous use of violence in ``Fight Club,'' which had been
delayed from a mid-summer release following last spring's shootings
at Columbine High School that left 15 dead.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Bucksbaum, president of the Reel Source tracking service,
said ``Fight Club'' performed poorly outside major cities. ``No one
in Middle America wanted to see this movie,'' he added, noting that
media coverage of the film's violence, the relatively long running
time and competition from Major League Baseball playoffs probably
held down business.
</P>
<P>
   Industry tracker Arthur Rockwell said he was surprised that
``Fight Club'' had not generated better numbers. ``It could be that
there's too much violence in it and that the female audience was so
turned off by it that they absolutely refused to see it,'' he
added. ``Anything that's this overdone tends to have these sorts of
problems.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Fight Club'' easily topped all movies on Friday with $3.8
million but ran into serious trouble Saturday when its total rose
just 10 percent to $4.2 million in an indication that the first
wave of customers were not issuing positive recommendations to
friends. By comparison, ``The Story of Us'' rose 37 percent on
Saturday and ``Double Jeopardy'' gained 79 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Nikki Rocco, Universal's distribution chief, said ``The Story of
Us'' drew audiences that were older than average with more females
than males and an interest in seeing Willis and Pfeiffer. Bucksbaum
noted that the drama-comedy is the fourth among current movies
portraying marriages in trouble, including ``American Beauty,''
``Random Hearts'' and ``Double Jeopardy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``So much for Ozzie and Harriet,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Warner Bros.' third weekend of ``Three Kings'' led the rest of
the pack with $7.3 million at 2,942 theaters to pass $43 million,
beating DreamWorks' fifth weekend of ``American Beauty'' with a
solid $6.8 million at 1,350 theaters for a $5,035 per-theater
average. ``Beauty,'' which has posted the highest per-theater
figure among major releases since it came out a month ago, has now
drawn over $41 million.
</P>
<P>
   Sony's second weekend of ``Random Hearts'' skidded from second
to sixth with $5.8 million at 2,697 theaters as the Harrison Ford
vehicle left a wake of disappointed fans with a stunning 55 percent
plunge from its opening weekend. ``Hearts'' barely edged
Paramount's second weekend of ``Superstar'' with $5.7 million at
2,016 locations, which lost 36 percent by comparison.
</P>
<P>
   Disney's 11th weekend of ``The Sixth Sense'' finished eighth
with $5.2 million at 2,682, leaving it $100,000 short of becoming
the 15th movie ever to gross one-quarter of a billion dollars
domestically.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sense'' should become 13th on the all-time list on Tuesday or
Wednesday when it passes ``Men In Black'' at $250.1 million and
``Batman'' at $251.2 million. ``Jaws,'' No. 12 at $260 million, is
likely to be eclipsed by the end of the month.
</P>
<P>
   Sony's fifth weekend of ``Blue Streak'' continued to show some
drawing power in ninth with $3.8 million at 2,353 theaters to go
past $60 million overall. Providence, a recently formed
distributor, took 10th with its opening of religious thriller ``The
Omega Code'' with $2.4 million at 305 sites to beat Fox's third
weekend of ``Drive Me Crazy,'' which has a tepid $15 million total
in 17 days.
</P>
<P>
   Disney's opening of David Lynch's ``The Straight Story,'' a
much-acclaimed true-life tale of a man's 350-mile journey on a
tractor-mower, generated strong response with $96,000 at seven
theaters. Disney will add 23 theaters next weekend and launch
another expansion Nov. 5.
</P>
<P>
   Overall business totaled about $80 million, down 4 percent from
the same weekend last year. Year-to-date business remains about 7
percent ahead of last year, however.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is still a strong market for what audiences perceive as
quality films like `Double Jeopardy,''' Rockwell said.
</P>
<P>
   After consecutive weekends of only two new movies coming into
the market, next weekend will see half a dozen _ Warner's romantic
comedy ``Three to Tango,'' Universal's wedding comedy ``The Best
Man,'' Paramount's drama ``Bringing Out the Dead,'' New Line's
mystery ``Body Shots,'' Sony's comedy-drama ``Crazy in Alabama''
and start-up Destination's horror project ``Bats.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Sooner or later, we were going to get a lot of new movies, so
the market is going to be pretty crowded,'' said Bucksbaum. ``Three
to Tango,'' starring Neve Campbell, has the best prospects of the
newcomers, he added.
</P>
<P>
   Final results for the Friday-Sunday period will be released
today.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
