<HEADER>
A0080 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-DEFENSE-     10-18 0669
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-DEFENSE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STELLAR `D' RINGS HOLLOW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARVIN PAVE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ They had been on the field for 40 minutes
and 7 seconds. For the New England Patriots' defense, they were the
longest 7 seconds of Sunday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Their two interceptions for touchdowns early in the first
quarter and their nine sacks of Miami quarterback Damon Huard _ the
most ever against the Dolphins _ were relegated to hollow
statistics.
</P>
<P>
   Huard, sacked for the final time by linebacker Andy Katzenmoyer
with three minutes to play on Miami's penultimate drive, went
untouched on the one that mattered. On the final drive, Huard
countered the New England blitz by targeting the flat and middle of
the field with quick passes and scrambling away from trouble.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Huard) made the plays when he needed to,'' said linebacker
Chris Slade, who, along with Katzenmoyer and Willie McGinest, had
two sacks each in the Patriots' 31-30 loss. ``But in a two-minute
situation, you have to make one play and get off the field. A field
goal would not have beaten us.''
</P>
<P>
   But a touchdown, Huard's 5-yard toss to Stanley Pritchett with
23 seconds to play, did.
</P>
<P>
   ``What did (Huard) have rushing, 50 yards?'' said cornerback
Steve Israel, who was not off by much as Miami's backup quarterback
took off six times for 54 yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing against Dan (Marino). He'll go down as one of the
best, if not the best quarterback in the game, but I don't think
Dan has 50 yards rushing in his career. And that made a huge
difference in the game because a couple of times we had him stopped
on third down, and I looked up from my coverage and this guy, he's
down the field. That hurts and it definitely wasn't in the game
plan to have a `spy' on the quarterback because he's a scrambling
guy, like Kordell (Stewart) at Pittsburgh. It was one of the major
factors in the game.''
</P>
<P>
   The nine sacks, including three straight in one third-quarter
sequence, were important, said Israel, but ``as a defense, we just
didn't get it done.'' ``We gave up 30 points and that's
unnecessary. I can't remember being part of a game where the
defense scores two touchdowns and we lose the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't tolerate that. It's unacceptable. Something
definitely has to be done.''
</P>
<P>
   But not necessarily with the defense. The Patriots were flat
offensively, going 2 for 11 on third-down conversions, which
prevented them from running time off the clock.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just weren't making the ball move, with the running game or
with enough completions to keep the sticks moving. We were just in
and out of there so quick,'' said Patriots coach Pete Carroll. ``We
weren't making any first downs.''
</P>
<P>
   And so the defense, pinned at times by poor special teams play,
had to keep running onto the field. They did pretty well in at
least forcing Miami into field goal situations, but when the
Dolphins needed a touchdown to win, the defense was a victim of its
own previous success.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the ways to effectively attack blitzes is to throw the
ball real quick,'' said Carroll. ``You have to play very tight
coverage and try to make your plays, but they just picked their way
down the field. We called everything we had to try and get them.
Things that we had been hitting earlier, they did a better job of
picking up.''
</P>
<P>
   There was no special coverage on Huard, no adjustment by the
defense, which had been preparing for Marino and got a big, lethal
dose of the more mobile backup.
</P>
<P>
   The antidote could have been provided by the New England
offense. But in the end, it was the Patriots' defense that took the
final hit.
</P>
<P>
   ``These last two weeks, it seems things have slipped away a
little bit from us,'' said linebacker Marty Moore. ``We were
bringing a lot of heat on that young quarterback. Then they just
started adjusting. He'd scramble out and (defensive) guys would
come up, and, boom, there's a touchdown.''
</P>
<P>
   And the football game.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
