<HEADER>
A0081 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BLEDSOE-     10-18 0567
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BLEDSOE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEFEAT THROWS BLEDSOE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SHIRA SPRINGER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ There are tests of skill. And there are
tests of character.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday at Foxboro Stadium, Drew Bledsoe failed the first, but
survived the second. The first test came on the field, where the
offense managed to score just one touchdown in a 31-30 loss. The
second test came in the interview room, where the quarterback had
to produce a reason for the Patriots' gradual collapse that gave
the Dolphins their first lead with 23 seconds left to play.
</P>
<P>
   With his eye black barely smudged and his uniform pants still
on, Bledsoe faced the questioners who critiqued the team's
performance. The 14-point lead provided by the defense in the first
quarter that disintegrated into a one-point loss. The double
coverage of top receiver Terry Glenn, who did not record a catch.
The time of possession that fell in Miami's favor, 40:07-19:53. The
inability to convert 9 of 11 third-down opportunities. The failure
to establish a potent running game.
</P>
<P>
   Bledsoe heard it all, over and over. And the quarterback
admitted he could not provide the answers. He conceded the red zone
offense was ineffective. He acknowledged New England's shortcomings
and took the criticism calmly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, when your defense scores twice, there's no way you
should ever lose a ballgame,'' said Bledsoe. ``They came out and
spotted us 14 points and then offensively we can't put up enough,
or hold the ball long enough, to come away with a victory. And that
never should have happened.
</P>
<P>
   ``Give their defense credit, we just didn't make the plays when
we needed to. We had opportunities towards the end to end the
ballgame and didn't get the plays made then. We didn't get the
plays made early in the game to put up some points and keep our
defense off the field when we needed to.''
</P>
<P>
   The lone offensive touchdown came with 23 seconds remaining in
the second quarter. Receiver Tony Simmons caught a 29-yard pass to
give the Patriots a 24-16 lead. The touchdown completed a
nine-play, 80-yard drive that clipped just 1:03 off the clock. The
29-yard reception marked Bledsoe's longest pass completion of the
day.
</P>
<P>
   New England's reliance on the passing game and Bledsoe's trouble
throwing the deep ball with consistency led to some
second-guessing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're a passing football team. That's what we are,'' said the
quarterback, who suffered with Glenn shut down by the Miami
defense. ``We do need to establish the run more than we have. When
or if that's going to happen, I don't know. But we need to
establish it more. But right now we're a passing football team.
That's what our makeup is. We need to win that way.''
</P>
<P>
   He added that he continues to work on the long ball. ``I can
think of one opportunity to Shawn (Jefferson) where I probably
should have hit him where I overthrew him a little bit. But you're
never going to hit all the deep balls. With our guys and with our
speed, we need to be able to hit a couple of those in the game.''
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots have suffered two close losses in a row and appear
to have difficulty maintaining an early lead. But Bledsoe did not
voice any alarm about the team's recent play. Instead, he spoke
about missed opportunities. A win would have placed the Patriots
one game up in the AFC East.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
