<HEADER>
A0082 &Cx1f; tth-z
r s BC-FBN-SEAHAWKS-SPI &LR;      10-18 0977
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-SEAHAWKS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEAHAWKS FINALLY GET BOOTED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CLARE FARNSWORTH  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO _ Twice in their first four games, the Seahawks
escaped with one-point victories when the opposing kicker missed a
field goal in the closing seconds.
</P>
<P>
   Not this time. Not in this game that was a showdown for the AFC
West lead.
</P>
<P>
   The San Diego Chargers escaped with an improbable 13-10 victory
over the Seahawks Sunday when John Carney kicked a 28-yard field
goal with less than three minutes left to tie the score and then
won the game with a 41-yarder that sailed through the uprights as
the final seconds ticked away.
</P>
<P>
   The Chargers, now 4-1, partied like it was, well, 1999. So did
the 59,432 fans at Qualcomm Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``We played with heart and soul and we pulled it off,'' said
linebacker Junior Seau, the heart and soul of a Chargers' defense
that stifled Seattle all day. ``You can call this win a steal, but
you've got to win these close ones.''
</P>
<P>
   The Seahawks did their best to lead with a stiff upper lip after
falling to 3-2. They talked about the continued growing pains that
should be expected with their complex new offense. They used words
like frustrating and disappointing in trying to explain how they
had lost this game. They steered locker room discussions toward
talk of regrouping and getting ready for next week's game against
the Buffalo Bills at the Kingdome.
</P>
<P>
   ``OK, we lost this game. But where do we go from here?'' said
running back Ricky Watters, in a voice that was several decibels
lower than the one that could be heard behind closed doors before
reporters were allowed to enter the locker room. ``Are we just
going to spiral downward? Or are we going to say, `You know what?
We're better than this. We've got a better team than this. And
we've just got to keep working and make sure we cut out some of the
mistakes we're making.'''
</P>
<P>
   Carney's late kicks won this game, but the Seahawks' offense
should be kicking itself for wasting the opportunities provided by
its big-play defense.
</P>
<P>
   Each of the Chargers' first four possessions in the second half
ended with an Erik Kramer interception. Nickel back Brian Walker
got the first and returned it 21 yards to the San Diego 34-yard
line. Nickel back Chris Canty was next. Then it was defensive
tackle Cortez Kennedy, who made like a 305-pound Barry Sanders in
returning his to the Chargers' 37. The last was turned in by
cornerback Willie Williams, who made his pick at the Seahawks'
5-yard line.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of putting the game away, the offense put the pressure
on the defense by scoring just once _ on Jon Kitna's 1-yard
touchdown pass to tight end Itula Mili.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's doubly frustrating when you feel like you're letting the
other side down,'' guard Pete Kendall said.
</P>
<P>
   Does that make it triply frustrating when a defense that had
held the Chargers to 240 yards and seven points in the first 55
minutes gives up 90 yards and six points in the final five minutes?
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot happened the last drive. Everything happened the last
drive,'' said defensive end Phillip Daniels, who spent most of what
was a very warm afternoon putting the heat on Kramer after blowing
around Chargers tackle John Jackson. ``All we needed was one big
play.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, it was Kramer who made the big plays.
</P>
<P>
   On what was really a one-play drive to the game-tying field
goal, Kramer got off a 41-yard completion to wide receiver Jeff
Graham just before being driven to the turf by Seahawks linebacker
Chad Brown.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew the offense was having a tough time,'' cornerback
Shawn Springs said. ``But once we have the lead we just have to
hold it. Say what you will about our offense, but if the Chargers
don't score, they don't win.''
</P>
<P>
   On the drive to Carney's game-winner, Kramer quickly and
accurately chewed up the needed yardage by passing 15 yards to
tight end Freddie Jones, 16 yards to wide receiver Chris Penn and
11 yards to running back Terrell Fletcher.
</P>
<P>
   ``Erik hung in there. Even though he threw some interceptions,
he came back and put our offense into field-goal range,'' Seau
said. ``That is a plus, when we can do something like this. It's
going to be positive. And it's going to remain positive because
this was a big win for us. It is going to carry us a long way.''
</P>
<P>
   Then there was the Chargers' first TD, which was set up when
cornerback Darryll Lewis intercepted a Kitna pass and returned it
to the Seahawks' 34. On first-and-goal from the 5, defensive end
Michael Sinclair stuffed the gap that Natrone Means was looking
for. But when Means bounced the play to his right, the Seahawks had
no one there to contain the outside and the Chargers' running back
was able to score.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not like we played the perfect game,'' Kennedy said.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the Seahawks were due to lose a game like this. After
all, they escaped with a one-point win in Chicago when Bears kicker
Brian Gowins was wide right on a 48-yard attempt with eight seconds
to play. They did it again against Oakland when the Raiders' Mike
Husted was just short on a 61-yarder with four seconds left.
</P>
<P>
   Law of averages? Or Murphy's Law?
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a tough one,'' Seahawks coach Mike Holmgren said.
``Any time you go down to the wire and lose, it's tough. But we
will be back.''
</P>
<P>
   To a man, the Seahawks believe that, even though they had just
blown an opportunity to take sole possession of the division lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a game to put us in first place,'' Daniels said.
``But it definitely wasn't to decide the AFC West. It will come
down to the end. We'll get another chance.''
</P>
<P>
   But none may be as easy to reach out and touch, or fritter way,
as the one Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   P-I reporter Clare Farnsworth can be reached at 206-448-8016 or
clarefarnsworth &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
