<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-DOLPHINS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO QB CONTROVERSY FOR JOHNSON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN VELLANTE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ His first pass on the second play of the
game was complete to wide receiver Tony Martin for 8 yards and made
him the first man in NFL history to throw for more than 60,000
yards.
</P>
<P>
   His second pass was intercepted by Patriots linebacker Andy
Katzenmoyer and returned 57 yards for a touchdown and a 7-0 lead
just 2:54 into the game.
</P>
<P>
   On the next series, he skipped a pass to Oronde Gadsden and felt
the pain run up his right shoulder and neck.
</P>
<P>
   Dan Marino's day was through and he knew it. He went to the
sidelines and told coach Jimmy Johnson that his day was done.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson called on Damon Huard and the immediate result was
anything but encouraging. His first pass was intercepted by
cornerback Ty Law and returned 27 yards for a touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   Not even seven minutes into the game, the Dolphins trailed the
Patriots, 14-0, and were without their starting quarterback. The
Patriots had everything going their way, right? Well, you'd
certainly think so.
</P>
<P>
   But Huard, who three years ago worked for the Seattle Seahawks
as a public relations intern, rallied the troops time and time
again. He made the comeback complete with a 5-yard touchdown pass
to Stanley Pritchett with 23 seconds left and the Dolphins stunned
the Patriots, 31-30, handing them their second last-second defeat
in seven days.
</P>
<P>
   The record will show that Huard completed 24 of 42 passes for
240 yards and two touchdowns, including a 69-yard strike to Martin.
He also rushed for 54 yards _ that's 36 yards more than Marino ever
rushed for in an NFL game.
</P>
<P>
   So, who gets the start next week when the Dolphins host
Philadelphia? Marino, who was battered last week against
Indianapolis, or Huard, who pulled the Dolphins from the brink of
defeat?
</P>
<P>
   ``Dan Marino is our starting quarterback,'' said Johnson Sunday.
``Let's not get any controversy started here. If he's ready to go,
he's the man and Damon Huard is the backup.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dan took himself out. This morning he thought he'd be OK once
he loosened up, but as the day went on, he said he was having to
make a conscious effort to put velocity on the ball. He apologized
to me at the end of the game about not being able to make it.''
</P>
<P>
   Marino, whose situation will be evaluated on a daily basis, said
he knew he was in trouble early on when ``I was throwing changeups
and I'm used to throwing fastballs. I had nothing. I just didn't
feel I could throw it. In order to help the team, the best thing
was for me to sit down.''
</P>
<P>
   It didn't look like the best thing considering the way Huard
started. But the free agent out of Washington, although sacked nine
times, hung in and pecked away at the Patriots' defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a pretty exciting day for me,'' said Huard, who drove
the Dolphins 59 yards on 14 plays on the winning drive after they
gained possession on a punt at their own 41. ``But I had a lot of
work this week with Dan being hurt and all, so I was ready to do
what I had to. We didn't put the ball in the end zone all that
much, but we did when it counted most. It was a great win on the
road for us.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dan had 36 of these (comebacks) and I got my first today.
(Marino) was absolutely first class. He was there all day for me
even when I was making mistakes. He was telling me to hang in there
and to not give up because I'd have a chance to win in the fourth
quarter. He really helped me on my reads and on seeing the
coverage.''
</P>
<P>
   What did Johnson tell Huard before he took the field for the
game-winning drive?
</P>
<P>
   ``We practice the two-minute offense every week with one minute
and 40 seconds and no timeouts. I told him this (two minutes and
one timeout) was easier. I told him just take your time and work
with the plays.''
</P>
<P>
   He listened very well.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
