<SLUG> BC-FBN-SEAHAWKS-SIDE-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLAYERS FUME AT FAILURE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By HOLLY CAIN  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO _ Running back Ricky Watters was angry. Tight end
Christian Fauria was frustrated. Quarterback Jon Kitna was
shouldering more than his share of the blame.
</P>
<P>
   Seahawks offensive players took Sunday's 13-10 final-second loss
to San Diego particularly hard, unanimously feeling they'd just put
on a three-hour clinic in missed opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hate losing,'' said Watters, who finished with 54 yards
against the NFL's fourth-best rush defense. ``We had more than
enough opportunities and we felt we should have won this game. As a
team, we didn't get it done.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's frustrating. We're better than this. We have a better
team than this.''
</P>
<P>
   Judging by the harsh self-criticism in the locker room after the
game, you'd think Seattle players had just suffered a blowout
defeat instead of losing by a field goal kicked with three seconds
remaining.
</P>
<P>
   But this was a tough one to lose. The Seahawks had just come off
a good week of practice and were playing for first place in the AFC
West. All week they'd heard about San Diego's stifling defense and
its all-world linebacker Junior Seau. But the Seahawks were riding
a three-game winning streak and felt prepared and energized when
they arrived at Qualcomm Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Fueled by a stellar defensive effort, Seattle performed well
enough to hold a 10-7 lead into the fourth quarter. But on this
day, 10 points wasn't enough to win. And it wasn't as if they
didn't have plenty of chances to score more.
</P>
<P>
   The offensive unit's aggravation was perhaps directed at a
nearly 12-minute period in the second half when Seahawks defenders
intercepted Chargers quarterback Erik Kramer on four consecutive
possessions, only to have the Seattle offense answer with a lone
touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   The Seahawks missed a field goal and went three-and-out twice on
the other three drives _ the latter part of a 3-for-13 futility in
third-down conversions on the day.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle got the ball with 2:54 remaining and the game tied at
10, but the drive stalled on the Seahawks' 30-yard line with 1:34
left. Kitna completed a 13-yard pass to Sean Dawkins on first down,
but the Seahawks couldn't manage another yard in the next three
downs. Watters was stuffed at the line of scrimmage and Kitna had
two incomplete passes to Derrick Mayes, who caught a third down
pass out of bounds deep in Chargers territory.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's frustrating,'' said Kitna, who threw his second
interception of the year and passed for 151 yards. ``It's a team
game, but I felt like I could have played much better. I played
hard, I just felt like I could play better. They're a great defense
and they seemed to make the plays just when we were trying to get
into a flow.''
</P>
<P>
   First-year Seattle head coach Mike Holmgren was equally
disappointed in the game's outcome, but like several of the veteran
players, he took a decidedly big-picture approach to the season and
his newly-implemented offense.
</P>
<P>
   Credit also must be given to San Diego's defense, which lived up
to its reputation. The Chargers haven't allowed a 100-yard rusher
in their last 24 games and are holding runners to less than 2.6
yards a carry. Seattle averaged only 2.3 yards per try.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm feeling we lost a tough game and I'm frustrated we
couldn't come out with a win,'' Holmgren said. ``But this wasn't
going to be an overnight thing. This is a process that takes more
than five games.''
</P>
<P>
   Watters agreed. ``We have to realize there will be growing
pains,'' he said. ``It (the new offense) is like a puzzle and
everyone has to fit in the right place. Everyone. We cannot make
these mistakes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're all new in this but believe me, when it clicks we'll be
a hot team.''
</P>
<P>
   P-I reporter Holly Cain can be reached at 206-448-8015
</P>
<P>
   or hollycain &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
