<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-18 01:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0085 &Cx1f; tth-z
r s BC-FBN-CHARGERS-SIDE-SPI     10-18 0682
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-CHARGERS-SIDE-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KRAMER TAKES LICKS, GETS OVER PICKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ALIYA SAPERSTEIN  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO _ When San Diego quarterback Erik Kramer learned
Wednesday he'd get the start against the Seahawks, he never
imagined the game would turn out the way it did.
</P>
<P>
   The 10-year NFL veteran was 27 of 44 for 296 yards, zero
touchdowns and four interceptions. The picks came on four straight
possessions in the second half and allowed the Seahawks to regain
the lead and momentum they'd lost going into halftime.
</P>
<P>
   ``The frustrating thing is when I make a bad play and throw a
pick, or somebody misses a block, or drops a pass, it all starts to
mount after a while,'' Kramer said.
</P>
<P>
   There were plenty of all of those mistakes to go around. Yet
with 1:34 left on the clock, San Diego found itself driving toward
the winning score.
</P>
<P>
   Kramer hit four consecutive passes to put the Chargers in
field-goal range and give kicker John Carney a chance to clinch the
13-10 victory. Suddenly, everything that had gone wrong for San
Diego in the second half went right.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody had breakdowns is basically what it came down to,''
Kramer said. ``Nobody missed any blocks, nobody dropped any balls,
I didn't make any poor decisions and that's how you play offense.''
</P>
<P>
   The last time Kramer threw a career-high four interceptions, his
team wasn't so lucky. It was two years ago at Arizona and his
Chicago Bears left with a loss.
</P>
<P>
   ``We weren't really executing throughout that game. I didn't
feel like we were ever going to get a break,'' remembered Kramer,
who signed a two-year contract with San Diego at the starting of
training camp this season. ``Today, I felt like everything was
there for us. We just had to keep (making plays) and it was going
to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   The Chargers rallied behind their backup quarterback. Jim
Harbaugh, left out of the game because of cracked ribs he suffered
against Kansas City three weeks ago, tried to keep Kramer positive
after the fourth and final pick that ended a San Diego drive in
field-goal range. Chargers coach Mike Riley said he never doubted
Kramer, and had no thought of taking him out of the game.
</P>
<P>
   According to tight end Freddie Jones, Kramer's receivers didn't
lose faith either.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a drop early for a big play and he came to me and said,
`Hey Freddie, if you didn't want to drop any more balls you'd have
to never play football again,''' said Jones, who had five catches
for 74 yards. ``He was saying, `Everybody makes mistakes.' He made
his mistakes. I made my mistakes. But the important thing is we
kept fighting and we found a way to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Coming into Sunday's game, San Diego was averaging just 232
total offensive yards a game. The league's fourth-best rushing
defense and a turnover ratio of plus-8 kept the Chargers in the
hunt for first place in the AFC West.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the interceptions and other problems offensively, Riley
said he saw improvement. The Chargers offense finished with 330
total yards, and did not rely on a single defensive score for the
victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no question it was the best day we've had where we
were able to take the ball down the field and make some plays,''
Riley said. ``Even though it was haphazard, there was enough stuff
today in the passing game against a good secondary to say that this
team is getting better in some sense.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we'll be No. 1 in the NFL in turnover ratio any
more,'' he added with a wry smile, ``... but we are 4-1 and we're
happy about that.''
</P>
<P>
   Riley was also happy with the toughness he saw in Kramer. Though
Harbaugh is cleared to play _ he was held out against the Seahawks
because he is not yet 100 percent healthy _ Riley said he will wait
to decide who will start next week when the Chargers face Green
Bay.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to wait before I say anything,'' he said, ``(but) I
love our quarterback situation right now.''
</P>
<P>
   P-I reporter Aliya Saperstein can be reached at 206-448-8370
</P>
<P>
   or aliyasaperstein &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
