<DOCNO> NYT19991018.0057 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-18 02:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0086 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BBA-ALCS-HNS &LR;      10-18 0928
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ALCS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOSEPH DUARTE  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
BOSTON _ After 81 years of suffering, the Boston Red Sox are still
waiting for the breaks to go in their favor.
<TEXT>
<P>
   So what's another day of misery?
</P>
<P>
   Andy Pettitte pitched 7 strong innings, but it was two costly
errors and an umpire's ruling that sealed Boston's fate in a 9-2
loss to the New York Yankees on Sunday night in Game 4 of the
American League Championship Series at Fenway Park.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, the talk was about a controversial call in the eighth
inning many Red Sox fans will remember as the ``Phantom Tag.''
</P>
<P>
   Only none of the Red Sox was talking. Neither Boston manager
Jimy Williams nor his players attended a postgame news conference.
</P>
<P>
   Williams, who was ejected in the ninth inning for arguing a call
at first base, said in a prepared statement: ``It's the first one
to win four (games), and it's not over yet.''
</P>
<P>
   New York holds a 3-1 advantage in the best-of-seven series and
can advance to its third World Series in four years with a victory
tonight in Game 5.
</P>
<P>
   Only three times since the LCS went to a seven-game format in
1985 has a team come back from a 3-1 LCS deficit. The Atlanta
Braves were the last team to do it, rallying to beat St. Louis in
1996.
</P>
<P>
   What had Boston fuming _ not to mention some Yankees _ was the
controversy that surrounded Sunday night's ending.
</P>
<P>
   First, with one out and the Yankees leading 3-2 in the eighth,
John Valentin hit a grounder to New York second baseman Chuck
Knoblauch. Knoblauch scooped up the ball and stretched
unsuccessfully to tag Jose Offerman, who was trying to advance to
second base.
</P>
<P>
   Second-base umpire Tim Tschida called Offerman out _ TV replays
clearly showed no tag was made, and Tschida later admitted blowing
the call _ and Knoblauch threw to first for the inning-ending
double play.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees turned the one-run game into a rout with six runs in
the ninth inning, which included a grand slam by Ricky Ledee off
Rod Beck.
</P>
<P>
   Then the game was delayed for eight minutes in the bottom of the
ninth when fans became upset over a close call at first base and
began littering the field with empty plastic bottles. With one out,
Nomar Garciaparra was called out at first on a grounder to third,
prompting Williams' ejection for arguing the call.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's inexcusable,'' Yankees manager Joe Torre said of
the crowd's behavior. ``Not what Jimy Williams did, because as a
manager I understand the frustration that goes on inside. I haven't
been exposed to Boston before these last four years, but people
have been genuinely nice. But to have people throw stuff is
disgraceful.''
</P>
<P>
   Closer Mariano Rivera pitched 1 scoreless innings to move the
Yankees one step closer to a shot at defending their World Series
title. Rivera has not allowed a run in his last 38 innings dating
to July 21.
</P>
<P>
   Darryl Strawberry gave the Yankees a 1-0 lead in the second
inning with a solo home run that hit the right-field foul pole.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox tied the game at 1 in the bottom half on Troy
O'Leary's RBI bloop single and took a 2-1 lead in the third on
Offerman's run-scoring base hit. It appeared they would take a
bigger lead when Valentin hit a double off the left-field wall that
Chad Curtis misplayed. But Offerman was nailed at the plate thanks
to shortstop Derek Jeter's relay from center fielder Bernie
Williams. Pettitte then struck out Mike Stanley with runners at
first and second to end the threat.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees took the lead for good courtesy of two errors in the
fourth inning.
</P>
<P>
   With one out, Williams hit a grounder to Garciaparra, who threw
the ball into the Red Sox dugout. Garciaparra has committed four
errors in the series, one shy of the ALCS record for shortstops set
by Boston's Spike Owen in 1986.
</P>
<P>
   Tino Martinez then doubled to right-center field to tie the game
at 2, and Strawberry was intentionally walked. After a strikeout of
Scott Brosius, Bret Saberhagen got Curtis to hit into what appeared
to be an inning-ending groundout.
</P>
<P>
   Stanley fielded the grounder behind first base and threw to
Saberhagen at the bag. But Saberhagen bobbled the ball, allowing
the go-ahead run to score from second base.
</P>
<P>
   After his rocky start, Pettitte shut down the Red Sox before
being lifted with one out in the eighth. The Deer Park native
retired 13 of the final 16 batters he faced and did not permit a
runner to advance past first after the third inning.
</P>
<P>
   But for the second time in this series, an umpire's call also
played a crucial role in a Red Sox loss.
</P>
<P>
   In Game 1, umpire Rick Reed ruled Knoblauch had possession of a
bobbled ball on a force at second with the game tied at 3 in the
10th inning. After Williams hit a game-winning homer and the
Yankees escaped with a 4-3 decision, Reed admitted blowing the
call, which preceded an inning-ending double play.
</P>
<P>
   As for Sunday's wrong call, Tschida said he made his judgment
based on ``reaction.''
</P>
<P>
   ``No, I did not make the right call,'' Tschida said. ``In my
judgment, (Offerman) made very little effort to avoid being tagged.
I called the play on reaction, on the reaction of the runner and
the reaction of the fielder. It appeared to me as though he got
him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't get into a position where I could see daylight
between the glove and the runner. The only position I ever got to
see that daylight came when I got to the dressing room and saw it
on television.''
</P>
<P>
   In keeping with the last 81 years, it was too late for the Red
Sox.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
