<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-18 02:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0087 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BBN-METS-VENTURA-BOS &LR;      10-18 0623
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-VENTURA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN END, VENTURA IS DRIVING FORCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE BURRIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Mets center fielder Shawon Dunston was the set-up
man.
</P>
<P>
   His misplay of a catchable ball in the top of the 15th inning
had resulted in a Keith Lockhart triple that allowed Atlanta to
take a 3-2 lead in Sunday &UR;  &LR; night's Game 5 of the National League
Championship Series. Dunston, therefore, came to bat in the bottom
of the inning hoping to play a part in keeping the Mets' season
alive.
</P>
<P>
   Nine minutes later, he safely reached first base, via a single
that followed six fouled-off pitches after the count had reached 3
and 2.
</P>
<P>
   The at-bat left Braves reliever Kevin McGlinchy, who had entered
in the prior inning, all but spent. He would watch Dunston steal
second, then give up a walk to Matt Franco and a sacrifice bunt to
Edgardo Alfonzo. Then, after intentionally walking John Olerud to
load the bases, he walked Todd Pratt to score Dunston and tie the
game, 3-3.
</P>
<P>
   That brought up third baseman Robin Ventura. If Dunston was the
set-up man, Ventura was the closer. And what a relief it was for
the Mets. The Shea Stadium crowd, which had sat through the
five-hour-plus thriller in steady rain, began cheering wildly.
Dunston sensed a fantastic finish coming on.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the count went to 1-1,'' he said, ``I had a feeling he
was going to hit it.''
</P>
<P>
   Two pitches later, Ventura sent a 2-1 delivery over the wall in
right field, sending the Mets and their raucous crowd into a
frenzy, so much so that Ventura was mobbed by his teammates before
reaching second, and the apparent home run was ruled a single.
</P>
<P>
   No matter. Two runs scored, and the Mets had closed out their
NCLS homestand with a 4-3 triumph that sent the series back to
Atlanta with the Braves ahead, 3-2. Now no one is doubting that New
York can become the first team in playoff history to rally from a
3-0 deficit to win a seven-game series.
</P>
<P>
   After the game, both the set-up man and the closer credited the
other for propelling the Mets to victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Shawon's at-bat really did a lot,'' said Ventura. ``He
fouled off a ton of pitches and then got a base hit. And then Matty
went up there and got a good at-bat. I think guys feed off that. It
was a great job by them.''
</P>
<P>
   Dunston said he approached the at-bat ``thinking hack all the
way. I have only two walks this season. I don't think I have 150
for my career. I just said to myself, `I'm not going to walk. If I
go down, I'm going down swinging.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Dunston attributed his grittiness at the plate to being around
players such as Ventura. ``Robin is our leader,'' said Dunston.
``He's one of the guys on this team that gives it all they have,
whether they're injured or not.''
</P>
<P>
   Playing with an injured left knee, Ventura said he knew
McGlinchy's margin for error was minimal since he had just given up
a walk to tie the game. ``So, I'm just trying to get a ball in the
air so the guy can score,'' he said. ``I saw it go over (the fence)
and then I just ran to first. I saw Todd Pratt running back at me.
I don't know, as long as I touched first, we won, so that's fine
with me.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mets seem to play their best baseball when it appears their
season is over. ``It's a team that obviously doesn't quit,'' said
Ventura. ``I think we've been in quite a few situations like this
during the course of the year. We really don't have a reason for
it.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the Braves, they went from three outs away from advancing
to the World Series to walking off the field looking shellshocked.
``We missed too many opportunities tonight,'' said manager Bobby
Cox. ``We should have scored many more runs.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
