u s BC-BBA-REDSOX-MERCKER-BO     10-18 0538
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RED </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MERCKER RED SOX' LAST HOPE 
</HEADLINE>
 SOX-MERCKER-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB DUFFY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ With characteristic eloquence, Jimy Williams offered
this resounding endorsement of the pitcher with whom he will
entrust the ball Monday night in the Red Sox' most vital game of
the season:
</P>
<P>
   ``Kent Mercker is going to be our Game 5 starter,'' the manager
said before the game. ``I don't assume anything . . . Mercker is
going to start our next game.''
</P>
<P>
   From the passion in his voice and his words, it was obvious that
Williams is calling upon Mercker for this critical assignment
because . . . because . . . well, because the rules stipulate that
somebody has to start the game.
</P>
<P>
   Williams didn't say so _ or much of anything else _ but Mercker
is his man basically because he has no alternative. And the truth
is that Mercker is his most experienced postseason pitcher, the
lefthander having appeared in 12 October games over four years with
the dynastic Braves of the early '90s. But his postseason
experience this year hasn't been particularly pleasant.
</P>
<P>
   In Game 4 of the Division Series at Fenway Park against the
Indians, Mercker was driven from the mound after 1 2/3 innings in
which he allowed three hits, two runs, and three walks. But he
happened to pick a fortuitous night to post that shabby line _
Boston's fusillade rendered its pitching irrelevant in a 23-7
bombing mission.
</P>
<P>
   In the opener of the American League Championship Series
Wednesday night at Yankee Stadium, Mercker was a portrait of
reliability in comparison to his 1999 postseason debut. In a 4-3,
10-inning loss to the Yankees, he lasted four innings, allowing six
hits and two runs. But the 83 pitches he used to reach that point
proved too taxing a toll.
</P>
<P>
   Monday night at Fenway, he hopes to make a more lasting impact,
which isn't a lofty goal, given his recent track record.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I need to get ahead of guys a little better,'' he
said. ``At this time of year, you can't afford to be behind guys,
1-0, 2-0. They're a patient ballclub. If they're willing to take a
strike, you've got to give it to them. Then they start to expand
the strike zone.''
</P>
<P>
   If that happens, Mercker believes, Williams will be able to keep
the bullpen phone mute a lot longer this time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope to keep (the relievers) more rested,'' he said. ``I
want to do that whether they're tired or they need the innings. My
job is not to win the game but to go as many innings as I can, keep
us in striking distance. I'm not going to think about going seven,
eight, or nine innings, just concentrate on each batter, on getting
outs.''
</P>
<P>
   His vast experience in pressure games would seem to be most
beneficial in that regard, and Mercker acknowledged that ``it's
more a state of mind than anything else. When you've been there
before, it helps calm you down. It's been invaluable for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps in a general sense. But as far as 1999 is concerned,
``if it is an advantage,'' said the self-effacing Mercker,
expressing in words the sentiments Williams had conveyed with
silence, ``I haven't tapped into it.''
</P>
<P>
   Like his manager, he has no other choice Monday night.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-18-99 0205EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991018.0060 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-18 02:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0089 &Cx1f; tth-z
r s BC-BBA-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI     10-18 0929
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RED SOX MUST GET BEYOND CURSING THE BAD CALLS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA VECSEY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ In the Red Sox locker room Sunday night, heads were
hanging, heads were shaking. The scrappy Sox were sure they were
being doomed by outside forces.
</P>
<P>
   Only this time, it's not the Curse of the Bambino the Sox are
cursing.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITAL) Hey, Jose Offerman. Are the umpires cheating the
Red Sox out of calls in favor of the Yankees? (END ITAL)
</P>
<P>
   ``It's true,'' said Offerman, who Sunday was involved in a
second controversial play this American League Championship Series
that resulted in a call going against him and the Sox. ``Every bad
call is against us,'' Offerman said.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, there's something new happening here in the land of the
tortured Sox. It's called The Boston Tear Party.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox and their fans are crying _ or at least crying foul
_ against the umpires in this ALCS, which is now 3-1 and tipped
heavily in favor of the reigning world champion Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   And for about eight lawless minutes Sunday night, it looked as
if a Boston Tear Gas Party might be needed to bring to order what
was left of a very peeved Fenway crowd.
</P>
<P>
   As if the four errors the Red Sox committed in Sunday's 9-2
meltdown against the Yanks did not have a little something to do
with the hateful, cursed position the Sox and their faithful
followers find themselves in.
</P>
<P>
   By the bottom of the ninth inning, after the second of two blown
calls went against the Sox, the irate fans _ those still
masochistic enough to remain in the stands _ showered the umpire
crew and the Yankees with water bottle bombs and soda cups,
stopping the game for eight minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The sad thing is that the ugly display came on the heels of one
of Boston's most celebrated playoff victories.
</P>
<P>
   Uplifted, chanting, basking in the glow of ace pitcher Pedro
Martinez, the Sox and their fans had spent Saturday beating up
Roger Clemens and the Yankees in what felt like a delightful
exorcism of the so-called curse.
</P>
<P>
   But whatever momentum the Sox had hoped to sustain from Game 3's
win turned into a train wreck.
</P>
<P>
   ``The sad part about it is you have a ballclub that has busted
their ass all year to play and give this city something to be proud
of, and I think it's inexcusable ... to have people throw stuff.
That's disgraceful,'' Yankee manager Joe Torre said, adding:
``Tonight was a bad mark against a very good team.''
</P>
<P>
   It was indeed an ugly display of collective anger, even if some
of the players were hard-pressed to fault the hometown crowd for
their obnoxious and dangerous reaction.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess they've been watching the games, too. That's why
they're reacting like that,'' Offerman said.
</P>
<P>
   Quite frankly, the Sox do have reason to question authority.
</P>
<P>
   In Game 1, second-base umpire Rick Reed admitted he blew a call
that cost the Red Sox an out and may have helped end a 10th-inning
opportunity for the Sox to take a lead against the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   The Sox are still wondering what might have happened if they had
that one out back.
</P>
<P>
   The shame of it was that Reed never asked one of his crewmates
for a second opinion on the play _ instigating a debate about why
baseball umps have such arrogant authority when other officials in
other leagues like the NBA and NFL check with each and override
calls.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday night, the Sox's fire was further stoked when second-base
umpire Tim Tschida also admitted he blew the call against Offerman,
who avoided a tag by Yankee second baseman Chuck Knoblauch but whom
Tschida called out.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, I didn't make the right call,'' Tschida said, echoing
Reed's admission that he blew the call and felt ``awful'' about it.
</P>
<P>
   Not as awful as Red Sox fans, apparently. Or manager Jimy
Williams, who has to take a little blame for inciting the crowd.
Williams was tossed after kicking dirt and tossing his hat and
arguing with first-base umpire Dale Scott in the ninth inning when
Scott called Nomar Garciaparra out at first. Garciaparra was
actually two strides past the bag when the blown call came.
</P>
<P>
   Later, Red Sox players could not stop thinking that more than
just their own shortcomings have gone against them in this series.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did some things that we normally don't do. We made some
mistakes but we had our chances to get back in that ballgame, but
for some reason we're not getting any help,'' Darren Lewis said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to be realistic. We made some mistakes defensively.
It's tough to rebound from that. But the nature of our team is that
we continue to battle. But for some reason, that's being taken away
from us,'' Lewis said.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're battling, you battle and you're making things
happen. But if you don't get any help, it's hard to get back in the
ballgame. And I don't have to be real specific. You all know what
I'm talking about, but it's too bad the mistakes (by the umps) are
being made at crucial times of the ballgames. We made mistakes and
hurt ourselves but at the same time, they're taking away something
from us that we do very well and that's battle.''
</P>
<P>
   Later on down the road, maybe baseball will take up the cause of
the Red Sox, asking umpires to stop being so immune to making sure
they make the right call.
</P>
<P>
   But the bewildered and persecuted Sox have a more immediate
problem: how to end the Boston Tear Party and get ready to play
better Monday night, so there will be no way an umpire's call can
kill them.
</P>
<P>
   Laura Vecsey is a P-I columnist
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
