<P>
   AFGHAN-MASSACRE (Bazarak, Afghanistan) _ Afghanistan's ruling
Taliban militia, along with thousands of Pakistanis lit with the
fervor of jihad, went on a destructive spree this summer. By Barry
Bearak.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: A map has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   JAMAICA-POLITICS (Kingston, Jamaica) _ The killing of a
successful businesswoman and former cabinet member has set off a
wave of confessions: not by sullen-faced killers, but by Jamaican
politicians who have apologized for creating a culture that
encouraged violence as a campaign tactic and self-interest as a
ruling tenet. By David Gonzalez.
</P>
<P>
   MONTENEGRO-INDEPENDENCE (Cetinje, Yugoslavia) _ With its economy
spinning toward disaster, tiny Montenegro is close to taking one
more formal step toward independence from Slobodan Milosevic's
Yugoslavia: the establishment of its own currency. By Steven
Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: A map has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   JERUSALEM-ARABS (Jerusalem) _ Israel has liberalized its rules
under which Arabs living in Jerusalem often were forced out of the
city. By Joel Greenberg.
</P>
<P>
   KYRGYZSTAN-ISLAM (Osh, Kyrgyzstan) _ Ever since five new nations
emerged in Central Asia from the ruins of the Soviet Union, there
have been warnings that the region was ripe for Islamic
insurrection and insurgency. This summer, just such an insurgency
erupted in Kyrgyzstan, the smallest and most democratic country in
the region. By Stephen Kinzer. (With a map.)
</P>
<P>
   MONTENEGRO-INDEPENDENCE (Cetinje, Yugoslavia) _ With its economy
spinning toward disaster, tiny Montenegro is close to taking one
more formal step toward independence from Slobodan Milosevic's
Yugoslavia: the establishment of its own currency. By Steven
Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Locator map has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-PEPSI-CAPITALIST (Moscow) _ Donald M. Kendall, the
American who arguably brought capitalism to Russia 40 years ago,
came back for a visit to reports of bribery and money-laundering,
to Mercedesful of impeccably suited thugs, to political wars raging
among the lap-dog newspapers and television networks of too-wealthy
tycoons, to the throngs of street urchins and dumpster-miners. All
in all, he said, it could have been worse. By Michael Wines.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SCI-ASTHMA _ This is the other inner-city epidemic: asthma. The
burden of AIDS on the poor and minorities has been well documented.
Asthma is less deadly; it claims about 5,000 lives in this country
each year, fewer than a third of those deaths attributed to AIDS.
Yet the death statistics do not begin to tell the story of how an
unprecedented _ and unexplained _ explosion in asthma cases is
suffocating the nation's poorest urban residents, especially
children. By Sheryl Gay Stolberg.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photos have been sent to NYT photo clients. A graphic
has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   CENSUS-POVERTY (Indianapolis, Ind.) _ The Census Bureau wants to
rewrite the formula it has used for 34 years to set the poverty
line. It proposes to raise the line to $19,500 from $16,600 for a
family four. The change would greatly increase the percentage of
Americans recognized by the government to be living in poverty. By
Louis Uchitelle.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo has been sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic has
been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   NY-SPANISH-BOOM (New York) _ How the influx of Hispanic people
in New York has created a boom in Spanish classes for non-Hispanics
for business and personal use, even for toddlers. By Mirta Ojito.
</P>
<P>
   NY-DEAD-LOBSTER _ Lobsters are dying all over Long Island Sound
and nobody knows why. By David Barstow.
</P>
<P>
   MISSILE-SILOS (Langdon, N.D.) _ Beneath the flat, broad plains
of North Dakota, where the push of a button could have ignited a
nuclear attack, the earth is exploding. It is the sound of peace.
In a thunderous exclamation point to the end of the Cold War, some
150 steel and concrete silos, once the launching tunnels of the
nuclear Minuteman III missiles, are being blown to bits by
dynamite. By Dirk Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CAMPAIGN _ (Moved in ``p'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-MINORITIES (Seattle) _ Texas Gov. George W. Bush's outreach
to minorities _ the visual complement to his oratorical slogan of
compassionate conservatism _ is his most powerful signal to swing
voters that he is not an extremist, that he occupies enough
territory near the center of the political spectrum to warrant
their allegiance. By Frank Bruni.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON _ (Moved in ``w'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   NUKE-PLANT _ Opponents of a government nuclear fuel processing
plant near Richland, Wash., seek to keep it idled. By Matthew L.
Wald.
</P>
<P>
   MCCONNELL-PROFILE _ A profile of Mitch McConnell, the senator
who staves off campaign finance changes. By Robin Toner.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS DAY _ (Moved in ``f'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ONLINE-TRADING (Undated) _ A look at how old-line Wall Street
brokerages are entering the Internet stock-trading bazaar. By
Joseph Kahn and Patrick McGeehan.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: A graphic has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   HARRY-POTTER-PUBLISHER (London) _ The remarkable success of the
``Harry Potter'' books has raised the profile _ and the profits and
share price _ of the series' British publisher, Bloomsbury
Publishing PLC, which hitherto has been an relatively obscure
producer of highly regarded, but slow selling, literary works. By
Alan Cowell.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   CHARITIES-TAXES-INTERNET (Undated) _ The detailed tax returns
that charities file annually with the federal government will be
posted on the Internet beginning on Monday, giving quick and easy
access for the first time to comprehensive details on how charities
use their money. By David Cay Johnston.
</P>
<P>
   PC-GAMES (Undated) _ From the fellow who prompted Wal-Mart to
back the ``Deerhunter'' PC games comes something else for the
heartland: ``The War in Heaven,'' an action-packed ``spiritual
warfare'' game based on Christian theology. By Steve Lohr.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: A photo has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   DATABASE-AD-COLUMN (New York) _ The trade organization
representing the nation's advertising agencies is planning one of
its most ambitious projects ever, providing information online
about members that could help them win new clients. The American
Association of Advertising Agencies, known as the Four A's, plans
to announce on Monday its sponsorship of what is intended to be a
nonpartisan, nonprofit data base devoted to new business. By Stuart
Elliott.
</P>
<P>
   ONLINE-SHOPPING (Undated) _ The E-Commerce Column: A look at the
peak shopping times of the day online for various retailers, and
the implications for retailers during normal months vs. the
implications for everyone during the holiday season. (Presumably,
if everybody shops online during their lunch hour during the
holiday season, the U.S. portion of the Internet could slow down
from noon until 4 p.m. ET _ not just e-comm sites.) By Bob
Tedeschi.
</P>
<P>
   PATENTS (Undated) _ The weekly patents column. By Sabra
Chartrand.
</P>
<P>
   MEDIA-TALK (Undated) _ A selection of short news items from the
media world.
</P>
<P>
   COMPUTER-BRIEFS (Undated) _ A selection of short news items
about computers.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CULTURE (Moved in ``e'' category) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   DANCE-PLAY (New York) _ How the dance play at Lincoln Center
Theater was put together. By Robin Pogrebin.
</P>
<P>
   NY-CANADA-ARCHITECTS (New York) _ A look at the finalists in the
Canadian Center for Architecture proposals for Manhattan's West
Side railyards. By Herbert Muschamp.
</P>
<P>
   ANIMALS-BOOK-REVIEW (Undated) _ Christopher Lehmann-Haupt
reviews ``Dogs That Know When The Masters Are Coming Home: And
Other Unexplained Powers of Animals,'' by Rupert Sheldrake.
</P>
<P>
   ANGER-THEATER-REVIEW (New York) _ Peter Marks reviews ``Look
Back in Anger,'' performed by the Classic Stage Co.
</P>
<P>
   EDNA-THEATER-REVIEW (New York) _ Ben Brantley reviews ``Dame
Edna: The Royal Tour'' at the Booth Theater.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY (Moved in ``k'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   HERBERT-COLUMN (Undated) _ Bob Herbert on basketball in Indiana.
</P>
