<HEADER>
A0115 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BBA-REDSOX-SABERHAGEN     10-18 0663
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RED </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SLOPPY DEFENSE OVERSHADOWS SABERHAGEN EFFORT 
</HEADLINE>
 SOX-SABERHAGEN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Playoff games in all sports expose weaknesses as much
as they crown champions, and Sunday &UR;  &LR; night's so-called playoff
game, won by the Yankees, 9-2, exposed weaknesses long known by
many.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox' infield defense, inconsistent all season, again
cracked at key moments as Nomar Garciaparra and Jose Offerman made
errant throws, giving extra outs _ and eventually extra runs _ to
the New Yorkers. And the Yankees' Chuck Knoblauch continued his
travesty of second base play; he's unable to catch some balls
cleanly and able to throw all balls anywhere but to Tino Martinez
at first.
</P>
<P>
   And American League umpires, with Tim Tschida the latest to blow
an obvious call, once again exposed their weaknesses of eyesight,
positioning, and overall competence. Knoblauch's throwing is no
more a debacle than umpires blatantly missing calls.
</P>
<P>
   Yet amid this comedy of fielding, throwing, and umpiring
incompetence, the most crucial error of all may have been when Red
Sox starter Bret Saberhagen dropped a throw while covering first in
the fourth inning, allowing the Yankees to take a lead they would
not relinquish.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always thought I make that play 10 out of 10 times,''
said Saberhagen, one of baseball's better fielding pitchers. ``I
guess now it's only nine out of 10 times. I should have been out of
that inning with only one run (given up).''
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox were leading, 2-1, in the fourth with one out when
Bernie Williams hit a shot to the right of Garciaparra, who fielded
the ball but fired high to first base, allowing the Yankee to reach
second. Tino Martinez then drove home Williams with a double toward
the Red Sox bullpen. After an intentional walk to Darryl
Strawberry, Saberhagen caught Scott Brosius looking at a third
strike for the second out.
</P>
<P>
   And when Chad Curtis hit a bouncer to Mike Stanley at first, it
seemed the damage would be minimal. But when Stanley tossed the
ball to Saberhagen covering, the pitcher seemed to take his eye off
the ball as he was trying to locate the first base bag with his
foot. Saberhagen not only dropped the throw but kicked it far
enough away that Martinez was able to score from second.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, I was looking down at the bag,'' said Saberhagen.
``(Stanley) said to me, `Maybe I should have thrown the ball a bit
harder to you,' but that had nothing to do with the deal. I was
trying to get the bag, and I didn't see the ball into the glove; I
didn't watch it all the way in.''
</P>
<P>
   Both before and after that fourth inning, Saberhagen pitched
sharply, allowing only a second-inning homer by Strawberry off the
right-field foul pole (the umpires did get that call right). ``I
adjusted my mechanics,'' said Saberhagen. The Yankees lineup also
is several notches below the Indians' in the fear-and-trepidation
department, but beyond that, Saberhagen said he intentionally
slowed down his mechanics, ``and I felt very good out there; I was
able to locate the ball a lot better.''
</P>
<P>
   Not so good afterward, though, as the pitcher voiced his
displeasure at two blown calls going against the Red Sox in the
series, both involving Knoblauch's misadventures at second base:
the first in the 10th inning of Game 1 when all the baseball world
saw Knoblauch drop a throw except umpire Rick Reed; a mistake
topped only by Tschida's mis-call in the eighth inning
Sunday &UR;  &LR; night, calling Offerman out when Knoblauch clearly had not
tagged him. In each case, Knoblauch was fumbling and bumbling but
was saved by the umpires.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're frustrated, and it doesn't sit well with us,'' said
Saberhagen. ``We were clearly disappointed (with Tschida),
especially with Nomar coming up with a chance to tie the ball game.
(Stuff) happens, I guess.
</P>
<P>
   ``I only hope that same (stuff) happens to the Yankees tomorrow
night.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-18-99 0223EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
