<DOCNO> NYT19991018.0075 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-18 02:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0116 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BBA-YANKEES-PETTITTE-     10-18 0593
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKEES-PETTITTE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PETTITTE QUIETLY EMPHATIC 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB DUFFY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ You could call him the forgotten man of the Yankees
rotation, but that would have been overstating his influence
entering the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   With the attention of the baseball world riveted on Apocalypse
Now _ the Saturday showdown between Red Sox Past and Present, New
York's Roger Clemens and Boston's Pedro Martinez _ nobody even
bothered to notice Andy Pettitte.
</P>
<P>
   Rocket Roger indeed supplied fireworks, but not the kind the
Yankees had in mind. By the tine Clemens finished imploding at
no-longer-friendly Fenway Park, allowing six hits and five runs in
two innings plus before leaving to standing derision, Martinez and
the Red Sox were on their way to a 13-1 anticlimax, and the Yankees
suddenly were in a most precarious position.
</P>
<P>
   True, they still led the best-of-seven American League
Championship Series, 2-1, but the momentum seemed to have taken up
residence on Yawkey Way, especially with the Sox hosting the next
two games and the marvelous Martinez brothers, Ramon and Pedro,
laying in wait for Games 6 and 7, if necessary.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, Pettitte, Sunday &UR;  &LR; night's starter, acquired an
identity _ last resort.
</P>
<P>
   But that didn't last long. By the time the lefthander was
finished with his work in Game 4, he could answer to no other name
than ``Series Saver.''
</P>
<P>
   It was easy to overlook him once again because of the farcical
umpiring and mob rule into which the game degenerated at the end.
</P>
<P>
   But throughout Pettitte's tenure, it was a taut, wrenching
struggle, and he never fell off the tightrope, nursing a one-run
lead from the fourth until he left, and then watching the Yankess
steamroll to a 9-2 triumph that leaves them one win from returning
to defend their World Series title.
</P>
<P>
   Pettitte was not dazzling, just remarkably resourceful. He
allowed eight hits but walked only one and struck out five. And
after donating a 2-1 lead to the Red Sox by allowing them single
runs in the second and third _ and being spared more severe damage
by a run-saving relay to the plate _ he made the next edge the
Yankees gave him, 3-2, nonrefundable.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel great, being able to get the win; obviously, it was
huge for us,'' he said. ``It was a very emotional game for us. It
seemed like I was in trouble every inning, but most of the hits
they were getting were ground balls through the infield.''
</P>
<P>
   That was the key. Unlike his predecessor the day before,
Pettitte didn't permit any fly balls into the net. And while
Clemens is still trying to get the ``Rog-er, Rog-er,'' chants out
of his ears, Pettitte wasn't rattled by the jeer du jour: ``An-dy,
An-dy.'' At least not overly so.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fans were really into it,'' he said. ``It was a very
emotional game. Sometimes it was tough to control my emotions.''
</P>
<P>
   But he had no problem deflating the Red Sox with his assortment
of curves, cut fastballs, and changeups.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last night they got some momentum back,'' said Pettitte. ``To
keep them from getting to 2-2 was huge.''
</P>
<P>
   By now, people were paying attention to Pettitte, whose major
achievement during his 14-11 season was surviving the trade
deadline. He insists that had nothing to do with his turnaround
from a 5-7 start to a 9-4 flourish after the All-Star break.
</P>
<P>
   All the Yankees know is that they're thrilled to have him in
October. Thanks to him, they got the pressure pitching they needed.
So what if it was a day late? Roger who?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-18-99 0224EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991018.0076 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-18 02:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0117 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BBA-YANKEES-STRAWBERR     10-18 0550
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKEES-STRAWBERRY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OLD FACE INFLICTS NEW PAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE FAINARU  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Darryl Strawberry, you may recall, had one RBI in the
1986 World Series. It was a dagger through the Red Sox' heart: a
home run off Al Nipper on the Straw Man's final at-bat in Game 7.
</P>
<P>
   Strawberry has been through many incarnations since then, but
you still can hear him coming before he actually appears. A
collective gasp is heard as he exits the on-deck circle, then the
familiar chant, ``Dar-ryl, Dar-ryl'' as he steps into the box.
</P>
<P>
   Strawberry, 37, may be close to the end now, but he still has
enough power to torture the Townies. He hit a home run off the
right-field foul pole off Bret Saberhagen in the second inning
Sunday &UR;  &LR; night, and it set the stage for the Yankees's 9-2 drubbing
over the Red Sox in the American League Championship Series.
</P>
<P>
   The homer had to be gratifyng for Strawberry, who almost
certainly drank, snorted, and otherwise abused himself out of a
Hall of Fame induction. He still has 332 career homers and 994
RBIs, but he will be recalled as much for his tumbles off the wagon
as for his hitting.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, he missed the postseason entirely when he was
diagnosed with colon cancer. After months of chemotherapy, he said
recently, he became depressed, and during spring training he was
arrested for soliciting an undercover police officer while
possessing a small amount of cocaine wrapped in a $20 bill.
</P>
<P>
   Strawberry called the incident ``one slip.'' Major League
Baseball suspended him 120 days for violating baseball's drug
policy and his own aftercare program. He said he then met with
George Steinbrenner to decided whether he had a future with the
team.
</P>
<P>
   ``He just basically told me that he knew I had been through a
lot,'' Strawberry said. ``He knew I was going through a lot of
pressure.''
</P>
<P>
   Strawberry ended up playing in 24 games this year, hitting .327
with three home runs. In Game 3 of the Division Series against the
Rangers, he hit a three-run homer in the first inning, creating a
cushion for Roger Clemens, who coasted to his first playoff win in
13 years.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, Torre has alternated at designated hitter with
Strawberry and the dangerous Chili Davis, who played 146 games and
hit 19 homers. ``I have no rhyme or reason,'' said Torre. He said
he makes the decision ``game to game with those guys because, you
know, if somebody gets hot, then they stay in there. Right now,
it's just a feel thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Strawberry's advantage, Torre said, is his big-hit potential.
``Darryl's a force,'' he said. ``The one thing that Darryl gives
you is the threat of a home run. And we may need a boom here
tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   As if on cue, Strawberry delivered in his first at-bat. As
Saberhagen ran the count to 2-2, the familiar chant washed over the
field. Strawberry got hold of the next pitch in dramatic fashion,
lofting the ball down the right-field line, toward the famous Pesky
pole.
</P>
<P>
   The only question was whether the ball would go out. It seemed
to hang for a second against the black sky, then smashed into the
mesh screen that extends from the pole and fell back to the playing
field. The crowd went limp. The Red Sox playoff hopes soon
followed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
