<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-18 02:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0120 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BBA-SHAUGHNESSYCOLUMN     10-18 0898
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-SHAUGHNESSY </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOORISH BEHAVIOR DISGRACEFUL 
</HEADLINE>
 COLUMN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ This was ugly. Fenway Park's Saturday euphoria gave way
to Sunday boorishness when some Red Sox fans disgraced the city of
Boston and risked causing a forfeit of Sunday &UR;  &LR; night's fourth game
of the American League Championship Series between the Red Sox and
Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   In a hail of errors, bad umpiring calls, and worse conduct by
Boston fans, the Yankees beat the Red Sox, 9-2, to take a 3-1 lead
in the best-of-seven series. The game was delayed for eight minutes
in the bottom of the ninth inning when nitwits threw debris at the
umpires and the Yankees, prompting home plate ump Al Clark to clear
the field.
</P>
<P>
   It was scary. Police were unable to stop dozens of unruly
spectators from tossing things and the reigning world champion
Yankees cleared the field while officials weighed the merits of
resuming the game.
</P>
<P>
   Said Yankee manager Joe Torre, ``The sad part about it is, you
have a ballclub like the Boston Red Sox who have . . .busted their
ass and given this city something to be proud of, and I think it's
inexcusable. It surprised me. Everywhere I've walked in Boston the
last four days, people have been genuinely nice. But to have people
throw stuff, that's disgraceful. I know it's not an indication of
Boston, Massachusetts. It's been a lot of class to me, but tonight
was a bad mark against a very good team.''
</P>
<P>
   Assuming she feels safe enough, Julia Ruth Stevens, the
82-year-old daughter of Babe Ruth, is scheduled to throw out the
first pitch of Game 5 Monday night. If Sunday &UR;  &LR; night is any
indication, whoever the Sox select to catch the toss will drop Baby
Ruth's pitch and get charged with a passed ball. Or the umps will
make a blatant mistake and call a balk on the Babe's little girl.
</P>
<P>
   A lot of frustration was built up in the eight-and-a-half
innings that preceded the unruly ninth of Game 4. It was a tight
game for a full eight innings, but the Sox were stymied by a close
play at the plate in which Jose Offerman was thrown out, several of
their own errors, and then a horrid call by second base umpire Tim
Tschida in the bottom of the eighth.
</P>
<P>
   Tschida joined Larry Barnett and Rick Reed in the pantheon of
umpires who've bungled calls against the Red Sox in October.
</P>
<P>
   The Yanks led, 3-2, in the eighth when John Valentin hit a
one-out grounder to Yankee second baseman Chuck Knoblauch. Offerman
was running from first and easily avoided Knoblauch's tag attempt,
but Tschida ruled Offerman out and the throw to first completed the
double play.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't make the right call,'' admitted Tschida. ``I got the
best position I could. It's difficult to get the angle you want
without getting in the way. I called the play on the reaction of
the runner and the fielder. It appeared to me that he got him.''
</P>
<P>
   Wow! Three Red Sox losses. Two midnight confessions by men in
blue.
</P>
<P>
   How can this stuff keep happening? Every time we are finally
convinced that there's no black cloud renting space over Fenway
Park, something new happens to reinforce the fear that Larger
Forces are calling the shots when the Red Sox play in October.
</P>
<P>
   Boston's protests went unheard and in the top of the ninth the
mighty Yanks broke it open with six runs. The Sox helped out with
their fourth error of the game.
</P>
<P>
   Then came Boston's ninth. Nomar Garciaparra grounded to third
and clearly beat the throw to first, but he was called out by Dale
Scott. That was enough for Jimy Williams. He'd seen the mistake by
Reed in Game 1 (the umpire issued a public apology) and the blunder
by Tschida, and now Scott. Williams got himself tossed from a 9-2
game. That's when the stuff started flying.
</P>
<P>
   Yankee owner George Steinbrenner told Fox-TV, ``It could happen
anywhere and I'm just sorry it happened here because we've been
treated well here. Their manager was my candidate for manager of
the year until tonight when he really invoked it. He incited it, I
should say.''
</P>
<P>
   Torre said, ``I think the crowd was frustrated and Jimy _ if he
incited the crowd _ that wasn't his intention. He was frustrated,
sure. Maybe the fans used (it) as an excuse to do what they did.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams refused to come to the interview room after the game
and sent this statement: ``It's the first one to win four, and it's
not over yet.''
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox are not done yet, but their fans did much to tarnish
the reputation of Boston sports spectators. There was some
well-documented unruliness at the Ryder Cup last month and a
nationally televised near-riot from Fenway won't soon be forgotten.
</P>
<P>
   Too bad. These should be proud days in old Boston. There is
stardust on the sidewalks of the Back Bay, the Pru at night is lit
up in ``Go Sox,'' and the ``Reverse Curve'' sign on Storrow Drive's
outbound lane near the Fiedler Bridge has been altered to read
``Reverse Curse.''
</P>
<P>
   But all of it was splintered by the behavior of frustrated fans.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox get to the playoffs and it happens. Umpires blow
calls that go against the Red Sox. Boston players make errors they
usually don't make. Easy grounders become adventures. Easy throws
go wild. Sure double plays become no plays. Games are lost that
should not be lost.
</P>
<P>
   And now the city is disgraced by a band of unruly fans.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
