<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991018.0080 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-18 02:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0121 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BBA-REDSOX-ANALYSIS-B     10-18 0942
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RED </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TSCHIDA: THE MAN IS BLUE 
</HEADLINE>
 SOX-ANALYSIS-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL HOLLEY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The call was awful. Even the man who made it, Tim
Tschida, could admit that. It was just after midnight, and the
umpire/suspect sat in an interview room and tried to explain why he
didn't do his job.
</P>
<P>
   Tschida's problem at Fenway Park Sunday &UR;  &LR; night was that he
claimed to see something that never happened. In the eighth inning,
he ruled that Chuck Knoblauch tagged out Jose Offerman to end the
inning. Knoblauch missed Offerman by at least two feet.
</P>
<P>
   It was a terrible call, the second the Red Sox have suffered in
four American League Championship Series games against the Yankees.
They now trail the series three games to one. Winter could begin
for them Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't make the right call,'' Tschida said after a couple of
minutes in front of the cameras. He explained that he was in bad
position on a tough play. ``I couldn't get into position where I
could see daylight between the glove and runner.''
</P>
<P>
   What he didn't say was that he was humiliated, but you could
tell that he was. He screwed up on national television. Before this
game, people probably didn't know how to pronounce his name. Now
they know (Chee-duh), because of his brutal night at the office.
They could start carving officials' faces into a new, dubious Mount
Rushmore, and he would be there with Rick Reed (Game 1 failure) and
Eugenia Williams (calling Evander Holyfield-Lennox Lewis a draw).
</P>
<P>
   After Tschida left the room, he stood in a Fenway Park corridor,
accompanied by Marty Springstead, the American League's supervisor
of officals. You would have thought Tschida was 2 years old because
Springstead did all the talking, as if Tschida couldn't speak for
himself. That seemed to be more humiliating than the blown call.
People throughout the park were saying that Tschida cost the Sox
the fourth game of this series, 9-2.
</P>
<P>
   I think that logic is worse than the phantom call at second base
itself. All Tschida did was make one error on a night when almost
everyone had a Do/Say Something Stupid quota.
</P>
<P>
   It started with the Sox, who handled the ball as if it were an
explosive. They had four errors in a championship series game,
something that championship teams never do. It continued with
Tschida, who never should have given Knoblauch the benefit of the
doubt. (Memo to the umps: Why don't you guys get it? The man is a
menace in the field. He barely can pick up a ball and throw it
straight. What makes you think he can make an athletic play,
running to his left, tagging out a runner, and throwing to first
without incident?) Stupidity reached its highest level when Sox
fans began throwing trash on the field, prompting the umpires to
clear the area for the safety of the players.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the night of errors could not end there. A security
guard, supposedly on the field to protect the Yankees, began
cursing out the players. ``The head of security for the Red Sox was
screaming at my players,'' Yankees manager Joe Torre said. ``That
was disappointing, the show of absolutely no class whatsoever.''
</P>
<P>
   Torre was right. But all he needed to do was look to his boss
for additional crassness. George Steinbrenner went on television
and said that Jimy Williams incited a riot-like atmosphere by being
thrown out of the game in the ninth inning. Williams was upset over
another questionable call in the ninth and went on the field to
vent. He was, predictably, tossed.
</P>
<P>
   All of that, and people were still complaining about Tim
Tschida.
</P>
<P>
   We are all aware of the problems umpires are having in the
majors. Many of them are arrogant. Many of them don't enforce the
strike zone. Many of them never would think of standing in front of
a national press corps and admitting to mistakes. But, please,
let's not confuse the arrogance of umpires with throwing bottles at
the New York Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't agree with the call,'' Sox first base coach Dave
Jauss said. ``But I didn't think the umpires deserved to have
bottles thrown at them. That's why I stood out there with them when
things were being thrown, hoping that people wouldn't throw if I
was with them.''
</P>
<P>
   Sorry, Dave. You were thinking too clearly and rationally for a
night like this. If you had done something inane, it would have fit
in with the evening.
</P>
<P>
   Yankees right fielder Paul O'Neill was nearly floored by a
bottle. The profane security guard nearly got into a scuffle with
Yankees reliever Jeff Nelson.
</P>
<P>
   And all anyone wanted to talk about was Tim Tschida.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not the story, guys,'' Jauss said. ``I know it works
out for you, but that's not the story.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sox' starting pitcher, Bret Saberhagen, said his teammates
don't feel the umpires have it in for them. Keep in mind that
Reed's call certainly could have changed Game 1, but
Sunday &UR;  &LR; night's call came when the Sox were trailing, 3-2, and
facing Mariano Rivera, the best closer in baseball. They could have
taken the lead. That's it. Could have. The umpires never should
have put themselves in position to be questioned in a loss like
this, but they were not the cause of the defeat.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Expletive) happens,'' Saberhagen said. ``Maybe some of that
(expletive) will happen to the Yankees (Monday).''
</P>
<P>
   Tschida and Reed certainly haven't done the Sox any favors this
series. But with Rod Beck's bad pitch in Game 1 and Jason Varitek's
drop in the same game and a failure to bring 13 runners home in
Game 2 and the four errors Sunday . . . well, they haven't done
themselves any favors, either.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
