<SLUG> BC-BBA-RED </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OFFERMAN STUCK IN MIDDLE 
</HEADLINE>
 SOX-OFFERMAN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK BLAUDSCHUN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Jose Offerman said he heard one explanation and then
another from second-base umpire Tim Tschida. And he didn't believe
either one.
</P>
<P>
   Not that it did any good for Offerman or the rest of the Red Sox
in Sunday &UR;  &LR; night's 9-2 loss to the Yankees in Game 4 of the
American League Championship Series at Fenway Park.
</P>
<P>
   Nor was there any solace for Offerman when Tschida conceded that
he didn't get the call right when he ruled that Yankees second
baseman Chuck Knoblauch had tagged Offerman out on a ground ball
hit by John Valentin in the eighth inning of a 3-2 game.
</P>
<P>
   It was just one of a series of controversial and pivotal plays
that Offerman found himself in Sunday &UR;  &LR; night.
</P>
<P>
   ``At first (Tschida) said he (Knoblauch) tagged me,'' said
Offerman in a quiet Red Sox clubhouse. ``And then when (Red Sox
manager) Jimy (Williams) came out to argue, he said that I ran out
of the basepath. I knew where I was, and I knew that he didn't tag
me. Once Jimy came out there, he changed his call.''
</P>
<P>
   Tschida said later, ``I didn't get the call right,'' but
contended that he never changed the ruling when he was on the field
with Williams and Offerman.
</P>
<P>
   It was a night of turmoil for Offerman. It started in the bottom
of the third, when he was thrown out at the plate after trying to
score from first following a Valentin double off the left-field
wall.
</P>
<P>
   The relay from Yankees shortstop Derek Jeter to catcher Joe
Girardi was perfect, and Offerman was tagged out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just running the bases and couldn't see where the ball
was,'' said Offerman. ``They made a good throw.''
</P>
<P>
   Red Sox third-base coach Wendell Kim said sending Offerman
wasn't even an issue. ``I've done it before, and it will happen
again,'' said Kim. ``You guys wouldn't even be talking to me if he
had been safe.''
</P>
<P>
   After the controversy in the eighth, Offerman again found
himself in the middle of the action when a throwing error on what
looked like a routine force play or even a rally-killing double
play to Nomar Garciaparra was low and wide, starting a series of
events that resulted in a six-run Yankee rally.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just a low throw,'' said Offerman.
</P>
<P>
   It was all he could do, all the Red Sox could do.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're good umpires,'' said Offerman. ``But they didn't make
the (right) calls.''
</P>
<P>
   But Red Sox relief pitcher Derek Lowe summed it up best for
everyone in the room.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure, it's frustrating,'' said Lowe. ``But despite all the
calls, right or wrong, we're still down, 3-1.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
