<DOCNO> NYT19991018.0082 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-18 02:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0123 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BBA-ALCS-UMPIRES-BOS &LR;      10-18 1477
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ALCS-UMPIRES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UGLY ENDING FOR UMPS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Fenway Park, baseball's emerald jewel, turned varying
shades of ugly Sunday &UR;  &LR; night, the pot of discontent stirred in the
stands by a combination of bad umpiring and the ejection of Red Sox
manager Jimy Williams, and followed by a heated verbal altercation
between Yankees reliever Jeff Nelson and Steve Corcoran, Fenway's
chief of security.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought he was just going to get ejected and that would
relieve the stress of the play,'' recounted Fenway security guard
Paul Anderson, reliving the moments after Williams was given the
heave-ho in the ninth inning. ``Then all of a sudden it got real
ugly, and some bottles and a lot of debris came from all around.
</P>
<P>
   ``For a while there, I thought I might have to go out on the
field and stop a riot situation.''
</P>
<P>
   For the second time in the best-of-seven-game American League
Championship Series, the Sox were battling the men in blue as much
as the men in Yankees gray. At the root of Sunday &UR;  &LR; night's hubbub
was a bad call by second base umpire Tim Tschida, who ruled that
New York second baseman Chuck Knoblauch tagged out Jose Offerman as
the Sox second baseman dashed toward second on a John Valentin
roller in the eighth inning.
</P>
<P>
   Tschida, in the media interview room after the game, explained
that it is difficult for an umpire to get a good angle on such
plays. He admitted, after watching a replay, that he should not
have flashed the out sign.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't make the right call,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The fans in the stands finally had enough of the arbiters'
ineptness in the ninth when Nomar Garciaparra clearly beat out a
roller to third baseman Scott Brosius. First base ump Dale Scott,
however, emphatically flashed the out sign, bringing the irked
Williams bolting from the dugout. Fed up, Williams tossed his Red
Sox hat into the air, earning the ejection, then kicked around some
Back Bay dirt before he exited.
</P>
<P>
   Only moments later, the umpiring crew was calling for all
players to leave the field. Debris was cascading from the
bleachers, the shower of cups and popcorn boxes aimed at the Yankee
bullpen. A cloud also came showering down toward the umpires, much
of it from the stands around first base.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have been treated beautifully in Boston,'' said Yankees
owner George Steinbrenner. ``Don't blame the umpires. When the
opposing manager threw his hat and kicked the dirt _ I think he
incited it.
</P>
<P>
   ``You guys don't remember the '70s. It was really brutal here,
brutal in New York, too. They didn't have a good game tonight _
these things happen. We didn't have a good game last night.''
</P>
<P>
   When peace in the stands was restored, following a delay of
eight minutes, it was only a few moments before more trouble
erupted. The Sox' No. 6 hitter, Troy O'Leary, shot a double to
right field, chased down by Paul O'Neill. As he dashed into the
corner, O'Neill had to duck more debris. After he collected the
ball and threw it to the infield, the Yankee right fielder pointed
out to the unpires a fan dressed in a bright orange wig, his face
painted white. Police and Fenway security personnel promptly
escorted the fan out of the park.
</P>
<P>
   When Jason Varitek fanned to end the night, Fenway security
personnel emphatically warned the players on the Yankee bench not
to go on the field. Catcher Joe Girardi needed no advice. Without
so much as lifting off his facemask, Girardi dashed off the field.
``I just didn't think it was smart to stay out there,'' said
Girardi.
</P>
<P>
   Other Yankees did gather on the field for a brief celebration.
</P>
<P>
   Not seen from the stands was a verbal altercation in the New
York dugout between Nelson and Corcoran. ``He was just cussin at
us,'' said Nelson, ``tellin' us to get the `F' in the dugout and
telling us to shut the `F' up. I mean, we've got the head of
security telling us that? I played for Seattle, and I've gotten
beer dumped on me, but nothing like this. This is ridiculous.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're sore losers. I think they are better off losing
(Sunday night). They'd better lose (Monday night), because I think
56,000 or 57,000 fans (at Yankee Stadium) are going to appreciate
(sic) what they did to us tonight. It shouldn't be retaliation, but
(Monday night) we just have to try to take care of business.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Neill was not as fazed by the fan reaction. ``They were
throwing a bunch of stuff,'' said O'Neill. ``There was a plastic
bottle. This is the story tonight. We just won the game, didn't
we?''
</P>
<P>
   The fans, said O'Neill, were obviously frustrated. ``It's not
the first time we've seen this,'' he said. ``I don't think anybody
got hurt. They just wanted to voice their opinion.''
</P>
<P>
   Capt. Charles Cellucci of the Boston Police Department, in
charge of the detail at Fenway, said at 12:10 Monday morning there
were two arrests at or around the time of the debris being thrown
on the field. He also said police made two arrests outside the park
after the game.
</P>
<P>
   Cellucci said he was notified of the problems by officers
working the detail. ``There was debris being thrown, missiles,
plastics soda bottles,'' he said. ``Some were filled, some were
half-filled, some were empty. They were being thrown from
everywhere around the field. As frustrated as the fans might be,
they have to realize that can cause serious injury. It's a crime to
disrupt a game like that. From what I could see, it was coming from
all over.''
</P>
<P>
   Cellucci said it was up to the umpires to stop the play, not the
police. He said that when notified of the debris being thrown he
had his officers on and around the field proceed toward the areas
of concern. ``We have to show a strong presence, and that's what
did it,'' he said. ``It didn't last more than two or three minutes.
The whole time the game was stopped was about eight minutes, so it
didn't last that long.''
</P>
<P>
   Yankees manager Joe Torre was upset that Corcoran had screamed
at his players. ``A show of no class, whatsoever,'' said Torre.
</P>
<P>
   After the game, a Red Sox initially said Corcoran had left
Fenway Park. When Corcoran later emerged, about an hour after the
last out, a security official tried to stand in front of a Globe
reporter who attempted to interview him.
</P>
<P>
   Corcoran, a long-time Sox employee, referred all questions to
Kevin Shea, director of public relations. Shea said he was not
certain what occurred in front of the Yankee dugout, but he
attributed the incident to tension surrounding the situation on the
field.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the Yankee reports that Corcoran repeatedly swore at
the players as they stood in the dugout, Shea said: ``I know the
man. I wasn't there, but I know him very well, as we all do around
here, and I cannot believe that he was swearing. But if there was a
sense of urgency, it was because of the safety for the fans and the
umpires.''
</P>
<P>
   Shea said he was not sure what action the Red Sox would take
regarding the incident. ``I think the first thing to do is to make
sure that nothing happens (Monday night),'' he said. ``For the
players' safety, the umpires' safety, and the fans' safety.''
</P>
<P>
   Cellucci said he was not certain what had happened in front of
the Yankee dugout. As for the fan who was escorted out of Fenway
after the incident with O'Neill, Cellucci said he had been involved
in an argument with the right fielder but police were unable to
determine who had actually thrown the bottle. ``No one could
identify him,'' Cellucci said.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the park, not long after the game ended, Boston police
broke up a small group of fans outside Gate A as they chanted,
``Yankees Suck.''
</P>
<P>
   Skip Bancroft, a fan who saw much of what happened inside and
outside the park, said it was ``the first time I'm embarrassed to
be a Red Sox fan _ and it has nothing to do with the team.''
</P>
<P>
   Peter deBernado was in the right-field stands and saw the Yankee
bullpen empty under a cloud of debris thrown from the bleachers and
stands. A life-long Yankee fan who grew up in Rochester, N.Y., the
34-year-old deBernardo now lives in Danvers and makes it a point
not to wear any Yankee gear when he attends games at Fenway.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know I'm happy,'' he said. ``But I don't like to win on
bad calls like that. It looks like the Sox are done now, but you
never know _ hey, look what happened to the Mets today. But I do
believe the Sox are cursed, too, and I'm not superstitious about
anything. You look at what happened in '78 and '86, it always comes
down to a moment when they collapse. Look at those two near home
runs the other night in New York. My father's 75 years old, and
he's seen a lot of Yankee success _ and he said he saw Ruth's ghost
out there when those balls didn't make it over the fence. There's
just always something _ like they're not going to do it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
