<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-18 02:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0124 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BBA-YANKEES-KNOBLAUCH     10-18 0595
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKEES-KNOBLAUCH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KNOBLAUCH ISN'T TELLING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN POWERS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ He couldn't say whether he'd tagged Jose Offerman or
not. ``I'm just playing the game, trying to make the play,''
Yankees second baseman Chuck Knoblauch said, after yet another Red
Sox nightmare had unfolded with him in the middle. ``Slow grounder
hit to me. I went after it, then I went after Offerman. Then I had
to continue and make the play at first.''
</P>
<P>
   Did his glove touch Offerman as he dashed to second on John
Valentin's one-out bouncer in the eighth? ``I have no idea,''
Knoblauch said. Did Offerman run out of the basepath? Knoblauch
couldn't say.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're asking me these questions, and you've seen the replay
15 times,'' Knoblauch told his inquisitors. ``I haven't seen it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It looked like you missed him,'' he was told. Knoblauch
shrugged. ``I have no comment on that.''
</P>
<P>
   The Boss pays him to lead off and to play second base for the
world champions. He is not paid to make calls on himself. ``If I
was an umpire, I would be wearing blue and white,'' Knoblauch said.
``Not Yankee gray.''
</P>
<P>
   He has been involved in double play situations thousands of
times since he first suited up for Little League. The first
instinct is to get the lead runner. The second is to get an out
somewhere.
</P>
<P>
   When Knoblauch saw Offerman sprinting past him, he took a swipe
with his glove and knew it had to be enough. There was no time to
toss to shortstop Derek Jeter for the force.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once I field the ball and try to get the man going by, I have
to go to first,'' Knoblauch said. ``I didn't know what else was
going on. I threw the ball to first and looked around and saw the
umpire call the double play.''
</P>
<P>
   He didn't know he would be in the middle of a firestorm. Not a
second time. In Game 1, with the score 3-3 in the top of the 10th
and Offerman on first, Knoblauch dropped an easy toss from third
baseman Scott Brosius on another double-play ball and was still
awarded an out by umpire Rick Reed, who later admitted to the world
that he blew the call.
</P>
<P>
   Somehow, controversy seems to follow him around like a mongrel
dog. In New York, bleacher creatures call WFAN radio and debate
whether Knoblauch should be in the lineup at all. Any time he's
come to a press conference during this series, it seems, manager
Joe Torre has had to explain and exonerate him.
</P>
<P>
   Knoblauch batted .292 during the regular season with 68 runs
batted in and a career-high 18 homers. He also made a career-high
26 errors, most on the club since third baseman Graig Nettles did
the same 26 years ago. ``That's part of the package,'' Torre keeps
saying. ``Whatever we get with Knoblauch, we get.''
</P>
<P>
   He is batting .308 against the Red Sox. Sunday &UR;  &LR; night, he was on
base three of five times and scored the run in the ninth that began
the six-run deluge that put Boston six feet under. But whenever the
ball is hit to second, Yankee fans hold their breath. Offerman had
reached base on a ball hit at Knoblauch. Though he was awarded a
single on a tough chance, Offerman would have been safe anyway.
Knoblauch threw the ball away.
</P>
<P>
   Once the nightmare was done, and the Fenway denizens walked out
cursing fate and anyone in arbiter blue, Knoblauch stood by his
clubhouse cubicle wearing a gray T-shirt that read HIT ME. ``Is it
a coincidence that you've been in the middle of both these
controversies?'' he was asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``A coincidence?'' Chuck Knoblauch pondered. ``I think it is.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
