<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-BRAVES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METS IN IT FOR LONG HAUL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALLEN LESSELS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Mets are halfway to another miracle.
</P>
<P>
   Third baseman Robin Ventura, struggling mightily at the plate
through most of this National League Championship Series, made sure
of that Sunday &UR;  &LR; night.
</P>
<P>
   With the bases loaded in the 15th inning and New York trailing,
3-2, Ventura drilled a 2-1 pitch over the fence in right field to
give the Mets a rainy and remarkable 4-3 win and send the series
back to Atlanta with the Braves ahead, three games to two.
</P>
<P>
   It was declared a 4-3 win, not 7-3, because Ventura was given
credit for just a run-scoring single because he never made it
around the bases to home. He was mobbed by his teammates before he
reached second base.
</P>
<P>
   ``It didn't look like he was going to run the bases,'' said Todd
Pratt, who had worked a walk to force in the run that tied it. ``He
tagged first. I tagged second. John (Olerud) tagged third. Grand
slam. Single. It doesn't matter.''
</P>
<P>
   All that matters is that the Mets outlasted the Braves. It took
a playoff-record 5 hours 46 minutes _ and a 14th-inning stretch
during which most of the 57,723 Mets drenched fans sang ``Take Me
Out to the Ballgame'' for a second time _ to do it. It took a
record total of 45 players. It took the Braves leaving 19 on base.
</P>
<P>
   It took players who hadn't played much and a hitter who hadn't
hit much.
</P>
<P>
   And it took a tremendous bottom-of-their-last-ups-of-the-season
to do it. And the Mets did.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a team that obviously doesn't quit,'' Ventura said.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously.
</P>
<P>
   Facing a task no Major League Baseball team has ever
accomplished _ winning a seven-game series after being down, three
to none _ the Mets get to play another day.
</P>
<P>
   Or night. Tuesday night. to be exact. Most likely it'll be New
York's Al Leiter vs. Atlanta's Kevin Millwood.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets, after falling behind, 3-2, in the top of the 15th,
pulled it out in dramatic fashion. Shawon ``I'm a hacker, not a
walker'' Dunston fouled back six straight 3-2 pitches, then singled
up the middle. He stole second on a 2-2 pitch before pinch hitter
Matt Franco walked. Edgardo Alfonzo sacrificed Dunston and Roger
Cedeno, who was running for Franco, to second and third.
</P>
<P>
   And Pratt, the backup catcher and home run-hitting hero of the
Mets' Division Series-clinching win over Arizona, began to smile.
``I knew it was going to come down to me,'' Pratt said. ``I knew
they weren't going to pitch to Olerud.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Kevin McGlinchy intentionally walked Olerud, who had hit
a two-run homer in the first inning.
</P>
<P>
   So McGlinchy faced Pratt.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bases were loaded,'' Pratt said. ``I knew he had to throw
me strikes.''
</P>
<P>
   Not so. He threw three straight balls, then a strike, another
ball. Pratt walked, forcing in a run.
</P>
<P>
   It was Ventura time.
</P>
<P>
   Ventura had come into the game zero-for-the-series and was up to
0 for 16 when he singled in the 11th.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's already walked a guy,'' Ventura said. ``He can't really
fool around and throw a bunch of pitches in the dirt. So I'm just
trying to get a ball in the air so the guy can score.''
</P>
<P>
   Ventura got it in the air a long, long way, over the fence in
right for what must be the longest single he's ever hit.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as I touch first, we win,'' Ventura said. ``So that's
fine with me.''
</P>
<P>
   For Mets manager Bobby Valentine, it was another display of
resiliency. ``Kind of getting used to it,'' he said. ``It seems
like we've been doing this for a couple of weeks now. And the guys
are getting used to it, too. And God bless them, they're
fabulous.''
</P>
<P>
   Two down. Two to go.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-18-99 0249EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
