<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-18 03:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0149 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r w BC-INTERNET-WINE-SFCHRON     10-18 1065
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-WINE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 THREAT TO INTERNET SALES UNCORKS A NEW ALLIANCE  &HT;     By CAROLYN LOCHHEAD 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In the geography of Washington lobbying, the
valleys Napa and Silicon share fame, cachet and that rawer
attribute, power.
</P>
<P>
   But there seemed little to join the interests of Cabernet and
computers until an assault on their mutual turf _ a bill to crack
down on Internet wine sales _ pushed the two powerful California
industries into an unusual alliance.
</P>
<P>
   The sponsors of the ``21st Amendment Enforcement Act'' say they
want to stop teenagers from buying booze in cyberspace. Wineries
contend the measure is actually aimed at protecting state liquor
wholesalers from direct sales of wine over the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Napa Valley was losing badly, but Silicon Valley largely ignored
the dispute until the bill breezed through the House of
Representatives on August 3 after passing the Senate on a voice
vote.
</P>
<P>
   At that point, the high-tech industry suddenly realized that if
states could ban Internet wine sales, they might restrict other
electronic commerce as well, opening a Pandora's box of
product-targeted Internet regulation.
</P>
<P>
   Within a month of the bill's House passage, Palo Alto chipmaker
Intel Corp. _ whose stationery commands attention on Capitol Hill _
fired off a letter to Senate Judiciary Committee Chairman Orrin
Hatch, the Utah Republican who has jurisdiction over the measure.
</P>
<P>
   ``Intel, like other companies that are collectively building the
`new economy' through the products and services which form the
infrastructure of e-commerce, has a great stake in the preservation
of an Internet free of discriminatory taxation and regulation,''
wrote F. Thomas Dunlap Jr., Intel's vice president for law and
government affairs.
</P>
<P>
   Whether the arrival of reinforcements from Silicon Valley will
be enough to stop the wine bill, which awaits a House-Senate
conference to shape its final version, remains to be seen. But
winemakers are joyous.
</P>
<P>
   ``The high-tech community has galvanized support,'' said John
DeLuca, president of the Wine Institute, representing California
wineries. ``It's new strength for us, new power for us, and new
credibility.''
</P>
<P>
   While framed as a debate over how to stop alcohol sales to
minors, the wine fight bears all the marks of a classic Washington
special-interest battle, this one pitting vintners against
wholesalers.
</P>
<P>
   The bill's chief sponsor, Republican Rep. Joe Scarborough, hails
from Florida, headquarters of Southern Wine and Spirits of America,
the nation's largest liquor wholesaler. Florida is one of five
states that has made it a felony for manufacturers to sell
alcoholic beverages directly to consumers.
</P>
<P>
   Scarborough's ``21st Amendment Protection Act'' is named after
the 1933 constitutional amendment that lifted federal Prohibition
and, in exchange, gave states the power to restrict alcohol sales.
In most states, those restrictions include bans or tight limits on
direct shipments of wine, beer or spirits to consumers. Most states
require alcoholic beverages to be sold through state-licensed
wholesale distributors and local retail outlets.
</P>
<P>
   (California permits residents to buy two cases of wine a month
from out-of-state wineries, if the state allows its own residents
to do the same.)
</P>
<P>
   For years, wineries battled in state legislatures to loosen the
restrictions, while wholesalers battled back to tighten them.
</P>
<P>
   The fight suddenly escalated with the arrival of the Internet,
which vastly widened the potential for consumers to buy wines _
often hard-to-find boutique labels that wholesalers don't carry _
directly from vintners. Wholesalers, arguing that state attorneys
general are unable to prosecute out-of-state wineries, went to
Congress to get a federal statute allowing them to sue wineries in
federal court.
</P>
<P>
   The political fault lines broke against the vintners from the
start. Although solid backing from the huge 54-member California
delegation usually gives winemakers the upper hand, local liquor
distributors dot every congressional district in the nation. With
the issue framed as a remedy for teenage drinking, the bill sailed
through the House 310 to 112.
</P>
<P>
   That set off a few alarms in Silicon Valley, which is acutely
aware that the explosive medium of the Internet threatens not just
the Prohibition-era liquor distribution system, but nearly all
traditional retail commerce.
</P>
<P>
   The Association for Interactive Media, representing America
Online, Yahoo, RealNetworks and other Internet companies, warned
Hatch that the wine bill could invite not just states, but even
nations, to restrict electronic commerce in the name of protecting
local laws and customs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Other nations are eager to impose language requirements,
prohibitions against importing clothing that violates religious
customs and other idiosyncratic restrictions of electronic commerce
that disadvantage remote sellers,'' the trade group wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than seek the bill's outright defeat, Californians are
backing a House amendment inserted by Rep. Chris Cox, a Southern
California Republican and a savvy opponent of Internet regulation
and taxation.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Cox's amendment in effect could force states that want to
sue a winery to first prove that they are not discriminating
against Internet sellers to protect their own local industries.
This provision, based on the Constitution's interstate commerce
clause, could pose a big hurdle to the very state lawsuits that the
wine bill is intended to permit.
</P>
<P>
   Both Silicon and Napa valleys are now throwing their combined
weight behind the Cox amendment and are bringing politicians with
them, including Sens. Daniel Patrick Moynihan and Charles Schumer,
both New York Democrats. Whatever the final outcome, the wineries
are so pleased with their newfound friends in high tech that the
Wine Institute's DeLuca said he hopes to forge a formal alliance in
the next six months.
</P>
<P>
   That's a view shared by Rep. Mike Thompson, a Democrat from the
Napa Valley who vainly fought the wine bill on the House floor.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most important thing the Cox amendment did was bring this
to the attention of the e-commerce community,'' Thompson said.
``There have been people who have tried to get them involved, but
they didn't for whatever reason. Maybe they didn't think it was a
real threat.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
