<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991018.0107 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-18 09:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0273 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-R-NOTEWORTHY-PAPERBAC     10-18 0935
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-NOTEWORTHY-PAPERBACKS-$ADV24-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW &AMP; NOTEWORTHY PAPERBACKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, Oct. 24)  
(lb) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; SCORPION TONGUES: The Irresistible History of Gossip in
American Politics &LR;  By Gail Collins. Harvest/Harcourt Brace, $14.
This compendium of political gossip includes both famous rumors
from the 19th and 20th centuries and others that were long
forgotten. Not surprisingly, there's a fat chapter on the Clinton
years, pre- and post-Monica. The result is ``a breezy, timely
history,'' Wendy Kaminer wrote in The New York Times Book Review
last year.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; OPENED GROUND: Selected Poems, 1966-1996 &LR;  By Seamus Heaney.
Farrar, Straus &AMP; Giroux, $15. This generous selection, which
includes works from the poet's 12 previous volumes, a few
uncollected poems and his 1995 Nobel Prize address, digs deep in
the ground of memory and is dense with the bodies of the ancient
and recent dead. Much of the verse is suffused with domestic detail
but is shadowed by the Troubles in Northern Ireland. ``Heaney has
assembled a collection with a satisfying heft and more than enough
variety of subject and style to delineate the shape of a long and
constantly evolving career,'' Edward Mendelson wrote in 1998. ``It
eloquently confirms his status as the most skillful and profound
poet writing in English today.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; GRAND CENTRAL WINTER: Stories From the Street &LR;  By Lee Stringer.
Washington Square/Pocket Books, $12.95. The author is a former
crack addict and homeless man who started writing after he found a
pencil in a crawl space beneath Grand Central Terminal in New York.
His unflinching memoir gives readers ``the long view of New York's
underbelly, born of pain but delivered with style and heart,'' John
Jiler wrote last year.
</P>
<P>
   In  &UR; SLEEPING WITH THE MAYOR: A True Story &LR;  (Hungry Mind, $15),
John Jiler chronicles New York's attempts to deal with the homeless
issue during the last decade, and his own interaction with a ragtag
group of protesters camped in City Hall Park during the
administration of Mayor Edward Koch. He ``offers a persuasive
portrait not only of a tough problem but of the larger society
surrounding it,'' Joyce Purnick wrote in 1997. ``He humanizes, but
refuses to romanticize, the characters he came to know.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE SMITHSONIAN INSTITUTION &LR;  By Gore Vidal. Harvest/Harcourt
Brace, $13. This novel about a young science prodigy summoned to
the Smithsonian to help a coven of physicists tinker with nuclear
fission and the space-time continuum is really an excuse to play
with the what-ifs of American history. Last year the reviewer
Christopher Benfey praised Vidal's ``eye for the freaks and foibles
of Washington.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; HERSELF SURPRISED &LR;  By Joyce Cary. New York Review, $12.95. The
robust heroine of this English novel, the first of a trilogy being
reissued by the publisher, is Sara Monday, a former housekeeper who
marries a rich gentleman and eventually winds up in prison. She is
``warm and real, and twice as natural as most women in fiction,''
Helen B. Parker wrote in 1948.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TO BE A PILGRIM &LR;  ($14.95) is narrated by one of Sara's lovers,
a pious, tight-fisted lawyer who reflects on his long life and lost
opportunities as he approaches death. In 1949 the reviewer George
D. Painter found the novel to have ``actuality like Defoe, humor
and energy like Dickens, hand-made prose and improvisation like
both these great writers.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE HORSE'S MOUTH &LR;  ($12.95) is the picaresque autobiography of
another of Sara's lovers, the irrepressible Gulley Jimson, a
raucous, bandy-legged artist who thumbs his nose at society in
grand style. ``Cary is a careful, even a profound, thinker'' whose
deeply moral tales are layered by the common themes of Protestant
grace and the conflict between individual freedom and authority,
Donald Barr wrote in 1950.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A MARITIME ALBUM: 100 Photographs and Their Stories &LR;  By John
Szarkowski and Richard Benson. Mariners' Museum and Yale
University, $24.95. This collection of images from 1859 to 1956 is
less a book about maritime history than a book that uses
photographs of shipyards, harbors and cockpits to fire the
imagination. The result is ``a moving testimonial to the exaltation
and apprehension of human interaction with the sea,'' W. Jeffrey
Bolster wrote last year.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BIG GIRLS DON'T CRY &LR;  By Fay Weldon. Atlantic Monthly, $13. This
wry novel about a circle of women who start a feminist publishing
company in 1970s London follows their quest for happiness and asks
the question: Was the women's movement worth all the fuss? ``Though
Weldon's satirical breeziness can be infuriating, it's always
entertaining,'' Elizabeth Gleick wrote last year.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; KING LEOPOLD'S GHOST: A Story of Greed, Terror, and Heroism in
Colonial Africa &LR;  By Adam Hochschild. Mariner/Houghton Mifflin, $15.
From 1885 to 1908, King Leopold II of Belgium directed a brutal
campaign of forced labor to plunder what is now the Democratic
Republic of Congo. This account of the frenzy of murder and
profiteering _ and of the figures, white and black, who rose up
against it _ is ``a superb synoptic history of European misdemeanor
in central Africa,'' Jeremy Harding wrote last year.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A LEXICON OF TERROR: Argentina and the Legacies of Torture &LR;  By
Marguerite Feitlowitz. Oxford University, $16.95. This grim book
focuses on the victims and crimes of the ``dirty war'' waged by the
military junta in Argentina. The result is ``a well-researched,
intimate and perceptive portrait'' of a nation still struggling
with its past, Tina Rosenberg wrote in 1998.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-18-99 0904EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991018.0108 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-18 09:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0279 &Cx1f; var-z
u a BC-R-THISWEEK-REVIEW-2TA     10-18 1106
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-THISWEEK-REVIEW-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWS OF THE WEEK IN REVIEW 
</HEADLINE>
  
(Repeating for all needing.)  (bl)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   A Bird's Eye View, for a Price
</P>
<P>
   Back-yard sunbathers and lovers on the beach have nothing to
fear. The resolution of the world's first private spy camera, now
orbiting 400 miles overhead, is insufficiently sharp to spot
individuals. But it can see much else, including buildings, roads,
pipelines, bridges, tanks, ships, jets and missiles.
</P>
<P>
   Space Imaging Inc., the private company in Thornton, Colo., that
built the spacecraft, made public the world's first commercial
image from space whose sharpness rivals those of military spies in
the sky. A closeup of Washington showed the intersection of 14th
and Constitution, cars and buses plainly visible.
</P>
<P>
   More orbiting snoops are on the way. Analysts see the
development as a boon for geographers and urban planners and a
potential nightmare for states and people with something to hide.
</P>
<P>
   _ By WILLIAM J. BROAD
</P>
<P>
   No Pain, Plenty of Gain
</P>
<P>
   Natural childbirth, drug-free in all its pain and glory, may be
losing its cachet. More and more women are saying no to labor pain
and yes to drugs, proffered by doctors with clever new ways of
giving spinal and epidural anesthetics that numb the pelvis but
still let a woman walk around.
</P>
<P>
   Advocates of natural childbirth demurred, warning of risks from
the drugs and lamenting the high-tech meddling with a rite of
passage. Some women do still want the full experience of labor and
the satisfaction of getting through it on their own.
</P>
<P>
   But plenty of others scoff at noble suffering. At an
anesthesiology conference in Dallas, doctors reported that from
1981 to 1997 there was a tripling of the percentage of women in
labor at large hospitals who had spinal or epidural injections,
from 22 percent to 66 percent.
</P>
<P>
   _ By DENISE GRADY
</P>
<P>
   Gore Lands Endorsement Of AFL-CIO
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore won the biggest plum awarded so far in
the presidential campaign: the endorsement of the AFL-CIO. With
Gore slipping in the polls and his rival, former Sen. Bill Bradley,
rising, Gore supporters hoped the labor federation's endorsement
would reverse the vice president's slide.
</P>
<P>
   Many Democrats hope the endorsement will do more for Gore than
it did for the last Democratic presidential candidate who received
such an early show of support from organized labor: former Vice
President Walter Mondale, who was swamped by President Ronald
Reagan in the 1984 election.
</P>
<P>
   _ By STEVEN GREENHOUSE
</P>
<P>
   California Sets Nurse Levels
</P>
<P>
   Managed health care began in California, and now the nation's
toughest health care regulations are springing up there, too. Gov.
Gray Davis signed a bill that will make California the first state
to require fixed staffing ratios of nurses to patients in
hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   Strongly backed by the state nurses' union _ and opposed by the
hospital industry _ the bill does not set specific ratios, but
leaves it up to the state Department of Health Services to set
staffing levels for various kinds of care.
</P>
<P>
   _ By TODD S. PURDUM
</P>
<P>
   Daily Cell Growth in Brain
</P>
<P>
   Biologists at Princeton University have found that the brain
generates a daily stream of new cells that migrate into the
cerebral cortex, the area that harbors higher intellectual
functions.
</P>
<P>
   Though it's too early to tell what the cells are doing, they
could be part of the brain's mechanism for learning. The discovery
was made in monkeys and is expected to prove true of people too. It
caps a series of findings that refute the longstanding view that no
new cells are formed in the adult brain.
</P>
<P>
   _ By NICHOLAS WADE
</P>
<P>
   New Clinton Plan for Forests
</P>
<P>
   Ever since President Clinton came to office, he's been at war
with timber companies, paper producers and others who want to
preserve and expand their use of the National Forest System to
harvest timber, dig mines and build roads. In his latest battle,
Clinton announced a plan that would ultimately put 40 million or
more acres of federal forests into a new category that would
prevent roads from being built _ and make them off-limits to
commercial activity.
</P>
<P>
   Western legislators were outraged, particularly because the
White House is using an administrative procedure that bypasses
Congress. But Clinton is betting that Republicans won't want to
take on the forest issue in an election year.
</P>
<P>
   _ By DAVID E. SANGER
</P>
<P>
   Fessing Up to Smoking Risks
</P>
<P>
   Philip Morris Cos., hoping to recast its corporate image and
make it more difficult for new smokers to sue, unveiled a new
Internet site that acknowledges the scientific evidence that
cigarette smoking is addictive and causes disease. But the company,
which had disputed such evidence for decades, soon confronted new
demands that it submit to federal regulation of cigarettes and
nicotine in light of its acknowledgment.
</P>
<P>
   _ By BARRY MEIER
</P>
<P>
   Suharto Case Is Dropped
</P>
<P>
   Many Indonesians were angry but few were really surprised. After
32 years in power during which he and his six powerful children
amassed fortunes, President Suharto saw his year-long corruption
case dropped for lack of evidence.
</P>
<P>
   This week an electoral assembly will choose a new Indonesian
president. Most people believe that only with a new government that
is not beholden to Suharto will there be any chance of a real
investigation and possible trial.
</P>
<P>
   _ By SETH MYDANS
</P>
<P>
   A Lean Fighting Machine
</P>
<P>
   After years of resisting change, the Army announced plans to
create lighter, more mobile combat brigades.
</P>
<P>
   With armored vehicles instead of tanks, the brigades would be
more agile than the ``heavy'' armored brigades, able to go anywhere
in 96 hours while still having more punch than light infantry or
airborne divisions.
</P>
<P>
   The new brigades are part of a ``major transformation'' planned
by the Army over the next decade, but restructuring efforts have
stalled in the past.
</P>
<P>
   _ By STEVEN LEE MYERS
</P>
<P>
   Colt's to Curb Gun Sales
</P>
<P>
   Colt's Manufacturing Co. is retreating from its 144-year-old
retail revolver business and will offer only boutique versions of
the Colt .45, the gun that won the West. Colt's, based in West
Hartford, Conn., had been struggling financially even before it and
other gun makers were hit with lawsuits from 28 cities and counties
seeking to recover costs from gun violence.
</P>
<P>
   Now the company plans to focus on sales to the military and to
collectors, and to lay off as many as 200 of its 700 workers.
</P>
<P>
   _ By MIKE ALLEN
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   No Charges in Ramsey Case
</P>
<P>
   After 13 months of grand jury testimony, the Boulder County,
Colo., district attorney decided there was not enough evidence to
indict anyone in the case of JonBenet Ramsey, the 6-year-old beauty
pageant queen who was found dead in her parents' home in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``We take no satisfaction in this result because a child killer
remains free and undetected,'' the parents, John and Patsy, said in
a statement, even though they had been the only real suspects in
the case.
</P>
<P>
   _ By MICHAEL JANOFSKY
</P>
<P>
   Big Move by Con Ed
</P>
<P>
   Consolidated Edison Inc. of New York announced plans to acquire
Northeast Utilities, the largest utility in New England, for $3.29
billion in a deal that could bring cheaper power to its customers.
Con Edison will become one of the largest utilities in the nation,
with a base of 4.7 million customers.
</P>
<P>
   Both companies want to be mainly distributors and not generators
of electricity. They are also preparing to sell electricity,
natural gas and other services to customers throughout the
Northeast as states open up their utilities to competition.
</P>
<P>
   _ By AGIS SALPUKAS
</P>
<P>
   A Nobel for Doctors' Group
</P>
<P>
   Doctors Without Borders won the Nobel Peace Prize for adhering
to ``the fundamental principle that all disaster victims, whether
the disaster is natural or human in origin, have a right to
professional assistance given as quickly and as efficiently as
possible.''
</P>
<P>
   The group of more than 2,000 medical professionals in 80
countries was formed in 1968 and often defied governments by
intervening without being asked.
</P>
<P>
   Among the places its volunteers have provided humanitarian aid
are Nicaragua, Vietnam, Lebanon, Afghanistan, Rwanda, Kosovo and
East Timor.
</P>
<P>
   Babbitt Inquiry Ends
</P>
<P>
   After an 18-month investigation, an independent counsel said
there was insufficient evidence to warrant charges against Interior
Secretary Bruce Babbitt or anyone else involved in a decision by
the Interior Department in 1995 to deny a permit for an Indian
gambling project in Wisconsin.
</P>
<P>
   The investigation centered on whether Babbitt lied in
congressional testimony about the decision. The statement by the
prosecutor vindicated Babbitt, a former Arizona governor.
</P>
<P>
   _ By DAVID JOHNSTON
</P>
<P>
   Drug Arrests in Colombia
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department said Colombia had broken that country's
biggest cocaine-trafficking ring with the arrest of the ring's
leader and other traffickers. Colombian officials pledged to
extradite the suspects back to the United States for trial. In
1991, Colombia stopped extraditions following a wave of killings
and bombings by drug cartels, but now officials are vowing to renew
the process even as they brace for possible violence.
</P>
<P>
   _ By BARRY MEIER
</P>
<P>
   Clintons Get New Home Loan
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton and Hillary Rodham Clinton have secured new
financing for their house in Chappaqua, N.Y. They now have a
30-year $1.36 million mortgage, with interest for three years at
7.5 percent and afterward at 2.75 percentage points over the
one-year Treasury bill rate.
</P>
<P>
   With the loan from PNC Mortgage, the First Couple no longer
needs the backing of Terry McAuliffe, a Democratic fund-raiser
whose offer of financial help had been criticized by Republicans
who said the arrangement smacked of special treatment.
</P>
<P>
   _ By DAVID STOUT
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
