   Also moved in the `a' category:
</P>
<P>
   LEWINSKY-LINGO-REVIEW (Undated) _ Although the epilogue to the
impeachment scandal is still being written, there are constant
reminders of our long national nightmare in Americans' every day
speech. Every era has its popular terms, but the impeachment
scandal _ with its overheated mixture of sex, lies, power and
audiotapes _ provided a bounty of material for Americans searching
for phrases that fit the cynical weariness that permeates so much
of the nation's popular culture. By Don Van Natta.
</P>
<P>
   TRIANGULATION-POLITICS-REVIEW (Undated) _ There is no higher
praise from Bill Clinton's devotees than when they applaud George
W. Bush for proving himself a deft triangulator. Bush says he does
not know what the word means. The definition, according to Dick
Morris, the former Clinton adviser who invented the idea, is: `A
process of taking the best ideas from each party and combining them
into a coherent policy and program. It is not just splitting the
difference, but molding a creative synthesis which rises above the
doctrine of either party.' By Richard Berke.
</P>
<P>
   CYBERWARFARE-REVIEW (Undated) _ The addition of an
information-war fighting capability to the U.S. military arsenal is
a watershed event, both adding cyberwar to the quiver of the
Pentagon and at the same time taking a set of military activities
which have for the last two decades largely been confined to the
black secret side of the military and intelligence world and making
them part of the military chain of command. At the same time the
new military command is a public acknowledgment that as the worlds
most technically advanced nation, the U.S. is also potentially the
most vulnerable to foreign cyberthreats. By John Markoff.
</P>
<P>
   MATHEMATICS-REVIEW (Undated) _ There is no Nobel prize in
metaphysics. But if there were, it would surely go to the thinker
who could solve the stubborn mystery of why mathematics so often
mirrors the workings of the physical world. Rocks arc through the
sky in parabolic trajectories, planets swing in ellipses around the
sun. And inside atoms, tiny particles move according to the
mathematics of quantum mechanics. A look at the work of Nobel
winners Gerardus 't Hooft and Martinus Veltman. By George Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   ENVIRON-COSTSBENEFITS-REVIEW (Seattle) _ Amid a study of whether
or not to breach four huge hydroelectric dams on the Snake River in
eastern Washington, which would restore 140 miles of it to a wild,
free-flowing condition and could revitalize endangered salmon runs,
government economists are adding a factor known as ``existence
value'' to their list of costs and benefits. Aside from calculating
the proposal's effects on jobs, electric bills and shipping rates,
the government is now hoping to assign a dollar value to Americans'
knowledge that a piece of their wilderness might be regained. By
Sam Howe Verhovek.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTSWRITING-REVIEW (Undated) _ The 1920s were the golden age
of sportswriting. A handful of talented and ambitious journalists
who found other paths to literary fame blocked began to notice, as
indeed their editors had already noticed, that an increasingly
affluent middle class was responding more to the exploits of Jack
Dempsey, Babe Ruth and Bobby Jones than to what would come to be
known as ``hard'' news stories. Within three decades, TV would make
athletes smaller than life. Rarely again would sportswriters see
athletes in such mythic proportions, outlined against skies
blue-gray or any other color. By Allen Barra. (moved in `a' and `s'
categories)
</P>
<P>
   NOBEL-TEXT-REVIEW (Undated) _ The Nobel Prize awards have often
provoked second-guessing. With the current Nobel season just
wrapping up, it's worth noting the critical reaction to some of the
disputed honorees of the past.
</P>
<P>
   WILT'S-WORDS-REVIEW (Undated) _ A look at some of the
controversial statements made by the late basketball star Wilt
Chamberlain. By Tom Kuntz. (moved in `a' and `s' categories)
</P>
<P>
   THISWEEK-REVIEW (Undated) _ Some highlights of the week.
</P>
<P>
   Also moved in `i' category:
</P>
<P>
   U.S.-WORLD-ROLE-REVIEW (Washington) _ The test ban treaty was
only the latest of a number of divisive issues in the capital that
share a common subtext: An argument not over whether the U.S. is
strong, but over how it should use its power. Should it strut the
global beach alone, or leverage that power by accepting restraints
on its freedom to act? It is that debate that has eroded the
``vital center'' that President Clinton talks about so often in his
laments about the disappearance of bipartisanship in foreign
affairs. By David E. Sanger. WITH GRAPHIC.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; QUESTIONS OR RERUNS: (888) 346-9867 &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Weekends, Tim Hilchey (e-mail, hilchey(at)nytimes.com).
</P>
<P>
   Phone: (888) 346-9867
</P>
