<DOCNO> NYT19991018.0120 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-18 09:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0296 &Cx1f; var-z
u a BC-R-RACE-HEALTH-REVIEW-     10-18 1066
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-RACE-HEALTH-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHITE DOCTORS, BLACK PATIENTS: NOT A SIMPLE CASE OF HEALTH RACISM 
</HEADLINE>
  
(Repeating for all needing.)  (The Week in Review)  
 (bl)  
 By DENISE GRADY  
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Not even sickness and death are beyond the reach of racial
inequality. Blacks are more likely than whites to suffer from
dangerous conditions like diabetes, high blood pressure and kidney
failure. Black women are more likely than whites to die in
childbirth.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most troubling news came last week: A study found
that blacks were less likely than whites to get surgery for early
stages of lung cancer and, as a result, more likely to die from a
potentially curable disease.
</P>
<P>
   What looked like a straightforward case of racism, though, may
well be something more complicated: a breakdown in doctor-patient
communications.
</P>
<P>
   The study is forcing doctors to confront what they may be doing
wrong: For some reason, their black patients are not getting the
message that surgery could save their lives.
</P>
<P>
   A legacy of suspicion may further cloud already emotionally
fraught doctor-patient consultations. For example, black doctors
say many black patients remain wary of the health care system
because of the notorious Tuskegee study, in which black men with
syphilis were left untreated for 40 years so that government
doctors could study the course of the disease.
</P>
<P>
   The new lung cancer study, based on the records of nearly 11,000
patients 65 and over, appeared in the New England Journal of
Medicine. The authors, led by Dr. Peter Bach of Memorial
Sloan-Kettering Cancer Center in New York, concluded that the
inequity in treatment seemed to stem from race itself. They found
no significant differences between the blacks and whites the study
tracked, in socioeconomic status, insurance, complicating illnesses
or access to care.
</P>
<P>
   When confronted with the racial disparities in care for blacks
and whites, many doctors have tended to blame the patient. Blacks
are prone to obesity, smoke more, and seek medical treatment later
_ often because they also tend to be poorer than whites, with lower
rates of health insurance and less ability to pay doctors' fees.
</P>
<P>
   But the study ruled out the usual excuses. That raised two
unpalatable possibilities. Either doctors were not recommending
surgery to blacks as often as to whites, or blacks, for some
mystifying reason, were more likely to say no to lifesaving
surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Harold Freeman, a cancer surgeon and president of North
General Hospital in New York's Harlem, dismissed the thought of
blatant racism. ``I'm not cynical enough to think people would
purposely deny someone treatment,'' said Freeman, who is black. ``I
have more faith in humanity than that.''
</P>
<P>
   Whites dominate the medical profession; only 4 percent of
doctors are black. In some cases white doctors and black patients
may have trouble talking to each other not just because of color,
or the undercurrent of tension between the races, but also because
of differences in social class, education, background and
attitudes.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Talmadge King, chief of medical services at San Francisco
General Hospital, said: ``We have tended to blame the patient, but
I think the problem is on the side of the doctors. It's up to us to
understand where the patient is and learn how to communicate so
they can understand what we're saying.''
</P>
<P>
   King said that if a doctor did not understand a patient's
background and presented information about cancer in a way that the
patient had trouble accepting, the patient might reject the advice
or might take so long to finally accept it that in the meantime the
cancer might advance and become inoperable.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a ticking time bomb,'' he said. ``Medical schools are
now getting very interested in training doctors to be culturally
sensitive and to understand diversity.''
</P>
<P>
   If a treatment is presented to a black patient as experimental,
King said, ``that can be really detrimental in your communication''
because it raises the specter of Tuskegee in some minds. In the
study, 400 black men were left untreated from 1932 until 1972, even
though penicillin came into use to cure syphilis during the 1940s.
And experimental treatment does come up in discussions about lung
cancer, because if the disease progresses after surgery, patients
may need chemotherapy and are often advised that they may benefit
from studies of new drugs. If that is not carefully explained by
someone the patient trusts, the patient may become alienated.
</P>
<P>
   Although Bach's study did not detect socioeonomic differences
between the black and white patients, Freeman said the records,
from the Medicare program for people 65 and older, may not have
been detailed enough to pick up such differences. Studies have
shown that blacks have less wealth _ fewer assets and savings, for
instance _ than whites even when their incomes are the same.
</P>
<P>
   Blacks, he said, ``are more often people with other priorities,
survival priorities like food, clothing and shelter, and avoiding
of crime, and then you tell them they also have cancer.''
</P>
<P>
   Doctors may have no idea what such patients' lives are like or
what sort of help they would need to rearrange their lives to deal
with a major illness.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Freeman said, ``I've practiced surgery in the black
community for 32 years, and it is a rare, rare patient who will not
follow my advice. So I am discomforted by somebody saying `We
couldn't communicate, we tried to tell this person and couldn't get
it over.' I say that's a poor excuse. If you take the time and say
it in the right way, the poorest people will understand. Poor black
people in Harlem are very reliable when you communicate to them in
an appropriate way. You can't throw up your hands and say, `I can't
communicate with these people.'''
</P>
<P>
   Telling someone he or she has cancer and must have all or part
of a lung cut out is a wrenching and arduous task. When the doctor
and patient come from different worlds and the patient seems
reluctant to listen, it may be easier for doctors to tell
themselves they have done their jobs and let the patient walk away.
</P>
<P>
   ``It comes down to, how much, really, fundamentally, deep down
in yourself do you value the other person?'' Freeman said. ``If you
were dealing with somebody who looked exactly like you look, would
you take it another step?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-18-99 0911EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
