<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-18 09:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0300 &Cx1f; var-z
u a BC-R-ENVIRON-COSTSBENEFI     10-18 1031
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-ENVIRON-COSTSBENEFITS-REVIEW-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THEY EXIST. THEREFORE THEY ARE. BUT, DO YOU CARE? 
</HEADLINE>
  
(Repeating for all needing.) 
 (ATTN: Wash., Ohio, Mass.)  (The Week in Review)  
 (bl)  
 By SAM HOWE VERHOVEK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ It sounds like a philosophical cousin to the age-old
question of whether a tree falling in the forest makes a sound if
no one is around to hear it. In this case, though, federal
officials are seeking to add an economic variable to the puzzle:
just how much is it worth to  &UR; you &LR;  to know that a once-dammed river
is running wild again _ even if you never visit it?
</P>
<P>
   In the midst of a major study of whether or not to breach four
huge hydroelectric dams on the Snake River in eastern Washington,
economists with the Army Corps of Engineers are adding a factor
known as ``existence value'' to their list of costs and benefits of
the contentious proposal.
</P>
<P>
   Breaching the dams would restore 140 miles of the lower Snake to
its wild, free-flowing condition and would, many biologists argue,
stand a good chance of revitalizing endangered salmon runs in the
river. Aside from calculating the proposal's effects on jobs,
electric bills and shipping rates, the government is now hoping to
assign a dollar value to Americans' knowledge that a piece of their
wilderness might be regained.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an indication that there are certainly folks out there
who are willing to pay for the existence of something in the
wild,'' said Dennis Wagner, the Corps official overseeing an
economic analysis for the agency. ``I think we'd be remiss in not
presenting something to the decision makers. How they use that
information is up to them.''
</P>
<P>
   The idea of existence value, favored by many environmentalists
as a legitimate policy tool in conservation debates and ridiculed
by critics as unquantifiable, meaningless or both, has been around
since the 1960s. ``There's not a single, agreed-upon definition,''
said Tom Stevens, a professor of resource economics at the
University of Massachusetts. ``But the basic idea is that yes,
people do place a value on things they know they are never going to
use, or maybe even to see.''
</P>
<P>
   The concept, also known as contingent value or passive-use
value, has been increasingly cited in legal battles over issues
like logging in the Alaskan wilderness or offshore oil drilling.
Yet many economists say that while existence value is, in theory, a
perfectly valid factor to bring to the table, coming up with
precise ways to gauge how much people value something like
wilderness is far more difficult.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea that you'd be willing to pay something for some state
of the world to exist, as you would pay for a commodity or a
contract for services, is not at all crazy,'' said Alan Randall,
chairman of the department of agricultural, environmental and
development economics at Ohio State University. ``The controversy,
really, is mostly about measurability.''
</P>
<P>
   In the Snake River debate, for instance, proponents of the
dam-breaching proposal have pointed to polls suggesting that
Seattle-area residents would be willing to pay a few extra dollars
a month on their electricity bills in order to save salmon runs. In
addition, Stevens and a team of economists at the University of
Massachusetts found in a survey several years ago that residents of
the Connecticut River Valley area said they would pay, on average,
$7.90 annually in higher electric bills for efforts to preserve
Atlantic salmon spawning in that river.
</P>
<P>
   And at the height of a legal fight with Exxon over the 1989 oil
spill from the Exxon Valdez tanker, the state of Alaska
commissioned a $3 million study of what Americans who said they
were unlikely to ever visit Prince William Sound would be willing
to pay to avoid a similar accident. About $30, was the average
respondent's figure.
</P>
<P>
   Using polls and other data, some economists at the Corps of
Engineers have calculated that breaching the four Snake River dams
and successfully restoring the salmon is an idea for which
Americans would be willing to shell out as much as $1 billion, but
others have pegged the figure much lower, said Wagner. ``It's
really not an exact thing,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, proponents of breaching the dams say that even if the
existence value of restoring the river and salmon can't be
precisely quantified, it is both large and meaningful. ``If that
guy in Dubuque thinks that this is important, that shows that this
is a national issue,'' said Chris Zimmer, a spokesman for Save Our
Wild Salmon, a Seattle-based environmental group. ``This is a
quality-of-life issue for people. It's important to their
well-being that they know we still have wild places left.''
</P>
<P>
   Critics argue, in effect, that it doesn't really matter what the
guy in Dubuque thinks. ``It's really an affront to the people who
live here,'' said Bruce Lovelin, executive director of the Columbia
River Alliance, which represents industrial users of the Columbia
and the Snake. ``I mean, unless you're going to come up here and
spend some money to recreate, don't tell us how we should run
things in the Northwest.''
</P>
<P>
   Others question whether such a value can be accurately measured.
``The only way to do it is to ask people what they would be willing
to pay, and in my view you ask people questions like that and you
get very upwardly biased results,'' said Jerry Hausman, an
economics professor at MIT. ``When somebody calls you on the phone
to ask, it's not real money.''
</P>
<P>
   Existence values are generally used to buttress the
environmentalists' side of the debate, but that doesn't mean all
environmentalists like the idea. ``Maybe it's really not
appropriate to try to put dollar values on something like
wilderness,'' Stevens said. ``After all, what if you add up all
those numbers and they don't come out in your favor?''
</P>
<P>
   Interior Secretary Bruce Babbitt, whose department oversees
national parks and much of the more than 100 million acres
designated as protected wilderness, also cautions against using
existence values in environmental debates _ but largely because
they may wind up understating the value of wilderness.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a huge collection of academic literature on all this,
and I've found it fairly unsatisfactory,'' Babbitt said in a
telephone interview. ``It all comes down to quantifying economic
activity, and I don't know if you can do that on any piece of
landscape.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know the cost of everything and the value of nothing, is
what this is all about,'' he added. ``You can't just cost this
stuff out.''
</P>
<P>
   The debate is complicated by the fact that many of the same
people who say they would pay to protect wild rivers and wild fish
would surely respond differently if asked whether they want to put
port workers in Idaho out of work or drive up shipping rates for
wheat farmers (both likely effects of the dam breaching plan).
</P>
<P>
   In the end, as Babbitt warns, economics could wind up driving a
debate that perhaps should be about something far deeper. Wallace
Stegner, one of the great writers of the West, was clearly talking
about existence value in his ardent calls for ``wilderness
preserved,'' but the author never veered into discussing actual
dollars and cents.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reminder and the reassurance that it is still there is
good for our spiritual health even if we never once in 10 years set
foot in it,'' he once wrote. ``It is important to us when we are
old simply because it is there _ important, that is, simply as an
idea.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-18-99 0915EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991018.0130 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-18 09:15 </DATE_TIME>
