<HEADLINE>
THE REAL POWER STRUGGLE ISN'T JUST ABOUT NUKES 
</HEADLINE>
  
(Repeating for all needing.)  (The Week in Review)  
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
 (bl)  
 By DAVID E. SANGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Step outside the United States for even a few days,
and the country has never looked more powerful: An economy that
won't quit, a military that has never faced fewer direct
challenges, a popular and business culture that has become the
world's most eagerly-sought export.
</P>
<P>
   But take one step back into Washington and it's easy to wonder
if you are talking about the same country. The president of the
most powerful nation at its most powerful moment has rarely looked
weaker than he did last week, when the Senate overwhelmingly
defeated the Comprehensive Nuclear Test Ban Treaty.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton responded with an hour-long recitation of the
dangers of a ``new isolationism.'' Republicans shot back that
Clinton had cynically sought to turn a popular but hard-to-enforce
treaty into a political weapon. Bickering along these lines will
doubtless go on for months. But it masks the real debate.
</P>
<P>
   The test ban treaty was only the latest of a number of divisive
issues in the capital that share a common subtext: An argument not
over whether the United States is strong, but over how it should
use its power. Should it strut the global beach alone, or leverage
that power by accepting restraints on its freedom to act?
</P>
<P>
   It is that debate that has eroded the ``vital center'' that
Clinton talks about so often in his laments about the disappearance
of bipartisanship in foreign affairs.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton himself, who has been episodic in focusing on foreign
policy, has ranged all over the map on this question. He preaches
cooperation one day and acts unilaterally the next _ whether the
issue is swatting Saddam Hussein or slapping huge tariffs on
low-cost Japanese steel. Usually, though, he has come down on the
side of power-sharing, either pressing for more arms control
accords even if that means a slow deterioration of the American
nuclear fleet, or granting more power to the World Trade
Organization even if sometimes strikes down American laws.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past three years battles have gradually gotten more and
more vociferous, as the Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty showed. Now
it has turned into an open fight, bound to haunt Clinton as he
finishes the last 15 months of his term. It is also certain to
plague his successor in a city where the consensus about U.S.
responsibilities in the world has splintered.
</P>
<P>
   It is a battle in which Clinton has steadily been losing ground.
In his first term he won over moderate Republicans to push through
the North American Free Trade Agreement and the global trade treaty
that created the World Trade Organization. True, these victories
came only after desperate legislative battles, but unlike the test
ban treaty, they were at least fought out in hundreds of hours of
hearings and public debate. But lately, with the exception of the
war in Kosovo, he has been unable to stitch together any kind of
majority for his international initiatives. He was unable even to
convince his own party to vote to give him authority to negotiate
new trade treaties _ a reminder that, for all his denunciations of
isolationism Thursday, most of the economic isolationists in
Congress are Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   And now, in a treaty that involved national security rather than
economic prosperity, the culmination of an idea whose intellectual
roots go back to Eisenhower Republicans, he became the first
president since Woodrow Wilson to face outright rejection of a
major international accord. The fact that Democrats and Republicans
were unable to agree on the obvious face-saving compromise _ a
delay of the vote until after the presidential election _ seems to
prove that the politics of post-Cold War Washington really are
different. ``It's inconceivable,'' one of Clinton's top advisers
said, ``that this would have been the outcome if the country still
felt under an imminent threat from a major enemy.''
</P>
<P>
   Even so, many of those who had doubts about the treaty and thus
voted against it would have preferred to see it postponed, amended
or at least fully aired in hearings rather than killed. Moderate
Republicans who voted no like John McCain, a presidential
candidate, were clearly uncomfortable with the message that the
treaty's rejection sent around the world. ``There has always been
an isolationist wing in our party and they were transcendent in the
'20s and '30s,'' McCain said Friday, trying to distance himself
from that group as fast as he could. ``It's still there, it will
always be there, yet I have every confidence that the majority will
take an international viewpoint.''
</P>
<P>
   Others say that the instinct in evidence on the Senate floor
Wednesday night was less about isolationism than about
unilateralism _ preserving America's ability to use its power
unchallenged. In the case of the test ban treaty, that means
retaining an ability to go back to traditional deterrence,
constantly improving America's nuclear arsenal and forcing a
resurgent Russia or an ambitious China to fear a financially
ruinous arms race. After all, the Soviet Union went that route and
bankrupted itself along the way.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think the Republican party has ever been or is now a
party of isolationism,'' said Michael Mandelbaum, a fellow at the
Council on Foreign Relations. Many of the Republicans who voted
against the treaty, he noted, rank among the Senate's strongest
internationalists. ``But there is a very strong unilateralist
impulse manifesting itself. That's very different. It's not opposed
to foreign entanglements, it just sends a message: `Don't tie our
hands.'''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton argued vociferously against that approach during his
press conference Thursday, warning that if an anti-test ban treaty
president ever gets elected (he named no names, but clearly had
George W. Bush Jr. in mind) ``we'll have China testing; we'll have
India testing; we'll have Pakistan testing.'' The result, he
argued, would be a return to an economically destructive arms race.
Sooner or later, he predicted, Republicans would be pressing for
``30 or 40 or 50 billion a year'' in additional defense spending.
</P>
<P>
   He may be right. But it is also possible that the lessons of the
Cold War run deep, and countries now feel far more competitive
pressure than they did a decade ago to invest that money in their
economic well-being.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the same moment that Clinton is talking about isolation,
American foreign investment is off the charts, American economic
engagement around the world is breaking all records,'' said Jeffrey
Garten, a former undersecretary of commerce and now dean of the
Yale School of Management. ``In some subtle way, this has
ricocheted back to Washington, and perhaps there are a lot of
people who feel that you can reject an arms control treaty and
still not be withdrawing from the world.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
