<SLUG> BC-R-WILT'S-WORDS-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WILT THE STILT'S VIEWS ON RACE AND HOOPS 
</HEADLINE>
  
(Repeating for all needing.)  (The Week in Review)  
 (duplication notice: also sent with `s' code)  
 (bl)  
 By TOM KUNTZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Basketball star Wilt Chamberlain, who died last week of a heart
attack at the age of 63, had a taciturn demeanor as a player, but
he was best-known off the court for bragging in his autobiography
that he had had sex with some 20,000 women.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, that wasn't nearly the half of Chamberlain's boasting
in ``A View From Above'' (Villard Books, 1991), which opened with
his disclaimer that although he was a big man, ``I am certainly not
 &UR; the &LR;  Big Man'' _ God _ in case anyone was confused.
</P>
<P>
   But perhaps most curious are Chamberlain's comments on race. At
one point in the book, he is derisive toward Al Campanis, the Los
Angeles Dodgers executive forced to resign in 1987 after he said on
national television that blacks ``may not have the necessities''
for management in baseball, and that blacks aren't good swimmers
``because they don't have the buoyancy.''
</P>
<P>
   In his book, Chamberlain asks why the Dodgers had no black
third-base coaches under Campanis. Was it because blacks ``can't
say stop?'' he asked. ``Or because they don't know when to go
home?''
</P>
<P>
   Yet at another point, Chamberlain offers his own views about
racial differences between black and white basketball players,
which attracted very little attention at the time.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps this is because there were juicier headlines in a former
star athlete claiming to have bedded 20,000 women, and because
Chamberlain was not an executive in a major sport using racial
stereotypes on ``Nightline'' to justify racial disparities in
management.
</P>
<P>
   This is what Chamberlain wrote:
</P>
<P>
   ``Men of color seem to be blessed with specific physical
attributes that benefit them in several sports, particularly
basketball. They have explosive muscle power that translates into
speed, quickness, and jumping ability (three major ingredients
needed to be a good jock, a good basketball player in particular).
</P>
<P>
   ``And there is another element that makes men of color tend to
stand out above the rest. For lack of a better word, let's call it
`flair' _ which translates into showmanship.
</P>
<P>
   ``A perfect example of this can be seen if you examine the
playing styles of the two best passers in the game of basketball
today, Magic Johnson and John Stockton,'' Chamberlain continued.
``At present, Stockton out-assists Magic _ on a per game basis _ by
approximately one assist. But Magic has that flair and Stockton
doesn't. It makes Magic appear as if he's doing much more than
Stockton. It's not ability, it's style. And in basketball, men of
color have all the style. Think about it.''
</P>
<P>
   He adds, ``I suppose this flair can be traced back to
environmental conditioning or heritage or even to the Harlem
Globetrotters, the true forefathers of all the showmanship that has
become the trademark of so many stars _ all men of color _ in the
NBA.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-18-99 0919EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
