<SLUG> BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Europe still going up in smoke
 &HT;    (For release Oct. 20, 1999.)
 &HT;    By Howard Kleinberg
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   THUN, Switzerland _ I am sitting in a delicious little
restaurant in this equally delicious lakeside town scarfing down a
pizza that is the best I have tasted in years. Nevertheless, I am
choking. There is so much cigarette smoke floating around the
establishment that I find it difficult to breathe. The smoke is
smothering _ and embedding itself in my clothing for me to savor
the remainder of the journey.
</P>
<P>
   If it is true, as most medical studies confirm, that cigarette
smoke is a catalyst for cancer, then the entire population of
Europe ought to be extinct before the end of the next century.
</P>
<P>
   As a former smoker (we're the worst kind), I found myself
strangling in secondary cigarette smoke in each and every Swiss
restaurant I ate in over a 10-day period _ as I have in other
European nations over the years.
</P>
<P>
   This surprised me about Switzerland. I've always connected
obsessive smoking to anxiety, tension. That's why the Israelis
smoke so much; they don't know when bombs will go off or armies
invade. The French also throw up clouds of smoke and I always have
attributed that to the apprehension that yet another labor strike
will close the airports, the Metro, the hotels _ that striking
truckers will block the highways, that irate farmers will dump
their produce on the road.
</P>
<P>
   The Brits smoke en masse, so do the Russians and just about
everyone else in Europe. This, despite overwhelming evidence of the
danger of cigarette smoke, certified by the announcement last week
that Philip Morris, the cigarette makers, have acknowledged that
smoking causes lung cancer and other diseases.
</P>
<P>
   But what are the Swiss so stressed about? One could stretch the
imagination by saying they smoke too much because they're
distraught over their tarnished image; the Nazi gold notoriety
contradicting an otherwise placid habitat in a remarkably beautiful
country. But I think too few Swiss are concerned about this, and
even fewer a party to it. So I can't explain their inclination to
kill themselves (and me) in clouds of lethal smoke.
</P>
<P>
   Interesting people, the Swiss. When traveling around the country
by train, you are afforded the choice of smoking or no-smoking
cars. In the hotels, there are no-smoking rooms if you so wish.
</P>
<P>
   But the restaurants? Open the door, walk in and expect the
worst. I did not find a Swiss restaurant that had a no-smoking
section. The best you can hope for is a table near the door, so
that when it opens a bit of fresh air blows in.
</P>
<P>
   We are not talking about just cigarette smoke here. We also are
dealing with pipes and cigars. It is a bombardment of assorted
fumes that permeate your food, your nostrils and your senses.
</P>
<P>
   I didn't realize until this visit how far ahead of the rest of
the world we Americans are when it comes to grappling with smoking
and its effects. We are eons ahead because we are making it safer
for non-smokers to dine, to attend public events, to do business in
public buildings without having second-hand smoke threaten our
tomorrows.
</P>
<P>
   The first thing people do here when they enter a restaurant is
reach into their pockets or purses and place a box of cigarettes on
the table, a statement that the smoke soon will begin to waft.
</P>
<P>
   And waft it does. It goes nowhere but into your lungs because
few of the restaurants are air-conditioned, the windows are shut
tight. The smoke spreads across the room much as an early-morning
fog settles over a field.
</P>
<P>
   You are the recipient.
</P>
<P>
   I'm always a sucker for Europe; love its culture, its
architecture, its scenery. But someday there might be an awful
price for me to pay for that enjoyment. My lungs can't take much
more.
</P>
<P>
   (Howard Kleinberg, a former editor of the Miami News, is a
columnist for Cox Newspapers. His e-mail address is
hkmiami(at)aol.com.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
