<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-18 10:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0389 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l BC-LATEST-SLANG-LIFEBEAT     10-18 1466
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LATEST-SLANG-LIFEBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KNOWING THE JARGON IS PHAT, PILGRIM
</HEADLINE>
  (Includes 6 color graphics illustrating words/Includes a 150-word
sidebar) 
 By BEN STEELMAN 
 c.1999 NYT Regional Newspapers 
 World rights 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   If it's phat, we're all about that, dude.
</P>
<P>
   Mouse potatoes in the cube farm may be ROFL over treeware, but
they're just whacked. And whatever you do, don't say ''groovy.''
</P>
<P>
   There's a whole new vocabulary of slang out there, pilgrim. If
you know it, you're mackin'. If you don't, you're a granny.
</P>
<P>
   ''It all changes so quickly,'' said Connie C. Eble, a professor
of English at the University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill, who
has gained national attention for her updated glossaries of college
slang.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, slang by its very nature is always changing, said Wayne
Glowka, a professor of English at George College and State
University, who edits the new words section of The Journal of
American Speech.
</P>
<P>
   By definition, slang is nonstandard and usually ephemeral,
Glowka said. It is primarily used for in-group solidarity, spread
by members of a subculture or clique to identify each other.
College students make up vast quantities of slang, Glowka said, to
signal that they're part of an in-crowd.
</P>
<P>
   However, once outsiders _ nonstudents or even worse, your own
parents _ decode the slang and start using it themselves, well, it
just turns bogus.
</P>
<P>
   Much once-potent slang has recently been ''outed'' (shortened
verb form of ''out of the closet,'' i.e., exposed as a homosexual,
or, more generally, exposed). Now its meaning has been frayed or,
in some cases, reversed. ''Radical'' or ''rad,'' once a synonym for
''good'' or ''cool,'' now implies ''uncool'' or ''phony.'' And
while Glowka noted that ''cool'' has had a remarkably long run as
slang, Filters, an online magazine for skateboarders, reports that
''cool guy'' refers to fakers with bleached hair and Billabong
shirts _ outsiders trying to fake their way into the group, but
failing in an obvious or inept way.
</P>
<P>
   So what's _ to use an aging piece of slang _ in?
</P>
<P>
   Among the new usages Eble has catalogued are ''all that,'' as in
the recent movie ''She's All That,'' a phrase meaning ''smart,''
''attractive'' or ''appealing.'' Another new phrase is ''all
about,'' implying interest or obsession, like ''He's all about
Phantom Menace'' or ''I'm all about dinner.''
</P>
<P>
   Rap music remains a fertile source of slang, for both black and
white students, Eble said. ''Phat,'' meaning good, rich or
desirable, is one longstanding example. Another, more recent one,
is ''Benjamin,'' as in ''Benjamin Franklin,'' an in-group reference
to the $100 bills commonly used in drug deals, now used by students
to refer to any denomination of cash or currency. (''Dead
presidents,'' a phrase which also became a movie title, has a
similar meaning.)
</P>
<P>
   Still more rap-inspired slang includes ''da bomb,'' referring to
something very, very fine; ''booty'' for body, especially the
posterior of same; ''ill'' for good; or ''chronic'' for
high-quality.
</P>
<P>
   The drug subculture also supplies slang to the general
population, even for youngsters not using drugs. ''Dope'' signifies
better than cool, at least among some skateboarders. ''Bogart''
still implies selfishness, 30 years after Fraternity of Man sang
''Don't Bogart That Joint, My Friend (Pass It Over to Me)'' on the
soundtrack of the movie Easy Rider.
</P>
<P>
   Yet another slang-generator is the virtual community of computer
users and hackers _ especially those forced to live in a symbiotic
relationship with corporate enterprise. The Berkeley Slang Database
notes a number of e-mail- and chat site-inspired abbreviations such
as ''ppl'' for ''people,'' ''lol'' for ''laughing out loud'' or
''rofl'' for ''rolling on the floor laughing.''
</P>
<P>
   The irony is laid on thick here; ''rofl'' implies a reaction to
something so dim or absurd, it's laughable.
</P>
<P>
   Other current computer-inspired slang:
</P>
<P>
   (BULLET) Mouse potato: The personal-computer equivalent of
television's couch potato; one who sits in front of a monitor,
playing with a computer mouse all day, while his physique
deteriorates to the approximate shape of a potato.
</P>
<P>
   (BULLET) Treeware: Anything, such as books or documents, in
old-fashioned paper form. Used derisively.
</P>
<P>
   (BULLET) Percussive Maintenance: The fine art of making
electronic hardware work properly by whacking it with one's palm or
fist.
</P>
<P>
   As you might have noticed, values are often transvalued in
slang; what was good for one generation becomes bad for the next
and vice versa. One example is the word ''geek.''
</P>
<P>
   When it first appeared, in the 1920s, the word referred to a
carnival performer who bit the head off live chickens or performed
some other disgusting act for money. Sometimes the word was used in
a pejorative sense as a synonym for freak.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, the term ''computer geek,'' arose and was adapted by
software fanatics as a badge of pride. Now the phrase ''alpha
geek'' is often applied to the best PC user in the office.
</P>
<P>
   The same subversive spirit that turned Scott Adams' ''Dilbert''
books into best-sellers seems to have coined a lot of employee
slang as well. A business whose office is filled with the
ubiquitous cubicles is often called a ''cube farm.'' A large cube
farm becomes a ''cube prairie,'' and when its inhabitants poke
their heads over the walls to see what's going on, the phenomenon
is termed ''prairie-dogging.''
</P>
<P>
   Some other recent slang specimens from the post-college
lifestyle:
</P>
<P>
   (BULLET) Body Nazi: An exercise and weight-lifting fanatic who
goes too far, especially one who looks down on anyone who isn't as
obsessed as he or she is. The ''- Nazi'' construction can also be
applied to any rigid or tyrannical person, such as an anti-smoking
''health Nazi'' or Seinfeld's Soup Nazi.
</P>
<P>
   (BULLET) Stress puppy: Someone who seems to thrive on being
stressed out, especially if he or she whines about it all the time.
</P>
<P>
   (BULLET) DINK: Acronym for ''Double Income, No Kids,'' the
epitome of the selfish (often yuppie) working couple. At the other
end of the spectrum from the DINKs are the SITCOMs (Single Income,
Two Children, Oppressive Mortgage).
</P>
<P>
   (BULLET) McJob: Minimum-wage employment involving mindless,
repetitive skills, often at a fast-food establishment; not a real
source of income. A more recent corollary to this is the GOOD Job,
or ''Get-Out-Of-Debt'' Job, which one quits once one reaches
solvency.
</P>
<P>
   (BULLET) Yuppie Food Stamps: The $20 bills spewed out of ATM
machines, usually to pay for lunch. Unavailable if the user has
been ''swiped out,'' i.e., if the magnetic strip on the ATM or
credit card has been worn off from overuse.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is the inevitable terminology for winners or losers.
A regular guy is still a ''dude'' it appears, and if he's ''mack''
or ''mackin' 6'' (a reference to ''Mack Daddy'' from rap lyrics),
he's in very good shape. Meanwhile a loser might be ''whacked,'' a
''trout'' or, in extreme cases, a ''chester.''
</P>
<P>
   The phrase ''pilgrim,'' as in ''Watch it, pilgrim!'' is often
used to address a newcomer or lesser member of the tribe _ a
backhanded tribute, apparently, to John Wayne. Somebody besides
Granny must be watching those old Westerns on AMC. bc-close
</P>
<P>
   (SIDEBAR)
</P>
<P>
   The Top 10 College Slang Terms, as reported at California State
Polytechnic University, Pomona:
</P>
<P>
   10. Cool: Well, like, cool.
</P>
<P>
   9. Grub, grub on: To eat. The word itself dates back at least to
the 1600s, although its use as a verb (''Let's grub downtown - know
a place?'') is fairly recent.
</P>
<P>
   8. Dope: Good, better than good.
</P>
<P>
   7. My bad: My fault, my mistake. Implies apology.
</P>
<P>
   6. Kick it: Relax.
</P>
<P>
   5. Tight: Way cool, sharp, attractive. (Remember Booker T and
the MGs' Time is Tight, recorded 1968?)
</P>
<P>
   4. Player, playa: An individual (usually male) who dates many
people (usually secretly) all at the same time. Someone not serious
about a relationship. A real player can be a cheater who gets
caught.
</P>
<P>
   3. Trip, trip out: A '60s survivor. To act crazy or
overemotional, to overreact.
</P>
<P>
   2. Chill, chill out: To relax.
</P>
<P>
   And the top college slang word
</P>
<P>
   1. Dude: A person, usually male, usually positive.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Ben Steelman writes for the Morning Star in Wilmington, N.C.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: Visit The New York Times Syndicate Website at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for more information on LifeBeat
and other features. &QL; 
 &UR; ------------------------------------------------- &QC;
</P>
<P>
   --------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To publish this ``separate buy'' article, call
New York Times Syndicate sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
(732) 390-4480 or fax her at (732) 390-4697.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
