<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PLANT-BULBS-NOW-LIFEBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLANT BULBS NOW: SPRING FLING BEGINS IN AUTUMN
</HEADLINE>
  (Includes color photo of a field of yellow daffodils) 
 By SUSAN McCLURE 
 c.1999 Susan McClure 
 World rights except Chicago 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Although autumn leaves are turning crimson and burgundy, there
is no better time than the present for thinking about spring.
</P>
<P>
   This is the season of new beginnings for spring flowering bulbs,
plump packets that contain everything necessary for springtime
bliss. Inside the brown wrapping of a bulb are primordia for roots,
leaves, and flowers _ golden daffodils and cobalt grape hyacinths.
</P>
<P>
   While most people are familiar with spring standards such as
tulips, hyacinths, and crocus, new colors, forms, and even new
species are now available, enough to satisfy even the experienced
plant collector.
</P>
<P>
   Daffodils that bloom in many shades of pink, tulips with
clustered flowers instead of the solitary tear drop and exotic
newcomers never before seen in American gardens are among the
dynamic new offerings available this spring. If you can't find them
at the local garden center, you can find them in specialty
catalogues such as McClure &AMP; Zimmerman (1-800-883-6998), or Brent
and Becky's Bulbs (804-693-3966).
</P>
<P>
   According to Brent Heath, owner of Brent and Becky's Bulbs, the
following are some of the hottest options for 1999.
</P>
<P>
   * Mariposa or fairy lantern (Calochorus venustus): A native of
the Rocky Mountains, this American wildflower makes a marvelous cut
flower that will stay fresh in a vase for a month. The name
Calochortus is Greek, meaning beautiful grass, in reference to the
grasslike, gray-green leaves.
</P>
<P>
   From late spring into early summer, cup-shaped flowers emerge,
varying from white, to yellow, purple, and red with a yellow-ringed
red eye.
</P>
<P>
   Mariposas thrive if allowed to dry out when dormant in summer
and winter, doing best in well-drained sandy soils, and raised beds
that are not regularly irrigated.
</P>
<P>
   In northern climates, they may winter best in a sheltered
southern exposure or near the house, microclimates that offer
protection from winter's worst. To prevent alternating freezing and
thawing, which is hard on these bulbs, mulch the planting site
after Christmas with old evergreen boughs when the soil is frozen.
Remove the mulch in spring just before the soil thaws.
</P>
<P>
   * Corydalis solida ''Beth Evans'': Some shade gardeners may be
familiar with yellow corydalis, a perennial that resembles a wild
bleeding heart but can bloom all summer. This is its cousin, a
native of the European Balkans to Scandinavia. Clusters of tubular
flowers open in April, drifting over finely cut ferny foliage.
</P>
<P>
   A low grower, staying under 6 inches tall, it is a graceful
companion for draping over steps, retaining walls, or the perimeter
of paths. Once you find the right place for it, don't be surprised
if it multiplies, making a bold companion for nearby daffodils and
tulips.
</P>
<P>
   * Firecracker flower (Dachelostemma ida-maia): Like
attention-getting Fourth of July firecrackers, these flowers snap,
crackle, and pop with color when they open their firecracker-red
tubular flowers. The tips of the petals are lit with a golden green
edging.
</P>
<P>
   Natives of California and Oregon, they jump to life in late
June, sending their flowers up and out on arching stems from 1 to 3
feet tall.
</P>
<P>
   Like mariposa, the hardiness of firecracker flowers are not
proven in cold winter areas. Protect them for best results.
</P>
<P>
   * New developments in classic bulbs: Some spectacular new colors
are available in our tried-and-true spring bloomers.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most dynamic is the ''Valerie Finnis'' grape
hyacinth, a small bulb known for its long blooming season. Valerie
Finnis has larger flowers with a smoky, steel-gray petal color that
is particularly striking.
</P>
<P>
   A British gardener discovered the bulb that bears her name
growing in her garden. She displayed the flowers at a Royal
Horticultural Society flower show where it caught the eye of bulb
nurserymen. It was promptly propagated and made it available
worldwide. Planting Tips
</P>
<P>
   Spring flowering bulbs are among the easiest flowers to grow,
but provide the biggest rewards if you do a little planning before
you plant.
</P>
<P>
   Formal vs. Informal: For formal gardens, you can plant stately
bulbs like tulips and hyacinths in matching rows, squares,
rectangles, or circles. For informal clusters, appropriate to most
landscape beds, plant 5, 7, 9, 11 or other odd numbers of bulbs
such as daffodils in freeform clusters.
</P>
<P>
   Consider planting bulbs around hardy geraniums, daylilies,
hostas, Siberian irises, and other perennials in a flower garden or
between shrubs in a foundation planting. Naturalized bulbs such as
daffodils look great growing in ivy or periwinkle under shade
trees.
</P>
<P>
   With most bulbs, more is merrier. Planting dozens or hundreds
will fill your yard with spring color.
</P>
<P>
   Drainage: Make sure the soil is well-drained. In heavy soil,
bulbs may grow best planted in raised beds of amended soil.
</P>
<P>
   Critters: If you have lost small and shallowly planted bulbs
such as crocus to hungry chipmunks and other critters, enclose new
plantings in a wire mesh cage to keep animals out.
</P>
<P>
   If deer are a problem, avoid tulips and hyacinths and stick with
inedible bulbs such as daffodils, flowering onions, and squills.
</P>
<P>
   Digging In: Most bulbs thrive if planted three times as deep as
the height of the bulb, although there are some exceptions to this
rule. If in doubt, ask your bulb supplier about the best planting
depth.
</P>
<P>
   On point: Many bulbs have a flat end where the roots emerge and
a pointed end where the shoots arise. Set them in the hole with the
flat end down and the pointed end up to get them started off right.
</P>
<P>
   Feeding frenzy: If the soil is not already fertile, you can add
some bulb fertilizer (available at most garden centers) before
covering the bulbs up.
</P>
<P>
   Mark your spot: Firm the soil around the bulbs and mark their
location with a colored golf tee so you won't dig into them by
mistake.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Susan McClure writes about gardening from Valpariaso,
Indiana.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: Visit The New York Times Syndicate Website at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for more information on LifeBeat
and other features. &QL; 
 &UR; ------------------------------------------------- &QC;
</P>
