<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-18 10:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0391 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l BC-HALLOWEEN-COSTUME-CLI     10-18 0948
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HALLOWEEN-COSTUME-CLICHES-LIFEBEAT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HALLOWEEN COSTUMES HIGHLIGHT SEX ROLE CLICHES
</HEADLINE>
  By LAURA TAXEL 
 c.1999 Laura Taxel 
 World rights 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Year after year I stand dutifully at my door dispensing
Halloween candy. And year after year I'm struck by the difference
between the fantasies of little boys and their female counterparts.
</P>
<P>
   The boys are always dressed as cowboys, pirates, soldiers,
spacemen, and monsters. When boys masquerade, they portray males
who do, who can. They become little men of action or powerful,
terrifying monsters. They fantasize dominance; if they can't
capture you, they'll eat you up. They also evince a peculiar
attraction for depicting mass murderers, serial killers and other
victims of an aberrant psychology.
</P>
<P>
   The girls show no such tendencies and their psyche seems
dominated by Walt Disney. They are princesses, fairies, brides, and
angels. In their glitter and flounces, the girls join the
time-honored tradition of helpless loveliness. Fairies are tiny.
The most potent thing they can do is be mischievous.
</P>
<P>
   And every time I ask a little girl if she's a queen, she assures
me she is actually a princess. Queens, I suppose, have a certain
authority and of course, they may not be pretty. They might be
evil, or heaven help us, old. Princesses on the other hand are
always gorgeous and need only wait for the appearance of princes.
Brides represent a perfect, passive ideal of beauty. And whoever
heard of an angel with much to dO but flutter around seraphically.
</P>
<P>
   Forty years ago, my mother saw boys and girls dressed in
precisely the same way. It seems that for children, nothing much
has changed in spite of the women's movement, men's groups, the Age
of Aquarius, and guys doing dishes. How have girls and boys
remained so untouched by all the years of social upheaval? Perhaps
they are not so much unaffected by that as more affected by
advertising, movies, and toys.
</P>
<P>
   Or is it some biological imperative that populates boy dreams
with superheroes, fanged werewolves, and blood sucking vampires,
while girls imagine being Miss America?
</P>
<P>
   If Halloween in my mid-American neighborhood is representative,
then today's girls want what females have always been allowed and
educated to want: to be not only beautiful, but more beautiful than
all the rest. Today's little girls may be free to wear pants to
school and join baseball teams, but it seems that when it comes to
expressing their fantasies, they still come out pink and pretty.
</P>
<P>
   One girl who came to my door took it one step further. She was
dressed as a French Maid, in a low cut, short-skirted black outfit
with a white apron and cap and a black velvet bow at her throat
that looked more like a dog collar than a decoration. This girl
opted not only for beauty, but for subjugation too.
</P>
<P>
   Is this ''you've come a long way, baby'' consciousness? If so,
where did we start and where are we going?
</P>
<P>
   There was one girl, a little woman after my own heart, who
bucked all the stereotypes for a while. She came to my door three
years in row in the same costume. She was dressed as a dinosaur,
Tyrannosaurs rex no less, and her bright-eyed hopeful face peered
out from between huge sharp teeth. I always gave her extra treats.
But last Halloween, she too came dressed as a princess.
</P>
<P>
   I must be honest. I do see an occasional kid, sex unknown,
dressed as a pumpkin or a mouse. I attribute these kinds of
artistic costumes to mothers with sewing skill, few outlets for
their creativity and kids too young to fight back. My mother did
that to me. Not having any idea of what I really wanted to be, she
made me clever costumes that I hated.
</P>
<P>
   I remember one year she dressed me in paper bags and made a
bird's nest, complete with bird, for me to wear in my hair. I was a
tree. I won a prize. I was miserable. I wanted beauty and glamour.
</P>
<P>
   Each year brings a few witches. None of these girls, however,
opt for an ugly crone-like visage _ no warts, wild hair, beaked
noses, or toad companions. Every witch I see is cute as a button.
There are a few gypsy women too, but as every girl worth her salt
knows, choosing to be a gypsy is just a sure-fire way to get
permission to put on a face full of makeup. The gypsy girls at my
door did not look free, mysterious, and exotic, but more like
Barbie run amuck.
</P>
<P>
   Where are all the Annie Oakley's, Amazon warriors, female
pirates and bandits supreme? Our newly revised histories tell us
there were plenty of them. Doesn't any girl want to dress up as
Joan of Arc? And where's the boy who dream of being an elf, a
Prince Charming, or a groom?
</P>
<P>
   My own sons, who are truly sweet and gentle boys, have always
chosen to be something disgusting risen from dead, and over the
years I've become as adept as a theatrical pro at creating scars,
wounds, and bloody mutilations.
</P>
<P>
   I keep asking myself why. I ask them, and they find my curiosity
vastly amusing. ''Because,'' they patiently explain to me, ''it's
fun.'' But I'm haunted by the question of why the girls don't want
to look dreadfully, wonderfully scary and horribly, terrifyingly
ugly.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Laura Taxel writes from Cleveland Heights, Ohio.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: Visit The New York Times Syndicate Website at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for more information on LifeBeat
and other features. &QL; 
 &UR; ------------------------------------------------- &QC;
</P>
