<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LANE-COLUMN19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    No semicolons? Give me a little break!
 &HT;    By Mark Lane
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. _ I heard Kurt Vonnegut on public radio
recently. He talked about his new book of old short stories, ``The
Bagombo Snuff Box,'' and his years selling bad cars before he
became A Famous Writer. He was a hoot. A world-weary hoot, but
still a hoot.
</P>
<P>
   The famous writer and world-weary hoot gave sound writerly
advice: Don't use semicolons.
</P>
<P>
   Listen:
</P>
<P>
   ``Let me note that Kilgore Trout and I have never used
semicolons. They don't do anything. Don't suggest anything. They
are transvestite hermaphrodites.''
</P>
<P>
   That's what he said in ``Timequake,'' his last novel, recently
out in paperback. He repeated it on the radio. (Kilgore Trout is a
character of his, a science-fiction writing fictional counterpart.)
</P>
<P>
   I must admit _ reluctantly _ that both he and Trout have a
strong point. We do not live in an age friendly to semicolons. We
expect stop-and-go, binary prose. They are out of place in a dot
com world.
</P>
<P>
   Semicolons are supposed to act like a stop sign on a deserted
street; they beg the reader to make a rolling stop.
</P>
<P>
   They are a halfway measure between the speed-bump of a comma and
the red light of a period.
</P>
<P>
   I got out of high school with no idea what to do with them. They
were squiggles as mysterious as a hieroglyph when I landed in
college freshman English. But once I learned how to work them, I
sought opportunities to show off my new-found knowledge.
</P>
<P>
   To my great disappointment, nobody was impressed. Editors
converted them all into plain old dots. Killjoys.
</P>
<P>
   But despite my editors and Vonnegut, I feel we are losing
something by letting semicolons fall into disuse. Semicolons are a
sigh before continuing; a pause before a punch line; a turn of the
head and folding of the arms before Jack Benny says anything else:
they are a tool of timing too finely calibrated for our age of
online speed reading.
</P>
<P>
   Here's one of cynical old Edward Gibbon's old-fashioned, long,
semicolon-studded sentences:
</P>
<P>
   ``The various modes of worship, which prevailed in the Roman
world, were all considered by the people as equally true; by the
philosopher, as equally false; and by the magistrate as equally
useful.''
</P>
<P>
   Reading that kind of perfectly tuned three-part sentence is like
watching a triple play.
</P>
<P>
   For the record, Vonnegut is stretching the truth when he boasts
of living well without semicolons. I have proof. Here's the opening
of his novel, ``Mother Night'':
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the only story of mine whose moral I know. I don't
think it's a marvelous moral; I simply happen to know what it is:
We are what we pretend to be, so we must be careful about what we
pretend to be.''
</P>
<P>
   He is pretending to be a man without semicolons. And as he would
predict, that is what he has become.
</P>
<P>
   So it goes.
</P>
<P>
   I should clarify here that I'm talking only about real
semicolons used in real sentences. Not the run-of-the-mill,
who-cares semicolons thrown in to break up lists.
</P>
<P>
   I used those when I used to prepare the hog markets. Like this:
``220-260 lbs., 31.00-33.00; 220-260 lbs., 29.00-31.00; 200-220
lbs., too few ... ''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe that's why I was never too proud of them. They were mere
pig-semicolons. But at least editors let me keep them.
</P>
<P>
   Encouraged by my success as hog-market compiler, I persisted in
my drive to revive the semicolon in modern journalism. I failed.
</P>
<P>
   I'm older now and don't need to show off. It's been ages since
my finger strayed east of the L key to plant a semicolon next to an
independent clause. But Vonnegut's dissing the dot-squiggle made me
realize there's a danger here. If we allow the semicolon to pass
away, it's only a matter of time before writers of short, punchy
sentences go after the colon, too.
</P>
<P>
   We risk a slippery slope. Already Internet travelers are calling
a period a ``dot'' as though punctuation were just visual
decoration. Even commas, which used to be cheap, are being used
less and less as writers let introductory phrases fly headlong into
nouns. Pow.
</P>
<P>
   Writers and students! Reclaim the semicolon; there comes a time
when everyone deserves a little break.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Lane is a columnist for The Daytona Beach (Fla.)
News-Journal. E-mail: marklane(at)n-jcenter.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
