<HEADER>
A0426 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN19-COX     10-18 0688
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Quality, not quantity, key in making a statement
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Schuett
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GIBSONBURG, Ohio _ In a move to trim the number of hereditary
peers and to give itself the appearance of being more democratic,
Britain's House of Lords
</P>
<P>
   has ordered its 759 members to submit a brief statement
defending their right to the seats they've been occupying. And to
do it in 75 words or less.
</P>
<P>
   Once all submissions have been considered and voted upon,
officials will then elect 92 of the most deserving to remain in the
house. The other 667 will be told to hit the road Jack, or in this
instance, (SET ITAL)Lord(END ITAL) Jack.
</P>
<P>
   As a result of finding themselves in such a shocking situation,
the noblemen are chortling, in a snide but dignified manner, and
insisting that it would be impossible to chronicle a lifetime in so
brief a missive. ``Ludicrous,'' one has
</P>
<P>
   commented, asking if he should include his shoe size and number
of brain cells.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, but only if the latter exceeds the former, and if he can
get the job
</P>
<P>
   done within the 75-word limit.
</P>
<P>
   Question is, could one sum up an entire life (or so much of it
as has been lived thus far) in so few words? Can great stories be
told, or arguments made with such brevity? After all, 75 is a mere
five words longer than the Lord's Prayer. On the other hand, the
Pledge of Allegiance is only 31 words.
</P>
<P>
   The secret of success for the milords would be to think in terms
of pithy
</P>
<P>
   but succinct. The KISS principle (Keep It Simple Stupid) that is
so useful in the classroom as the basic structure of a three-point,
five-paragraph essay could be of some assistance here. That is,
unless the peers, like politicians, are incapable of applying such
a formula to their rhetoric.
</P>
<P>
   On occasion, however, history records a success.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, the hand-lettered sign President Truman had on his
desk: ``The buck stops here.'' Point well made, I think, and in
only four words.
</P>
<P>
   October 1, 1939, and Britain is in the first month of a war with
Germany. Winston Churchill is speaking to his countrymen in a BBC
address, and in an attempt to explain the conundrum that is Russia,
he states simply: ``I cannot
</P>
<P>
   forecast to you the action of Russia. It is a riddle wrapped in
a mystery
</P>
<P>
   inside an enigma. ...'' Twenty words _ still true.
</P>
<P>
   Seeking to reassure a deeply troubled nation, Franklin D.
Roosevelt in his first inaugural address on March 4, 1933, spoke
these words: ``Let me assert my
</P>
<P>
   firm belief that the only thing we have to fear is fear
itself.'' Seventeen
</P>
<P>
   words that worked.
</P>
<P>
   Tongue-in-cheek, as was usually the case, Mark Twain wrote:
``Man is the only animal that blushes. Or needs to.'' Ten words.
</P>
<P>
   Then there was my father's dinner blessing that, because of his
rapid-fire delivery, was open to misinterpretation, but
nevertheless effective: ``Lord make us thankful for these and all
our blessings. Amen.'' Eleven words, including the Amen, although
for years I thought he was saying: ``Lord megga-sankle freeze
</P>
<P>
   and all our blessings.''
</P>
<P>
   The noble British gentlemen have a lot riding on a mere 75 words
where a lack of brevity and pith could be catastrophic. Of course,
it's possible they might take a lesson from Minnesota's Gov. Jesse
Ventura, who tells it quick and straight
</P>
<P>
   (as he sees it), but they'd have to bear in mind that this guv'
seems to
</P>
<P>
   open a can of worms every time he opens his mouth.
</P>
<P>
   Summing up one's life and accomplishments in so few words could
be a formidable, but not impossible task. My son did rather well, I
thought, once he quit goofing around. ``The most important thing I
have accomplished,'' he wrote
</P>
<P>
   at my request, ``is the true friendship of a very select few
individuals and
</P>
<P>
   the love of my family. Notable enough, I'm happy.'' Twenty-seven
words, one contraction, and enough said.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Schuett writes for Cox News Service. Mail: 320 West
Madison, Gibsonburg, OH 43431 or e-mail: eschuett(AT)nwonline.net.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
