r k BC-YOUNG-COLUMN19-COX     10-18 0674
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOUNG-COLUMN19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    College students have it good because others have seen to it
 &HT;    By John Young
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ Talk about changes. Send your daughter to college
and she gets a mustache.
</P>
<P>
   The wipe-off kind, that is. It's mustaches across the board on
any Tuesday, which is Dr Pepper Hour at Baylor University.
</P>
<P>
   For over 40 years the university has maintained a tradition:
invite students for floats _ Dr Pepper and Blue Bell _ or the hard
stuff straight up.
</P>
<P>
   At the Bill Daniel Student Center recently I was struck by this
scene and by this great concept.
</P>
<P>
   College, that is.
</P>
<P>
   Take an idyllic setting. Stock it with magnificent buildings,
brainy mentors and books. Stir in sports and lively arts, not just
for spectating but for participating.
</P>
<P>
   Better still, stock with really fine young people and tell them,
``Here. Become friends for life.''
</P>
<P>
   Quite a concept, and quite in contrast to the concept I remember
trying to nurse away from a certain high schooler one night last
year.
</P>
<P>
   He had a deep case of sophomore blahs. Pointless, he said about
college. Pointless and dull and perfunctory. You punch a time
clock, sit in rows, for the privilege of living.
</P>
<P>
   Not pointless, we said. A means of living beyond the means of,
say, the guy emptying the grease trap at Burger City.
</P>
<P>
   Well, let me tell you. That ``means'' stuff may pay bills later
on, but it won't get you to the counter with a high school
sophomore.
</P>
<P>
   Now he's a junior. Though still not ready to model anyone's
letter sweater, I do think I heard him say the other day that _ in
concept _college had a certain appeal.
</P>
<P>
   I swallowed the impulse to stand on the table and sing the alma
mater. Any alma mater.
</P>
<P>
   Certain appeal? You've got that right. I was ruminating on it
the other day while strolling the Baylor campus, just one of
countless options.
</P>
<P>
   I got my first look at the new Drayton McLain Student Life
Center. If that doesn't put a smile on a young person's lips, I
want to see what does. You've seen Emerald City in the movies?
Well, this involves more green ($21 million to be exact).
</P>
<P>
   Inside, you're reminded of Neil Young's song ``Sugar Mountain,''
in part because there's a man-made mountain inside, a
two-story-high climbing rock with youngsters clinging and
clambering, and others admiring as if it were a sundae. In a room a
few feet away is a pool with a water slide and a ``lazy river.''
Most densely populated is the fitness room, where a veritable
dormful of students sweat out some spare time before a row of
monster TVs.
</P>
<P>
   Out on the intramural field is multicolored commotion that
really strikes a chord with me. In addition to working on the
college newspaper, I must have played every intramural sport there
was.
</P>
<P>
   College is just one of the greatest concepts ever invented _
fields of green laid out before you, time to work, time to play,
time to establish yourself as something far beyond a worker drone.
</P>
<P>
   Little discoveries made in college often are major.
</P>
<P>
   At my college we had an on-campus night spot called the
Ramskellar _ live entertainment, commonly bands, but sometimes
stand-up comedians.
</P>
<P>
   A roommate who was into comedy kept bugging me to go see one
comedian who put him in stitches. The man was unknown, but my
roomie assured me we'd hear more of him.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Martin was the stand-up's name.
</P>
<P>
   The Rolling Stones played our campus. I learned to bowl. I
learned photography and Marshall McLuhan and Immanuel Kant.
</P>
<P>
   That's college. And that is a gift.
</P>
<P>
   No, it's not a freebie. Your share of actual costs aside, with
excellent grades and test scores you'll have earned it. In the end,
however, you'll have to admit that someone you never knew did you a
huge favor just because he or she bought into a splendid concept.
</P>
<P>
   You and college, that is.
</P>
<P>
   John Young is opinion page editor of the Waco Tribune-Herald.
E-mail: jyoung(at)wacotrib.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
