<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETWATCH19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Deal puts spotlight on unsigned musicians of MP3.com
 &HT;    By Frances Katz
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ While the rest of the recording industry tries to
figure out what to do about digital music downloads, some prominent
industry executives are actually hiring bands from MP3.com, the
popular digital music download site.
</P>
<P>
   For those with the time and patience to wade through the
thousands of artists on the site, there's a good chance that you
might find, as Chief Executive Michael Robertson puts it, ``the
best music you never heard.''
</P>
<P>
   Book publishers have been trolling through ``slush piles'' for
years, hoping to find the Great American Novel buried among the
thousands of unsolicited manuscripts.
</P>
<P>
   MP3.com _ the ultimate slush pile _ eliminates the middleman for
music industry executives. Sure, they can spend every night in a
smoke-filled rock club checking out every unsigned band from Maine
to Monterey _ and some people do enjoy passing the time this way.
</P>
<P>
   However, with MP3.com, you can pretty much do the same thing in
the comfort of your home or office. The beer is cheaper, and you
can get a clean glass if you want one.
</P>
<P>
   This week, producers Francis Ford Coppola and Larry Sugar said
they would be picking out tunes for their cable TV series ``First
Wave'' solely from artists who make their music available on
MP3.com. Artists who'd like to submit their work for inclusion on
the show can get information at www.mp3.com/firstwave. Fans of the
show who like the music they hear will be able to listen to it or
purchase it only on the MP3.com site.
</P>
<P>
   Both MP3.com and Coppola's production company are enthusiastic
about the deal. Steve Love, the music executive who helped
orchestrate the deal, said in a statement that the relationship
helps offer potentially global exposure to MP3.com artists.
</P>
<P>
   TV and movie producers turning to MP3.com will show a lot of
ordinary consumers that there's some good music out there on the
Web _ and that the site will help them find it.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Hardie, a senior analyst at Forrester Research, says this
type of deal is part of a continued effort by MP3.com to make order
out of chaos.
</P>
<P>
   ``MP3.com as a big flea market,'' he says. ``The number of
relationships they've announced lately is designed to help people
sort through that flea market and give traditional television
production companies and radio stations access to that flea
market.''
</P>
<P>
   MP3.com says it wants to be the biggest source of music on the
Web, but the bigger it gets, the more urgent it will be to develop
ways for consumers to separate good online music from bad online
music.
</P>
<P>
   Deals with TV, movie and radio companies, such as the deal
earlier this year with Cox Interactive Media, allow those companies
to sort through MP3.com's vast roster of artists, choosing some of
the better music for their projects. Listeners and viewers will
then be directed to MP3.com to download the music. But instead of
going to MP3.com and hoping for the best, they'll have major media
properties guiding them to the best music, and MP3.com will promote
the music on the Web site.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts say this is a good move because most consumers don't
want to wade through piles of unfamiliar music. They want someone _
whether it's Rolling Stone magazine or the local radio station _ to
do the dirty work of finding good music for them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Consumers want access to enjoyable entertainment, with some
degree of filtering,'' Hardie says. ``That's how the real world
works. And the real world does work. It's not broken.''
</P>
<P>
   Internet executives like to talk about building and establishing
their brand and branding themselves with consumers. At first it
sounds like a bunch of techno-marketing speak, but what they are
really saying is they have to persuade consumers to take their
products seriously.
</P>
<P>
   They realize they have to build credibility with people who
really don't believe anything that only exists online can possibly
be good. Cross-promotion with familiar brands, such as television
and movies, is designed to make online music, magazines and even
e-commerce sites more acceptable to consumers unused to making
purchases, listening to music or reading magazines over the Net.
</P>
<P>
   On the Web, anybody can be a publisher, open a store or be a
recording artist. The only way Web surfers can separate the good
from the bad is to read every online e-zine or listen to every file
on MP3.com, which nobody really has the time or inclination to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``Consumers have a perception that absent some sort of
filtering, it's not the same quality as what they might buy in a
record store,'' Hardie says. ``It hasn't proven itself yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
