<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECHNOBUDDY19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Flashy download speed often immaterial to task at hand
 &HT;    By Bill Husted
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Come a little closer. Today I'm going to tell you a
dirty little secret that all those folks pushing high-speed
Internet access _ whether through a cable modem, digital subscriber
line, ISDN or satellite receiver _ would just as soon you not
understand.
</P>
<P>
   Most of what you do on the Internet at home works fine at the
speeds you get from an old-fashioned telephone line modem. If, like
most folks, your prime use of the Internet is sending and receiving
e-mail, you probably won't notice any difference between that now
old-fashioned analog modem and a high-speed connection. If you
enjoy chat _ either in one of the Internet chat groups or on AOL _
same thing, no difference.
</P>
<P>
   It's on the Web _ where many pages contain enormous amounts of
data, including photographs, videos and sound _ where the speed
difference pays off. I have a cable modem at home, and I do see a
big difference on the Web. But, for me now, the Web is a place to
look up specific information. I don't ``surf'' as often anymore _
aimlessly wandering from one site to another just for amusement.
So, if I still used my old-fashioned modem instead of the cable
modem I use (mostly because I do this stuff for a living), it would
be a matter of waiting 30 seconds for the answer to my question
about the population of Sao Paulo, Brazil, instead of the
five-second wait with my cable modem.
</P>
<P>
   Here's another thing that you may not know. Often, the real
delays on the Web have nothing at all to do with how fast a
connection you have to the Internet. Sometimes _ lots of times, in
fact _ it's the traffic on a particular Web site that is slowing
things down, not your connection.
</P>
<P>
   Don't get me wrong. I love my cable modem. But I am saying that
_ depending on how you use the Internet and how much money you have
to spend _ you may be able to live a reasonably full and productive
online life without the added expense of high-speed access.
</P>
<P>
   While we are at it, let's talk about another misconception about
Internet speed _ and maybe save you some money.
</P>
<P>
   It's not at all uncommon for me to receive a long e-mail from a
reader, asking what kind of new computer they need to speed things
up. These aren't dumb questions because even some of the national
advertising I see from computer companies, including Dell, seems to
equate a high-power PC with high-speed Internet access.
</P>
<P>
   But the truth is that your PC (unless it is an old 80486
machine) probably is plenty fast enough for using the Internet. I'd
rank PC power way down on the list when it comes to making a
difference in how fast a Web page loads. The most important factor
is connection speed, followed by general conditions on the Web (how
much traffic there is). In fact, I'd rank the stage of the moon and
the way you hold your mouth when you type ahead of computing power
when it comes to making a difference in Net speed.
</P>
<P>
   Here's why. For the most part (and there are exceptions, but
they aren't important) your PC _ when connected to the Net _ is
acting as a ``dumb terminal.'' The real computing work is being
done by the computers on the Web and on the Net. Your computer is
simply taking this information _ relayed by the Web site and your
Internet provider _ and displaying it on the screen. Some amount of
computing is going on, mostly by Windows and the Web browser, but
the really heavy lifting doesn't happen on your machine.
</P>
<P>
   So, here's my advice. If you want a new PC, if you want a
high-speed Internet connection, go ahead and buy one and get
high-speed access if you can afford it and understand the
limitations. But if you're counting pennies at your house _ as I do
_ then don't feel obliged to own the best of everything when it
comes to the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
