<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    New call-waiting modem actually works as billed
 &HT;    By Jack Warner
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ It's always a real thrill when I try out a piece of
hardware and find that (1) it does what it's supposed to do without
threats or pleas and (2) what it does is actually useful.
</P>
<P>
   Thus it is a pleasure to report my experience with a little item
called the Call Waiting Modem, made by Actiontec. It's close to an
ideal solution for those folks who don't want to get a telephone
line just for their computer.
</P>
<P>
   It works, of course, only if you subscribe to the call-waiting
feature on your line. It's a stylish little purple-and-cream box _
although you can get an internal version, as well. In stand-alone
versions, it comes in a standard serial port model and another for
the new-fangled USB ports.
</P>
<P>
   Bold as brass, I tried the USB model. It could not have been
simpler to install. Once plugged in, Windows 98 recognized it,
called for the driver provided on a CD-ROM, and set it up without a
fuss.
</P>
<P>
   Then, it actually worked, just as advertised. When calls came
in, the modem rang. Then I picked up the telephone to see who was
there. The modem gave me about seven seconds to get rid of the
caller; if I didn't hang up by then it severed the Internet
connection.
</P>
<P>
   It can also be set to cut the online connection the minute you
pick up the phone, or you can instruct it to ignore incoming calls.
</P>
<P>
   Initially, I had a problem with the speed of the Actiontec Call
Waiting Modem. But in the course of spending several hours fooling
with it, I learned a few things.
</P>
<P>
   To begin with, it wants to connect using the old 56KFlex
standard, which few ISPs support any longer. It routinely dropped
back to the standard V34 protocol, and we crawled along at 28k. The
manual suggests a register setting to dispense with the 56KFlex
business and go directly to V90, the most modern 56k protocol.
That, however, only got us up to around 31.6k.
</P>
<P>
   We have two telephone lines coming into our house, one for the
computers and one for voice. To test the modem's call-waiting
feature, it was easier to use the voice line. So, in an effort to
give the little guy every break, I hooked it up to the regular
modem line.
</P>
<P>
   Bingo. Right away it was cooking along at 49k, and you can't ask
for much better than that.
</P>
<P>
   I have spent a lot of time through the years hectoring the
telephone company into improving the quality of that line, but I
wouldn't have guessed it made that much difference.
</P>
<P>
   The modem has a list price of $135. It can probably be found at
retail stores for considerably less. Actiontec, at
www.actiontec.com, has a $50 rebate deal going now, which brings it
down to a very reasonable price.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
