<SLUG> BC-NFK-FEATURE-GUNPLEDGE19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Students asked to take pledge against gun violence
 &HT;    By Keith Still
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Every day, kids throughout the country pledge
allegiance to the flag of the United States, but on Thursday,
thousands of Georgia kids will make a different type of pledge.
</P>
<P>
   The Student Pledge Against Gun Violence calls on children of all
ages to promise not to bring a gun to school or to use violence to
settle an argument.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it's right that kids are getting killed every
day,'' said East Cobb Middle School eighth-grader Michael Schlact.
``By signing this pledge, we're trying to put an end to it.''
</P>
<P>
   The 13-year-old said he feels safe at his own school, but gun
violence is always a worry after shootings such as the ones in
Colorado and Georgia last school year.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Michael signed the pledge. This year, he helped
distribute packets to every school system in Georgia asking them to
participate. The packets include the official pledge for older
students and a similar pledge more simply worded for younger
children.
</P>
<P>
   The Student Pledge Against Gun Violence began four years ago.
While some Georgia schools participated at that time, it wasn't
until two years ago that Georgia got involved on a statewide level.
</P>
<P>
   Alvin Lindsey, youth service chair for the Georgia Parent
Teacher Association, said everyone is getting involved because
they're realizing that violence can occur anywhere _ from urban and
suburban to rural areas.
</P>
<P>
   ``This pledge really focuses on educating kids to use nonviolent
means of settling disputes,'' Lindsey said.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, more than 1 million American kids _ including 67,000
Georgians _ signed the Student Pledge Against Gun Violence. This
year, organizers expect Georgia's number to double.
</P>
<P>
   Here's what the pledge says:
</P>
<P>
   ``I pledge: I will never bring a gun to school; I will never use
a gun to settle a dispute; I will use my influence with my friends
to keep them from using guns to settle disputes; my individual
choices and actions, when multiplied by those of young people
throughout the country, will make a difference. Together, by
honoring this pledge, we can reverse the violence and grow up in
safety.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
