<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    6 billionth child is born
 &HT;    By Staff Reports
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The number of people living on Earth doubled in less
than 40 years, hitting 6 billion on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Really, tens of thousands of children were born on that day. But
the United Nations _ which we learned about last week in NFK _
chose one child to represent the rest.
</P>
<P>
   The U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan welcomed a baby boy in
Bosnia-Herzegovina. He was born to refugee parents in that East
European nation.
</P>
<P>
   United Nations officials and others around the world worry about
the rapidly increasing population. Many children will live in
poverty in developing nations. In fact, one-third of those who live
in the world's poorest countries won't survive past age 5.
</P>
<P>
   ARMY TAKES OVER PAKISTAN
</P>
<P>
   Army Chief Gen. Pervaiz Musharraf toppled the elected government
of Pakistan last week. He then declared himself the supreme leader
of the Asian country. He suspended the constitution, which is the
document that establishes the way the government will run. He also
dissolved the legislature, which is similar to our Congress.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement came three days after the general ousted the
prime minister in a bloodless ``coup d'etat.'' A coup d'etat is a
sudden change of government that is unlawful or by force.
</P>
<P>
   The coup is not expected to affect the nation's nuclear weapons
because they were always controlled by the military.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
