<SLUG> BC-TECH-REPORT19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    One site can manage all passwords
 &HT;    By Mark Clothier
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ First there was the PC. Then they added things to make
it worthwhile to us, programs that process words and crunch numbers
_ and an operating system to make it all manageable.
</P>
<P>
   Then came the Internet, and they added things like search
engines and e-mail accounts and airline reservations and online
banking to make it worthwhile to us. But how do you manage it all?
How do you keep track of all the sites and all the passwords?
</P>
<P>
   Companies like Vertical One, in Atlanta, have a way to reach all
your online accounts through one site and one password. Microsoft's
Passport product does something similar on sites that are part of
the Microsoft Network.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's Desktop.com, a San Francisco start-up that has
developed a desktop interface for the Internet. The idea is to make
all Internet functions _ e-mail, calendars, bookmarks, phone lists
_ accessible from the Web, which means it would be accessible
anywhere there's Internet access.
</P>
<P>
   The free service is available at www.desktop.com. Users can
store files that can be shared with other users, as well as
bookmarks. The service logs users on to the sites that require
passwords. Desktop.com does not yet work on Macintosh computers.
</P>
<P>
   PRIVACY LAWS TACKLE SPAM, SECURITY ISSUES
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, state legislators introduced 59 bills dealing with
online and Internet privacy issues, according to the Center for
Social and Legal Research. This year, about 80 online
privacy-related bills have been introduced in state legislatures.
Of those, 14 have been enacted into law.
</P>
<P>
   Most were related to a few specific areas: the sending of spam,
or junk e-mail, and the verification of digital signatures and
records. Eight states _ Virginia, North Carolina, West Virginia,
Connecticut, Nevada, Oklahoma, Washington and Tennessee _ enacted
anti-spam laws. Most try to ban deceitful in-state spam by
requiring that people or companies that send large amounts of spam
use accurate names, addresses and subject lines. In New York,
California, Connecticut, North Carolina, Virginia and West
Virginia, sending spam can be a criminal offense.
</P>
<P>
   Resume on Web OK with most workers
</P>
<P>
   The high-tech labor crunch certainly has skewed the job market
toward sellers. People are becoming more comfortable with the idea
of posting resumes on the Web, even if their boss is looking.
</P>
<P>
   According to a survey sponsored by CareerMosaic, an online job
site, 80 percent of the 400 asked said they had no concern about
posting their resume on a Web site where it can be viewed by
anyone. Most people, 95 percent of those asked, said they were
comfortable applying online to job openings. The survey was
conducted by Cyber Dialogue.
</P>
<P>
   Among the findings:
</P>
<P>
   _ Some 83 percent of those interviewed and almost all college
graduates (94 percent) have a resume prepared.
</P>
<P>
   _ About the same number, 82 percent, know how to cut-and-paste
their resume into a job search database.
</P>
<P>
   _ Everyone asked said they would go back to the Internet to
research a company before interviewing there.
</P>
<P>
   _ Most online access (93 percent) takes places at home. But 59
percent are on the Internet at work, 58.5 percent at school and
19.1 percent at places like libraries.
</P>
<P>
   _ Men are more likely than women to be online at work, 67
percent to 48 percent.
</P>
<P>
   _ Most job hunters, 79 percent, check the Web more than once
each day. And most, 73 percent, said they have been using the
Internet since before 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
