<P>
   These columns for release Tuesday, October 19, 1999 are moving
today to clients of the New York Times News Service.
</P>
<P>
   All columns have moved, in the commentary (k) category. If you
have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the Cox News
Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   GEEWAX-Y2K-COLUMN _ Marilyn Geewax's weekly column looking at
issues raised by the coming of 2000. (Geewax, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED THURSDAY
</P>
<P>
   SCHUETT-COLUMN _ GIBSONBURG, Ohio _ Could one sum up an entire
life in 75 words? Can great stories be told, or arguments made with
such brevity? After all, 75 is a mere five words longer than the
Lord's Prayer. On the other hand, the Pledge of Allegiance is only
31 words. The secret of success would be to think in terms of pithy
but succinct. (Schuett, Cox News Service) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   LANE-COLUMN _ DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. _ Writers and students!
Reclaim the semicolon; there comes a time when everyone deserves a
little break. (Lane, Daytona Beach News-Journal) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   YOUNG-COLUMN _ WACO, Texas _ College, what a great concept. Take
an idyllic setting. Stock it with magnificent buildings, brainy
mentors and books. Stir in sports and lively arts, not just for
spectating but for participating. Better still, stock with really
fine young people and tell them, ``Here. Become friends for life.''
(John Young is opinion page editor of the Waco Tribune-Herald)
MOVED
</P>
