<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONSUMERQ&AMP;A19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Consumer Q&AMP;A
 &HT;    By Jane Greig
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Q: What is the story behind the three longhorns
that roam the ``front yard'' at the Westinghouse building on
Interstate 35? Could we have our photograph taken with them or
perhaps other longhorns in this area, such as Bevo? It would be fun
to send such a picture of us back to our old neighborhood to show
them that we have a new ``pet.'' _ K.G.
</P>
<P>
   A: Well, cowgirl, you can have your picture taken with a
longhorn, but not these longhorns. These steers are not docile
enough to entertain humans. The land was originally planned as a
park, but became pasture instead. The Longhorns grazing at
TECO-Westinghouse are named Freeloader, Fiddlesticks and Remington.
They were preceded by Sancho, Quijote, El Tejas and Scooter, whose
horns are on display inside the facility. Years ago El Tejas jumped
the company fence and strolled Interstate 35. El Tejas survived.
Bet he made a few Suburbans dance, though. To take a ``Merry
Christmas Y'All'' or ``Look at us Now'' photo for a small fee,
contact Ralph Fisher at (409) 247-4999, whose longhorns are famous
(and very tame), or Pat Beach of CalPat Ranch at (512) 281-9603,
where you can pose on top of Nike the red steer.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I bought my father some Scotch whisky in a 1.75 liter bottle
back in December 1997. He is the only one who drinks scotch. Is it
safe to serve now? _ B.F.
</P>
<P>
   A: Should be fine. Technically liquor, unlike wine, will last
forever, says Todd Murrell of Steve's Liquor &AMP; Fine Wines. Of
course, when scotch is stored in extreme temperatures, the taste
may be adversely affected. Scotch, the heart of a Rusty Nail or a
Rob Roy cocktail, is often consumed neat _ no ice, no water, no
kidding. Whiskey is an interesting word from the Irish ``uisge
beatha,'' meaning water of life.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I was curious if the use of waterless hand soaps is OK or
even better than the time-honored way. And if so, is the same
amount of time for washing the hands, 15 or 20 seconds, necessary?
Most of the waterless hand soaps are alcohol-based, so I assume
they would be good for killing germs.
</P>
<P>
   _ Don Zappone
</P>
<P>
   A: The traditional soap and water combo reaches into the pores
better than waterless hand soaps. When you are traveling or have no
other way to wash your hands, waterless soaps are great, says
pharmacist J.D. Harper at Crestview Pharmacy. Anywhere from 5-15
seconds should do it. These soaps contain alcohol or an antiseptic
as an antibacterial agent. Still doubtful? Harper uses them on
occasion. Q: I conducted an interview using a recorder and
audiocassette. The sound quality is fine except for a 30-minute
portion of the discussion that I recorded in a moving car. The
background noise makes the discussion inaudible, though our voices
are clearly present under the roar of the vehicle. Can anyone
remove the unwanted noise, heighten the voices or in some way save
my interview?
</P>
<P>
   _ Michael S.
</P>
<P>
   A: Hard to know until an expert listens to the tape.
Thebackground noise will be sampled and then attenuated (weakened)
with computer processing. The background noise cannot be completely
eliminated without affecting the quality of the recorded
conversation, but the contrast between the conversation and the
background can be enhanced.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I ordered a cord of wood, but I do not know what a cord is.
Is there a way to be sure I got what I paid for? _ Doris R.
</P>
<P>
   A: You bet. Measure. A cord is 128 cubic feet (4 by 4 by 8 feet,
or 2 by 8 by 8 feet). So, if the logs are two feet long, the wood
stack should be one log width, 8 feet high and 8 feet long.
</P>
<P>
   Q: There must be two days a year when the sun rises exactly in
the east at a given latitude. What days are they in Austin? Don't
say, ``Who cares?'' _ David Alger
</P>
<P>
   A: I care. Brad Armosky of McDonald Observatory and Stardate
Magazine cares. The two days are the vernal (March 20, 2000) and
the autumnal (Sept. 23, 1999) equinoxes. ``On the equinox the sun
rises and sets due east and west regardless of latitude,'' says
Armosky. However, the angle at which the sun rises and sets is
affected by latitude. If you are at the North Pole on either
equinox day the sun appears to swim around the horizon rather than
rise or set; at the equator, the sun shoots straight up over the
horizon, is directly overhead at noon, and sets due west.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Is the employer required by law to give you two weeks' pay if
you have turned in a written notice of termination, and they let
you go? One of my co-workers says yes, I say no. _ A. Seguin
</P>
<P>
   A: You win. It is common for employers to ask an employee to
leave without working the full two-week notice period. Based on the
Texas Pay Day Law, ``the employer would not owe the employee money
for the two weeks where no service was performed,'' advises Laura
Thomas of the Texas Workforce Commission. Unless there is a written
policy stating ``leave will be paid upon termination,'' generally,
reimbursement for unused vacation or sick leave would not be paid.
Check that employee handbook. And think before quitting. For more
information on payday (and child labor laws) contact the
Commission's Labor Law Section at (800) 832-9243.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I have not written a ``Dear Jane'' letter for 48 years, but
this is a little different. We have a water cooler that is not used
by many people, and sometimes the water is not used up for three
weeks. How long is it safe to have a bottle on a dispenser before
it should be removed and a new bottle installed? _ Bill S.
</P>
<P>
   A: Three weeks should not be a problem. Packaged and labeled
water is regulated by the Texas Department of Health. The water in
the bottle must come from an approved source, says Joe Dixon of the
Texas Department of Health. Bottled water plants are tested weekly
to ensure the bottling process is sanitary. Manufacturers of
bottled water are required to do a final sanitization before
capping to remove harmful bacteria (usually with ozone gas). If you
maintain the water cooler properly, the water should be potable for
6 to 12 months, concludes Dixon. Cheers.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Quick question _ I have several of the old Silver Certificate
dollar bills that I saved when they were eliminated and replaced by
the Federal Reserve note. Can these be presented for silver at a
bank (silver bars, not coins)? _ Rick O.
</P>
<P>
   A: Quick answer: no. You are 31 years too late. An act of
Congress (June 24, 1967) provided that Silver Certificates could be
exchanged for silver bullion for one year (until June 24, 1968).
Your certificates are still legal tender. The Department of the
Treasury issued Silver Certificates beginning in 1878, and they
were redeemable for silver dollars until 1964.
</P>
<P>
   Contact Jane Greig, author of ``Thanks for Asking,'' at P.O. Box
670, Austin, TX 78767; (512) 445-3697; e-mail
jgreig(at)statesman.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
