<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   GORE-CALIFORNIA (Sacramento, Calif.) _ Maybe California Gov.
Gray Davis didn't get the memo from Tennessee. As Vice President Al
Gore was trying to inject some excitement into his button-down
campaign, Davis snatched Gore right back into the Land of the
Political Dweeb by urging AFL-CIO audience to embrace Gore like
they did him _ a ``boring, dull fellow dismissed as roadkill and
yesterday's news.'' By ROBERT SALLADAY.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SCREENWRITER-KAUFMAN (San Francisco) _ The 1949 movie ``Home of
the Brave,'' the story of a black Marine having a breakdown because
of racism in his unit during World War II, originally was a play
about prejudice against a Jewish soldier. Asked why the change was
made, veteran screenwriter Millard Kaufman shrugged. ``You might
ask, first, why the subject was changed from a gay man to a Jew,''
said Kaufman, a good friend of the play's author, Arthur Laurents.
By EDVINS BEITIKS.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL (``t'' category)
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-COLUMN (Houston) _ All sorts of studies and surveys have
measured the lifestyles and tendencies of travelers. Adult
travelers, that is. For the first time, a comprehensive study
focuses on parents and kids, with more than 500 children
interviewed. Some of the findings are surprising. By HARRY
SHATTUCK.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-OKLAHOMA (Oklahoma City) _ In a recent telephone poll,
just 2 percent of 514 respondents from Texas, Oklahoma, Missouri
and Kansas said they would consider the Sooner State as a vacation
destination. Based on recent developments in Oklahoma City _ where
new enticements include a Riverwalk and water taxis akin to San
Antonio _ they may be missing out on a lot of fun. By SYD KEARNEY.
(Photo available on NYT database.)
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-TIPS (Oklahoma City) _ A guide to lodging, dining and
activities in Oklahoma City. By SYD KEARNEY.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE-FEATURES (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   GARDEN-COLUMN (Houston) _ A reader asks, ``When do I plant
pansies?'' Assorted Q&AMP;As. By KATHY HUBER.
</P>
<P>
   FINANCIAL-BUSINESS NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   EBAY (San Francisco) _ It's a worldwide flea market filled with
millions of buyers, sellers and stuff you never knew you needed or
even imagined existed _ from tacky oil paintings and diaper coupons
to Texas ranches and million-dollar jewelry. You name it, covet it,
disdain it, don't know what to call it _ it's on eBay, the
granddaddy and titan of online auctions. By MARIANNE COSTANTINOU.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FBN-KNAPP-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ George Seifert came out of
the tunnel for warm-ups, and a huge roar went up in the nearby end
zone. The applause seemed even louder and warmer than Seifert had a
right to expect, dressed as he was, in the garb of a turncoat, a
black Carolina Panthers polo shirt over a pair of khakis. By GWEN
KNAPP.
</P>
<P>
   FBN-RATTO-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ There is no exclamation point
in Steve Mariucci's world right now. The facts have hit him flush
in the yap one too many times for him to pretend any longer. His
job as coach of the San Francisco 49ers is not football's dream job
any more, and he knows it as only someone with a foot-sized knot in
his gut can. By RAY RATTO.
</P>
<P>
   OUTDOORS-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ The airline passengers were
just settling in when suddenly this red, foul-smelling juice
started flowing out of the overhead baggage compartment and on to
the passengers below. When the plane leveled off, the juice
stopped, and a flight attendant opened an overhead bin _ and a wet,
slippery 30-pound salmon fell out, right on the lap of one of the
horrified passengers. By TOM STIENSTRA.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MORSE-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ The guys next to me at Peet's
coffeehouse in the Marina, a couple of blocks from where buildings
collapsed and burned in 1989, were looking at a newspaper article
on the odds of a Big One in the Bay Area. ``Seventy percent chance
by the year 2030?'' said one guy. ``That means there's a 30 percent
chance of not having a big quake in the next 30 years.'' That's the
way people look at things in this land of perpetual start-ups. By
ROB MORSE.
</P>
<P>
   ROSENFELD-COLUMN (Albany, N.Y.) _ With the fuss over privacy on
the Internet heating up, it's past time for American consumers,
which is every one of us, to make the principles of the market
economy work for them. By HARRY ROSENFELD.
</P>
<P>
   ROBISON-COLUMN (Austin, Texas) _ Appealing to the center makes
sense as Texas Gov. George W. Bush runs for president. But some
issues are easier to walk a tightrope over than others, and one of
the most difficult _ so difficult it is virtually impossible _ is
abortion, perhaps the most emotional political issue of our era. By
CLAY ROBISON.
</P>
