<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991018.0189 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-18 12:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0486 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k BC-ROSENFELD-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      10-18 0814
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROSENFELD-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONSUMERS OF AMERICA, UNITE 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By HARRY ROSENFELD  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ With the fuss over privacy on the Internet
heating up, it's past time for American consumers, which is every
one of us, to make the principles of the market economy work for
them.
</P>
<P>
   The next time you buy goods or services and pay for them with a
credit card, and the sales clerk asks you to share some personal
information, you face a couple of pivotal choices.
</P>
<P>
   You can, as probably most people do, simply comply when your
phone number or ZIP code is solicited. Many don't so much as
question why this information is being sought, supposing the seller
is entitled to ask. Others may be uneasy about providing it, but do
so because they don't want to make a fuss.
</P>
<P>
   If, however, you feel such questions are intruding into your
private life to an unwarranted degree, then, of course, you can
decline to respond, even in the face of insistence by the seller
that this information is required.
</P>
<P>
   In almost all circumstances, that is a false claim and violates
one or another law, and occasionally some companies' written
policy. The rationale for the legal protection is that your credit
card already establishes your credit with the issuing bank. No
additional information is needed to validate your purchases.
</P>
<P>
   Businesses of all stripes, shapes and sizes lust after every
tidbit they can gather about the consumer because it is a terrific
way to make extra dough. These business are on their toes, not so
dull as to be content with having sold you the goods you bought,
and satisfied with a deserved profit. For them the quid pro quo of
a sale is not enough.
</P>
<P>
   To them, the consumer is a bountiful resource. However, unless
merchants take steps, that resource just lies there inert and
undeveloped. To make it productive, the resource needs to be
exploited, just as coal is mined and oil is pumped to provide for a
payoff.
</P>
<P>
   To develop a consumer to his or her fullest potential, the
essential first step is to harvest as much information as possible
about where you live, your phone number, your family, your
education, your income and the kinds of things and services you
have so far purchased.
</P>
<P>
   With those data in hand, a smart merchandiser has the means to
analyze what else you might be convinced to be interested to buy.
By refining the data into all their particularities, your simple
purchase of a widget one Saturday afternoon will surely lead to
your being offered by direct mail, telephone or Internet, widget
cleansers, widget holders, widget storage and widget insurance, not
to overlook bigger and better widgets. From being a one-time widget
buyer, you have been magically transformed into almost a cornucopia
of potential profits.
</P>
<P>
   If this is just fine with you, or at least acceptable, you are a
member of the silent majority.
</P>
<P>
   But as long as everyone else in the economy is doing so well by
you, this is also your opportunity to hop on the bandwagon and do
something for yourself.
</P>
<P>
   When you are in a drugstore emporium wanting to have a roll of
film developed, and you are asked to first fill out a questionnaire
to join a ``photo club'' in which you are not the least interested
...
</P>
<P>
   Or the checker at the department store asks you for additional
personal info ...
</P>
<P>
   Your correct response is not to meekly fork it over nor to throw
a fit of indignation.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, you look the sales representative, or associate _ as
they have come to be widely known _ coldly in the eye, and in a
level tone of voice, you ask: ``What's it worth to you?''
</P>
<P>
   Depending on how much you value yourself, you might conclude a
deal on the spot. If in a supermarket, say, trade your data for all
the milk, cheese and eggs in your shopping cart.
</P>
<P>
   That's a pretty good deal, but not good enough. After you and
yours have ingested and processed the milk, cheese and eggs, they
will be gone. But your personal information will be lodged in the
seller's computer forever.
</P>
<P>
   So you are advised to strike a harder bargain. Agree to share
your data for a set period of time and for a defined fee, in kind
or money. Remember, you are entitled to it. You are, after all, the
resource everyone covets. And by marketing yourself, you are only
doing for yourself as you have been done to.
</P>
<P>
   As a full-fledged participant in the free market, you are
entitled, like everyone else in it, to a decent profit.
</P>
<P>
   You may select whatever method of payment you can work out with
the seller. But whatever you do, do not, repeat not, give your data
away for nothing. As mothers have counseled throughout the
generations, if you do, no one will respect you.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Harry Rosenfeld is editor-at-large at the Albany Times Union,
P.O. Box 15000, Albany, NY 12212.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
