<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-18 12:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0495 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-MORALS19-COX     10-18 0936
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MORALS19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BRAIN INJURIES SEEN INHIBITING DEVELOPMENT OF MORAL COMPASS
 &HT;    By JEFF NESMITH
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Magnetic imaging and psychological tests of two
persons who suffered brain injuries as small children suggest that
damage to a specific part of the brain may hinder the development
of a moral compass.
</P>
<P>
   The studies also raise the possibility that neuroscientists may
one day use drugs or other interventions to modify severe
anti-social behavior resulting from such injuries.
</P>
<P>
   The two individuals, a man and a woman, had suffered injury to
the prefrontal cortex, the area of the brain above the eyes, as
small children. Both had psychological profiles similar to patients
who have been diagnosed as ``psychopaths'' or ``sociopaths,'' said
a team of Iowa researchers in an article published in the current
issue of the journal Nature Neuroscience.
</P>
<P>
   They were reared in stable, middle-class homes by caring,
college-educated parents and had socially well-adapted siblings.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, they each had a pervasive disregard for moral and social
standards, lifelong irresponsibility and lack of remorse over harm
they caused other people.
</P>
<P>
   Their social and moral impairment seemed even worse than the
kind that has been observed in persons who experience similar brain
injuries as adults, said neuroscientist Antonio Damasio and his
colleagues at the University of Iowa College of Medicine.
</P>
<P>
   Start optional trim
</P>
<P>
   Since 1848, when railroad worker Phineas Gage made medical
history after surviving a dynamiting accident in which an iron rod
was driven through his head, researchers have known that certain
brain injuries can lead to a type of moral impairment.
</P>
<P>
   Although the rod was removed from Gage's brain and he evidently
emerged from the accident superficially normal, the experience
radically changed his personality.
</P>
<P>
   Once a conscientious worker, he became a hopeless drifter with a
callous disregard for his former loved ones.
</P>
<P>
   End optional trim
</P>
<P>
   Modern research has shown that adults injured in the prefrontal
cortex, especially an area known as the orbitofrontal cortex, or
OFC, seem to understand ``right from wrong'' but are unable to
incorporate that understanding into their everyday decisions.
</P>
<P>
   But studies of the two persons with lifelong injury to the same
areas suggest they never were able to acquire moral or social
knowledge in the first place. ``Right'' and ``wrong'' were concepts
they appeared never to have been able to learn.
</P>
<P>
   Start optional trim
</P>
<P>
   In a commentary on the research, British neuroscientist Raymond
Dolan noted that Damasio is the originator of the ``somatic-marker
hypothesis'' to explain the role of the OFC has on complex
decision-making.
</P>
<P>
   End optional trim
</P>
<P>
   The OFC, Damasio suggests, links current decisions to knowledge
and feelings acquired in past experience. On the basis of brain
lesion studies and psychological tests, he has suggested that
persons with injury to the OFC are unable to invoke emotions that
normally bias their decisions on the basis of previously learned
lessons.
</P>
<P>
   Start optional trim
</P>
<P>
   Without this emotion-based guidance, such persons may be unable
to adjust their decisions to future expectations or past
experience. They rely on the immediate gratifications a particular
action appears to offer.
</P>
<P>
   End optional trim
</P>
<P>
   The Iowa researchers compared detailed psychological studies of
the two individuals, a man and a woman, with magnetic resonance
imaging of their brains. Although they do not report why they chose
these two individuals for study, they note that persons with known
prefontal cortex damage and lifelong ``behaviorial dysfunction''
are exceedingly rare.
</P>
<P>
   The woman was 20 years old at the time of the studies. She had
been run over by a vehicle when she was 15 months old, and by the
time she was three years old, she was first noted to be largely
unresponsive to verbal or physical punishment.
</P>
<P>
   Intelligent and academically capable, she nonetheless failed in
school, was disruptive, frequently stole from other children and
was arrested for shoplifting. She could not hold a job and was
largely insensitive to the needs of the infant born because of her
early and risky sexual behavior.
</P>
<P>
   The man was 23 and had undergone surgery for a right frontal
tumor at age three months. He recovered with no sign of recurrence.
By age nine, he showed general lack of motivation, limited social
interaction and brief, explosive outbursts of anger. He became
progressively more obese, could not hold a job as an adult, often
ate uncooked frozen foods, lied frequently without apparent motive
and showed no remorse for his behavior or ability to formulate
realistic plans. He exhibited no interest in the child he fathered
in a casual relationship.
</P>
<P>
   Start optional trim
</P>
<P>
   Magnetic resonance imaging of both subjects' brains showed
damage in the prefrontal cortex, the brunt of it borne by the OFC.
</P>
<P>
   ``The crucial element may involve a deficit in representing the
value of behavioral options that involve other people,'' Dolan
noted.
</P>
<P>
   If neurological and biological factors underly the ability to
acquire and use knowledge relevant to social and moral behavior, he
said, ``we will need to reappraise the societal challenges posed by
psychopathy and relarted disorders, which currently (and
conveniently) linger in a hinterland between psychiatry and
criminal services.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
