<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-18 12:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0507 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      10-18 0865
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHAKE, RATTLE AND ROLL: '89 QUAKE HAD ITS FINE MOMENTS 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROB MORSE  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The guys next to me at Peet's coffeehouse in the
Marina, a couple of blocks from where buildings collapsed and
burned in 1989, were looking at a newspaper article on the odds of
a Big One in the Bay Area.
</P>
<P>
   ``Seventy percent chance by the year 2030?'' said one guy.
``That means there's a 30 percent chance of not having a big quake
in the next 30 years.''
</P>
<P>
   He was half-joking, but that's the way people look at things in
this land of perpetual start-ups.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, buy San Francisco real estate. It has less chance of
collapsing than Amazon.com.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday was the 10th anniversary of The Pretty Big One that
registered 7.1 on the Richter scale, wrecked freeways and buildings
and killed 63 people.
</P>
<P>
   Denial, repression, too many scare stories, willful
miscalculation of the casino odds against us _ many are the things
that make us ignore a threat to our lives. But I have another
theory why people in the Bay Area aren't sufficiently frightened of
earthquakes.
</P>
<P>
   The last one was too much fun.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps a better word is ``exciting.'' The '89 quake definitely
wasn't fun for those who lost friends and relatives or had houses
and freeways collapse around them. But the Bay Area was on a manic
edge for weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Loma Prieta was the seismic equivalent of the Persian Gulf War.
It was a low-casualty quake, and we think of it as a time of glory
and heroism. That teaches us all the wrong lessons about
earthquakes, just as Operation Desert Storm was a misleading
example of a war.
</P>
<P>
   We lived very intensely for a few days and have stories to tell
forever. A man in Menlo Park called in late October of 1989 to say
he'd been out of town and had started a support group for those who
missed the quake.
</P>
<P>
   After the quake, everybody was in streets, many drinking beer on
that strange, hot night. Most of San Francisco was a party.
</P>
<P>
   Some yuppies I overheard in North Beach sucked on bottles of
Veuve Cliquot champagne, and one said cavalierly, ``Maybe after
this we'll go looting.''
</P>
<P>
   Only a few people remained indoors, like the guys looking at
skin magazines by flashlight in a porno shop on Broadway.
</P>
<P>
   For several days San Franciscans pulled together, were polite to
each other and even stopped at traffic lights that weren't working,
something they don't do when the lights are working.
</P>
<P>
   The quake managed to be mythic without destroying everything.
</P>
<P>
   It stopped a World Series, diverting blimp coverage to the
burning Marina and a collapsed section of the Bay Bridge.
</P>
<P>
   The video of a burning block that seemed to be the whole city
caused great concern among out-of-town relatives. At some level,
that made us happy.
</P>
<P>
   The quake was exciting. Why else would local television keep
running all that videotape of volunteers manning hoses?
</P>
<P>
   I must admit, I felt some exhilaration in having the routines of
society shaken apart for a few days. Everyone performed above and
beyond expectation, and I contributed to the myth of Loma Prieta by
writing about the generosity of people's response.
</P>
<P>
   Restaurants gave away food and coffee. Food Not Bombs, whose
street soup kitchens are usually suppressed by the authorities, fed
tired and hungry San Francisco cops and firemen.
</P>
<P>
   A courier who had been trapped in his car under the fallen upper
deck of the Cypress Structure told me of his new ``best friend,'' a
man on his way home from shopping who found the courier in his
flattened Datsun. When the man dug a crowbar into what was left of
the courier's door, he said, ``I'm going to scratch your car. Is
that OK?''
</P>
<P>
   We loved our neighbors. But I hated the earthquake as soon as I
got to the office, where we had to put out a newspaper without
anything that runs on electricity.
</P>
<P>
   I was a rich man because I had a flashlight.
</P>
<P>
   Nowadays I keep two flashlights and spare batteries in my car,
along with clothes, work boots, a first aid kit and a canteen of
water that's probably turned green by now.
</P>
<P>
   The stuff looks pathetic in the trunk, but it's probably more
than most people have.
</P>
<P>
   The Loma Prieta anniversary and the U.S. Geological Survey
report on earthquake odds seem to have convinced some people to be
prepared for the earth to move. I swear I'll refill that canteen.
</P>
<P>
   ``As soon as something starts shaking, people start coming in,''
said Stan Deorian, co-owner of the Earthquake Store in Emeryville.
``They just need something to push them away from ... I mean, back
to reality.''
</P>
<P>
   That slip of the tongue said it all. The human brain says
reality is a stable earth. But it isn't, not in the San Francisco
Bay Area, where the map of faults looks like a railroad yard in
Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   Like the guys at Peet's, most people are betting on the Earth
not convulsing for a while. Or else their attitude is to let the
chips fall where they may. And their homes, too.
</P>
<P>
   The next one won't be fun at all.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Rob Morse is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner, P.O.
Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
