<HEADLINE>
APPEALING TO CENTER MAKES POLITICAL SENSE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CLAY ROBISON 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Former Agriculture Commissioner Jim Hightower,
an accomplished quipster and one of the last openly liberal
politicians to get elected to statewide office in Texas, has
observed on numerous occasions that there is ``nothing in the
middle of the road but yellow stripes and dead armadillos.''
</P>
<P>
   Somehow, he overlooked hundreds of election winners who owe
their victories to their ability to appeal to the political center.
</P>
<P>
   As most people know by now, Texas Gov. George W. Bush has
collected a lot of yellow paint on his shoes in his carefully
scripted campaign for the White House. The strategy, so far hugely
successful, is not unlike what he employed to win two races for
governor.
</P>
<P>
   And, with some partisan variations, it is not much different
than the strategy that the eventual nominee for either major party
will have to use in the general election in order to capture the
White House.
</P>
<P>
   But some issues are easier to walk a tightrope over than others,
and one of the most difficult _ so difficult it is virtually
impossible _ is abortion, perhaps the most emotional political
issue of our era.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has made it pretty clear that he opposes most, if not all,
abortion rights. But mostly he is trying to ignore the issue,
banking on his record fund raising and the widespread perception
that he is unbeatable for the Republican nomination to avoid
antagonizing abortion-rights supporters any more than necessary.
Some of those people are Republicans. Others are independents whose
votes he will need in the general election next fall if he actually
becomes the GOP nominee. Even some Democrats may want to vote for
Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Bush would never say that he is taking the social and religious
conservatives in his own party for granted. But he certainly is
betting that he can win the GOP nomination without putting abortion
and other social issues at the top of his agenda, despite the
importance of those issues to that influential element of the
Republican Party.
</P>
<P>
   As Texas governor, Bush has spoken out against abortion. He has
urged premarital abstinence among young people and advocated
adoption as the best alternative in cases of unwanted pregnancies.
Last spring, he signed a new state law, which he had strongly
advocated, to require doctors to notify the parents before
performing abortions on unmarried minors.
</P>
<P>
   But, in his national campaign, Bush has declared that he
wouldn't require his potential federal court appointees to pass a
litmus test on abortion, and he has refused to rule out an
abortion-rights advocate as a potential running mate.
</P>
<P>
   Bush continues to take shots on social issues from Gary Bauer,
Steve Forbes and Alan Keyes _ three Republican candidates who are
actively courting the party's right wing. But they aren't making
any noticeable headway against the front-runner in voter preference
polls.
</P>
<P>
   Perennial Republican candidate Pat Buchanan, a longtime hero of
social conservatives, has all but given up on the GOP and is
flirting with the idea of seeking the Reform Party's presidential
nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Coming from the other direction, meanwhile, Vice President Al
Gore, who is battling former Sen. Bill Bradley for the Democratic
presidential nomination, warned abortion-rights activists that
Bush, if elected, would try to overturn the U.S. Supreme Court
decision that legalized abortion more than 20 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Without mentioning Bush by name, Gore told a Women for Choice
group in Los Angeles that ``moderate-sounding'' Republican
candidates say different things about abortion to the religious
right in private than they do to everyone else in public.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has been praised by Christian Coalition founder Pat
Robertson as a ``very acceptable candidate'' who was ``committed''
to the conservative social agenda. Robertson has either received
private assurances from Bush or is being pragmatic in commending a
conservative candidate with a strong chance of winning the White
House.
</P>
<P>
   Still, some anti-abortion hardliners are unhappy that Bush
hasn't made their issue a prominent, public part of his national
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``If George W. Bush wins the nomination while alienating
conservatives, as his father did in 1992 ... he is doomed to repeat
history and the country will be the big loser _ again,'' recently
wrote Phyllis Schlafly, chairwoman of the Republican National
Coalition for Life.
</P>
<P>
   But at least one prominent Texas anti-abortion leader is, like
Robertson, more pragmatic. Bill Price, president of Texans United
for Life, is convinced that Bush is a strong anti-abortion
candidate.
</P>
<P>
   ``But campaigning isn't always a pretty process,'' Price added.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
