<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KIDS SPEAK OUT ON FAMILY VACATIONS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By HARRY SHATTUCK 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   They prefer to travel by airplane, not in the family car. Their
ideal companion: a best friend. They relish theme-park thrills,
swimming, snorkeling and a CD stereo system in their hotel room.
</P>
<P>
   Ask the No. 1 place to visit with a family, and they answer
Florida. In case the message isn't clear, their second choice is
Walt Disney World in Orlando, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   They have a significant say in planning a family trip. And 87
percent have access to a personal computer _ 71 percent to the
Internet _ in aiding their research.
</P>
<P>
   Recognize them? They're our kids.
</P>
<P>
   Or at least they fit the profile of the typical American child,
according to the 1999 Portrait of Family Travel, an extensive study
undertaken by Orlando-based marketing research firm Yesawich,
Pepperdine &AMP; Brown.
</P>
<P>
   During the second quarter of this year, YP&AMP;B conducted
interviews with 506 adults who traveled with children within the
previous 12 months.
</P>
<P>
   But what makes this 102-page report especially compelling are
additional interviews conducted with 525 children randomly selected
from four age categories: 6-8, 9-11, 12-14 and 15-17.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
ADULTS VS. CHILDREN &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   First, the adult perspective:
</P>
<P>
   Ninety-six percent of the adults interviewed said travel is an
experience all children should have and that travel is educational
for children. Ninety-one percent said travel brings a family closer
together. Eighty-four percent said traveling with kids is rewarding
for parents.
</P>
<P>
   Also, 93 percent said their children's interests are an
important factor in planning vacations. Sixty-four percent
described kids as ``extremely/very influential'' in picking a
destination.
</P>
<P>
   Children, however, sense a less significant role in travel
planning. Only 48 percent of those ages 12-17 consider themselves
``very important'' in determining where the family vacations.
</P>
<P>
   Also intriguing: Although 83 percent of the children interviewed
said they ``really like'' taking a family vacation, neither Mom nor
Dad _ and certainly not little brother or sister _ gets the nod as
the person they ``really like to vacation with'' most.
</P>
<P>
   Allowing for multiple responses, 91 percent of the kids prefer
to travel with a best friend. Other named: Mom (80 percent); Dad
(77 percent); cousins or other relatives the same age (72 percent);
older sisters or brothers (47 percent); grandparents (46 percent);
and _ ouch _ younger sisters and brothers (35 percent).
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
MORE DISAGREEMENTS &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   More food for family thought:
</P>
<P>
   _ Asked what kind of vacation they prefer, 83 percent of the
kids said theme park, 80 percent listed beach, 80 percent answered
water park, 72 percent suggested a cruise, and 67 percent listed an
adventure trip and a visit with family or friends.
</P>
<P>
   Surprising to me, only 57 percent (and only 44 percent of kids
ages 15-17) named camping. But throughout the study, parents tended
to rank nature-oriented vacations significantly higher than did
kids.
</P>
<P>
   _ Asked the top places they would like to experience on vacation
with their children, parents surveyed named Walt Disney World,
Hawaii, the Grand Canyon, Orlando and Washington, D.C., in that
order. Kids' preferred choices, following Florida and Walt Disney
World, are California (home to Disneyland), Hawaii and Australia
(remember, they're not balancing the family budget). Among those
ages 15-17, Australia is the No. 1 choice, even ahead of Florida
and Disney World.
</P>
<P>
   _ According to parents, 89 percent of families took at least one
vacation over the previous year in the family automobile (and only
22 percent took a trip via airplane). Kids surveyed prefer airplane
(54 percent) over car (36 percent).
</P>
<P>
   Parents and kids also differ in evaluating accommodations.
</P>
<P>
   Hotel and resort amenities considered most important by the
adults: (1) security and safety; (2) discounts for additional rooms
for children traveling with parents; (3) a restaurant where kids
eat free; (4) larger guest rooms designed to accommodate children;
and (5) a restaurant with special menu items for children. Within
guest rooms, amenities judged most important are (1) in-room movies
and (2) childproofing.
</P>
<P>
   Hotel and resort amenities considered most important by
children: (1) a swimming pool with slides and waterfalls and
separate from the parents' pool; (2) an area for kids to hang out;
(3) a separate room that attaches to the parents' room; (4) a video
arcade; and (5) a restaurant that features hamburgers and pizza.
Beyond CD music, other guest-room amenities preferred _ I sense a
pattern here _ are (2) movies, (3) a VCR and (4) video games.
</P>
<P>
   Also eye-opening are numbers involving the Internet. It's
impressive enough that 71 percent of the kids surveyed have access
to an online service. But 58 percent of those ages 12-17 said they
research travel information online.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, although Internet access figures are similar, only
32 percent of parents had obtained travel information and prices
online. Ten percent had booked travel online. (For the record, 34
percent said they referred to the Sunday travel section of their
local newspaper for family vacation planning.)
</P>
<P>
   ``The results of our study suggest that (previous surveys of
adults only) overlooked the sentiments of some of the most
important decision-makers in the households: kids,'' said YP&AMP;B
president Peter Yesawich.
</P>
<P>
   The YP&AMP;B study is available to businesses as a tool in planning
marketing efforts. Cost is $1,600. Custom analyses also are
available. Call 407-875-1111. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-18-99 1300EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
