<DOCNO> NYT19991018.0194 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-18 13:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0527 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-GORE-CALIFORNIA-HNS &LR;      10-18 0909
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-CALIFORNIA-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE A BORE? GOVERNOR SAYS IT MAY NOT BE A BAD THING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROBERT SALLADAY  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO, Calif. _ Maybe California Gov. Gray Davis didn't get
the memo from Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   At the exact moment Vice President Al Gore was trying to inject
some excitement into his campaign, Davis was taking the stage at
the AFL-CIO convention last week in Los Angeles, snatching Gore
right back into the Land of the Political Dweeb.
</P>
<P>
   Davis, a Democrat, urged union workers from across the nation to
embrace Gore as they did him _ a ``boring, dull fellow dismissed as
roadkill and yesterday's news.''
</P>
<P>
   There may be good reason for Davis' backhanded endorsement:
Davis beat former Attorney General Dan Lungren last year in one of
the largest landslides in state history, and helped sweep other
Democrats into near-total power.
</P>
<P>
   If California is a microcosm of the nation, then the Davis
campaign and how he won offer an important star chart to the White
House. Never have the signs been more apparent than during the last
few weeks on the presidential campaign trail.
</P>
<P>
   His new Tennessee campaign headquarters and cowboy boots aside,
Gore is running a campaign that parallels Davis' in many ways. Last
week, he courted and secured the endorsement of the influential
AFL-CIO. Trade unions helped sweep Davis to victory by working the
phones and energizing rank-and-file members.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, too, has stayed cautious when it comes to tipping the boat
with expensive policy initiatives. Davis has perfected that
strategy, despite being identified by Time magazine as the most
``fearless'' governor in America. Davis is convinced that a
don't-rock-the-boat philosophy wins races, especially when the
economy is reaching Xanadu status.
</P>
<P>
   Gore recently introduced a series of health-care reforms that
would be roughly $50 billion cheaper than those proposed by his
Democratic opponent, former Sen. Bill Bradley of New Jersey. For
his part, Bradley has been busy courting liberal Democrats while
maintaining the patina of an outsider charging the net in
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   When Davis marched into the 1998 Democratic convention before
the gubernatorial primary, he faced a sea of Davis signs and
hundreds of chanting supporters. Down in the polls at the time,
insiders dismissed the convention support as just party faithful
rallying around a party insider.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley, too, has been counting signs, and he's worried about
it. Last week in Iowa, the two candidates spoke at the annual
Jefferson-Jackson Day dinner in Des Moines. Seeing all the Gore
signs, Bradley remarked: ``There is no question we are up against
entrenched power. I don't have high expectations. We have to do
OK.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be a little bit like going into Boston Garden in
the seventh game.'' the former New York Knicks basketball player
said. ``You never know, you could turn around some of the Boston
fans.''
</P>
<P>
   There is a clear difference between Gore and Davis.
</P>
<P>
   Jaime Regalado, executive director of the Edmund G. ``Pat''
Brown Institute of Public Affairs at California State University in
Los Angeles, said Gore ``carries a lot of baggage from the worst of
the Clinton years. Gray Davis didn't suffer from that.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Another student of the 1998 California race has been Texas Gov.
George W. Bush, the apparent Republican front-runner. Although he
agrees with Lungren on many crucial conservative issues, Bush has
in recent weeks begun veering toward the center, at least in words.
</P>
<P>
   That is the primary lesson for Republicans from the California
race. Lungren, a conservative to the core, never really liked
pretending to be a centrist. Amid President Clinton's sex scandal,
Lungren injected religion into the debate as he lectured about
morality and politics.
</P>
<P>
   Now Bush is lecturing his own party.
</P>
<P>
   ``Too often, on social issues, my party has painted an image of
America slouching toward Gomorrah,'' Bush said recently. Bush, in
another speech, chastised the Republican-led Congress for
attempting to ``balance their budget on the backs of the poor'' and
later said his party often ignores `human problems that persist in
the shadow of affluence.''
</P>
<P>
   Since taking office, Davis has gone out of his way to alienate
the far reaches of the Democratic Party. He revels in it. Like Bush
_ and Clinton before him _ Davis is antagonizing the left and the
right in order to appear centrist and connected to real voters in
the middle. It's an extension of the monotonous drone of Davis'
1998 campaign _ moderation, centrism, no huge promises.
</P>
<P>
   The far reaches of the GOP huffed and protested that Bush is
dismissing his core voters by ripping into the conservative side of
the party. But the base in American politics consists of millions
of independent voters within both major parties.
</P>
<P>
   It will be up to Gore to convince voters that Bush isn't on
their side. That means going after his public record, just as Davis
hammered Lungren on issues such as guns, abortion and tobacco.
</P>
<P>
   While Bush has so far avoided critical scrutiny of his record in
Texas, he continues to score points in an area where Lungren
foundered. Bush has received critical support from Hispanic voters
in Texas, whereas Lungren alienated Hispanic voters with his
support for an anti-immigrant ballot initiative.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
