homosexuals. Garcia thinks that Bush's silence sends a disturbing
message _ namely that Bush is less interested in taking a
principled stand against the likes of Buchanan than he is in
holding on to a few more right-wing votes. PLEASE NOTE: This is a
strong opinion piece which may provoke reactions from readers.
</P>
<P>
   THE TALE OF THE `INDIAN' TRADEMARK. Before Karen Lincoln
Michel's tribe legally changed its name to Ho-Chunk, they were
known as Winnebago. ``The motor-home connection to my tribe
wouldn't be so demoralizing, I used to think, if we were reaping
some of the profits from the RV maker,'' Michel writes. An Indian
tribe in southern Oregon can relate. The Cow Creek Band of Umpqua
Tribe of Indians wanted to revive the vintage Indian Motorcycle by
manufacturing a new version on reservation land. But a white-owned
company beat them to the rights to the ``Indian'' trademark a year
ago. Michel reports that it is unlawful under the federal Indian
Arts and Crafts Act to label products as ``Indian made'' when they
are not. Her take: ``Most companies neither verbalize nor
demonstrate any kind of respect for Native-Americans unless they
can make a buck from it.'' Lincoln is a past president of the
Native-American Journalists Association.
</P>
<P>
   ON ISRAEL, I'LL CALL IT AS I SEE IT _ Columnist Bill Maxwell
knows that his commentaries about Israel anger many American Jews
nationwide. He is often asked why he, an American black, is
interested in Israel and Jews. Maxwell tries to answer this
question, as well as examine a related issue, that of Jews
selectively misreading anything they deem unflattering to Israel _
even if the issue in question is indisputably true. '' ... too many
American Jews see the nation as an innocent land that can do no
wrong. The truth is that the Promised Land _ while giving Jews a
sacred homeland and while inspiring millions of other people
worldwide to wonder and to affirm their religious faith _ has warts
just like other nations. Acknowledging this simple truth does not
make a journalist an anti-Semite,'' Maxwell writes.
</P>
<P>
   IS THE GOVERNMENT TELLING US THE TRUTH ABOUT THE MOSQUITOES?
Mayor Giuliani and his health-department aides would like New
Yorkers to believe that the pesticide malathion that has been
sprayed all over the city's neighborhoods recently to kill off any
mosquitoes carrying the West Nile virus is perfectly safe. How safe
it is really? Columnist Juan Gonzalez reports that on a data sheet
from one of the city's main malathion suppliers, a company called
Cheminova Agro, a note to physicians reads: ``Fyfanon ULV
(malathion) is a cholinesterase inhibitor affecting the central and
peripheral nervous systems, and producing cardiac and respiratory
depression.'' According to Dr. Adrienne Buffaloe, who runs a
private environmental medicine center on Manhattan's upper East
Side, ``the city and federal governments are deceiving the public
about the dangers of malathion ... A good number of medical
professionals have been troubled by the massive pesticide spraying
that went on in New York.''
</P>
<P>
   ASIAN-AMERICAN STUDIES IN THE FAST LANE. There's a new momentum
in Asian-American studies (AAS) at the university level, reports
Mitchell J. Chang in this excerpt from A. Magazine. Way back in
1968, AAS emerged out of the social unrest at San Francisco State
University. It grew slowly, mainly across the West Coast and in
pockets in the East until the '90s, when the field experienced a
turbo-charged expansion. So why the sudden growth spurt? For one
thing, there has been as jump in Asian Pacific American student
enrollment. In addition to this, students in the '90s are the
children of the civil-rights struggles that established the
original AAS courses and programs. They fully expect to have the
opportunity to take such courses. In this feature, Chang, an
assistant professor at the Graduate College of Education at the
University of Massachusetts, Boston, offers a primer on the boom in
Asian-American studies.
</P>
