<SLUG> BC-GLORIA-ESTEFAN-IN-MUSIC-OF-THE-HEART-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VIOLINS AGAINST VIOLENCE: GLORIA ESTEFAN SINGS `MUSIC OF THE
HEART' 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 (Includes a color slide of Gloria Estefan with Meryl Streep and
Angela Bassett in a scene from ``Music of the Heart.'') 
 By CINDY PEARLMAN  
 World rights except Chicago 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    Gloria Estefan doesn't seem to get being a celebrity.
 &HT;    A small figure curled up on a coach at New York's Regency Hotel
on a fall afternoon, Estefan apparently can't master the rules of
divadom.
 &HT;    She serves soft drinks to journalists.
 &HT;    She makes sure her handlers have enough cookies.
 &HT;    She even asks a publicist from Miramax Films when she will have
time for a bathroom break.
 &HT;    ``I never complain about anything in this life,'' says the
singer _ who, only a few years ago, was grievously injured in a
highway accident and told that she would never walk again.
 &HT;    ``When a complaint is on the tip of my tongue, I remember the
day, months after my own accident, when I was able to put my
underwear on myself,'' the 42-year-old Estefan says. ``I could lift
my leg an inch off the ground and maneuver it. That day always
brings everything else into focus, so nothing is a big deal to me
now.
 &HT;    ``I can get up and walk across this room to get myself a glass
of water,'' she says. ``I can hold my child. I can carry her in my
arms. I can run up to my husband and hug him. What else is there in
this life?''
 &HT;    Well, for starters there's a movie career.
 &HT;    The singer will make her big-screen debut in ``Music of the
Heart,'' opening Oct. 29. The film stars Meryl Streep as a violin
teacher who comes to Harlem to start a school music program, with
Estefan in a small but pivotal role as a supportive teacher.
 &HT;    The director is Wes Craven, best known for ``A Nightmare on Elm
Street'' (1984) and ``Scream'' (1996).
 &HT;    ``When I heard Wes was doing a violin movie, I said, `What, is
he going to slit my throat with the strings?''' Estefan says with a
laugh. ``I thought it was a horror movie.''
 &HT;    For the singer, making her film debut _ after rejecting numerous
scripts in the past _ was scary enough without a mad slasher.
 &HT;    ``My husband Emilio and I always knew if a great movie role
didn't come along, we could create our own project eventually,''
Estefan says. ``But I really wanted to get my feet wet outside my
own power base.''
 &HT;    That power base lies in music and the Cuban community, into
which Estefan was born in 1957 as Gloria Fajardo in Havana. Her
father was a soldier in the security detail for the family of Cuban
dictator Gen. Fulgencio Batista.
 &HT;    In 1959, when Fidel Castro seized power, the Fajardos fled Cuba.
Estefan was 2 years old when her family settled in Miami.
 &HT;    Soon, however, her father was recruited into a C.I.A.-backed
brigade of 1,300 Cuban refugees that launched the unsuccessful Bay
of Pigs invasion two years later. He landed in a Cuban prison for
two years.
 &HT;    After his release he joined the U.S. Army and was sent to
Vietnam, where he was exposed to the defoliant Agent Orange, which
his daughter believes triggered the multiple sclerosis which struck
him soon thereafter.
 &HT;    A young Gloria had to tend her sick father and raise her younger
sister, while her mother struggled to support the family by working
as a teacher.
 &HT;    ``Those were very rough moments,'' she says. ``My Dad was a big
guy. My Dad would forget that he couldn't walk and he would fall.
Then I would have to find ways of trying to lift him back up again.
I had to bathe him _ he was very embarrassed.
 &HT;    ``But in retrospect, it taught me so much,'' she adds. ``I
learned how to deal with everything that life throws at you. I
think it toughened me. It taught me how to be patient.''
 &HT;    Young, overweight and burdened with her family responsibilities,
Estefan had virtually no social life, she says. She found joy in
singing and playing her guitar, and devoted herself to school,
earning a scholarship to study psychology at the University of
Miami.
 &HT;    Those plans ended one night at a local club, however, when she
saw a local Cuban-American quartet called the Miami Latin Boys.
 &HT;    The band's leader, Emilio Estefan, immediately fell for the
young girl, and invited her to try singing with the band.
 &HT;    ``I wowed them with my voice because I had so much angst,''
Estefan recalls. ``It came out through my singing.''
 &HT;    Soon the bandleader and the aspiring singer were an item and,
under his guidance, she found her confidence growing.
 &HT;    ``He saw that I had this shell, and said, `You can keep your
shell and still be a performer, but you'll be a tortured one,'''
she recalls. ``So I thought, `I love music. I want people to see
how much I love it.' Slowly, I began to feel more and more
comfortable and lost the weight.''
 &HT;    One year later, the group was renamed The Miami Sound Machine
and released two albums, and the road to success opened before
them. During the early 1980s the band's Spanish-language albums
soared to the top of the Latin American charts.
 &HT;    Life was good for the Estefans, who had married in 1978, but
they wanted more than Latin success. In 1984 they took on the
American market with the dance single ``Dr. Beat,'' which debuted
at number 10 on the U.S. dance charts. The all-English album
``Primitive Love'' (1985), with its hit single ``Conga,'' made
Gloria Estefan an international sensation.
 &HT;    Soon the band became Gloria Estefan and The Miami Sound Machine,
then simply Gloria Estefan. Her solo album ``Cuts Both Ways''
(1989) and its singles ``Can't Stay Away From You,'' ``Anything for
You'' and ``Don't Wanna Lose You'' all hit No. 1 on the charts.
 &HT;    And then, seemingly at the pinnacle, Estefan almost lost it all.
 &HT;    In 1990, as the band was in the middle of a successful tour, a
truck broadsided the tour bus. Estefan suffered broken and
dislocated vertebra in her back, and underwent four hours of
surgery in which two 8-inch titanium rods were permanently
implanted to stabilize and align her spinal column.
 &HT;    The singer credits her husband for her all-but-miraculous
recovery.
 &HT;    ``This man literally didn't leave my side for three months,''
she says. ``He would spend his days lifting me up and putting me
down. I couldn't sleep for more than 45 minutes at a time. He would
get up with me each time and force me to move as much as possible.
In the hall, I would hear him crying.''
 &HT;    Fans sent 4,000 floral arrangements, 11,000 telegrams and 50,000
postcards and letters.
 &HT;    ``In my heart, I knew I would be OK,'' Estefan says. ``I willed
myself not to end up in a wheelchair like my father. And I honestly
think the human mind can achieve miracles.''
 &HT;    The next year, Estefan had a new album, ``Into the Light,'' and
returned to the stage with a yearlong, 29-country tour. She even
got a hit song, ``Coming Out of the Dark,'' out of her health
crisis.
 &HT;    Next up for Estefan is a new Spanish album, due out in March,
and a world tour which will kick off next year.
 &HT;    ``I sing because I want to touch everyone in what I call `that
place,''' Estefan says. ``When people pay to see me, I want them to
know that they have me for that one night. It's personal _ it's
about me and that fan.''
 c.1999 Cindy Pearlman  
<TEXT>
