<HEADER>
A0570 &Cx1f; tab-z
w e BC-HALLOWEEN-HORROR-MOVI     10-18 1493
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HALLOWEEN-HORROR-MOVIE-QUIZ-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCARE TACTICS: A HALLOWEEN QUIZ FOR FRIGHT-FLICK FANS 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 (Includes a color slide of Anthony Hopkins in a scene from ``The
Silence of the Lambs.'') 
 By S. BURELISON  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    Wall paintings dating from 3000 B.C., depicting evil figures and
piles of skeletons, suggest that people back then loved a good
scare.
 &HT;    Since then, it's been the same story: The ancient Greeks traded
tales of flesh-eating creatures, and the second-century Roman
author Pliny wrote about haunted houses.
 &HT;    But horror stories took on a whole new life _ or living death? _
with the invention of the motion picture.
 &HT;    The earliest film pioneers didn't have to stage spooky scenarios
to frighten their audiences _ merely watching moving pictures was
pretty scary to most people a century ago. When Paris viewers saw a
train speed toward them for the first time in 1895's one-scene
movie ``L'Arrivee d'un Train a la Crotat,'' many ran screaming for
the nearest exit.
 &HT;    Advances in movie technology enabled filmmakers to show us the
demons that the storytellers couldn't, but _ as ``The Blair Witch
Project'' (1999) demonstrated all over again _ sometimes the unseen
is more frightening. Alfred Hitchcock, hailed as ``the master of
suspense,'' said he believed in ``putting the horror in the mind of
the audience,'' not on the screen.
 &HT;    In a way, he was following in the footsteps of those ancient
Greeks, as have filmmakers through the decades, whether their films
were elegantly ambiguous or stomach-turningly graphic.
 &HT;    How well do you remember these films that gave viewers the feel
of reel terror? 
 -0- 
 TEST YOUR TERROR QUOTIENT  
 &HT;    1. Besides rats and armadillos, who shares the count's
Transylvanian castle in ``Dracula'' (1931)?
 &HT;    2. What is the name of Dr. Frankenstein's hunchbacked assistant,
who steals an ``abnormal'' brain for his boss in ``Frankenstein''
(1931)?
 &HT;    3. Why was Imhotep, title character in ``The Mummy'' (1932),
buried alive in the first place?
 &HT;    4. The East Indian drug monocane transforms scientist Jack
Griffin into ... who?
 &HT;    5. You too may succumb to lycanthropy, like ``The Wolfman''
(1941), if you have a certain mark on your palm. What mark is it?
 &HT;    6. Graf Orlok, the title character in ``Nosferatu'' (1922), is
far uglier than Dracula. And, unlike his more famous counterpart,
he doesn't perish by a stake through the heart. What destroys him?
 &HT;    7. Like, this guy Merrick (Donald Sutherland) shows up and tells
what title teen that she has to, like, stop some kind of dark evil
forces instead of going to the mall?
 &HT;    8. According to Armand (Antonio Banderas) in ``Interview With
the Vampire'' (1994), what is the only act that is considered a
crime among his fellow neck-nibblers?
 &HT;    9. What is the name of the possessed estate that is explored in
``The Haunting'' (1963)?
 &HT;    10. ``The House on Haunted Hill'' (1958), ruled by Vincent
Price, has a particularly distinctive amenity in the basement. What
is it?
 &HT;    11. What gift enables little Danny Torrence (Danny Lloyd) to
foresee horror in room 237 of the Overlook Hotel?
 &HT;    12. What is kept in ``The Cabinet of Dr. Caligari'' (1919)?
 &HT;    13. Who teaches the Monster (Boris Karloff) to speak in ``Bride
of Frankenstein'' (1935)?
 &HT;    14. According to the advertisements, medical student Herbert
West (Jeffrey Combs) ``has a very good head on his shoulders _ and
another one in a dish on his desk.'' What film was being
advertised?
 &HT;    15. ``The Tingler'' (1959) looks like a lobster tail with little
legs, but Dr. Chapin (Vincent Price) says it's fear incarnate, and
can be escaped in only one way. How?
 &HT;    16. What two words appear on the stomach of poor, possessed
Regan (Linda Blair) before ``The Exorcist'' (1973) shows up?
 &HT;    17. Guy (John Cassavetes) agrees to allow ``Rosemary's Baby''
(1968) to be Satan's son in exchange for what?
 &HT;    18. What's the significance of the license plate ``CQB 241?''
 &HT;    19. In ``The Night of the Living Dead'' (1968), what are the
only two ways to kill the man-eating zombies?
 &HT;    20. According to the catchy slogan for ``Motel Hell'' (1980),
what does it take to produce Farmer Vincent's Fritters?
 &HT;    21. In ``The Silence of the Lambs'' (1991), what dead-giveaway
evidence does FBI Agent Clarice Starling (Jodie Foster) spot that
reveals she's in the home of killer Buffalo Bill (Ted Levine)?
 &HT;    22. When does Michael Myers go on his first murderous rampage in
Smith's Grove, Ill.?
 &HT;    23. Gunnar Hansen portrayed what cut-up in the cult slasher film
``The Texas Chainsaw Massacre'' (1974)?
 &HT;    24. Norman Bates (Anthony Perkins) doesn't spend all his time in
the shower in ``Psycho'' (1960). What is his hobby?
 &HT;    25. What former child star is the first to die in ``Scream''
(1996)? 
 THE AWFUL TRUTH  
 &HT;    1. Dracula shares his abode with three ``brides,'' two brunettes
and a blonde _ who was usually Greta Garbo's stand-in. And yes,
there are indeed armadillos on the stairs.
 &HT;    2. I bet you said ``Igor,'' didn't you? Well, Frankenstein's
henchman is Fritz, played by Dwight Frye, who was often typecast as
a mad sidekick after his memorable 1931 portrayal of Dracula's
slave, Renfield.
 &HT;    3. Imhotep was punished for having used the Sacred Scroll of
Thoth to restore his beloved Princess Ankh-es-en-Amon to life.
 &HT;    4. Monocane makes Jack Griffin into ``The Invisible Man''
(1933), played by Claude Rains in his screen debut.
 &HT;    5. A pentagram _ a five-pointed star _ on your hand means that
you'd be best advised to beware of the full moon.
 &HT;    6. Orlok stands in front of a window at dawn, and the sunlight
dissolves him.
 &HT;    7. Merrick delivers his warning to ``Buffy the Vampire Slayer''
(1992), who continues her quest for the undead and the hottest new
styles on television.
 &HT;    8. The worst thing Anne Rice's vampires can do is to kill a
fellow vampire.
 &HT;    9. Hill House is explored in ``The Haunting'' and its 1999
remake, both based on Shirley Jackson's novel, ``The Haunting of
Hill House.''
 &HT;    10. Price's basement features an acid pit, bubbling with the
bones of its victims.
 &HT;    11. Danny has second sight, also known as ``The Shining''
(1980).
 &HT;    12. The mad doctor keeps his sleepwalking slave, Cesare (Conrad
Veidt), in his cabinet ... or so we think.
 &HT;    13. A blind hermit (O.P. Heggie) teaches the Monster to speak.
His first words are ``bread,'' ``good'' and ``friend,'' in that
order.
 &HT;    14. Herbert's experiments earn him _ and the 1985 film _ the
name ``Re-Animator.''
 &HT;    15. ``Scream,'' Price says, ``Scream for your lives!''
Apparently, expressing fear thwarts The Tingler.
 &HT;    16. Regan's abdomen reads ``help me.''
 &HT;    17. Rosemary's rotten hubby asks for, and receives, career
opportunities as an actor.
 &HT;    18. ``CQB 241'' is the license plate of the haunted 1958
Plymouth Fury in ``Christine'' (1983).
 &HT;    19. Only a shot or heavy blow to the head, destroying their
radiation-activated brains, can kill the Living Dead.
 &HT;    20. ``It takes all kinds of critters to make Farmer Vincent's
Fritters!'' _ including people fattened up and murdered by motel
owner Rory Calhoun.
 &HT;    21. Starling spots a death's-head moth. Actually, tomato
hornworms were used, made up to resemble the rare moth, which was
also pictured in the film's memorable poster, covering Foster's
mouth.
 &HT;    22. Myers' carnage occurs on ``Halloween'' (1978).
 &HT;    23. Gunnar Hansen played ``Leatherface,'' who wields the
chainsaw in the cult favorite.
 &HT;    24. Norman enjoys taxidermy _ his specialty is stuffing birds.
 &HT;    25. Trick question _ actually, no one. Casey Becker, played by
former child star Drew Barrymore, is actually the second ``Scream''
victim. The first, Casey's boyfriend, was not played by a former
child star.
 c.1999 S. Burelison  
<TEXT>
