w e BC-SELA-WARD-IN-ONCE-AND     10-18 1415
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SELA-WARD-IN-ONCE-AND-AGAIN-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`ONCE' UPON A HIT: SELA WARD RETURNS WITH `ONCE AND AGAIN' 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 Not to be released in Canada before Oct. 24, 1999. 
 (Includes a color slide of Sela Ward in a scene from ``Once and
Again.'') 
 By ANDREW RYAN  
 c.1999 TV Guide Canada  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sela Ward might almost have been waiting for this.
</P>
<P>
   In the years following her five-season run on the acclaimed
drama ``Sisters'' _ which earned her a Best Actress Emmy in 1994 as
the exotic, neurotic Teddy _ Ward chose work judiciously: a few
small parts in movies such as ``The Fugitive'' (1993), ``My Fellow
Americans'' (1996) and ``54'' (1998), the occasional television
movie such as ``Almost Golden: The Jessica Savitch Story'' (1995)
and even the odd quirky sitcom one-shot, as a gorgeous love
interest for ``Frasier.''
</P>
<P>
   All along, she had offers for other drama series, but she always
declined.
</P>
<P>
   ``I swore I would never, ever do another hour-long series,'' the
actress says. ``It's just too many hours, too draining.''
</P>
<P>
   All that went out the window, though, when Ward was approached
by ``Thirtysomething'' creators Marshall Herskovitz and Edward
Zwick about a new drama, ``Once and Again,'' which they were
prepping for ABC.
</P>
<P>
   The central character was Lily, a newly divorced, 40-year-old
mother of two whose already frenetic life is turned upside down
when she meets and falls for a ruggedly handsome, divorced dad
named Rick _ played by Bill Campbell, best known for ``The
Rocketeer'' (1991) _ who also has two kids.
</P>
<P>
   When Ward read the script, she reports, she was instantly
hooked.
</P>
<P>
   ``On page one,'' she says, ``in that interview with Lily, where
she's speaking about how all she wants is to feel safe in life, I'm
going, `Oh, that's me!' I make every decision in my life based on
that kind of thing. By the time I got through with the script, I
couldn't get it out of my head.''
</P>
<P>
   Ward's instincts were on the money. ABC liked ``Once and Again''
enough to launch it in ``NYPD Blue's'' time slot for a six-week
test in late September.
</P>
<P>
   Smart move: So far ``Once and Again'' is this season's
second-highest-rated new drama, closely trailing NBC's much-hyped
``The West Wing.'' ABC is pleased, and the series will reportedly
receive a Saturday-night slot of its own starting in January.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once and Again'' is an offbeat venture for its creators. A
good deal of screen time is spent alternately with Lily and Rick,
in stark black-and-white, speaking into the camera about their
innermost personal feelings. As a result, both actors say they've
gotten a grasp of their characters deeper than usual so early in a
series.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rick is unsure of himself, a little swamped and a hopeless
romantic,'' Campbell says.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lily is smart, a great mother, neurotic, not self-assured,
vulnerable, funny and a blast to play,'' Ward adds.
</P>
<P>
   The dramatic content on ``Once and Again'' is heightened by
dialogue that's vintage ``Thirtysomething'' _ brutally honest and
fraught with human frailties.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've coined them `the Dream Team of all time,''' Ward says of
Herskovitz and Zwick, who also created the Emmy-winning ``My
So-Called Life.'' ``They write such honest, compelling dialogue. It
was the exact same way on `Thirtysomething' _ that's how real
people actually talk.''
</P>
<P>
   One thing for sure, though: This is not ``The Brady Bunch.'' The
families on ``Once and Again'' enter the picture with plenty of
emotional baggage: Lily's daughter Grace (Julia Whelan) is freaked
out about her mother's new boyfriend, while her 9-year-old sister
Zoe (Meredith Deane) still thinks her mom is going to get back
together with her irresponsible ex-husband, Jake (Jeffrey
Nordling).
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Rick's kids are similarly messed up: At 16, young
Rick (Shane West) is already having sex _ unlike his dad, at least
in the first few episodes _ and 12-year-old Jessie (Evan Rachel
Wood) is feeling ignored and confused.
</P>
<P>
   It's not happy talk, but it is reality.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we did `My So-Called Life,''' Zwick says, ``it was about
the teen-age experience, and that will be this to some degree. And
it's also subjectively about the experience of love and about
parenting teen-age children. I think that's maybe the fulcrum that
draws those two things together _ I think that will allow us to
actually do a show that's about both. Because, in my experience,
they can't exist exclusive of one another.''
</P>
<P>
   Even ``Once and Again's'' young co-stars have been struck by the
show's realism.
</P>
<P>
   ``My parents have been divorced twice, actually _ once at 2 and
once at 13,'' West says. ``So a lot of this was like therapy. I got
to see things from a different viewpoint, and it was very easy to
identify with the character.''
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, Deane says she can recognize the in-family
squabbling.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though my parents aren't divorced, I think it's easy to
relate to a character that you can really understand,'' she says.
``Everyday fights with your sister, getting in the way of your mom
_ just being there and being part of a family. It's easy to relate
to.''
</P>
<P>
   As the pivotal figure on ``Once and Again,'' Ward also sees a
lot of honesty in the storytelling, particularly in those scenes in
which Lily and Rick simultaneously rediscover their physical
feelings and are fumbling with each other's clothes like a pair of
teen-agers.
</P>
<P>
   ``One reason I fell so in love with this show,'' she says, ``is
because I think, perhaps unwittingly, they've written something
that celebrates age, that celebrates that at 40 there is life. At
40, there are new experiences _ at 40, you can have the same
feelings and emotions and state of expectancy that you had when you
were 18 and 19.''
</P>
<P>
   Offscreen, Ward says she isn't at all the harried mother she
plays on her show. At 43, the onetime model is a happily married
mother of two young children.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, the semi-sabbatical she took after ``Sisters''
wasn't her idea, she adds. It was just that most of the lead roles
she pursued went instead to younger women.
</P>
<P>
   Such is the reality of Hollywood casting.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a wasteland of roles for particular women,'' Ward says.
``I mean, if you look at the actresses playing opposite the Michael
Douglases and even Harrison Ford, you know, excuse me? They can't
play opposite someone close to their own age? Or even 15 years
younger?''
</P>
<P>
   Herskovitz and Zwick planned the ``Once and Again'' trial run to
end with a teasing finale involving a major crisis in the
burgeoning Lily-Rick relationship. How things will work out after
the series returns, they aren't telling.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we did `Thirtysomething,''' Herskovitz says, ``we were
very clear in our minds that we didn't want people to know what was
coming, because somehow knowing what was coming would change the
experience of it happening. That served us very well in the past.''
</P>
<P>
   Either way, you won't hear Ward complaining about the veil of
secrecy _ or, for that matter, about anything else. She's back in
the spotlight on a hit series and, like Lily, she's on a voyage of
rediscovery.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like my life is just beginning,'' Ward says. ``I don't
think I've ever been happier. I feel right. I feel ... yummy.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Andrew Ryan is the features editor for TV Guide Canada.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: For further information on ``Once and Again,'' consult the
official Website at www.onceandagain.com. And don't forget to visit
The New York Times Syndicate Website at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for information on StarBeat and
other features. &QL; 
