<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOHN-MALKOVICH-IN-BEING-JOHN-MALKOVICH-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOHN MALKOVICH'S STATE OF `BEING' 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 (Includes a color slide of John Malkovich in a scene from ``Being
John Malkovich.'') 
 By IAN SPELLING  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    He's just being John Malkovich.
 &HT;    That is to say, the enigmatic actor is being typically
enigmatic. In New York to promote his latest movie, ``Being John
Malkovich,'' he cuts a businessman-suave figure in a navy-blue
suit, speaks in a decidedly nonmenacing whisper and utters deep
thoughts in bursts of oddly constructed sentences laden with mixed
messages and the occasional SAT-caliber word.
 &HT;    Listen, for example, to his thoughts on the perception, in
Hollywood and among the general public, that he's a screen villain
without peer.
 &HT;    ``It's irritating,'' he says, taking a long drag on a cigarette.
``Look at my films this year: I've played John Malkovich, the king
of France, F.W. Murnau and Herman Mankiewicz. But if people want to
say I only play bad guys, what am I going to do about it?
 &HT;    ``Certainly, I've gotten more laughs in straight plays than most
comedians get in their f---ing lives.''
 &HT;    The frustration in his voice comes across loud and clear.
 &HT;    ``On the other hand, so what?'' he continues. ``I have to look
at it in a secondary and a tertiary way. I'm a saxophonist who got
known for playing the drums. I'm not a movie actor, and I'm lucky
to get another job. So it's already fine _ I'm way ahead of the
game.
 &HT;    ``And it's not a real frustration, really at all,'' Malkovich
adds. ``The camera likes what it likes. They says the camera
doesn't lie, and I say that's what it's for.''
 &HT;    All of which may be a bit hard to follow, but it's nothing
compared to the wonderfully warped ``Being John Malkovich,'' which
will open nationwide on Oct. 29. In the film, Malkovich plays ...
well, John Malkovich, as a put-upon, womanizing and
more-than-a-little-arrogant movie icon.
 &HT;    John Cusack stars as a luckless Manhattan puppeteer who lands a
day job as a file clerk and soon discovers, hidden behind a
cabinet, a boarded-up portal into the mind of John Malkovich.
Cusack and co-worker Catherine Keener promptly hawk tickets to ride
for 15 minutes in Malkovich's head, eventually wreaking havoc for
them and for Cameron Diaz, who plays Cusack's disheveled wife, as
well as for Malkovich himself.
 &HT;    ``I don't think anybody reading `Being John Malkovich' who ever
lived or worked in Hollywood for more than a second would ever
expect this film to get made,'' the actor says.
 &HT;    Why not?
 &HT;    ``Because it's good,'' he says. ``Of course, they probably never
thought I'd make it. If I didn't say yes, then this original,
interesting movie wouldn't get made.
 &HT;    ``You don't see enough original, interesting movies,'' Malkovich
adds, ``and I wasn't going to be the guy to kill this.''
 &HT;    Still, it's a surprise that Malkovich agreed to participate in
the film. He has a notorious disdain for the Hollywood machine _ he
refuses to read any press about himself, for example _ and
ferociously guards his private life with his family in France. Not
to mention the genuine risk of further blurring the line between
reality and fiction.
 &HT;    ``It could be dangerous,'' Malkovich concedes with a shrug. ``It
was a concern, but it was also an unknowable. We'll see.
 &HT;    ``There are two things in the movie about wanting to be someone
else,'' he adds. ``One is very harmless and very good, and that's
that it addresses and encompasses native curiosity and our very
human _ and not very have-able, in today's society _ need to leave
ourselves, to get away from whatever is in our heads or hearts for
some period of time.
 &HT;    ``The second thing, which is more sinister and deeply
concerning, is the celebrity thing, the need to lead a virtual
life, meaning your sorrows and joys and passions aren't as
interesting as mine, of course, or George Clooney's or John
Goodman's,'' he says.
 &HT;    ``We go to McDonald's. We have to decide if we're going to park
the car or go through McDrive, get a Coke or an iced tea. Life goes
on.''
 &HT;    On the less serious side, Malkovich was often amused to find
himself getting instructions from director Spike Jonze on how to
play his character. In other words, Jonze was telling Malkovich how
to play Malkovich.
 &HT;    ``How can you really argue?'' Malkovich says, smiling. ``If
someone says, `You wouldn't do it that way,' what do you do? I'd
say, `OK, how do you think I'd do it?' He'd say, `Well, I think
you'd do it like this ... '
 &HT;    ``I didn't write it,'' he adds with a chuckle. ``I had nothing
to do with it. I just played it.''
 &HT;    Malkovich earned his status as at least a cult icon in going on
three decades of work on television, film and the stage. The
45-year-old Illinois native first made his mark in 1976 as a
founder of the Chicago-based Steppenwolf Theatre Company, with
which he participated in dozens of shows as producer, director
and/or actor. He later scored a hit in New York with Sam Shepard's
``True West'' (1982), which won him an Obie Award. His Broadway
debut in ``Death of a Salesman'' (1984) was followed by ``Burn
This'' (1987), both of which earned glowing reviews.
 &HT;    On television, Malkovich won an Emmy for ``Death of a Salesman''
(1985) and also appeared in ``Heart of Darkness'' (1994). His
latest small-screen project, ``RKO 281,'' will debut Nov. 20 on
HBO. The behind-the-scenes saga of the troubled production of the
classic film ``Citizen Kane'' (1941), it casts Malkovich as
screenwriter Herman Mankiewicz.
 &HT;    Moviegoers know the two-time Oscar nominee for ``Places in the
Heart'' (1984), ``Dangerous Liaisons'' (1988), ``In the Line of
Fire'' (1993) and ``Con Air'' (1998). One of the industry's busiest
actors, he has a full slate of upcoming projects which, besides
``Being John Malkovich,'' includes ``The Messenger: The Story of
Joan of Arc,'' due out on Nov. 12, and ``Burned to Light,'' with
Malkovich as F.W. Murnau, director of the classic horror film
``Nosferatu'' (1922).
 &HT;    The actor is currently in Canada, filming the mob drama
``Knockaround Guys.'' Early next year, he'll make his
feature-directing debut, after many successful stage productions,
with a drama entitled ``The Dancer Upstairs.''
 &HT;    Clearly Malkovich likes to work, and he takes that work very
seriously.
 &HT;    ``I'm personally happiest when I'm working on a script with a
writer,'' he says. ``After that, I'm happiest when I'm directing a
play.
 &HT;    ``I love acting on the stage,'' Malkovich adds, ``but I'm old
and it's tiring. It's great when you're 25, but I don't have that
energy anymore. That's probably why I do so many films.''
 &HT;    He pauses.
 &HT;    ``And, despite how much certain people want me to be, I'm not
really very unhappy with myself,'' he says. ``Nor am I particularly
happy with myself.''
 &HT;    Malkovich squints.
 &HT;    ``I'm just pretty OK being who I am and what I am,'' he says.
``I'm used to being me.''
 c.1999 Ian Spelling  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Ian Spelling is a New York-based free-lance writer.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: For further information on ``Being John Malkovich,''
consult the official Website at www.beingjohnmalkovich.com. And
don't forget to visit The New York Times Syndicate Website at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for information on StarBeat and
other features. &QL; 
