<BODY>
 AM-NYT-BUDGET  
(gm) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; FOR TUESDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Tuesday, Oct. 19
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   PAKISTAN-ASSESS (New Delhi, India) _ News Analysis: Pakistan's
new military ruler, Gen. Pervaiz Musharraf, is talking about
reform, but previous military dictatorships have left the country
and its democratic institutions in worse shape than ever. Can
Musharraf deliver on his promises? By Celia W. Dugger.
</P>
<P>
   INDONESIA-POLITICS (Jakarta) _ Two days before the presidential
selection by the National Assembly, no one seems to know what is
going to happen. By Seth Mydans.
</P>
<P>
   ALBRIGHT-AFRICA (Freetown) _ Secretary of State Albright visits
Sierra Leone at the start of an African trip. By Norimitsu Onishi.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (``w'' code)
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS-RDP (Washington) _ A roundup: The Supreme Court rules
there is no such thing as a crime scene exception to the
requirement for a search warrant; a lower court had said that some
incriminating evidence found at the scene was admissible because it
was taken at the crime scene. But it wasn't evidence in plain view;
it was sealed in an envelope inside a briefcase. For that, the
court said, a warrant was needed. The high court also took a case
involving railroad liability for gate crossings. By Linda
Greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   SPEND-CONGRESS (Washington) _ Developments: possible Clinton
vetoes; Hill leaders meet with the president, other action. By
David E. Rosenbaum.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POLITICS &LR;  (``p'' code)
</P>
<P>
   MCCAIN-MOLINARI (Undated) _ Sen. John McCain gets the
endorsement of Rep. Susan Molinari of New York. By David M.
Herszenhorn.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL GENERAL &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   DENVER-SHOOTING (Denver) _ Accused Columbine High School killer
Dylan Klebold's parents have notified the local sheriff and two
local officials that they may sue, according to published reports.
The legal document filed by Tom and Sue Klebold, is more popularly
known as a ``notice of intent to sue.'' Under Colorado law, state
and local government officials and entities cannot be sued unless
they are notified first. The Klebold family says school should have
recognized troubling signs in Eric Harris, the other student
involved in the killings last April in Littleton, Colo. By Michael
Janofsky.
</P>
<P>
   KISSINGER-TEACH (New York) _ Henry Kissinger, as a teacher for
the day, returns to the Washington Heights public school he
attended as a young refugee from Nazi Germany. Oprah Winfrey
teaches a class too. By Jodi Wilgoren.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-BARTER (Undated) _ Since the first cave man exchanged
his favorite club for a neighbor's animal pelt, barter has been an
accepted form of commerce. Now some Internet companies have turned
themselves into virtual trading posts, making barter a way of life.
Such exchanges have become so common that they may in fact be
skewing the financial picture for the Internet industry. Because
these new companies rarely have profits, revenues are often the key
determination of their value. Strong revenue growth, therefore, can
translate into higher stock prices. By Edward Wyatt.
</P>
<P>
   NISSAN-CUTBACK (Tokyo) _ Nissan Motor says it will close three
assembly plants and cut its work force by 21,000 jobs, or 14
percent, in the next three years, in the most sweeping
restructuring ever attempted in Japan. By Stephanie Strom.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   BANKS-EARNINGS (New York) _ Citigroup says third-quarter
earnings more than tripled. Also reporting much
stronger-than-expected results are BankAmerica, J.P. Morgan and
Bank of New York. By Patrick McGeehan.
</P>
<P>
   STOCKS-MARKETPLACE (New York) _ Twelve years ago, the stock
market crashed in the largest one-day fall ever. Now, by some
measures, the stock market is even more volatile than it was then.
Volatility can sharply increase, as it did in 1980, when a leading
sector _ then, energy stocks _ has risen to unsupportable
valuations. It is possible that the current surge in volatility is
foretelling a similar turn in this era's dominant sector,
technology. Not all increases in volatility, however, tell such
stories. New ways of trading, brought on by technology and
financial engineering, can roil the markets until other traders
become used to the impacts generated by such trading. That was true
of institutional block trading in the 1970s and computerized index
arbitrage in the 1980s. And it may be true now of Internet-based
day trading. By Floyd Norris.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ Stocks are mixed in mid-afternoon trading.
At 2:05 p.m., the Dow Jones industrial average was up 39 points,
the S&AMP;P 500 down 4 points and the Nasdaq composite down 71 points.
The 30-year Treasury bond yield was at 6.30 percent. European
markets were lower: London was down 0.79 percent and Frankfurt down
0.60 percent. Tokyo's Nikkei index closed down 1.85 percent. The
Hong Kong market was closed for a holiday, Chung Yeung Festival. By
Kenneth N. Gilpin.
</P>
<P>
   FORD-EARNINGS (Dearborn, Mich.) _ Ford Motor reports an 11
percent rise in third-quarter earnings, higher than the consensus
forecast. North American truck sales and cost reductions helped it
overcome losses in South America and Europe. By Keith Bradsher.
</P>
<P>
   DRUGS-EARNINGS (Undated) _ Looking at third-quarter earnings for
pharmaceutical companies, as the most profitable, Warner-Lambert
reports a 38 percent gain. American Home Products posts results at
the high of end of forecasts. By David J. Morrow.
</P>
<P>
   XEROX-EARNINGS (Undated) _ Xerox reports an 11 percent decline
in third-quarter earnings, in line with sharply reduced
expectations. By Claudia H. Deutsch.
</P>
<P>
   BRITISH-AEROSPACE (London) _ Looking at British Aerospace's
options in the wake of the merger between Dasa and Aerospatiale.
Also, Marconi, which British Aerospace acquired, is joining a
satellite consortium with Dasa and Aerospatiale. By Alan Cowell.
</P>
<P>
   FRANCE-TELEKOM (Frankfurt) _ France Telekom establishes a
beachhead in the home market of its former ally and now bitter
rival Deutsche Telekom, buying the cellular telephone venture of
RWE and Veba for $8 billion. By Edmund L. Andrews.
</P>
