<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-18 14:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0584 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r f BC-EBAY-HNS &LR;      10-18 1021
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EBAY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON-LINE AUCTIONS TURN YARD SALES INTO SUCCESS STORIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARIANNE COSTANTINOU  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ It's a worldwide flea market filled with
millions of buyers, sellers and stuff you never knew you needed or
even imagined existed. You name it, covet it, disdain it, don't
know what to call it _ it's on eBay, the grandaddy and titan of
on-line auction houses.
</P>
<P>
   For the obsessed, it is changing the way people buy, sell and
plan their daily lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's given me a whole new life,'' said Penny Walden, 54, of
Seattle, who is about to quit her job as a cancer researcher so she
can sell antiques full time. Her business partner, Sarah Peyton,
35, already has stopped working as a Russian interpreter to handle
the bookkeeping and research end of the business. They say they
have made $100,000 in nine months, and Peyton can stay home with
her infant daughter.
</P>
<P>
   Their antiques store: eBay.
</P>
<P>
   This success story is not unique.
</P>
<P>
   Pick any 20 eBay users at random from across the United States
and Canada, and they are almost giddy talking about their
experiences. Not that eBay is without controversy. Items for sale
have included babies, a human kidney, racist memorabilia and 500
pounds of Dutch marijuana.
</P>
<P>
   There have been scams, like the woman in Hesperia, Calif., who
was arrested for fraud after hawking rare Barbies she did not own.
And few buyers have been spared the inevitable disappointment of
receiving merchandise not as mint or authentic as described.
</P>
<P>
   Yet many buyers and sellers view eBay with evangelical fervor.
They cannot believe the number of customers they're reaching, the
money they are making, the treasures they have found and how it has
changed their lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of mom and pops who used to answer my ads or put stuff
out on garage sales are now becoming computer literate,'' said Jim
Gambino, 37, of Belle Meade, N.J., a laser copier repairman who
collects Beatles memorabilia. ``Instead of putting that Beatles
`Flip Your Wig' game at a garage sale for $20, they're putting it
on eBay and getting $100.''
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone is a true believer. At the September sale at the
Harvey Clars auction house in Oakland, buyers and sellers swore
that a virtual auction can't begin to compare with the fun of
rummaging through store racks or the thrill of a live auction with
its ``Going! Going! ... Gone!''
</P>
<P>
   There also is the advantage of seeing the item in real life.
``People still want to see, feel, sit in the real thing,'' said
David Van Derlin, 47, manager of Empire Furniture in Eureka.
</P>
<P>
   As a dealer, though, he senses he cannot avoid on-line auctions
forever. Even with the biggest antiques store in Humboldt County,
in Northern California, there is still the allure of a worldwide
market.
</P>
<P>
   People do not need a huge inventory to sell stuff on eBay. There
is no need for a store, a license or training. With on-line
auctions, a lot of the old rules of doing business are gone.
Suddenly, people with little or no retail experience are becoming
instant entrepreneurs.
</P>
<P>
   In the old days _ circa 1995, before eBay went on line _ there
were many ways to hawk stuff. Garage sales. Classified ads. Flea
markets. Resale stores.
</P>
<P>
   With on-line auctions, you are the dealer, and you have many
more potential customers than the people likely to stop by your
garage sale or the dealers listed in the Yellow Pages.
</P>
<P>
   What is more, you do not end up selling it for the first price
someone's willing to give you. There is no face-to-face haggling.
</P>
<P>
   The market, not sweet-talk or hardball tactics, decides the
price. The virtual marketplace can turn a hankering for
collectibles and cash into a thriving business, as more and more
people are discovering.
</P>
<P>
   Even shopkeepers see eBay as a bonanza.
</P>
<P>
   Like many owners of antiques and specialty shops, Jim Thomason,
59, of A Toy Train Depot in Oakland, had things around for years
that he couldn't sell. Most customers were regulars who had already
seen his treasures.
</P>
<P>
   In June, he decided to try eBay. He sold 45 item, each one for
more than twice the price he had hoped. To reach those customers,
he paid only the 25 cents to $2 that eBay charges to list an item
for sale, plus the 1.25 percent to 5 percent commission.
</P>
<P>
   What is more, Thomason said he had an average of 6 1/2 bids on
each item, 200 different bidders in all.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can you imagine how long it's been since I had 200 different
bidders? And that was in just one week,'' he said. ``What eBay does
is give incredible leverage to a small shopkeeper or individual.''
</P>
<P>
   Most customers at Sanderson's Antiques in West Monroe, La., are
either Texas dealers or the occasional tourist. With so little foot
traffic, Lynette and Michael Sanderson kept prices low just to make
sales.
</P>
<P>
   Not anymore. With eBay, they are close to tripling their income
in less than a year, said Lynette Sanderson, 26.
</P>
<P>
   Recently the Sandersons sold a mahogany dining room set on eBay
for $15,100. If the set had been in their store, it would have gone
unsold for months, she said.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, a tabulator on their page showed that 1,490 people
had eyeballed the furniture.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't get that much traffic in our store in a year,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Foot traffic at auctions has skyrocketed in recent months. At
eBay alone, the number of registered users almost tripled the first
six months of this year, from 2.1 million in January to 5.8 million
at the end of June, according to Kevin Pursglove, the San Jose
company's spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Although several Internet giants _ like Amazon.com and Yahoo _
host auctions, and Microsoft and some partners are about to join
the fray, none comes close to eBay in size and scope.
</P>
<P>
   According to eBay's home page, some 3 million items are up for
bid in more than 2,000 categories at any given second.
</P>
<P>
   From the inception of eBay four years ago, some 60 million items
have sold, Pursglove said. Each day, sales worth $6.8 million take
place. The company claims that only 0.30 percent of the sales have
involved fraud.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
