<P>
   POLITICS
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-COLOMBIA _ AUSTIN, Texas _ Without leaving home _ save for
a trip to Israel _ Gov. George W. Bush has seen the world and many
of its leaders. On Tuesday, Colombia President Andres Pastrana
drops by the mansion to meet the man who might be president. A look
at the world leaders with whom Bush has met. (Herman, Austin
American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-BUDGET- WASHINGTON _ President Clinton vetoed the
foreign aid spending bill Monday, setting the stage for a
contentious end game with Congress over this year's federal budget.
(Cox News Servi
</P>
<P>
   MORALS _ WASHINGTON _ Modern studies have shown that damage to
the prefrontal cortex area of the brain can produce servere
impairments in social and moral decision-making in adults. Now,
scientists at the University of Iowa College of Medicine have found
evidence of even more profound ``moral damage'' in persons whose
brains were damaged in the prefrontal cortex as small children.
Persons injured as small children appear to have never been able
even to fully learn moral and social knowledge. (Nesmith, Cox News
Service)
</P>
<P>
   TAXBREAKS-HEALTHCARE _ The popular political strategy of using
tax breaks to help reduce the number of 44.3 million Americans
without health insurance could backfire if the breaks are not
significant, according to a National Coalition on Health Care
report released Monday. (Dayton Daily News)
</P>
<P>
   TEACHER-TEST _ WASHINGTON _ A new tougher version of the PRAXIS
test, which many states require for obtaining a teacher license, is
unveiled Monday by the Educational Testing Service and endorsed by
the NCATE, the accrediting body for schools of education. The new
test will force almost every education school to make big changes
in the way it trains future teachers. (Mollison, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   FLEE-BAILEY _ ORLANDO, Fla. _ Famous attorney F.Lee Bailey faced
the music at a 9 a.m. hearing on how he handled money for a client.
Last time, he delayed the hearing because his wife was sick. She
has since passed away, he is now a widower and in dire financial
straits. (Staletovich, Palm Beach Post).
</P>
<P>
   SCIENCE/MEDICINE
</P>
<P>
   SYPHILIS-ROCKDALE _ CONYERS, Ga. _ Before this year's Heritage
High shooting, an earlier scandal shook Rockdale County _ the
diagnosis of a cluster of syphilis cases among affluent teens less
than 18 years old. In 1996, as Atlanta was preparing for the
Olympics, 17 teens tested positive for syphilis, more than 200 were
treated, and about 50 acknowledged being part of a ring of kids who
would meet for group sex at each other's houses while parents were
not around. Tonight (Tuesday) a PBS Frontline documentary, ``The
Lost Children of Rockdale County,'' tells the story of the outbreak
and talks to many teens and some parents; it ultimately traces both
the outbreak and the school shooting to teen alienation, peer
pressure and lack of parental involvement. (McKenna, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   w/SYPHILIS-FRONTLINE _ Review of Frontline's ``Lost Children of
Rockdale County.'' (Jubera, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   SYPHILIS-PARENTS _ Sex. Drugs. Condoms. Alienation. All topics
that can send parents running for cover. As PBS prepares to air a
Frontline documentary that explores these topics by profiling a
Rockdale teen syphilis outbreak promoted by group-sex parties, we
offer some advice on opening a dialogue with teens about such tough
subjects. QA with Sarah Brown, director of the National Coalition
of Teenage Pregnancy Prevention, and a boxed list of resources,
advocacy groups, contacts, books and websites. (Lore, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   SYPHILIS-RESIDENTS _ CONYERS, Ga. _ Residents are bracing for
what many expect to be a harsh national spotlight on the community,
with tonight's airing of ``The Lost Children of Rockdale.'' The
program has been the buzz of Rockdale for weeks among community
leaders, teachers, parents and teens. A community forum is set to
discuss the segment Oct. 26 at the local library. (Stafford,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   AIDS-KING _ ATLANTA _ Coretta Scott King will make her first
statement about the AIDS epidemic in the African-American community
on Monday, helping to launch a national AIDS memorial quilt tour
and prevention effort on the campuses of historically black
colleges and universities. (Kim, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
