<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCIENCE-TIMES-BUDGET-NYT </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service plans the following  &UR; Science
Times &LR;  stories for papers of Tuesday, Oct. 19:
</P>
<P>
   SCI-CATHEDRAL-ASTRONOMY (Undated) _ While the Roman Catholic
Church condemned Galileo, new research shows that centuries of
oversimplifications have concealed how hard Rome worked to amass
astronomical tools, measurements, tests and lore. In its scientific
zeal, the Church adapted cathedrals across Europe, and a tower at
the Vatican itself, so their darkened vaults could serve as solar
observatories. Beams of sunlight that fell past religious art and
marble columns not only inspired the faithful but provided
astronomers with information about the Sun, the Earth and their
celestial relationships. By William J. Broad. (1800 words)
</P>
<P>
   With photos and graphic.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-ASTHMA (Undated) _ For most people with asthma, the proper
use of medication, education and self-management can go a long way
to keeping them out of the emergency room functioning at home,
school or work, experts say. But sadly, many patients with the
diseases fail to adhere to the regimen and many others simply do
not understand it. By Denise Grady. (1950 words)
</P>
<P>
   With photo and graphic.
</P>
<P>
   With
</P>
<P>
   SCI-ASTHMA-TREAT (Undated) _ A rundown of the various medicines
available in the treatment of asthma. By Denise Grady. (600 words)
</P>
<P>
   And
</P>
<P>
   SCI-ASTHMA-RESEARCH (Undated) _ Despite the seemingly endless
rise in asthma cases, new treatments for the disease have been
noticeably slow in coming. Within the past two years, for example,
three new drugs have been released to treat migraines, with another
due in the spring. But for asthma, which accounts for more
pediatric hospitalizations each year than any other illness, only
two significant drugs were approved in the same time period,
Accolate by Astra-Zeneca and Singulair from Merck. By David J.
Morrow. (1200 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-BLACK-HOLES (Undated) _ A new calculation suggests that
dense star clusters, which are sprinkled throughout galaxies in
Earth's cosmic neighborhood, act as assembly lines for tightly
orbiting pairs of black holes and then spit them out of the
cluster. There, they eventually fall together and merge into one.
Next year, if all goes well, scientists will be able to take the
first steps toward testing that theory with a new $350 million
instrument called a gravity wave observatory. By James Glanz. (1200
words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-MAMMARIES (Undated) _ According to the commonly accepted
``one-half rule,'' the average number of young in a litter is one
half the typical number of mammaries and the maximum litter size is
equal to the total number of mammaries. But studies of naked mole
rats defy that rule, in part, scientists suspect, because of the
docile behavior of the offspring and the protected environment in
which mole rats raise their young. By Carol Kaesuk Yoon. (1250
words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-LEOPOLD-CONSERVATION (New York) _ In the field of
conservation, Aldo Leopold is a titan. His ``Sand County Almanac''
is a bible of the environmental movement every bit as much as
Rachel Carson's ``Silent Spring.'' In Washington, where national
conservation policy has been going through major changes of
philosophy in recent years, his name and ideas are everyday
currency. So it is that in this 50th anniversary year of the book,
which has sold more than 1.5 million copies and is still going
strong, Leopold's ideas are being scrutinized afresh. A recent
conference was convened here by the Wisconsin Academy of Sciences,
Arts and Letters to examine his legacy and its relevance for the
future. By William K. Stevens.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-WATCH (Undated) _ News and notes on science: Items on
plastics made from plants, pheromones in frogs and a spider's sun
compass. By Henry Fountain.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-BRODY-HEALTH (Undated) _ Since the mid-1980s, the yearly
total of Americans given diagnoses of brain tumors has doubled, and
it is expected to exceed 100,000 this year. More than half the
increase has occurred in people over 65. Survival rates, too, have
been inching upward, thanks to improved diagnostic techniques and
more precise and inventive methods of treatment, like stereotactic
radiosurgery (a pinpoint form of radiation) and laser surgery with
a gamma knife. Further progress is expected to result from some
still experimental treatments, including immunotherapy, gene
therapy and wafers of chemotherapeutic agents implanted in the
tumor site. By Jane E. Brody. (1275 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-AIDS-MORNING-AFTER (Undated) _ Frustrated by the continued
spread of HIV, a growing number of AIDS doctors are trying out a
kind of morning-after treatment: an experimental application of
drugs meant to abort infection in a person who was recently exposed
to the virus through unsafe sex. By David France. (1340 words)
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-IRONMAN (Undated) _ How grownups with real jobs make the
time to train for physical endurance tests like the Ironman World
Championships in Hawaii. By Jill Agostino. (1100 words)
</P>
<P>
   With photos.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-VITAL-SIGNS (Undated) _ News and notes on health and
fitness:
</P>
<P>
   _ Zapping a heart back into normal rhythm is so simple a group
of sixth graders can learn how to do it in about a minute, new
research proves. (255 words)
</P>
<P>
   _ Yale researchers have developed a new blood test to help
detect ehrlichiosis, a disease carried by deer ticks that often
goes undiagnosed because it lacks a telltale sign like the
bull's-eye rash of Lyme disease. (355 words)
</P>
<P>
   _ Cigarettes do help smokers relax _ from tension caused by
smoking, a new study argues. The study, published in this month's
issue of American Psychologist, reviewed research into one of
tobacco's central paradoxes: smokers universally say that lighting
up gives a sense of relief and well-being, but as a group, they
hardly seem all that relaxed. (235 words)
</P>
<P>
   _ Heart attack victims who are generally hostile people tend to
be younger, heavier and unhappier than most coronary patients _ and
to get more benefit from a cardiac rehabilitation program, a study
conducted in New Orleans has found. (300 words)
</P>
<P>
   _ The 300,000 Americans who may have been exposed to the
hepatitis C virus through tainted blood transfusions before 1992
can take an Internet quiz this week to gauge their risk and order a
free home test kit. (300 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-BREAST-CANCER (Undated) _ Optimism and a fighting attitude
may help breast cancer patients cope with their illness, but
positive thinking is unlikely to increase the chances of survival,
according to a study by British researchers. At the same time,
persistent hopelessness may lower a woman's chances of survival. By
Erica Goode. (530 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-Q&AMP;A (Undated) _ A science question answered: How and why
does a chameleon change its colors? (300 words)
</P>
