<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-18 14:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0601 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-FINANCE-HOOKER-BOS &LR;      10-18 1114
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FINANCE-HOOKER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GETTING MOST FOR RETIREMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KENNETH HOOKER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. I am 52 and single and make $62,500 a year. I am vested in a
401(k) plan with a value of $52,000, of which 25 percent is in a
guaranteed interest account, 25 percent is in a stock-oriented
balanced fund, 25 percent in a Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 Index fund,
and the rest in a mid-cap blend stock fund. I contribute 9 percent
of my salary to the 401(k). I also have a $133,000 IRA with $68,000
invested in common stocks, $14,000 in international mutual funds,
and the rest in small-cap mutual funds. I also have a $39,000 stock
account to which I contribute $500 a month. I hope that this
account will allow me to pay off my mortgage early, which has a
balance of $177,000. I have $40,000 in another common stock
account. And I own two condos, with combined market values of
$140,000 and combined mortgages of $69,000. These will be paid off
in 10 years, at which time they will provide about $1,000 a month
income. I would like to retire at age 62. I see that I am heavily
invested in stocks and need to make changes. What do you suggest I
do to be able to retire in 10 years with an income of $4,000 a
month?
</P>
<P>
   I.D., San Diego &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. If you realize an average 10 percent growth from your 401(k),
your IRA, and the stock account that is not earmarked to deal with
your mortgage, you would accumulate $677,347 over the next 10
years, presuming continued contributions at the current level.
</P>
<P>
   In retirement you would need about $555,000 in a fixed-income
account to bring you the $3,000 monthly income that, combined with
your expected rental income, would give you the money you require.
And you would have about $122,000 that you could leave in stocks,
with this account calculated to protect you against inflation.
</P>
<P>
   This isn't as much as I'd like to see in that last account, but
there are two other factors that should work in your favor.
</P>
<P>
   First is the possibility you will be eligible for Social
Security, which would mean you would have to put considerably less
in the fixed-income account.
</P>
<P>
   Second is the account that you have earmarked to pay off the
mortgage on your primary residence. I presume you are calculating
this stock portfolio should bring you returns in excess of the
mortgage interest rate, and the deductibility of the mortgage
interest provides an extra fillip.
</P>
<P>
   With your $500 monthly contributions and presumed 10 percent
annual portfolio growth, this account would reach $201,162 in a
decade. By that time, of course, 10 years of amortization through
your regular mortgage payments would have taken the balance well
below the current level, so you would be in a position to pay it
off with a tidy bit left over. You could then add this to the stock
accounts.
</P>
<P>
   My guess is that you now have about 10 percent on the
fixed-income side of the portfolio that is apart from the account
you have earmarked to pay off the mortgage.
</P>
<P>
   I agree that a little more on the fixed-income side would be a
good idea. You might first go through the common stock portfolio in
the IRA, looking for issues with the weakest prospects, and then go
through the taxable account to determine if selling some of these
shares would not have ugly tax consequences.
</P>
<P>
   I suggest that at this point you divert about $25,000 to the
fixed-income side. But I also would look at the menu of options for
your 401(k) to determine if there is an intermediate-term bond fund
that is likely to outproduce the guaranteed interest account.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, to slowly build the fixed-income side of the retirement
portfolio, I suggest you allocate 50 percent of your ongoing
contributions there.
</P>
<P>
   Q. We started a serious plan for retirement much later than we
should have. At present, my wife and I both have IRAs invested in
the same funds _ United Income and United Science and Technology.
We also have taxable holdings in United Accumulative, United New
Concepts, and in the same two funds we hold in our IRAs. All of
these accounts combined amount to $80,000, and we are adding to
them at a rate of $1,233 per month. The funds have been doing
fairly well, but what troubles us is the 5 3/4 percent upfront fee
we pay every month as we make our payments. In our research, the
Vanguard funds seem to be some of the best in both performance and
the amount of fees charged. We recently opened a money market
account there, but are confused as to which way to go. We are in
our late 50s and have an adequate amount in real estate
investments, but still want to do better at getting diversified
investments before retiring in about five years.
</P>
<P>
   M.W., Seaside, Ore. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Although the United Science and Technology Class A shares
carry a 5 3/4 percent upfront charge, as you cite, the fund has an
overall expense ratio of 1.05, according to the latest figures from
Morningstar Mutual Funds.
</P>
<P>
   That figure is about 70 basis points lower than the typical
expense ratio among its peer funds, so the long-term investor will
eventually find that the upfront charge is a bargain.
</P>
<P>
   More critical is the question of total returns and risk, and in
those categories United Science and Technology is a winner.
Moreover, if you went to Vanguard, you couldn't find a similar
investment. The United fund focuses its portfolio on both health
care and technology issues.
</P>
<P>
   The closest you could come at Vanguard is its excellent Health
Care fund, but that is closed to new investors, and wouldn't
provide you with the technology exposure. So in this case the nod
would go to the United fund.
</P>
<P>
   You could make just as powerful an argument on the other side of
the issue by comparing United Income fund with similar Vanguard
issues. Currently United Income invests in a portfolio of
value-oriented large-cap stocks, favoring those with established
payout records. It has a five-year record of 19.54 percent average
annual growth, a 0.89 percent expense ratio, and an average rating
from Morningstar.
</P>
<P>
   At Vanguard, Vanguard Index Value has a similar portfolio focus,
a five-year record of 20.03 percent, an expense ratio of 0.22, and
an above-average rating from Morningstar.
</P>
<P>
   Vanguard is the logical choice for the parts of a portfolio that
focus on fixed-income holdings, index offerings, and the kind of
plain-vanilla offerings typified by its Asset Allocation and Growth
and Income funds. But beyond that, you need to analyze the options
fairly carefully.
</P>
<P>
   (Send letters, including your name, address and telephone
number, to: Kenneth Hooker, The Boston Globe, Boston, Mass.
02107-2378.)
</P>
</TEXT>
