<HEADER>
A0605 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-GOLAN-HOUSING-BOS &LR;      10-18 1191
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOLAN-HOUSING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN GOLAN HEIGHTS, BETTING ON A US PAYOFF 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES M. SENNOTT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   KATZRIN, Israel _ The Golan Heights would seem an unlikely place
for real estate speculation.
</P>
<P>
   After all, Prime Minister Ehud Barak is hinting in talks with
Syria that in return for peace Israel might give back the beautiful
and strategic hills and lush vineyards of the Golan that Israel
captured in 1967.
</P>
<P>
   So how to explain that developer Motti Cohen is going ahead with
a 52-lot project in the Golan and sold 12 houses in the last two
weeks? And that hundreds more people have come out to visit the
site and seem interested.
</P>
<P>
   It's a no-brainer, says Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   ``They think it's a good investment. If Israel keeps the Golan,
they get a good deal,'' says Cohen, who is among a half-dozen
developers now building in the Golan. ``If Israel gives back the
Golan, the government will get the United States to compensate the
owners. They feel they can't go wrong on this.''
</P>
<P>
   So widespread is the presumption that the United States will
pick up the bill to compensate losses to Israeli farmers,
winemakers, and homeowners on the Golan that opponents of a
giveback are hoping to use the staggering price tag _ some
estimates put it as high as $10 billion _ to dissuade the United
States from backing a Golan deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is an acceptance here, an unspoken belief, that Uncle
Sam will foot the bill for this,'' says Avi Zeira, chairman of the
Golan Residents Committee. A tough, native-born Israeli, he is
girding for battle in order to save the Golan, in part by trying to
raise awareness in the US Congress of the costs of a possible peace
deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you think Americans realize just how much they could be
paying for the anxiousness of Barak and (President) Clinton to
reach a deal? Well, we are going to try to make sure they do
know,'' he added. It's not only insane for Israel in terms of its
security, it's insane for American taxpayers to pay for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Zeira's calculation of the cost is based on a recent study by
Yoash Tzidon, a retired Israeli Air Force colonel and respected
analyst for the Tel Aviv-based Ariel Center for Policy Research.
Tzidon puts the cost at roughly $10 billion for compensation
packages to cover Israeli agriculture, wineries, water bottling
plants, and the relocation of roughly 17,000 Israeli residents of
the Golan. As much as $20 billion more would be needed, Tzidon
figures, for the Israeli military to put a standing army along the
border and establish antimissile defense systems.
</P>
<P>
   Zeira's Golan settler group now finds itself in the unique
position of arguing against aid to Israel to a US Congress that
historically has been more than ready to channel foreign aid to
Israel. Currently, Israel receives one-third of the total US
foreign aid package.
</P>
<P>
   The status of the Golan Heights has shifted drastically since
Barak's election. Under former Israeli prime minister Benjamin
Netanyahu, talks with Syria had hopelessly collapsed.
</P>
<P>
   Barak's more liberal Labor Party is trying to get the ball
rolling again, but for now Syrian president Hafez al-Assad is
publicly showing no willingness to reopen negotiations. He is
insisting that Israel commit to giving back all of the Golan, to
the border as it existed on June 4, 1967, as a precondition for
talks. That would mean Syria would control the northern bank of the
Sea of Galilee and other valuable water sources now under Israeli
control. Israelis insist if there is any relevant historical
precedent, it is the border established in 1923, which would leave
all of the Galilee and substantial high ground in the Golan in
Israeli hands.
</P>
<P>
   But some analysts see Syria's retrenching as last-minute
posturing that could come before a breakthrough.
</P>
<P>
   The Israeli left generally accepts a giveback of the Golan as
the only way to achieve peace with Syria and end the conflict in
neighboring Lebanon, in which Syria plays a key role. Syria has
some 30,000 troops in Lebanon and buttresses the Lebanese army,
while Hezbollah guerrilla fighters continue to try to force Israel
out of the 9-mile wide ``security zone'' it occupies in southern
Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   Zeira, of the Golan Residents Committee, says the reason Barak
and the left can be cavalier about giving up the Golan is because
they know in the end that they will not be the ones paying the
price. The belief that residents of the Golan would be reimbursed
with American cash if they were forced to move runs deep. It is
based, some observers say, on the historic 1979 peace agreement
with Egypt, under which Israeli residents of the Sinai Peninsula
who were forced to leave received compensation packages funded by
US aid.
</P>
<P>
   US diplomatic sources here say they are keenly aware of the
widespread belief in Israel that America would foot the bill in the
Golan, too. Barak discussed the funding of a possible peace deal
with Syria in his meetings with Clinton last month, sources said.
The US position has been that if a deal is cut, the cost should be
shared with other European countries and Japan, and not fall solely
on the US.
</P>
<P>
   In a sign of new reluctance to blindly fund Middle East peace
agreements, meanwhile, the US Congress is withholding the first
payment of a promised $1.2 billion to be paid to Israel and the
$400 million to Palestinians for signing the interim Wye agreement
one year ago. The money is expected to go through, but the delay,
observers say, is intended as a message.
</P>
<P>
   As Moshe Zak, an Israeli commentator for the Jerusalem Post,
recently pointed out, ``This delay in receiving vital American aid
forces us to reconsider certain axioms that have taken root in the
Israeli establishment: that the US will bear the financial expenses
of peace.''
</P>
<P>
   Larry Schwartz, press attache to US Ambassador Edward S. Walker
Jr., said, ``The United States will undoubtedly play a role in
helping to implement whatever agreement is made. However, the
discussion is premature about any aid that would be part of that.
They haven't even begun the negotiations yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Many Golan residents are indignant about the land speculation by
other Israelis, most of whom they say are not from the Golan. And
there are many Israelis, including Zak and Tzidon, who feel that
there is no price that can make up for the strategic security that
Israel gains by holding onto the high ground along the northern
border with Syria.
</P>
<P>
   In the lush vineyards where the Yarden Winery makes Israel's
most prized wines, the sentiment against giving up the Golan is
strong. Executives of the company, one of the most successful
businesses in Israel, are fiercely proud of the wine they have
produced since the early 1970s and are insulted at the thought that
anyone would try to buy them out. The winery is continuing to
produce its wine and plant new vineyards with the faith that Israel
will not give up the Golan.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want peace, but we want a good peace,'' said Adam
Montefiore, a senior executive at Yarden. ``But if peace means
ripping up vineyards, what kind of peace is that?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
