<SLUG> BC-CHINA-RUSSIA-SCHOLARS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO EXPERTS GAZE INTO THE CRYSTAL BALL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   They are a dynamic duo, no matter how you look at it. Merle and
Marshall Goldman are considered among the leading scholars in their
respective fields. She has China, he has Russia. They also know a
bit about the other's country, and are not shy about expressing it
_ or about disagreeing.
</P>
<P>
   Merle, 68, is a professor of Chinese history at Boston
University and a member of the executive committee of the Fairbanks
Center at Harvard, while Marshall, 69, is a professor of Russian
economics at Wellesley College and associate director of the Davis
Center for Russian Studies at Harvard University. Both have offices
(one floor apart) at Harvard's Coolidge Hall. For 40 years, they
have traveled to Russia, and for 20 years to China, often together,
most recently this past summer.
</P>
<P>
   So what insights can they offer into the future of Russia and
China? What is happening with the countries' relations with the
United States? What about the Russia-China relationship? John
Donnelly, the Globe's diplomatic corresponent, recently posed those
questions, and others, to the Goldmans.
</P>
<P>
   Q. What are the chances of Russia, China and even India forming
a closer alliance to counter-balance the United States's position
as sole superpower?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Marshall Goldman:  &LR; Certainly Russia and China will get closer
together. But I don't see it as a long lasting thing . . . Their
interests are too different.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Merle Goldman:  &LR; The Russians truly fear the Chinese. They fear
if the Chinese come in large numbers they will take over that area
on the border. I see them coming closer together, but not too
close. There is a long legacy of conflict between Russia and China
and, perhaps more important, China can get much more from the
United States than it can from Russia. Russia is a market, but it's
not the kind of market that the Chinese have in the United States .
. .
</P>
<P>
   The Chinese are worried about the US as the only one great world
power and there is no countervailing power. But the prospect of
China and Russia and India joining together in some sort of
alliance against the United States is low.
</P>
<P>
   Marshall: With one exception. It depends on what the United
States does, because if we go and act as a hegemonic power, and we
try to intervene in, say, Pakistan or Tibet, that may provoke
something.
</P>
<P>
   Q: You visited both Beijing and Moscow during the Kosovo war.
What was the attitude toward the United States then?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Merle:  &LR; When we intervened in Kosovo, the Chinese looked at
this as a precedent that could happen in Tibet or Taiwan. They
really talked about that. The sense is no one is there to stop us
from intervening. If Russia had been stronger, as it had been
during the Cold War, the Chinese believe we wouldn't have done what
we did in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Marshall: The anger in Russia and China wasn't for show. In the
case of Russia, these were the Serbs, their little brothers, (that
the US was targeting.) The irony, of course, is that the Russians
in Chechnya are doing the same thing as we did in Kosovo. On
Russian TV the other day they showed the cross hairs and showed the
bomb going down. But that's on their territory. They still see the
US as being a big bully in other countries.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What's the longterm effect of the US role in Kosovo?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Merle:  &LR; I think it's limited.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Marshall:  &LR; I would say it's longer lasting. First there was
NATO expansion. Then, when Kosovo came, it added to the concerns
that the US could do what it wants.
</P>
<P>
   It's like a marriage: tensions build up, the next time you get
into a fight, there's not only the current issue but you bring up
things that have been accumulating.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Why does the United States often take a softer line toward
China than Russia, even when China issues threatening statements
over Taiwan?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Marshall:  &LR; Someone once said that American foreign policy now
has to deal with the declining empire on the one hand and the
rising superpower on the other. It's easier to know how to deal
with Russia, much more difficult to deal with the Chinese, who are
not only a rising political power, but a rising economic power.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Merle:  &LR; That's the major point: Russia was primarily a
military-industrial complex. China is a major economic power.
</P>
<P>
   Marshall: What happens in this process is large vested groups of
special interests in the US don't want to pull the chain on China.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Merle:  &LR; The Fortune 500 companies were just meeting in China,
and they are just bending over backward, really somewhat kind of
disgustingly, fawning over Chinese leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Marshall But it's not just the Fortune 500. It's the consumer.
You're going to take away these cheap Chinese products? You have a
very one-sided balance of trade. The Russians never had that.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Merle:  &LR; The point is, if not the Chinese goods, it's the Indian
goods.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Marshall:  &LR; It's going to take a long time for India to catch
up.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Merle:  &LR; Or the Indonesians. China is a very different kind of
rising power. You could have said that Japan in the '30s was
attempting to be both a military and economic power, not unlike
China today . . .
</P>
<P>
   One of the major differences between Japan in the '30s and China
today is that China's internal problems are huge, despite their
growing economy. Visualize a country with 1.3 billion people that
has to feed and clothe that many people. Something that haunts the
Chinese leadership is that this population might explode in some
kind of massive social protest. This has been part of Chinese
history from the beginning of time and it is a major concern for
this leadership.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Marshall:  &LR; There is an irony here. The Chinese are very much
focused on domestic stability and to do this they must continue to
have an expanding economy. To do this, however, they must be able
to find markets for their growing output and we are their best
customer. So we are the key player. Without American markets, the
Chinese would not have been able to develop their industry and
would not be able to continue to grow.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Merle:  &LR; They would have gone to Europe.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Marshall:  &LR; But the Europeans wouldn't let them in.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Merle:  &LR; I'm not even sure foreign trade is that important.
</P>
<P>
   Marshall: It's an outlet for their industry. In some sense, they
need us now more than we need them. But when it comes to a
showdown, it's very difficult for us to say to Boeing or anybody
else, we are going to let that market go.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How should the US address human rights concerns with China?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Merle:  &LR; If China continues with human rights abuses, there's
not much we can do but speak out at international forums. But China
is affected by that. They do care about their image in the outside
world. They want to be regarded as a mainstream power. They don't
want to be seen as a pariah power. I'm not saying it will stop the
abuses, but it might limit them.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Can the countries learn from one another now?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Merle:  &LR; In many ways, Gorbachev was advocating what the Chinese
are doing, that is reform through the existing system, with a
gradual process of economic change and political change. The
Chinese excuse for going slowly in political reform is that if they
go quickly like Russia did, they will have chaos, and that is what
everyone fears _ the dissidents as well as the leadership.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Marshall:  &LR; To some extent the Chinese are right because the
point is, once Gorbachev started messing around, it was very
difficult to restrain 70 years of pent-up demands and persuade the
public to move gradually.
</P>
<P>
   Q. What's ahead for both countries?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Merle:  &LR; In China, there is genuine social unrest now. In the
short run, there are going to be problems: their banks are close to
bankruptcy, the reforms in the countryside have petered out and
reform of state industries are slowing. But once they get through
this very difficult period, I expect the economy to continue to
grow. The hope is they will continue the gradual political reforms
they have started.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Marshall:  &LR; The hope for China resolving these problems will be
very much dependent on markets being open to them. What is
interesting in China is when there are problems people seem to
protest.
</P>
<P>
   In Russia, people seem to roll with the punches. How are the
Russians going to get rid of this legacy of corruption, theft and
dishonesty? The economy is beginning to show some growth, but where
will they go from here? There is a general feeling of rot that
pervades everything from Yeltsin down.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
