<HEADLINE>
SETTING OUT TO SELL ITALY ON A PIZZA CHAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTA MARIA DI LEUCA, Italy _ Here, at the southernmost tip of
Italy's heel, Paolo Micheli says, there is nowhere to go but up.
</P>
<P>
   Micheli's pizza parlor sits, appropriately enough, on a street
named for Christopher Columbus. Micheli has the same sense of
restlessness that drove the great Italian explorer to look beyond
the safe and the familiar.
</P>
<P>
   At 24, Micheli has already lived in a half-dozen countries,
including the United States. He left home for the first time at 15,
to work as a busboy at a restaurant on the island of Elba.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mama cried,'' he said. ``I cried, too, but I didn't let her
see.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, something always brings him home to this quaint harbor
village of 1,000, where everyone knows everything about everyone, a
fact that both appeals to and appalls Micheli.
</P>
<P>
   For Americans used to Pizza Hut, Bertucci's, Domino's and other
pizza chains, Micheli's franchising dreams may seem uninspired,
especially in the land that created the pizza pie.
</P>
<P>
   But here in southern Italy, there is no such thing as a pizza
chain. The winding roads of regions like Puglia are lined with
pizzerias, so many that it seems impossible that all of them could
stay open. But they are almost all mom-and-pop operations, the type
and quality of pizza depending on the proprietor.
</P>
<P>
   (at)j
</P>
<P>
   Having sampled fare at pizza chains in various American cities
and in London, Micheli was convinced that he could produce a good,
unprocessed pizza that could be made with such consistency that it
could be franchised.
</P>
<P>
   With his brother Salvatore, his sister Adriana, and her husband,
Michele, they approached local businessman Fabio Martinucci, owner
of the village's most popular bar. With Martinucci's backing, they
opened Gnam on the waterfront last year.
</P>
<P>
   Pronounced by Italians, Gnam sounds like ``Yum,'' which is a
common reaction of those who eat one of its pizzas. Micheli and his
partners found a machine that creates a thin, crisp pizza crust
with remarkable consistency. But changing attitudes here about the
desirability of chain food outlets is a bigger challenge than
creating the perfect pizza crust.
</P>
<P>
   Micheli realizes that there is something contradictory about his
wanting to create predictability about something as simple as pizza
in a culture that considers eating to be something more than
subsisting. But, he says, Italians are full of contradictions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes I get crazy here,'' he said, sitting at a table on
the sloping terrace overlooking the sleepy harbor. ``I don't
understand the mentality of people here. I'm not perfect. But
people will wait for two hours at the post office. When they get to
a table, they want things fast, but they expect it to be good,
too.''
</P>
<P>
   (at)j
</P>
<P>
   It is that contradictory expectation _ good food fast _ that
Micheli believes his pizza can satisfy. But finding the popular and
financial backing to translate his dream into a reality has proved
so far elusive.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's difficult to open another place. Banks don't give money
easily,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   While Micheli tends to look at things and ask why not, many
people here ask why anyone would want to create a franchise of
something as ubiquitous as pizzerias.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not about money,'' Micheli said. ``This is about an
idea. This is about translating what I know about growing up here,
in the south of Italy, and what I have seen, all over the world.''
</P>
<P>
   For all his ambition, Micheli is a patient man. He believes
expansion can only be slow, and can only begin locally. If it
doesn't work in southern Italy, it won't work in southern France,
South London, or the South Shore.
</P>
<P>
   For now, it's 18-hour days and waiting for a break. And for
Micheli, like other big thinkers, it means knowing that a break
might not come.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, who knows?'' said Micheli, jumping up to bus a table.
``Next year, maybe I'll be closed. Maybe next year I'll open
something different.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
