<HEADER>
A0612 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u l BC-GARDEN-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      10-18 1480
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLANT PANSIES IN COOL WEATHER 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By KATHY HUBER 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Q: When do I plant pansies?
</P>
<P>
   A: Eager for cool-season blooms, we sometimes rush and plant
pansies when it's really too warm for these annuals. Although more
varieties are now being touted as ``heat-tolerant,'' I try to avoid
putting them out until Halloween or later. But it can be difficult
to resist those colorful faces _ and the faceless varieties _ at
the nursery.
</P>
<P>
   We did have a brief spell of cooler weather, and many of us
popped pansies into summer-weary beds. Recently, temperatures have
again hovered at the 90-degree mark. I returned home one day to
find newly planted pansies, a gift from a friend, sprawled in the
afternoon sun. At least nighttime temperatures have been lower, and
by early morning the plants had recovered, to my relief.
</P>
<P>
   These lower nighttime temperatures may be enough to keep plants
from stretching too tall. You know how leggy pansies can get in
warm weather. Not attractive.
</P>
<P>
   Remember to pinch the top growth back only about half an inch to
spruce up leggy pansies. This will encourage side branching and
eventually more blooms, they say.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, those who have not yet planted will find great
selections of pansies at area nurseries.
</P>
<P>
   The pansy plant is generally no more than 8 inches in height and
width, but flower sizes vary, and blooms generally are categorized
as large (3-4 inches), medium (2-3 inches) to multiflora (1-2
inches).
</P>
<P>
   The popular Majestic Giant series features large-flowered
pansies available in six colors and a mix, all with faces. This
1966 All-America Selections winner has a free-flowering habit.
</P>
<P>
   Pansies in the Crown series fall into the medium category and
are available in nine bright, clear colors. The Imperial series is
also in this size category and offers mostly faced flowers in blue,
pink and other colors. Imperial was a 1975 AAS winner.
</P>
<P>
   In the multiflora category, the Crystal Bowl series features
pansies in one clear color without a face. There are 11 colors.
</P>
<P>
   There are 14 Maxim colors, including the 1991 AAS winner, `Maxim
Marina,' a light-blue pansy with a dark blue face outlined in
white. All Maxims are faced and fall into the multiflora category.
Universal is another series of multiflora pansies, clear or faced.
There are 13 colors, as well as a mix.
</P>
<P>
   Two additional series are Bingo and Baby Bingo. Bingo cultivars
produce 3 1/2-inch blooms in 14 colors, including some great shades
of blue and rose. The Baby Bingos, like the Bingos, are 8 inches in
height and 6-8 inches in width but produce 2- to 2 1/2-inch
flowers.
</P>
<P>
   Pansies are late-fall-to-spring bloomers in Houston-area gardens
and, given sun, a rich, well-draining soil and varied use, provide
gardeners a wealth of blooms. Planted en masse, the cool-season
annuals are a colorful ground cover. Large groups of one cultivar
are more effective in a landscape than a couple of this and one of
that. Pansies' compact habit makes them ideal as edging material
and container subjects, complementing taller-growing bulbs such as
tulips and daffodils, taller snapdragons or a collection of herbs.
Organically grown pansy blooms are edible, too.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I am unable to keep tropical plants in bloom. They are on my
deck and get several hours of sun each day. I have learned that
bougainvilleas need to be kept thirsty to get them to bloom, but
even then the blooms have been sporadic. What do I fertilize the
plumeria with to increase blooms? The ginger has never bloomed.
What do I need to do? And what is causing the brown tips on the
ginger leaves?
</P>
<P>
   The nun's orchid is barely alive. I purchased it last spring, in
gorgeous bloom. In the fall, I divided the plant, and now they just
languish. There is little growth, and the leaf tips are brown.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A:  &LR; Many gardeners do maintain that bougainvilleas color best
after some moisture stress. Boost color by fertilizing monthly with
hibiscus food with a little Epsom salts. But remember,
bougainvilleas, like many plants, have bloom cycles. They are not
in constant color. And some color better at different times of the
year.
</P>
<P>
   Plumerias must must reach a certain maturity and produce a
blooming hormone in their tips before flowering. This may take a
year or two if you purchase a rooted cutting. It may take up to
five years for a plumeria to bloom if you start with seed.
</P>
<P>
   Plumeria, or frangipani, does well in sunny areas, and this
tropical responds best to an organic-based, well-draining soil.
Frequent supplemental fertilizing is helpful, because plumerias are
heavy feeders. Plumerias like a low-nitrogen, high-phosphorus
fertilizer that has a good amount of potash and trace elements,
particularly iron and magnesium. While plumerias need nitrogen for
good growth, too much will produce a lot of leafy growth at the
expense of flowers. There are fertilizers specially formulated for
plumerias.
</P>
<P>
   Even if you grow your plumerias in containers, mulch to minimize
loss of soil moisture and to keep soil temperatures down.
</P>
<P>
   This fall when the weather cools and you notice the leaves on
your plumeria beginning to yellow, move your plant to a warm spot
for winter. You can keep the plant in the pot, or remove the plant
from the pot and just store the leafless plant. You can wrap the
small root system in newspaper. That's all there is to it. No
fertilizing. No watering. When the weather warms in spring, repot
and return the plant to the outdoors.
</P>
<P>
   There are so many gingers that will thrive in our gardens, and
they vary in light preferences and bloom times during warm months.
All will grow in filtered sunlight, but some (shell gingers)
tolerate more direct sun when established, while others (peacocks)
will burn in scorching summer sun. All like a well-draining,
organically enriched soil. All like a moist soil, although some are
surprisingly drought-tolerant once established, but none like
extremely wet soil. All dislike cold.
</P>
<P>
   The shell gingers (Alpinia zerumbet) will only flower on growth
that survives winter undamaged by cold weather. This year we had
many blooms from late spring into summer, since we had such a mild
winter. These plants like partial sun. I leave frost-damaged stalks
as long as I can stand looking at them, then remove at ground
level.
</P>
<P>
   Hidden gingers (Curcuma spp.) are spring or summer bloomers.
Spring bloomers produce flowers before or while the foliage is
first emerging; summer bloomers produce a central inflorescence
surrounded by the foliage midsummer to early fall. Spiral gingers
(Costus spp.) produce blooms that attract hummingbirds.
</P>
<P>
   The low-growing peacock gingers (Kaempferia spp.) produce flat,
iridescent summer flowers daily given a rich, moist, but
well-draining soil. Avoid harsh sunlight.
</P>
<P>
   The butterfly gingers (Hedychium spp.) flower in summer and only
once per stalk, so you can remove that stalk at any time after
flowering. More stems will appear. The butterfly ginger's fragrance
is wonderful.
</P>
<P>
   Given proper light, moisture and soil, gingers usually thrive
without much care. You can apply a slow-release fertilizer every
three months after growth begins in the spring or use an
all-purpose fertilizer monthly. Mulch, but do not fertilize in
winter.
</P>
<P>
   The leaf you sent seems damaged by moisture stress. Try to keep
soil moisture even. Improper light could also be a factor.
</P>
<P>
   The nun's orchid, Phaius tankervilliae, is a terrestrial orchid
that naturalizes here, but I would mulch well when growing it
outdoors to ensure winter protection. A well-draining, organically
enriched soil is ideal. Some gardeners prefer to grow this plant in
a container. Divide before the plant becomes too crowded _ every
two or three years after flowering. Do not allow water to collect
in the crown to avoid any rotting. Perhaps your divisions had
less-than-ideal roots so have been slow to establish.
</P>
<P>
   Many plants _ of all kinds _ have barely hung on this summer, so
it's good that yours have at least shown some growth. A diluted
application of fertilizer, with water, may give them more energy.
The brown tips are likely a sign of water stress _ either too much
or too little. Avoid hot afternoon rays, too.
</P>
<P>
   Partial morning sun and bright shade in the afternoon is ideal.
This beautiful orchid, native to China, has lush, broad green
foliage and flower scapes up to 3 feet long in late winter-early
spring. The scapes bear numerous and fragrant silvery-white, 4-inch
flowers. The inside of each bloom is reddish-brown. A well-balanced
fertilizer is adequate.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Mail garden questions to Kathy Huber, garden editor, Houston
Chronicle, P.O. Box 4260, Houston, Texas 77210. The bulk of mail
prevents an individual reply to each unpublished letter.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
