<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-18 14:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0615 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-FIGHTING-CULTURE-BOS &LR;      10-18 1719
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FIGHTING-CULTURE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE NEW CULTURE OF FISTICUFFS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOT LEHIGH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The slam of a fist, the sudden snap of a head, the explosion of
sweat, and the smear of blood as two fighters square off. It's as
old as human history, a rite that incites the instinct even as it
appalls the intellect.
</P>
<P>
   Once mostly illegal here, professional fighting is in a period
of perplexing evolutionary renewal, both as sport and idea. Last
week in New York, in a development sure to elevate the growing
sport of women's boxing, Laila Ali, daughter of Muhammad Ali,
fought her first match, sending her opponent to the canvas before
the fight was a minute old.
</P>
<P>
   Two days later, Seattle hosted the United States' first
gender-blender boxing match, a spectacle that filled Mercer Arena
with women screaming ``Kill him, Margaret,'' as Margaret MacGregor
squared off against Loi Chow. (She won.)
</P>
<P>
   And in the new sport called ``ultimate fighting,'' a
few-holds-barred combination of boxing, wrestling, and martial
arts, two American men have died.
</P>
<P>
   And now comes ``Fight Club,'' a made-for-controversy movie about
disaffected young men who discover bare-knuckled brawling is a
life-affirming antidote to the ennui of consumer culture.
</P>
<P>
   Strange as it seems, the further our official march toward
enlightenment proceeds, the more market there appears to be for the
most elemental of confrontations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't quite understand the psychology of it, but people
obviously like the idea of watching people fight,'' says Richard
Lapchick, director of Northeastern University's Center for the
Study of Sports in Society.
</P>
<P>
   No one quite does, though theories abound.
</P>
<P>
   Cultural critic and author Camille Paglia thinks the monotony of
daily life has left the public thirsting for ``gladiatorial''
entertainment that pushes the boundaries of brutality.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are now in a middle-class office culture that is very
sterile, very banal, people are looking at computers, all the
physicality of life gone,'' Paglia theorizes. ``These cartoonish
sorts of confrontations are a way to engage physically, if only
vicariously.''
</P>
<P>
   Historically, gladiatorial combat was boxing at its most
bloodthirsty. Then, the stakes were literally life and death, the
bloodlust as evident as the gore. When cestus-clad Romans performed
for their emperor, the object was to kill one's opponent, and kill
they did. One champion is said to have bludgeoned more than 1,400
opponents to death.
</P>
<P>
   In its early days, American prizefighting was a brutal
bare-knuckle affair that took place in semi-secret locations, its
contestants subject to prosecution if discovered. Fights lasted
until a pugilist was knocked out or couldn't answer the bell.
</P>
<P>
   But if combat as sport has lost some of its savagery with the
adoption of gloves, fixed rounds, and stricter rules, it's never
truly been tamed. As a spectator sport, boxing has been transformed
from weekly occurrence to periodic mega-matches. Still, it remains
popular enough that 1.25 million people ordered the Sept. 18
welterweight championship bout between Oscar De La Hoya and Felix
Trinidad on pay-per-view, while almost 2 million bought the July
28, 1997, rematch between heavyweights Mike Tyson and Evander
Holyfield.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the more regulated boxing has become, the more people
seem to crave even more violent alternatives. Witness the
``ultimate fighting'' competitions that have cropped up in the last
half-decade, brawls arguably as brutal as boxing was in its
bareknuckle days.
</P>
<P>
   Those lightly regulated contests have blossomed in the Ukraine,
Japan, Brazil, England, and Canada _ and in several states, such as
Mississippi, Alabama, Louisiana, and Georgia. These are matches
where it's well within the rules to throw a foe to the ground, then
send a flurry of fists to his face.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, Douglas Dedge, 31, of Florida, died in Kiev after his
opponent sat on him and repeatedly slammed punches into his head.
In 1995, Eric Crow, 23, of Kansas City, hoping to win a little
extra money for Christmas gifts, instead died of brain damage after
taking repeated punches to the head in a ``Toughman'' contest in
that city.
</P>
<P>
   Now the notion of fisticuffs as elixir for alienated souls has
arrived on the silver screen in the form of ``Fight Club,'' the
dark, dystopic movie about alienated young men who band together to
batter one another in a search for a way to feel alive.
</P>
<P>
   ``Getting hit in the face is one of the ways to be present in
the here and now,'' director David Fincher told London's Sunday
Times. ``When somebody hits you in the mouth and you get that first
rinse of salty something under your tongue, and you spit into your
hand to see what it is, you are truly alive in the moment.''
</P>
<P>
   Odd as that idea seems, the film, which opened Friday, seems
sure to fill the theaters, just the way the promise of a slugfest
between two hard-hitters of almost any weight class invariably
captures the American imagination.
</P>
<P>
   And it's not boxing skill we want so much as furious-fisted
combat. How else to explain the delirium when a fight crowd senses
one boxer is dazed and vulnerable, when the aggressor, in fight
parlance, ``moves in for the kill''? Or the derision heaped on De
La Hoya for sitting on what he believed was a lead in his bout with
Trinidad, and thus losing his share of the welterweight title to
the challenger.
</P>
<P>
   That's because, as any honest fan can tell you, boxing's is an
atavistic appeal. To watch two fighters square off is to move from
the realm of the intellect to that of brutal basic instinct and
thus to surrender to something deep, raw, satisfying _ and
sadistic.
</P>
<P>
   Which is why it's both sad and incongruous that the long journey
toward the notion that gender differences should be minimized in
modern society should count, as one of its results, the explosion
of women's boxing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Women seem to be taking on some of the worst aspects of men,''
laments Al Cardarelli, professor of sociology at the University of
Massachusetts at Boston, who says the renewed interest in a culture
of fisticuffs represents a reversal of the '60s and '70s interest
in creating a more peaceful social milieu.
</P>
<P>
   Oddly, the intellectualized idea of equality has opened a door
that gut instinct would prefer to keep closed; for many, there
remains something particularly disquieting about watching two women
beat each other bloody. State auditor Joseph DeNucci, a former Top
10-ranked middleweight, expresses that sense of distaste among the
sport's traditionalists.
</P>
<P>
   ``I may be sounding sexist, but I don't think it is right for
women to get banged and hurt and busted up,'' DeNucci says. ``I
think boxing is a man's sport.''
</P>
<P>
   No longer. Women are asserting their right to fight in
increasing numbers, and though men may respond with the same
concerned disapproval with which Muhammad Ali initially greeted his
daughter's decision to lace up the gloves, it's unlikely to make
any difference _ as he discovered,
</P>
<P>
   Yet as gloved combat becomes a sport for both sexes, it's
important to remember that boxing remains the Saturn of sports,
greedily devouring its own offspring.
</P>
<P>
   For some, it happens quickly, the way it did for welterweight
champion Benny Paret, who died after a savage pounding by Emile
Griffith in 1962, or for South Korean boxer Duk Koo Kim, who
suffered fatal brain damage in a lightweight title bout with Ray
``Boom Boom'' Mancini in 1982.
</P>
<P>
   In ``On Boxing,'' Joyce Carol Oates writes that between 1945 and
1985, ``at least 370 boxers have died in the United States of
injuries directly related to boxing.''
</P>
<P>
   For many others, the toll has been the slower and more insidious
effects of pugilistic dementia, or punch-drunkenness, the condition
that reduced Jerry Quarry, the all-heart heavyweight who in his day
battled Ali and Joe Frazier, to a man-child unable to feed himself
or sign his name, before his death in January at 53. Or which has
rendered former heavyweight champ Floyd Patterson, 64, a sad figure
who often can't recall the hallmarks of his own life. Or even, some
days, the name of his wife.
</P>
<P>
   But it's Ali, the most gifted boxer in history, who visits the
most troubling doubts on fight fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't get hit. I'm the fastest thing on two feet,'' the
brash young contender said as he prepared to fight Sonny Liston for
the heavyweight title in 1964. He was, and he hardly did. Not then,
anyway.
</P>
<P>
   But time waits for no fighter, and a decade later, Ali could no
longer dodge the blows. ``It was like death, the closest thing to
dying that I know of,'' he said after his epic 1975 ``thrilla' in
Manila'' with Frazier, a match many fans consider the best
prizefight ever.
</P>
<P>
   Three years later, reflexes slowed, skills eroding, Ali,
training for a rematch with Leon Spinks, the rough fighter 11 years
his junior who had taken his championship, spoke the new truth.
``To win, all I need to do is suffer,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Who could imagine how much he would suffer? Fight fans have
suffered with him as boxing-induced Parkinson's Syndrome has slowed
his gait and reduced his once famous voice, his quicksilver wit, to
little more than a slow whisper.
</P>
<P>
   For Ali, the fame, the glory, the accomplishment were worth the
loss of physical capacity, says Northeastern's Lapchick, a friend
who says he's heard the former champion say as much.
</P>
<P>
   And certainly America's fascination with all things fistic seems
ineradicable. And yet, if Ali was your childhood hero, if you
listened with your heart in your throat as the end-of-round radio
summaries made it seem as though George Foreman was destroying him
in their October 1974 bout; if you felt a near-religious rush of
joy when miraculous word came that somehow, some way, Ali had come
off the ropes to knock Foreman out in the eighth; if you willed
yourself to believe a 38-year-old Ali could come back to beat
30-year-old Larry Holmes in 1980, if you shook your head in
dejected disbelief when he couldn't answer the bell for the 11th
round; and if you've watched him survive the years since as a mind
imprisoned in a body that barely responds, perhaps you've wondered
if it was really worth it to you, whether you, as a fan, would do
it all over again.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
