<HEADER>
A0625 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k BC-JORDAN-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      10-18 0935
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JORDAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A SELF-SERVING GOP VOTE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROBERT JORDAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Senate Republicans stuck their heads in the sand last week
and rejected the global nuclear test ban treaty, they may have put
more than just themselves at risk.
</P>
<P>
   As President Clinton and Democratic senators warned, the GOPs
self-serving vote _ in which only four Republicans joined Democrats
in voting for ratification _ makes the United States and other
nations more vulnerable than ever to nuclear terrorism.
</P>
<P>
   The GOP-led rejection was primarily aimed at embarrassing
President Clinton, who made the test ban treaty a major goal of his
administration. Most media reports called the vote a ``major
defeat'' for the president. That's just how the GOP hoped the vote
would be portrayed.
</P>
<P>
   But in reality, the Republican-led vote is a resounding defeat
of a long, arduous effort of both Democratic and Republican
presidents to bring an end to the nuclear arms race and make the
world a safer place. Nations engaging in a nuclear arms race, such
as India and Pakistan, can now continue its testing and implicit
threats to each other, without any justifiable moral admonition
from the United States. Other nations can also use the Senate
rejection as an excuse to escalate their own nuclear arsenals.
</P>
<P>
   In essence, Senate Republicans may have jeopardized the security
of the United States just to enhance their own political security.
But in the end, the GOP may have made itself more vulnerable _ to a
Democratic takeover of the House and Senate in the 2000 election.
The GOP's rejection of the test ban may, on its own, not be enough
to oust the GOP leadership. But consider it along with the other
GOP actions over the past few years that were primarily aimed at
embarrassing, if not destroying, President Clinton and his
administration. It could prove to be the proverbial last straw that
finally breaks the GOP's already shaky grip it has on the House and
Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton and other Democrats have vowed to make the GOP's
rejection of the test ban treaty a campaign issue in the 2000
election. Apparently, so have the Republicans, who are betting that
voters will give them credit for US on top as the world's leading
nuclear power. The test ban, some GOP members argue, would have
weakened the nation's nuclear dominance.
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore, a presidential contender, said if he is
elected, he would re-submit the test ban treaty for US
ratification. Texas Gov. George W. Bush and other Republican
hopefuls such as Elizabeth Dole and Sen. John McCain oppose the
treaty, signaling that the ban may become a definitive issues in
the presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, voicing the GOP's view,
labeled the treaty deeply flawed; he called in unverifiable, and
said it would harm US efforts to maintain the strength and
reliability of its nuclear arsenal. But that argument flies in the
face of the United States' self-imposed moratorium on nuclear
testing, which was done primarily to maintain and improve its
nuclear strength. This moratorium has not met with Republican
criticism.
</P>
<P>
   Passage of the test ban treaty would have allowed the United
States to retain its supremacy in nuclear weapons, as it is now
doing under its own nuclear moratorium _ a fact that Sen Patty
Murray, a Democrat from Washington, pointed out during the debate.
</P>
<P>
   If the treaty is ratified by all 44 nuclear powers, the treaty
would have stopped all nuclear tests, established 300 monitoring
stations and, as supporters argued, maintained US nuclear
superiority. Thus far, the treaty was signed by 154 nations,
including the US, but has been ratified by only 51 nations. Had the
United States ratified the treaty, other nations likely would have
followed suit.
</P>
<P>
   China, for example, which had signed but not ratified the
treaty, expressed, through its foreign ministry, ``profound
regret'' over the rejection, adding that the United States ``has
great influence in bringing the treaty into effect.''
</P>
<P>
   The Japanese foreign ministry said of the rejection that the
``adverse effects are inestimable, and it is of extreme concern.''
It said it had hoped for the US's leadership in nuclear disarmament
and stopping nuclear proliferation.
</P>
<P>
   The Russian foriegn ministry said the rejection ``deals a
serious blow to the whole system of agreements in the field of
nuclear disarmament and non-proliferation.''
</P>
<P>
   And US allies such as France and the European Union expressed
``disappointment'' in the Senate rejection.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, on the right side of this issue, said he would continue
to work ``to strengthen the worldwide consensus in favor of the
treaty'' while continuing to observe the moratorium on nuclear
testing that has been in effect for the past seven years.
</P>
<P>
   But that is not nearly as good as ratifying the treaty _
something that the GOP has been angling to avoid for quite some
time. Sen. Jesse Helms, chairman of the Senate Foreign Relations
Committee, had reportedly kept the treaty bottled up in his
committee for two years before suddenly bringing it before the
committee a few weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   Helms and other conservative Republicans apparently knew that
they had enough votes to reject the treaty and strategized to give
Clinton and other Democrats little opportunity to lobby lawmakers,
and the public, for support of the treaty.
</P>
<P>
   The conservative Republicans strategy apparently worked, to the
detriment of US leadership and world peace.
</P>
<P>
   (Robert Jordan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
