<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LONG-MARRIAGES-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COUPLES PROVE LOVE IS AGELESS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GLORIA NEGRI  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ In the rooftop restaurant on the 17th floor of the
Ritz-Carlton hotel, they danced to music popular half a century ago
with stars in their eyes and a spring in their step, proving, once
again, that love is ageless.
</P>
<P>
   For the 20th year, the city's Commission on Affairs of the
Elderly brought together 60 couples married 50 years or more to
celebrate the longevity of their unions.
</P>
<P>
   For better or for worse, in sickness and in health, through
World War I, the Great Depression, and World War II, they stuck
together and made their marriages work.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know some of the men I see out there in the audience,''
Mayor Thomas M. Menino joked Friday in giving the toast, ``and I
have to say, their wives must be saints.''
</P>
<P>
   All of the couples interviewed said that it was love, simple
love, that kept them together _ that and being adept at the fine
art of compromise.
</P>
<P>
   This year's longest married couple _ at 71 years _ was Joseph
and Edith Arena of East Boston, 89 and 88, respectively. They were
married at St. Bridget's Church in Maynard, Mass. _ where Edith is
from _ on Sept. 2, 1928, when she was 17 and Joe, from Boston's
North End section, was 18.
</P>
<P>
   Today, they have two daughters, seven grandchildren, and four
great-grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
   The answer to a successful marriage, Edith said, is in ``taking
care of each other.''
</P>
<P>
   Joe said the secret was ``to agree on everything'' and agreed
with Edith, adding, ``especially on finances.'' He recalled that
before he became a labor union organizer at local racetracks, he
sold vegetables from pushcarts in Haymarket and was worth ``exactly
$2.59 cents the day we were married.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to respect each other's point of view and
compromise,'' Joe said, ``and never go to bed mad.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps one key to the durability of the marriages of all the
couples at the Ritz was that their definition of love was similar:
Taking care of each other. Most said their love is stronger today
than it was on the day they were wed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Never argue, go to bed mad, or fight over money,'' said Robert
Pigott, 71, a retired mail handler, who has been married to
Margaret, 72, for 51 years. They have three children and three
grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
   ``The words, `I'm the boss,' should never be said in a
marriage,'' said William Janey, 82, of Boston, a retired lieutenant
colonel in the National Guard. ``When the kids come along they have
to pitch in with the chores and we all sit down to dinner at the
same time.''
</P>
<P>
   Janey and wife, Hortense, 78, who worked as a teacher's aide,
have been married 57 years. They raised three boys and two girls.
They met at the Twelfth Baptist Church in Boston's Roxbury section,
which they still attend, and say going to church, no matter which
one, is important to keeping a marriage intact. ``When things go
wrong, it's good to sit down to talk to God,'' Janey said.
</P>
<P>
   Big families also make for lasting marriages, said Martin and
Catherine O'Brien of Boston's Charlestown neighborhood, who have
been married 51 years. The O'Briens, 74 and 71, have 10 children,
21 grandchildren, and six great-grandchildren. ``We help one
another and stay very close,'' said Martin, a Boston firefighter
for 33 years before retiring.
</P>
<P>
   Catherine says today's high divorce rate stems from ``kids
having had everything and expecting a lot in marriage. They can't
handle problems.'' She recalled that when Martin was a fireman in
1948, his salary was $51 a week. ``We didn't have health
insurance,'' she said, ``until I had our seventh child.''
</P>
<P>
   John and Betty Kelly of Charlestown, who have six children and
13 grandchildren, said a sense of humor helps during 50 years of
marriage. ``Why did our marriage last?'' chuckled John Kelly, 73.
``She worked nights (in the office of the old Jordan Marsh), and I
worked days (as a construction inspector).''
</P>
<P>
   In one touching moment, though, John looked into his wife's eyes
and said, ``I truly love her.''
</P>
<P>
   That's also what Sal Ciacchella, 92, of the Roslindale area said
of Josephine, 89, his wife of 60 years. ``She is a truly wonderful
woman.'' They are parents of twin daughters. For 53 years, Joe
owned a grocery store in Newton. Josephine worked as a seamstress.
He met her when he went to date her sister. She played the piano
then and he sang. They still do.
</P>
<P>
   The Ritz-Carlton's manager, Henri Boubee, honored the couple by
providing free meals and a free room.
</P>
<P>
   As Enrico and Ida Gambale of Roslindale, parents of two, danced
to Glenn Miller tunes played by the John Rampino Band, they said
their 50 years of marriage have been one long dance.
</P>
<P>
   ``A woman has to give 90 percent,'' said a happy Ida, 70, a
cosmetologist, as Enrico, 84, looked on with a smile. They met, she
said, when Enrico was her girlfriend's butcher. ``He asked me for a
date and we went on the trolley car to go swimming. To me, he is
forever romantic. I tell him he has bedroom eyes.''
</P>
<P>
   Jacob Robinson, 81, a retired leather worker from Boston who
with Dorothy, his wife of 59 years, had one child, made the most
succinct observation about marriage.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know the song, `Sunrise, Sunset,' from `Fiddler on the
Roof?' '' he asked. ``Well, marriage is like that. One day
following another.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
