<HEADER>
A0631 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-ART-HEADE-2TAKES-BOS &LR;      10-18 1060
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ART-HEADE-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRINGING OUT THE REAL MARTIN JOHNSON HEADE 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRISTINE TEMIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ In 1996 a lush little painting of magnolias by Martin
Johnson Heade turned up at an estate sale in Tucson, where it sold
for under $100. The other day, a dealer turned up at the Museum of
Fine Arts to ask curator Theodore Stebbins Jr. and conservator Jim
Wright to authenticate another Heade magnolia. They did. The dealer
turned around and sold it to a private collector in New York for $2
million, a price Stebbins believes is a record for the artist.
</P>
<P>
   Stebbins is your expert if Heade is your painter. The curator
organized the very first Heade show, at the MFA in 1969, as well as
the current quite ravishing one at the museum _ which is only the
third Heade solo show in history, Stebbins says. The one that came
between his two was a 1980s exhibition of the artist's thunderstorm
scenes.
</P>
<P>
   Heade is the hummingbird and orchid painter, the 19th-century
adventurer who made three journeys to Latin America in search of
his subjects, who painted them in front of jungles so humid-looking
they make you want to mop your brow. He started as portraitist and
branched into landscape, but it's as depicter of the sexiest
flowers this side of Mapplethorpe that he's known to the public.
The Boston public knows him better than any other, thanks to the
three dozen Heades given to the MFA by the visionary patron and
American art champion Maxim Karolik, starting in 1945. It's the
largest public collection of Heades, rivaled only by the private
holdings of Detroit collector Richard Manoogian.
</P>
<P>
   The Karolik Heades lived in MFA basement storage before
Stebbins's first show. Not highly regarded by the art-world
establishment of his day, Heade, who lived from 1819 to 1904, was
selling works for $200 when his &UR;  &LR; Hudson River contemporary
Frederick Edwin Church was getting $10,000 for major canvases.
After his death, Heade was almost completely forgotten until 1943,
when a couple of art dealers stumbled on his ``Thunder Storm on
Narragansett Bay'' in a Larchmont, N.Y., antique store.
</P>
<P>
   That find led to Heade's inclusion in a Museum of Modern Art
show called ``Romantic Painting in America'' the same year. His
name began circulating among astute collectors and curators, but he
never achieved the acclaim of his Hudson River counterparts, whose
grandiose landscapes have little in common with Heade's more
intimate and intense ones, although he's sometimes lumped under the
Hudson River heading. He's also called a Luminist by those who see
a kinship between his still seascapes and those of Fitz Hugh Lane,
another painter forgotten and then sensationally rediscovered.
Stebbins says it's pointless trying to fit Heade into any category.
He was an eccentric both professionally and personally. His sheer
weirdness is in large part why he's treasured today _ that, and the
sheer exquisiteness of his painting once he hit his stride.
</P>
<P>
   Which took a while. ``Heade spent 20 years as a bad painter,''
says Stebbins, who has edited those early years out of his new
73-painting show, which is not a full-fledged retrospective. Born
to a farming family in Bucks County, Pa., Heade learned to paint
from his neighbor, the folk artist Edward Hicks. Heade's early
portraits have the stiff, flat, formulaic look of Hicks's
``Peaceable Kingdoms.'' Traveling extensively in America and Europe
in the 1840s and '50s, Heade may have seen the Dutch and Flemish
still lifes that some of his later canvases resemble. Despite the
exposure, Heade remained a hack _ until his 1858 move to the same
New York City building where Church and the other Hudson River
painters had their studios.
</P>
<P>
   In that milieu, he switched to landscape and still life,
developing highly idiosyncratic styles in both. While Church and
Bierstadt were churning out Wagnerian views where mountain ranges
resemble the EKGs of a patient with a wildly irregular heartbeat,
Heade was painting horizon lines as flat as those in Dutch
painting.
</P>
<P>
   Myriad marshes
</P>
<P>
   Salt marshes punctuated by haystacks were his favorite subject.
He painted the marshes of Newburyport, Mass., and North Shore
locations during his frequent forays into New England, and was even
more loyal to these mundane views than to hummingbirds. There are
over 150 marsh scenes _ at last count. Heades are constantly being
unearthed. Stebbins's 1975 monograph on the artist identified 381
paintings by his hand; in the hefty expansion of that tome that
Yale publishes this year, there are 619, with four more discovered
after the book went to press. And as more were discovered, ``we
kept asking if it was too late to squeeze just one more into the
book,'' Stebbins says.
</P>
<P>
   An entire room in the MFA show is ringed with Heade haystacks;
no one, not even Stebbins, has seen them lined up together before.
Stebbins presents Heade as a series painter, even a Monet
forerunner, and offers Heade paintings of haystacks at different
times of day and under varying climactic conditions. Some seem
factual; others, ultra-romantic. Heade packs extremes of light and
shade, wet and dry, into ``Sudden Shower, Newbury Marshes'': He was
brilliant in conveying the passage of time through passing weather,
here through a veil of gray rain falling over a background still
sunlit. Fog and mist enshroud ``The Great Swamp,'' where a farmer
pilots a dinghy through the water to check on whether his haystacks
had gone adrift. The stacks have a mystical presence, like the
post-and-lintel markers at Stonehenge. They're enigmatic
collaborations between man and nature, standing sentry in territory
neither wilderness nor farmland, luring the eye back in space on a
meandering path.
</P>
<P>
   The Heade show is laid out thematically, to characterize him as
a serial, even conceptual, artist. It opens with 16 of the 45 known
``Gems of Brazil,'' a grand, failed project that began with Heade's
journeys south. Only one species of hummingbird lives in eastern
North America. Heade, long obsessed with the little creatures, went
to South America in search of others, which he intended to paint
and publish in a book of chromolithographs. But chromolithography
couldn't replicate the delicate colors of the paintings, and the
project fizzled.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
