<HEADER>
A0634 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-BOOK-HARUF-BOS &LR;      10-18 0972
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-HARUF-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RESTORATION, UNEXPECTEDLY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GAIL CALDWELL  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PLAINSONG &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By Kent Haruf. Knopf. 301 pp. $24. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One of the great nourishments of living close to the earth is
that you get to see time in motion. It bends and sways according to
wheat and dawn and universal law, not man-made schedules, and its
rhythms are as synchronized as a heart beating underneath a rising
moon. The meter of Kent Haruf's quiet novel possesses this same
sense of calm and certainty, so that the story it tells feels as
unadorned and appropriate as muslin in church.
</P>
<P>
   ``Plainsong'' (a finalist for the 1999 National Book Award)
covers a couple of seasons in the small town of Holt, Colo., on the
high plains east of Denver. Steeped in the taciturn codes and
traditions of the rural West, the novel gives little hint of its
actual time period _ only someone's offhand reference to Nancy
Reagan tells us the setting is roughly contemporary. Not that it
matters: The modern age hasn't really had much impact on Holt,
except for an occasional upgrading of farm equipment and a bus
station that will try to get you there on time.
</P>
<P>
   With its title taken from the vocal melodies of early Christian
music, ``Plainsong'' delivers the stories of several interlocking
lives, their daily dramas played out in relation to and in spite of
one another. The first of these belongs to Tom Guthrie, a tall,
soft-spoken schoolteacher with two young sons whose wife is
somewhere between clinically depressed and just plain miserable.
Ike and Bobby, who are 10 and 9, cope with their mother's bedridden
ennui and her eventual departure by using the age-old tools of
children: They worry to themselves; they buy her perfume at the
drugstore; they get into minor trouble and couldn't really tell you
why. Guthrie, for his part, is equally laconic: Love is not
something talked about much in ``Plainsong,'' and yet you can feel
the depth and emotionality of these characters by the blessed way
they don't often say what they need to.
</P>
<P>
   That particularly holds true for the show-stealers of the novel,
two crotchety old brothers who've lived together out south of town
since time began. We first meet Raymond and Harold McPheron when
Guthrie and his boys go out to help them vaccinate their cattle and
check to see which of their herd will be calving in the spring.
This is Haruf at his best: He knows how to describe a working
spread with dignity and precision, rather than romance or
sentimentality, so that you can feel the intensity of a rancher's
no-nonsense life with metal-cold realism.
</P>
<P>
   The McPheron brothers circled their wagons after their parents
were killed in a truck accident when the boys were teenagers. Since
then they've had little trouble in their lives, or at least not the
right kind of it, as good-hearted Maggie Jones tells them. A
colleague of Guthrie at the local high school, Jones has taken in a
girl named Victoria Roubideaux; locked out of her house by her
mother, Victoria is frightened, alone, and pregnant. Approached by
Jones, who knows them to be the finest of men, the McPherons bring
Victoria into their home; they have to move old boots and machinery
off the kitchen chairs to make room for her, but soon they're
teaching her the finer points of farm reports and cattle markets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Plainsong'' is a sweet novel. Not cloying, but kind and
gracious, and enamored with the simplicity of a story based on
human decency. There's a bad kid in the story just to provide a bit
of agon, a big, scary thug who threatens Guthrie and terrorizes his
boys. And there's sadness aplenty: This is the West, after all,
where animals teach humans how to die simply by possessing shorter
life spans, and where a calf breach can give you plenty of
instruction about the perils of labor. But mostly there is goodness
in ``Plainsong,'' whether in the dear old Mrs. Stearns who
befriends Guthrie's sons or in the mere absence of evil's
complexities. Some of this tone is achieved by the stripped-down
equanimity of Haruf's style, which for the most part conveys
precisely what you need to know. When Guthrie goes to visit his
estranged wife, worried about her decline, we understand that she's
turned it around just by this description of Guthrie's initial
impression: ``She had lost weight since he'd last seen her, but it
didn't appear that she would lose any more.''
</P>
<P>
   That's an atmospheric mood difficult to sustain, and
occasionally Haruf staggers in two equally dire directions: One is
in sounding like bad Cormac McCarthy in his opening pages (high
drama and no punctuation); the other is the unfortunate choice of
the comedic verb form to ``sally forth,'' which Richard Russo has
already overused terribly and which ought to be put out of its
misery. ``Plainsong'' is neither McCarthy nor Russo, and is better
off staying away from either; instead, it is a simple field planted
with one rather unexciting crop, which is the staff of life. That
is the silent asset of this novel, which in its most resonant
moments is as understated and true-blue as Raymond McPheron
himself. When Victoria begins to worry that she may have endangered
the baby she's carrying, Raymond rushes (well, ambles) to console
her. ``I knew of this heifer we had one time that was carrying a
calf,'' he tells the girl, ``and she got a length of fencewire down
her some way and it never hurt her or the calf.''
</P>
<P>
   That may be one of the nicest stories Raymond ever told anybody,
and you can tell it took hold by the fact that Victoria's eyes tear
over with gratitude. It's one of the ways people say they love you
out in Holt, and ``Plainsong'' shows that somebody must have been
listening back.
</P>
<P>
   (Gail Caldwell chief book critic for the Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
