<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-18 15:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0640 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-STAGE-CHAMBERLAIN-BOS     10-18 1447
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STAGE-CHAMBERLAIN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RICHARD CHAMBERLAIN GROWS UP TO HEAD VON TRAPP CLAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRUCE MCCABE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW HAVEN _ Richard Chamberlain is bemused, perhaps amused.
</P>
<P>
   He's been asked to find the connecting thread in his diverse
acting experiences.
</P>
<P>
   Start with ``Dr. Kildare,'' take it through ``Shogun'' and ``The
Thorn Birds'' and Hollywood farragos like ``The Towering Inferno''
and ``The Swarm'' and features like ``Petulia'' and ``The Madwoman
of Chaillot.'' Connect those to the interludes in England and some
stage and television performances of ``Hamlet'' and touring with
``My Fair Lady.''
</P>
<P>
   And then, well, what about his most recent creepy role,
torturing an emaciated Lauren Bacall to a lingering death in the TV
movie ``Too Rich: The Secret Life of Doris Duke''?
</P>
<P>
   Chamberlain, 64, trim, fit and radiating energy in a sport shirt
and slacks, sits in a chair in a hotel room and takes a thoughtful
swig from his bottled water. He doesn't answer the question, not
directly. But for most of an hour he reviews that crazy variety of
work in Hollywood and in recent independent films. And his roles on
stage.
</P>
<P>
   He also traces his development from ``leading boy'' to leading
man and then character actor, and he describes what it's like
living in Hawaii and touring in ``The Sound of Music,'' which
arrives at Boston's Colonial Theatre Monday and plays there through
Nov. 7.
</P>
<P>
   He begins by talking about the actor's feel for a role. ``Never
underestimate the actor's instincts,'' he says. ``The actor can be
closer than the writer is to a character.'' He cites Gary Cooper as
an example of someone who ``conveyed extraordinary things about his
character without saying anything.''
</P>
<P>
   He wanted to go with his instincts in ``Doris Duke,'' he says.
``I could have been creepier. I wanted to play my character with a
ponytail and an Irish accent. The network vetoed it. Some of my
friends didn't like me in it, either. They said, `Richard, you
weren't very nice.' They like you more as a leading man than a
character actor.''
</P>
<P>
   Chamberlain's hotel room is just a stone's throw from the Yale
campus, and it's mid-afternoon of a warm, sunny New England fall
day. But in a few hours, he'll be on a stage set walking through
the doors of his manse high on an Austrian mountaintop to the warm,
friendly applause of a large family audience at the SNET Oakdale
Theatre in nearby Wallingford.
</P>
<P>
   ``I find acting rather difficult,'' he says. ``I'm hopelessly
shy and inhibited. When what you're doing is working for you, it
feels great. But it can be difficult before you find out what it is
you want or have to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Forty-one years ago, a Rodgers &AMP; Hammerstein musical called
``The Sound of Music'' was going into rehearsals a few blocks away,
readying for a run in this tryout city before its scheduled opening
in New York. Does it need saying that the rest is history, that
jaded professionals call the durable musical ``The Sound of
Money''? And now, here's Chamberlain, an actor with his rather full
resume, playing Captain Georg von Trapp, the lonely widower/father
of seven children, in a touring production once again telling the
story of Austria's real-life von Trapp family, who fled their
native country in 1938 to escape Nazi repression.
</P>
<P>
   Chamberlain's von Trapp isn't the familiar martinet played by
Christopher Plummer in the 1965 movie. In fact, Chamberlain's is
closer to the more avuncular father figure that Raymond Massey
played to Chamberlain's Dr. James Kildare in the popular NBC
medical drama series that had a five-year run, from 1961 to 1966.
</P>
<P>
   As it happens, Chamberlain's ``Dr. Kildare'' was something of a
watershed for the actor. It established his credentials as what he
calls a ``leading boy,'' who evolved into a leading man in some of
television's biggest miniseries, ``Shogun'' and ``The Thorn Birds''
among them. Here's his description of what it takes to be a leading
man: ``Tall, good-looking, a straight shooter, honest, good,
forthright, reliable, upright _ and seldom funny.''
</P>
<P>
   Although he was the leading man in ``Shogun'' and ``The Thorn
Birds,'' he ``had to stand in line'' for both roles. He says
director Peter Weir ``had an eye on Robert Redford'' for ``Thorn
Birds.'' And author James Clavell wanted Sean Connery, a Scottish
actor, for ``Shogun.'' He adds: ``But I was patient. I talked with
Clavell for a couple of days and convinced him.''
</P>
<P>
   Chamberlain's success as Dr. Kildare also prompted some advice
from British actor Sir Cedric Hardwicke at a lunch at Raymond
Massey's house. ``You're a star,'' Hardwicke told him. ``Now you
have to get your basic training'' as an actor.
</P>
<P>
   So when ``Kildare'' ran its course, Chamberlain essayed summer
stock, hoping he could develope his stage acting technique. It
didn't work: Summer theater was too helter-skelter. So he decided
to try his luck in England with British repertory theaters and a
mix of feature and television work.
</P>
<P>
   ``I stepped off the plane in London and into a job. A director,
James Cellan Jones, thought I might be right for the role of Ralph
Touchet in the six-part BBC-TV serial adaptation of Henry James's
`Portrait of a Lady.' And I kept working after that. Julie
(Christie) and (director) Richard (Lester) wanted me for `Petulia.'
I never got (around to) drama school.'' England provided his escape
from what he calls ``the gravitational pull of the force of
`Kildare' which had made me a `friend in the living room' for five
years.''
</P>
<P>
   Chamberlain went to England for a different milieu. He contrasts
the English theater to Hollywood this way: ``In Hollywood there's
this driving fear that if you're not hot, you might as well be
dead. If you're not going to parties, you might as well be dead.
Actors in England have a different value system. The quality of the
work counts.''
</P>
<P>
   As he moved further away from leading man into character roles,
Chamberlain found acting more interesting. He also developed an
interest in working in independent films where he could be/play
anything he wanted. He could cut loose, open up. He says his most
recent effort in this vein is ``definitely'' his ``best work
ever.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I play an extraordinary character in an independent film we
made in North Carolina called `The Pavilion.' It's adapted from a
Robert Louis Stevenson short story about a banker-swindler-slave
trader. He's living on an island with his daughter whom he may or
may not have slept with.''
</P>
<P>
   When it was noted that this seemed like a surfeit of character
traits, Chamberlain said: ``The more the merrier with me.''
</P>
<P>
   When he's not working, Chamberlain lives in the Hawaiian
islands. ``Nothing happens there,'' he says. ``I love to play. I'm
good at not working. I can go for long stretches doing it. But then
I get the itch to work. When I was approached by the producer for
`Sound of Music,' I said why not? I've paid my dues. And it's
turned out to be fun being on the road (it's a 40-week tour). It's
like a kids' adventure. The company's all in the same hotel, all
going out and eating together. It's very self-contained. There's
nobody else to go out with.''
</P>
<P>
   He says his role is ``a more interesting part'' than expected.
``I didn't expect this to be the real ensemble it turned out to be.
It's a quality show with a lot of strengths.'' Asked how he feels
about his singing, he responds, ``It's better if you can sing. I
sing pretty well, even though air conditioning sometimes gets me.
I'm a bass-baritone with a low range. I took singing lessons. I've
recorded songs and I did do `My Fair Lady.' I thought `Sound of
Music' would be easier. I thought I'd have time between
performances to do some of my own things, learn Italian and learn
how to use a computer. It turns out to be a big part, even though
not as exhausting as `My Fair Lady.' I do eight shows a week.''
</P>
<P>
   Chamberlain differentiates television movies, miniseries, and
feature films this way: ``You shoot five pages a day for a
television movie, nine or 10 for a miniseries, and one or two for a
feature.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're a puppet of the director in film acting. He's the boss.
It's extraordinarily mechanical. Everything is dictated by what
scene you're doing. The whole idea is to `beat the machine.' But
it's so exciting once you get the knack. You have to keep your
energy near perfect pitch so that when they say `OK, let's do it,'
you can.''
</P>
<P>
   ``In television, there's an unspoken atmosphere of mediocrity.
The rationale is `we can get by with this.' You work five to six
weeks and you stamp it out. And you get by. It's an oppressive
atmosphere.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
