<SLUG> BC-OLIPHANT-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FINALLY, THE SCANDAL-MONGERS ARE OFF BABBITT'S CASE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (w and k coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By THOMAS OLIPHANT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In all fairness, Carol Elder Bruce bent over
backwards to be thorough and do the right thing by a scandalously
wronged man, Interior Secretary Bruce Babbitt _ for which she
deserves no credit whatsover.
</P>
<P>
   For some reason (protecting the rear end comes to mind), the
peculiar patois of prosecutors (and especially special prosecutors)
requires that no one ever be let off the hook, including those who
have never really been on it.
</P>
<P>
   And so it is supposed to be par for the course that after an
18-month independent counsel investigation into what may have been
the driest hole in history, Last-Name Bruce can say with defamatory
tentativeness that that the fruits of her labor ``would not support
a finding'' that First-Name Bruce committed perjury or any other
crime.
</P>
<P>
   The truth is that her fruits left the record exactly where it
was when politicians and the press began taking supposition and
insinuation to new depths after the 1996 election: blank, empty,
clean, unblemished. Nothing ever happened.
</P>
<P>
   That's exactly what you'd expect regarding someone with a
lifelong and deserved reputation for the highest probity and
integrity as a state attorney general and governor in his native
Arizona, a delightful-in-failure presidential candidate and a
secretary of the interior who in conservation history will belong
with Gifford Pinchot and Stewart Udall in the same sentence.
</P>
<P>
   But this insult to justice occurred nevertheless, with all the
attendant blood shed in the Congress, the press, and then grand
jury rooms, simply because of the frightening ability of the Great
American Scandal Machine to suggest that something might have
happened.
</P>
<P>
   If you went anywhere near political news in the year following
the election, you know about Native American casino cash and
lobyists blocking other Native Americans hunting casino permits in
some remote part of Wisconsin, about White House middlemen,
Interior Department complicity and Babbitt somehow in the
crosshairs of it all.
</P>
<P>
   Senator Fred Thompson's special committee made mountains out of
this molehill, feeding mammouth press interest, prompting de
rigueur calls for an independant counsel from politicians that
Attorney General Janet Reno (who is always damned when she does and
damned when she doesn't) proved unable to resist because of an
astonishing defect in her legal mind that rewards uncorroborated
accusations no matter how implausible.
</P>
<P>
   And Senator Thompson's special committee also made sure that the
evidence _ in person and documentary _ showing what baloney all
this is, and which formed the core of Bruce's belated discovery
that nothing happened, was suppressed from those telegenic,
informative hearings that the American people remember so well and
so fondly.
</P>
<P>
   The mess resulted from an effort to open a casino at a failing
dog track in Hudson, Wis., as an off-reservation facility that
began seven years ago. It had regional Interior support, but none
in the White House, like all such casino efforts in the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   After the casino was rejected by department civil servants in
mid-1995, the losers cried foul and pressed lawsuits and political
retribution just as other tribes that opposed the project had
lawyered up and got out their political checkbooks.
</P>
<P>
   After 1996, and given disclosure of the Clinton-Gore campaign
and the Democratic Party's ugly ethical record in handling soft
money donations and granting access to donors, things got out of
hand.
</P>
<P>
   All of a sudden, the department's rejection of the Native
American casino-dog track business venture became criminally
``suspect'' simply because the opponents made $300,000 in soft
money gifts to the Democrats. And Babbitt became a suspected
perjurer because of a testimonial conflict between the secretary
and an old friend from Arizona who had been hired by the proponents
to lobby his (now former) buddy.
</P>
<P>
   We now know, after all that junk, that the only evidence ever in
existence proved the casino rejection was handled routinely, and
without Babbitt's involvement in any way, much less with any
political pressure from the White House or DNC on the career
officials involved; there is and never was evidence of a quid pro
quo.
</P>
<P>
   Reno could have stopped all this, but under the unlamented
independant counsel law she insisted that a simple conflict between
two sworn witnesses (even a minor one) must trigger a criminal
investigation, even if it expanded (which it did) to the underlying
casino decision that she said didn't merit further investigation.
</P>
<P>
   The result was 18 months, 400-plus witnesses, and 600,000-plus
pages of evidence, as well as defamation and legal bills.
</P>
<P>
   The pols and press all had their fun. Now the drill here is to
say the system worked and justice was done.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't and it wasn't.
</P>
<P>
   (Thomas Oliphant is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
