<SLUG> BC-BOSTON-BRAVES-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT HOME WITH THE BRAVES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By THOMAS FARRAGHER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The players are just tiny names in box scores now, distant
cousins who evoke only traces of the passion their forebears
commanded when Braves Field still stood and Boston was a two
baseball-team town.
</P>
<P>
   But as the Red Sox try to catch the Yankees in the American
League championship, the dwindling fans of the old Boston Braves
are keeping score of the National League series and watching the
ballplayers from Atlanta, whose team traces its roots to New
England, try to eliminate the New York Mets.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no question about it, there's still a few people who
are carrying a torch for the Braves,'' said Dick Johnson, curator
of the New England Sports Museum. ``It's been diluted over the
years, but for some the allegiance for that old team is still quite
strong.''
</P>
<P>
   With a spanking-new ballpark, an impressive record of recent
wins, and a billionaire owner who pantomimes tomahawk chops with
his movie-star wife, the team of Ted Turner and Jane Fonda is
barely distinguishable as the modern incarnation of the club that
left Boston in March 1953 because of sagging attendance.
</P>
<P>
   But if he squints hard enough, and allows his mind to drift back
to the era of President Truman, Mayor Hynes, and the Korean War,
Philip Cahill can easily conjure up images of Warren Spahn, Johnny
Sain, Earl Torgeson, and Willard Marshall.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've followed them ever since they left town,'' said Cahill,
76, of Wellesley, who grew up across the street from Braves Field,
now the site of Boston University's Nickerson Field. ``If there's a
Braves game and a Red Sox game on TV, I'll watch the Braves. I will
confess to having a great problem if the two teams were to meet in
the World Series. I know there's a thing called hometown loyalty.
But I'm not sure what I'd do.''
</P>
<P>
   Cahill may be getting a little ahead of himself.
</P>
<P>
   Even among members of the Boston Braves Historical Association,
his allegiance _ following the team through its travels from Boston
to Milwaukee to Atlanta _ is unusual in a society that is as much
about nostalgia as it is about derring-do on the baseball diamond
</P>
<P>
   ``I just really enjoy revisiting that era. It's when I grew up
and went to the games with my father,'' said John Brooks, who was
raised in Newton and now lives in Westchester County, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   ``The players were more familiar to me then,'' Brooks said.
``They all seemed pleased to be playing. You could almost see it in
the way they would lean, the way they looked, the angle of their
caps. I just like to bury myself in the memories of those days.''
</P>
<P>
   Those days were 82 seasons long, played by the Red Stockings,
Red Caps, Doves, Beaneaters, Rustlers, Bees, and _ ultimately _ the
Braves. While in Boston, the franchise won 10 pennants, one World
Series (1914), and was followed by fiercely loyal fans who grew
accustomed to pulling for the underdog.
</P>
<P>
   ``The division between the Red Sox fans and the Braves fans were
along class and ethnic lines and the Braves were much more the poor
people's team and the team of choice for immigrants,'' said
Johnson, co-author of an upcoming book chronicling a century of Red
Sox history. ``The Red Sox were more of the white-shoe team. The
Braves were blue collar.''
</P>
<P>
   Their young fans clipped newspaper coupons, redeemed at the park
off Commonwealth Avenue in Allston where a nickel bought a ticket
in the third-base pavilion along with other members of the group
known as the Knothole Gang.
</P>
<P>
   ``The players were very, very approachable and they still are to
this day,'' said Bob Brady of Braintree, who produces a Boston
Braves newsletter every few months.
</P>
<P>
   When the Braves returned to Boston in the summer of 1997 with
the introduction of interleague play, their old fans broke out
their faded jerseys and broken-billed caps to celebrate the sons of
Sibby Sisti and Johnny Logan.
</P>
<P>
   Five hundred members strong, the team's historical association
holds reunions at which old fans reminisce with aging players like
Tommy Holmes, Ray Martin, Norm Roy, and a pitcher named Art
Johnson, who led the team in strikeouts in 1941 and then blew out
his arm in spring training 1946.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the fans can still tell you the records of the old
Braves players and we can't lie about it because they have one of
those big baseball encyclopedias,'' said Art Johnson who lives in
Holden.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think our fans favored National League baseball and, of
course, we were almost always the underdog,'' he said. ``You know
how people feel about the underdog? They still think the wrong team
left town. That's their favorite expression: The wrong team left
town.''
</P>
<P>
   But over the years, the team that stayed has acquired the
loyalties of most of the old Braves followers. And to them, if the
Red Sox were to beat the odds and meet the team from Atlanta in the
final World Series of the century, nostalgia would be little match
for pennant-winning passion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody loved the Braves more than I did, but if it's the Red
Sox-Braves in the World Series, that won't put me into a corner for
a second,'' said former state Treasurer Robert Q. Crane, who rode
the streetcar to Braves Field as a kid. ``I did root for them for
the longest time. But there's no residual allegiance. I've never
enjoyed a ballplayer as much as I've enjoyed (Nomar) Garciaparra.''
</P>
<P>
   Gerald Eskin, another Boston Braves booster, said the only tie
linking the old Braves with the new is the uniform.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would rather see the Mets win, quite frankly, because
they're both underdogs and the Red Sox have a debt to pay to the
Mets,'' said Eskin, alluding to Boston's World Series heartbreak in
1986.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
