<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-QUESTIONS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATURE'S INTERNAL BARBER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID ROPEIK  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. If a man didn't shave his face or his head and lived to, say,
75 years old, how long would his hair be?
</P>
<P>
   G.R., Mendon, Mass. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Rapunzel notwithstanding, neither men nor women can grow head
hair much longer than 4 feet, or facial hair much longer than 2.
Nature has a kind of internal barber. Here's how it works,
according to Dr. Michael Holick, professor of medicine, dermatology
and physiology at the Boston University School of Medicine.
</P>
<P>
   The follicles from which hair grows have on and off periods.
``On'' is called the anagen phase. The off period is called the
telogen phase. The anagen, or growing, phase lasts between two to
six years on the scalp, and about two and four years on the face.
</P>
<P>
   Telogen, the off phase, lasts about two to three months, both on
the top of the head and on the face.
</P>
<P>
   During the anagen phase, the follicles are adding keratin, a
protein, to the base of the hair shaft so that it gets longer and
longer.
</P>
<P>
   During the telogen phase, the follicle stops making keratin, and
the shaft gets a little loose inside the follicle. Any kind of
abrasion or pulling, and that hair comes out. That's why you'll
always see a few strands of hair in your comb or brush.
</P>
<P>
   You always have some follicles in the telogen phase, and you're
pulling out hairs that have stopped growing. All the hair from
follicles in the telogen phase loosens and falls out before the
anagen phase in those follicles kicks in again.
</P>
<P>
   Then why don't we go bald for a few months when the telogen
phase starts? Because fortunately not all our follicles follow the
same schedule. They don't all turn on and off at the same time.
While some are off, many are still on, busily growing longer and
longer hair.
</P>
<P>
   So here's the math of hair length. A hair on your head grows 1/2
to 3/4 of a foot per year, for up to six years. It can get only
about four feet long before the follicle switches off and that hair
falls out.
</P>
<P>
   Face hair grows 1/4 to 1/2 a foot per year, for up to four
years. It can only get two feet before the facial follicle switches
off.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Holick has isolated what appears to be the stimulus that
controls this on-off cycle. It's called parathyroid hormone related
peptide. PTHrP for short. It builds up in the follicle, finally
reaching a level that triggers the telogen phase.
</P>
<P>
   Holick has made a molecule that works like PTHrP, and on mice,
it turns follicles off and the mice lose their hair. Mickey Mouse
bald as Telly Savalas.
</P>
<P>
   He has also made a molecule that blocks the effects of PTHrP,
and when that's used on the mice, their hair never stops growing.
Minnie Mouse with the tresses of Crystal Gale.
</P>
<P>
   Will it work in humans? Holick is about to find out. He's
seeking government approval to try a topical treatment on cancer
patients who have lost their hair because of chemotherapy.
</P>
<P>
   Bad news for bald guys, though. The Yul Brynner look is caused
by the outright death of follicles, not because they're on a
temporary telogenic time-out. No follicle, no hair.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Readers are invited to send science questions to How&AMP;Why. Write
to How&AMP;Why, Health/Science, Box 2378, The Boston Globe, Boston, MA
02107; or send via Internet to: howwhy(at)globe.com.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-18-99 1514EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
