<SLUG> BC-WHITE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BONING UP ON CALCIUM INTAKE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE WHITE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Osteoporosis is no laughing matter. And yet, each day, as I suck
down enough yogurt to choke a goat, I wonder if maybe our national
obsession with calcium consumption isn't just a tiny bit funny.
</P>
<P>
   Got milk? You bet. How could I not get milk with the dairy
industry on my case? Virtually every magazine I pick up has another
article about calcium. Where to get it. How to get it. How to make
sure you're getting enough of it.
</P>
<P>
   And the ads are everywhere. I'm looking at one featuring photos
of Tracey Ullman as four different characters, each wearing a milk
mustache, with a caption that reads: ``There's one person I won't
be. A woman with osteoporosis.''
</P>
<P>
   Women should be careful to get enough calcium in their teens and
20s, when bones are developing, advises Ruth S. Jacobowitz, author
of ``150 Most-Asked Questions About Osteoporosis.'' A youthful diet
of black coffee and cigarettes can come back to haunt you when
you're older, in the form of hip and spinal fractures.
</P>
<P>
   Generally speaking, young women don't think much about
osteoporosis, but by midlife most are aware that lack of calcium
can lead to bone loss, to breaks, to shrinking. One day you notice
that an older friend or relative is looking through the steering
wheel instead of over it. ``That won't happen to me,'' you say to
yourself, and run off to gobble up as much calcium as possible
before it's too late.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, I have developed calcium-related anxiety. At night,
just before I close my eyes, I wonder, ``Did I get enough calcium
today?'' I turn off the light and toss and turn and worry. Maybe I
should get up and eat some calcium-rich ice cream. Or chew a couple
of Tums. The ice cream calls out to me. Consuming enough calcium
can be fattening.
</P>
<P>
   Post-menopausal women who aren't on hormone replacement therapy
should have 1,500 mg of calcium a day. According to a food chart in
Jacobowitz's book, that's the equivalent, more or less, of two
8-ounce containers of plain yogurt (415 mg each), a cup of collards
(357 mg), plus a half-can of sardines, bones and all (372 mg). Or,
alternatively, nine cups of ice cream (176 mg per cup), give or
take.
</P>
<P>
   No matter how you go about it, no matter how carefully you plan,
it's not easy to take in so much calcium every day, even with
calcium-fortified foods such as juice and cereal available. And
it's not just a simple matter of eating calcium-rich foods. Certain
foods must be eaten cautiously because they hinder calcium
absorption. Sodas. Caffeine. Too much salt. Oxalic acid, found in
spinach, parsley, and a variety of other vegetables.
</P>
<P>
   Until somebody invents a calcium-fortified potato chip, the only
way I'm going to get 1,500 mg of calcium every day is to take
supplements. At the drugstore, I find a bewildering variety.
Calcium citrate. Calcium carbonate. Calcium from oyster shells.
Calcium gluconate. Calcium lactate. All kinds of calcium with or
without magnesium, vitamin D, vitamin K. It seems foolish to make a
choice without the advice of a lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   They're offering free samples of a new calcium supplement. It's
chocolate and chewy. Yummy, in fact. I decide to buy some.
</P>
<P>
   ``Be careful with these, ma'am,'' the pharmacist says, in a tone
that suggests he's handing me an explosive device. ``Don't eat more
than three a day.''
</P>
<P>
   I remember Jacobowitz's warning that too much calcium can upset
your body chemistry and may actually be harmful. It can cause
kidney stones, various intestinal unpleasantries.
</P>
<P>
   Too little calcium. Too much calcium. Does worrying about your
calcium intake hinder calcium absorption? I wouldn't be surprised.
</P>
<P>
   (Diane White is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-18-99 1515EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991018.0245 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-18 15:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0648 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-ART-HEADE-2ND &LR;  &UR; TAKE-B     10-18 0916
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ART-HEADE-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 BOSTON: ... project fizzled.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The paintings survived. They have the preciousness and precision
of Faberge eggs. The introductory ones in the MFA are framed in
fours, in windowlike panes outlined in gold moldings, an odd
presentation Stebbins says was probably the doing of their previous
owner, British art historian Kenneth Clark. The paintings are pas
de deux between a male and female of each species, engaged in what
humans read as flirtatious conversations, with swordlike beaks
sometimes aiming toward each other, as if zeroing in for a kiss.
Heade went beyond Audubon descriptiveness: He'd even pair
hummingbirds that didn't share the same habitat, inventing
fictional turf wars between them. He's got a whole aviary's worth
of species in the 1870 ``Tropical Landscape with Ten
Hummingbirds,'' a chockablock fantasy that suggests Bosch. On the
other hand, in the interest of accuracy, Heade stocked up on
hummingbird skins in Rio, to prompt his memory of their dazzling
colors _ including a pink that shrieks across the room even in
small doses.
</P>
<P>
   The flaring orchids, with their hot-hued, beckoning interiors,
are erotic _ especially in tandem with those pointy-beaked birds.
They were considered erotic in Heade's time, too. Orchids were
sometimes omitted from 19th-century books on the meanings of
various flowers, because they were so blatantly sexual to Victorian
eyes.
</P>
<P>
   Heade's flowers make you want to know more about his take on
nature. ``For Church and the Hudson River painters, nature was a
fixed, Emersonian Garden of Eden,'' says Stebbins. ``Heade was
their age, but a generation ahead of them. To him, the tropics were
not fixed but in flux, not an Eden but a dangerous, malarial place.
Heade saw the tropics as Darwinian, with species competing for
survival, a place of rot and decay offset by eggs in a nest
suggesting rebirth.''
</P>
<P>
   Heade's orchids stand up for themselves, poised and receptive
vessels. The magnolias he painted late in his career, after moving
to Florida and marrying, at age 64, swoon in submission. Made at a
moment when Impressionism was coming to the fore, they're sleek and
seamless, with nothing of that style's flickering paint
application. Heade had his one fling with Impressionism before the
term was coined, in the stippled strokes of his 1868 ``April
Showers.''
</P>
<P>
   Flower power
</P>
<P>
   Once Heade sketched a flower, he'd recycle the same bloom in
painting after painting. It's a modernist approach, and a practical
one. Stebbins has hung a quartet of apple-blossom canvases in a
row, emphasizing how different the same bloom can look in various
surroundings, like a diamond in different settings. Hovering
against a cloudy void, the flower is an icon. Plopped into a
nautilus shell in a suffocatingly cluttered Victorian interior,
it's a mere accessory.
</P>
<P>
   Heade had lapses. The one huge work in the show, the 1887 ``View
From Fern-Tree Walk, Jamaica,'' is bland in both color and
composition, as if its scale had diluted it. The room of seascapes
is uneven. The stunner is the painting that was key in Heade's
rediscovery, ``Thunder Storm on Narragansett Bay,'' a scene of
blackness overtaking sailboats on a glassy sea. Pale birds are
silhouetted against dark sky, and vice versa. A jagged line of
lightning divides the picture vertically, offsetting a horizontal
sandbar where a tiny figure is taking down a sail whose voluptuous
white folds prefigure those magnolia petals of a couple of decades
later. Other figures are carrying off oars, an everyday activity in
a scene that balances the transient and timeless.
</P>
<P>
   Heade also had a sense of humor. One little work that isn't in
the MFA show, alas, is a wacko image, ``Gremlins in the Studio,''
recently bought by the Wadsworth Atheneum in Hartford. It's a
painting of one of Heade's marsh paintings, propped up on
sawhorses, with a cartoonish gremlin cavorting underneath.
</P>
<P>
   After Boston, the Heade show heads to the National Gallery of
Art in Washington, D.C., then winds up its tour at the Los Angeles
County Museum of Art. Although the MFA organized the exhibition and
Boston is its first stop, it's not in the Gund Gallery, the
museum's largest and most high-profile temporary exhibition space,
but in the smaller Torf Gallery. In the rotunda adjacent to Torf,
the MFA has installed a small and none-too-stellar selection of
paintings by Heade's contemporaries: They seem almost deliberately
chosen to make Heade look even better. In a hallway off the
rotunda, Stebbins has hung R. J. Thornton's ``Temple of Flora''
prints, published in London from 1799 to 1807: Their in-your-face
foreground flowers suggest Heade's bizarre compositional format _
birds and orchids shoved to the front of the picture plane, set
against jungly dampness.
</P>
<P>
   For a broad context for Heade, and one that gives him stiffer
competition than the rotunda display, stroll through the American
paintings galleries. Here you can take in the Luminism of Lane or
Sanford Gifford, and William Harnett's trompe l'oeil still lifes
that share the velvet seductiveness of Heade's magnolias. Here you
can even compare the gritty, white, full frontal flowers of Georgia
O'Keeffe to his sleekly groomed ones. These works flesh out the
Heade exhibition, which would have benefited from a sampling of the
early portraits and even those ``Gremlins.'' Tucked into Torf, the
show feels somewhat incomplete. And that, because what is there is
so splendid, feels sad.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
