<DOCNO> NYT19991018.0247 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-18 15:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0650 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-MUSIC-EURYTHMICS-2ND &LR;      10-18 0727
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-EURYTHMICS-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 NEW YORK: ... started singing. ...''  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Lennox has one of richest voices in pop music, and is arguably
the best white female soul singer. In the early days, Eurythmics
material was often shaded toward the dark side. On that first tour,
Lennox was in Boston, riding in a cab to her hotel. Discussing
Eurythmics, she called them a ``serious'' band and said, pointedly,
``This is not good-time rock 'n' roll.'' Lennox laughs when that
anecdote is recalled and says, ``I hope I have developed a sense of
humor since then.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When we did the `Sweet Dreams' album,'' says Stewart, ``Annie
was living in a basement, we had just broken up, we had no idea
whether we were going to have a record. It was all bad.''
</P>
<P>
   Writing ``Dreams''
</P>
<P>
   ``The lyrics are a blueprint of your soul at the time,'' Lennox
picks up, ``but you don't sit down and say `I am going to do this
kind of song now.' It is actually just the soul speaking, and David
has this very special thing where he (helps) make it happen. It is
a little hard to explain what he does, something typical of what we
write, but that day (we wrote `Sweet Dreams') I was very depressed
and we were trying to write something and it didn't fit and I
sulked about it, and then without talking I said listen to this
little rhythm'' _ she sings it _ ``and then all of a sudden I got
this idea and in five minutes the whole thing was done. It wouldn't
have happened if I hadn't been with Dave, because he kind of
instigates things.''
</P>
<P>
   Stewart compares Lennox to another singer with whom he's
recently worked, Bryan Ferry. (Stewart helped produce Ferry's next
album of original work, not the upcoming covers album ``As Time
Goes By.'') Ferry, he says, is severely self-critical and suffers
from writer's block and the same goes for Lennox. The music is a
collaborative process, but the lyrics are just about always
Lennox's.
</P>
<P>
   ``I go, `Ahh . . . it's rubbish,' '' says Lennox, ``and he goes
`No, no' while he's organizing it. It's got so much to do with
self-actualization. You feel there's nothing there and it's very
odd. Nevertheless, I think I've grown in my confidence about my
abilities and the thing that really helped that was us working
together.''
</P>
<P>
   The first single from the new album is ``17 Again.'' It begins:
``Yea, though we venture through the valley of stars / You in all
your jewelry and my bleeding heart / Who couldn't be together and
who could not be apart / We should have jumped out of that airplane
after all.''
</P>
<P>
   It is, quite obviously, autobiographical, and it was the first
song they cowrote for the album. ``I think Annie was sitting at
home at her grand piano,'' says Stewart, ``and she had something
that she really liked. And she said, `You've got to start
somewhere.' I liked it straightaway.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I just got this (melody) line in my head,'' says Lennox, ``and
you sort of sit and stare at the line. That's how I get the words _
I sit and stare at it. And then I go through all the things that
rhyme and see what fits. It's sort of biblical _ going through the
valley of death, the shadow of death, fame also. We face an awful
lot today, that whole process of being revealed in such a public
way. The differences between us two _ we couldn't be together and
could never be apart. And that part about the airplane _ we should
have jumped.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, that's a curious bit. Where does that come from?
</P>
<P>
   ``We have very vicious and excruciating journalists in
Britain,'' says Lennox. The acerbic critic Julie Burchill ``had
written that we should die famously (that way). Why do people write
like that? You know there is something in you that is hurt. The
airplane was our aspirations and ambitions, if you like, so we
should have jumped out because we are not worth anything. It was
hard not to fall because we were up there in the ether of stardom.
What a place to be. I had so many crashes that I could not feel at
all. I kept on crashing and crashing with myself.''
</P>
<P>
   But ``17 Again'' is, ultimately, full of hope, as are
Eurythmics. The song circles back at the end to the chorus of
``Sweet Dreams.'' Says Lennox: ``It's like full circle. When you
were 17 it is an extraordinary moment, after childhood and
pre-adulthood. You think you know everything, but you don't know
anything and yet it is a special time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
