<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-18 15:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0651 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r s BC-FBN-KNAPP-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      10-18 0890
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-KNAPP-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEIFERT HITS THE CENTURY MARK BY DEFEATING FAMILIAR TEAM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By GWEN KNAPP  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Carolina Panthers coach George Seifert came out
of the tunnel for warm-ups, and a huge roar went up in the nearby
end zone. The applause seemed even louder and warmer than Seifert
had a right to expect, dressed as he was, in the garb of a
turncoat, a black Panthers polo shirt over a pair of khakis.
</P>
<P>
   Were there really this many San Francisco 49ers fans willing to
cheer for a rival coach, just because he had once been theirs? Were
they nostalgic for the old days, and perhaps so unconcerned about
what Seifert's 1-3 Panthers might do to their own depleted team,
that they could blithely cheer their lungs out for him?
</P>
<P>
   One look in the direction of that frenzied end zone explained it
all. At the very moment that Seifert stepped onto the grass at
Candlestick, Jerry Rice ran out of the Niners' locker room about
100 feet away. The cheers were for him, not for Seifert.
</P>
<P>
   The returning coach slipped onto the field in relative peace and
anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   But his exit? Well, that was different.
</P>
<P>
   He left a winner, which is the way he usually left the field at
Candlestick, so it wasn't all that different, except for the black
shirt and the fact that he had to squint into the sun on the
visitors' sideline all game.
</P>
<P>
   There are all sorts of statistics, arcane and otherwise, to
suggest the significance of this victory. It was Seifert's 100th
regular-season victory as a head coach in the NFL. He has a 100-33
regular-season record, making him the quickest coach ever to hit
the century mark for wins. Don Shula, the runner-up, had 35 defeats
before his 100th victory.
</P>
<P>
   The win also kept alive Seifert's distinction as the head coach
with the highest winning percentage in history. Vince Lombardi, at
.741, was closing fast. A win by the 49ers would have dropped
Seifert down to .740 and second place. But the Panthers won, 31-29,
in a game of anarchy, a game that looked as if it could have been
moved to the parking lot without a substantial drop in quality of
play.
</P>
<P>
   Seifert had beaten his successor, Steve Mariucci, in their first
meeting since Eddie DeBartolo and Carmen Policy dispatched Seifert
to his fishing boat in January 1997. Mariucci had never before lost
a regular-season game at the 'Stick, and here was Seifert upending
him, delivering a devastating blow to 49ers prestige.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm about as worn as I can ever remember after a game,''
Seifert said, in what amounted to a major concession. He tried all
week to pretend that meeting the 49ers meant nothing special.
Barely five minutes into his postgame news conference, he said:
``If we were in Washington and won this game, I'd be on top of the
world.''
</P>
<P>
   To which Wesley Walls, the discarded 49ers tight end in Carolina
colors, said: Nonsense, or some football-player version thereof.
``He was really excited,'' Walls said. ``I could tell, even though
he was good at playing it cool. He'll probably get mad at me for
saying this, but it's 49ers week, and whenever it's 49ers week,
it's special.''
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the game, Seifert's daughter, Eve, and son-in-law
Bill Dunkle, found him as he started to leave the field and gave
him big hugs. His wife, Linda, stayed back at their new home in
Charlotte, avoiding all of the emotions of the day. But Eve and her
husband own a coffee shop in Larkspur, Calif., and they had to be
at the homecoming.
</P>
<P>
   They went down on the field late in the fourth quarter, when
Carolina had a comfortable lead. The 49ers pulled within two points
in the final minute and a half, and Eve started worrying that she
had counted unhatched chickens.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were only supposed to come down if he won,'' she said,
``and so I was thinking, `Shoot, should I race back up?''
</P>
<P>
   He started talking about her father's career in San Francisco,
and what this game meant, but quickly stopped herself. ``I'm not
going.''
</P>
<P>
   During those last crazy minutes, Seifert paced in tight circles,
head down slightly, almost averting his eyes from the field. It was
a familiar scene for Bay Area sports fans and for television
broadcasters, who have always treated footage of an excited George
Seifert as if it were buried treasure. Mariucci and Jon Gruden, the
new breed of Bay Area coaches, show more emotion before the first
commercial break than Seifert has revealed in his entire career.
</P>
<P>
   Seifert chatted amiably with Mariucci before the game, both men
with their hands in their pockets. At the end, he found a weary
Jerry Rice leaving the field and gave him a quick embrace.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll always be a 49ers fan,'' Seifert said matter-of-factly.
``I grew up with them. The Bay Area is home to me. That'll always
be there, down deep, at gut level.''
</P>
<P>
   That was as animated as he became publicly, except for a
conversation a few minutes later, when he was asked for the name of
his daughter's coffee shop.
</P>
<P>
   ``Would you give it a plug?'' he replied enthusiastically, then
started gushing, like any proud parent. ``It's called the Java
Cafe. They've done a great job with the place. It's a lot of fun,
and it has a wonderful hostess ... my daughter.''
</P>
<P>
   OK, George, there it is, a plug for your kid. You win. Again.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
