<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-18 15:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0653 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r s BC-FBN-RATTO-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      10-18 0858
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-RATTO-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
49ERS COACH FACES THE SORRY TRUTH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RAY RATTO  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The stride isn't as purposeful as it used to be.
The grimace is stretched rubber bands. The voice, a lifeless
monotone of resignation.
</P>
<P>
   In short, there is no exclamation point in Steve Mariucci's
world right now. The facts have hit him flush in the yap one too
many times for him to pretend any longer. His is not football's
dream job any more, and he knows it as only someone with a
foot-sized knot in his gut can.
</P>
<P>
   Mariucci endured his first home loss as head coach of the San
Francisco 49ers Sunday, a 31-29 defeat at the hands of the Carolina
Panthers, and he couldn't dress it up as anything other than the
kick in the sweetbreads that it was. He couldn't claim, as is
mathematically the case, that if the season were to end today, the
49ers would still obtain a place in the NFC playoffs. He certainly
couldn't boast that he was steering a very special ship, because he
would look far too much the fool.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he acknowledged the world as it is _ a grim and forlorn
place, where nothing can be taken for granted, and history is not a
guide to the future but an immense dark hand pointing accusingly at
him.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, it's . . . we've been good, we've been lucky, we've
been able to respond,'' he said when asked to address the end of
his 19-game winning streak in the 415.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had some close ones, some barn-burner type games here.
We've won in overtime, we've had last-second field goals, we've had
come-from-behind-type games. You don't want to make a living like
that. You'd like to get ahead right away, and have the people go
home early. ...''
</P>
<P>
   Then he gathered himself, took a breath, and dropped the punch
line.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's just not reality any more.''
</P>
<P>
   No, it surely isn't. Mariucci, though, seems to have realized it
at last, and very much the hard way.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it was the listless way he tried to enumerate the excuses
he could have used. Maybe it was knowing that the architect of the
49er legacy, Bill Walsh, was standing over his shoulder, in spirit
when not in fact. Maybe it was seeing George Seifert, the man who
followed Walsh, across the field with that fisherman's squint of
his wearing the silly teal-and-black of Carolina. Maybe it's
finally understanding that the empire cannot stand proudly forever,
what with Steve Young, Terrell Owens and Garrison Hearst in civvies
and the cornerbacks in uniform.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Steve Mariucci has finally lost his cheery, sometimes even
cockeyed optimism.
</P>
<P>
   There was no sign of that optimism Sunday afternoon. He wasn't
even outwardly angry about the myriad breakdowns that caused them
to fall two touchdowns behind a tea that in the old days wouldn't
have been within two touchdowns. That, was then. This is now, and a
hell of a hard now it is at that.
</P>
<P>
   The two defensive touchdowns they scored Sunday nearly hid the
fact that their most effective offensive weapon was kicker Wade
Richey. The defense allowed 300 passing yards to Steve Beuerlein,
which Beuerlein hadn't done in six years, and the third time it had
allowed 300 yards to any quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   Mariucci knows it, and surely coached like it Sunday. He made
what seems now to have been a significant tactical error not
letting Wade Richey try a 51-yard field goal on the first
possession of third quarter and the boys down, 24-16. He cited the
wind as a factor, but mostly he didn't want to put his paycheck in
Wade Richey's mouth, even though the offense under the oddly
skittish quarterback Jeff Garcia was doing nothing of note.
</P>
<P>
   True, he was doing what 49er coaches have done since Walsh _
disdaining the field goal as the mark of a sissy-boy, denying the
greatness of the system and its practitioners. But the system is
being placed in the hands of lesser talents now, and in the new
pie-fight NFL, the Walshian idea of standard of play is simply no
longer applicable.
</P>
<P>
   Some folks saw these days coming; indeed, some saw them coming
10 years ago, which turns the corner from prescience into
stupidity. Mariucci surely sees them now, and even when his words
hide the truth, his actions and body language expose it all the
more.
</P>
<P>
   The 49ers have won their three games by a total of 23 points.
</P>
<P>
   They have lost their three games by a total of 62. Sunday's was
the closest of the three, and yet the most galling. And even if you
want to make the perfectly reasonable claim that every team in the
NFL is either 3-3 or ought to be, the fact is the 49ers didn't used
to be any team. They won all the time; more impressively, they
routinely covered large point spreads, which means that in their
prime they won by a lot of points, and to do that, you dominate
your inferiors.
</P>
<P>
   There is no domination in these 49ers. There may be survival,
but there won't be another take-it-for-granted game this year; you
think happy thoughts about the Dec. 2 game at Cincinnati at your
peril.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Mariucci won't. He knows better now. Those cleat marks in
his face are all the education he needs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
