<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-18 15:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0654 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-MUSIC-EURYTHMICS-2TAK     10-18 1006
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-EURYTHMICS-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SWEET DREAMS AGAIN FOR LENNOX AND STEWART 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM SULLIVAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Annie Lennox and David Stewart _ former lovers,
forever the best of friends, and once again musical collaborators _
share a couch in a hotel suite high above Manhattan. Together
again, as Eurythmics. It's the morning after their televised
reemergence, where they played a truncated ``hits'' medley on the
``Saturday Night Live'' 25th-anniversary show. ``Bizarre, a
one-second sprint,'' says Lennox. ``It reminded me of comedians _
you've just got to go boom, boom, boom,'' says Stewart. Today,
they're moving a little slowly, still jetlagged after the flight
from London and suffering, perhaps, from a bit too much wine after
the show. They didn't join the cast party; they celebrated on their
own.
</P>
<P>
   After a decade apart, these two are one and they are happy
together. The warmth and respect are apparent as they swap stories,
employing gentle humor and self-deprecating wit. It is evident on
their glistening new album, ``Peace,'' which will be released by
Arista on Tuesday. It is an unabashedly uplifting effort, strong,
confident, and soaring.
</P>
<P>
   ``I noticed when we first played the songs live in the studio
they had a more ominous feeling,'' says guitarist Stewart, ``and
then when we played them (later) it was really up.''
</P>
<P>
   Up it is.
</P>
<P>
   As Eurythmics, Lennox and Stewart sold more than 30 million
records. They don't see this phase of their group as a comeback or
reunion. They've both been working, Lennox scoring with the solo
albums ``Diva'' and ``Medusa,'' for which she won Grammys; Stewart
operating at a lesser commercial level, releasing two albums with
his band, the Spiritual Cowboys, the latest being 1995's
``Greetings From the Gutter.'' He also produced scads of artists.
And, really, Eurythmics never ``broke up'' per se; they just
dissipated. Strangely, Stewart notes, ``even though we haven't been
playing or making records in 10 years, we have never been off the
radio. So there are a lot of people who are 18 or whatever who have
heard us on the radio, but never seen us.''
</P>
<P>
   Lennox and Stewart share a laugh at their own expense about how
old that makes them feel.
</P>
<P>
   The 26-date worldwide tour they are now on does hop across
continents, but it's a far cry from their road warrior days _ ``We
played 283 gigs one year, or something,'' says Stewart _ and there
are only two US dates, Nov. 4 in Los Angeles and Nov. 9 in New York
at Madison Square Garden. They plan on riding out 1999 and seeing
if, in 2000, they feel like touring. Maybe yes, maybe no. Lennox is
married to Israeli film director Uri Fruchtmann and has two
daughters; Stewart is unmarried but has a girlfriend. Priorities
have changed over time. Neither seems to want to reenter the pop
world at a frenzied pace.
</P>
<P>
   All proceeds from the current tour benefit Amnesty International
and Greenpeace. ``We have hooked our souls into working with these
organizations,'' says Lennox, ``and I feel it empowers me as an
individual to do that. I want to work for them. I mean, I want to
do what I'm doing (musically) but I also want it to benefit people.
It actually just gives me a feeling that I exist when I'm doing
that, and that keeps me very happy.''
</P>
<P>
   As to this reemergence, ``There is no master plan,'' insists
Stewart.
</P>
<P>
   Reunion for John
</P>
<P>
   Lennox, 44, and Stewart, 46, got back together again last year.
``It was for John Preston, a guy who was head of RCA in England
when we were sort of successful,'' says Stewart. ``He was a really
lovely guy from Scotland, really young, and all the people in the
industry loved him. We did this as a surprise for him. There were
all these people there in this tiny place with curtains across the
stage. Everybody was having a nice time, and all of a sudden
somebody stood up, gave a speech, and then said, `Anyway, for John,
Eurythmics' and the curtain opened. We played 10 songs, acoustic,
and he was crying his eyes out.''
</P>
<P>
   One thing led to another. They did a breast cancer benefit,
performed on the Brit Awards, and received a Lifetime Achievement
Award. They started working on tunes again at the Church, a London
studio they co-own. ``It just started happening,'' says Stewart.
``We would sit down, have a glass of wine, and start writing a
song. We realized we had written about eight or nine songs and that
made an album.''
</P>
<P>
   What is their motivation, as this quintessential band of the
'80s returns at the close of the '90s?
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, just to do it,'' says Lennox. ``To have a dream and a
burning desire to achieve it. Just getting the opportunity to do
it, to make it, create it.''
</P>
<P>
   As to ambition, Stewart laughs and says, ``I have been plagued
by it. It is nonstop. I was just showing my girlfriend the other
day, some early stuff, a video, and I realized that in looking at
myself, I was fulfilling a dream.''
</P>
<P>
   They met when he was 23 and worked in a health food shop, and
she 21, a Scottish dropout of the Royal College of Music. They
originally played in the excellent, but largely overlooked, new
wave band the Tourists. But that was Pete Coombes's project. Lennox
and Stewart were not focal points. The two began a romance and
split to form Eurythmics. The romance ended; the band took off, and
in 1983 Eurythmics became one of the first of the MTV-aided video
sensations. People wondered: Sure, they look great, but could they
actually play?
</P>
<P>
   Stewart recalls their first club gig in Los Angeles, where Bob
Dylan (who became a friend later) and other musicians were in the
crowd, with a prove-it atttitude.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were born in the video generation,'' says Stewart. ``And
when we arrived everybody already knew who we were. Everybody was
confused about the video age: Does it mean no one is singing or
playing anymore? Fortunately, we were good. When they came to see
us live, they ended up loving it. When Annie started singing . . .
''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
