<HEADER>
A0656 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-MOVIE-GUIDE-BOS &LR;      10-18 0544
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-GUIDE-BOS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Recent movie reviews from The Boston Globe:
</P>
<P>
   (BS)(BS)(BS) ``All the Little Animals'' An allegory about the
healing power of nature, made with the English love of nature and
eccentricity. Christian Bale stars as a troubled boy fleeing from a
cruel stepfather, finding refuge with John Hurt's cranky old
hermit, whose life work is saving animals and burying the ones he
can't save. (R)
</P>
<P>
   (BS) 1/2 ``Breakfast of Champions'' Kurt Vonnegut Jr.'s
Vietnam-protest-driven novel is transformed into an uneasy misfire
of an anti-consumerism cartoon. Bruce Willis gamely unravels as an
unhappy used-car king, Nick Nolte bravely plays his cross-dressing
sales manager, and Albert Finney lurches in to offer sage if
cockeyed advice as Vonnegut's stand-in. (R)
</P>
<P>
   (BS)(BS)(BS) ``Earth'' The second of Deepa Mehta's films named
for the four elements of antiquity is a rightly horrific depiction
of the slaughter that followed the partition of British India in
1947. Seen though its impact upon a supposedly neutral Parsee
family, the clash between Hindus and Moslems is put in context as a
ghastly (10 million dead) conclusion to British colonialism.
(Unrated)
</P>
<P>
   (BS)(BS)(BS) ``Fight Club'' A dark, sizzling comedy of male
rage. Brad Pitt stars as an anarchic soap salesman bent on world
domination, and Edward Norton plays the corporate drone for whom he
plays evil angel. The two start an underground ``fight club'' whose
pugilistic members become Pitt's own private neo-fascist army. The
film ultimately collapses into explosive silliness, but
audaciousness and style carry it until then. (R)
</P>
<P>
   (BS)(BS) 1/2 ``Get Bruce!'' Half-documentary, half-testimonial
focusing on Bruce Vilanch, the fey writer of what Hollywood calls
``special material'' (remarks at award ceremonies and the like).
His satisfied customers include Billy Crystal, Robin Williams,
Whoopi Goldberg, and Bette Midler and there are interesting
glimpses of their working methods. But the film doesn't much try to
give us the man behind the gags. (R)
</P>
<P>
   (BS)(BS) ``Lucie Aubrac'' Claude Berri's film is based on the
real-life heroics of a French woman during the Nazi occupation. The
story of how she managed to snatch her Resistance-fighter husband
from Klaus Barbie, the butcher of Lyon, emerges in handsomely
crafted but curiously stilted fashion. (R)
</P>
<P>
   (BS)(BS)(BS) ``Stiff Upper Lips'' Entertaining sendup of
Merchant-Ivory, D. H. Lawrence, and a few other British cultural
icons of Edwardian and later vintage. A batty family journeys from
its stately home to Italy and then India, where it gets into the
same sorts of trouble that Lawrence, E. M. Forster, Stella Gibbon,
and others have turned into big-screen bywords. Georgina Cates
stars as the impetuous heroine. (Unrated)
</P>
<P>
   (BS)(BS) ``The Story of Us'' Bruce Willis and Michelle Pfeiffer
give it a good try, and even a warm one, in Rob Reiner's comedy
about a couple coming apart after 15 years of loving but wearing
marriage. The behavioral details are good, but the tone and
resolution are too sitcom-like in tone: We don't feel we've covered
enough ground in enough depth and complexity. (R)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
