<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-BLAIR-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLAIR WITCH'S NEXT PROJECT: VIDEO MARKET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL BLOWEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When my father wanted me to fall asleep when I was a kid, he
told me the following, oft-repeated story: ``It
</P>
<P>
   was a dark and stormy night. We were all seated around the
campfire. The captain said to his trusty lieutenant, `Come,
Antonio, and I'll tell you a story,' and the story went like this.
`It was a dark and stormy
</P>
<P>
   night . . .' ''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Blair Witch Project'' is the ultimate ``dark and stormy
night'' movie. Three student filmmakers head to the woods to make a
documentary about the legend of the Blair Witch and disappear. A
year later, their footage is found. That's it. No plot. No real
character development. No special effects. Nothing except the
genius of some college kids from Central Florida University using
about $35,000, some second-rate equipment, and their ingenuity to
scare the wits out of an audience mostly composed of their
contemporaries. The only ones more frightened than the kids are the
heads of every Hollywood studio, who watched this no-budget college
project horrify most of their big-budget summer releases.
</P>
<P>
   As ``Blair Witch'' co-director Eduardo Sanchez put it in an
interview with Britain's ITN network, ``We broke all of Hollywood's
rules; people digged the whole underdog thing. It was like these
guys coming out of nowhere . . . they have no money, and they just
have a good idea and they break every rule that Hollywood has
etched in stone.''
</P>
<P>
   On Oct. 26, ``The Blair Witch Project'' hits video stores in
both the VHS and DVD formats. Fueled by a $15 million advertising
campaign, about 428 times the movie's cost, and a flurry of
interest on the Internet, the distributors and retailers expect the
home video sales to dwarf the approximately $125 million the movie
made in American theaters.
</P>
<P>
   Artisan Entertainment, the film's savvy distributor, has added
several enticing special features to the home-video versions. Both
the VHS and DVD versions include the Sci-Fi Channel special ``The
Curse of the Blair Witch,'' a pseudo-documentary on the
pseudo-documentary. It includes interviews with ``experts'' on the
Blair Witch and other bits and pieces of fictional evidence.
</P>
<P>
   The DVD includes conversations with the actors and filmmakers,
and the DVD-ROM adds a map of the Black Hills Forest, a dossier,
and ``special'' access to the various Blair Witch Internet sites.
</P>
<P>
   Some video stores are planning midnight ``Blair Witch'' parties,
and on-line home-video providers, such as DVD Empire, are tossing
in ``Blair Witch'' necklaces to the first 1,000 customers who
pre-order the feature film. They are also selling the DVD for
$20.95, 30 percent below the list price of $29.98.
</P>
<P>
   What's the fuss? It's really not a very scary movie, especially
for those who were terrified by Alfred Hitchcock's ``Psycho,''
Steven Spielberg's ``Jaws,'' and Stanley Kubrick's ``The Shining.''
There are dozens of redundant shots of woods and darkness with the
actors seeming more angry than scared. But that's also part of its
charm.
</P>
<P>
   `Us vs. them'
</P>
<P>
   Many theatrical releases, inflated by big budgets and handsome
stars, create an ``us vs. them'' mentality, born of the dichotomy
between what's on the big screen and who's sitting in the little
seats. ``Blair Witch'' invites us in. Made for chump change with
equipment easily available at the mall by students at a school with
a film department dwarfed by the University of Southern California,
New York University, and Boston University, ``Blair Witch'' is the
first guerrilla movie to hit the financial jackpot. While not a
brilliant movie, it is a brilliant notion created by some very
smart kids.
</P>
<P>
   When Truman Capote wrote ``In Cold Blood,'' he used the
conventions of the novel to create a work of nonfiction.
Essentially, the filmmakers have done exactly the opposite by using
the conventions of nonfiction filmmaking to create a work of
fiction. That's not new. Albert Brooks did it in 1979 when he
satirized a PBS documentary in ``Real Life'' and it certainly had
its apotheosis with Rob Reiner's mockumentary, ``This Is Spinal
Tap,'' one of the biggest hits on DVD. But all of the early
pseudo-documentaries wore their pseudo on their sleeves. They let
you in on the joke.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Blair Witch'' characters are played by actors who use
their real names _ Heather Donahue, Michael Williams, and Joshua
Leonard _ helping to maintain the illusion that the story is
fact-based. The film looks like the sort of messy home-video
footage associated with ``America's Most Wanted.'' It looks
believable.
</P>
<P>
   According to several sources, the actors were never told what to
expect, so when they look scared and surprised, they are. While the
movie may not be ``truthful,'' the performances are. It's precisely
that sort of authenticity that the audience responds to.
</P>
<P>
   The film also plays to the ever-burgeoning Internet crowd that
spends hours a day interacting with itself. In my memory, it's the
first film that advertised its Internet affiliation with a
full-page ad in Variety, declaring over 20 million hits at
Blairwitch.com following its opening weekend. The Internet
connection energized the ``Blair Witch'' phenomenon: Fans entered
chat rooms, discussed the film, and felt that they were a part of
what has become the ``Blair Witch'' experience. The various maps,
affidavits, and testimonials associated with the different Web
sites lent another level of creative authenticity to the story.
</P>
<P>
   Consequently, while ``The Blair Witch Project'' may not be the
scariest movie ever made, it has Hollywood executives shaking in
their portfolios. The people who give out the outrageous
multimillion-dollar, multiyear contracts are asking why they spend
$50 million on a picture and watch it get destroyed by a bunch of
kids from a podunk film school.
</P>
<P>
   The answer is simple. The college students had the one thing
going for them that hasn't been seen in the Hollywood Hills in many
moons _ originality.
</P>
<P>
   But there's a problem up ahead. The prequel to ``Blair Witch,''
an investigation of the witch's early years, is in pre-production
with a start date planned for later this year or early January in
Halifax, Nova Scotia. The budget is bigger. They're shooting it in
35mm color, and the cast wants to be paid big bucks.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe some enterprising Canadian film students will borrow a few
thousand dollars and some antiquated equipment, hire a few no-name
actors, and make a documentary on the making of the prequel. Or,
even better, maybe some young film student out there has another
idea that no one's ever thought of. That would keep the Hollywood
executives bewitched.
</P>
<P>
   These kids proved that they could make millions with a new idea,
and if ``The Blair Witch Project'' accomplished nothing else, that,
in itself, is a major victory.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
