<HEADLINE>
HIGH-FLYING SALMON GIVES PASSENGERS A FRIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TOM STIENSTRA  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The passengers were just settling in for a
flight from Redding to San Francisco when suddenly, on climb-out
for 26,000 feet, this red, foul-smelling juice started flowing out
of the overhead baggage compartment and onto the passengers below.
</P>
<P>
   Several of the passengers shouted, one screamed, and all tried
to shield themselves from the pervasive red juice. It was sticky,
foul and just kept coming, dripping on the passengers despite their
best efforts to avoid it.
</P>
<P>
   As the plane angled for higher altitudes, the juice seemed to
move to the rear of the plane, as if alive in the baggage
compartment. Meanwhile, one of the passengers aboard, Larry
Ivancitch of Glendora, just smiled nervously.
</P>
<P>
   When the plane leveled off, the juice stopped, and a flight
attendant opened an overhead bin _ and a wet, slippery 30-pound
salmon fell out, right into the lap of one of the horrified
passengers.
</P>
<P>
   It turns out that Ivancitch had caught the fish earlier that day
from the Sacramento River, then had taken it aboard the plane and
had stowed the fish in an overhead bin as carry-on baggage.
</P>
<P>
   WILDLIFE WATCHING: This past year has been one of wildlife
revelations for field scout Rich Callas, a California Department of
Fish and Game biologist who has been tracking deer and elk using
global positioning radio transmitter collars.
</P>
<P>
   In one case, Callas tracked Deer 369 for two months, during
which it moved infrequently, holding its range. Then at 12:16 one
morning, it suddenly covered 15 miles in a seven-hour span. Once
the deer was motivated, Callas said it completed 25 percent of its
migration in one 24-hour period.
</P>
<P>
   The study will allow the Department of Fish and Game to track
elk and deer in order to learn precise timing of their habitat
preferences as the species migrate between summer and winter range.
That information can later be used to protect valuable habitat
niches on their migration routes.
</P>
<P>
   PARK MAINTENANCE: Voters have financed land purchases of 91,000
acres in Alameda and Contra Costa counties for 59 parks in the East
Bay Regional Park District. But now rangers are trying to figure
out how to finance the maintenance of these parks. The bond money
is earmarked for land purchases, not park operations.
</P>
<P>
   The idea now being floated is a small tax on landowners in East
Bay counties, though it would face a very difficult two-thirds
required yes vote at the ballot box.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, a bond measure for the March 2000 ballot to fund
state parks, with some money for regional and city parks, will
require only a simply majority.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
