<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEONE-ALBRIGHT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALBRIGHT TO SEE PEACE'S HIGH PRICE IN SIERRA LEONE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By COLIN NICKERSON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FREETOWN, Sierra Leone _ Special units had special names. There
was the Cut Hands Commando and the Bloodshed Squad and the Burn
House Unit. There was the Born Naked Group, which stripped people
of their clothing before killing or mutilating them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We attacked everybody. We feared nobody,'' boasted Josep
Sonah, a 19-year-old veteran of the rebel horde responsible for
eight years of torture, murder, and mayhem in this tiny West
African nation. ``We were very bold. Everyone is knowing our hot
tempers.''
</P>
<P>
   During nearly a decade of insurgency driven by little more than
a lust for spoils and the sheer thrill of killing, rebels chopped
off the limbs of thousands of civilians, kidnapped children to
serve as ammunition bearers and front-line fighters, put whole
villages to the torch, and drove nearly a million people _ a fifth
of the population _ from their gutted homes.
</P>
<P>
   It is in this violence-racked nation, where a peace, of sorts,
has finally descended, that Secretary of State Madeleine K.
Albright began a six-nation African tour on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The end to the savagery came at a price: The government had to
grant the perpetrators not only amnesty but a share of political
power and control over the nation's mineral wealth.
</P>
<P>
   As Sierra Leoneans swallow this bitter pill, Albright arrived
here in the capital Monday to show that the United States cares
about Africa. In her weeklong tour of the world's most troubled
continent, Albright will also travel to Nigeria, Guinea, Mali,
Kenya, and Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
   Although the stopover here will last only a few hours, it is
still more attention than the brutalized and impoverished nation of
5 million people has typically received from the West during its
long nightmare.
</P>
<P>
   ``We jumped in to defend Albanians being driven out of Kosovo,''
the Rev. Jesse Jackson, President Clinton's special envoy to
Africa, said at a Freetown news conference earlier this year. ``But
Africans have to defend themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Sierra Leone is famed for its wealth of diamonds. These days,
however, the national symbol might as well be the raw stump of an
arm or a severed hand flopping to the red mud. Hideous things
happened here.
</P>
<P>
   Rehabilitation camps for amputees are overflowing with victims
of machete- and ax-wielding rebels whose sadism, especially over
the past two years, far surpassed the usual savageries of a bush
conflict.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was an organized campaign of terror,'' said Corinne
Dufka, a Freetown-based researcher for Human Rights Watch and
author of a detailed report on the terror. ``Instead of just
killing, they hacked off arms to show their power over people. The
atrocities were methodical and deliberate.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, those who wreaked that horror are swaggering back to the
capital to claim their economic and political reward for stopping
the slaughter.
</P>
<P>
   For the peace of Sierra Leone is the devil's peace, a desperate
UN-brokered deal that essentially grants amnesty to leaders and
followers of the Revolutionary United Front _ a ragtag movement of
no discernible ideology _ and guarantees them jobs, positions of
influence, and other boons in exchange for an end to violence.
There's even talk of granting pensions to the now idle but still
heavily armed guerrilla ``liberationists,'' many of whom fought
under such noms de guerre as Captain Crazy Cool and Dr. Blood.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a perfect situation, but it was the best agreement
under the circumstances,'' said Francis Okelo, United Nations
special envoy to Sierra Leone. ``At least there is an end to the
fighting. At least the country can breathe again.''
</P>
<P>
   In any event, with no Western power willing to take direct
action in ending the bloodshed, it seemed the best deal possible
for President Ahmad Tejan Kabbah, one of the few democratically
elected leaders of an African nation.
</P>
<P>
   Kabbah defends the accord. ``After so much pain, suffering, and
destruction, what has been achieved from the peace agreement should
not be measured only in terms of what . . . has been given away to
the rebels,'' he told Parliament.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, as billions of dollars of Western aid flow to Kosovo,
and as an international military contingent rides to the rescue of
Indonesia's East Timor, only a modest trickle of assistance is
reaching Sierra Leone. Aside from a few dozen UN observers and a
request for a broader international force from UN Secretary General
Kofi Annan, no peacekeeping force has been dispatched there,
although private relief agencies from the United States and Europe
are on the scene.
</P>
<P>
   By the grim standards of Africa, the death toll of Sierra
Leone's civil war is not especially remarkable: an estimated 50,000
civilians and combatants killed in a series of revolts, coups, and
counter-coups since 1991.
</P>
<P>
   But few conflicts of this decade can match the Sierra Leone war
for gruesomeness, with rebels led by former Army Corporal Fodaj
Sankoh adopting amputation as their terror trademark. Thousands of
men, women, and children had their limbs cut off by rebels as a
sort of calling card _ ``double upper-limb amputation,'' the
removal of both arms, was a macabre specialty.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Angola, in Cambodia, in most places of war, you will of
course find many, many people who have lost limbs, usually legs or
feet to land mines,'' said Alexis Randin, a prosthetics specialist
with Handicap International, a French aid organization. ``But only
Sierra Leone has these terrible numbers of upper limb amputations.
It's shocking.''
</P>
<P>
   Even three months after the halt of hostilities, surgeons from
the aid group Doctors Without Borders spend long shifts in the
tents of the War Wounded Camp _ a settlement set in a former
tropical resort studded with palm trees _ tending dangerously
infected stumps or, too often, removing the remainder of arms that
refuse to heal. Almost all victims are civilians.
</P>
<P>
   A Human Rights Watch report prepared by Dufka _ a war
photographer for Reuters news service before joining the New
York-based watchdog agency _ documents how rebels high on cocaine,
in a January attack on Freetown, burned people alive, abducted
children to serve the militias, gang-raped women and girls, and
removed hands and arms with practiced machete blows.
</P>
<P>
   ``The rebel who cut my hands had a white T-shirt with `Captain 2
Hands' written in what looked like blood,'' recounted a 42-year-old
man named Osman. ``My 4-year-old son was screaming, `Don't cut off
my papa's hands.' But they did it anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   On the UN's index of human development, Sierra Leone ranks last
_ the worst place on earth. Nonetheless, the country managed
democratic elections in 1996, although President Kabbah was
overthrown in a 1997 military coup.
</P>
<P>
   Backed by a Nigerian-led West African force, Kabbah was restored
to office in 1998, while the junta, led by Major Johnny Paul
Koroma, fled to form another rebel faction.
</P>
<P>
   But Sankoh's Revolutionary United Front kept Sierra Leone in
such bloody turmoil that Kabbah earlier this year yielded to quiet
US and British pressure to accept a deal described as ``peace at
any cost'' _ one granting the rebels amnesty for war crimes,
positions of power in government, status as a political party, and
effective control over the country's diamond fields and other
mineral wealth.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are told we must forgive these war criminals for what they
did,'' said Muctarr Birma, 30, whose left arm was chopped off at
the elbow last January. ``That is very hard because we would prefer
justice. But the world turns its face from Sierra Leone. We have no
choice.''
</P>
<P>
   (at)8sierra leone warfare
</P>
</TEXT>
