<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-18 16:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0698 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-SCI-IRONMAN-ART-NYT &LR;      10-18 1114
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-IRONMAN-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IRONCLAD REGIMEN FOR IRONMAN TRAINING 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: N.Y., Mass., Minn.)   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (af)  
 By JILL AGOSTINO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Most mornings, Bob Spina Jr. is up by 5 and out the door before
his wife and three daughters are awake. It is still dark, but he
gets in a 15-mile run, a 60-mile bike ride or a swim before most of
his neighbors in Massapequa, N.Y., are putting filters in their
coffee makers.
</P>
<P>
   He is back in time to help get the girls ready for school and
give his wife, Lori, time to take her own five- or six-mile run.
Then it's off to work, as a real-estate and estate lawyer. But the
day's workouts are not done: after all, as Spina says, training for
an Ironman triathlon _ a 2.4-mile swim, a 112-mile bike ride and a
26.2-mile run _ is a job in itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to give up things,'' said Spina, 36, who is in his sixth
triathlon season and plans to compete in the Ironman World
Championships in Hawaii on Saturday. His training regimen takes 20
to 25 hours a week. ``Golf went first,'' he said. ``I haven't
played basketball in three years. I had to make the choices.''
</P>
<P>
   Anybody with a commitment to regular exercise knows that
sticking to it requires motivation and discipline. But
increasingly, amateur athletes and the people who train them are
borrowing a tool from the workplace, time management, to plan and
keep to a schedule that works for them.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a client comes to me and says, `I want to work out every
day; what do I do?''' said Cheryl Richardson, a personal coach near
Boston and the author of ``Take Time for Your Life'' (Broadway
Books, 1998), ``I tell them that we need to make a list of the top
10 things that are draining their energy'' _ a messy office,
dealing with their children's teachers, or anything else they have
been putting off _ and ``then let's take the next 30 days and clear
off your plate and prepare your life so you can succeed.''
</P>
<P>
   Then she asks her clients to figure out what type of person they
are. ``Are you a morning person or a midafternoon person or a night
person?'' she said. ``Do you prefer to work out alone? Do you like
taking exercise classes? Do you need variety?
</P>
<P>
   ``Then I tell them to take out a calendar, and for the next six
months let's figure out when you're going to work out five days a
week or three days a week, and write it in there _ in pen.''
</P>
<P>
   Kathleen Weisman, 43, has her workouts scheduled for every
Monday, Wednesday and Friday, without fail. In January, when her
daughter Hope was 3 months old, she joined Brad Schoenfeld's
Personal Training Center for Women in Scarsdale, N.Y., which
provides one-on-one regimens with personal trainers. She has lost
about 20 pounds and says she feels better all around.
</P>
<P>
   ``I needed to be motivated,'' said Ms. Weisman, who has a
20-year-old son in college. ``With the baby, it's very easy to put
exercise last. But now I make it part of my day _ like on Mondays,
I know I go food shopping, then I go work out.''
</P>
<P>
   Schoenfeld, author of the book ``Sculpting Her Body Perfect''
(Human Kinetics), which comes out later this month, says the
professional women who work out at his center schedule their
workouts around their jobs and family obligations. ``Most women do
it before work, from about 7 to 9 a.m.,'' he said. ``Housewives can
come whenever they want, but they also have to manage it into their
day. Many of them have to get a baby sitter.''
</P>
<P>
   Many gyms have day care rooms for parents who have to bring
their children, but Ms. Weisman, who lives in Larchmont, N.Y., says
she still keeps her daughter with her during workouts because she
does not yet crawl around much. And on days she does not go to
Schoenfeld's center, she said, she manages to do some other type of
workout, and she always does it with her daughter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I take Hope for a walk or I can take her on the bike,'' she
said. ``As you get older, it gets harder and harder. I was a young
mother, but now that I'm older I want to be able to do everything
with her that I could do with my son.''
</P>
<P>
   Some people even manage to make their workouts part of their
work. ``It's an extension of how I live,'' said Ms. Richardson, the
personal coach near Boston. ``I wrote the last chapter of my book
when I was on a 15-mile bike ride with a hand-held tape recorder.''
</P>
<P>
   Alan Page, 54, the former Minnesota Vikings star who is now a
justice of the Minnesota Supreme Court, has been making exercise
part of his routine for 20 years. He says he rises at 5:15 every
morning with his wife, Diane, and they run six to eight miles
together _ no matter what the weather.
</P>
<P>
   The key is exercising first thing in the morning, he said,
adding: ``Then it's not a matter of fitting it in. It's done.''
</P>
<P>
   And it helps, he said, to have friends along. ``Some come by our
house, others meet us,'' he said. ``There's no plan or rhyme or
reason to it.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Richardson agrees that working out with friends is an
excellent way to stay dedicated to an exercise program. ``Find a
partner and do it with a partner,'' she said. ``Every morning, meet
someone at the track. It's an opportunity to nurture a friendship
and get exercise.''
</P>
<P>
   But the hardest part is balancing job, family and the need to
spend hours exercising. ``It's a constant struggle,'' said Spina,
the lawyer training for the Hawaii Ironman. ``What's the right
thing to do?
</P>
<P>
   ``The sacrifice is there not only from me, but from the whole
family,'' Spina said. ``It's a commitment for the whole family _
even the kids are on board.''
</P>
<P>
   In the final 10 to 12 weeks before an Ironman competition, he
picks the workouts over going home. But, he said, his family
understands, because it is only short term. The rest of the year,
he added, his family comes first.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's an imaginary line that you can't cross or the family
part of your life falls apart,'' he said, ``and I've seen it happen
to other people. You have to be careful. You have to juggle.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Richardson says you have to set up your workout program _
whether it is five times a week or three times a week _ so that you
succeed. ``If you're going to work out at lunch, run for 20 or 30
minutes, don't schedule an hour run,'' she said. ``If you have to
squeeze it in, the chances of blowing it off are greater.''
</P>
<P>
   There is no right way or wrong way to work out, she said _ it
needs to be your way. ``Once you clear your plate,'' she said,
``you can begin to succeed, and then build on that success.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
