<HEADER>
A0699 &Cx1f; gen-z
u f BC-STATES-COLUMBINE-NAT     10-18 0561
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STATES-COLUMBINE-NAT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;        LITTLETON CONGRESSMAN TALKS HEART TO HEART ON COLUMBINE
LESSONS LEARNED
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;     By Tania Anderson  
 &HT;    c. 1999 States News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON, Oct. 18 -- On a recent trip to Russia, Tom Tancredo
was introduced as the congressman from Littleton, the man who
represents the city where the worst school shooting in history took
place.
</P>
<P>
   At that moment, the first-term Republican lawmaker knew that the
incident had changed his life - and his role as a lawmaker. And on
the six-month anniversary of the school shooting in Littleton,
Tancredo's role on Capitol Hill continues to develop.
</P>
<P>
   No longer simply the congressman from Colorado's 6th district,
Tancredo, after Littleton, looked at his grandson differently. He
wondered what kind of role he should play in the three-year-old's
life. And the incident made him reflect on his role as a parent to
his own adult children.
</P>
<P>
   ``How good a parent was I just because our kids never picked up
a gun and went to school and shot anybody? Am I satisfied that we
gave them a good solid moral underpinning?'' Tancredo said recently
in his Washington office. ``You realize that there are such
enormously powerful influences that sometimes conflict with that.''
</P>
<P>
   Tancredo, who lives less than a mile from Columbine, was
watching CNN on April 20 when Eric Harris and Dylan Klebold went on
a shooting rampage. The immediate feeling of helplessness and
frustration swept Tancredo as the words ``Columbine High School,
Littleton, Colorado'' were stripped across the bottom of the
television screen.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was almost surreal in that you can't believe you're seeing
that,'' Tancredo said. ``It took a while just to sink in and then
you begin to pray that this is going to end without loss of life or
injury.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though he lives so close to the school, Tancredo did not
know any of the victims or the families of the shooters. Tancredo's
first response was to call local sheriff's departments to find out
details. He was originally told that the death toll had reached 25.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt like there was nothing you could do to address the pain
that so many of your neighbors and constituents were
experiencing,'' Tancredo said. ``How do you make it better? That's
really it.''
</P>
<P>
   The first test of the shooting's influence on Tancredo came this
summer when the U.S. House of Representatives voted on the juvenile
justice bill that would require background checks at gun shows,
child safety locks on handguns, and ban importation of large
capacity ammunition clips.
</P>
<P>
   Although he received more than $10,000 in campaign contributions
from gun rights groups - the highest amount of the three Colorado
congressmen who receive gun rights contributions - Tancredo voted
in favor of all three measures. However, the entire bill failed.
</P>
<P>
   He admits that he would have voted against the legislation if
the school shooting had never happened. And he said he would have
never fought for federal funding for school safety hotlines, a
program launched in August. His role as the congressman from
Littleton additionally got him appointed to a congressional
committee on youth violence.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would have never spent months to implement such a thing in
Colorado if it had not been for Columbine,'' Tancredo said.
``Certainly I am doing things today that I would not have done
otherwise.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-18-99 1617EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991018.0266 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-18 16:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0701 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-SCI-ASTHMA-ART-1135(2     10-18 1200
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-ASTHMA-ART-1135(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW DRUGS ARE KEY TO A GOOD LIFE WITH ASTHMA 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Science Times)  
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036.) 
(lh) 
 By DENISE GRADY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Until about three years ago, Dawn Bosquez, a 30-year-old
resident of Denver, was getting most of her medical care for asthma
in emergency rooms. About once a month, she would wake up unable to
breathe and would frantically call an ambulance or friend to rush
her to the hospital, where she would be given oxygen and inhaled
medications to bring the attack under control.
</P>
<P>
   Then, a doctor would prescribe a short course or ``burst'' of
prednisone tablets, a powerful corticosteroid drug, to ease the
inflammation in her lungs that was bringing on the attacks.
Corticosteroid inhalers were recommended, too, but Ms. Bosquez
tended to try them and then quit. For a few weeks she would feel
better. But then, as the prednisone wore off, the cycle of
breathlessness would begin again.
</P>
<P>
   At one point she was referred to a specialist, but she found him
coldhearted, ignored his advice and never went back.
</P>
<P>
   She began to suffer side effects from all the prednisone: she
put on weight, and a hump grew on the back of her neck. And after
one particularly harrowing night in the emergency room, a doctor
who had pulled her through several crises told her that if she did
not get her asthma under control, it might kill her.
</P>
<P>
   At the doctor's urging, Ms. Bosquez made an appointment with Dr.
Esther Langmack at the National Jewish Medical and Research Center
in Denver, a leading asthma hospital.
</P>
<P>
   In the three years since that visit, Ms. Bosquez has not been
back to the emergency room. Daily use of inhaled medicines has kept
her so healthy that she has needed prednisone only once. The ugly
bulge on her neck has disappeared. And she has learned to manage
her children's asthma, along with her own.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the majority of people with asthma, the proper use of
medication, education and self-management can go a long way to keep
them out of the emergency room and keep them where they want to be,
at school or work,'' Dr. Langmack said.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Bosquez said: ``I knew I had asthma. I was born with it. It
runs real strong through my family. But I didn't know what I could
do about it. Nobody ever taught me.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, she said, she is trying to talk her brother into seeing Dr.
Langmack, too, because his asthma is nearly as bad as hers used to
be.
</P>
<P>
   There are many patients like Ms. Bosquez, doctors say: people
who spend much of their time wheezing and hacking, always on the
threshold of the emergency room, not realizing life does not have
to be that way.
</P>
<P>
   For most patients, the key to living with asthma is accepting
that it is a chronic disease, often lifelong, that must be treated
with daily doses of medication, even when the patient is feeling
fine. Asthma attacks are a symptom of lung inflammation, and simply
treating the attacks does not help that underlying condition, any
more than taking aspirin for a toothache will fix the cavity that
is causing the pain.
</P>
<P>
   Because asthma is often brought on by allergies to molds,
pollens, animal dander, dust, dust mites and other airborne
``triggers,'' most patients are urged to keep their homes as free
of irritants as possible. That usually means getting rid of carpets
and other dust collectors, enclosing mattress and pillows in
special covers and banishing cats, dogs, birds and other
warm-blooded pets, if not from the home entirely, at least from the
bedroom.
</P>
<P>
   For many patients, sinus problems and respiratory infections
like colds and flu are important triggers of attacks, and patients
with asthma are taught to track their symptoms carefully when they
are ill so that they can take extra medicine to prevent a crisis.
They are also urged to get a flu shot every year.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Frank Adkinson, a professor of medicine at the Johns Hopkins
asthma and allergy center in Baltimore, said: ``From the point of
view of coping, there are two major groups that have the most
difficulty. One is children, with asthma severe enough to interrupt
their normal lives. They have ongoing attacks, middle-of-the-night
emergency room visits, a lot of time out of school, and it becomes
so unpredictable that the family feels out of control and, indeed,
things are out of control. They need a comprehensive management
program to restore the child to the mainstream.''
</P>
<P>
   The other patients who have trouble coping, Adkinson said, are
people who develop asthma after the age of 30, more often women
than men.
</P>
<P>
   ``Typical of many diseases that hit people in midlife who were
otherwise healthy, they start out with a lot of denial,'' Adkinson
said. ``They think it's not asthma, they put off care and don't
listen to what they're told. They're often psychologically not
prepared to accept a diagnosis of a disease they're going to have
to cope with for the rest of their lives. We have to get them to
recognize it. We have great drugs that can control asthma and
maintain a high quality of life in the vast majority of patients,
probably 95 percent or more. But despite that good prognosis, this
middle-aged group often takes a number of years to settle into a
regimen.''
</P>
<P>
   Treatment for asthma, like that for any chronic disease, works
best when it is individualized for each patient.
</P>
<P>
   To help Ms. Bosquez, Dr. Langmack said: ``I ended up doing
several things. One was good education about asthma, which she'd
never had. I also started her on a high-potency inhaled
corticosteroid.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Dr. Langmack prescribed Serevent, a drug with
long-lasting effects that opens the airways and is used to help
prevent attacks in some patients, like Ms. Bosquez, with severe
asthma.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Bosquez also learned how to use a peak-flow meter, a device
that patients blow into to determine how well their lungs are
functioning. When asthma is worsening, the peak flow often
decreases before the patient notices any symptoms, and can be a
signal that more preventive medication is needed to head off
attacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We also addressed two other problems,'' Dr. Langmack said,
explaining that Ms. Bosquez had sinus and digestive disorders that
aggravated her asthma.
</P>
<P>
   Chronic sinus problems are a frequent trigger of asthma attacks.
Ms. Bosquez's sinus infections were treated with antibiotics, and
she was taught a technique for rinsing mucus and other secretions
out of her nasal passages. And because her sinuses were also
chronically inflamed, Dr. Langmack prescribed a corticosteroid nose
spray.
</P>
<P>
   The other problem that Dr. Langmack treated Ms. Bosquez for was
gastroesophageal reflux, a condition like heartburn in which
stomach acid backs up into the throat and can irritate the airways
and touch off asthma attacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dawn has done really well,'' Dr. Langmack said. ``I credit her
with learning about her asthma and how to look for symptoms and
when to call us. But not everybody's like that.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Some patients do everything they are told to do, and still their
asthma rages out of control and responds only to oral steroids.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fortunately, they're relatively rare among asthmatics,'' Dr.
Langmack said. ``But they are the folks who run up huge medical
costs for themselves and nationally for the entire country. They
are a focus of research here. What is it about these people that
makes their asthma so difficult to control?''
</P>
<P>
   But in many cases, both adults and children who wind up in the
emergency room because of asthma are there because they have not
been using preventive medicines or peak flow meters, or keeping
track of their symptoms.
</P>
<P>
   In a small study at the National Jewish hospital, researchers
found that children, even those supervised by parents, used their
steroid inhalers far less than they were told to use them. Their
average use was 58 percent of what was prescribed, and among those
who had the worst flare-ups, the average use was only 14 percent.
And yet all the families had passed a quiz indicating they had a
basic understanding of asthma management.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers knew how much medication had been used because,
unbeknownst to the families, they had attached monitoring devices
to the patients' inhalers.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to skipping their medicine, both the patients and
their parents failed to tell the truth in records they were asked
to keep. More than 90 percent of them exaggerated how much
medication they had used.
</P>
<P>
   But Dr. Bruce Bender, an author of the study and head of the
division of pediatric behavioral health, said it was not fair to
blame the patient. ``Asthma takes a lot of work,'' he said. ``You
have to take daily medication, at fixed intervals, and sometimes in
response to changes in symptoms. And inhalers are fundamentally
unpleasant devices. Many patients have at least two inhalers that
have to be taken at different times. The more you ask patients to
do, the less they do.''
</P>
<P>
   Also, he said, many patients and families do not get the proper
guidance. ``They're just handed a prescription and told to use it,
without an in-depth explanation of the disease,'' Bender said.
``You can hardly expect them to take it every day.''
</P>
<P>
   When asthma goes out of control, Bender said, doctors should
consider the possibility that the patient is just not taking enough
medicine, and not admitting it.
</P>
<P>
   But, he cautioned, doctors should ask patients whether they are
using their medication ``in a nonthreatening way so that they'll be
open and honest instead of telling you the answer they think you
want to hear.''
</P>
<P>
   Even people who do understand the disease may harbor stubborn
attitudes that are hard to overcome. ``People think you should take
as little medicine as you need, and if you feel OK, you should
stop,'' Bender said. ``But we're treating asthma asymptomatically.
Your airways can have inflammation even when you feel fine.'' Then
suddenly, he said, it can flare up.
</P>
<P>
   Flare-ups tend to be milder in people who use corticosteroid
inhalers, but, he said, some patients hesitate, for fear of side
effects from the steroids.
</P>
<P>
   It is also human nature for people to deny illness. ``There is a
desire to not see yourself as sick,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Friends and relatives commonly report that patients with asthma,
in between coughs and wheezes, will insist that they are just fine
and do not need their inhalers.
</P>
<P>
   ``What to the rest of us would be very uncomfortable, they get
used to,'' Bender said. ``Some obstruction, some coughing, that's
daily life. It's normal to them.''
</P>
<P>
   The best way to break through misconceptions and denial is for
patients to find doctors that they like and trust.
</P>
<P>
   ``Patients are more likely to be adherent if they have one of
those Marcus Welby kind of doctors who takes the time to listen and
talk and explain,'' Bender said. ``But doctors are under great
pressure to see more patients in less time. They don't have time to
sit and talk to patients. Are we undermining the relationship in a
way that will make patients less adherent and more likely to get
sick and wind up in the hospital?''
</P>
<P>
   Medications that are easy to use can go a long way toward
getting people to follow their doctors' orders. Pills like Accolate
and Singulaire, which help to ease inflammation and are not
steroids, are becoming popular with patients.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have evidence that they control bad asthma as well as
the steroids,'' Bender said. ``But from the evidence so far,
patients are more willing to take them. We still have to come back
and ask the behavioral question: Is it better to give people the
best medicine, if they won't take it? Or should we give them a
medicine that is slightly less effective, but easier to take? It's
the question of the millennium.''
</P>
</TEXT>
