<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-18 16:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0706 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-SCI-ASTHMA-RESEARCH-A     10-18 1203
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-ASTHMA-RESEARCH-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW TREATMENTS FOR ASTHMA HAVE BEEN SLOW IN COMING 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Science Times)  
(lh) 
 By DAVID J. MORROW   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Despite the seemingly endless rise in asthma cases, new
treatments for the disease have been noticeably slow in coming.
</P>
<P>
   Within the past two years, for example, three new drugs have
been released to treat migraines, with another due in the spring.
But for asthma, which accounts for more pediatric hospitalizations
each year than any other illness, only two significant drugs were
approved in the same period, Accolate by Astra-Zeneca and Singulair
from Merck.
</P>
<P>
   These drugs, taken as pills, address the chief problem with
asthma treatments: the sheer inconvenience of juggling multiple
inhalers and other medications. But the new pills have not been
proved to be as effective as the inhaled corticosteroids that are
part of standard asthma treatment. Nor do they eliminate the need
to carry special inhaled drugs for asthma attacks.
</P>
<P>
   Asthma therefore offers an enormous potential bonanza for
pharmaceutical companies. Worldwide sales of asthma drugs should
top $7 billion this year and swell 74 percent by 2003 to $12.2
billion, according to Wall Street analysts. Analysts say that any
new treatment that eliminates the need for multiple inhalers could
easily reap more than $2 billion in annual sales.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, asthma is the only disease category we cover where
the death rate is rising,'' said Ian Sanderson, a managing director
at S.G. Cowen Securities. ``That proves that the disease is not
being treated properly.''
</P>
<P>
   Mamie Bryan, for one, sees room for improvement. Ms. Bryan, a
music teacher in Bellview, Neb., gets up half an hour earlier than
she normally would each day just to supervise her children's asthma
treatments. Her three children, ages 9 to 13, take 10 medications
among them, including six inhalers and four types of pills. Even
with insurance, her pharmacy bill is more than $1,500 each year.
</P>
<P>
   ``For my younger children, this is far too much medication for
them to deal with,'' Ms. Bryan said. ``It would be better if the
medication were more convenient to take. Most of this isn't put
this in your mouth and swallow.''
</P>
<P>
   Doctors and health officials say advances in medications have
been hindered by the complexity of the disease, as well as the
legacy of misconceptions about it. In a theory that now seems
laughable, scientists once thought asthma was a psychological
illness. Only in recent decades have doctors started to recognize
it as a chronic inflammation of the lungs, which requires daily
treatment.
</P>
<P>
   ``The technology in the 1950s and the 1960s wasn't very good,''
said Dr. Linda Ford, an allergist in Omaha, Neb., and the past
president of the American Lung Association. ``We didn't know
anything about allergic antibodies.'' Now, she said, ``We know that
90 percent of asthma is allergic by nature.''
</P>
<P>
   These discoveries have led to more effective asthma drugs, like
the inhaled corticosteroids that are ``still the gold standard in
asthma treatment,'' Dr. Ford said. Since 1991, the National
Institutes of Health has stressed their use to reduce inflammation
in the lungs.
</P>
<P>
   But the inhaled steroids are cumbersome and carry potential side
effects. Other new drugs have limited benefits. The national
institutes recently recommended that long-acting drugs called beta
agonists (like Serevent by Glaxo-Wellcome or Foradil by Novartis)
be given along with inhaled steroids to help prevent a sudden
narrowing of the airways known as a bronchospasm. But if used
alone, some doctors warn, the beta agonists can prevent someone
from realizing his condition is deteriorating.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of these drugs, like inhaled steroids, work well with
asthma,'' said Dr. Michael McDermott, the attending physician for
adult emergency services at Cook County Hospital in Chicago. ``But
with a lot of these drugs, people are just casting about with
chemicals. Until there's a real breakthrough, most of the new
treatments are just hustles for the stock market.''
</P>
<P>
   The drugs that have caused the most excitement in recent years
are Accolate and Singulair, part of a new class of drugs called
leukotriene modifiers. Regarded by some scientists as breakthrough
therapies, these drugs block leukotrienes, chemicals that can
trigger asthma attacks.
</P>
<P>
   When Acculate and Singulair were introduced, doctors and drug
industry analysts believed they would become popular alternatives
to inhaled corticosteroids. As pills, Acculate and Singulair can
easily be swallowed, and Singulair even comes as a chewable tablet
for children.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the health institutes give these pills only limited
support. The leukotriene modifiers can be considered as an
alternative therapy to low doses of inhaled corticosteroids in mild
asthma cases, NIH guidelines say, adding that more studies are
needed ``to establish their roles in asthma therapy.''
</P>
<P>
   Astra-Zeneca and Merck have promoted their asthma medications
aggressively, with big dividends. Singulair's sales are projected
to swell 320 percent from some $500 million this year to $2.1
billion in 2003, according to S.G. Cowen.
</P>
<P>
   Several other new drugs are expected to be very popular with
asthma sufferers. Glaxo-Wellcome filed a new drug application in
March for Advair Diskus, an inhaler that combines a long-acting
bronchodilator with a corticosteroid. Company officials say the
Advair Diskus, which is still awaiting approval, would simplify the
asthma drug regimen for patients who use numerous inhalers.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers also have hopes for several drugs in the early
stages of development. SmithKline Beecham is experimenting with a
drug that inhibits phosphodiesterase 4, an enzyme known to cause
inflammation. The company's drug, Ariflo, is in early stages of
testing for asthma and chronic obstructive pulmonary disease.
</P>
<P>
   Other companies are testing inhaled medications that they hope
will eliminate the need for daily doses of inhaled steroids.
Immunex Corp. of Seattle is developing Nuvance, a compound that
blocks interleukin-4, a chemical that is released as part of the
body's normal immune response and is present at high levels in the
lungs of people with asthma. Blocking interleukin-4, researchers
theorize, will reduce asthma symptoms. If Nuvance eventually wins
approval, the company said, it will be given as an inhaler used
only once a week.
</P>
<P>
   The interleukin blockers are not expected to reach the market
for several more years, but doctors hope that a similar compound,
E25, may be introduced in 2001. Developed by Novartis and
Genentech, E25 neutralizes a chemical that is a cause of asthma.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, we're testing the drug on severe and moderate
asthma patients,'' said Jorg Reinhardt, head of pharmaceutical
development for Novartis. ``People will use it once or twice per
month, but they may have to still use an inhaled steroid or beta
agonist.''
</P>
<P>
   Given that new asthma treatments are so infrequent, it should
come as no shock that E25 would sell at top dollar. Analysts
estimate that a one-year treatment of the drug will cost around
$10,000, making it one of the most expensive medicines available.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
