 AM-PAGE1-CONSIDER-NYT 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are considering for
the Page 1 of Tuesday, Oct. 19. The N.Y. Times News Service night
supervisor is Pat Ryan; phone: (888) 346-9867; e-mail:
patryan(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   PAKISTAN-ASSESS (New Delhi, India) _ News Analysis: Pakistan's
new military ruler is talking about reform, but every previous
military dictatorship has left the country and its democratic
institutions in worse shape than ever. Can this guy deliver on his
promises? By Celia W. Dugger.
</P>
<P>
   COLOMBIA-REFUGEES (Cucuta) _ As Colombia's longstanding civil
conflict grows, the fighting is inflicting a huge social crisis on
a country that is already deeply fractured. Hundreds of thousands
of civilians, the vast majority of them peasants caught in the
crossfire between Marxist guerrillas and the right-wing
paramilitary forces that seek to wipe them out, are being forcibly
uprooted and turned into fearful, persecuted migrants. By Larry
Rohter.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``w'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-MEDICARE (Washington) _ In a break from three decades of
Medicare policy, the Clinton administration asked Congress on
Monday to steer Medicare patients to certain doctors and hospitals
that offer discounts on the price of care they provide to people
who are elderly or disabled. By Robert Pear.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICS
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``p'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   WEB-CAMPAIGNING (Undated) _ The modern campaign headquarters is
no longer a rented storefront decorated with bumper stickers,
bunting and empty soda cans. It is open any hour of the day or
night. And it isn't a place at all, just an address starting with
www. If in 1996 a candidate could prove hipness simply by posting
an electronic version of a campaign brochure on the World Wide Web,
White House hopefuls for 2000 are learning to use their Internet
sites to raise money and rally troops. The Web page is the new
whistle stop, a way for candidates to bring their messages to more
people a day than they can reach on the campaign trail. By Tina
Kelley.
</P>
<P>
   FINANCIAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``f'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   NISSAN-CUTBACK (Tokyo) _ The Nissan Motor Co. has stunned Japan
and the global automotive industry with details of an unprecedented
overhaul plan that makes cuts far deeper than had been expected at
the No. 3 Japanese auto maker and will reverberate throughout the
economy. Under the plan, designed by the company's aggressive new
chief operating officer, Carlos Ghosn, Nissan will close three
plants, eliminate 21,000 jobs, halve its supplier base, close 10
percent of dealerships and return to profitability in the next
fiscal year, which will start April 1. By Stephanie Strom.
</P>
<P>
   SCIENCE
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-ASTHMA (Undated) _ For most people with asthma, the proper
use of medication, education and self-management can go a long way
to keeping them out of the emergency room functioning at home,
school or work, experts say. But sadly, many patients with the
diseases fail to adhere to the regimen and many others simply do
not understand it. By Denise Grady.
</P>
<P>
   With photo and graphic.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-BRAIN-MORALS (Undated) _ Scientists have identified rare
cases in which injuries to the brain, in infancy, prevented people
from learning normal rules of social and moral behavior during
childhood and adolescence. When the infants reached adulthood, they
showed no remorse, guilt for their rotten behavior and seem
destined to never get along in social situations. The finding
raises important questions about the biological origins of human
empathy and is likely fodder for creative defense attorneys who may
argue that clients who have committed antisocial acts are not
responsible for their behavior because a brain injury prevented
their normal socialization. By Sandra Blakeslee.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' code)
</P>
<P>
   BBA-YANKS-BOSOX (Boston) _ Yankees-Red Sox, Game 5, 8:17 p.m.
EDT start at Fenway Park. By Buster Olney.
</P>
