<HEADLINE>
`FIGHTING SPIRIT' IS LITTLE HELP IN CANCER FIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
  (The Science Times) 
(th) 
 By ERICA GOODE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Optimism and a fighting attitude may help breast cancer patients
cope with their illnesses, but positive thinking is unlikely to
increase the chances of survival, according to a study by British
researchers.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, persistent hopelessness may lower a woman's
chances of survival.
</P>
<P>
   The new study, which appeared in the Oct. 16 issue of The
Lancet, an international medical journal, found that of the women
who agreed with statements like ``I feel like giving up,'' only 58
percent were alive or in remission five years later, compared with
72 percent who did not report feeling hopeless.
</P>
<P>
   The notion that a ``fighting spirit'' helps cancer patients
survive longer, the researchers noted, ``has been embraced with
enthusiasm, especially by practitioners of alternative therapies.''
</P>
<P>
   But the results, they continued, suggest that ``such claims
should be far more cautious and circumspect.''
</P>
<P>
   A small number of women who scored high on a scale measuring
clinical depression also had an increased risk of dying within five
years, the study said.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Margaret Watson, a consultant clinical psychologist at the
Royal Marsden Hospital in Sutton, England, and the lead author of
the report, said that because a positive attitude did not seem to
prolong survival, she hoped the findings took away ``any burden of
guilt'' for women who had ``difficulty feeling positive all the
time.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it is important for women to feel that they should go
on fighting,'' Dr. Watson said, ``but many women who have fought
will very likely have times when they don't feel like it.''
</P>
<P>
   The results indicate that doctors need to watch for signs of
depression and hopelessness in cancer patients and offer treatment,
Dr. Watson added.
</P>
<P>
   ``The message is that something can be done about this,'' she
said. ``Doctors can be more rigorous in trying to diagnose these
emotions in their patients, and in so doing improve their quality
of life and maybe their quantity of life, as well.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Watson and her colleagues followed 578 women with
early-stage breast cancer over a five-year period. At the end of
five years, 50 of the women had suffered a relapse and 133 had
died. The remaining 395 women remained in remission.
</P>
<P>
   Women in the study who showed a ``fighting spirit,'' as measured
by a frequently used questionnaire called the ``Mental Adjustment
to Cancer'' scale, showed no significant difference in survival
rates.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Watson said the study, one of the largest to examine the
effect of psychological state on disease outcome, was carefully
designed ``to be credible to the cancer doctors, so it wouldn't
easily be dismissed.''
</P>
<P>
   The study also cast doubt on the idea that some people are more
likely to die of cancer because they suppress negative emotions
like anger and hostility.
</P>
<P>
   Women in the study who showed a high degree of emotional
control, indicating on questionnaires that they had trouble venting
anger or other negative emotions, were no more likely than other
patients to die or suffer a relapse within the five years.
</P>
</TEXT>
