<SLUG> BC-SCI-WATCH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLASTICS FROM PLANTS  
 FROGGY'S SEX APPEAL  
 SPIDER'S SUN COMPASS 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By HENRY FOUNTAIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When it comes to the future, plastics researchers want to say
one word to you: Plants.
</P>
<P>
   In a complex feat of genetic engineering, scientists at the
Monsanto Co. have developed a plastic-producing plant, one that may
some day help reduce the plastics industry's heavy reliance on
petroleum.
</P>
<P>
   The plastic is a biodegradable one, a member of a family of
compounds called PHAs. It has long been known that PHAs are
produced by certain forms of bacteria from glucose, and some
companies have sought to develop bacterial production of these
plastics on an industrial scale. They have been deterred by high
costs.
</P>
<P>
   The Monsanto scientists took the approach that since plants are
low-cost producers of natural fibers, perhaps they could also be
low-cost producers of plastic, getting the necessary carbon not
from expensive glucose but from the atmosphere. The researchers,
who described their work in the journal Nature Biotechnology, set
about trying to insert bacterial genes into two types of plants,
rape and thale cress.
</P>
<P>
   Most genetic engineering projects involve one gene; the Monsanto
work eventually involved four, and the alteration of two metabolic
pathways, for the synthesis of fatty acids and amino acids. The
results were plants that produced significant quantities of a type
of PHA called PHBV. But much work remains before such a process
could become commercially viable.
</P>
<P>
   ---
</P>
<P>
   Scientists in Australia have revealed more secrets behind the
sex lives of amphibians, discovering the first frog pheromone.
</P>
<P>
   Pheromones are chemical signals secreted by one member of a
species that induce a behavioral response in another. With sex
pheromones, which have been found in many species, the behavioral
response is this: the opposite sex is driven wild.
</P>
<P>
   The Australian scientists, from the University of Adelaide, used
very sensitive chromatographic and spectroscopic techniques to
analyze water in which they kept specimens of a type of tree frog,
Litoria splendida.
</P>
<P>
   They noticed one compound that showed up only in the male frogs'
water, secreted from glands in the head. This compound, which they
gave the wonderful name splendipherin, is produced in amounts that
are 10 times as great in breeding season as at other times of the
year.
</P>
<P>
   To test whether the chemical was a pheromone, the researchers
applied a small amount to a gauze pad and put it in the water about
three feet from a female. The results were startling: within 20
seconds, the female frog became more alert, then sat on the pad and
refused to budge.
</P>
<P>
   ---
</P>
<P>
   Sun compasses, which use polarized light as a direction finder,
are not unknown in the natural world. Some bees and ants have them,
though they are usually just specialized areas of the eye that is
otherwise used for sight.
</P>
<P>
   A team of scientists led by a Swedish zoologist has now
discovered a different kind of sun compass, in a spider. Like a
fashion model with her sunglasses pushed up onto her hair, the
spider, Drassodes cupreus, has a secondary pair of eyes on top of
its head that act as filters to determine the degree of
polarization.
</P>
<P>
   The secondary eyes are oriented roughly at right angles to each
other. Light that is polarized in one direction _ that is, the
light waves are vibrating in the same plane _ is reflected strongly
by a mirrorlike structure in the eye, while light whose plane of
polarization is rotated by 90 degrees is barely reflected at all.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers, writing in the journal Nature, suggest that the
spider compares signals from the eyes to determine the degree of
polarization of the light, and thus the position of the sun.
</P>
<P>
   The spiders' behavior seems to confirm that they use this system
to navigate. They are active mainly at dusk, when sunlight is
polarized largely in one direction, which makes it easier for the
spiders to pick up polarization cues.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
