<SLUG> BC-SCI-AIDS-MORNING-AFTER-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EMERGENCY TREATMENT TO STOP AIDS VIRUS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Mass., R.I., N.Y.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036.) 
 (The Science Times)  
(lh) 
 By DAVID FRANCE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Frustrated by the continued spread of HIV, a growing
number of AIDS doctors are trying out an experimental treatment: an
application of drugs meant to abort infection in a person who was
recently exposed to the virus through unsafe sex.
</P>
<P>
   Called post-exposure prophylaxis, or PEP, the emergency
treatment incorporates the same powerful, toxic drugs commonly
given to people with AIDS. Only in this case, the drug regimen is
initiated in the hours after suspected exposure, and months before
a blood test can verify infection.
</P>
<P>
   There is no proof that the treatment works, and few insurance
companies are likely to cover the cost, around $2,500 including 30
days of drugs, lab tests and doctors' visits. But on the basis of
successful experiments on animals and studies of transmission from
mother to child, many clinicians think it is at least plausible.
</P>
<P>
   ``The body of evidence now available provides pretty solid
indirect evidence that this works in preventing infection,'' said
Dr. David Henderson, a deputy director at the Warren G. Magnuson
Clinical Care Center, part of the National Institutes of Health, in
Bethesda, Md.
</P>
<P>
   The treatment seeks to attack the virus after it attaches to a
lymph cell but before it has a chance to burrow into the nucleus
and begin reproducing, within two to three days. The aim is to
contain and eradicate the viral invasion before it can embark on
its destructive path through the body. For this reason, the
clinicians say, prompt treatment is essential. Most clinics aim to
treat in the first few hours of a suspected exposure, and 72 hours
is considered the absolute latest.
</P>
<P>
   Round-the-clock PEP clinics have proliferated in the past 18
months, with public or nonprofit ones opening in Los Angeles, San
Francisco, Boston and Providence, R.I. Patients can call at any
hour after an exposure, and be connected to a screening counselor _
who weeds out people with improbable risk behavior, like kissing _
and a doctor and all-night drugstore, if necessary.
</P>
<P>
   Next month in New York City, Dr. Bernard Salick plans to begin a
pilot PEP program at his for-profit clinic in New York City, the
first one based at a private practice. Even before opening, the
demand is astounding.
</P>
<P>
   ``The number of calls we get is beyond belief,'' said Dr.
Gabriel Torres, a medical director at the practice who has been
trying the treatment on his own patients. ``I had a guy calling me
on day 2 from Albany who was driving at 90 miles an hour to get to
me in time. I kept saying, `Just pay attention to the road!'''
</P>
<P>
   It will take thousands more cases and many more years before any
conclusions can be drawn about how well, or even whether, the
method works.
</P>
<P>
   ``No matter how effective these medications are in a preventive
mode,'' said Dr. Michelle Roland, director of San Francisco General
Hospital's Positive Health Program, ``they are never going to be
100 percent effective.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, early indications are favorable. In San Francisco, a
city-run PEP clinic treats an average of one new patient a day, and
a joint study by the city and San Francisco General Hospital found
no HIV transmission among 436 sexually active patients who had
received the treatment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I certainly believe there is some efficacy to this, or I
wouldn't do it,'' said Dr. Joshua Bamberger, the medical director
for special projects at the San Francisco Department of Public
Health.
</P>
<P>
   The federal Centers for Disease Control and Prevention said last
year that it ``cannot definitively recommend for or against'' the
treatment, citing a lack of research.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very interesting area that we're all watching very
closely,'' said Dr. Robert Janssen, the deputy director of the
centers' Division of HIV/AIDS Prevention, Surveillance and
Epidemiology. This summer, the centers established a national
registry for doctors to report their PEP experiences. It will be
years before the data can be analyzed, Janssen said.
</P>
<P>
   The standard PEP regimen is similar to the one used for a decade
whenever a health care worker is accidentally exposed to infected
blood or needles. It used two antiretroviral drugs, AZT and 3TC,
for seven to 30 days, depending on how early the treatment is
started. Many doctors also add one of the powerful new class of
anti-HIV drugs called non-nucleoside reverse transcriptase
inhibitors, like Sustiva or navirapine.
</P>
<P>
   Advocates are encouraged by successes in blocking HIV in other
settings. Transmission rates from mother to child have been reduced
to less than 5 percent from 25 percent with prophylactic
treatments. Retrospective studies of the thousands of health care
workers who have taken PEP suggest that such workplace treatments
are 81 percent effective in thwarting infections.
</P>
<P>
   Extrapolating from these findings, the New York state Department
of Health last year recommended that PEP be routinely prescribed in
emergency rooms to rape victims whose assailants cannot be found.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   But until recently, the treatment was not widely available to
people who fell into more typical risk categories: those who
engaged in unprotected intercourse with a partner known or
suspected to be HIV-positive, whether through carelessness or
condom error. These lapses are especially dangerous among gay men
in cities like New York and San Francisco, where one-third of them
harbor the virus.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the overwhelming majority of people getting PEP treatment
were never infected to begin with. HIV is not easily transmitted;
fewer than 1 percent of those exposed to the virus through rectal
or vaginal contact will become infected, and the numbers are
smaller for oral or penile contact.
</P>
<P>
   Side effects can be severe in the short term, including nausea,
headaches and hallucinations affecting three-quarters of patients,
the health institutes report. Long-term effects are believed to be
minor, as long as the drugs are taken for short periods.
</P>
<P>
   Public health experts have raised some concern about PEP, which
they fear may be misconstrued as something of a morning-after
alternative, a pharmacological substitute for latex condoms and
good sense.
</P>
<P>
   Especially troublesome, they say, is the prospect that its
availability may undermine a commitment to proven prevention
methods like abstinence, needle-cleaning, and safer sex. If so, it
risks causing more transmissions than it is averting.
</P>
<P>
   So far, there is little evidence that this is happening. The San
Francisco study found that 56 patients returned within a year for
another round of PEP. But Bamberger said it was clear in follow-up
interviews that their behavior had not altered because of the
availability of medication.
</P>
<P>
   Still, this fear has kept most PEP clinics from promoting their
services too widely, their directors say. Boston's Fenway Community
Health Center has treated 74 PEP patients, mostly gay men, in the
past year and a half, but has refused to advertise the program in
the community for fear of sending the wrong message.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're happy to offer the information to people who ask, but we
don't want to do social marketing,'' said Fenway's medical research
director, Dr. Ken Mayer. ``We are very concerned about the specter
of some people using lots of medication and knowingly exposing
themselves to HIV. If you rely on it as the magic bullet, a
chemical condom, people are going to get burned.''
</P>
<P>
   Each PEP clinic also provides extensive counseling to patients,
capitalizing on what Mayer called an ``educable moment.
</P>
<P>
   The PEP procedure itself, with its toxic side effects, may also
help to underscore the need to return to vigilant behavior, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   That was the case with Dan Feldman, 30, a neuropsychology fellow
at the Weill Medical College of Cornell University, in New York.
Just 36 hours after he had reason to believe he had been exposed to
HIV, his doctor put him on a 30-day PEP course.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a good reinforcer for staying with safe sex,''
Feldman said. ``I kept thinking, `Thank God I'm just doing it for
30 days and not the rest of my life.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
