<HEADLINE>
LITTLE FEAT STILL TRYING TO FILL THE LARGE SHOES OF LOWELL GEORGE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVE FERMAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   On a cold night in December 1978, Little Feat played Will Rogers
Auditorium in Fort Worth, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   And played. And played. One hour, two. More. Encores.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, the lights came up and the roadies began unplugging the
amps, the two universal signals for ``go home now _ show's over.''
</P>
<P>
   Only, we wouldn't go home. We cheered and we cheered, and after
a long, long time the roadies began plugging the amps back in. The
lights came back down, a huge cheer went up, and a large man in
white overalls walked up to the mike.
</P>
<P>
   ``You people are crazy,'' said Lowell George, and the band lit
into another half-hour or so of funky rock 'n' roll. It is one of
the sweetest rock 'n' roll memories I have.
</P>
<P>
   Within a few months, on June 29, 1979, George (the Feat's
founder and best guitarist, vocalist and songwriter) would be dead
in an Arlington, Va., hotel room. He was only 34, he was on his
first solo tour, in support of his first solo LP, ``Thanks, I'll
Eat It Here,'' and he died of a heart attack, at least partially
brought on by his weight and fondness for drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Lowell George got crazy, did too much of everything, played a
mean slide guitar, wrote wonderfully weird _ and sometimes
wonderfully straightforward _ songs, and left us too soon.
</P>
<P>
   And now, 20 years later, he's often overlooked altogether as one
of America's greatest rock musicians.
</P>
<P>
   George grew up in California, played oboe and saxophone on Frank
Sinatra records, started a folk-rock group called The Factory in
1965, joined Frank Zappa's Mothers of Invention _ you can hear him
on Zappa's 1970 album ``Weasels Ripped My Flesh'' _ and formed the
Feat in 1970.
</P>
<P>
   It was, then, his band: He was the group's main songwriter and
lead singer, and only guitarist; here, too, he has been overlooked.
When people think of great slide players, guys like Duane Allman
and Johnny Winter come to mind: George wasn't as flashy, but he had
a touch and an ability to say a whole lot in a little space.
</P>
<P>
   And he shaped the band as a true American hybrid, combining New
Orleans funk, rock 'n' roll, soul and country into something that
was almost magical _ at least on their finest LPs, 1972's ``Sailin'
Shoes'' and '73's ``Dixie Chicken''; the title track of the latter
gave the band an enduring rock-radio staple. They were, for a while
there, a perfect rock 'n' roll band _ funny, musically thrilling,
and not quite popular enough to be truly mainstream, a cult act in
the best sense of the word. One could certainly hear touches of
Zappa _ and Captain Beefheart _ but George never sounded like
either of them.
</P>
<P>
   Within just two years, though, there were problems: Guitarist
Paul Barrere and keyboardist Bill Payne began taking the band in a
jazzier (and far less satisfying) direction; George wrote only one
song for 1977's ``Time Loves a Hero.'' And by the next year, the
rift was even more obvious. Barrere and Payne wanted to be Weather
Report (or something) and there were long stretches at the Fort
Worth show where George wasn't even onstage.
</P>
<P>
   It was a sad end; the band broke up in the spring of '79, George
went out on the road, and died after a sold-out solo performance in
Washington, D.C., always a Feat stronghold.
</P>
<P>
   There was talk, at the time, of his re-forming the band without
Payne and Barrere, and taking full control again. What happened
instead was far sadder: Payne and Barrere re-formed the group in
1988. And, wonder of wonders, the sound this time was an imitation
of the funky good-time rock 'n' roll of the George-led band; hey,
they knew what the fans wanted, even if they didn't used to want to
give it to them.
</P>
<P>
   And far fewer fans want it these days. The Feat ambles on, a
decent oldies act but utterly rudderless, banking on the past
glories (and, really, the sound that George was largely responsible
for) and playing clubs, such as Fort Worth's Caravan of Dreams.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, George's legacy slips into the shadows just a little
bit more every year. If you haven't ever heard ``Sailin' Shoes''
and ``Dixie Chicken,'' go get them. Two other good bets are the
live ``Waiting for Columbus'' and the
hits-and-rarities-and-live-versions collection ``Hoy-Hoy!'' But
whatever you get first _ or go back and listen to again _ don't
forget this man.
</P>
<P>
   (Dave Ferman is pop music critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Contact him at dfer(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
