<SLUG> BC-TV-PERKINS-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHICH NEW SHOWS WILL SEE SWEEPS AND WHICH WILL GET THE BROOM?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEN PARISH PERKINS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Which network series will live and which will die is being
decided right about now, four weeks into a new season that's hardly
the creative apocalypse we initially warned you about. Of course,
it's not the richly textured season that the network executives and
producers so breathlessly promised, either. But is it ever?
</P>
<P>
   As the networks implement strategy in preparation for the
November sweeps, it's easy to determine what's going well, what's
going wrong, and what needs more time to find an audience. Because
November is so economically crucial, shows that disappear next
month are considered to be in trouble.
</P>
<P>
   But good news first. ``Third Watch,'' NBC's frenetic ``ER'' in
the streets, is showing glimpses of staying power, as is the
network's political drama ``West Wing'' and its ``Law &AMP; Order''
spinoff, ``Law &AMP; Order: Special Victims Unit.'' Also doing well:
the female-driven law show ``Family Law,'' starring Kathleen
Quinlan and airing Mondays on CBS.
</P>
<P>
   But so far, it's the CBS drama ``Judging Amy,'' with Amy
Brenneman as a rookie judge, that has shown the most promise.
Airing at 9 p.m. Tuesdays, the series, which has distinguished
itself with clever writing, high ideals and a solid supporting cast
led by Tyne Daly, attracted a little over 16 million viewers and
ranked No. 12 in last week's Nielsens. And all without much
critical buzz.
</P>
<P>
   It built viewership over its lead-in, ``60 Minutes II,'' and
clobbered ``Once and Again,'' the ABC romantic drama that received
good reviews and whose promos alone generated water-cooler
word-of-mouth.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, ``Judging Amy'' is the second-highest-rated new show
behind NBC's dismally reviewed ``Stark Raving Mad,'' the Neil
Patrick Harris sitcom that seems to owe its viewership to its
Thursday-night time slot.
</P>
<P>
   ``Judging Amy'' may be pulling away from ``Once and Again,'' but
that drama, about love developing between a pair of 40-ish
divorcees, is in no danger of getting booted. Some watchers I've
talked with consider Sela Ward's Lily a bit too upbeat and perfect
to be a divorcee eight months removed. Those viewers have bailed,
calling it ``unrealistic.'' (I have to disagree with this on a
couple levels: People react to divorce in differing ways, and the
ex-wife of Lily's new beau is emotionally unstable enough to
balance the scales.)
</P>
<P>
   ABC is so pleased with ``Once and Again's'' ratings (it placed
27th last week) that it may leave the series in its Tuesday-night
spot and find another place for permanent tenant ``NYPD Blue.''
</P>
<P>
   This has reportedly infuriated ``Blue'' creator and executive
producer Steven Bochco. ABC thinks audiences will follow the show.
I'm not so sure.
</P>
<P>
   ``NYPD Blue'' was somewhat rejuvenated with the exchange of Rick
Schroder for Jimmy Smits, but its story-line redundancy is a sure
sign of old age. And star director Paris Barclay is now off
preparing the new ``City of Angels'' for a midseason launch on CBS.
I think a different night would kill ``Blue'' within two seasons,
tops.
</P>
<P>
   But, in TV, this is a time for heightened emotions. Surely the
cast members of ``Manchester Prep,'' the TV version of the teen
film ``Cruel Intentions,'' were shocked when their show got canned
before it aired. And what's Mike O'Malley thinking, now that his
second consecutive show (remember ``Life With Roger''?) has bitten
the dust? NBC axed ``The Mike O'Malley Show'' after two episodes.
</P>
<P>
   Fox's ``Get Real,'' which offered a pilot I thoroughly enjoyed
(although my colleagues shook their heads in amazement), has
staggered out the gate. Same with Chris Carter's dark drama,
``Harsh Realm.'' Just as wobbly: ``Cold Feet'' on NBC, ``Work With
Me'' on CBS, ``Wasteland'' and ``Oh Grow Up'' on ABC, and ``Shasta
McNasty'' on UPN.
</P>
<P>
   And it has been shocking to see viewers hightail it away from
``Action.'' Critics adore the Fox sitcom, about a film producer
willing to sell his soul for success, but many viewers have found
it ``revolting,'' as one reader told me. Fox will shelve the series
during November, bringing it back Dec. 2.
</P>
<P>
   And what about David E. Kelley's experimental ``Ally''? It
doesn't look good. What is essentially a well-edited clip show has
garnered so little interest, you have to wonder whether Fox
research showing that viewers wanted to see more of Calista
Flockhart meant they just wanted her to gain some weight.
</P>
<P>
   With new episodes of ``Ally McBeal'' returning as soon as this
baseball mess is over, the most interesting aspect of the two
series will be comparing the tiny Ally and the REALLY tiny Ally.
</P>
<P>
   Now that's a series I'd watch.
</P>
<P>
   (Ken Parish Perkins is TV critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Contact him at kperkins(at)star-telegram.com. Visit
the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
