<HEADLINE>
FAT'S IN THE FIRE, ONCE A DIET BEGINS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MONICA ANDERSON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Americans are overweight. We eat too much junk food and exercise
too little.
</P>
<P>
   Our kids are overweight, too. Our pets are too fat and the
problem is getting worse with every generation. At least, that's
what the reporter said the other night. He went on and on about it.
He was sort of skinny, though, and you know I got the impression
that he thought the rest of us just want to be fat.
</P>
<P>
   But he's probably allergic to Twinkies and chocolate, so he
wouldn't understand our problem anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Well, I got to thinking about what he said as I sat eating a
large bag of chips while I waited for my pork ribs to baste. You
know, he's right. We are getting a little big in the britches.
Maybe I do need to start exercising every day and laying off the
Kool-Aid a bit. OK, maybe not every day because I just don't do
Mondays, but I could exercise several days each week if I put my
mind to it.
</P>
<P>
   I'm going to start my new exercise plan right after the New Year
begins. If all this Y2K doomsday stuff is correct, there is no
point to me suffering for the last few months of civilization as we
know it. I might as well enjoy these last moments.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, I will go ahead with my new diet plan. I've read
several books on the subject and I looked at the labels on a bunch
of diet pills. I compiled all the information and I've come up with
a great new four-day diet plan that's guaranteed to help you lose
weight without emptying your wallet.
</P>
<P>
   Day 1: You can have four small, nutritious meals over the course
of the day or you can have a chocolate bar for breakfast. You must
eat the chocolate before 10 a.m. or you will gain weight.
</P>
<P>
   Day 2: You have a choice between a large bowl of orange rinds
for breakfast followed by a delicious dish of grape skins for lunch
and dinner OR you can jog to the grocery store and eat a pint of
Ben &AMP; Jerry's ice cream as you walk home.
</P>
<P>
   Day 3: How about a delicious protein shake for breakfast and
lunch followed by a sensible dinner? Or you can drink 12 glasses of
water and eat a ribeye steak with a plain baked potato.
</P>
<P>
   Day 4: You've suffered enough. Have some pizza, but don't eat
all of the crust. Wash it all down with a glass of prune juice.
</P>
<P>
   Day 5: Time to weigh! Go to the bathroom, remove everything,
floss and shave twice. Sit in a hot place and perspire for two
hours, then step on the scale.
</P>
<P>
   Remember to deduct 10 pounds for stress and tension. (Hey,
burdens weigh you down.) Congratulations, you're well on your way
to leanville.
</P>
<P>
   This is a surefire, can't-miss diet plan. I tried it myself and,
incredibly, I lost 10 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   Who needs diet pills when you've got good old American ingenuity
to rely on?
</P>
<P>
   (Monica Frazier Anderson is an Arlington, Texas, wife, mother
and dentist. Write in care of the Arlington Star-Telegram at 1111
W. Abram St., Arlington, TX 76013. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
