<HEADER>
A0736 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a BC-TIGUAS-GAMBLING-2000(     10-18 0852
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TIGUAS-GAMBLING-2000(2TAKES)-TEX </SLUG>
 
TIGUA INDiANS RAKING IN GAMBLING BUCKS 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BARRY SHLACHTER 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   EL PASO, Texas _ In what was once a crumbling barrio on the edge
of El Paso, a small band of American Indians has defied the state
of Texas by erecting a 24-hour money machine called the Speaking
Rock Casino.
</P>
<P>
   The glittering gaming house, made of fake adobe and decorated
with Pueblo Indian motifs, reportedly brings in about $60 million
per year. It is lifting the tribe of 1,200 Tiguas out of poverty
while making it a political force.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were the poorest of the poor,'' said Elias Torrez, 40, who
was the tribe's governor when the casino opened in 1994, a year
after the Tiguas began their high-stakes bingo games. ``Now we have
everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Aside from bringing material gains, Speaking Rock's success has
instilled a new pride among Tiguas, some of whom had hidden their
Indian heritage in the face of prejudice. A Franciscan friar at the
neighboring Our Lady of Mt. Carmel Church said elders remember
being stoned while performing traditional dances on the feast of
St. Anthony.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were treated with a lot of disrespect,'' said Jesus Padilla
Sr., 49, tribal sheriff of what is formally known as the Ysleta del
Sur Pueblo tribe. ``We didn't have shoes; we bathed in the canal.''
</P>
<P>
   Tomas Silvas, 61, another member of the tribal council, recalled
bitterly: ``People would say, `Here comes this dirty Indian.' Now
everyone wants to be a Tigua.''
</P>
<P>
   And it pays to be one.
</P>
<P>
   In December, each Tigua received a payment of $15,000, up from
$8,000 the year before. This year's share of casino profits has not
been set.
</P>
<P>
   Filbert Candelaria, 37, the tribe's acting governor, said of
last year's payout: ``Some people used it wisely. Others spent like
crazy, buying cars and trucks.''
</P>
<P>
   He noted that stockbrokers and bankers were on hand to give
investment advice when the checks were distributed.
</P>
<P>
   Casino earnings have also financed the tribe's purchase of the
local Mobil lubricant distributor, a separate fuel distributorship,
a chain of Running Bear convenience stores and a 68,000-acre spread
near Valentine valued at $6 million. The tribe uses the land for
recreation and plans to start a dude ranch there for American and
European tourists.
</P>
<P>
   The first of a chain of tribe-owned fast-lube outlets will open
this winter. Also planned are a shopping center, a hotel, a
spring-water bottling facility and a wind-powered generating plant,
said Alberto Alvidrez, 27, a tribal council member.
</P>
<P>
   Such a turnaround in Tigua fortunes is all too rare.
</P>
<P>
   Tribe members are descendants of 305 Tiguas _ ``hostages''
according to their account, loyal subjects according to the Spanish
_ brought out of New Mexico after a Pueblo Indian revolt in 1682.
Whether captives or not, 100 Tigua braves did help colonial forces
recapture the lost territory a dozen years later. In 1751, Madrid
granted them 36 square miles in Ysleta, but the document was lost
by the time El Paso annexed the area in 1871.
</P>
<P>
   Tiguas served as scouts for the Texas Rangers and for the U.S.
Cavalry during the Apache campaigns. Legend has it that several
enemy scalps were incorporated into an old adobe wall in El Paso.
</P>
<P>
   Most Tiguas became farm laborers on the bottom rung of the
social ladder. By 1902, visiting scholar J. Walter Fewkes found
only a few Tiguas left and predicted their extinction. But an
effort aided, if not orchestrated, by attorney Tom Diamond finally
won the tribe federal recognition in 1968.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the Tiguas have never had it so good.
</P>
<P>
   They are given hiring preference at the casino and other tribal
enterprises, meaning that every member who wants a job has one,
Candelaria said. A dozen years ago, unemployment among tribe
members was above 40 percent, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Families have moved into 25 spacious, Santa Fe-style homes
complete with fireplaces and two-car garages on a sprawling tract
just outside El Paso; an additional 31 homes are nearing
completion. Although the largest is 3,500 square feet, the average
cost per house in the first phase was $80,000 and within guidelines
of the Department of Housing and Urban Development, which gave the
tribe a $1.92 million grant, said HUD spokesman Scott Hudman. The
site was improved with $4 million in casino earnings.
</P>
<P>
   The tribe's senior citizens receive meal tickets for the
casino's Wyngs restaurant. After school, children are bused to free
Tiwa language and culture classes at the tribe's new
library/education center. Later, they can tap a college scholarship
fund. Soon they'll have a recreation complex with a gymnasium and
swimming pool.
</P>
<P>
   The bingo games and Las Vegas-style gambling draw heavily from
El Paso and neighboring Juarez, Mexico, as well as from communities
in nearby New Mexico and from Midland-Odessa in West Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Seated at a salmon-pink bingo table one recent evening were
trucker Jerry Zenkner and his wife, Debbie, of Des Moines, Iowa.
They had just delivered a load of frozen pork bellies in Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   MORE nn
</P>
<P>
   Speaking Rock flourishes despite its legal dispute with the
state. Gov. George W. Bush contends that Texas law forbids the
casino's sea of 1,000 chiming and flashing slot machines, bounded
by tables where poker and a blackjack derivative called Tigua 21
are played.
</P>
<P>
   A lawsuit, filed in September by Texas Attorney General John
Cornyn, will determine the casino's future.
</P>
<P>
   ``They say it's illegal,'' said Tigua Police Chief Raul Takiashi
Candelaria, 34, the acting governor's younger brother. ``But it's
our sovereign right to do it, and we'll do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Federal law allows tribes to operate types of gambling that are
permitted in their state. The Tiguas contend that Texas'
legalization of the lottery opened the door for their gaming
enterprise.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas lottery is ``like a giant slot machine with 10,000
terminals,'' Diamond said last year. ``This is just a political
move. ... The tribe is of the opinion that this involves (Bush's)
running for president of the United States, and this is a
grandstand play to just look good to some religious
conservatives.''
</P>
<P>
   One possible snag is a 1987 federal law that, among other
things, specifically ruled out Tigua-sponsored gaming.
</P>
<P>
   ``So we broke a treaty. It's 200 to 1,'' the former governor,
Torrez, said dismissively, referring to Washington's spotty record
of adhering to Indian treaties.
</P>
<P>
   The tribe's sudden, casino-induced wealth has not come without a
price.
</P>
<P>
   Since November, 200 people have been removed from the tribal
roll on grounds that they were not at least one-eighth Tigua _
meaning that at least one great-grandparent was a full-blooded
Tigua.
</P>
<P>
   Disenfranchised members lost tribal benefits, subsidized housing
and jobs. Some said they were forced out at gunpoint after refusing
to heed eviction demands. One, Grace Vela, who ran the tribal
seniors' center, said she was led out of her home in handcuffs. The
tribe denies that guns were drawn or that handcuffs were used.
</P>
<P>
   Victims blame greed and say it's tearing the tribe apart.
</P>
<P>
   Tigua leaders are unapologetic and assert that non-Indians had
slipped onto the roll through corruption in the 1970s. Unity has
never been better, insisted the Tiguas' official spokesman, a
non-Tigua political and marketing consultant named Marc Schwartz.
</P>
<P>
   Negotiated cash settlements were subsequently given to those who
lost homes. Vela said she received $30,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you spoke out (against the expulsions), you'd be thrown out
with them or be punished,'' said a Tigua who supports the current
leadership but declined to be identified for fear of reprisals.
``It was sad. We had to look the other way when neighbors of 17
years were taken from their homes.''
</P>
<P>
   Last month, the tribe's dynamic governor, Vince Munoz, was
unceremoniously removed from office amid allegations of official
misconduct. But members said they were told that the leadership is
investigating questionable payments during Munoz's tenure. Munoz
did not return calls left on his home answering machine.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Tiguas are now an economic power and have been very
generous, helping people in need and donating $100,000 to restore
the church,'' said the Rev. Steve Stowe, a friar at the mission
church overlooking the casino. ``The downside is the evictions, the
infighting and lack of unity. All the way around, it's been a mixed
bag.''
</P>
<P>
   In March, the tribe paid $1 million for the return of its most
sacred object, a drum called the ``juanchido,'' after accusing a
former war captain, Marty Silvas, of stealing it. Silvas was
acquitted of theft charges, arguing that he had a lifelong right to
protect the drum. Silvas said an unknown party removed the drum
from a hiding place and sold it to the tribe through an attorney.
He and his brother, ex-tribal Gov. Manny Silvas, were ``banned''
for not returning the drum, then expelled for not having Tigua
blood, which they dispute.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had to punish people who disobey or (are) sacrilegious,''
explained Raul Candelaria, the police chief.
</P>
<P>
   Tribal leaders bristle at the criticism and at the attention the
expulsions have received in local news media.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why don't they check out the 40 to 50 evictions by the city of
El Paso every day for nonpayment of taxes?'' asked Candelaria, the
acting governor. ``Why the bad press? We are a thorn. El Paso is
controlled by little circles of rich people, and now they're
worried because we're asserting our rights.''
</P>
<P>
   The tribal leadership has scored some victories as well. The
Tiguas, for example, successfully campaigned against a plan by El
Paso Mayor Carlos Ramirez to locate a bus depot in a congested area
near the reservation.
</P>
<P>
   And their officials don't hide their eagerness to play politics.
The tribe hired former Texas lottery chief Lena Guerrero as its
lobbyist in Austin, the state capital, and in the past 18 months
has donated more than $200,000 to political candidates.
</P>
<P>
   ``But all losers,'' Filbert Candelaria said jokingly, referring
to the tribe's contributions to such star-crossed Democrats as
gubernatorial candidate Garry Mauro, who received $89,000, and
attorney general hopeful Jim Mattox, who got $46,000.
</P>
<P>
   About $36,000 went last spring to Ramirez's challenger, Barbara
Perez, prompting the mayor to make the Tiguas themselves an issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they call themselves a sovereign nation and don't want us
to get involved in their internal politics, then they shouldn't get
involved in ours,'' Ramirez fumed. During the campaign, the mayor
took out a full-page ad that declared in bold letters, ``SHAME ON
THE TIGUAS.'' It accused the Tiguas of trying to put Perez in
``their back pocket.''
</P>
<P>
   Tigua leaders seethe when anyone questions their right as U.S.
citizens to participate in politics.
</P>
<P>
   ``They want us to be illiterate Indians who don't speak up,''
said Candelaria, the police chief.
</P>
<P>
   Despite their bad luck at picking winners, the Tiguas say
they'll continue to exercise whatever political influence they can.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before, you had a tribe that might give $100 to a candidate,''
the acting governor said. ``Now we're able to finance a whole
campaign, and that scares the El Paso political establishment.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
