<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WRIGHT-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LABOR IS BACK _ AND IT'S BACKING GORE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
By JIM WRIGHT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Spending the past week in Los Angeles observing the national
AFL-CIO convention as it endorsed Al Gore for president convinced
me that organized labor has ended its three-decade decline in
political influence and may be on its way to being a major player
again _ not as strong as it once was, but stronger than it has
been.
</P>
<P>
   As in every organization devoted to human endeavor, there is a
tug of war between the idealistic and the pragmatic, the ideal and
the attainable. The hearts of some in labor's leadership _ thinking
of union colleagues whose jobs have been cut from under them by
corporate mergers and foreign competition from low-wage countries _
were torn. Should they, sensing Gore's apparent momentary
vulnerability, hold out for promises of an even more labor-friendly
executive stance? Or should they recognize the vice president's
lifelong attitude toward wage-earning America and reward his
history of instinctive friendship with loyalty in his moment of
need?
</P>
<P>
   When the chips were down, the membership chose the latter.
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing you have to say about labor,'' remarked Texas
businessman and lifelong political activist Bernard Rapoport, ``it
rewards its friends.''
</P>
<P>
   What can labor actually give at this point? Help in the
primaries, for starters.
</P>
<P>
   It can't begin to match the millions poured into George W.
Bush's coffers by wealthy contributors, some motivated by the Bush
campaign's impressive advance latch on money and its smell of
success. Labor can compensate for the GOP's overpowering money
advantage with only one ingredient: numbers. People. Quiet block
workers willing to ring doorbells and round up neighbors in
personal, one-on-one contacts.
</P>
<P>
   Given the easy access of conservatives to megabucks for TV
extravaganzas, it looks like a contest between the tortoise and the
hare. There are so many phone numbers to dial, so many blocks to
walk, so many individual conversations needed to counter commercial
television's ubiquitous impact with its costly and cleverly
scripted political spots.
</P>
<P>
   But don't forget: The 68 affiliated unions of the AFL-CIO have
13 million members. Counting families dependent on the
bread-earners' wages, they potentially speak for the interests of
one American in every five. And if organized labor's volunteers can
reach out to other unorganized wage-earners with a commonly
appealing message, their influence could be potent.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's David vs. Goliath,'' said one labor activist with whom I
talked, saying that Bush is looking for scores of ``fat cats,''
each of whom will raise tens of thousands of dollars for him.
``Obviously, we're not in that league. We'd have to find a million
people to contribute $100 apiece. Even that sum would be
sacrificial for some of our members. But we're working at it. We're
way ahead of them in shoe leather!''
</P>
<P>
   Don't sell labor short. When its volunteer troops are motivated
to mobilize against their corporate nemeses, they've been known to
do impressive things.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, labor-associated families accounted for only 13 percent
of those who actually showed up at the polls to cast ballots. That
was labor's low point, and the year that aggressive conservatism
triumphed. Republicans took the House for the first time in 20
years and began their essentially anti-labor reign.
</P>
<P>
   Two years later, thanks to the quiet, productive work of AFL-CIO
President John Sweeney's newly invigorated leadership team, labor _
with minimal fanfare but a lot of shoe leather _ turned out 22
percent of all those who cast ballots. A 70 percent gain! Clinton
and Gore were re-elected handily. Democrats gained seats in the
House. Last year, with labor's help, Democrats inched even closer,
within five of retaking the speakership.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's crucial convention vote to back Gore for the
nomination was almost anti-climactic. Sweeney had lobbied hard for
the endorsement _ which, when it came, was overwhelming. Fifty-two
unions for, two against, with a few abstentions.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, when the national convention formally opened, its
delegates were moved to repeated outbursts of spontaneous applause
by a fiery speech delivered by House Minority Leader Dick Gephardt.
On Wednesday, when Gore appeared, his humor was intact and his
manner relaxed. His spirited presentation and the enthusiastic
crowd reaction offered a fairly convincing answer to journalists
who keep whining that Gore is dull and colorless.
</P>
<P>
   Asked to explain the delegates' thunderous response to the
Gephardt and Gore speeches, a speech critic cited two factors. For
a crowd to be set on fire like that, he said, the speaker first
must be saying things he obviously means. Second, the audience must
be not only ready but eager to be ignited. A combination of things
are sticking in workers' craws.
</P>
<P>
   In a period of unprecedented business prosperity, wage-earning
families are struggling to stay even. Since 1990, corporate profits
have risen by 108 percent. Executive salaries increased by 481
percent. Workers' wages are up only 28 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to the GOP Congress, help is down for public schools.
HMOs keep squeezing medical care, making it more expensive.
Employers are outsourcing more work, sometimes threatening to move
American factories overseas unless workers accept cuts in health
and retirement benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Judging by what I saw and heard in Los Angeles, the accumulating
grievances of wage-earning Americans who see their families' upward
mobility stymied and living standards stalemated while the
corporate sector amasses unprecedented wealth are reaching a
combustible point. Whether a unified labor movement can sustain
that drive and urgency until November of next year will be the
test.
</P>
<P>
   (Jim Wright of Fort Worth is a former speaker of the U.S. House
of Representatives. You can write him at P.O. Box 1413, Fort Worth,
TX 76101 or at j.wright &LR; tcu.edu. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
