<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-18 17:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0741 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-SCI-MAMMARIES-2TAKES-     10-18 0680
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-MAMMARIES-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LINKING BREASTS, BEHAVIOR AND SIZE OF LITTER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: N.Y., Wash., Mass., Fla.)   (af)  
 By CAROL KAESUK YOON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Though much has been said and thought about the female breast,
there remains one aspect that has received little consideration:
the actual number that a woman has, with two accepted as the
immutable standard.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, humans, like other mammals, can vary in their numbers
of nipples and more rarely breasts, raising this little-pondered
question: Why do humans, or for that matter any mammals, have the
number of mammaries that they do?
</P>
<P>
   The few people who have considered this question, including
Aristotle and Alexander Graham Bell, have discovered that mammals
follow what is now known as the ``one-half rule.'' According to the
rule, the average number of young in a litter is one half the
typical number of mammaries and the maximum litter size is equal to
the total number of mammaries.
</P>
<P>
   (Humans conform perfectly to the rule with two breasts and a
typical litter size of one-half that, and a standard maximum litter
size, without fertility drugs, of two.)
</P>
<P>
   It has remained largely a mystery, however, why mammals so
slavishly follow this rule.
</P>
<P>
   But now, a new study on naked mole rats, a curious breed of
mammal that breaks the one-half rule, suggests that the reason for
having what seem to be so many extra mammaries may be to keep
sharing and fighting to a minimum in the largest litters.
</P>
<P>
   ``These animals turn the one-half rule upside down,'' said Dr.
Paul W. Sherman, behavioral ecologist at Cornell University who
with colleagues published a new study on mole rat mammaries in a
recent issue of The Journal of Mammology. Naked mole rats are able
to break the rule, having many fewer mammaries than it dictates,
because they are good at sharing, even when there are more than two
pups for every teat.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Avery N. Gilbert, biological psychologist at a private
research firm, Synesthetics Inc., and the namer of the one-half
rule, said, ``With a lot of pups you could have one pair of very
large mammary glands, but with only two spigots that would involve
a lot of sharing'' _ a behavior, he said, that is in short supply
among most young mammals. He added, ``It's tough down there in the
huddle.''
</P>
<P>
   Sherman and colleagues, Dr. Stanton Braude of Washington
University and Dr. Jennifer Jarvis of University of Cape Town in
South Africa, discovered that naked mole rats tend to bear about 11
young and tend to have 11 mammaries. In the biggest litters, there
can be as many as 28 pups.
</P>
<P>
   But unlike other animals that fight over access to teats _ most
famously pigs whose vicious scrambling for the more milk-rich
mammaries near the mother's head spawned the phrase ``sucking hind
teat'' _ mole rat young do not fight.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no jostling or shoving or grabbing onto a nipple,''
Sherman said. ``They just take turns without any aggression
whatsoever and mother doesn't have to adjudicate.''
</P>
<P>
   They do not need to fight, researchers suggest, because their
mother is heavily pampered, unlike most mammalian mothers who have
to leave the nest to find food for themselves and whose milk can
sometimes be in short supply.
</P>
<P>
   In mole rat colonies, as in bee or ant colonies, only a single
female reproduces with the others at her beck and call. Fed and
protected by members of the colony, the reproductive female appears
able to provide so much milk that the young can all amicably share
to satiation.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, in other social mammals, mothers are also cared for,
though to a lesser degree, and in those groups females also tend to
have more young per mammary than the one-half rule would dictate.
</P>
<P>
   But why not have more mammaries anyway so that even mole rat
young need not ever wait for their milk? Sherman said the fact that
naked mole rats do not have a nipple for every pup in their largest
litters suggests that females have only as many mammaries as
absolutely necessary, possibly because mammaries may carry a high
cost.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In particular, he said, mammaries are openings to the outside
world that carry the risk of mastitis, a sometimes dangerous
infection. Mammary tissue also carries the risk of cancers.
</P>
<P>
   While cooperative sharing of teats may be rare in many mammals,
in some it is out of the question. Dr. John Eisenberg, curator of
mammals at the Florida Museum of Natural History, said that in
marsupials, a group including kangaroos and opossums, the young are
born as tiny, fetuslike creatures that must find a way to a teat
and latch on, remaining attached until they are fully developed. In
such cases, young that do not find a nipple are doomed.
</P>
<P>
   There is even some evidence that in opossum mothers the number
of offspring far exceeds the number of nipples, creating an instant
struggle for access and an early lesson in the survival of the
fittest, Eisenberg said.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers also discovered that the number of mammaries an
individual had was highly variable and that the left and right
sides of mole rats often had different numbers of mammaries, with
totals ranging from 9 to 15.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers have tended to think of every species as having a
set number of mammaries and nicely matched pairs as well, Sherman
said, with animals built otherwise being viewed as rare
aberrations. Sherman suggests instead that variation in mammary
number may be much more common than researchers had thought.
</P>
<P>
   In some bats like the false vampire, there are extra teats known
as pubic teats found around the groin. Typically mammaries tend to
appear along the so-called milk line running from the armpit into
the groin.
</P>
<P>
   It is unclear if these extra teats in bats ever produce milk,
said Dr. Nancy Simmons, the curator of mammals at the American
Museum of Natural History, but even without milk they are of great
use to baby bats. Hanging upside down, a young bat grabs the pubic
teat with its mouth and wraps its legs around its mother's neck,
hanging on safely as the mother flies about.
</P>
<P>
   Even humans exhibit more variation in nipple and breast number
than is widely recognized. Dr. G. Gregory Gallico III, plastic
surgeon at Massachusetts General Hospital, said both polythelia,
the condition of having extra nipples, and polymastia, the
condition of having extra breast tissue, are viewed as harmless.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers say these conditions can also be quite common, with
some estimating that about 1 percent of the population carries
either an extra nipple or extra breast tissue.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most people who have them probably never know,'' said Gallico,
explaining that accessory nipples can look like little more than
moles or brown dots.
</P>
<P>
   But while largely viewed as benign medical oddities, extra
nipples and in particular extra breasts, which Gilbert says have
been reported in the clinical literature to weep milk during
pregnancy, can also be viewed as a kind of evolutionary tinkering
in increased mammary number in humans.
</P>
<P>
   In earlier times, however, such evolutionary experimentation was
viewed in a much more sinister light. Dr. David D. Hall, religious
and cultural historian at Harvard Divinity School, said that during
the witchhunts in America and Europe, women suspected of being
witches were often searched for extra nipples or breasts
particularly in the groin area. Known as witches' marks, the
nipples were thought to be used to nurse cats, dogs and other more
fantastical creatures, known as their familiars.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
