<HEADER>
A0746 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-SCI-VITALSIGNS-NYT &LR;      10-18 1431
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-VITAL </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
READING, WRITING AND DEFIBRILLATION; DETECTING TICK-BORNE
EHRLICHIOSIS, THE STRESS AND SMOKE CYCLE; HOSTILE HEART PATIENTS
FACING REHAB; A TEST AND A QUIZ FOR HEPATITIS C  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
 SIGNS-NYT  
 (ATTN: Wash., Conn., La., Britain)   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   On television, zapping a heart rhythm back to normal looks so
simple a class of sixth graders probably could learn it in a
minute, right?
</P>
<P>
   As a matter of fact, they can, according to a Seattle study
published today in the journal Circulation. Researchers there gave
15 sixth graders a one-minute demonstration _ no questions allowed
_ of how to use an automated external defibrillator, a twin-paddle
electrical device used in cases of sudden cardiac arrest.
</P>
<P>
   The students were then asked to do what they had watched, and
they were able to use the device correctly in an average of 90
seconds _ only 23 seconds longer than needed by a control group of
paramedics using the device for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   The point of the study was not to argue for replacing Game Boys
with defibrillators in sixth graders' backpacks, but rather to make
the case that the devices should be more widely available. Every
minute of delay in restoring heart rhythm cuts the odds of survival
by 10 percent, and previous studies have estimated that greater
access to the devices could save 50,000 lives a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``While this study proves that AED's are extremely easy to use,
it's important that you can't just arrive on the scene of an
emergency and hook someone up to the device,'' wrote Dr. Gus Bardy
of the University of Washington Medical School in Seattle, the
paper's author. ``You need training to learn how to assess the
emergency and determine if it's CPR, an AED, the Heimlich maneuver
or something else the patient needs.''
</P>
<P>
   DIAGNOSIS: TEST ZOOMS IN ON TICK-BORNE AILMENT
</P>
<P>
   Researchers at Yale and the Connecticut Agricultural Experiment
Station have developed a new blood test to better detect
ehrlichiosis, a disease carried by deer ticks that often goes
undiagnosed because it lacks a telltale sign like the bull's-eye
rash of Lyme disease.
</P>
<P>
   Like Lyme disease, ehrlichiosis causes fevers, aches and other
flulike symptoms. But without a rash as a tip-off, health officials
suspect, most infections go undetected. Even when the disease is
suspected, testing has been slow and expensive.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the number of diagnosed cases has grown steadily in
Connecticut since ehrlichiosis was first identified in 1994; more
than 100 cases were confirmed there last year, said Dr. Jacob IJdo,
a rheumatologist who led the Yale research team.
</P>
<P>
   The new, simpler blood test, described in an article to be
published in the November issue of The Journal of Clinical
Microbiology, should help researchers address many unknowns
surrounding ehrlichiosis, including its range, prevalence and its
long-term course. ``It's like the early days of Lyme disease,''
IJdo (pronounced EYE-doe) said in an interview. The test was
developed by researchers for Yale and for the State of Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   IJdo described the disease, which can usually be treated with
antibiotics, as ``very variable'' in its severity. Most cases
resemble the flu, with high fevers, headaches and muscle cramps. In
a few cases, the fevers have been accompanied by drops in white
blood cell count that have left patients open to fatal infections.
</P>
<P>
   IJdo said patients should not suspect ehrlichiosis with every
runny nose in the summertime. But people who know they have been
bitten by a deer tick and who have what seems to be a severe flu
during the warm-weather months should consult a physician.
</P>
<P>
   PATTERNS: RIDING THE CYCLE OF STRESS AND SMOKE
</P>
<P>
   Cigarettes do help smokers relax _ from tension caused by
smoking, a new study argues.
</P>
<P>
   The study, published in the October issue of American
Psychologist, examined one of tobacco's central paradoxes: smokers
say that lighting up provides a sense of relief and well-being, but
as a group, they hardly seem that relaxed.
</P>
<P>
   The new study, conducted by Dr. Andy Parrott, a psychologist at
the University of East London, found that adult smokers report
higher levels of stress between cigarettes, that teen-agers report
increased tension as they move from experimental to regular smoking
and that former smokers report lower or similar stress levels than
current smokers.
</P>
<P>
   Parrott conceded that one explanation could be that people with
higher levels of stress are drawn to smoking.
</P>
<P>
   But more likely, he said, smokers are suffering the whipsaw
effect of addiction.
</P>
<P>
   ``The regular smoker needs nicotine to maintain normal moods,''
Parrott wrote, ``and suffers from unpleasant feelings of
irritability and tension between cigarettes when his or her plasma
nicotine levels are falling.''
</P>
<P>
   He suggested that pointing out the link between nicotine and
stress could be useful in helping smokers face the undeniable
stress of quitting.
</P>
<P>
   WHEN HOSTILE HEART PATIENTS FACE REHAB
</P>
<P>
   Heart attack victims who are generally hostile people tend to be
younger, heavier and unhappier than most coronary patients _ and to
get more benefit from cardiac rehabilitation programs, a study
conducted in New Orleans has found.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier research has established that a pattern of hostility or
unexpressed anger can greatly increase the odds of contracting
heart disease, perhaps because anger can drive up blood pressure.
Other studies have found that adding psychological counseling to
standard cardiac rehabilitation programs can help prevent future
heart attacks in patients with depression.
</P>
<P>
   In the new study, Dr. Carl J. Lavie, a cardiologist at the
Ochsner Clinic in New Orleans, and a colleague, Dr. Richard V.
Milani, reported finding high levels of hostility in 65, or 13
percent, of 500 heart attack victims. They found that the hostile
patients had higher levels of weight, cholesterol, anxiety and
depression.
</P>
<P>
   But if the ``before'' differences were striking, so were the
``after'' changes. ``The patients with high levels of hostility got
dramatically greater benefits from the rehabilitation program
compared with other patients,'' said Lavie, even though the program
included only general counseling about diet, exercise and the
patients' state of mind.
</P>
<P>
   The prevalence of high hostility levels dropped 40 percent, and
the hostile patients reported bigger than average gains in energy,
mental health and general health.
</P>
<P>
   Lavie said he hoped the research, published this month in The
Mayo Clinic Proceedings, would ``raise the level of concern
directed at behavioral factors in general.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though physicians are aware of the role emotions play in
promoting risk of heart disease, Lavie said, ``It's easier to
address cholesterol and weight or things like that.''
</P>
<P>
   RISKS AND REMEDIES:FOR HEPATITIS C, A TEST AND A QUIZ
</P>
<P>
   The 300,000 Americans who may have been exposed to hepatitis C
through tainted blood transfusions before 1992 can take an Internet
quiz this week to gauge their risk and order a free home-test kit.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, a far-ranging effort was begun to trace and notify
these patients, who had transfusions before reliable screening
became available in 1992. But many recipients may not be notified
for months or even years, so the American Liver Foundation is
offering the test and kits as part of National Hepatitis Awareness
Week, available at www.liverfoundation.org or at (888) 888-HEPC.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Henry Bodenheimer Jr., a liver specialist and professor of
medicine at the Mount Sinai School of Medicine in New York,
described hepatitis C as a serious but slow-moving disease. ``Many
people infected with it are unaware, because it can be asymptomatic
for a long time,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   For some, especially those who contract the disease later in
life, it may have no affect on their health, he said. In others, it
can lead to the progressive scarring called cirrhosis, or to liver
cancer. Hepatitis C kills about 10,000 people a year.
</P>
<P>
   The disease is most often treated with a combination of
interferon alpha, which stimulates the immune system, and
ribavarin, an antiviral compound. But the treatment is expensive,
is effective in only 40 to 50 percent of patients and has
significant side effects.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Bodenheimer said, people at risk should take the test for
hepatitis C. ``Not to be alarmist, but it is the leading cause of
liver transplants,'' he continued. ``What is crucial is early
detection and awareness so that people can make important decisions
about their health care.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
