<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A SOOTY CLINTON CALLS THE SENATE'S KETTLE BLACK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
By BILL THOMPSON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   As we count down the final 15 months of Bill Clinton's
presidency, the time has come to think of him as a ``lame duck'' _
a president whose term is expiring and whose power is declining
because nobody cares what a soon-to-be-former officeholder wants to
do.
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton doesn't see himself as a lame duck. There are things
he wants to do. There are laws he wants passed, treaties he wants
ratified. The 42nd president of the United States wants to be
remembered for something other than fooling around with an intern
and beating the rap in an impeachment trial.
</P>
<P>
   So. That nuclear test ban treaty he'd been touting was a big
deal to Clinton. It was a symbol _ to him, at least _ of his
stature as a world leader. Its ratification would have contributed
to a presidential legacy that transcended the scandals and the
controversy.
</P>
<P>
   It is perfectly understandable that the Democratic president was
ticked off when the Republican-controlled Senate rejected the
treaty by a 51-48 vote. It would have been more understandable, of
course, if he hadn't set the stage for his own defeat by playing
politics with an issue that he would like us to believe is above
politics.
</P>
<P>
   By all accounts, Clinton was well aware that he could never
muster the two-thirds vote required to ratify the treaty _ and that
his best hope for avoiding an embarrassing defeat was to reach an
agreement with the Senate to delay a vote until after the 2000
elections. But he demanded a vote, gambling that the Republicans
would not risk the fallout of rejecting a politically correct
treaty.
</P>
<P>
   How ironic that Clinton would react to the Senate's action by
accusing his opponents of political gamesmanship when in fact it
was his political gamesmanship that tripped him up.
</P>
<P>
   Or maybe it wasn't ironic at all. Maybe it was exactly what we
could have expected from a president whose favorite tactic is to
turn reality upside down in hopes of gaining some political
advantage.
</P>
<P>
   Leave it to Clinton to be up to his neck in partisan politics
and simultaneously accuse the other side of being up to its neck in
partisan politics.
</P>
<P>
   In this case _ as in so many others _ Clinton's duplicity went
beyond the simple matter of misrepresenting which games were being
played by which gamesmen. That part was just politics as usual.
</P>
<P>
   Far worse was his outrageous claim that Senate Republicans had
compromised the nation's security and the safety of the world by
rejecting the nuclear test ban treaty. The truth is the opposite:
Ratification of the treaty would have jeopardized the ability of
the world's lone remaining superpower to protect itself and its
allies from nuclear attack.
</P>
<P>
   The problem with a treaty like this is that the outlaw nations
who pose a threat to the rest of us won't obey the agreement even
if they are party to it. Does anyone actually believe that China
and Iran, for example, would suddenly shut down their nuclear
weapons programs just because they had signed and ratified a
document that many experts say is completely unenforceable?
</P>
<P>
   But the United States would obey the treaty. We always obey the
treaties. Because we're the good guys. Because we are honorable,
dependable and trustworthy _ not to mention hopelessly naive when
it comes to the intentions of less honorable nations.
</P>
<P>
   Curtailing the proliferation of nuclear arms is certainly a
legitimate and desirable goal for the United States and for the
world. But it's not a goal that can be achieved by trading the
security of the U.S. and its friends for the illusion that our
enemies share our commitment to peace.
</P>
<P>
   Someday, perhaps, an anti-nuclear treaty can be devised that
addresses the problem of proliferation without leaving the world's
preeminent nuclear power vulnerable to tyrants and troublemakers
who covet our status.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, the U.S. Senate has fulfilled its
responsibility by saying ``no'' to a dangerous treaty. Clinton's
deceitful portrayal of what happened should make all Americans glad
that he is in the lame-duck phase of his presidency.
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Thompson is a columnist for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can contact him at (817) 390-7787. Visit the Star-Telegram's
online services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
