<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-OKLAHOMA-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OKLAHOMA CITY: IT'S MORE THAN OK AS A VACATION SPOT 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Photo available on NYT database) 
 
By SYD KEARNEY 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   OKLAHOMA CITY _ We bring up Oklahoma today because, frankly, no
one else will.
</P>
<P>
   That's the consensus of a recent survey conducted by the
Oklahoma Department of Tourism and Recreation. In a telephone poll,
just 2 percent of 514 respondents from Texas, Oklahoma, Missouri
and Kansas said they would consider the Sooner State as a vacation
destination.
</P>
<P>
   Ouch.
</P>
<P>
   That must hurt state officials who have spent $2.5 million on a
campaign to promote tourism.
</P>
<P>
   ``What this report shows us is that we need to spend more money
on advertising,'' Lt. Gov. Mary Fallin, head of the state's Tourism
and Recreation Commission, told The Associated Press after the
survey's release.
</P>
<P>
   The $3.2 billion question _ matching the amount of money spent
annually in Oklahoma by domestic travelers _ is whether an
advertising campaign can spur tourism. In the survey, respondents'
top two reasons for not visiting Oklahoma were ``no desire to go''
and ``nothing to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Recent visitors to bustling Oklahoma City may dispute the latter
sentiment.
</P>
<P>
   The state's capital is approaching tourism development with an
earnestness no doubt inspired by the state motto: ``Labor omnia
vincit,'' or labor conquers all things.
</P>
<P>
   Construction sites dot the landscape, billboards tout new
businesses, and locals gather to gawk at all the action downtown,
where a renaissance is under way.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest (tourism) problem for Oklahoma City isn't
`misconception,''' said Doug Stafford of the Oklahoma City
Convention &AMP; Visitors Bureau. ``It is `no conception.' People think
about Oklahoma, and they think Cowboys, Indians and prairie.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like, `Where are the tepees?'''
</P>
<P>
   What visitors will find instead of tepees are dozens of new
theaters, museums, restaurants and attractions. Many of them are
part of the $300 million Metropolitan Area Projects program,
approved by voters in 1993. Among such projects under construction
are a sports arena, an art museum, a convention hotel, a history
center and a music hall.
</P>
<P>
   Already complete are the renovated and expanded convention
center and the new 12,000-seat Southwestern Bell Bricktown
Ballpark, home of the Oklahoma Redhawks, a Class AAA baseball team
affiliated with the Texas Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   Grabbing most of the spotlight, however, is the new Riverwalk.
The milelong, 4-foot-deep canal made its debut July 4, when more
than 250,000 spectators gathered on its wide sidewalks and
low-slung bridges.
</P>
<P>
   If the canal's water taxis remind visitors of a certain Texas
town, that's OK with Oklahoma City tourism officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``We could consider San Antonio to be our biggest competitor for
the tourism dollar,'' Stafford said. ``We did a lot of research and
found that most tourism attractions center on water. We said, `Hey,
we don't need all these streets.'''
</P>
<P>
   The canal runs through the heart of Bricktown, a century-old
warehouse district that was all but abandoned in the 1950s. The
neighborhood takes its name from the red-brick buildings. Several
fountains, a waterfall and more than 300 trees were added along the
canal, which was dug so that its sidewalks are at basement level of
surrounding buildings. This design provides for multiple levels of
canal-side dining and retail display.
</P>
<P>
   The 30-minute water-taxi tour is short on narration and long on
potential.
</P>
<P>
   During an August visit, a sweaty but cheerful driver pointed out
attractions and construction sites to tourists melting in the
105-degree heat as they passed restaurants such as Chileno's and
Monkey Moose Grill and the ballpark with its shops and eateries and
then crossed under Interstate 40.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're coming up to our most popular attraction,'' she chimed
as we approached the looming freeway. ``Shade.''
</P>
<P>
   Transportation for the Oklahoma City visitor isn't limited to
the canal's single mile. More appealing and practical is the
Oklahoma Spirit Trolley, also created by Metropolitan Area
Projects.
</P>
<P>
   Begun in May, the trolley bus service runs on a downtown route
and a western route. The latter makes stops at the city's
stockyards and fairgrounds. The trolleys run every day, with fares
starting at 50 cents. A three-day pass costs $2.
</P>
<P>
   The downtown route provides an unnarrated tour past some of the
city's top attractions, including Bricktown, City Hall, the Myriad
Botanical Gardens and the Oklahoma City National Memorial.
</P>
<P>
   The memorial is being built on the site where the Alfred P.
Murrah Federal Building was destroyed by a bomb in 1995. The fence
surrounding the construction site is still one of the city's most
frequently visited attractions; at any hour, you can see people
attaching notes, flowers and stuffed toys to the fence.
</P>
<P>
   A symbol of tragedy and hope, the fence is cleared periodically.
The mementos are cataloged and will become part of the memorial's
archives.
</P>
<P>
   The memorial, expected to open in April, will comprise two
massive gates, a reflecting pool, and 168 glass-and-granite chairs,
one for each of the people killed in the bombing.
</P>
<P>
   Not far from the memorial's dusty construction site is another
construction site.
</P>
<P>
   Tons of earth are being moved to make way for an arena complex
that will house sports contests, concerts and exhibitions. The
20,000-seat arena will allow the city to host such high-profile
events as NCAA basketball tournaments.
</P>
<P>
   The arena illustrates Oklahoma City's tourism-development
philosophy: Build it, and they will come.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
