r w BC-CHINA-TRADE-SPI &LR;      10-18 1065
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-TRADE-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DESPITE AGREEMENT WITH CHINA, U.S. EXPORTERS STILL WAITING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MICHAEL PAULSON  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Pacific Northwest wheat farmers, California and
Florida citrus growers, and poultry and meat producers from around
the country were delighted in April when China, as a goodwill
gesture to the United States, agreed to end years of bans against
importing their products.
</P>
<P>
   But six months after President Clinton and Chinese Premier Zhu
Rongji celebrated the deal at a joint news conference, not one of
the agricultural groups has seen any benefits.
</P>
<P>
   A review by the Seattle Post-Intelligencer has found that China
has not followed through on its promise to immediately remove
barriers to the purchase of the U.S. agricultural products. In the
most glaring example of the deal's false start, China has twice
agreed to send inspectors to California to start the process of
buying that state's citrus, and both times China has canceled the
appointments.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. officials say the deal is still intact, just moving slowly.
But grower groups say they believe the agreement was essentially
scuttled when NATO bombed the Chinese Embassy in Belgrade and the
United States accused China of spying. The grower groups say they
don't believe the deal will have any impact unless China is
admitted to the World Trade Organization, a complex step that was
supposed to be unrelated to this agricultural agreement.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the beginning, it was our understanding that this was going
to be a really big deal, but it didn't turn out to be,'' said Toby
Moore of the USA Poultry &AMP; Egg Export Council. ``From our
perspective, it has done nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   The bilateral agricultural agreement was announced at an April 8
news conference by Zhu and Clinton, who said the pact would be
``highly important for our farmers.'' The agreement was signed two
days later in Washington by U.S. Trade Representative Charlene
Barshefsky and Chinese Foreign Trade Minister Shi Guangsheng, and
was supposed to be effective immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Under the agreement, China agreed to lift longstanding bans on
the export of U.S. citrus, grain, beef and poultry. China had been
banning the import of wheat and other grains from the Pacific
Northwest for 26 years, citing concerns over a wheat disease called
TCK smut. China also had a 16-year ban against citrus from
California, Florida and other states, citing concern over fruit
flies, and had sharply limited importation of meat and poultry,
citing concerns over the U.S. inspection system.
</P>
<P>
   The bans, which Barshefsky called ``unfair trade barriers,'' had
cost American farmers billions of dollars in sales, according to
Agriculture Secretary Dan Glickman.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. officials acknowledge that they are disappointed with the
turn of events, but say they believe the deal is still in place.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have had a slow start in implementation, but expect that
things should move forward again,'' the Department of Agriculture
said in response to inquiries by the P-I. ``We believe this
agreement is a fundamental breakthrough for American agriculture.''
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the Chinese Embassy did not return calls seeking
comment, but a U.S. trade official says there have been some
incrementally positive developments. In June, the United States
held a meat seminar in China, showing how the U.S. meat inspection
system works, and China and the United States have held several
scientific exchanges aimed at resolving Chinese concerns over the
quality of U.S. foods.
</P>
<P>
   But the trade official, who asked not to be named, said the two
countries haven't even finished translating the April agreement
from English to Chinese, and acknowledged that the downturn in
U.S.-China relations as a result of the bombing seemed to have
stalled implementation of the pact.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do think it needs to move forward,'' the trade official
said. ``We've just started re-engaging.''
</P>
<P>
   One China expert said the collapse of the deal was predictable
once the United States had rejected a separate, and supposedly
unrelated, offer China made in April of concessions to win
admission to the WTO.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once the U.S. side failed to endorse the Chinese (World Trade
Organization) offer, I thought there was a significant possibility
the bilateral agricultural agreement would become a casualty of the
whole affair,'' said Nicholas Lardy, a China specialists at the
Brookings Institution. ``If there is some improvement in relations,
maybe we can get them to live up to it, but in the short run, I
don't think there is a high probability of success.''
</P>
<P>
   U.S. growers face other obstacles _ their products are currently
being smuggled into China through Hong Kong, China had a bountiful
wheat crop of its own this year, and China maintains high tariffs
against some U.S. agricultural commodities. But the collapse of the
bilateral agricultural agreement is a major disappointment for U.S.
growers who have been hurt by a variety of economic factors and are
eager to be able to sell to China's vast population.
</P>
<P>
   In April, Florida Citrus Mutual issued a news release calling
the bilateral agreement ``a fantastic opportunity,'' and predicted
exports this season. Today, council executive vice president Andy
LaVigne has no such hopes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We expect it down the road to have a large impact on the
citrus industry, but to date it hasn't had any,'' he said. ``Until
the political unrest is settled, that's where we are.''
</P>
<P>
   California Citrus Mutual President Joel Nelson said China has
twice scheduled inspection teams to come examine how well
California growers are trapping fruit flies, but the trips, a
necessary first step before exports can begin, were canceled.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything from accusing them of spying to blowing up their
embassy has hurt us,'' Nelson said. ``This season I would
anticipate very few shipments to China.''
</P>
<P>
   In the Northwest, wheat growers are also waiting.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was supposed to be separate from the whole WTO accession
deal, but we suspect not much will go until they finish negotiating
all of the different areas for China's accession,'' said Chris
Holdgreve, assistant director of the Wheat Export Trade Education
Committee. ``We're holding off on any celebration until we actually
see a ship go into port with Pacific Northwest wheat on it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
