<SLUG> BC-LAWRENCE-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`LAWRENCE': SHIFTING SAND BENEATH A HEROIC IMAGE 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: Publication notes appear at the end of the review.) 
(th) 
 By MICHIKO KAKUTANI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Few historical figures have been as vigorously mythologized as
T.E. Lawrence, the British soldier and archaeologist who helped
lead the Arab Revolt against the Turks during World War I.
</P>
<P>
   Lawrence, of course, started the process himself with a
theatrical self-portrait in ``Seven Pillars of Wisdom'' (1926), and
David Lean galvanized that legend with his stunning 1962 epic,
``Lawrence of Arabia,'' a movie that immortalized its hero against
the sweeping desert vistas of the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
   In the latest biography of Lawrence, Michael Asher, an explorer
and author, attempts to sort fact from fiction, retracing his
subject's travels across the Arabian peninsula while sifting the
biographical record for inconsistencies and contradictions.
</P>
<P>
   Asher is an Arabic speaker who lived with a traditional Bedu
tribe for several years, and he uses his intimate knowledge of the
Arabian desert to provide the reader with a palpable sense of the
beauties and hardships of life in that part of the world.
</P>
<P>
   But while his narrative account of Lawrence's role in the Arab
Revolt often rivals Lean's movie in sheer drama, his portrait of
the man himself is decidedly more problematic, relying on
paint-by-numbers Freudianisms to decipher this most enigmatic of
men.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout this volume Asher harps on Lawrence's masochistic
nature as an overarching explanation for the twists and turns of
his life. He argues that Lawrence (who was subjected to fierce
beatings by his domineering mother) developed an acute fear of pain
as a boy, and that the courage he would later exhibit in battle
stemmed from his willful ``flight forwards'' toward the very thing
he dreaded.
</P>
<P>
   Asher also suggests that the most infamous incident in ``Seven
Pillars'' _ involving Lawrence's capture, torture and homosexual
rape by the Turks of Dara'a in November 1917 _ may have been
invented (or exaggerated) by Lawrence as a means of
self-humiliation, as an act of public expiation for his failure to
carry out a mission strategic to the Allies.
</P>
<P>
   On other debated points in his life, Asher argues that Lawrence
was homosexual by nature but probably never consummated his
passion, given the horror of physical intimacy he developed as a
child. Contrary to some commentators, he contends that Lawrence in
all likelihood did ride back through the desert alone to rescue a
man named Gasim who had become separated from the Aqaba raiding
party, but he argues that Lawrence lied in ``Seven Pillars'' when
he claimed that he traversed the Sinai by camel in a mere 49 hours
to deliver the news of the capture of Aqaba to the British at Suez.
</P>
<P>
   Asher suggests, as others have before him, that Lawrence was an
expert at ``massaging the truth,'' both in manipulating public
opinion in his official capacity as a British officer during the
war and later as a writer intent on mythologizing his own exploits.
</P>
<P>
   As for the Arab slaughter of a Turkish column at Tafas in
September 1918 and the subsequent massacre of Turkish and German
prisoners (an incident some critics have taken as evidence that
Lawrence was a bloodthirsty sadist), Asher questions Lawrence's
actual involvement in the killing, suggesting that his penchant for
self-sacrifice ``may have obliged him to assume responsibility for
savage acts in which he personally had played no part.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Indeed,'' Asher writes, ``there is a sense in which Lawrence,
the masochist, liked to absorb the sin and suffering of the world:
the duplicity of the British he bore on his shoulders, together
with the inconstancy, cruelty and barbarousness of the Arabs.''
</P>
<P>
   As a boy Lawrence had absorbed Victorian preconceptions of the
East as ``a place of mystery and exoticism,'' and throughout his
life he would romanticize the Arab peasant as a kind of noble
savage, possessing a childlike faith and certainty that eluded his
own ``insanely rational'' mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although Lawrence genuinely tried to see things from an Arab
point of view,'' Asher writes, ``and did so more successfully than
most, his technique of `empathy' remained a method of control. He
believed the traditional Arabs morally superior to Europeans
because they were `primitive' and therefore `innocent,' but not
intellectually so. The reality of his privileged position was
stated frankly when he wrote: `Really this country, for the
foreigner, is too glorious for words: one is really the baron in
the feudal system.'''
</P>
<P>
   Asher argues that Lawrence saw the Arab leader Feisal and the
Arab Revolt as ``an expression of his own rebellion'': against his
mother, against the establishment, against the status quo. He also
points out, however, that the paternalistic Lawrence believed that
he alone could provide the Arabs with the leadership they lacked by
using the malleable Feisal as his surrogate.
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of the daring raid on Aqaba (which put the last
Ottoman Red Sea port in Allied hands and provided the Arabs with a
supply base in Syria), Lawrence was able to convince his British
superiors that he was ``the indispensable conduit through which
arms and money must flow to the Arabs.'' This, in turn, helped him
to persuade the Arabs that he was essential to their cause.
</P>
<P>
   In the course of rallying his Arab troops, Lawrence had
repeatedly reassured them that they were fighting for their own
independence, not to further Allied objectives, even though Britain
had already signed the Sykes-Picot agreement with France, cynically
vowing to carve up the Middle East between themselves in the event
of an Allied victory.
</P>
<P>
   Asher suggests that ``the wily intelligence officer who had at
first accepted the realpolitik of sacrificing Arab priorities to
those of the Allies became increasingly plagued by doubt,'' and
that he felt considerable guilt over his determination to raise
these ``tides of men'' on a sham promise. But while Lawrence
promised his old friend Feisal that he would fight the French for
the Arab cause in Syria after the war, he instead settled down to
write ``Seven Pillars.''
</P>
<P>
   Lawrence died in 1935 in a motorcycle accident in the English
countryside. A monument was later erected in the old Anglo-Saxon
church of St. Martin at Wareham in Dorset, complete with a stone
effigy of Lawrence wearing an Arab headdress and robe.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `Lawrence: The Uncrowned King of Arabia'
</P>
<P>
   By Michael Asher
</P>
<P>
   Illustrated. 419 pages. Overlook Press. $37.95.
</P>
</TEXT>
