<HEADLINE>
WHEN YOU GO: OKLAHOMA CITY 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By SYD KEARNEY 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   _ Getting there: There is a romantic way to reach Oklahoma City,
but you have to start in Fort Worth, Texas. Amtrak has begun daily
service between the cities. Passengers arrive in the old Santa Fe
Depot, currently undergoing renovation in the downtown area. Trains
depart Fort Worth at 5:25 p.m. daily, arriving in Oklahoma City at
10 p.m. Trains depart Oklahoma City at 8:25 a.m., arriving in Fort
Worth at 1 p.m. They make several stops, including Norman and
Ardmore, Okla., and Gainesville, Texas. One-way fares on the
Heartland Flyer start at $24. Call 800-872-7245; access
www.amtrak.com.
</P>
<P>
   _ Lodging: Most of the city's hotels are found north of the
airport, where you'll find something for every budget.
Unfortunately for those wishing to stay downtown, choices are few.
Consider the Westin Oklahoma City (800-937-8461), where rates
reflect its position as the only luxury hotel downtown, or go for
the more budget-priced Super 8 Bricktown (800-800-8000).
</P>
<P>
   The Westin will be getting some competition early next year with
the opening of the 311-room Renaissance Hotel, which will be
connected to the Myriad Convention Center.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL; 
ACTIVITIES: &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ Take a ride on the Bricktown Canal on a water taxi. The
narrated tours allow you on and off privileges all day. Cost is $5;
$1 for age 5 and younger. Call 405-234-8294.
</P>
<P>
   _ Explore the myth and reality of the Old West at the National
Cowboy Hall of Fame and Western Heritage Center. The museum
displays everything from masterpieces by artists Frederic Remington
and Charles Russell to artifacts such as rodeo trophies and barbed
wire. The museum is open 9 a.m.-5 p.m. Admission is $6.50; $3.25
for age 12 and younger. Call 405-478-2250.
</P>
<P>
   _ Savor the exotic flora of the 17-acre Myriad Botanical
Gardens. The gardens' focal point is the seven-story Crystal Bridge
Tropical Conservatory. The conservatory is open 9 a.m.-6 p.m.
Admission is $4; $2 for age 12 and younger. Call 405-297-3995.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Omniplex bills itself as a museum for the mind, offering
three museums, a planetarium, a greenhouse, and spaces dedicated to
African art and American Indians. Kids particularly enjoy the
Hands-On Science Museum. Hours vary. Admission is $7.60; $6 for
children.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Dining:  &LR; Visitors will find plenty of familiar chain
restaurants here. Head to Bricktown, though, and you'll discover
casual restaurants with character and tasty food:
</P>
<P>
   _ Pearl's Crabtown is part of a local chain that includes
Pearl's Oyster Bars. The New Orleans-inspired menu features Shrimp
Creole, Pecan-Crusted Catfish, and deep-fried specialties such as
oysters and clams. After dinner, head upstairs to the Left Field
Sports Grill with its small but busy off-track betting parlor. Call
405-232-7227.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Varsity, another local chain, offers pizza, pasta,
burgers, ribs and plenty of cold brews in a friendly sports pub
setting. Call 405-235-5525.
</P>
<P>
   _ Chelino's serves up Tex-Mex comfort foods such as cheese
enchiladas and sizzling fajitas on two decks overlooking the new
canal. If it is hot out, go for the Shrimp Cocktail _ a massive,
thoughtfully spiced soup filled with seafood and fresh avocado.
Call 405-235-3533.
</P>
<P>
   _ Coach's boasts perhaps the best location in Bricktown. The
restaurant's terrace overlooks the right field of Southwestern Bell
Bricktown Ballpark. On game days, sports fans can watch the action
while feasting on barbecue, pizza and signature ales.
</P>
<P>
   _ Additional information: To receive a free Oklahoma City
visitors guide, call 800-225-5652; or access www.okccvb.org. For
Oklahoma state tourism information, call 800-652-6552; access
travelok.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
