<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOING FOR BROKE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARIANNE MEANS  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Life is unfair, as President John Kennedy memorably
observed.
</P>
<P>
   The scorched-earth campaign for the Senate in New York already
figuratively resembles Union Gen. William Tecumseh Sherman's Civil
War march through the South, burning everything in sight. When it
is over, reputations will be in ruins. Fairness will not enter the
equation.
</P>
<P>
   Will this race be about issues? Much lip service will be paid to
that noble concept, and in fact the two contenders have serious
policy differences.
</P>
<P>
   But, nope, this is about personalities. Mostly, hers.
</P>
<P>
   This is inevitable. It's the way politics is.
</P>
<P>
   First Lady Hillary Clinton, as a pioneering female in politics,
has always been super-visible, super-admired, super-loathed and
super-investigated. Nothing about her life as Bill Clinton's
partner has been what most wives would consider normal, in public
or private.
</P>
<P>
   How many other women live under threat of indictment from a
special prosecutor for several years and feel compelled to defend a
husband who is an acknowledged philanderer _ and are not only still
standing but slugging it out?
</P>
<P>
   Hillary Clinton's campaign swing this week through New York
state highlights both her problems and her blessings as a candidate
on the ballot for the first time in her own right. Everyone in the
country knows she is running and knows who she is. The press is on
her case, big time.
</P>
<P>
   Her likely GOP opponent, New York Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, is no
political pipsqueak and is legendary for a ruthlessness that
matches her own. He shares her take-no-prisoners mentality.
</P>
<P>
   But he cannot compete with her for national star power. He
cannot win by campaigning as the better man. He must rely on
bringing her down.
</P>
<P>
   There are no precedents. If Eleanor Roosevelt had run for public
office instead of contenting herself with using her husband's
stature to push for her own policy goals, we might have something
to go by here. As it is, no prior president's wife has had the
inclination, the political will or the independence to stand before
the voters.
</P>
<P>
   Hillary Clinton is out there alone. Okay, that's the way a
campaign is supposed to be. One name on the ballot. And anything,
it seems, is fair game.
</P>
<P>
   The first lady and the mayor are engaged in what is
statistically a dead heat. Sometimes one is up and the other down,
sometimes the reverse. But they have never been far apart in the
polls and neither has ever held a decisive lead. This is truly a
battle royal.
</P>
<P>
   New York Republicans have tried to scare her out of the race,
complaining about her lack of state residence, her blind defense of
her husband's sins, her mortgage financing, her ignorance of local
issues, her Secret Service protection at taxpayer expense.
</P>
<P>
   If they think this will work, they badly underestimate her. She
has a long public record of digging in her heels when either she or
her husband is under attack. She believes that the best defense is
a good offense.
</P>
<P>
   She bought a New York home and refinanced the original dubious
mortgage arrangement. She went a long way toward defusing the
infidelity issue by addressing it and forgiving the president in
Talk magazine, after which she shot up 10 percentage points in the
New York polls.
</P>
<P>
   Her unfamiliarity with local issues can be easily solved. She is
a quick study and she is now focused. Besides, the
Manhattan-oriented Giuliani is not exactly immersed in upstate New
York issues either.
</P>
<P>
   The White House travel cocoon is a more difficult problem. As
first lady, she, as well as her husband, gets death threats. She
simply is not free to wander the New York countryside or fly the
skies on commercial airliners without official protection.
</P>
<P>
   But to defuse the complaints, she must figure out a compromise
between the law's requirements and the actual cost of using
government transportation that is not for official purposes. Under
federal election rules, she and her key staffers already repay the
government for the cost of a first-class commercial airline ticket
each time they fly on a military aircraft. But since she must use
an entire military jet, the costs far exceed the reimbursement.
</P>
<P>
   It will never be totally possible to separate her duties as
first lady from her role as Senate candidate, but voters will
accept some common-sense judgments. The Republicans go too far in
complaining that taxpayers should not pick up the tab for a Middle
East trip she is planning next month as first lady.
</P>
<P>
   Of course this has political implications for a state with a
large Jewish voting bloc, but from now on everything has political
implications, in this country or abroad. To say the first lady
should be grounded for her entire last year in office or abandon
her duties in that role is ridiculous. She has a history of travel
abroad as a good-will ambassador promoting equal rights for women
and further trips are a natural extension of her prior activities.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton nemesis Kenneth Starr resigned his job Monday as
independent counsel without clearing the first lady of allegations
of lying about her role in her former law firm's missing records,
the firing of White House travel office aides and strange fiddling
with FBI records of Republicans. Asked about that, Starr said,
tersely, ``No comment.''
</P>
<P>
   The prospect that his successor, Robert Ray, may yet indict her
hangs in the air but is highly unlikely. His official report on the
probe, however, is not going to be kind and may appear next summer
just in time to mess up her Senate campaign. Why would we not be
surprised?
</P>
<P>
   (Marianne Means can be reached by e-mail at
means(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
