<HEADER>
A0788 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-LEVENDOSKY-COLUMN-NYT     10-18 1093
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEVENDOSKY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITHOUT FREE PRESS, REPORTER FACES PRISON FOR 'INSULTING THE
MILITARY' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 (EDITOR'S NOTE: Charles Levendosky, editorial page editor of the
Casper (Wyo.) Star-Tribune, has a national reputation for First
Amendment commentary. His e-mail address is
levendos(AT-sign)trib.com.)  
(gm) 
 By CHARLES LEVENDOSKY   
 c. 1999 Casper (Wyo.) Star-Tribune   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Turkish journalist Nadire Mater faces up to six years in prison
for interviewing 42 Turkish army conscripts who fought in their
country's civil war against the Kurd guerrillas. These Kurds have
been fighting for more than a decade to carve a separate state out
of a portion of Turkey.
</P>
<P>
   Mater edited the interviews and wrote a preface for ``Mehmed's
Book.'' The interviews give a picture of life on the southeastern
front of the war from the Turkish draftee's perspective. The book
was published in April.
</P>
<P>
   An Istanbul court banned the book in June and ordered the
seizure of all remaining copies. Mater was charged with Article
159, ``insulting and belittling the military.'' If she is found
guilty of the charges, she could be sentenced to prison for a
period of one to six years.
</P>
<P>
   Mater, as a freelance correspondent out of Istanbul, has covered
the civil war for Inter Press Service (IPS), a global news agency.
She interviewed the Turkish soldiers in order to give these
``heroes in the mountains'' a chance to talk. ``Since they are the
heroes,'' she said in a telephone interview last week, ``we should
listen to what they are saying.''
</P>
<P>
   Mater said she worked on the book ``in order to know the war
better _ what is it?'' Some of the Turkish draftees she interviewed
are Kurds but they do not support the independence movement nor the
militant PKK (Kurdistan Worker's Party). Nevertheless, they were
sent to fight people of their own ethnic origin. And their feelings
needed to be told, too.
</P>
<P>
   An English translation of selections from the soldiers' book was
published in the latest issue of the British periodical ``Index on
Censorship.''
</P>
<P>
   In these interviews, the soldiers talk of evacuating Kurdish
villages and burning them down, of shooting old men, women and
children. They speak of the corruption in the military, of mine
detectors that don't work, of officers getting the better food, of
taking PKK guerrillas as prisoners then summarily executing them.
</P>
<P>
   The men outline the horrors of war, especially a civil war. As
one conscript put it: ``Down there you are fighting scores of wars.
Psychologically you are fighting against yourself as well as your
adversary. Whether you actually take part in a conflict or not, you
are a part of it; you have to protect yourself. If you don't want
to harm them, you are believed to be on the other side ... The
toughest of all the wars you fight is against your own presence
there against your will: your civil war against yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the interviews may insult and belittle the military, but
they are really a denunciation of the Turkish government and a
political system that has treated the Kurds as second-class
citizens and refused to make serious overtures to solve their
poverty.
</P>
<P>
   It's easier to prosecute journalists in Turkey. So Mater faces
charges under Article 159: ``insulting and belittling the
military.''
</P>
<P>
   Turkey is a republican parliamentary democracy, but ``there is
no jury system in Turkey,'' according to Mater. She will be tried
before a three-judge panel: ``Three judges and one prosecutor _
it's a crew,'' as she put it with a rueful laugh. ``It makes no
difference, sometimes, whether you have a good lawyer or not. It
depends upon the political winds.''
</P>
<P>
   The General Staff of the Turkish military wrote a letter to the
court, Mater said, which her lawyer obtained. And in the indictment
against her, the General Staff is listed as an informer. And the
charges in the indictment, she claims, came directly from this
letter.
</P>
<P>
   When asked if Turkey had a tradition of protecting freedom of
the press, Mater laughed: ``A tradition? No. (laughter) No.
Unfortunately, no. It's a pity.'' Mater has been arrested and held
in a detention center more than once while trying to pursue a
story.
</P>
<P>
   Once, she was detained with two Finnish journalists. At the time
Turkey's prime minister was holding a press conference in Helsinki
and talking about freedom of the press in Turkey. One of the
detained Finnish reporters called his editor in Helsinki and, much
to the prime minister's embarrassment, the editor asked the prime
minister about the detainment. Needless to say, the reporters were
immediately released.
</P>
<P>
   Political winds.
</P>
<P>
   Now Mater faces six years in prison _ for insulting the
military.
</P>
<P>
   There is a lesson here for Americans, who sometimes think
newspapers and the media go too far, are too nasty and should be
regulated, or at least restrained, by the government.
</P>
<P>
   Who hasn't insulted the American military, or the government, or
the president _ at one time or another? Should we all be locked up?
</P>
<P>
   Associated Press reporters recently uncovered an alleged
civilian massacre that occurred during the Korean War. The
reporters interviewed a number of veteran American soldiers who
fought in the Korean War and admitted gunning down 400 South Korean
refugees trapped underneath a bridge at a hamlet called No Gun Ri
in South Korea. If the accounts are true, these reporters have done
our nation a great favor and deserve serious consideration for a
Pulitzer Prize. And the soldiers who talked deserve our deep and
sad appreciation.
</P>
<P>
   The American people must know how we conduct wars. We must know
the injustices committed in our name, or we cannot begin to correct
them.
</P>
<P>
   The Department of Defense has been denying the massacre for
nearly half a century. Finally, after the AP stories, the
department promises a serious investigation into the matter.
</P>
<P>
   Would there have been a Tailhook news story and subsequent
investigation had it not been for good journalism and reporters who
didn't have to fear government reprisal? That story and its
consequences put a halt to that kind of sexual partying and sexual
harassment in the military. The news story helped correct a wrong.
</P>
<P>
   We can hope the political winds blow in favor of Nadire Mater
and the charges are dropped, but she has no constitutional
guarantees to protect her from government abuse of power and
threats of prosecution _ and, unfortunately, no jury of her peers
to see that justice is done.
</P>
<P>
   There's a lesson here.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
