<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-18 18:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0792 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a BC-FOOD-STAMPS-1STLDWRIT     10-18 1435
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-STAMPS-1STLDWRITETHRU-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HUNGER PAINS 
 
AS TEXAS LEADS THE NATION IN CURTAILED FOOD-STAMP ROLLS, POOR MOMS
SUE OVER FOOT-DRAGGING 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Photo available on NYT database) 
(Sun to correct headline) 
 
By POLLY ROSS HUGHES 
and PATTY REINERT 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Maria Diaz works full time weekdays cleaning rooms at
a hotel in the glitzy Galleria, but the $850 she brings home each
month doesn't put enough food on the table.
</P>
<P>
   So when months went by with no response to her food stamp
application, Diaz had a choice: Feed her two children or clothe
them.
</P>
<P>
   ``My money wasn't lasting, so I had to pay half of the electric
bill and half of the telephone bill,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The working mother, her 13-year-old son, Christopher, and
8-year-old daughter, Cynthia, at first resigned themselves to
eating less. After a few months, though, Diaz, who is separated
from her husband, contacted a lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   Today, her name tops a list of poor mothers in Houston who are
suing the Texas Department of Human Services for illegal
foot-dragging in the processing of food stamp claims.
</P>
<P>
   The complaint, recently updated, comes at a time when Texas
leads the nation with a decline of more than a million people from
its food stamp rolls since 1995 _ a 41 percent drop vs. a national
drop averaging 28 percent.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, 13 percent of Texas households are either
hungry or threatened with hunger, according to a study released
last week by the U.S. Department of Agriculture. Only New Mexico
and Mississippi are worse off.
</P>
<P>
   Even as food stamp rolls plummeted, the number of poor families
in Texas did not. In Harris County, 27 percent of people at the
poverty level did not receive food stamps four years ago. Now, 68
percent of Houston's poor who qualify for food stamps do not
receive them, an analysis of government records shows.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you see really high poverty rates with 13 percent
considered `food-insecure' and this big drop in food stamp rolls,
there's a real disparity there that Texas is going to have to
examine,'' said Celia Hagert, a policy analyst at the Center for
Public Policy Priorities in Austin, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Just over a year ago, the distraught Diaz turned to Mario
Caballero, a lawyer for Gulf Coast Legal Foundation. She had
applied for food stamps in July and still had no response in
September. Next came Mayra Zamora with a strikingly similar tale.
Soon word of legal help had spread to an entire community of women
complaining of the same plight.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had scores of clients come in and say, `I applied three
months ago, four months ago. I haven't heard anything.' Client
after client saying the same thing over and over. This was going on
in a massive scale,'' said Caballero.
</P>
<P>
   Soon, he sought local and state data from DHS that gave
substance to the anecdotal stories. In an 11-month period beginning
September a year ago, DHS' Gulf Coast region, including Houston,
had processed only 85 percent of its food stamp claims within the
30-day time frame that federal regulations require. Fifteen of
every 100 applicants were being held at bay, the numbers show.
</P>
<P>
   The Diaz lawsuit cites a 1991 court decision in a similar case,
Robertson vs. Jackson. A federal court in that case found the state
of Virginia in serious violation of federal timeliness standards
for processing food stamp claims and described the state's delays
as an ``intolerable, heartless and blatant disregard of the law.''
</P>
<P>
   The court then ordered the state to process all claims in the
first month in at least 97 percent of all cases. Texas, the Diaz
suit notes, has set a goal of processing at least 95 percent of
applications on time.
</P>
<P>
   ``The agency is investigating families too much prior to an
application being approved,'' Caballero said. ``That's why the
applications are behind. I can't say for sure that I can tie it to
Gov. (George W.) Bush, but the last three years have been bad.
People can draw their own inferences.''
</P>
<P>
   Texas DHS officials do not deny a problem exists, but they
insist they are not intentionally trying to discourage the needy
from getting nutritional help. Unlike the cash payments of
Temporary Assistance for Needy Families, food stamps act as a
nutritional supplement not only for families on welfare but also
for the working poor.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a handout. It's to supplement a person's nutrition,
and once again the children are key here. These are services for
people who qualify. One day it may be you or me, God forbid,'' said
Hoxi Jones-Carranza, a DHS spokeswoman in Houston. ``We in no way
want to deny anyone their benefits.''
</P>
<P>
   DHS officials say the food stamp logjam arose for a myriad of
reasons: a high turnover of DHS employees as the booming economy
lures them to better-paying jobs, a constantly changing staff that
lacks adequate training, and even the agency's own success in
preventing benefits from going to those who don't qualify.
</P>
<P>
   Last June, the USDA awarded the state human services agency a
record $19.7 million bonus for its ``accurate handling'' of the
federally funded food stamp program in 1998. Republican Lt. Gov.
Rick Perry praised DHS, saying the national honor shows that
``Texas can deliver social services in very efficient, effective,
and technologically advanced ways to the benefit of taxpayers and
needy families alike.''
</P>
<P>
   However, DHS officials acknowledge now that the gains they made
in accuracy resulted from more thorough investigations, with
supervisors carefully reviewing each application. That zealous
effort, in turn, has slowed the process.
</P>
<P>
   Several needy Houstonians and their advocates voice the belief
that Texas' drastic drop in the food stamp rolls is a symptom of
frustration with a system that is fraught with hassles.
</P>
<P>
   Food stamp recipients lose confidence in the system and drop
out, said Caballero. ``It's a combination of hassles and delays.''
</P>
<P>
   Diaz said each time she applies to renew her family's food
stamps (every three months), she gets a letter telling her a time
and date for her appointment to be interviewed. Usually, the letter
arrives only a day or two before the appointment and she has to
scramble to get time off from work. It often takes a full day and
accomplishes nothing.
</P>
<P>
   She recalls arriving by bus to the DHS office downtown at 8 a.m.
three times, only to wait with many others all day long. By 4 p.m.
or so, she or someone else would get up to ask (again) when they
could get their appointments. Several times, she would be told,
after waiting all day, that the person who was to interview her
wasn't even there.
</P>
<P>
   Exactly, agrees Virginia Flores, another Houston woman who is a
plaintiff in the lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I went to ask for an appointment, they treated me
badly,'' she said. ``They look down on us.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went there three or four times. One day, I showed up at 8
a.m. and they just talked to me through the little window at the
receptionist's desk. I waited several hours and the person who was
supposed to interview me never showed up. I finally called the
supervisor and she was no help either.
</P>
<P>
   ``They'd say, `Come back on Monday, and when I'd go back, they'd
say, `Check back on Friday,''' she said. ``It just went on like
that.''
</P>
<P>
   DHS has offered to settle the suit, Caballero said, but so far
no out-of-court agreement has been reached.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, improvements are under way, said Sherron Heinemann, a
DHS spokeswoman in Austin. She said that after stepped-up training
for the workers on how to schedule and interview, 94.9 percent of
Harris County food stamp applications in September were processed
within the required 30 days.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel it is very important to do two things when we're
providing services. One is that we provide accurate benefits to
those that qualify and that we also do that in a timely manner,''
Heinemann said. ``The timeliness, particularly in (certain)
regions, is not what we would like it to be.''
</P>
<P>
   The Diaz case is set to go to court in May. Despite the sudden
improvement in September, the fact remains that Houston has one of
the highest food stamp denial rates in the state, Caballero said.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't until her lawyer stepped in, Diaz said, that her
treatment by the state agency suddenly improved. She agreed to take
part in the lawsuit to change the system for everyone else.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still know other people who don't have a lawyer. They are
being treated the same way I was,'' she said. ``I hope this will
change that for everybody because it's not fair.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
