<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-18 18:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0809 &Cx1f; taf-z
s t BC-TRAVEL-Q&AMP;A-$ADV24-NYT     10-18 1101
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-Q&AMP;A-$ADV24-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PHOTOGRAPHY IN TUSCANY; BRITISH TRANSPORTATION PASSES; HALLOWEEN ON
THE HUDSON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, Oct. 24)  
(lh) 
 By SUZANNE MacNEILLE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOTOGRAPHY IN TUSCANY
</P>
<P>
   Q. I'd like the names of photography workshops in Tuscany. I
understand they fill up quickly, so I'd like to make arrangements
as early as possible for next year. _ Randy Chase, Burlington, Vt.
</P>
<P>
   A. Tuscany, Italy, with its lovely towns and serene countryside,
is a popular region for photography workshops, and tour operators
say their programs often do fill up early. But you may be a little
too early; some have not yet finalized the details of next year's
programs, but expect to do so in the next few months.
</P>
<P>
   Toscana Photographic Workshops holds sessions every year in
Buonconvento, a small town near Montalcino. Next year, about 60
one-week workshops will run from June to August. Several weekend
sessions will be offered in September and October. Students and
teachers are housed in traditional Tuscan estates. The classes are
limited to 14 students, and prices begin at $1,350 a week including
accommodations and workshop and lab fees. Information: (39-05) 1636
0519, fax (39-05) 1399 626; Web address www.tpw.it.
</P>
<P>
   For one week each summer, the Toscana Foto Festival in Massa
Marittima, a small city in the foothills of the Colline
Metallifere, presents workshops (this year they ran from July 11 to
18). They cover portraits, fashion, infrared and news photography.
Courses are limited to 20 people and cost from $352 to $468.
Housing in small hotels is extra and ranges between $250 and $400 a
week, double occupancy. Meals are not included. Information:
(39-05) 6690 2756, fax (39-05) 6694 0095; www.cometanet.it/tff. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In Florence, the chief city in Tuscany, Click Up holds fashion
and still-life photography courses throughout the year for
beginning and advanced photographers. Sessions last a minimum of 16
days and range from $1,190 to $1,935. The school also offers
three-day workshops for $365. Prices do not include food or
housing; a list of hotels will be provided on request. Information:
telephone and fax (39-05) 5229 8548; www.clickup.net.
</P>
<P>
   BRITISH DISCOUNT CARDS
</P>
<P>
   Q. I'm planning a trip to England and would like some
information on passes that offer price breaks on transportation and
admission to tourist sites. _ Anita Vine, New York, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   A. There are more than a dozen discount cards and passes you can
choose from, including the following:
</P>
<P>
   Britrail passes, which allow unlimited travel on Britain's rail
network within a designated time frame, must be bought before
leaving home. There are many options. For example, a Flexipass
valid for four days within a two-month period costs $350. Details
are available on the Web at www.Britrail.com. Tickets may be
purchased through Rail Europe's United States office: (888)
422-2748. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The National Express bus company offers a Tourist Trail Pass for
unlimited travel throughout England and Wales. Figured at a rate of
60 pence to the dollar, prices start at $81 for two days within a
three-day period. The passes are available from National Express
bus stations and from travel agents throughout England. In the
United States you can buy Tourist Trail Flexipasses _ which start
at $111 for five days within a 30-day period _ from British Travel
International, Post Office Box 299, Elkton, Va. 22827; (540)
298-1395. Information: (44-121) 625-1122.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A Great British Heritage Pass allows entry to Windsor Castle,
Stonehenge and about 600 historic houses and sites belonging to
such conservation bodies as the National Trust and English
Heritage. A seven-day pass costs $48, 15 days $70, and one month
$93. The cards can be purchased at the Britain Visitor Center, 1
Lower Regent St., London, telephone (44-181) 846-9000, at Tourist
Information Centers throughout England, Scotland and Wales, and at
many U.S. travel agencies. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Go See card provides unlimited access to 17 of London's
major museums and tourist sites, including two recent additions:
Shakespeare's Globe Exhibition and Guided Tour and the new South
Bank IMAX theater. Prices start at $26 for three days. The cards
may be purchased from participating museums or through travel
agencies in the United States and England. The Web site is
www.london-gosee.com. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For more information, contact the British Tourist Authority, 551
Fifth Ave., Suite 701, New York, NY 10176, (800) 462-2748, fax
(212) 986-1188.
</P>
<P>
   HALLOWEEN ON THE HUDSON
</P>
<P>
   Q. I'm entertaining my two Halloween-obsessed nephews, ages 5
and 8, next weekend. Do you know of any events in the Hudson
Valley? _ Patricia Buford, New York, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   A. Scary stories, costume parades and guaranteed ghost sightings
are among your options.
</P>
<P>
   Historic Hudson Valley, which manages several historic houses
along the river, has organized a Legend of Sleepy Hollow Weekend at
the Philipsburg Manor and Sunnyside estates Friday through Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday and Saturday, from 6 to 9 p.m., visitors to
Philipsburg Manor in Sleepy Hollow, about 25 miles north of New
York, can wander the grounds, which will be haunted by ghosts and
other frightening characters, including the Catskill Witch and the
Headless Horseman. Spooky tales will be told in the 18th-century
barn. From 10 a.m. to 4 p.m. on Saturday and Sunday, there will be
more storytelling, as well as games, pumpkin carving and
demonstrations of traditional farming techniques.
</P>
<P>
   A 10-minute drive away, at Sunnyside, Washington Irving's home,
there will be scarecrow-making, shadow-puppet plays and readings
from 10 a.m. to 4 p.m. Saturday and Sunday. Reservations are
required for the haunted woodland walks.
</P>
<P>
   For information and reservations, call (914) 631-8200, extension
628; on the Web, www.hudsonvalley.org. Admission to each site is
$8, $5 for ages 5 to 17.
</P>
<P>
   On the other side of the Hudson River, the town of Nyack (an
hour's drive from New York) will be host to its 14th annual
Halloween Parade, which the town claims is one of the largest
outside New York City, attracting some 30,000 spectators. It's an
elaborate community event, with theme floats, school bands and
hundreds of Halloween revelers showing off their costumes. The
parade is scheduled to begin at 5:30 p.m. on Saturday at McCalman
Field on Midland Avenue. Assembly is at 4 p.m. Anyone can join in.
Adults must pay a $2 registration fee if they wish to be judged in
the best-costume contest. Prizes will be awarded in Memorial Park.
Information: (914) 353-2221.
</P>
</TEXT>
