<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-BRIEFS-$ADV24-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MASK EXHIBIT; SOUTH AFRICAN ROAD SAFETY; Y2K WARNINGS; CELEBRATING
PICASSO 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mo., Ill., Texas, )   (For release Sunday, Oct. 24)  
(lh) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEHIND THE MYSTERIES OF MASKS
</P>
<P>
   Over the millenniums, masks have been disguises, ritual objects,
protective instruments, mystical sources of strength, scarifying
devices and _ often _ works of art. Nearly 150 choice examples are
on view through Jan. 2 at the St. Louis Art Museum in ``Masks:
Faces of Culture.'' Thirty of them will be shown with their
complete costumes. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Drawn from nearly 50 countries on six continents, ``Masks''
explores design, imagery and purpose of masks, which can be found
in nearly every culture, age and region.
</P>
<P>
   The exhibition includes familiar faces, like an Egyptian mummy
mask and an Apollo 15 space helmet, and introduces lesser known
examples, particularly from rural Europe, Central America and
Siberia. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Organized thematically, the exhibition begins with a gallery
that studies the Paleolithic origins of masks, starting with a
reproduction of the Lascaux caves in France, where the earliest
known image of a mask, used by hunters 17,000 years ago, was found.
</P>
<P>
   Next comes a section of ritual and celebratory masks that were
used to signify coronations and changes in status or title.
</P>
<P>
   A section on festival masks features 25 costume ensembles and
masks from Caribbean, Mexican, African and European carnivals and
rites of renewal. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Then there are the masquerade pieces in ``Men as Women,'' and an
area with masks that figured in Greek, Japanese Noh and other
theater traditions. Darth Vader's facial armor and Scar's mask from
``The Lion King'' are on view, too.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Masks'' will move to the Field Museum in Chicago, Feb. 19 to
May 14, 2000, and to the Museum of Fine Arts in Houston, June 25
through Oct. 1. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The St. Louis Art Museum, 1 Fine Arts Drive in the Forest Park
section, is open Tuesday through Sunday, and admission is free.
Admission to ``Masks'' is $8, $6 for students and seniors, $4 for
children. Information: (314) 721-0072, extension 204, or
www.slam.org.
</P>
<P>
   _ JUDITH H. DOBRZYNSKI
</P>
<P>
   SOUTH AFRICA MOVES TO CUT HIGHWAY DEATHS
</P>
<P>
   South African authorities say that the government is stepping up
efforts to make the country's notorious roads safer after a bus
crash last month killed 26 British tourists and highlighted the
dangers of driving in South Africa. Earlier this month, even as
reform measures were being considered, 19 people were killed and
dozens hurt in a crash in the Eastern Cape Province, bringing the
death toll to 79 in less than three weeks. Even by the standards of
South Africa, where speeding, drunken driving and unlicensed
drivers are common and traffic enforcement is rare, the toll has
been remarkably high. President Thabo Mbeki and others have worried
publicly about the effect that the bus crashes will have on the
country's reputation, which is already suffering because of its
high crime rate. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The most significant step taken so far has been to lower the
speed limit for long-haul buses, to 62 miles an hour from 75. A
number of other ideas remain on the drawing board, most notably
proposals that buses receive annual inspections and that passengers
on long-distance bus trips be required to wear seat belts. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   South Africa's Automobile Association says that unless the
government also hires more traffic enforcement officers and makes
it harder to get licenses and easier to lose them, the country will
continue to have too many car accidents, according to Petro Kruger,
an association spokeswoman. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A total of 9,068 people died in motor-vehicle accidents last
year, which, based on a population of 42 million, the number the
Transportation Department works from, means nearly 22 out of every
100,000. (Last year's figure for the United States, according to
the U.S. Department of Transportation, was 15.3 per 100,000.)
</P>
<P>
   With many new bus companies popping up in recent years, visitors
to South Africa should do what they can to check out the carriers
they will be using, Ms. Kruger said. The Automobile Association,
(27-11) 799-1736, will provide basic information about companies'
reputations and safety records.
</P>
<P>
   _ HENRI CAUVIN
</P>
<P>
   A BRITISH WEB SITE OFFERS Y2K ALERTS
</P>
<P>
   If you plan to travel by rail in Japan on Dec. 31, don't panic
if the train suddenly stops at midnight. The interruption, expected
to last only 10 minutes, is intended by Japan Rail as a precaution
against Y2K disruption. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If you are in Britain or France, and plan to celebrate the new
century whizzing through the Channel Tunnel by train, forget about
it _ Eurotunnel has canceled all commercial trains through the
tunnel on the night of Dec. 31. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   These travel tidbits, with implicit warnings, are among the many
that can be be found on a Web site inaugurated last month by
Britain's Foreign Office (www.fco.gov.uk). Designed as a guide for
the British public and British businesses, the Web site consists of
``country statements'' relating to the Y2K preparedness of other
countries _ 55 as of this writing, expected to increase to about
100. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Among other implicit warnings are not to find yourself short of
cash in Taiwan at the end of the year, because banks there will be
closed from Dec. 31 through Jan. 3, 2000, to avoid the risk of
disruption. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In fact, if you travel abroad at all over New Year's, be aware
that money may be hard to come by. In Mexico, for example, the
central bank is working with its U.S. and Canadian counterparts to
increase the number of notes and coins in circulation from late
December through early January. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As might be expected, most developed countries come off well in
the Foreign Office ``statements.'' While the Web site states that
almost anything can happen, it says that little disruption is
likely to occur in most major cities of North America, Western
Europe or Asia (including Japan and Thailand), or in Australia,
Brazil, Hong Kong or New Zealand. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Travelers to the United States are warned about ``problems with
the potential readiness of airports and transit services in small
communities and rural areas.'' The site also notes that while the
pharmaceutical industry is ready for the date change, there may be
supply problems if people decide to stockpile prescriptions. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Potential problems exist in Russia _ where 400 of the 00
airports are described by a Russian official quoted by the Foreign
Office as ``sure to have some Y2K difficulties'' _ and in China
(where ``hospitals face the problem of large numbers of items of
equipment with imbedded chips and the difficulties in getting
adequate information from suppliers''). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Those shortcomings could be rectified by the end of the year,
but anyone traveling to either country would be wise not to count
on it.
</P>
<P>
   CELEBRATING PICASSO IN BARCELONA
</P>
<P>
   The Picasso Museum in Barcelona, Spain, will hold a double
inauguration on Tuesday, adding two medieval mansions to its
exhibition space and unveiling in them what the museum considers to
be its most important temporary exhibition ever, ``Picasso:
Interior and Exterior Landscape,'' on view through Jan. 30. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The expanded museum, which opened in 1963 in a former
13th-century mansion, now comprises five adjacent medieval
mansions, or palaces, on Montcada Street, Nos. 15 to 23. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The gray stone Gothic buildings, with significant Renaissance
and neo-classical renovations, belonged to local gentry until they
were bought successively by the Barcelona City Hall for the museum.
The museum expanded into a second mansion in 1970 and a third in
1982. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The newest additions, which increase the museum's size by a
third, will be used for temporary exhibitions, starting with the
show on landscapes. It features 117 paintings and 95 drawings,
engravings and ceramics, lent by 13 foreign museums, including the
Museum of Modern Art in New York and the Picasso Museum in Paris,
as well as by private collectors. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The show focuses on Picasso's art from 1917 until his death in
1973, including his Cubist work. That complements the museum's
permanent collection, on display in the first three mansions, which
is strong on his formative work from 1890 to 1904, encompassing his
Blue Period (1901-1904) and the years 1895 to 1904, when he lived
in Barcelona not far from the museum. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The museum, (34) 93-319-6310, is open Tuesday to Saturday from
10 a.m. to 8 p.m. and Sunday from 10 a.m. to 3 p.m. Closed Monday.
Admission to the permanent collection is $4.50; the temporary
exhibition is $5.15 and a ticket for full access is $7.75.
</P>
<P>
   _ AL GOODMAN
</P>
</TEXT>
