<HEADLINE>
MORE FLIGHTS TO THE CARIBBEAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, Oct. 24)  
(lh) 
 By EDWIN McDOWELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Caribbean has long held a special allure for vacationers,
but even today the logistics involved for most Americans to get to
such islands as Nevis, St. Vincent, Bequia and St. Bart's usually
require a minimum of three flights, including at least one leg on a
puddle jumper. Not only does that make even a long weekend to those
islands nearly impossible, it also cuts deeply into a vacation. And
after American Airlines replaced most jets with turboprops last
year on routes between San Juan and other Caribbean islands, travel
time to many Caribbean destinations increased even more.
</P>
<P>
   But this winter, help is on the way, with more flights to more
Caribbean destinations.
</P>
<P>
   On Nov. 1, shortly before the start of prime vacation season in
the Caribbean, Trans World Airlines will begin adding nonstop
round-trip flights to San Juan, Puerto Rico _ but not the one or
two extra flights that airlines usually add during high season at
beach or ski resorts. TWA will add 12 daily flights year round _ a
400 percent increase over its current three nonstops. Eight of the
new flights will serve six cities on the mainland; Los Angeles;
Fort Lauderdale, Fla., and Orlando, Fla., will have TWA service to
San Juan for the first time. A fourth and fifth daily flight will
depart from Kennedy Airport in New York, and in Boston, the current
five-day-a-week flight schedule will be replaced with two daily
flights while St. Louis will gain a daily nonstop. TWA will also
add a daily nonstop between San Juan and Aruba, a new market for
TWA, and three daily nonstops between San Juan and Santo Domingo,
Dominican Republic.
</P>
<P>
   Other airlines are increasing service to the Caribbean, where
many officials complain that they are losing tourists who stay over
a night or more to other regions because of limited air service and
high fares. But others in the travel trade, including tour
operators in the United States, cite prices, rundown hotels and
little to do but water sports.
</P>
<P>
   YEAR-ROUND NONSTOP SERVICE
</P>
<P>
   On Oct. 31, United Air Lines will begin nonstop service each
Saturday and Sunday between Chicago and St. Thomas, the U.S. Virgin
Islands, and between Washington and St. Thomas. The flights are
intended to be year-round, not just seasonal. On Dec. 1, Delta Air
Lines will begin first-time nonstop service between Atlanta and
Aruba and Atlanta and St. Maarten, with one flight a day on each
route. Continental Airlines will begin daily nonstops from Newark,
N.J., to St. Thomas on Dec. 16, a route it suspended after
Hurricane Georges damaged much of the island's infrastructure in
1998. And beginning Dec. 18 and continuing at least through June,
it will fly on Saturday from Newark to Cozumel.
</P>
<P>
   American Airlines will begin two daily nonstops Dec. 15 between
Miami and Marsh Harbour, the Bahamas, and the next day TWA will
begin Thursday-to-Monday daily nonstops between La Guardia Airport
and Grand Bahama Island. And US Airways has begun daily nonstop
service between Philadelphia and Nassau. Although not in the
Caribbean, the Bahamas is a member of the Caribbean Tourism
Organization.
</P>
<P>
   While more flights usually mean more convenient schedules and
lower fares, even TWA's big increase in flights to San Juan is
unlikely to bring sizable permanent fare cuts because a big
majority of passengers to Puerto Rico and the Caribbean are leisure
travelers, most of whom fly on discounted advance-purchase fares.
But to call attention to its new nonstops, TWA has a sale on 14-day
advance-purchase fares on those routes for travel originating
between Nov. 1 through Dec. 11 and ending by Dec. 15. These
round-trip fares include Los Angeles to San Juan for $398, instead
of the current $845 (aboard a connecting flight); St. Louis to
Santo Domingo for $348, instead of $627; and New York to Aruba for
$298, instead of $644. Reservations must be made no later than
midnight Nov. 5, and other restrictions apply.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Stelzer, TWA's senior vice president for planning, listed
several reasons why TWA decided to go into Puerto Rico with such an
immediate strong presence. ``American Airlines' decision to serve
the Caribbean largely from Miami provided an opportunity for us,''
he said. Another reason is that the Caribbean has made a gradual
recovery from Hurricane Georges, the strongest storm to hit Puerto
Rico in 70 years. (Last month's Hurricane Floyd inflicted
relatively limited damage.) And, Stelzer said, ``our new planes
have given us the flexibility to go where we expect growth to take
place,'' and the airline expects increased traffic to San Juan and
beyond. TWA is adding 50 jets this year, and will add another 125
in the next few years.
</P>
<P>
   SAN JUAN SEEN AS HUB
</P>
<P>
   Pedro Rosello, the governor of Puerto Rico, expressed gratitude
for TWA's new flights, and if other Caribbean officials are
disappointed that only two of the flights will go someplace other
than to San Juan, they've been careful not to express it. But since
American Airlines pulled most of its jets off its routes between
San Juan and other islands in the spring of 1998, replacing them
with turboprops operated by American Eagle, American's commuter
carrier, officials on those other islands have clamored for more
jet service.
</P>
<P>
   American Airlines said that it substituted turboprops because
flying jets on those routes cost it millions of dollars. TWA has
apparently made a similar calculation, since its passengers
connecting to TWA in San Juan for other islands will travel on
19-seat Beechcraft turboprops. Beginning in mid-November, pending
government approval, Trans World Connection, TWA's commuter airline
operated by Gulfstream International, will fly from San Juan to St.
Thomas, St. Croix, St. Kitts and St. Maarten. Early next year it
will add Tortola and Virgin Gorda, bringing the number of Trans
World Connection flights to more than 50 a day. Each of those
destinations will be new for TWA except St. Maarten.
</P>
<P>
   Other airlines are also adding first-time service in the region.
They include United and Continental, which will begin new service
on Nov. 1 between San Juan and St. Thomas, St. Croix, St. Maarten
and St. Kitts, a result of separate code-share flights with
Gulfstream. On Nov. 19, American Eagle will add seasonal flights
from San Juan to Anguilla, Tortola, St. Kitts and St. Maarten, and
on Dec. 2 will reinstate a daily round-trip between San Juan and
Grenada. Last month it started a daily nonstop between San Juan and
Port-au-Prince.
</P>
<P>
   Two Caribbean airlines are also expanding service to the United
States. A few months ago BWIA added twice-weekly nonstop flights
from Kennedy Airport to St. Kitts. Air Jamaica, which has almost 50
flights a day between the United States and the Caribbean,
including three daily flights to Atlanta, recently began flying
five nonstops a week between Kennedy and Barbados, continuing to
St. Lucia, and two nonstops between Kennedy and Grenada, continuing
to St. Lucia, as part of a code share with Delta. And in one case,
a new airline has been added. Philip J. Pierre, tourism minister of
St. Lucia, announced that a new regional airline, Eastern Caribbean
Express, will begin operations to at least a half-dozen islands
next year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
