<HEADLINE>
LITTLE CHIP, BIG BUSINESS: INDUSTRY MAKES NOISE OVER TINY DSP
SEMICONDUCTORS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Photo available on NYT database) 
 
By TRICIA SERJU-HARRIS 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ After placing a pair of black headphones over your
ears, the sound in the room becomes slightly muffled.
</P>
<P>
   People across the room explaining the controls for the digital
music player in your hand can still be heard. A phone rings in a
distant office.
</P>
<P>
   The staff at Texas Instruments' campus in the Houston-area city
of Stafford point out a special feature on the Lyra digital audio
player _ a simple button labeled ``DSP.''
</P>
<P>
   Then something happens that makes these seemingly ordinary
headphones turn magical.
</P>
<P>
   You push the button and all outside noise _ the people talking
across the table, the phone ringing down the hall _ disappears,
replaced by the purest quality of music ever heard.
</P>
<P>
   Though digital signal processors _ specialized semiconductors
that can be programmed _ can be found in virtually every mobile
telephone, they are quickly finding their way into a host of new
consumer products.
</P>
<P>
   ``The evolution of the digital world will be powered by DSP,''
boasts Leon Adams, worldwide DSP strategic marketing manager at
Texas Instruments. ``The applications are unlimited.''
</P>
<P>
   DSP is considered by Texas Instruments to be the processor that
will take consumers closer to the technology-rich world of ``Star
Trek,'' with such products as portable universal translators.
</P>
<P>
   ``It may look like science fiction, but it's our digital
future,'' proclaims Texas Instruments in a video on DSP technology.
</P>
<P>
   Companies that make DSP chips, including Texas Instruments,
Lucent Technologies and Motorola, are quickly making deals with
companies like Cisco Systems, which makes routers and servers for
the Internet, and Thomson Electronics, which makes the Lyra and
other electronic products.
</P>
<P>
   IBM said in September it would use DSPs from Texas Instruments
in upcoming versions of its Aptiva personal computers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The DSP is already in the cordless phone. In fact, there are
already more DSPs than (personal computers),'' said Sidney Burrus,
dean of the George R. Brown School of Engineering at Rice
University.
</P>
<P>
   One of the benefits of DSP is that apart from being a fast chip,
it specializes in turning analog signals _ such as sound or light _
into digital information that can then be manipulated.
</P>
<P>
   For example, a DSP-enhanced speakerphone could be used in
conference calls to isolate the voice of one individual while
eliminating all extraneous noise.
</P>
<P>
   With DSP, sound is turned into data, and the processor is
controlled by software that tells the chip to look for a speaker's
voice. The voice is enhanced, allowing that person to come through
digitally clear.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the first applications of DSPs include:
</P>
<P>
   _ Internet audio players that allow music to be downloaded off
the Web and played on devices that are smaller than a deck of
cards.
</P>
<P>
   _ Broadband modems that dramatically increase Internet
connection speeds.
</P>
<P>
   _ Digital still cameras.
</P>
<P>
   _ Digital hearing aids.
</P>
<P>
   But the DSP is more than gee-whiz. It's also big biz.
</P>
<P>
   The use of DSPs has grown 26 percent since 1998, partly because
the tiny devices are flexible and can fit into new, fast-changing
niches. Projections have the market jumping to $13.6 billion in
2003 from $3.5 billion last year.
</P>
<P>
   Recognizing three years ago that DSPs were going to be a
struggling company's salvation, Texas Instruments _ better known in
its heyday for making calculators and guidance systems that guided
bombs during the Persian Gulf War _ decided to focus most, if not
all, of its corporate energy on improving and selling the DSP.
</P>
<P>
   It's clear how important this chip is to Texas Instruments. The
company sold off 14 divisions while making 15 acquisitions to build
a stronghold in DSPs and analog chips.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have refocused our company on the DSP and analog segments
of the semiconductor market because they are large, fast-growing
and we have a commanding position in both segments,'' said Greg
Delagi, a Texas Instruments vice president.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Instruments currently leads the industry in the number of
programmable DSPs sold to the worldwide market.
</P>
<P>
   Though the company didn't invent the DSP, it was one of the
pioneers in the DSP industry, introducing the first commercially
viable DSP chip to the market in 1982.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the company has a 47 percent market share, followed by
Lucent Technologies with 28 percent of the DSP market, Motorola
with 13 percent and Analog Devices with 9 percent, said Will
Strauss, president of Forward Concepts, a Tempe, Ariz., market
research firm.
</P>
<P>
   The Dallas-based company also is making large investments in the
study of DSP. In March 1996, it donated $7 million to Rice
University to fund long-term cooperative research projects
involving DSP and information engineering.
</P>
<P>
   ``We work on longer-term research ideas, not on product ideas,''
Burrus said.
</P>
<P>
   Cisco Systems has used the company's DSPs in several of its
products, including remote access servers, which provides Internet
users dial-up access, and multiservice access routers, which direct
data flow on the Net.
</P>
<P>
   ``DSPs are a fundamental device in fueling the convergence that
is taking place in the telecommunications and data networking
industry today,'' said Lou Santora, vice president of engineering
for Cisco's Remote Access Business Unit, adding that DSP chips
becoming more powerful and less expensive.
</P>
<P>
   DSPs vary range in price from $2 each to $200 each, based on the
needs of the applications.
</P>
<P>
   According to Forward Concepts, Texas Instruments' DSP chips are
found in one out of three modems shipped worldwide; one out of two
digital cellular phones shipped worldwide; and in nine out of 10
high-performance disk drives shipped globally.
</P>
<P>
   ``The increased functions, better call quality, smaller size and
better battery life in the cellular phone are good examples of what
DSP technology is enabling,'' Delagi said.
</P>
<P>
   Among its other myriad uses are helping consumers shop online
and doctors assist with operations using Web technology.
</P>
<P>
   ``DSP is a lot like the peanut,'' said TI's Adams. ``It's
incredible what you can do with it.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
