<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-18 18:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0841 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-TV-NEWSHOUR-NYT &LR;      10-18 0951
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-NEWSHOUR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRITIC'S NOTEBOOK: NOW A WORD FROM OUR SPON ... UH, UM ... OUR
FRIEND 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By WALTER GOODMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Fans of the PBS ``Newshour'' must have noticed by now, with
gratitude let's hope, that the program has gained two new
correspondents.
</P>
<P>
   Gwen Ifill, lately of NBC, and Ray Suarez, from National Public
Radio, made their debut with informed and informative interviews,
she on the new Supreme Court season, he on the mega-merger between
Sprint and MCI Worldcom.
</P>
<P>
   On a busy news day, they were joined by Jim Lehrer, the
program's proprietor, who talked with Defense Secretary William
Cohen about the debate over the nuclear test ban treaty, and by
Margaret Warner, who took a look at the Gore campaign. Terence
Smith was off for the evening, but as media correspondent since he
joined up last year, he has been doing an enterprising job on a
significant beat.
</P>
<P>
   We all have our ``Newshour'' favorites as well as features we
can do without. I tired of hearing from Mark Shields and Paul Gigot
even before they began popping up on cable, and I rarely find the
round tables of editors and other folks from here and there
particularly stimulating. Still, they all have their good nights.
</P>
<P>
   More steadily reliable are Kwame Holman, who has been with the
program since 1983 and seems able to get the gist of any subject on
short notice, and Paul Solman, who brings energy and an appropriate
touch of skepticism to his reports on business.
</P>
<P>
   Despite innovations, the interviews with officials and with
experts remain the inimitable strength of the ``Newshour.'' Its
chronic problem is the periodic lapse into formula, owing to a
guest who doesn't have much to say or the knack to say it or to a
desperate interviewer who settles for questions like ``And what do
you think about that, senator?'' Some evenings can be wearing, and
the hope is that fresh high-quality talent can stave off the
occasional yawn.
</P>
<P>
   But such talent cannot come cheap. Even if Ms. Ifill took a cut
from her pay as a commercial-network personality, she must command
a substantial salary by PBS standards, and presumably nobody wants
to court a discrimination suit by paying Suarez much less. Where is
``Newshour'' getting the money for its evidently increased budget?
Alas, the answer in part must be the commercials that have grown
like sores on this purportedly noncommercial endeavor.
</P>
<P>
   Although the commercialization of public broadcasting is being
done discreetly (the ``Newshour'' viewers who time their watching
can avoid the plugs with which the program begins and ends),
advertising of any sort runs smack against the ideal of public
broadcasting as an oasis in a desert of marketing.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the ads are more stylish than others, but all are an
affront to the highest hopes of the enterprise. There is something
about a commercial that does not love common sense. On the
``Newshour,'' only the Mercedes-Benz ads, with their droll use of
old movies and their understated, allusive lines, can give viewers
the feeling that they are watching something approaching a level of
sophistication that public broadcasting proclaims for itself at
fund-raising time.
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise the high-class audience has to settle for vacuous
slogans from the CIT group about ``money well lent'' and the
dismaying sounds of David Brinkley ending his career as a flack for
Archer Daniels Midland. (Maybe that's grist for Smith.)
</P>
<P>
   The grants from foundations, like the Pew Charitable Trusts,
which supports Smith's work, and the Henry J. Kaiser Family
Foundation, which pays for the new ``Newshour'' unit on health
policy and Social Security, come without the commercial stigma, but
they do not suffice.
</P>
<P>
   To the degree that programs even as distinguished as the
``Newshour'' have to succumb to market imperatives, it puts the
nation on notice that public broadcasting in the United States is
fated never to be able to make it in an unadulterated form. I don't
mean that Lehrer and his associates are in imminent peril of going
soft on Archer Daniels Midland, a company that evidently hopes to
shine up its spotty image by association with the likes of Lehrer
and Brinkley. But the influence cannot be wholesome. The
``messages'' themselves are an insult to viewers' intelligence.
</P>
<P>
   This is not by way of begrudging Ms. Ifill (a former
correspondent for The New York Times), Suarez or the rest of the
``Newshour'' team their good fortune: as things go on television
news, they are doing more than most to earn their salaries. What is
disheartening is that in the clutter of what passes as news on the
networks, on cable, on the Internet, so little remains untouched by
merchandising.
</P>
<P>
   Even on the best of the commercial news programs, soft features
keep gaining (no day seems to pass without attention to a medical
wonder) and international news is slighted. Journalists become
entertainers, and production gizmos proliferate even while the
programs cover the same stories in the same ways.
</P>
<P>
   An hour given to Supreme Court issues and the ramifications of a
corporate merger and a nuclear treaty will not be found anywhere
but on the ``Newshour,'' but such reporting is not deemed important
enough for a government subsidy that would completely free it from
advertising.
</P>
<P>
   So, welcome, Mr. Suarez; welcome, Ms. Ifill. May you do the jobs
you are capable of doing unhindered by advertisers. I hope you feel
you are being paid your due. I am sure that despite the grouching
of critics, you can accept your good fortune in good conscience.
You deserve a gibberish-free environment; it's not your fault if
that is inconceivable in a gibberish-dominated public forum.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
