<HEADER>
A0843 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT     10-18 0410
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
 (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Tuesday, Oct. 19, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call 212-556-4204.) 
(th) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The weather pattern in the East resembles a situation that would
precede a snowstorm during the winter. Expansive high pressure
building into New England will transport unseasonably chilly, dry
air into the region. A disturbance moving through the Great Lakes
will draw milder, moist air northward into the Mississippi Valley.
</P>
<P>
   The boundary with warm, humid air along the Gulf Coast will
become active with a band of showers spreading northeast toward the
Ohio Valley. However, the air mass is generally not cold enough to
sustain snow and the disturbances are too weak to produce
widespread precipitation. There could be a narrow swath of wet snow
later Tuesday night in the northern Appalachians.
</P>
<P>
   Sunshine will dominate the Northeast, though clouds will spread
quickly into the Middle Atlantic States. Increasing onshore winds
in the Southeast will trigger a few showers near the Carolina
coast. The weather will turn dull and cool in the Ohio Valley ahead
of a weak cold front.
</P>
<P>
   Mixed rain and snow showers are expected in the upper Middle
West. A surge of warmer, humid air from the Gulf of Mexico will
rise over the dome of cool air in the South causing abundant clouds
and patches of showers from the East Texas coast to Kentucky.
</P>
<P>
   Upslope flow along the east slopes of the Rockies in southern
Colorado and New Mexico will lead to low elevation drizzle and wet
snow in the mountains. High pressure over the northern Rockies
should sponsor sunny and warmer weather from the Southwest to the
north Pacific Coast.
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: SECOND PEAK
</P>
<P>
   The peak of the hurricane season occurred about five weeks ago,
on September 11, the date on which more than 90 percent of the
time, a tropical storm or hurricane is present in the Atlantic
Ocean or Gulf of Mexico. However, during the declining days of the
hurricane season, there is a smaller maximum in the frequency of
storms that takes place in the middle of October. Indeed, the
emergence of hurricane Irene late last week and now tropical storm
Jose, which formed Monday near the Windward Islands, matches this
lesser peak in tropical storms. Both storms come after a three-week
lull in activity in the Tropics.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
