<HEADLINE>
WILDLIFE WATCHERS HAVE A LOT TO LOOK AT IN CALIFORNIA'S PACIFIC
WATERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (dw) 
 By GEORGE LAUER   
 The Press Democrat, Santa Rosa, Calif.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTA ROSA, Calif. _ This is an unusual year in the Pacific
waters off Northern California.
</P>
<P>
   Wildlife watchers are spotting record numbers of blue whales and
sea birds. Gray whales are dining differently _ in new spots, on
different food and at different times _ and dying in inordinate
numbers up and down their migration trail from Mexico to
Washington. Huge eruptions of bait fish, krill and algae are
showing up in unusual circumstances up and down the coast.
</P>
<P>
   All this may be a series of coincidences, insignificant in the
larger picture. They may be connected to residual effects of El
Nino, or tidal shifts or weather changes or some other influences
no one has considered yet. But no matter what the cause, the effect
is a particularly good year to watch wildlife on the ocean.
</P>
<P>
   Oceanic Society Expeditions, which operates regular
whale-watching day trips from San Francisco, has logged in the past
two months the most productive trips in the organization's 27-year
history. In August, on one of the society's trips through the Gulf
of the Farallones National Marine Sanctuary, whale watchers saw 30
blue whales, a one-day record. In September, another one-day trip
spotted 32 seabird species, a record in the Society's 16 years of
keeping records of bird sightings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Usually, I make a big deal about talking about how these are
not whale-watching trips, they're wildlife expeditions,'' says
David Wimpfheimer, the naturalist who led the Oceanic Society's
record sea bird trip in September. ``I like to stress that we're
looking at all kinds of marine life because sometimes you just
don't see whales. But that really hasn't been the case this year.
We're seeing a lot of whales as well as a lot of other wildlife.''
</P>
<P>
   Marine experts up and down the Western seaboard agree.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a very exciting time on the ocean right now,'' said
Will Borgeson, aquarist at the University of California Bodega
Marine Lab. ``The weather is fairly clement, making it easy for us
to observe things and we're seeing some significant algae blooms,
some krill and bait fish in places we don't generally see them.''
</P>
<P>
   For several days off Bodega Bay last month, acres of ocean were
turned into a chocolate sea, an eerily matte reddish brown that
robbed the water of its usual luster. Known as a ``red tide,'' the
dinoflagellate algae bloom attracted swarms of bait fish
(anchovies, most likely), which in turn attracted all kinds of
larger life under water _ whales, dolphins, seals, sea lions _ and
hundreds of birds above water.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're a little at a loss to explain it all, but there's no
question this is proving to be a very productive year along our
coast,'' said John Calambokidis, one of the most respected whale
researchers in the West.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last couple of weeks off Bodega Bay down to Point Reyes,
for instance, we saw 20 to 30 blue whales and large concentrations
of sea birds in specific areas, and that puzzles us,'' Calambokidis
said. ``If the numbers are up significantly of a certain species,
you'd think there would be a more dispersed distribution, but it
doesn't seem to be working out that way.''
</P>
<P>
   At some spots along the coast, probably where the krill is more
plentiful, blues are coming closer to shore in larger numbers than
usual. Krill, a pink shrimplike creature the size and shape of a
chubby earthworm, travel in huge swarms and are the favorite food
of the gigantic blue whale, the largest creature ever to live on
earth. Blues, which can grow 100 feet long and weigh more than 200
tons, have to eat several tons of krill a day. They go where
pickings are plentiful and easy.
</P>
<P>
   Calambokidis said the West Coast hot spots this year appear to
be from Bodega Bay to the Farallones, parts of the Monterey Marine
Sanctuary and the Santa Barbara Channel.
</P>
<P>
   Calambokidis is associated with Cascadia Research in Olympia,
Wash., which is conducting a whale photo identification project.
Over the past 14 years, Cascadia has individually identified more
than 1,000 blue whales and more than 800 humpback whales along the
California coast. Pigmentation and other unique markings on flukes,
fins and heads allow researchers to identify individuals.
</P>
<P>
   They don't get names. ``We give them affectionate numbers,''
Calambokidis said with a chuckle.
</P>
<P>
   The research has revealed larger populations of blues and
humpbacks along the California coast than previously thought.
Cascadia estimates about 2,000 blue whales and about 700 humpback
whales call California's coastline home.
</P>
<P>
   Research has shown low reproductive rates among humpbacks in
these waters.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't know why, just like we don't know why so many grays
are dying this year,'' Calambokidis said.
</P>
<P>
   So far this year, more than 40 grays have washed up dead or been
stranded along California's shore. Last year's total was 30.
</P>
<P>
   Gray whales are typically bottom feeders. They suck up sediment
from the ocean floor, sift out nourishing organisms and jettison
the rest. This year, they've been spotted out of season along their
migration trail, lunge feeding on krill and eating bait fish, like
their cousins, the blues and humpbacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their unusual behavior and their high mortality rate all
suggest some sort of food related problems,'' Calambokidis said.
``We're concerned, certainly, but this could just be a cyclical
thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Such close scrutiny of whales is a relatively new thing so it's
difficult for researchers to see the big patterns.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're kind of hard pressed to say what normal is,'' he said.
``We can certainly say this is an unusual year, but beyond that, we
just don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   (The Press Democrat in Santa Rosa, Calif., is part of the New
York Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
