<HEADER>
A0864 &Cx1f; ttf-z
u v BC-EARLY-FRONTPAGE-NYT &LR;      10-18 0766
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EARLY-FRONTPAGE-NYT </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (gm) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Tuesday, Oct. 19 Page 1. The NYT frontpage advisory, with layout
description, will move by 7:30 p.m. ET. The NYT News Service Night
Supervisor is Pat Ryan. (888-346-9867).
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-BANK (Undated) _ How a Russian emigre with a physics
degree and scant business experience ended up running (or being
front man for) a company that handles billions of dollars and is at
the center of the money-laundering inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   A Special Report by Timothy O'Brien; 3,500 words. With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   ALBRIGHT-AFRICA (Freetown, Sierra Leone) _ Shortly after holding
a three-year old girl with a missing arm, Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright on Monday met the leaders of a rebellion known
for hacking off the limbs of civilians and urged them to stick to a
fragile peace agreement to end this country's eight-year civil war.
Albright was on the first day of a week-long visit through Africa.
By Norimitsu Onishi.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   WEB-CAMPAIGNING (Undated) _ The modern campaign headquarters is
no longer a rented storefront decorated with bumper stickers,
bunting and empty soda cans. It is open any hour of the day or
night. And it isn't a place at all, just an address starting with
www. If in 1996 a candidate could prove hipness simply by posting
an electronic version of a campaign brochure on the World Wide Web,
White House hopefuls for 2000 are learning to use their Internet
sites to raise money and rally troops. The Web page is the new
whistle stop, a way for candidates to bring their messages to more
people a day than they can reach on the campaign trail. By Tina
Kelley.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   PUERTORICO-NAVY (Washington) _ A presidential panel recommended
Monday that the U.S. military be allowed to resume live firing
exercises at a Navy base in Puerto Rico but ordered the range shut
down in five years, despite demands from the territory's governor
that the base be closed immediately and all bombing halted. Since
April, when a Marine pilot killed a Puerto Rican guard in a bombing
accident on the Vieques base, Puerto Rican activists have occupied
the base while the territory's politicians have argued that the
base represents an unacceptable threat to the island's livelihood
and environment. By Elizabeth Becker.
</P>
<P>
   NY-PSYCHOLOGISTS-UNION (New York) _ The New York State
Psychologists Association is joining the American Federation of
Teachers, making it the first time in the nation that such a group
is joining a union. The group is unhappy with managed care and a
push by psychiatrists to limit the scope of psychologists'
practice. By Steven Greenhouse. (1200 words)
</P>
<P>
   Reefers:
</P>
<P>
   NISSAN-CUTBACK (Tokyo) _ The Nissan Motor Co. has stunned Japan
and the global automotive industry with details of an unprecedented
overhaul plan that makes cuts far deeper than had been expected at
the No. 3 Japanese auto maker and will reverberate throughout the
economy. Under the plan, designed by the company's aggressive new
chief operating officer, Carlos Ghosn, Nissan will close three
plants, eliminate 21,000 jobs, halve its supplier base, close 10
percent of dealerships and return to profitability in the next
fiscal year, which will start April 1. By Stephanie Strom.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-ASTHMA (Undated) _ For most people with asthma, the proper
use of medication, education and self-management can go a long way
to keeping them out of the emergency room functioning at home,
school or work, experts say. But sadly, many patients with the
diseases fail to adhere to the regimen and many others simply do
not understand it. By Denise Grady.
</P>
<P>
   With photo and graphic.
</P>
<P>
   STOCKS-MARKETPLACE (New York) _ Twelve years ago, the stock
market crashed in the largest one-day fall ever. Now, by some
measures, the stock market is even more volatile than it was then.
Volatility can sharply increase, as it did in 1980, when a leading
sector _ then, energy stocks _ has risen to unsupportable
valuations. It is possible that the current surge in volatility is
foretelling a similar turn in this era's dominant sector,
technology. Not all increases in volatility, however, tell such
stories. New ways of trading, brought on by technology and
financial engineering, can roil the markets until other traders
become used to the impacts generated by such trading. That was true
of institutional block trading in the 1970s and computerized index
arbitrage in the 1980s. And it may be true now of Internet-based
day trading. By Floyd Norris.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
