<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-18 18:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0866 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-MCCAIN-2000-HNS &LR;      10-18 0855
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCAIN-2000-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 
MOLINARI STUNS REPUBLICANS BY SWITCHING FROM BUSH TO McCAIN  
 
By GREG McDONALD 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., stole one of Gov. George
W. Bush's most influential New York backers Monday, dealing a blow
to the Texan's presidential campaign in a crucial state.
</P>
<P>
   In a move that stunned Republicans around the country, Staten
Island Borough President and former U.S. Rep. Guy Molinari publicly
withdrew his support for Bush at a New York news conference and
handed his endorsement to McCain, who stood beaming at his side at
the Vietnam Memorial in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   Molinari, the father of former Rep. Susan Molinari, who has also
endorsed McCain, will become the senator's New York chairman.
</P>
<P>
   Molinari, who ran the 1988 New York campaign of former President
George Bush and urged the governor to follow in his father's
footsteps, said he decided to ``place principle above politics'' by
swinging his support to McCain, whom he described as having a
``fierce streak of independence'' on issues even when they conflict
with those of his own party.
</P>
<P>
   ``Americans are looking for leaders. Sadly, there aren't many
out there anymore who will stand up independently for what they
believe,'' Molinari said. ``Too many candidates, both Democrat and
Republican alike, define their beliefs and shape their convictions
by taking polls. John McCain is a notable exception, and I respect
him for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Referring to Bush as ``the present front-runner'' in the race
for the 2000 GOP nomination, Molinari said he still has ``great
respect and admiration'' for the governor, whom he once called
``the best candidate'' for president in 2000. But Molinari added
that he has no reservations about switching his time and political
resources to helping McCain beat Bush in the New York state primary
March 7.
</P>
<P>
   McCain and Molinari served together in the U.S. House for
several years, and the senator said he was ``humbled'' by his old
friend's decision to back his candidacy. With his help, McCain
said, ``We can win New York.''
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Bush tried to shrug off the the desertion.
``That's what happens in politics,'' he said during an Arizona
campaign stop.
</P>
<P>
   In Austin, Texas, Bush spokeswoman Mindy Tucker also sought to
play down the significance of Molinari's switch by emphasizing that
the governor still has the support of New York's two top elected
Republicans _ Gov. George Pataki and New York Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel like we have a really strong organization in New York,
and we hope to have Guy Molinari's support when Gov. Bush wins the
nomination,'' Tucker said.
</P>
<P>
   Molinari dismissed reports that he decided to pull his support
for the Texas governor because of an on-going feud with Pataki. The
two men, Republican sources said, have often disagreed over how to
direct Bush's New York campaign effort. Their disagreements came to
a head recently when, the sources said, Pataki insisted that Bush
forego a visit to Staten Island earlier this month in favor of
making three stops in Manhattan boroughs considered to be
Democratic strongholds. Molinari was said to have taken the
decision as a ``personal snub.''
</P>
<P>
   The sources said Molinari was also upset over Empire State
Development Corp. Chairman Charles Gargano being recommended by
Pataki to run Bush's state campaign.
</P>
<P>
   But Molinari, when pressed about it, said Pataki ``played no
role'' in his decision.
</P>
<P>
   Although Bush is considered the top contender for the GOP
nomination, McCain has been moving up in recent polls. Bush still
maintains a commanding lead among registered Republicans and
independents.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the senator has declined to criticize or engage Bush
directly on issues, except to say, as he did Monday in a speech to
Vietnam veterans, that he's unclear what Bush's positions on issues
are.
</P>
<P>
   McCain seems in favor of engaging Vice President Al Gore on a
number of issues, including the recent Senate defeat of the
Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty.
</P>
<P>
   McCain challenged Gore, who is running against former Sen. Bill
Bradley for the Democratic nomination, to a debate on the issue
Sunday. He accused Gore of playing politics with the treaty by
remaining silent before the vote and then airing a campaign
commercial critical of Republican senators, including McCain, for
voting to kill it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The vice president was completely absent from the debate. I do
not know of a single senator who was called or written to by Vice
President Gore urging his or her support for the CTBT,'' McCain
said ``I've always found it more useful to support a treaty before
it is actually voted on, but better late than never, I suppose.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If the ... vice president sincerely wants to enhance the
treaty's prospects in the future, he should think about debating
its merits rather than disparaging the motives of its opponents,''
McCain said, reissuing his challenge to Gore to debate the issue.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman said Gore would gladly debate McCain if he became
the Republican nominee.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-18-99 1854EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
