u f BC-STATES-NASA-NAT     10-18 0225
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STATES-NASA-NAT </SLUG>

 &HT;        NASA Awards $20 Million to Small Businesses 
 &HT;     By Alex Canizares  
 &HT;    c. 1999 States News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON, Oct.18 - NASA will give $70,000 each to 220 small
businesses in 34 states for research and development, in the first
phase of a program to help little firms conduct work related NASA
missions that have commercial potential.
</P>
<P>
   Three Houston firms won awards in the first phase of NASA's
Small Business Innovation Research program (SBIR), which will
allocate a combined total of $20 million for 290 research and
development proposals.
</P>
<P>
   Astro Technology of Houston is one of the recipients. The
six-person firm will get $70,000 to develop fiber-optic sensors for
a robotic hand that NASA already uses on its space shuttles.
</P>
<P>
   Astro then hopes to put the sensors on the commercial market for
a variety of uses, such as deep-water oil drilling.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to go after those programs that have commercial
potential,'' said Astro president David Brower.
</P>
<P>
   Congress created SBIR in 1982 to help small businesses conduct
research and development that benefit federal agencies, as well as
the private sector. 40 percent of the proposals chosen for Phase I
will be chosen for Phase II, which will allocate an additional
$600,000 each to proposals that stand a good chance in the
commercial market.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-18-99 1901EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
