<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PAKISTAN-ASSESS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: MILITARY COUP UNLIKELY TO STRENGTHEN DEMOCRACY 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By CELIA W. DUGGER    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW DELHI, India _ Pakistan's new dictator, Gen. Pervaiz
Musharraf, essentially told the nation Sunday that he had to
destroy democracy temporarily to save it.
</P>
<P>
   His was a familiar message in a country where military despots
have ruled for 25 of its 52 years. Many in Pakistan, including some
in the liberal intelligentsia, desperately want to believe in the
general after a decade of corrupt, incompetent and often autocratic
elected leaders.
</P>
<P>
   But if history has a lesson to teach in Pakistan _ a still
feudal society of 150 million where more than two-thirds of adults
cannot read _ it is that each episode of repressive military rule
makes democracy weaker, not stronger, say some social critics and
scholars.
</P>
<P>
   The generals promise democracy, but are too impatient to wait
for voters to boot out bad elected leaders. They give lip service
to an open society, but crush dissent. And when these men,
unschooled in the arts of managing a government or an economy,
finally hand power back to politicians, the problems still loom
large.
</P>
<P>
   With his ramrod demeanor and personal vow of integrity,
Musharraf embodies the hope that an honest tough guy can fix what
ails Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
   In his nationally televised address Sunday evening, he promised
to root out corruption, restore the economy and ``true'' democracy,
show restraint with Pakistan's nuclear arsenal and respect freedom
of the press _ which he somewhat ominously said he trusted would
``play a positive and constructive role.''
</P>
<P>
   He also said that as Pakistan's ``chief executive'' he was ready
to resume talks with its rival and neighbor, India.
</P>
<P>
   This was clearly meant to reassure a world nervously eying a
coup in an avowedly nuclear power, and more particularly the United
States _ which has yet to decide whether to support a continuing
economic bailout _ and which has been pressuring Pakistan to resume
negotiations with India.
</P>
<P>
   Musharraf's offer of talks was regarded with skepticism in
India. The general, who was Pakistan's army chief, is held
responsible here for having brought his country to the brink of
all-out war with India this summer over a portion of the Himalayan
territory of Kashmir called Kargil.
</P>
<P>
   Both countries want Kashmir for their own and their conflict
over the area has flared periodically since they were created from
the British Indian empire in 1947.
</P>
<P>
   If a leader is to judged by his record, Musharraf has not had an
auspicious beginning. The Kargil conflict, the most notable action
of his year-long tenure as army chief, was a diplomatic fiasco. For
more than two months, Indian troops battled to drive out hundreds
of infiltrators now believed to have been mainly Pakistani army
regulars.
</P>
<P>
   Pakistan's incursion ended ignominiously when the now-deposed
prime minister, Nawaz Sharif, bowed to American pressure and called
for the unilateral withdrawal of the Pakistan-backed forces.
</P>
<P>
   Like Pearl Harbor, the operation was brilliant tactically, but
disastrous strategically, said Stephen P. Cohen, an expert on the
Pakistani army at the Brookings Institution in Washington. And
India has not forgotten or forgiven.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a government here which would perceive Pervaiz
Musharraf as the man behind the Kargil misadventure,'' said P.R.
Chari, director of the Institute of Peace and Conflict Studies in
New Delhi. ``So they're not going to feel like kissing and making
up.''
</P>
<P>
   But even those who doubt that relations with India will markedly
improve say it is unlikely the general will create any new large
scale mischief soon because he is confronting a more serious and
immediate problem: Pakistan's crumbling economy.
</P>
<P>
   Its economic lifeline has been endangered by the coup. Pakistan
is awaiting a $280 million installment of a $1.56 billion line of
credit from the International Monetary Fund, but the military
takeover may further jeopardize the loan, which had already been
delayed.
</P>
<P>
   Pakistan is down to about $1.5 billion in foreign exchange
reserves, at most enough to pay for two months of imports _ oil,
food and other essential commodities. Their loss could lead to even
greater hardships for Pakistanis.
</P>
<P>
   The United States, the most important voice in deciding whether
to go forward with the loan, has not yet stated a position.
American officials have condemned the military takeover and called
for a return to democracy, though not for Sharif's restoration. And
they are clearly worried about the prospect of a nuclear-armed
Pakistan disintegrating economically.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, the American ambassador, William B. Milam, described
Musharraf as ``a moderate man who is acting out of patriotic
motivations.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have business with governments, good governments and bad
governments,'' he said. ``We will have to do business with this
government. I don't know how much.''
</P>
<P>
   In the longer term, the military is unlikely to pursue the
deeper social reforms that would produce a more educated, assertive
electorate. Most of Pakistan's federal budget now goes to the
military and debt service. And the military has always jealously
guarded its share.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why is it that Pakistan has not devoted significant resources
to health, education, repairing irrigation canals?'' asked Gowher
Rizvi, a former professor of international relations at Oxford
University who now directs the Ford Foundation's South Asia
operation. ``It's because the military takes the largest chunk of
the budget.''
</P>
<P>
   In his speech, Musharraf said he had had no choice but to
sacrifice a limb (the constitution) in order to save the body (the
nation). But one could also say that Pakistan is like a body
builder who has over-exercised one portion of his anatomy (the
military), while others (democratic institutions) have withered.
</P>
<P>
   The reasons for the weakness of Pakistan's democracy are
complex. It has a landed feudal class that was not subjected to
vigorous land reforms as in India. The country never developed mass
political movements of the poor and oppressed. Its bureaucracy is
highly politicized and corrupt.
</P>
<P>
   And it has a military that sees itself as the last bastion of
honesty and stability _ and has often short-circuited the slow,
painful and flawed democratic process.
</P>
<P>
   ``The military could do good if the leaders of the new
government are truly brilliant, economically informed, politically
adept, principled, tolerant of genuine dissent and protective of
human rights,'' said George Perkovich, a South Asia expert. ``But
men of such virtue are extremely rare anywhere, let alone in
Pakistan.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
