<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-VETO-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON TO MEET WITH GOP LEADERS AFTER VETOING FOREIGN OPERATIONS
SPENDING BILL 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By NANCY MATHIS 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton stepped up his showdown with
Republicans as he vetoed a foreign operations spending bill Monday
and called on congressional leaders to meet with him to resolve the
2000 budget impasse.
</P>
<P>
   GOP leaders, enmeshed in a spending dilemma of their own
creation, agreed to a White House session Tuesday, contending
Clinton has conceded there will be no money taken from the Social
Security surplus. But Clinton accused them of already spending the
surplus, making the issue a moot point.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides said there will be another stopgap spending measure
necessary to avoid a government shutdown. A 21-day temporary
spending agreement expires at midnight Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we're going to finish the job the American people sent us
here to do _ reach real results in educating our children, fighting
crime, protecting the environment _ then we have to put politics
aside and seek common ground,'' Clinton told reporters after
vetoing a $12.6 billion foreign operations bill.
</P>
<P>
   ``In that spirit, I am inviting the congressional leadership to
come here and meet with me and our economic team at the White
House, to see if we can agree on an overall budget framework,''
Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   The session would be the first this year on the budget.
Republicans initially intended to avoid a summit with the president
because they felt they had lost past battles to curtail spending
amid the budget surpluses, an aide said.
</P>
<P>
   House Majority Leader Dick Armey, R-Texas, said the White House
wants to meet with congressional leaders ``to talk about how we can
complete this spending cycle on the budget without touching Social
Security. That's music to my ears.''
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton told reporters that Republicans already have spent
portions of the surplus and ``everyone but them'' has acknowledged
it. He cited a recent Congressional Budget Office report that
Congress was on track to spend $16 billion to $30 billion of Social
Security surplus.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not interested in being able to walk out of here and win a
(political) battle on whether they spent the Social Security
surplus or not _ as a matter of fact, they have, and it's been
acknowledged for months, but that's not the point. The point is, we
need a responsible budget here,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   Armey and other Republicans, however, received a letter from CBO
stating that, using different budget numbers, Congress was not
dipping into the Social Security surplus.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said he vetoed the foreign operations bill because it
excluded his spending priorities, including removing money for the
Middle East peace process and funding to Russia to continue
dismantling some nuclear weapons.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems to me to be the next big chapter in the new American
isolationism right after the Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty,''
Clinton said, linking the foreign operations bill to the Senate's
rejection last week of the treaty banning nuclear weapons tests.
</P>
<P>
   The foreign operations spending bill was $2 billion less than
Clinton requested and $2.7 billion less than the 1999 spending
level.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. J.C. Watts, R-Okla., chairman of the House Republican
Conference, said the GOP version was ``a responsible measure to
make the investments critical to U.S. national security without
spending one penny of the Social Security trust fund.''
</P>
<P>
   There are 13 spending bills, but Congress has yet to complete
work on all of them. The 2000 fiscal year began Oct. 1. The
president has signed five spending bills and rejected two. Three
others are pending on his desk and may face a veto. Congress is
still working on three others, including the Labor, Health and
Human Services and Education bill.
</P>
<P>
   Both Armey and Clinton said a second stopgap spending measure
will be needed this week. Armey said the temporary spending likely
would be extended by another week.
</P>
<P>
   Unable to adhere to their pledge not to spend the Social
Security surplus without major spending cuts, Republican leaders
last week agreed to reduce spending across-the-board in the
remaining three measures, contending cutbacks would amount to 1
percent to 3 percent.
</P>
<P>
   However, White House spokesman Joe Lockhart said the reductions
would amount to 17 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``That would be a devastating cut to hundreds of thousands of
families around this country,'' Lockhart said, citing spending
reductions in education, services for women and infants, and for
law enforcement.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they're more concerned at this point with losing a
political fight and less concerned with getting this done in a way
that makes the right investments and guards our fiscal
discipline,'' Lockhart said.
</P>
<P>
   The House Republicans this week will consider, and then defeat,
Clinton's proposed tax increases on tobacco companies and plan to
close corporate loopholes. The vote would be a symbolic statement
on their efforts to hold the line on both tax increases and
spending.
</P>
<P>
   Republican leadership plans for resolving the budget problem
such as creating a ``13th month'' or delaying tax credits back to
the working poor have been denounced by other GOP members as well
as Texas Gov. George W. Bush, a front-runner for the presidential
nomination.
</P>
<P>
   A recent poll by the Pew Research Center for People and the
Press found the approval rating for Republican leaders in Congress
fell to 34 percent, its lowest level since June 1997 when it was 33
percent. However, Clinton's approval rating stood at 59 percent.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
