<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCOTUS-RDP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COURT UPHOLDS SEARCH WARRANTS ARE NEEDED AT CRIME SCENES 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By LINDA GREENHOUSE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ There is no exception for crime scenes to the
Constitution's requirement of a search warrant, the Supreme Court
ruled Monday. The unanimous opinion overturned a West Virginia
man's conviction for murdering his wife and reaffirmed a principle
the court established 21 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The man's conviction may have been influenced by photographs the
police took from a briefcase they found at the scene and opened
without a warrant. The photographs, introduced at the 1996 trial of
the man, the Rev. James Flippo, over his objection, suggested that
he was having a homosexual relationship with a member of his church
and provided a possible motive for killing his wife, a crime that
he told the police had been committed by an unknown intruder.
</P>
<P>
   In allowing the photographs into evidence, the trial court said
the police ``were clearly within the law'' to examine ``anything
and everything found within the crime scene.''
</P>
<P>
   But that was a misstatement of the law, the unsigned Supreme
Court opinion said Monday, one that ``squarely conflicts'' with a
1978 precedent by which the court rejected a ``murder scene
exception'' to the Fourth Amendment's warrant requirement.
</P>
<P>
   ``A warrantless search by the police is invalid unless it falls
within one of the narrow and well-delineated exceptions to the
warrant requirement,'' the justices said Monday, noting that there
was no emergency or danger to the police or others that would have
precluded getting a warrant after the site of the crime, in a
remote state park, had been secured.
</P>
<P>
   The West Virginia Supreme Court of Appeals upheld Flippo's
conviction and his prison sentence of life without parole. The
minister's appeal to the U.S. Supreme Court, brought by the public
defender's office in Charleston, W.Va., presented an issue that was
evidently so clear to the justices that they proceeded to decide it
without hearing arguments or calling for further briefing. That is
a once-common practice that is now relatively rare, given the
court's deep divisions on many important issues.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1978 precedent, Mincey vs. Arizona, the court saw the
question as equally obvious when it unanimously rejected the
Arizona Supreme Court's creation of a ``murder scene exception'' to
the warrant requirement. In that case, homicide detectives
conducted a warrantless, four-day ``exhaustive and intrusive''
search of the apartment where the defendant had fatally shot a
police officer.
</P>
<P>
   Rejecting the state's argument that the man had forfeited any
reasonable expectation of privacy by shooting the officer in the
first place, the court said that ``this reasoning would
impermissibly convict the suspect even before the evidence against
him was gathered.'' The opinion, by Justice Potter Stewart,
continued: ``the mere fact that law enforcement may be made more
efficient can never by itself justify disregard of the Fourth
Amendment.''
</P>
<P>
   The decision Monday, Flippo vs. West Virginia, No. 98-8770,
addressed only the application of the 1978 precedent, sending the
case back to the state courts with other issues unresolved. State
prosecutors remain free to argue, for example, that Flippo in
effect consented to the warrantless search by summoning the police
to the vacation cabin, where he said both he and his wife had been
attacked. The state is also free to argue that the photographs did
not play an important role in his conviction, and that their
introduction at the trial was ``harmless error'' in light of other
incriminating evidence presented by the prosecution.
</P>
<P>
   These were among the other developments on a generally quiet day
at the Court.
</P>
<P>
   RAILROAD SUITS: For the second time in six years, the justices
agreed to decide whether suits brought under state law against
railroads for accidents at grade crossings are pre-empted by the
federal law governing grade-crossing safety.
</P>
<P>
   A 1993 Supreme Court decision on the subject, CSX Transportation
vs. Easterwood, has caused considerable confusion in the lower
courts. That decision held that if federal money had been used to
install warning devices at crossings, and the devices met federal
standards, people could generally not sue on the ground that the
devices were inadequate.
</P>
<P>
   The question in the case the court accepted Monday, Norfolk
Southern Railway vs. Shanklin, No. 99-312, raises the further
question of whether, in order to bar lawsuits, officials of the
Federal Highway Administration, which runs the federal program to
improve grade crossing safety, must have inspected a particular
site and approved the selection of the particular devices.
</P>
<P>
   The 6th U.S.Circuit Court of Appeals, in Cincinnati, imposed
that further requirement in upholding a $430,000 jury verdict won
by the widow of a man who was killed when a train hit his car at a
rural Tennessee grade crossing that was equipped with reflective
warning signs but not with an automatic gate.
</P>
<P>
   In its appeal, Norfolk Southern is arguing that the appeals
court's approach requiring specific on-site inspection ``cannot
reasonably be administered.'' The appeals court said the
requirement was necessary because if railroads could avoid
liability simply because federal funds had been spent, while at the
same time the federal agency was not required to check on whether
the money was used properly, then ``no one is responsible for the
safety of the motorists who use the crossing.'' A $3 billion
federal program helped pay for improvements at 30,000 grade
crossing over the past 25 years, cutting fatalities by more than
two-thirds.
</P>
<P>
   EXPANDED ARGUMENT: The court took the unusual step of
rescheduling a case that was argued earlier this month for a second
argument, early in the new year, and of instructing the lawyers to
address additional questions at that time. The case is Slack vs.
McDaniel, No. 98-6322, an appeal by a Nevada prison inmate whose
effort to challenge his murder conviction through a petition for a
writ of habeas corpus was denied by the lower federal courts.
</P>
<P>
   The inmate, Antonio Slack, initially filed his petition before
the Antiterrorism and Effective Death Penalty Act of 1996 took
effect, imposing new hurdles to habeas corpus review. In accepting
his appeal last spring, the justices assumed that the new law did
not apply. But now they evidently believe that it might, and have
asked the lawyers to address the new law's potential implications
for prisoners like Slack, who seek to add new issues to an existing
habeas corpus petition. One question is whether the new issues
should be treated as a second petition, which the 1996 law
essentially bars.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-18-99 1920EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
