A0879 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r p BC-BUSH-MOLINARI-TEX     10-18 0686
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-MOLINARI-TEX </SLUG>
 
(For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
By RON HUTCHESON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A key early backer of Texas Gov. George W. Bush
defected to a rival presidential campaign on Monday, offering
another reminder that the race for the Republican nomination is far
from over.
</P>
<P>
   Former New York Congressman Guy Molinari, a name with
considerable clout in delegate-rich New York GOP circles, switched
his allegiance to Sen. John McCain of Arizona in the latest a
series of bumps for what had been the smooth-running Bush campaign.
Although Bush remains the clear frontrunner in the GOP contest, his
efforts to set himself apart from the pack have alienated some
important factions within the party.
</P>
<P>
   First, Bush angered Republican lawmakers by accusing them of
trying to balance the federal budget ``on the backs of the poor.''
Then he seemed to go after social conservatives by saying that his
party sometimes seems obsessed with ``an image of America slouching
toward Gomorrah.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Bush's once-surging poll numbers, while still
impressive, have begun to level off. He continues to hold a
commanding lead in every credible poll, capturing more than 40
percent of the vote in a six-person race.
</P>
<P>
   ``More and more I wonder if George W. hasn't `Forest Gumped' his
way into this,'' said New York pollster John Zogby, referring to
the movie character with an uncanny knack for turning up at the
right place at the right time. ``We're one inch from a real race.
Whether or not it will happen, I don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   While no one suggests that Bush is an any immediate danger of
losing his frontrunner status, there are enough uncertainties to
give his rivals hope. He is scheduled to participate in the first
of a series of presidential debates on Dec. 2, giving the other
candidates a chance to exploit any gaffe.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's advisers are also bracing for a bruising ad campaign by
rival Steve Forbes, the only candidate who can match Bush's
campaign bankroll. Forbes, a millionaire magazine publisher, is
preparing a series of ads that will attack Bush's record in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will engage and do what I'll call contrast advertising when
the time comes,'' one Forbes adviser said. ``I'm not going to tip
my hand by saying when that will be.''
</P>
<P>
   In a sign of the concern in Bush's camp, the candidate's media
experts recently tested possible Forbes attack ads, as well as
Bush's likely response, on focus groups.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's McCain, who has emerged as Bush's closest rival in
some recent polls.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he drops four or five points and McCain moves up four or
five points, it's a race,'' Zogby said of the polls. ``McCain has
the potential to take off. People can visualize him as president.''
</P>
<P>
   Molinari, a leader in the effort to coax Bush into the race,
said he changed his mind after comparing the two candidates. The
former Republican congressman currently serves as Staten Island
borough president, a job that gives him considerable clout in a
heavily Republican section of New York City.
</P>
<P>
   ``The frontrunner always starts to fade. This could become a
real horse race,'' Molinari said. ``Somebody had to emerge as a
challenger. I think it's pretty clear at this point that John
McCain is that Number 2 challenger.''
</P>
<P>
   Molinari, who once called Bush ``the best candidate the
Republican Party can put forward,'' said he was stunned when Bush
criticized congressional Republicans. Molinari had personally
lobbied lawmakers to support the Texas governor.
</P>
<P>
   ``They gave him such tremendous support, and then he turned
around and bit them,'' he said. ``There is some ill will about
that.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain also scored points with Molinari by urging conservative
commentator Pat Buchanan to leave the Republican Party. Bush said
Buchanan should stay with the GOP.
</P>
<P>
   The Bush campaign responded to Molinari's defection with a terse
statement inviting him to reboard the Bush bandwagon ``when Gov.
Bush becomes the Republican presidential nominee.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
