<SLUG> BC-VIEQUES-BOMBING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PENTAGON ASKS FOR DIALOGUE TO END STANDOFF ON TARGET RANGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEWART M. POWELL  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Clinton administration pleaded Monday for
Puerto Rico's political leaders to open discussions with the
Pentagon on resumption of target practice on the island of Vieques
after a presidential panel failed to find a compromise acceptable
to Puerto Rico.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon panel, appointed at President Clinton's request,
recommended that the Navy and Marine Corps should be permitted to
use the target range for 130 days a year in order to get forces
ready for possible combat.
</P>
<P>
   The 58-year-old bombing range has been closed since April 19
when a Marine pilot mistakenly targeted a range observation post,
killing a Puerto Rican security guard working for the Navy, and
wounding four civilian personnel working on the range.
</P>
<P>
   Puerto Rico Gov. Pedro Rossello and allies in Congress have
demanded a permanent end to Navy bombardment and a phased Navy
withdrawal from the island, where more than 9,300 civilians reside
on a swathe of land about 10 miles from the bombing range.
Rossello's representative in Washington reiterated those goals
after the four-member panel's report was released.
</P>
<P>
   In accepting the panel's report, Defense Secretary William Cohen
said he would await the outcome of ``further discussions'' before
making his recommendation to the president on the future of the
bombing range. Cohen said he had asked the panel members to have
further talks with representatives of Puerto Rico, Vieques and the
Navy in an effort toward ``achieving consensus.''
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon panel also recommended immediate Navy closure of an
8,000 acre ammunition depot; phased Navy withdrawal from 16,000
remaining acres by 2005; and Navy support for economic development
and studies of residents' claims that 58 years of target practice
has contributed to a high incidence of cancer.
</P>
<P>
   After the panel released its report Monday, Hillary Rodham
Clinton broke months of public silence on the topic and issued a
statement during a visit to upstate New York in which she expressed
support for the Puerto Rican campaign to end the Navy's use of the
island.
</P>
<P>
   ``Live ordinance training should not take place on a small,
inhabited island,'' Mrs. Clinton said. ``There should be an
immediate and permanent end to the bombing.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton echoed the Clinton administration's call for
continued efforts at compromise, however, saying: ``I hope the
parties will keep working on this matter to the satisfaction of all
involved.''
</P>
<P>
   About 60 percent of New York's 2.6 million Hispanics are U.S.
citizens born in Puerto Rico and Mrs. Clinton is hoping for their
support in her pending run for the U.S. Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Hispanic lawmakers from electorally important states, including
California, New York, Texas, Illinois, New Jersey and Arizona, have
also taken up Puerto Rico's demands that the Navy should leave
Vieques.
</P>
<P>
   Alcides Ortiz, director of the Puerto Rico Federal Affairs
Administration and the representative for Puerto Rico's governor in
Washington, D.C., rejected the panel's recommendation for
resumption of live fire training.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is nothing to negotiate,'' Ortiz said. ``I don't think
anything has changed _ the permanent cessation of the bombing
exercises is not open for negotiation.''
</P>
<P>
   Ortiz said that the Rossello administration will only discuss
Navy withdrawal and the transfer of Navy-owned land to Puerto Rico,
as well as cleanup operations at areas where exploded and
unexploded ordnance pose a hazard.
</P>
<P>
   On Vieques, where dozens of protesters have camped out on the
target range since April to prevent resumption of bombing,
demonstrators expressed concern that the Navy might use the panel's
recommendation to resume target practice.
</P>
<P>
   Carlos Ventura, president of the Fishermen's Association of
Southern Vieques, said it remains ``unacceptable that the Navy
start exercises again,'' adding that fishermen would continue their
civil disobedience protest.
</P>
<P>
   Navy Secretary Richard Danzig accepted some of the
recommendations of the report and said the Navy will immediately
take steps to improve the Navy's relationship with the people of
Vieques, including seeking a meeting with Puerto Rico's leaders to
map greater economic assistance, the return of Navy-owned land and
construction of infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
   Danzig said he had asked the Pentagon-funded think tank, the
Center for Naval Analyses, to study possible alternatives to the
training facility on Vieques that began operations in 1941.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have believed from the beginning of the current situation
that both the legitimate national security needs of the United
States and the needs of the residents of Vieques can be
accommodated,'' Danzig said.
</P>
<P>
   A White House official, speaking on condition of anonymity, said
the president believes that the Pentagon panel has established the
basis for a ``open and free dialogue'' among officials from the
Pentagon, the Navy, residents of Vieques and Puerto Rico.
</P>
<P>
   The official said Clinton is hopeful that the parties will find
a solution that balances national security with the needs of the
people of Vieques.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon-dominated panel included Frank Rush, acting
assistant secretary of defense for force management policy; former
House Foreign Relations Committee Chairman Lee Hamilton, D-Ind.;
retired Marine Corps Gen. Richard Neal; and retired Navy Vice Adm.
Diego Hernandez, a native of Puerto Rico.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Stewart M. Powell can be reached at 202-298-6920 and via
E-mail: stewart(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
