<HEADER>
A0883 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-PSYCHOLOGY-AND-YOU19-     10-18 0495
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PSYCHOLOGY-AND-YOU19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Y2K may exacerbate life's outlook for some
 &HT;    By Dr. Hap LeCrone
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ Mental health professionals, including social
workers, psychologists and psychiatrists, may expect to see an
increase in psychological difficulties among certain groups of
people as the year 2000 approaches.
</P>
<P>
   Some of these individuals believe that the year 2000 will mark
the beginning of the apocalypse. Cults and extreme religious sects
have been predicting an apocalyptic conclusion to the 20th century
for quite some time. Similar problems occurred a thousand years ago
when a segment of the population believed that the world was coming
to an end around the 1,000th anniversary of Christ's birth.
</P>
<P>
   This pre-millennia tension is increasing in some circles because
of the belief that our technology is going to fail, and that our
society will become chaotic and return to primitive-like existence.
</P>
<P>
   Other mental health authorities predict increases in suicides
and domestic tensions within families before the end of the year.
Unfortunately, if enough people believe that terrible events are
going to occur because of a predestined prophecy, then they may act
out their beliefs in spite of objective reality.
</P>
<P>
   One interesting variation of this ``millennium madness'' is
known as the ``Jerusalem Syndrome.'' An Israeli mental health
professional, Dr. Yair Bar-el, is credited with identifying and
naming this problem. Dr. Bar-el, who directs a psychiatric hospital
in Jerusalem, first noted the problems in the early 1970s. This
rather bizarre psychological condition seems to affect visitors to
Jerusalem, causing them to believe that they are on a mission from
God and proclaim that they are ancient religious figures. Jesus,
Moses and the Virgin Mary are the three most frequent choices, but
Samson, John the Baptist and Mary Magdalene have also emerged as
assumed identities.
</P>
<P>
   Often, these individuals tend to have pre-existing psychiatric
problems, but interestingly enough, a smaller sub-group appears to
have no history of psychological difficulties prior to the
development of the Jerusalem Syndrome. Some of the effected
individuals don white sheets, toga-like clothes and start singing
hymns or preaching. The afflicted generally recover after a week or
so and usually express embarrassment and a lack of willingness to
discuss their departure into ``never-never land.''
</P>
<P>
   An influx of long-term visitors has already begun to settle in
Jerusalem. Preparation is beginning to be made to deal with the
anticipated increase in ``Jerusalem Syndrome'' that is expected to
occur in the next few months.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Hap LeCrone writes for The Waco Tribune-Herald, Waco, Texas.
If you have questions or topic ideas, write him at 4555 Lake Shore
Drive, Waco, Texas, 76710; E-mail: hlecrone(AT)aol.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
