<SLUG> BC-STOCKS-MARKETPLACE-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKET PLACE: UNDERSTANDING VOLATILITY 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By FLOYD NORRIS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In 1987, the stock market seemed to go crazy, with
prices first soaring and then plunging _ a process that culminated
in the crash 12 years ago Tuesday. The volatility, which was
greater than at any time since the 1930s, stunned and scared
investors around the world.
</P>
<P>
   Now, by some measures, the stock market is even more volatile
than it was then.
</P>
<P>
   That is particularly true in the NASDAQ market, where sudden
price moves are more common than at any time since the NASDAQ
composite index was created in 1971. The market of large stocks, as
reflected by the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index, is not as
volatile, but it, too, is far less steady than it was a few years
ago.
</P>
<P>
   That volatility has grown to the point that most investors have
become inured to big daily moves. Only a decade ago, the NASDAQ
composite averaged about one big day _ defined as a close at least
1 percent above or below the previous day _ each month. So far this
year, it is averaging three such days every week.
</P>
<P>
   Or consider how rapidly a new high for the NASDAQ index can
crumble. Twenty years ago, in October 1979, the index plunged 8.5
percent within three days of setting a record. That came after the
``Saturday Night Massacre,'' when Paul Volcker, the Federal Reserve
chairman, abruptly announced a change in Fed policy that sent
interest rates skyrocketing and soon brought on a recession. Until
this year, that was the record for biggest fall within a week of
setting a record.
</P>
<P>
   Then, in April, the index fell 9.7 percent in five trading days
amid a sharp selloff in the technology issues that have come to
dominate it. The current plunge is not quite as steep, with the
index down 7.8 percent since it peaked last Monday. That makes it
the third-sharpest decline from a record close in NASDAQ history.
</P>
<P>
   Rapid increases in volatility reflect forces both within the
stock market and outside of it. Volatility can sharply increase, as
it did in 1980, when a leading sector _ then, energy stocks _ has
risen to unsupportable valuations. It is possible that the current
surge in volatility is foretelling a similar turn in this era's
dominant sector, technology.
</P>
<P>
   Not all increases in volatility, however, tell such stories. New
ways of trading, brought on by technology and financial
engineering, can roil the markets until other traders become used
to the effects generated by such trading. That was true of
institutional block trading in the 1970s and computerized index
arbitrage in the 1980s. And it may be true now of Internet-based
day trading, which has made it possible for individual speculators
to trade much more rapidly, and with lower trading costs, than ever
before.
</P>
<P>
   That sort of volatility presumably says little about the
underlying economy or the long-term trend of stock prices, and as
such is relatively benign. The 1987 crash in significant part
reflected such volatility. The then-popular fad of ``portfolio
insurance,'' which held that profits could be locked in by selling
stock index futures when prices began to fall, led to widespread
selling of such futures into a market that could not cope with the
selling and did not fully understand what was behind it.
</P>
<P>
   Another cause of volatility is changes in macroeconomic
conditions, particularly the level of interest rates. Expectations
of such changes can drastically affect the expected value of future
profits and cause widespread shifts in investment patterns. Rising
interest rates played a role in 1987, as well as in a minor upswing
in volatility in 1994, and probably have something to do with the
current increase.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, a chief cause of volatility is the long-term movement
of the market itself, which affects investor attitudes and
expectations. The 1973-74 bear market, the worst since the Great
Depression, ended an era in which a large part of the public
thought that stocks were an investment likely to rise forever, and
volatility rose drastically. Similarly, it began to rise again in
1982, when a long period of poor returns ended with the market's
upward explosion. That shook the belief that the stock market was
permanently a poor investment.
</P>
<P>
   All those types of volatility may be present today, to one
degree or another. But the current volatility seems most similar to
that of 1980, when energy stocks climbed so high that they
represented 30 percent of the valuation of the S&AMP;P 500. That was a
far greater percentage of the market than energy represented in the
underlying economy. But the prevalent economic forecast of the era
was for ever-higher prices for oil and other natural resources as
the world ran short of almost everything.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of such a run the buyers are primarily momentum
players, who are interested in the stocks not because they see them
as valuable but because they have been going up for so long. In
addition, the sector is expanded by new stocks that go public with
more hope than experience and whose business plans depend on a
continuation of the trend.
</P>
<P>
   That may also be happening now, with technology stocks as the
oil shares of this era. They now make up a quarter of the S&AMP;P 500,
far more than their share of gross domestic product or corporate
profits. The proportion is even more extreme in the NASDAQ, where
the five largest computer-technology companies _ Microsoft, Intel,
Cisco, Dell and Sun Microsystems _ together account for a third of
the value of the more than 4,000 stocks in the index.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, fluctuations in technology stock prices have been the
largest cause of volatility in the stock market this year. Internet
stocks peaked in April and then tumbled. While they had recovered a
good part of their losses before slipping again in last week's
selloff, they had not reached new highs. The larger technology
companies did recover, however, enabling the NASDAQ composite to
reach last week's peak.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   That kind of volatility _ brought on by shifts in the values of
the dominant stocks of an era _ probably has more significance for
the market than for the economy as a whole, although it can be a
wrenching process for areas that based their economies on a growth
industry that faltered. It took Texas years to recover from the end
of the oil boom.
</P>
<P>
   The rise in NASDAQ volatility has been going on for several
years, but it accelerated last year and kept growing this year. To
some extent, that simply reflects the volatility of the
now-dominant technology stocks. In that regard, the NASDAQ
composite is a very different index now from what it was a decade
or more ago, when it was often used as a proxy for the movement of
smaller stocks. Nonetheless, the rise in volatility is eye
catching.
</P>
<P>
   In 1987, the NASDAQ composite rose or fell at least 1 percent in
23 percent of the trading sessions, and it rose or fell at least 2
percent on 7.5 percent of the trading days. Both were the highest
for that index since the deep bear market of 1974.
</P>
<P>
   Another way of looking at volatility is to compute the standard
deviation of daily percentage returns. That has the advantage of
better taking into account long-term trends in the stock market. A
market that went up half a percent every day would be a phenomenal
bull market, but the standard deviation would be zero.
</P>
<P>
   By that measure, volatility in the NASDAQ market set a record in
1987, with a standard deviation of 1.57 percent, easily exceeding
the 1974 peak of 1.12 percent. That was a record that stood until
1998, when the figure hit 1.66 percent. So far this year, it is
1.79 percent.
</P>
<P>
   For the S&AMP;P 500, the volatility explosion is not nearly as
great. On average, there are about two days a week with a
percentage change of at least 1 percent, compared with three for
the NASDAQ. But that figure is higher than for any full year since
1974, slightly exceeding the 1987 figure. The standard deviation of
daily returns, however, is down to 1.18 percent so far this year
from 1.28 percent in 1998. Those are the two highest figures since
1987, but they are far below that year's figure of 2.02 percent.
</P>
<P>
   That this year's volatility is primarily a reflection of the
lively market in the stars of the era, the technology stocks, is
shown by the relative peace and quiet shown in the market for small
company shares, as measured by the Russell 2000 index. That index
is less than half as likely as the NASDAQ composite to rise or fall
by a percentage point on any given day.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
