<SLUG> BC-SCOTLAND-PARLIAMENT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REBIRTH HASN'T BEEN EASY FOR SCOTTISH PARLIAMENT 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By SARAH LYALL    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   EDINBURGH, Scotland _ The first Scottish Parliament in nearly
300 years opened in July with pomp, circumstance and the queen of
England herself, wearing a special dress with a Scottish-thistle
motif.
</P>
<P>
   It was the dawn of ``a new constitutional age,'' proclaimed the
queen, whose presence was intended as much to remind the unruly
Scots who is sovereign (she is) as to wish them well.
</P>
<P>
   But for all the soaring speeches and high-blown sentiment, the
new Parliament was consumed by a series of peculiarly solipsistic
issues, at least in the opinion of the pugnacious Scottish
newspapers. There was the issue of the new legislators' bonus
packages. There was the issue of their parking spaces. And there
was the issue of why each legislator received a handsome new
commemorative medal, when the Parliament hadn't actually done
anything yet.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Russell, the business manager of the Scottish National
Party, said his medal made him feel as if he were an old-time
Communist. ``It is like something a Politburo chief would wear
during the Stalin era, watching a May Day parade,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The new Parliament is the fruit of years of campaigning by Scots
who have long felt undervalued by London. Under Prime Minister Tony
Blair's policy of devolution _ which aims to give more
self-determination to Britons outside of England _ Scotland and
Wales have both elected legislatures with responsibility over a
host of local matters.
</P>
<P>
   Most Scottish newspapers supported the effort. But suddenly,
tacitly egged on by opposition parties eager to attack the majority
Labor Party, the newspapers seemed to compete to see who could be
meaner about Parliament.
</P>
<P>
   The Edinburgh Evening News printed a drawing depicting the
legislators as lounging pigs in sunglasses, in a reference to their
salaries, perks and vacations. Dredging up a selection of outraged
veterans to denounce the parliamentary medals, The Daily Record
printed a headline saying ``For Services to Nobody at All.''
</P>
<P>
   The papers attacked so long and so hard that finally Sir David
Steel, the Parliament's presiding officer, declared that he had had
enough. Asking the news media to give ``the new Parliament a
chance,'' he took The Daily Record, the scrappiest of the Scottish
tabloids, to the Press Complaints Commission, saying that it had
violated its duty not to ``publish inaccurate, misleading, or
distorted material.''
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Sir David said The Daily Record's editor,
Martin Clarke, had been unfair to a young institution trying to
find its way. ``The Parliament has been subject to a fairly
systematic denigration,'' he said. ``One particular editor was
repeatedly abusing the Parliament in a false manner, and possibly
affecting public opinion.''
</P>
<P>
   Sir David's effort failed when the complaints commission ruled
in favor of The Daily Record, giving a delighted Clarke the perfect
opportunity to add ``arrogance'' to his list of Parliament's
shortcomings. ``He's bonkers,'' he said of Sir David. ``They've had
300 years to think about getting their Parliament right.''
</P>
<P>
   Personal disputes aside, even people who campaigned fiercely for
the new Parliament acknowledge that the first few months did not go
very well, at least from a public relations point of view.
</P>
<P>
   Many new legislators were so unschooled in the cut-and-thrust of
parliamentary debate that at first they seemed unable to open their
mouths without a piece of paper in front of them. ``A lot of people
were reading from scripts, and some of us doubted whether they'd
even written it themselves,'' said Shona Robison, parliamentary
group secretary for the Scottish National Party.
</P>
<P>
   Alan Cochrane, a columnist for The Daily Telegraph, agreed. ``To
call the Labor backbenchers drones and robots would be an insult to
drones and robots,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   OK, Sir David said, maybe ``some of the maiden speeches were not
so brilliant.'' But he added: ``They come from all walks of life.
They're not 129 models of Demosthenes, but so what?''
</P>
<P>
   And that's not really the issue, said Magnus Linklater, a former
editor of The Scotsman who is a columnist for The Times of London
and who feels that the legislature has taken an unfair beating.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a way to insure that time will be given to Scottish
issues,'' he said of the Parliament. ``And in the short time it's
been in existence, a range of issues has been debated and discussed
that wouldn't have been at Westminster.''
</P>
<P>
   On the legislative agenda, among other things, are a proposal to
abolish tuition for students in Scottish colleges (colleges
throughout Britain currently charge tuition) and a sweeping
land-reform proposal that would subject large landowners to
increased government control.
</P>
<P>
   ``The interesting development is not that the Scottish
Parliament is being seen to be a kind of minor assembly, but that
it actually might turn out to be a body whose measures have an
influence south of the border,'' Linklater said.
</P>
<P>
   Annabel Goldie, deputy leader of the Scottish Tories, said it
was up to Parliament to prove that Linklater was right.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was new, it was naked, it was vulnerable and it was a
fairly obvious object for the attentions of the press,'' Miss
Goldie said. ``But if any institution says of another, `You are
weak and undeserving of public confidence,' it is for the second to
turn around and say, `We are reliable, we are strong, and we are
people of ability.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-18-99 1933EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
