<SLUG> BC-WOMEN-AWARDS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HAMM, INKSTER NAMED SPORTSWOMEN OF THE YEAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BARBARA HUEBNER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ At a lavish and lively ceremony Monday night in the
Grand Ballroom of the Waldorf-Astoria, Mia Hamm and Juli Inkster
were honored as Sportswomen of the Year by the Women's Sports
Foundation at its 20th annual Salute to Women in Sports.
</P>
<P>
   Hamm, a forward for the US women's national soccer team that won
the Women's World Cup last summer, was recognized for the second
time in three years in the team category, while Inskter, in the
midst of a phenomenal season on the LPGA tour that has included 16
top 10 finishes, was named in the individual category.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time someone wants to throw out superlatives about me, I
cringe,'' an emotional Hamm said at a morning news conference,
addressing teammates who included captains Julie Foudy and Carla
Overbeck. ``I think anybody who participates knows who's
responsible for your development, and it's not me, it's my
teammates. I'm so glad you guys are here; you guys are everything
to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the other honorees was Joan Benoit Samuelson. The
42-year-old Samuelson, who in 1984 became the first woman to win an
Olympic gold medal in the marathon, was one of four women inducted
into the International Women's Sports Hall of Fame. The honor comes
15 years after the Maine native was named Amateur Sportswoman of
the Year by the foundation for her historic victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it wasn't for all the pioneers in the world of sports, I
wouldn't be here today,'' said Samuelson, her voice quavering,
looking around the room Friday morning. ``They taught me to lead
with my heart, to believe in myself. If you don't have passion,
there isn't fire.''
</P>
<P>
   Also inducted into the Hall of Fame were:
</P>
<P>
   --Sandra Haynie, 56, a member of the LPGA Hall of Fame who was
forced out of the sport in 1977 by arthritis, only to come back
four years later and compete until 1989, winning three more
tournaments;
</P>
<P>
   --Betty Jameson, 80, a founding member of the LPGA who created
the prestigious Vare Trophy, given annually to the player with the
lowest scoring average;
</P>
<P>
   --Tina Sloan Green, 55, one of the top coaches in the history of
women's lacrosse and cofounder of the Black Women in Sport
Foundation, in addition to teaching field hockey and lacrosse to
inner-city Philadelphia children.
</P>
<P>
   Receiving the Wilma Rudolph Courage Award was three-time Olympic
gold medalist Gail Devers, the track star who for the last decade
has battled Graves' disease. Deborah Slaner Larkin, executive
director of the Women's Sports Foundation from 1986-1991, was given
the Billie Jean King Contribution Award for, among other things,
helping to conduct the ground-breaking 1997 report ``Physical
Activity and Sport in the Lives of Girls.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
