bill for foreign operations and urges the Republican leadership in
Congress to meet with him to resolve the 2000 budget impasse. By
NANCY MATHIS. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   VIEQUES-BOMBING (Washington) _ The Clinton administration pleads
for Puerto Rico's political leaders to open discussions with the
Pentagon on resumption of target practice on the island of Vieques
after a presidential panel fails to find a compromise acceptable to
Puerto Rico. By STEWART M. POWELL. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   POLITICAL NEWS (``p'' category)
</P>
<P>
   McCAIN-2000 (Washington) _ An influential early supporter of
Texas Gov. George W. Bush, former Rep. Guy Molinari of New York,
jumps ship to join the Republican presidential campaign of Arizona
Sen. John McCain. The endorsement by Molinari, the Staten Island
borough president, is a blow to Bush's campaign to solidify support
in a crucial state. By GREG McDONALD. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   DSP-CHIPS (Houston) _ Though DSP chips _ specialized types of
semiconductors that can be programmed _ have been around for a few
years and can be found in virtually every mobile telephone, they
are quickly finding their way into a host of new consumer products.
DSP is considered by Texas Instruments to be the processor that
will take consumers closer to the technology-rich world of ``Star
Trek,'' with such products as portable universal translators. By
TRICIA SERJU-HARRIS. (Already filed. Photo available on NYT
database.)
</P>
<P>
   BARLOW-COLUMN (Houston) _ The Beagle Brigade, dogs wearing green
coats, is being used to sniff out foreign plants and other animals
as travelers come through Bush Intercontinental Airport in Houston.
The U.S. Department of Agriculture estimates that these plant and
animal species cause about $140 billion a year in damage. By JIM
BARLOW. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FOOD-STAMPS (Houston) _ A lawsuit claims Texas, whose leaders
are proud of the state's success in getting people off the food
stamp rolls, is actually violating federal rules by taking too long
to approve people for food stamps. By POLLY ROSS HUGHES and PATTY
REINERT. (1stld-writethru filed; photo available on NYT database.)
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEANS-COLUMN (Washington) _ First Lady Hillary Rodham Clinton's
campaign swing across New York this week highlights both her
problems and her advantages as a Senate candidate. She gets lots of
public attention, but it isn't all favorable. By MARIANNE MEANS.
(Already filed.)
