<HEADLINE>
HUMAN TESTS OF ENDOSTATIN SET TO BEGIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD SALTUS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Amid great expectations and scientists' cautions, the first
volunteers to receive the tumor-starving drug endostatin will begin
receiving it this week in an initial round of safety tests.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Dana-Farber/Partners Cancer Care in Boston said
Monday that a small number of cancer patients is about to get the
first infusions of endostatin, which has wiped out large tumors in
mice without toxic side effects.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of people have volunteered for the Phase 1 trials, but
a total of only about 30 patients will receive endostatin in tests
aimed mainly at revealing any toxic side effects. Researchers will
also look for any signs that the drug is halting the growth of
tumors or shrinking them, but they say even an ultimately valuable
cancer drug is unlikely to demonstrate much effect in these early
tests.
</P>
<P>
   The drug, discovered in the laboratory of Dr. Judah Folkman at
Harvard and Children's Hospital, is the most potent _ in mice _ yet
discovered of substances called angiogenesis inhibitors. They
attack the blood vessels nourishing tumors rather than being aimed
at the cancer cells themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Endostatin and another compound, angiostatin, have so
dramatically shrunk tumors in animals, without adverse side
effects, that some believe a new era in cancer treatment is
opening. But scientists emphasize that what works in mice might not
work in people.
</P>
<P>
   ``We always feel hopeful, but the failure in clinical trials can
be of so many things,'' Folkman said in a recent interview. For
example, he said, the drug is to be given once a day in the Phase 1
study, ``but what if the optimal dose is twice a day?''
</P>
<P>
   Cancer patients, oncologists and investors in the stock of the
Rockville, Md., company EntreMed that developed endostatin as a
drug are poised in anticipation, waiting for any word that it is
working. That could take months or years, researchers say.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, cancer specialists at the M.D. Anderson Cancer Center in
Houston briefed reporters on the endostatin trial _ also a Phase 1
safety trial _ due to begin there early next month. A third trial
will be carried out at the University of Wisconsin in Madison.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. James Abbruzzese, one of the lead investigators of the
research at M.D. Anderson, said, ``we are years away from knowing
what benefit _ if any _ this drug will have in humans with
cancer.'' Patients are being recruited somewhat differently than
they have been in Boston, where volunteers called a hotline or
contacted a Web site if they wanted to be in the trial, and a
computer randomized their names.
</P>
<P>
   At M.D. Anderson, patients must be referred to one of the
hospital's cancer clinics where a cancer specialist will determine
whether endostatin is an option. ``They can't call specifically for
endostatin,'' said Dr. Roy Herbst, the principal investigator for
the trial.
</P>
<P>
   The M.D. Anderson trial hopes to recruit patients with tumors of
the breast, head and neck that can be easily biopsied to look for
any signs of endostatin's effectiveness.
</P>
<P>
   A bioethicist at the cancer center said there is a special
emphasis on making sure the volunteers understand that there is
little likelihood they will personally be helped in the early
safety trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're afraid that people's expectations will have been raised
by the media,'' said the ethicist, Rebecca Pentz.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-18-99 1945EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
