<DOCNO> NYT19991018.0371 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-18 19:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0901 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-INDONESIA-POLITICS-NY     10-18 0931
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDONESIA-POLITICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUST BEFORE INDONESIA'S FINALE, THE CAST IS CHANGING  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By SETH MYDANS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JAKARTA, Indonesia _ Just two days before an electoral assembly
votes to choose Indonesia's next president, it is impossible to
predict the outcome or even to say, in the final moments, who all
the candidates will be to lead the world's fourth-most-populous
nation.
</P>
<P>
   Four months after a general election that chose most of the
delegates to the assembly, a fast-moving shell game of political
maneuvering is scrambling the field and creating political
uncertainty.
</P>
<P>
   The candidate to beat remains Megawati Sukarnoputri, the
opposition leader who won a plurality of 34 percent in the June
election and who remains by far the most popular figure outside the
halls of the electoral assembly.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing else seems sure in the presidential race.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's complicated, it's fluid _ cross your fingers,'' said
Jusuf Wanandi, a prominent political analyst. Even this close to
the vote, the presidential field could become unrecognizable to the
millions of people who voted in June in Indonesia's first
democratic election in a generation.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Megawati's chief rival, the increasingly unpopular
incumbent president, B.J. Habibie, could be jettisoned by his party
before the vote is taken. A prominent Muslim leader, Abdurrahman
Wahid, could drop his own candidacy, which seems unlikely to
succeed. A respected Muslim scholar, Nurcholis Madjid, could emerge
as a compromise candidate.
</P>
<P>
   In another twist, the politically powerful chief of the armed
forces, Gen. Wiranto, made a television address Monday evening in
which he said he would not be a candidate for president or vice
president.
</P>
<P>
   The statement appeared to be a rejection of Habibie's invitation
to be his vice presidential running mate. It was one more blow to
the president's hopes of election, following days of criticism in
speeches on the floor of the assembly.
</P>
<P>
   As the last-minute maneuvering went on, political talk in
Jakarta focused Monday on the possibility of an extraordinary
coalition of rivals in which a breakaway faction of Habibie's party
would support Mrs. Megawati.
</P>
<P>
   Deal-making like this underscores the pragmatic nature of the
presidential race, following a general election suffused with
idealism. In the election, voters campaigned for Mrs. Megawati to
overturn the old order embodied by Habibie's party.
</P>
<P>
   But in the proposed coalition, which has been under discussion
for some time, the current governing party's leader, Akbar
Tandjung, would become vice president and would bring along with
him as many as half of the party's 120 votes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The numbers stack up,'' said a foreign election expert,
calculating the expected grouping of coalitions. ``I think the
numbers would give Megawati a majority.''
</P>
<P>
   But vote counting like this is risky as long as the leanings of
key groupings like the military and Wahid's supporters remain
uncertain.
</P>
<P>
   In an emotional address on Monday to soldiers at the
presidential palace, Habibie said he would fight on until the end,
but his remarks did not sound like those of a man who expected to
win.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to continue the struggle until the last minute,'' he
said. ``I don't want to say goodbye.''
</P>
<P>
   As Indonesia undergoes its risky on-the-job training course in
democracy following three decades of autocratic rule under former
President Suharto, it is not only the presidential candidates who
remain to be decided in the final moments of the race.
</P>
<P>
   Even the rules of the game are still unclear.
</P>
<P>
   The electoral assembly has still not determined whether the vote
will be conducted by a closed or open ballot or whether the winner
will need a plurality or a majority of the votes.
</P>
<P>
   That determination is to be made on Tuesday, the day before the
vote. Parliamentary committees proposed over the weekend that the
voting be closed and that the winner be required to get a simple
majority of votes, which could require several rounds of voting.
</P>
<P>
   Another committee proposed on Monday that the assembly accept
the results of a referendum on Aug. 30 in which the people of East
Timor voted to break free of Indonesia after 24 years of
occupation. A vote on that proposal is also scheduled for Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   After the election in June, many Indonesians thought they had
elected Mrs. Megawati. But that voting produced just 462 of the 700
members of the electoral assembly. The rest were appointed, opening
the way to the back-room deals that have taken the final decision
out of the hands of Indonesia's people. As a result, the
temperature on the streets of Jakarta has risen rapidly.
</P>
<P>
   Many people have made their voices heard in continuing mass
rallies and in outbursts of violence.
</P>
<P>
   The military announced Monday that more than 40,000 troops and
police officers had been deployed around the capital in
anticipation of large demonstrations over the next two days and the
possibility of widespread social unrest if Mrs. Megawati is not
selected.
</P>
<P>
   Scores of people were injured and scores more were arrested last
Thursday and Friday in major clashes between demonstrators and
security forces. Largely peaceful demonstrations continued through
the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   A new element has increased the potential for violence: the
deployment of separate, antagonistic uniformed security forces
loyal to Mrs. Megawati and to Habibie.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there is at least a potential for large-scale
confrontations even before the session starts to vote,'' said a
Western diplomat.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-18-99 1948EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
