r l BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRO     10-18 0743
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHARING HIS PAIN
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: This story also moved in the ``a'' national news file)  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   Perhaps it was more than concern for his brethren that prompted
 &UR; Bob Dole &LR;  to share his own story while touting a remedy for
erectile dysfunction.
</P>
<P>
   A lobbyist for Pfizer, the company that makes Viagra, told U.S.
News &AMP; World Report that Dole received $45,000 a week while his
Viagra ads were on TV. Pfizer also made a major donation to the Red
Cross, which used to employ the Dole Mrs.
</P>
<P>
   P.S. A Restonic Mattress survey found that women are twice as
likely as men to watch TV, read, eat, drink, talk or play with the
kids in bed, but men are twice as likely to make love (and report
on it in a survey).
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WATCHING TECHNIQUES AT THE BEACH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Everywhere you look at the beach, writes ethnologist  &UR; Orvar &LR; 
 &UR; Lofgren &LR;  in ``On Holiday: A History of Vacationing'' (UC Press;
$29.95), ``there are bodies, old and young bodies, fat and thin,
swimming or sleeping bodies, running bodies, bodies doing
somersaults or rolling in the sand.''
</P>
<P>
   Although going to the beach is supposed to be relaxing, the
truth is that watching can be just as taxing as holding your
stomach in while you're being watched. Lofgren describes the
research of French sociologist  &UR; Jean-Claude Kaufmann &LR; , to whom the
beach is ``a laboratory for sophistication of the gaze. ... People
are constantly testing different ocular techniques, consciously or
unconsciously switching between different ways of seeing: watching,
staring, glancing, scanning, looking from the corner of your eye,
pretending not to look, making brief eye contact, looking away.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When bodies are naked,'' said sociologist  &UR; Erving Goffman &LR; ,
``glances are clothed.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Shannon Faulkner &LR; , who dropped out of the Citadel after five
days as the first woman in the South Carolina military school, is a
24-year-old high school teacher in Greenville, S.C. ``It took a
while for me to be able to do whatever I wanted, to smile, be
upbeat and happy,'' she told the Greenville News about post-Citadel
life.
</P>
<P>
   _ More museums, more preservationist controversies: Artnet.com
reports that at the Kimbell Art Museum in Fort Worth, Texas, fans
of modernist tradition ``are up in arms'' over Milan designer
 &UR; Mario &LR;   &UR; Bellini &LR; 's plan to cover Travertine marble walls _
designed by the building's original architect,  &UR; Louis Kahn &LR;  _ with
pine green cloth on which paintings will be hung. The museum board
refused comment, says Artnet.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Betsy Nolan &LR;  visited a trendy new bar outside Sydney and sent
word on the latest in Australian cocktails: butterscotch schnapps
and Bailey's is a Liability; Kahlua, Bailey's and banana liqueur is
a Gun in My Pocket; creme de menthe and Bailey's is S_ in the
Grass. Nolan says she taught the bartender how to make a Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WERE YOU THERE? &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ The national DJ magazine Mixer described the South of Market
scene at Release, right here in San Francisco: ``Inside the main
room, the floor is rocking to Tom Thump's funky beat as a wash of
pristine visuals illuminate the packed, softly lit dance floor.
High above the fall, a male and female dancer ... are moving their
waistlines to the funky basslines. Down below, the mix of kids
wielding glowsticks as if they were  &UR; Bruce Lee &LR; , waif-like
model-types in capri pants with Cosmopolitans, and even underground
heads high on the music are all just freaking to the groove. ...
Nobody's looking at their watches. Nobody's brought a bad vibe.
Nobody's planning on going home before dawn.''
</P>
<P>
   This educational material is for readers who pride themselves on
being able to stay awake for the Weekend Update on ``Saturday Night
Live.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Reporting on an eerie San Francisco confluence,  &UR; Ken Maley &LR; 
describes Union Square at noon on Saturday: A street-blocking
ear-splitting protest against the planned December 2 execution of
 &UR; Mumia Abu-Jamal &LR;  coincided with a three-piece band playing in front
of Macy's for a free bread giveaway celebrating Boudin's 150th
anniversary.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``The key is to not look so perfect. I walk in and it looks like
my outfit cost about $12, but it's the complete opposite.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Actress, model and record company executive Kidada Jones
giving Elle magazine the key to becoming a Hollywood fashion icon:
Spend a lot of money, but look as though you dressed cheaply.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
