<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-APPLE-PRICING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
APPLE BACKPEDALS ON G4 ORDERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HIAWATHA BRAY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Apple Computer Corp. has reversed course on an unpopular plan
that would have raised prices on its forthcoming Power Mac G4
computers to customers who had already placed orders for the
machines.
</P>
<P>
   ``We apologize to our customers for upsetting and disappointing
them during this past week,'' said Steve Jobs, Apple's interim
chief executive. ``Our actions today will hopefully set things
right.''
</P>
<P>
   Apple's attempt to reprice the G4, because of shortages of the
advanced processor chip at the heart of the machine, threatened
last week to become a public relations fiasco for the company,
which has staged a dramatic comeback since Jobs regained control of
Apple in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   The G4 computer was originally to have been sold with processor
speeds of 400, 450, and 500 megahertz, with prices of $1,599,
$2,499, and $3,499, respectively. But Motorola Inc., which makes
the G4 processor, informed Apple it couldn't produce the chips in
sufficient quantity, and that the 500-megahertz version of the G4
wouldn't be available until next year.
</P>
<P>
   Apple last week responded by resetting the speed range of the G4
product line to 350, 400, and 450 megahertz without adjusting the
prices. But the real outrage was caused when Apple said it was
canceling all existing orders for the G4. People who had placed
advance orders would have to reorder, and accept a slower machine
for the same price.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whoever does marketing for them needs to be looking for
another job,'' said Manny Paraschos, a journalism professor at
Emerson College. ``I have never felt so outraged in my life.''
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of other customers reacted in the same way. By last
Friday, Apple had agreed to reinstate orders submitted through its
Internet site, but still planned to cancel all others. By Monday,
however, Apple had agreed to honor all of the original orders
placed before Oct. 13 at the original prices.
</P>
<P>
   Customers who had ordered the unavailable 500-megahertz model
would be offered the 450-megahertz version at a lower price. The
new, higher pricing announced last week will apply to future G4
orders.
</P>
<P>
   The reversal mollified Apple customer K.M. Peterson, a systems
manager at the Whitehead Institute, a research institute affiliated
with the Massachusetts Institute of Technology.
</P>
<P>
   ``They really screwed up, they badly screwed up,'' said
Peterson. ``And yet, after a fashion, they realized how badly they
screwed up and they've tried very hard to make good.''
</P>
<P>
   But Roger Kay, a computer industry analyst with International
Data Corp. in Framingham, said the incident illustrates the dark
side of Apple's way of doing business.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's indicative of a personality trait that Apple has had from
the beginning,'' said Kay, ``a tendency to lock customers in and
then sort of jerk them around.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-18-99 1951EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991018.0375 </DOCNO>
