<DOCNO> NYT19991018.0376 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-18 19:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0927 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-HEALTH-MEDIA19-COX     10-18 0564
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEALTH-MEDIA19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Read of the week: Nutrition
 &HT;    By Lillian Lee Kim and M.A.J. McKenna
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QR;  ``The American Dietitic Association's Complete Food &AMP;
Nutrition Guide'' by Roberta Larson Duyff, M.S., R.D., C.F.C.S.
(Chronimed Publishing, 1998. $24.95 paperback.)
</P>
<P>
   Everyone who professes to care about what they eat should have a
copy of this book. It covers everything about nutrition from how
much vitamin A you need, to how long you can keep raw eggs in the
refrigerator, to how often you should get screened for diabetes.
Parents will find the guide particularly useful, as it includes
sections on nutrition for pregnant women, breast-feeding mothers
and children.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Nutrition for Dummies'' by Carol Ann Rinzler. (IDG Books,
1999. $19.99 paperback.)
</P>
<P>
   The ADA's nutrition book (see preceeding) is more comprehensive
and a better value, but this volume of the ``Dummies'' series is
more fun to read _ probably in part because it's only half as
heavy. The book contains sound information and includes a basic
calorie-counter nutritional guide for various foods.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``The Nutrition Bible'' by Jean Anderson, M.S., and Barbara
Deskins, Ph.D., R.D. (William Morrow, 1995. $17 paperback.)
</P>
<P>
   This book is organized like a dictionary, with more than 5,000
alphabetized entries from ``A, Vitamin'' to ``Zwieback.'' So it's
useful for looking up specific terms, but not conducive to easy
browsing.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``The Complete Book of Food Counts'' by Corinne T. Netzer.
(Dell, 1997. $7.50 paperback.)
</P>
<P>
   This compilation of nutritional information about generic and
brand-name foods is impressively inclusive. For each item, Netzer
provides calories, protein, carbohydrates, fat, cholesterol, sodium
and fiber. But only total grams of carbohydrates and fat are given;
those looking for more specific information, such as sugar or
saturated fat content, may need to consult another book, such as
Dr. Art Ulene's ``NutriBase Guide to Fat &AMP; Cholesterol.''
</P>
<P>
   _Lillian Lee Kim
</P>
<P>
   NTERNET SITE OF THE WEEK
</P>
<P>
   The head bone's connected to the neck bone, the neck bone's
connected to the ... Web surfers can see for themselves just what's
connected to what at the National Library of Medicine's Visible
Human project (www.nlm.nih.gov/research
</P>
<P>
   /visiblehuman.html). Using the cadavers of people who willed
their bodies to science, the project is building a digital library
of three-dimensional anatomical images. For a literally head-to-toe
trip through one body, go to www.nlm.nih.gov/research
</P>
<P>
   /visible/visiblegallery.html and click on the first bulleted
item. The final image _ the imprint of the toes of one foot _ is
haunting.
</P>
<P>
   _M.A.J. McKenna
</P>
