<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWSSTAND19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The lineup: 100 years of sports
 &HT;    By Don O'Briant
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   In one of the most interesting issues in a while, Newsweek
($3.50) looks back at the century in sports and interviews some of
the athletes and those who knew them. Muhammad Ali promises _
jokingly, we hope _ to get back into the ring for an exhibition
bout with two or three contenders. ``I'll dance for 15 rounds, and
whup 'em. I haven't forgotten.'' Other interviews include one by
Atlantan Charlie Yates about his friend, golf legend Bobby Jones.
When a reporter asked Jones if he was sad about having to give up
golf because of health problems, Jones replied: ``Remember, you
play the ball as it lies.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The gospel truth: U.S. News &AMP; World Report ($3.50) seems
determined to stir up a controversy with its cover story and book
excerpt, ``Is the Bible True?'' Recent archaeological discoveries
are shedding new light on some biblical figures once considered
fictional legends. The unearthing of a 900 B.C. stone tablet in
Galilee with an inscription about the House of David is the first
historical evidence that King David existed. Now some scholars are
attempting to reconcile the scientific idea of evolution and the
biblical concept of divine creation. There is a middle ground, says
author Jeffery L. Sheler. ``Now a growing number of conservative
scholars embrace theistic evolution _ a view that considers
evolution, like all other physical processes known to science, to
be divinely designed and governed.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  A family affair: Maybe parents have gotten a bad rap.
According to a survey on the American family by Life ($3.99),
fathers in intact families spend more time with their children than
their fathers or grandfathers did. And even working moms spend
twice as much time with each child as mothers did in the 1920s. The
reason so many think American families are facing worse problems
now, says historian Stephanie Coontz, is that they are comparing
them to the seemingly more idyllic 1950s. But, she adds, ``much of
the nostalgia for the 1950s is a result of selective amnesia.''
Despite the rise in youth violence, an infant was four times more
likely to die in the 1950s than today.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  School daze: It's no ``Fast Times at Ridgemont High,'' but
it's pretty close. Time ($3.50) sent eight reporters and five
photographers to chronicle a week at Webster Groves High School in
suburban St. Louis. The reporters wanted to find out if the school,
portrayed as complacent and directionless in a 1965 Charles Kuralt
documentary on CBS, had changed. At no time did the reporters try
to hide their identities, but students still confided in them.
Students divide themselves into social groups as they always have,
but several things have changed in post-Columbine America: An armed
security guard is on duty, and the principal and her deputies roam
the halls with walkie-talkies in an attempt to stop disasters
before they start.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Quick reads: What do Sigmund Freud and Bill Clinton have in
common? Well, besides the obvious, Cigar Aficionado ($4.95) has
chosen them as two of the Top 100 cigar smokers of the century. The
Top 5 are Winston Churchill, John F. Kennedy, Fidel Castro, George
Burns and Mark Twain. Burns, who lived to be 100, smoked 10 to 15
cigars a day. ... P.O.V. ($2.99) picks the 100 best sites on the
Internet that allow you to play doctor, invest well and have fun.
The top five are broadcast.com, MP3.com, Amazon.com, Den.com and
ESPN.com. ...You would expect Bob Guccione Jr. to feature a
centerfold in Gear ($3.50), but not a life-size poster of Mini Me.
A more attractive layout features photos of VH1 VJ Madison Michele.
The photos are more revealing than the interview.
</P>
<P>
   Don O'Briant writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
