<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    No miracle, but `Omega' finds success
 &HT;    By Bob Longino
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Fight Club'' ultimately won Hollywood's weekend box office
brawl, taking in just over $11.13 million to finish No. 1 in final
figures released Monday.
</P>
<P>
   But another film _ Trinity Broadcasting Network's ``The Omega
Code'' _ also scored a small victory in its quest to become a force
in Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Omega Code,'' with a plot reminiscent of the biblical book
of Revelation and a mission to lure evangelical Christians to the
movies, garnered an impressive $7,622 per-screen average while
totaling $2.28 million to finish No. 10.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Omega Code'' opened at about 300 theaters nationwide while
the mega-hyped ``Fight Club'' debuted at about 2,000. ``Fight
Club's'' per-screen average was roughly $5,500.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's great,'' said Stephan Blinn, associate producer and
screenwriter of ``The Omega Code.'' ``We set out with our goal to
be the No. 1 independent movie for the weekend and the No. 1 film
in per-screen average and we did both. It was cool to also crack
the Top 10 overall. That's something we hadn't made a goal.''
</P>
<P>
   While ``The Omega Code's'' first per-screen take is certainly
respectable, it pales in comparison to that of ``The Blair Witch
Project,'' which astonished experts last summer with a whopping
initial per-screen average of more than $56,000.
</P>
<P>
   But many major Hollywood films have opened _ and later won
Oscars _ with a smaller per-screen average than that garnered by
``The Omega Code.'' ``L.A. Confidential,'' for instance, opened two
years ago to critical raves and a per-screen average of $7,152.
</P>
<P>
   Finishing behind ``Fight Club'' at this weekend's box office was
``Double Jeopardy,'' with Ashley Judd and Tommy Lee Jones. It
ranked second, with a total box office of $10.13 million and a
per-screen average of $3,450. ``The Story of Us,'' featuring Bruce
Willis and Michelle Pfeiffer, was third, with a total take of $9.75
million and a per-screen average of $4,506.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, ``The Sixth Sense'' will undoubtedly break the $250
million mark this week. The Bruce Willis film, which finished
eighth over the weekend, has a total box office so far of $249.92
million.
</P>
<P>
   A final rundown of the weekend's box office:
</P>
<P>
   1. ``Fight Club'' _ $11.13 million
</P>
<P>
   2. ``Double Jeopardy'' _ $10.13 million
</P>
<P>
   3. ``The Story of Us'' _ $9.75 million
</P>
<P>
   4. ``Three Kings'' _ $7.39 million
</P>
<P>
   5. ``American Beauty'' _ $6.49 million
</P>
<P>
   6. ``Random Hearts'' _ $5.80 million
</P>
<P>
   7. ``Superstar'' _ $5.73 million
</P>
<P>
   8. ``The Sixth Sense'' _ $5.22 million
</P>
<P>
   9. ``Blue Streak'' _ $3.78 million
</P>
<P>
   10. ``The Omega Code'' _ $2.28 million
</P>
<P>
   Bob Longino writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
