<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SYPHILIS-FRONTLINE19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Frontline' in metro Atlanta a troubling look at teen syphilis
outbreakBy Drew Jubera
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Do you know where your children are?
</P>
<P>
   No, you don't. Not if you're a parent of the kids portrayed in
PBS's ``The Lost Children of Rockdale County,'' tonight's chilling
``Frontline'' presentation that centers on the binge decadence of
suburban high school kids outside Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   The 90-minute documentary, which includes explicit sexual
descriptions that might startle some viewers, plays like a
real-life companion to the new film ``American Beauty:'' a
dark-side tour behind the suburbanscape that once defined the
American dream, but which a recent trail of school shootings has
reconstructed for some into an updated version of the American
nightmare.
</P>
<P>
   Producers Rachel Dretzin Goodman and Barak Goodman spent five
months among a circle of mostly well-off teens in Conyers, 25 miles
east of Atlanta. They were there during the months leading up to
last May's shooting at Rockdale's Heritage High, which came a month
after the shootings at Columbine High, in suburban Denver.
</P>
<P>
   The result, shown tonight with unsettling, if sometimes
unrelenting, frankness, is ``a deeper story of lonely kids
desperate to belong, a secret world of sex ... of disconnection and
regrets.''
</P>
<P>
   Or as a 14-year-old puts it: ``It was more an underground
railroad thing: Everybody would secretly have sex with everybody,
and the parents never knew.''
</P>
<P>
   This ``underground railroad thing'' was uncovered three years
ago, as Conyers prepared to host equestrian events for the Atlanta
Summer Olympics. A syphilis outbreak among 17 teens alerted
authorities and parents. A pattern of orgiastic sex was eventually
discovered that effected as many as 200 kids, some as young as 13.
A public health chart that linked these kids's sexual histories had
so many lines drawn to so many participants that it looked, says
Georgia public heath director Kathleen Toomey, like ``a ball of
yarn.''
</P>
<P>
   When Rockdale officials called a town hall meeting, parents
recited a litany of culprits for their childrens' behavior: TV,
video games, movies.
</P>
<P>
   ``None of them looked to themselves,'' says Toomey. ``The
community was in total denial.''
</P>
<P>
   What emerges from tonight's emotional travelogue is a dark,
darkly heart-breaking terrain _ a kind of neutron-bombed community
where houses are intact but families are shattered. Careerist
parents work long hours to provide kids with material wealth, but
give up on giving the contact and structure they need. Kids turn
their lack of direction into a madate to veer out of control.
</P>
<P>
   The producers convincingly frame it all as an of
end-of-the-century consequence of families caught up in a life at
the ``outer edge of what has been called the fastest growing
settlement in human history: the rings of suburbs surrounding
greater Atlanta.''
</P>
<P>
   After an hour, however, the documentary loses some direction
itself. It veers from those affected by the 1996 syphilis outbreak
to a current crop of Rockdale teens, oblivious to their
predecessors and repeating their behavior.
</P>
<P>
   The last third provides some of the film's most disturbing
images_ three young girls use their stuffed toy animals to
demonstrate the complex couplings of group sex. But it also
underscores the documentary's weakness. Teens here are either
sex-mad or devoutly Christian virgins. How the forces of these
extremes affect those in the vast, confusing middle is left mostly
unexplored.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the overall effect is so disturbing it's as hard to
imagine parents not rushing afterward to talk with their teens, as
it is hard to imagine their teens not talking back. ``The Lost
Children of Rockdale County'' demonstrates just how rare that would
be.
</P>
<P>
   ``Frontline: The Lost Children of Rockdale County''
</P>
<P>
   10 tonight on PBS. A discussion of issues raised in the
documentary airs at 11:30 p.m. E.S.T.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B+
</P>
<P>
   Drew Jubera writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
