A0931 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-HEALTH-CONSUMER19-COX     10-18 0772
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEALTH-CONSUMER19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Book, matching service offer new help in finding top docs
 &HT;    By Diane Lore
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Most of us find a doctor in a very measured,
scientific and logical manner: We ask our friends.
</P>
<P>
   But what if you could ask doctors where they would send their
families or friends if they needed medical care?
</P>
<P>
   That's the foundation of a new book titled ``Guide to Top
Doctors'' ($19.95), published by the Center for the Study of
Services, a nonprofit heath care consumer group based in
Washington. More than 15,000 physicians are listed by region, and
sometimes by cities, with each receiving at least three
recommendations from their peers. In Atlanta, 310 doctors were
selected by their peers as being outstanding. The center then
back-checked the doctors' board certifications, licenses and office
telephone numbers.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a precise science,'' said Robert M. Krughoff, the
center's president. ``But the bottom line is, if a physician keeps
showing up on other doctors' lists, odds are they're going to be
pretty good.''
</P>
<P>
   In a nationwide survey, more than 260,000 doctors were asked to
recommend two doctors in 30 specialties.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the names of metro Atlanta physicians listed in the book
come as no surprise. But the book also lists some suburban doctors,
who typically don't get a lot of notice. And that means that many
people living outside the Perimeter won't feel they need to head to
the city to get excellent care.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of stuff that doesn't need a university teaching
center,'' Krughoff said. ``This gives consumers some choices beyond
the obvious.''
</P>
<P>
   The book is also extremely helpful because patients can compare
the list with their managed care networks and hopefully find some
matches _ instead of picking a doctor with the accuracy of pitching
a dart.
</P>
<P>
   Krughoff also recommends that patients use the book to:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Discuss specialists with their primary care physician. The
primary care practitioner might know some of those listed and be
able to direct the patient to the best choice for a given
condition.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Get an unbiased second opinion. It's human nature that a
doctor whom your first doctor has referred you to for a second
opinion might hesitate to disagree with the first doctor.
Sometimes, people would be better off picking someone totally
unrelated to the first doctor.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Bolster a case against a managed care company. If a patient
believes that a doctor is denying needed treatment because he or
she is too constrained by the company, the patient would have some
place to turn for another opinion outside the network. If that
doctor reaches a different conclusion, the patient might have a
stronger argument.
</P>
<P>
   The idea for such a book isn't new. In the early 1990s, a
company called Best Doctors Inc. of Aiken, S.C., began publishing a
similar volume. But people who were seriously ill found that such
lists have major limitations, the company says.
</P>
<P>
   ``Often, it's not good enough to simply find the best
oncologist,'' explained Stephanie Spooner, spokeswoman for Best
Doctors Inc. ``You need to find the specialties and subspecialties
(of physicians) to be truly useful.''
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Best Doctors Inc. altered its approach. Instead of
publishing the books, it offers patients an ``accumatch.'' The
patient works with a company caseworker on the specifics of
diagnosis and treatment; then the company matches him or her to
appropriate doctors in the city, state, region, nation or even
worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   It's expensive. The matches cost $2,000, although Spooner said
she expects that price to fall by about half in about two months.
Patients receive a detailed folder of information about doctors,
contacts and time frames (one of the advantages is that you don't
get hooked up with doctors who can't see you for six months).
</P>
<P>
   As for Krughoff, he's hoping ``Guide to Top Doctors'' will be a
welcome addition to any family library _ and notes that compiling
it was a labor-intensive, expensive process. ``Try reading
thousands of doctors' prescription handwriting and then try
matching them up,'' he said, laughing. ``What a nightmare!''
</P>
<P>
   You can purchase the book by calling 1-800-213-7283 or writing
to Center for the Study of Services, 733 15th St. N.W., Washington,
DC 20005. The price of $19.95 includes shipping and handling.
</P>
<P>
   For more information about getting a Best Doctors match, call
1-888-362-8677 (1-888-DOCTORS).
</P>
<P>
   Diane Lore writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
