<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NUTRITION19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    FDA may OK labels for `functional foods'
 &HT;    By Rachael Kennedy
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Ketchup to prevent cancer? Grape juice to ward off
heart disease?
</P>
<P>
   Don't be surprised if, in the near future, you see those labels
on products on grocery store shelves.
</P>
<P>
   Ketchup and grape juice are among a growing number of so-called
``functional foods'' _ whole foods and fortified, enriched, or
enhanced foods that have a potential beneficial effect on health
when part of a varied diet.
</P>
<P>
   Natural foods such as broccoli and tea have been making
headlines as functional foods for a few years. Dietitians attending
the American Dietetic Association's Annual meeting in Atlanta on
Monday learned that the Food and Drug Administration is reviewing
the scientific data and may approve ``functional labels'' soon.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Functional Foods for Health Program at the
University of Illinois, in Urbana-Champaign and Chicago, foods to
watch over the next year and their anticipated labels include:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Soy protein and grape juice for their ability to reduce the
risk of heart disease.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Tomato products and broccoli for their ability to reduce the
risk of various cancers.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Foods enhanced with plant-based substances such as psyllium,
phytosterol and stanolesterol, known for their ability to lower
blood cholesterol.
</P>
<P>
   Other foods currently under research include other cruciferous
vegetables, carrots, citrus fruits, cranberries, dairy, fish,
flaxseed, garlic, meats and oats.
</P>
<P>
   Rachel Kennedy writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
