u f BC-DELTA-EARNINGS-COX     10-18 0347
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DELTA-EARNINGS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Delta's profit dips, but tops expectations
 &HT;    By Scott Thurston
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Blame it partly on Floyd.
</P>
<P>
   Delta Air Lines on Monday said profits fell 11 percent in its
first fiscal quarter, hurt by the effects of 1,100 flight
cancellations during Hurricane Floyd.
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta-based airline said the September storm, which hit
Florida and rolled up the East Coast, cost it more than $20 million
in lost revenue.
</P>
<P>
   The airline also said average fuel prices rose about 4 percent
from a year earlier. That reversed the trend of the past two years,
when falling fuel costs boosted Delta's profit growth.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Delta's net profit of $290 million, or $1.96 a share,
exceeded Wall Street forecasts. The results compared with a profit
of $327 million, or $2.08 a share, in the same quarter of 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Revenue rose about 2 percent, to $3.88 billion, while seat
capacity climbed 3 percent. Delta's operating margin fell from 14.5
percent to 12.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The results don't include gains on the sale of investments or
one-time charges. Including those items, first-quarter profit was
$352 million, or $2.38 a share.
</P>
<P>
   About $255 million in gains came on the sale of stock in
Singapore Airlines and shares in Internet start-up Priceline.com.
</P>
<P>
   Continental Airlines also reported quarterly results Monday,
posting a 27 percent profit drop to $110 million. Like Delta, it
cited the effects of Hurricane Floyd and higher fuel costs.
</P>
<P>
   But analysts also say big airlines are struggling to maintain
unit revenues in the face of plateauing traffic growth. At Delta,
the proportion of seats filled dipped to 75 percent for the
quarter, down from 76.7 percent a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Both Delta and Continental, the first major airlines to post
results this quarter, also lost the benefit of a year-earlier
strike at rival Northwest Airlines.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Thurston writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
