<DOCNO> NYT19991018.0385 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-18 19:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0936 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-DELTA19-COX     10-18 1030
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DELTA19-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   New regional jets part of motivation
</P>
<P>
   By Scott Thurston
</P>
<P>
   C. 1999 Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ With its buyout of Comair, Delta Air Lines has spent
$2.5 billion this year to purchase its two biggest regional
affiliates.
</P>
<P>
   The moves give Delta the dual benefits of absorbing the smaller
carriers' strong profit margins and gaining full control of their
growing fleets of small jets, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   Delta on Monday announced it will spend $1.8 billion to buy
Cincinnati-based Comair, a highly successful regional carrier that
provides connecting service at Delta's hubs in Cincinnati and
Orlando.
</P>
<P>
   The deal calls for Delta to pay $23.50 a share in a tender offer
for the 78 percent of Comair stock it doesn't already own, and it
will assume $110 million in debt. The buyout should close by year's
end, Delta said, pending completion of the tender offer and
regulatory approval.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta-based Delta, which had about $1.6 billion in cash as of
Sept. 30, said it will finance the deal with a mix of cash and
debt.
</P>
<P>
   The purchase follows a $700 million buyout earlier this year of
Atlanta-based Atlantic Southeast Airlines, Delta's primary regional
feeder in Atlanta and Dallas-Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   Both the Comair and ASA purchases are mostly transparent to
passengers but bring a large fleet of new regional jets under
Delta's direct control. Comair has been an industry pioneer in
moving away from the turboprop ``puddle jumpers'' long used by
feeder airlines and into the new breed of small jets. It now has 82
Canadair Regional Jets, with 48 more on order.
</P>
<P>
   The planes fly as far, as fast and as high as some larger
airliners, and they are blurring the lines between major airlines
and their regional partners.
</P>
<P>
   Major airlines are increasingly using the regionals' small jets
not just to connect to small cities near their hubs, but also to
augment their mainline schedules and serve longer-range routes that
don't support big-jet service.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, ASA this year opened new routes between Atlanta
and Islip, N.Y., and Des Moines, Iowa, using regional jets.
</P>
<P>
   ``The markets served by RJs are the fastest-growing segment in
the industry right now,'' said Delta Chief Executive Leo Mullin.
``These planes represent a tremendous service improvement and can
bring a lot of growth into our system.''
</P>
<P>
   By buying full ownership in ASA and Comair, Delta assures
decisions about deployment of the small jets will be to its best
advantage, said analyst Thomas Longman of Arnhold &AMP; S.
Bliechroeder. ``This gives Delta the ability to control Comair's
scheduling and marketing to a much larger extent than it had in the
past,'' he told Bloomberg News.
</P>
<P>
   But James D. Parker, an analyst at SunTrust Equitable
Securities, said Delta effectively controls the jets already
because it provides most of Comair's passengers. He believes
Delta's main motive is financial.
</P>
<P>
   He said Comair has a 28 percent profit margin, largely as a
byproduct of a longstanding revenue-sharing contract with Delta.
Comair had revenue of $763.3 million and a profit of $132.9 million
in its fiscal year ended March 31.
</P>
<P>
   ``Delta wanted some of that, and they also had excess cash on
hand,'' Parker said. ``This addresses both issues.''
</P>
<P>
   The 10-year Delta-Comair contract ends this month, and Delta was
pushing for more favorable terms. The talks shifted to the
acquisition mode late last week, according to Mullin.
</P>
<P>
   Both companies' boards approved the deal Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Comair could have parted ways with Delta and tried to go it
alone or align with another carrier,'' Parker said. ``But they
would have had to work harder, and their stock price would have
suffered.''
</P>
<P>
   The tender offer represents a 31 percent premium over Comair's
closing stock price before the deal was announced. Shares jumped
$5.06 1/4 to $23 Monday but are under a 52-week high of $29.
</P>
<P>
   Like ASA, Comair will operate as a separate unit within Delta.
Comair President and Chief Operating Officer David Siebenburgen,
52, will become Delta's top executive for regional feeder
operations.
</P>
<P>
   The Comair purchase is allowed under Delta's contract with its
unionized pilots. However, it's expected to play into just-started
talks between Delta and the union over a new contract.
</P>
<P>
   Pilot unions view expanded regional jet flying as a potential
form of outsourcing, since pilots at the smaller carriers are paid
substantially less.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Renkel, vice chairman of Delta's Air Line Pilots
Association unit, said the Comair purchase ``underscores the
importance of attaining protections and job security'' during the
new contract talks. He said the union wants ``aggressive
enhancements'' in that regard.
</P>
<P>
   Mullin said he's aware of the pilots' concerns but contends
ownership of Comair and ASA will strengthen Delta's total system,
boosting job growth and security for pilots at all levels.
</P>
<P>
   Comair pilots are represented separately by ALPA. Comair flight
attendants are represented by the Teamsters, while the Machinists
union represents mechanics. Delta said there will be no work force
integration and that all labor contracts will remain in place.
</P>
<P>
   Delta still has contractual arrangements with four other
regional carriers. They include SkyWest through its Salt Lake City
hub, and Business Express and Trans States in the Northeast. Delta
recently inked a deal for the exclusive right to book seats on 45
new regional jets ordered by Atlantic Coast Airlines, based near
Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   Mullin said those deals ``make great sense'' in their current
form.
</P>
<P>
   ABOUT COMAIR
</P>
<P>
   Headquarters: Cincinnati, Ohio
</P>
<P>
   Primary operations: Connecting service for Delta in Cincinnati
and Orlando, flying mainly to points in the Midwest and Northeast
and within Florida
</P>
<P>
   Fleet: 82 Canadair Regional Jets (48 more on order), 20 Embraer
Brasilia turboprops
</P>
<P>
   Employees: 4,400
</P>
<P>
   Financial performance: $132.9 million profit on revenue of
$763.3 million in fiscal year ended March 31
</P>
<P>
   Scott Thurston writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
