u f BC-DOWDOW19-COX     10-18 0560
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOWDOW19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Wall Street sees glimmer of improvement
 &HT;    By Tom Walker
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   A measure of hope returned to Wall Street on Monday as blue chip
averages recovered a portion of recent losses.
</P>
<P>
   Both the Dow Jones industrial average and the Standard &AMP; Poor's
500 index rebounded. The NASDAQ composite fell again, but managed
to trim some of the day's earlier decline.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts have decided that investors over-reacted to last
week's worse-than-expected wholesale inflation report and to the
cautionary comments by Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan to a
bankers' group.
</P>
<P>
   Perennial bull Abby Joseph Cohen, strategist at Goldman, Sachs,
also gave investors a boost when she declared the market's
fundamentals are still intact and that recent weakness was
``unfounded,'' Dow Jones News Service reported.
</P>
<P>
   Other analysts think the current correction that started about
six months ago still has a way to go, and could send the Dow Jones
industrial average to closings below 10,000.
</P>
<P>
   But A.G. Edwards &AMP; Sons strategist Alfred Goldman said he
believes ``the Dow is about there,'' referring to the bottom of
this year's sell-off.
</P>
<P>
   What most analysts can agree on is that the major stock market
averages don't convey the extent of the damage that has already
occurred in the market.
</P>
<P>
   Ricky T. Harrington, technical analyst for Wachovia Securities,
said indexes such as the Dow and the S&AMP;P-500 are driven by a
handful of big stocks that continue to do well, while most other
stocks are in the tank.
</P>
<P>
   ``Almost 80 percent of all stocks are down 20 percent from their
highs in 1998,'' said Harrington. ``I think this qualifies as a
bear market.''
</P>
<P>
   The plus side is that it means the sell-off is probably nearing
a bottom, they say.
</P>
<P>
   As for Greenspan's speech to a bankers group last Thursday
night, which added momentum to Friday's selling, Goldman said the
message was nothing new.
</P>
<P>
   ``He told the bankers to be prudent. I think the market
overreacted,'' said Goldman.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, the Dow wrapped up its worst weekly point loss ever _
and dipping briefly below 10,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``Would I panic if it dropped to 9,500? It could happen,'' said
Goldman. ``But I see it at 11,300 at year-end, and the (30-year
Treasury) bond yield at 5.6 percent to 5.7 percent.''
</P>
<P>
   A Treasury yield of better than 6 percent since June is one of
the factors that has depressed stock prices, analysts agree, since
it gives investors a favorable alternative to stocks.
</P>
<P>
   But the yield has come under pressure in the latest stock market
sell-off. As investors bailed out of stocks and into bonds _
perceived as a safe haven _ increased bond demand has driven prices
higher and yields lower.
</P>
<P>
   Goldman contends that the nation's economic fundamentals are
still too strong to permit a sustained down market.
</P>
<P>
   The market's chief concern is the prospect of higher interest
rates, which analysts believe is likely if the inflation news
worsens. That was the significance of Friday's Producer Price Index
report.
</P>
<P>
   If today's Consumer Price Index is also significantly worse than
expected, analysts fear another wave of selling could occur.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Walker writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution, Atlanta,
Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
