NYT-10-18-99 1958EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991018.0388 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-18 19:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0939 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-CLINTON-BUDGET19-COX     10-18 0870
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-BUDGET19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CLINTON, CONGRESS LEADERS SET BUDGET TALKS
 &HT;    530&AMP;add.
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Cloaking sharp political differences behind
professions of good will, President Clinton and Republican
congressional leaders agreed to seek a way out of a tax and
spending impasse in White House budget talks Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   On the eve of negotiations, however, both sides drew stark
battle lines, conceding that they wouldn't bridge their differences
in time to meet a Thursday deadline for completing the $1.8
trillion budget for the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Underscoring those differences, Clinton vetoed a Republican bid
to slash $2.2 billion _ 14 percent _ from the White House request
for foreign aid and diplomatic operations spending.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton blasted the proposed cuts, which targeted $1.2 billion
the administration had sought to promote Mideast peace, and
millions more the White House wants to help safeguard Russia's
nuclear weapons program and reduce Third World debt.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems to me to be the next big chapter in the new American
isolationism,'' Clinton said of the cuts, ``right after the
Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week the Senate voted down the treaty, which Clinton has
signed. It would have called for an end to test explosions of
nuclear weapons among the United States and 153 other nations.
</P>
<P>
   The fight over the test ban treaty and the funding of foreign
aid were only the latest in a weeks-long series of bitterly
partisan battles over taxes, spending and judicial appointments.
</P>
<P>
   Amid the rising rancor, Clinton called for Tuesday's budget
talks, saying the essential business of funding the government
could not be held hostage to politics.
</P>
<P>
   ``Inaction is not an option,'' Clinton told reporters at the
White House. ``We have to put politics aside and seek common
ground.''
</P>
<P>
   Republicans responded in kind.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's music to my ears,'' House Majority Leader Dick Armey,
R-Texas, told reporters in response to Clinton's invitation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I look forward to a productive discussion,'' echoed his Senate
counterpart, Trent Lott, R-Miss.
</P>
<P>
   Behind such pledges of good faith, however, both Clinton and his
Republican foes cast hard-line opening bids on the eve of talks
scheduled for late Tuesday afternoon at the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton vowed not to surrender his demands for money to hire
additional teachers and police and to press for full funding for a
slate of environmental initiatives.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans, for their part, countered with a proposal for
across-the-board cuts in so-called discretionary spending _ the
one-third of the budget that doesn't include such mandatory
programs as Social Security, Medicare, Medicaid and veterans'
benefits.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're willing to talk about that,'' Armey said of the
discretionary cuts, ``but what we're not willing to do is to
discuss either raiding Social Security or raising taxes.''
</P>
<P>
   Both Clinton and his Republican foes have pledged publicly not
to balance the budget by tapping into the surplus from the Social
Security program.
</P>
<P>
   Budget analysts, however, believe that is where the process is
headed. The political game, at the moment, is for each side to try
to make it appear that the other side caved in and tapped the
Social Security cash cow for its own partisan purposes.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no answer to this,'' said former Congressional Budget
Office director Robert D. Reischauer.
</P>
<P>
   ``You either have to cut spending or raise taxes, or agree that
some of the Social Security surplus will be used to fund non-Social
Security programs, as it has over the last 30 or 35 years,'' said
Reischauer, senior economics fellow at the Brookings Institution, a
Washington research center. ``It's not what they both want to do,
it's what they know they are going to end up doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's negotiations were not expected to resolve such
matters. Privately, the best either side appeared to hope for was
some sort of road map for further negotiations aimed at settling
the tax and spending issues over the next 10 days or so.
</P>
<P>
   Conceding as much, Clinton said he was prepared to sign a
temporary spending bill on Thursday to keep government operations
funded. The federal government has been operating under such
temporary funding since Oct. 1, the official start of the fiscal
2000 budget year.
</P>
<P>
   Federal spending is governed by 13 huge appropriations bills
that Congress approves each year and sends to the White House for
the president's signature. So far, Congress has sent the White
House 10 appropriations bills, two of which he has vetoed and five
of which he has signed. Three remain on his desk and the House
intends to get the remaining three to him ``by the end of the
week,'' Armey told reporters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly, this is about money,'' Armey said. ``As long as we
can work out a compromise that fulfills the initial commitment, and
the overwhelming commitment, to not touch a dime's worth of Social
Security, we'll discuss any matter of spending priority the
president wants to discuss.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
