<SLUG> BC-GAPACIFIC-SUIT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Georgia-Pacific faces reverse racial bias suit
 &HT;    By Patti Bond
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ A white former employee of Georgia-Pacific Corp. is
suing the company, accusing it of racial discrimination.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph D. Green alleges he was unjustly fired last year from
Georgia-Pacific's tissue mill in Palatka, Fla., because the company
wanted to appease black workers who had complained about racial
problems there. Green, a 32-year employee of Georgia-Pacific, filed
the suit Friday in U.S. District Court in Jacksonville.
</P>
<P>
   In his complaint, Green said he was fired in an attempt to curb
racial tension between management and some of the plant's black
employees. According to the suit, a group of workers objected to
disciplinary actions taken against a new black employee who was
still on probation.
</P>
<P>
   A Georgia-Pacific spokesman said Monday that the company had not
yet seen the lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be inappropriate to make any comments until we've
reviewed the complaint,'' said Greg Guest.
</P>
<P>
   Guest added that the company does not tolerate race or gender
discrimination.
</P>
<P>
   Green is seeking punitive and compensatory damages, plus lost
wages and benefits.
</P>
<P>
   He also wants to be reinstated in his former position as
coordinator of training and resource development.
</P>
<P>
   Patti Bond writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution, Atlanta,
Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
