<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-18 20:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0945 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-COCACOLA-COX     10-18 0733
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COCACOLA-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Coke canvassing world to reshape Classic's image
 &HT;    By Henry Unger
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Anthropologists in Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Sociologists in Japan.
</P>
<P>
   And ethnographers in Europe and Thailand.
</P>
<P>
   You might not expect all that brainpower to go into the
marketing of just one soft drink, but it does.
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola Co. has called on a variety of academics to work with
its own global marketing team to develop a new direction for its
flagship brand, Coke Classic.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a virtual network of researchers around the world to
give us (consumer) insights,'' Charlie Frenette, the company's
chief marketing officer, said Monday in one of his first interviews
since ascending to that position 18 months ago.
</P>
<P>
   Frenette said the information provided by the researchers is
critical to the company's strategic plans.
</P>
<P>
   Early next year, consumers will see the results of that research
with the debut of the first major changes in the marketing of Coke
Classic in seven years. The ``Always'' Coca-Cola theme is being
replaced on Classic packages with ``Enjoy.'' And there will be new
media spots.
</P>
<P>
   But there's a lot more behind the change than just a word,
Frenette said. The message the company will be trying to sell,
along with the reasons for it, are key to understanding the remake
of Classic.
</P>
<P>
   It starts with an illustration.
</P>
<P>
   The bottle cap is popped, and the drink dances out of the
container. That's being done in hopes of stimulating your taste
buds and turning on the rest of your senses, including any positive
associations you might have with Coke.
</P>
<P>
   The company calls the concept ``sensation graphics,'' which
tries to exploit any ``magical delight'' consumers have had with
the product. For example, when the Atlanta Braves hit homers at
Turner Field, the Coke bottle above left field erupts in fireworks.
</P>
<P>
   The message of the new campaign is simple, Frenette said:
``Coca-Cola supports your quest to enjoy life at a higher level.''
</P>
<P>
   By taking this approach, the company hopes to bring Classic to a
higher level of sales. While the brand is still, by far, the
world's most popular soft drink, its growth rate has been trailing
such non-cola flavors as the company's Sprite brand and Pepsi's
Mountain Dew.
</P>
<P>
   To boost Classic, Frenette said the researchers, along with the
company's own employees, have studied several issues, including the
``human condition,'' or ``how people live their lives,'' in diverse
parts of the globe. That's important to a company that sells its
brands in 200 countries.
</P>
<P>
   The effort, he said, was not a superficial one, but an in-depth
study into consumer culture and behavior, and what motivates people
to purchase specific products.
</P>
<P>
   ``Charlie Frenette makes decisions on an intensely researched
basis,'' said John Sicher, editor and publisher of Beverage Digest.
``He has a deep understanding of the soft drink business, like few
others today.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the things Frenette said he learned from the research is
that consumers are seeking ``touchstones of stability'' and
genuineness.
</P>
<P>
   That's different from the goal of the ``Always'' campaign, he
said, which was created to give Classic a ``multidimensional view''
with a ``plethora of messages,'' depending on the target audience.
The campaign's TV ads featured everything from talking ice cubes
and animated ants to senior citizens sipping Coke and a youth
orchestra playing on the streets of New York.
</P>
<P>
   Now, however, the goal is singular: ``Awaken the senses.'' Just
how that will be executed in ads and other promotions is still
being discussed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't shot a foot of film yet,'' said Frenette, who spoke
about the new campaign after word leaked out about it last week.
``What we've got is a strategy.''
</P>
<P>
   The strategy will be executed differently in different nations.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a local business at the end of the day,'' he said. What
works in the United States may fall flat in Thailand.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, Frenette said, the company knows that to beef up
Classic sales it has to provide relevant marketing on a consistent
basis.
</P>
<P>
   ``People wake up thirsty everyday,'' Frenette said. ``We've got
to re-connect with consumers everyday.''
</P>
<P>
   Henry Unger writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
