<SLUG> BC-MARKET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STOCKS CLOSE MIXED AS HESITATION PERSISTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also STOCKS-MARKETPLACE) 
(mk) 
 By KENNETH N. GILPIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Stock prices were mixed Monday, but investors
remained hesitant and analysts said there were no indications that
the recent steep slide in the market had ended.
</P>
<P>
   Led by shares of banks, which posted strong third-quarter
earnings, the Dow Jones industrial average staged a late surge and
closed nearly 100 points higher. But technology shares, led lower
by Dell Computer, remained weak, and the NASDAQ composite index,
which registered a new high on Oct. 11, fell for the fourth time in
five sessions.
</P>
<P>
   At the close, the Dow Jones industrial average was up 96.57
points, or 1 percent, to 10,116.28, led by J.P. Morgan, Citigroup
and big drug stocks like Merck and Johnson &AMP; Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index gained 6.72 points, or 0.5
percent, to 1254.13, as gains in stocks like Walmart and Bristol
Myers Squibb offset big declines in computer makers like Dell and
high-flyers like Lucent Technologies.
</P>
<P>
   The NASDAQ composite index fell sharply, but with an hour left
in the trading day the losses were far worse.
</P>
<P>
   At the close, the index fell 42.68 points, or 1.6 percent, to
2689.15. Earlier, the index was down nearly 100 points. Since it
peaked on Columbus Day, the index has slid 226 points, or nearly 8
percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Dow stocks led the tech stocks higher,'' said Richard
Cripps, chief market analyst at Legg Mason in Baltimore. ``As the
Dow improved, that at least got traders to cover their shorts in
the NASDAQ composite.''
</P>
<P>
   Traders said that most of the issues that have been plaguing the
stock market for months remain in place. Near-term, the dominant
worry is about Tuesday's report from the Labor Department on
consumer prices. Last Friday, the market swooned after the
government reported that producer prices had posted their biggest
one-month gain in nine years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think the selling is over,'' said Ned Collins, head
stock trader at Daiwa Securities America. ``With the consumer price
report coming on Tuesday, the threat of a Fed rate hike still there
and worries about Y2K, it is hard to tell people they have to own
stocks.''
</P>
<P>
   Those concerns, particularly worries about rising interest
rates, have pushed large numbers of investors to the sidelines over
the past several months.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have been waiting and worrying about the Fed since May,''
said Arthur Hogan, chief market analyst at Jefferies &AMP; Co. ``That
worry has take about 10 percent to 20 percent out of daily trading
volume since then.''
</P>
<P>
   Monday's session was again marked by fairly low trading volume.
</P>
<P>
   On the New York Stock Exchange, 818.7 million shares changed
hands. Trading volume on the NASDAQ stock market was 997.3 million
shares.
</P>
<P>
   J.P. Morgan, which has seen its stock fall sharply in the last
two months, was the Dow's best performer Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The bank holding company, which reported third-quarter earnings
that exceeded analysts' expectations, saw its stock price jump 7
5/16 to 113.
</P>
<P>
   Investors also rewarded Citigroup, another Dow component that
reported strong earnings. The stock closed at 43 13/16, up 1 11/16.
</P>
<P>
   Drug stocks also had a good day.
</P>
<P>
   Merck, a Dow component, rose 2, to 72 3/16. Bristol Myers Squibb
was up 1 9/16, to 43 13/16. And Warner Lambert, which reported
strong earnings, gained 2 11/16, to 70 9/16.
</P>
<P>
   On a day when interest-rate-sensitive bank and financial stocks
were rising, fears about further increases in rates helped to push
down technology stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Dell Computer lost 1 1/2, to 41 5/16, and dropped even further
in after-hours trading after announcing that rising prices for
computer memory chips would hurt third-quarter profit. Intel fell 1
1/2, to 69 3/4. Lucent dropped 2 3/16, to 57. And Oracle shed 1
1/8, to 43 7/8.
</P>
<P>
   Investors continued to batter companies that come to market with
bad news.
</P>
<P>
   The most recent example is Lexmark International.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, the world's second-biggest maker of ink-jet and laser
printers said profits for its fourth fiscal quarter will be at the
low end of analysts' estimates.
</P>
<P>
   The stock, which has been a high-flyer, fell 29, to 65.
</P>
<P>
   Despite last week's big selloff, demand for initial public
offerings does not appear to have cooled.
</P>
<P>
   Due to strong demand, bankers at Morgan Stanley Dean Witter on
Monday raised their price target for a 7.2 million share offering
of Martha Stewart Living Omnimedia Inc. to $16 to $18 per share,
from $13 to $15 a share. The offering was scheduled to be priced
Monday night.
</P>
</TEXT>
