<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-18 20:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0952 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-SCI-BRAIN-MORALS-2TAK     10-18 0751
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-BRAIN-MORALS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO CASES FOUND WHERE INFANT BRAIN DAMAGE PREVENTED LEARNING MORAL
BEHAVIOR 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Iowa, Calif.)  (The Science Times) 
(DW) 
 By SANDRA BLAKESLEE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Scientists have identified rare cases in which injuries to the
brain in infancy prevented people from learning normal rules of
social and moral behavior in childhood and adolescence. When the
infants reached adulthood, they showed no guilt or remorse for
their extremely bad behavior and seemed destined never to get along
in social situations.
</P>
<P>
   The finding raises important questions about the biological
origins of human empathy and is likely to be fodder for creative
defense lawyers who may argue that clients who have committed
antisocial acts are not responsible for their behavior because a
brain injury prevented their normal socialization.
</P>
<P>
   The new research was carried out by Dr. Antonio Damasio and
colleagues at the University of Iowa College of Medicine in Iowa
City and appears in the November issue of the scientific journal
Nature Neuroscience.
</P>
<P>
   The research involves only two people, and it remains to be seen
if the findings will be confirmed or if people who have such
anomalies can be identified in infancy.
</P>
<P>
   Also, Damasio said, his findings do not explain what turns some
people into cold-blooded killers. The people he studied were more
likely to hurt their own prospects than harm anyone else. But the
new work fits nicely with earlier research, including studies of
people with other kinds of brain damage, that suggest injury to the
brain can alter moral judgments.
</P>
<P>
   The new findings have ``profound implications,'' said Dr.
Raymond Dolan, a neuroscientist at University College London in
England and an expert on human development. If it turns out that
the human brain has a special circuit for learning right from
wrong, and that this circuit can be faulty from birth, Dolan said,
``we will need to reappraise psychopathy, which currently and
conveniently lingers in a hinterland between psychiatry and
criminal services.''
</P>
<P>
   Damasio is an expert on how emotions and bodily sensations drive
a person's conscious awareness and decision making. He is
especially interested in how a primitive brain region involved in
emotions, called the limbic system, interacts with a highly
advanced brain region involved in decision making and planning,
called the prefrontal cortex. When people think about doing
something, a part of the prefrontal cortex calls up knowledge
related to the feelings they have stored about similar situations
in the past, he said. These unconscious emotional signals are then
used to help select the best course of action.
</P>
<P>
   When this region of the prefrontal cortex, located just behind
the eye sockets and above the bridge of the nose, is damaged
because of a stroke or other trauma, Damasio said, the
decision-making circuit breaks down. People who suffer such
injuries may fall into debt, betray their spouses, lose their jobs
or abandon their friends. But if asked in a laboratory setting to
tell right from wrong, they do fine, Damasio said. Their knowledge
of how to behave properly in social situations is intact but their
ability to act on what they know is impaired.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wondered what would happen if a person's prefrontal cortex
was damaged in infancy,'' Damasio said. Although such injuries are
extremely rare, the Iowa researchers found two young adults who had
exactly what they were looking for _ specific damage in infancy to
one or both sides of the prefrontal cortex, especially in the
so-called ventromedial sector of the orbitofrontal cortex.
</P>
<P>
   Now in their early 20s, both people were highly intelligent and
grew up in stable homes with college-educated parents, Damasio
said. Their siblings were well-adjusted and healthy.
</P>
<P>
   The first subject was a woman who was run over by a car when she
was 15 months old. She recovered in a few days but by age 3 she was
ignoring all verbal and physical punishment. As a teen-ager she was
disruptive at home and at school. A compulsive liar, she refused to
follow rules, stole from her family, shoplifted and had no friends.
She had no plans for her future and could not hold a job. She never
expressed guilt or remorse for her behavior but blamed others for
her misdeeds and social problems. There is little or no evidence
that she felt empathy, Damasio said. Pregnant at age 18, she was
dangerously insensitive to her baby.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   The second subject was a young man who had a brain tumor removed
from his right frontal lobe when he was 3 months old. He recovered
quickly and appeared to develop normally. But by age 9, he showed a
lack of motivation, had few friends and would occasionally explode
in anger. He managed to graduate from high school but could not
hold a job, turned to thievery and sometimes lashed out with his
fists. Also a compulsive liar, he showed no empathy, remorse or
guilt and had no plans for the future.
</P>
<P>
   Both subjects were dependent on their parents and seemed to be
impervious to efforts to help them. The basic rudder driving their
behavior was broken, Damasio said.
</P>
<P>
   Both were given batteries of tests to assess their
decision-making abilities. For example, they were asked to choose
between two decks of cards in a game that simulated gambling. One
deck consistently gave high payoffs in the short term but less in
winnings in the long term. The second deck gave less money each
time but more winnings over the life of the game. Most people soon
realize they should choose the second deck, Damasio said. But these
adults stuck with the first deck, he said, ``because the present
gain seems higher and they don't care about the future.'' In a test
that measures moral development, both young adults behaved at the
level of 10-year-olds.
</P>
<P>
   Most important, Damasio said, neither could figure out how to
act in social situations. In this, they differed from people who
have similar brain injury later in life; the people injured later
may not be able to act normally, but they are aware of what social
norms are and have a sense of right and wrong. The people who were
brain-damaged in infancy never seemed to learn rules of social and
moral behavior, Damasio said.
</P>
<P>
   Damasio's work raises important questions about the brain's
ability to reorganize after injury, said Dr. Jordan Grafman, chief
of the cognitive neuroscience branch at the National Institute of
Neurological Disorders and Stroke. When brain regions that underlie
language are surgically removed in early childhood, for example,
children go on to develop language using other parts of the brain.
But this circuit in the prefrontal cortex seems to be
irreplaceable, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Damasio goes so far as to say that this circuit helps give rise
to consciousness and conscience itself, an idea he explores in a
new book, ``The Feeling of What Happens,'' published by Harcourt
Brace and Co..
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want people to misunderstand our research and think
that we have identified a biological basis for psychopathy,''
Damasio said. The two young people just studied, he emphasized,
were not purposeful in their bad behavior. They tended to bumble
along and mostly harm themselves, he said, whereas true psychopaths
are highly purposeful in their deeds.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. William Hurlbut, a bioethicist at Stanford University, said
it was likely that there were many recipes for making bad human
beings. Empathy and the lack of empathy probably have many sources,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, some experts say, the new findings are likely to fuel
efforts by criminal lawyers mounting biological defenses for bad
behavior.
</P>
<P>
   But others say these efforts won't wash. Except in the case of
the criminally insane, biological explanations for behavior cannot
prove cause and effect, said Robert Weisberg, a professor at
Stanford University School of Law. But Weisberg said biological
arguments might find their way into courtrooms in the penalty phase
of a trial. Lawyers throw out everything they can think of to get a
more lenient sentence, he said. This is just one more thing to
throw into the pot.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
