A0955 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-SYPHILIS-PARENTS-COX     10-18 0347
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SYPHILIS-PARENTS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Let kids set the tone for sexual discussions
 &HT;    (EDS: Moving to (a) General news and (L) Lifestyle categories.
Runs with SYPHILIS-ROCKDALE, SYPHILIS-FRONTLINE and
SYPHILIS-RESIDENTS.)
 &HT;    By Diane Lore
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The Big Talk doesn't cut it when parents are trying to
discuss their sexual values with teens, according to Sarah Brown,
director of the National Campaign to Prevent Teen Pregnancy.
</P>
<P>
   As PBS prepares to air ``The Lost Children of Rockdale County,''
a Frontline documentary about a cluster of teen syphilis cases,
Brown urges parents to look for opportunities to have an ongoing
dialogue with teens about tough subjects.
</P>
<P>
   A television show or a magazine article can open the door to
such conversations, said Brown, mother of three teenage daughters.
But when dealing with sex, parents need to be guided by their
children's interest level _ and most importantly, such moments are
not a time for parents to instantly climb their values soap box,
she said. Instead, they should let the child start the
conversation.
</P>
<P>
   Other tips for setting the stage for good communication include
giving your teen a purpose in the family. Chores are not evil, but
help a child develop self-esteem. Don't assume anything from your
child's body language _ just because they appear distracted,
doesn't mean they're not listening. And finally, supervise your
teenagers, giving them clear boundaries for behavior.
</P>
<P>
   Parents can turn to several resources for more tips, including:
</P>
<P>
   _ Families First, a private, nonprofit social service agency ,
at 404-853-2800, or www.familiesfirst.org.
</P>
<P>
   _ The National Parenting Center, ParenTalk Web site for
adolescents at www.tnpc.com/parentalk/adoles.html
</P>
<P>
   _ The Underground Guide to Teen Sexuality: An Essential Handbook
for Today's Teens &AMP; Parents ($14.94 Fairview Press) by Michael J.
Basso.
</P>
<P>
   Diane Lore writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution, Atlanta,
Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
