<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-18 20:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0959 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-GLENNIE-PROFILE-TEX     10-18 1025
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLENNIE-PROFILE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EVELYN GLENNIE: A FEEL FOR THE BEAT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
By TIM MADIGAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ To a city still healing from the church
shootings and a human spirit gone bad, comes a person whose life
and art happily occupy the opposite end of that spectrum.
</P>
<P>
   Her name is Evelyn Glennie, the first and only full-time solo
percussionist in the history of classical music, a 33-year-old
musician who in 15 years has revolutionized her craft.
</P>
<P>
   She headlines performances with the world's finest orchestras
and conductors, but is equally comfortable playing with
international pop stars. Universally fawning critics have variously
praised her as a ``musical genius'' and a ``wild woman.''
</P>
<P>
   Her favorite instrument is the traditional snare drum, but in
concert and on records she has played a starter's pistol, water
tank, exhaust pipes, flower pots and kitchen utensils.
</P>
<P>
   And then this _ a fact irrelevant to her, but amazing to her
listeners: Since the age of 12, the world's most famous
percussionist has been profoundly deaf.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday night at the Bass Performance Hall, Glennie performs
again with an a capella group, The King's Singers. As in all her
appearances, the Scottish redhead will be barefoot, for that is the
means by which she hears her music, vibrations absorbed by her
body.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview at Bass Hall Monday morning, Glennie fields
questions about her impairment politely but with a hint of
exasperation. She refers her questioner to an essay on a Glennie
website that answers all the pertinent questions.
</P>
<P>
   Her web page indeed says that the essay is ``designed to set the
record straight and allow people to enjoy the experience of being
entertained by one of the world's great musicians, rather than some
freak or miracle of nature.''
</P>
<P>
   As such, her promotional literature rarely mentions her
deafness, adhering instead to the litany of her 12 records, a
Grammy award, a bestselling book ``Good Vibrations'' and growing
worldwide celebrity.
</P>
<P>
   But any discussion of her art must inevitably return to her
childhood, during which Glennie tended lambs on her family's farm.
Neither parent was musical, and it was at her own initiative that
Glennie began taking piano lessons when she was 8. It was about the
same time that her hearing began to deteriorate for reasons never
fully understood.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was very gradual over four years or so,'' Glennie says.
``As an 8-year-old kid you somehow adapt. You don't have the
vocabulary to understand particularly what's going on. You don't
even know what the word deaf means.
</P>
<P>
   ``If something like this happened in my teenage years or even in
my 20s it would have been a very different story. But as a kid, you
are so adaptable. I think it was worse for those around me. They
were conditioned and they did know about the word, `deafness', and
they said, `Oh my God.' It was a scary experience for them.''
</P>
<P>
   Glennie, on the other hand, learned to listen in other ways. As
a 12-year-old, she was intrigued by percussion instruments in the
school orchestra so she insisted on pursuing that course. From
early on, her ambition went further than just learning how to play.
She began to formulate the notion of becoming a solo percussionist,
unheard of at the time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't have the same enthusiasm in an orchestra,'' she said.
``I needed an audience. I needed to play, like the violins or the
piano players. I don't know why. I think that if I start analyzing
it, it will all kind of crumble. It's just one of those things I
can't explain.''
</P>
<P>
   Glennie speaks today of her teenage years as frustrating times
when her musical ideas and ambition exceeded her ability.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I had absolutely no doubt in my mind that this would
work,'' she says, ``not because of me as a player, but just
something inside that I just knew this was going to be what I would
do.''
</P>
<P>
   Three years at the Royal Academy of Music was followed by a
Grammy award at age 21. Her performances, with Glennie racing from
instrument to instrument to instrument in a montage of varying
musical hues, left international audiences slack-jawed.
</P>
<P>
   ``One had to pause in sheer wonder at what she has
accomplished,'' said The New York Times. ``She is quite simply a
phenomenon as a performer.''
</P>
<P>
   More than anyone before her, ``Evelyn now shows you that
percussion is more than drums and more than just being able to keep
time,'' Leonard Slatkin, music director of the National Symphony
Orchestra said in a television interview. ``It's a whole world of
color and vitality and energy and subtlety that perhaps people
didn't know about before.''
</P>
<P>
   On Monday at the Bass Performance Hall, hundreds of local
students filed in to listen as Glennie whispered on the snare drum,
then hammered out thunder. She did the same on a set of bongos,
then on paddle drums, the snippets of her performance interspersed
with light-hearted lecture.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, she had been introduced to the youngsters as ``the
finest percussionist in the world. She does all of these things
through the vibrations in her feet, because she is deaf.''
</P>
<P>
   The faces of some students registered surprise. Then Glennie
appeared, dressed in black jeans, and a black blouse, and barefoot.
The novelty was quickly forgotten. Glennie is not a deaf performer,
but as she says, ``a sound creator ... to make those sounds into
some sort of emotional experience for people.''
</P>
<P>
   Toward the end of the 45-minute session, the young audience was
mesmerized by Glennie's haunting performance of ``Danny Boy'' on
the marimba.
</P>
<P>
   ``You participated in that piece, because I would have
interpreted it very differently if you were moving, or decided to
have your lunch early,'' Glennie told the students. ``In fact you
gave me a canvas to work with. You really, truly helped me
experience the piece because you experienced it yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   At the end, she fielded a half-dozen questions about her
instruments and her music. Glennie's deafness never came up.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
