u w BC-SPEND-CONGRESS-ART-NY     10-18 0793
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPEND-CONGRESS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON AND REPUBLICANS TO MEET ON BUDGET DIFFERENCES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ill., Texas)  (ART ADV:  Photo  is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By DAVID E. ROSENBAUM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton and Congress moved closer to a
showdown over the federal budget on Monday as the president vetoed
a foreign aid bill and then invited congressional leaders to a
meeting at the White House on Tuesday to discuss their differences.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are going to have to make tough choices, and we are going
to have to make them together,'' Clinton told reporters at the
White House.
</P>
<P>
   He sounded less confrontational than last week at his news
conference after the Senate's rejection of the nuclear test-ban
treaty.
</P>
<P>
   At the Capitol, Republican leaders accepted the president's
invitation. They emphasized, however, that they were not going to
participate in a ``budget summit'' as they had in the past, and
insisted that they deserved credit for persuading Clinton to
negotiate a budget that did not dip into Social Security reserves.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president agrees with us that we ought not to touch Social
Security,'' said Rep. Dick Armey of Texas, the House majority
leader. ``That's music to my ears.''
</P>
<P>
   The rather conciliatory tone on both sides Monday masked the
breadth of the differences between Clinton and Congress in terms of
policy and politics. The outlook is for weeks more of sparring and
jockeying before an agreement is reached.
</P>
<P>
   Since neither Clinton nor Congress is prepared to make the
spending cuts necessary to meet the limits set in the 1997 Balanced
Budget Act, they must take one of three courses to resolve their
differences:
</P>
<P>
   --They can increase taxes. Clinton has proposed an increase in
the cigarette tax, for instance, but the Republicans in Congress
have vowed not to raise taxes.
</P>
<P>
   --They can dip into money raised in Social Security taxes that
is not needed this year for benefits. This has been done every year
for generations. But to illustrate their commitment to Social
Security, Republican leaders have pledged not to take this course,
and Clinton has agreed.
</P>
<P>
   --They can resort to gimmicks. Already, the Republicans have
taken steps like declaring the 2000 census and other programs
emergencies so they do not count against budget ceilings, pushing
billions of dollars of spending into the next fiscal year,
including the postponement of one payday for the military, and
ordering the Congressional Budget Office to adopt a different
method of projecting spending that will result in a lower total.
</P>
<P>
   The best bet is that the recourse will be more gimmicks.
Gimmicks can meet the problem of spending too much money, but they
cannot resolve the differences over policy. For example, Clinton
intends to veto the spending bill for the Departments of Labor,
Education and Health and Human Services in part because it does not
adopt the administration's plan for reducing class size in the
nation's schools and paying for more teachers.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton plans to veto the bill for the Interior Department
because it includes Republican measures favorable to the oil,
timber and cattle industries that he considers harmful to the
environment.
</P>
<P>
   The foreign aid bill was the second spending measure Clinton
vetoed this year. Last month, he vetoed the appropriations bill for
the District of Columbia. Lawmakers expect to send a slightly
revised district bill this week.
</P>
<P>
   In the veto message he sent to Congress Monday morning, Clinton
said the foreign aid measure was ``another sign of a new
isolationism that would have America bury its head in the sand at
the height of our power and prosperity.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton objected to the failure of the bill to provide money he
had sought for the Middle East peace accord negotiated last year at
Wye River, Md.
</P>
<P>
   Speaker J. Dennis Hastert of Illinois accused the president of
wanting to ``raid the Social Security trust fund to pay for more
foreign aid.''
</P>
<P>
   Of the 13 spending bills to finance the various departments and
agencies in the fiscal year that began Oct. 1, five have been
signed into law, and three are likely to be signed this week. But
the White House says that Clinton will probably veto the bill for
the Departments of Commerce, State and Justice in addition to those
for Labor and Interior and the District of Columbia.
</P>
<P>
   Since Oct. 1, government offices have stayed open under a
temporary spending measure that expires on Thursday. The president
and Republican leaders said Monday that they would agree to another
stopgap measure so they would have more time to work out their
differences. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
