<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-18 20:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0980 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BBN-BRAVES19-COX     10-18 0878
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Now, pressure's on Braves
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Considering what the Braves have _ and have not _
accomplished this decade, they might have felt less pressure this
season than any other.
</P>
<P>
   But on the longest Sunday afternoon in playoff history, it all
changed.
</P>
<P>
   An epic, 15-inning loss to the New York Mets sent the Braves
home contemplating an offense gone stagnant, a rotation with little
room for error, a bullpen looking strangely vulnerable and an
opponent still very much alive.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves still hold a 3-2 lead in the National League
Championship Series, which resumes tonight at Turner Field. But
it's a different series now. This NLCS just got interesting.
</P>
<P>
   The tide turned Saturday night with John Olerud's chopper off
Ozzie Guillen's glove, giving the Mets their first victory of the
series. By the time Robin Ventura hit the grand-slam-that-wasn't in
the bottom of the 15th on Sunday, the Mets had left New York in
bedlam and the South in shock.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets don't have much to lose at this point, having been all
but finished three different times this season.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves have so much to lose. If they don't get their offense
going and win either tonight or Wednesday night in a potential Game
7, they would become only the third team in professional sports
history _ and the first in Major League Baseball _ to blow a 3-0
lead in a best-of-seven series. They would do it in the final year
of the decade they still have a chance to claim as their own. They
would fall a giant step short of the World Series for the third
year in a row to finish the 1990s with one World Series title in
four trips.
</P>
<P>
   So where does all of that leave the Braves?
</P>
<P>
   They were last seen around 10 p.m. Sunday in a quiet visitors'
clubhouse at Shea Stadium. Greg Maddux, one of the least outspoken
but most respected players in their clubhouse, had nodded that,
yes, Sunday's loss was the most heartbreaking he ever had endured.
</P>
<P>
   But he also said of winning the NLCS: ``You don't care when or
how, you just want to do it. We're still breathing.''
</P>
<P>
   And he could break into an easy smile as he said, ``It's a good
thing we won the first three games.''
</P>
<P>
   Maddux spent 10 to 15 minutes in front of his locker quietly
talking to wave after wave of reporters. After that, he walked over
to 22-year-old pitcher Kevin McGlinchy, who lost in a heap of mud
and walks in Game 5 Sunday, and gave him a pat on the back.
</P>
<P>
   For all the killer instinct the Braves have displayed over the
past several weeks, including using Kevin Millwood to shut the door
on the Astros in Game 3 of the Division Series and John Smoltz to
close out Game 2 of the NLCS against the Mets, they had a glaring
lack of it in Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The game wound down with McGlinchy a sitting duck in the pouring
rain as Ventura came up to bat in the 15th. Millwood and Tom
Glavine were not an option, manager Bobby Cox said, because he
didn't want to take a chance on either one getting hurt in the poor
conditions and he didn't want to disrupt the rotation for the final
two games of the series, if both are necessary.
</P>
<P>
   That reasoning might have had some Braves quietly frustrated.
But it also might have the opposite effect. That Cox felt secure
enough to look beyond the kind of loss that could rip a team apart
might give the Braves some reason to feel at ease in the greatest
pressure this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``You just have to have a short memory,'' infielder Keith
Lockhart said. ``You can't dwell on it.'' Lockhart would like to
forget getting thrown out at the plate in the 13th and then having
his run-scoring triple in the top of the 15th wasted in the Mets'
two-run rally in the bottom of the inning.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves didn't work out Monday. Cox gave the team the day off
to spend with their families. Only Millwood, tonight's starter,
came to the ballpark, to meet with the media. There, he explained
that having Monday to themselves could help the Braves put Sunday
behind them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think if (Games 5 and 6) were back-to-back it would have an
effect,'' Millwood said. ``But I think with us having today off and
being able to go home and get the game out of our head a little
bit, I don't think it will be that big of an effect tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   The Braves would prefer to focus on a change of scenery and the
comforts of Turner Field, where they have won 13 of their past 14
games against the Mets. And focus on having their best pitcher this
season and one of their best pitchers in the postseason scheduled
for Games 6 and 7.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just need one more win,'' shortstop Walt Weiss said.
``We'll take our chances with Millwood on the mound.''
</P>
<P>
   Millwood last saw his teammates on the team's charter flight on
Sunday night. It was quiet, as expected, but Millwood said that
reaction was normal.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the same old, same old,'' he said. ``If we had lost the
game on getaway day (during the regular season), it's pretty much
the same thing. Nobody is too down; nobody is too up. I think
everybody is just preparing for tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   Carroll Rogers writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
