A0982 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BBN-METS-MANIA-COX     10-18 0525
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-MANIA-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mets mania grips Big Apple
 &HT;    By Bob Dart
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Ya gotta believe that this place was nuts about the
Mets on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Their team's amazing 15-inning win over the Atlanta Braves
Sunday evening gave New Yorkers at least one more day for goading
and hoping, and they took advantage of the opportunity. ``Tomahawk
chop that, Atlanta,'' gloated The New York Daily News. ``They
cannot be killed,'' declared The New York Post.
</P>
<P>
   On the day after the longest playoff game ever, Mets fans
marveled at the pluck and luck of their team and proclaimed that
the win was yet another miracle. They see destiny as on their side
after the second dramatic win in a row.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even Yankee fans were happy about it,'' said Don Murphy, the
bartender at Mustang Sally's, a 7th Avenue sports bar. ``What can
you say? These guys won't quit.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, we've got a good chance,'' said Mike Telfer, a Mets fan
working security at Madison Square Garden. ``That's the reason
they're called amazing.''
</P>
<P>
   There was special delight in beating the Southern team that has
dominated the league for a decade.
</P>
<P>
   ``I definitely don't like the Atlanta Braves,'' said Harry
Appel, another guard at the Garden. ``They're a lot like the
Yankees with their rich owner. They're just a team with a lot of
money that thinks you can buy wins.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the Braves still lead three games to two in the
best-of-seven series to determine the National League champion.
</P>
<P>
   But with the Yankees leading the Boston Red Sox in the American
League Championship Series, this whole town is in a tizzy over the
prospect of the first Subway Series in the last 43 years. Some fans
have even taken it as an omen that the city's underground rail
system will likely record a 30-year low in felonies this year, the
fewest since 1969, the year of the original Amazin' Mets.
</P>
<P>
   ``The town must be excited,'' said Jim Root, who manages a
sports memorabilia store near Pennsylvania Station. ``Not many
people showed up for the Rangers game last night. They sat in bars
holding their hockey tickets and watching the baseball games.''
</P>
<P>
   For the first season in quite a while, Root said, he's selling
as many Mets caps and jerseys as Yankee gear.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm hoping for a Subway Series,'' he said. ``That way the city
could just schedule the ticker tape parade ahead of time because
one of our teams would definitely win it all.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope to God there is a Subway Series,'' echoed Mike Booth, a
Yankees fan sitting in Cafe 31, a sports bar on 31st Street.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there's a good chance,'' said Kevin Roundtree, who was
sitting on a nearby stool wearing an orange Mets jersey, ``although
we'll be playing with two pitchers going on three days' rest.''
</P>
<P>
   Many fans were still reliving the previous night's excitement.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was crazy. Nuts. The best game I ever saw in my life,''
said Rich Morrison, who watched at Mustang Sally's. ``I can't wait
till tomorrow night.''
</P>
<P>
   Bob Dart writes for Cox News Service.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
