A0983 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-MCCAIN-MOLINARI-NYT &LR;      10-18 0754
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCAIN-MOLINARI-NYT </SLUG>
  
 McCAIN WINS ENDORSEMENT OF INFLUENTIAL NEW YORK REPUBLICAN  
(th) 
 By DAVID M. HERSZENHORN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In an abrupt turnabout, Staten Island Borough
President Guy Molinari endorsed Sen. John McCain of Arizona for
president on Monday, breaking ranks with Mayor Rudolph Giuliani,
Gov. George Pataki and a host of other New York Republicans who
have lined up behind Gov. George W. Bush of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   The switch by Molinari, who had been an early supporter of Bush,
reflected his anger at Pataki over a recent series of snubs and
over the controlling role the governor has taken in the Bush
campaign in New York state. And it immediately created an awkward
situation for Giuliani, who remains a close friend of McCain even
after endorsing Bush.
</P>
<P>
   In accepting Molinari's endorsement, McCain, a leading proponent
of campaign finance reform, said he believed that Giuliani had
endorsed Bush to help the mayor raise money for his prospective
campaign for U.S. Senate next year. Giuliani later rejected that
assertion, saying he was impressed by Bush's executive experience.
</P>
<P>
   Just 18 days ago, Molinari stood next to Giuliani in the Blue
Room at City Hall as the mayor endorsed Bush in a telephone call to
Texas that was broadcast over a loudspeaker for reporters. The
three men joked and laughed as Giuliani proclaimed unanimous New
York support for Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have with me Borough President Guy Molinari of Staten
Island, who is an old friend of President Bush and of Governor
Bush,'' the mayor said then. ``And he and I and Republicans all
throughout the city of New York and the state of New York are
united in our support of Governor Bush for president.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush replied, jokingly: ``You said Guy Molinari is my old
friend. He is not that old.''
</P>
<P>
   But Monday, the white-haired Molinari stood next to the
white-haired McCain at the Vietnam veterans' memorial in lower
Manhattan and said that after a month of soul-searching about the
impending presidential race, he had decided to switch camps and had
agreed to serve as chairman of the McCain campaign in New York
state.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could have continued to support Governor Bush, who of course
is the present front-runner,'' Molinari said. ``After all, he has
amassed far more financial resources than any other candidate. But
sometimes, sometimes, you just have to stand up and say, `Despite
all the odds, my overwhelming respect for a candidate like John
McCain demands that I rise to endorse him.'''
</P>
<P>
   But Republican officials have pointed to a number of recent
incidents that have widened a rift between Molinari and Pataki. In
the spring, Molinari accused Pataki of trying to hinder Giuliani's
efforts to raise money for a Senate bid. The governor has also
ignored Molinari's requests that he pardon a former police
lieutenant in prison for carrying out illegal raids.
</P>
<P>
   And Mmlinari has bristled at reports that Pataki wants Charles
A. Gargano, chairman of Empire State Development Corp., to be
chairman of the Bush campaign in New York. Molinari repeated his
criticism Monday, saying Gargano worked against Bush's father in
the 1988 presidential race.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani, at his daily news conference, said Molinari was wrong
about Pataki. ``I think the reason that he's doing it is wrong,''
the mayor said of the McCain endorsement. ``I think Governor Pataki
is doing a good job in running not only the state but running the
party. I think he has organized it correctly behind the candidate
who has the best chance to win the presidency.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain said he understood the mayor's decision to support the
Republican front-runner. ``A few weeks ago he and I went to lunch
and I urged the mayor to do whatever is necessary so that we could
have him in the United States Senate,'' McCain said. ``The best
way, probably, for him to get the United States Senate would be to
take the present course that he is on.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked why endorsing Bush would help the mayor's Senate chances,
McCain, whose campaign finance reform bill is being debated in the
U.S. Senate this week, replied simply, ``Money.'' Asked what he
meant, McCain repeated, ``Money.''
</P>
<P>
   At a campaign stop in Scottsdale, Ariz., on Monday, Bush said:
``Guy's a good _ I've known him for a long time. He's a good man.
And we just disagree. I think I ought to be the party's nominee and
he thinks the senator from Arizona ought to be the party's nominee.
Should I win the nomination, I hope he'll help me in the general
election.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
