<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SBC-INTERNET-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SBC TO UPGRADE ACCESS TO INTERNET
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
By ANDREA AHLES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SBC Communications unveiled a $6 billion initiative to provide
high-speed Internet access to about 80 percent of its customers in
the next three years, the company said on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The San Antonio-based company, which is the nation's largest
local phone provider, intends to sell voice, data and video
services over its upgraded infrastructure in the 13 states it
currently serves. The initiative is expected to reduce operating
expenses and generate $3.5 billion in new revenues by 2004, SBC
said.
</P>
<P>
   SBC's network upgrade plans are the latest development in the
ongoing battle between telecommunications and cable companies for
high-speed Internet customers.
</P>
<P>
   Cable companies offer access through cable modems while
telephone companies can provide access via digital subscriber
lines, or DSL.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said SBC had been expected to make some type of
announcement about its broadband plans after the completion of its
merger with Ameritech, taking advantage of the new markets and 60
million access lines the merger gave SBC. When the three-year
deployment is complete, SBC will be able to offer high-speed
Internet service to 77 million Americans.
</P>
<P>
   ``As of today, our broadband capabilities are going to take a
quantum leap,'' said Edward E. Whitacre Jr., SBC's chairman and
chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   SBC has upgraded 58 central offices in the Fort Worth-Dallas
area and will have all 63 offices equipped for DSL by the end of
the year, said Chris Rice, regional vice president of network
engineering for Southwestern Bell, an SBC subsidiary.
</P>
<P>
   With the new initiative _ called Project Pronto _ DSL service
will be available to the majority of Southwestern Bell customers in
Tarrant and Dallas counties, the company said.
</P>
<P>
   SBC also expects to hire several hundred new employees in Fort
Worth-Dallas to help build and install the service for customers,
Rice said.
</P>
<P>
   Although analysts said the push to upgrade its network is a key
growth opportunity for SBC, the market did not respond as favorably
to the announcement. SBC stock was down 25 cents on Monday, closing
at $48.4375.
</P>
<P>
   Investors might be concerned about the $6 billion expenditure,
which will affect SBC's revenues for the next three years, analysts
said.
</P>
<P>
   But the program is expected to increase SBC's earnings about 14
to 15 percent from 2000 to 2001, said Omar Melo, an associate
analyst at Banc of America Securities.
</P>
<P>
   Several analysts said the initiative nicely positions SBC to
take advantage of the growing high-speed market and puts it ahead
of its competitors.
</P>
<P>
   The company that is first to the market often is the one that
has the most success with the new product, said Robert Wilkes, a
telecommunications analyst at Brown Brothers Harriman.
</P>
<P>
   ``To some extent, you are having a race between the phone
companies and the cable companies to have high-speed services
available to their customer bases,'' Wilkes said.
</P>
<P>
   The number of DSL users is expected to grow from 250,000 in 1999
to 2.7 million in 2002, according to the Yankee Group, a market
research firm in Boston. Cable modem users are also expected to
grow from 1 million this year to 4.3 million in 2002, the Yankee
Group said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We envision a time when the computer Web-based experience and
the traditional telephone experience come together,'' said James D.
Gallemore, SBC executive vice president of strategic marketing and
planning. ``We intend to create an easy-to-use tool that people can
use to surf the media-rich Net, complete with video, and manage and
use all of their communications.''
</P>
<P>
   With the initiative, SBC said it will guarantee customers an
Internet connection of 1.5 megabits per second, about 50 times
faster than a standard 28.8 kilobyte-per-second dial-up modem.
</P>
<P>
   SBC currently guarantees a connection of only 384 kilobytes per
second, and the service costs about $40 a month.
</P>
<P>
   The company also announced on Monday that it would provide DSL
access to active investors on E-Trade, an online investing site.
</P>
<P>
   In a separate announcement, SBC will provide DSL service to
about 15,000 IBM telecommuting employees in select areas.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
