<SLUG> BC-FBN-NOTES19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Quarterbacks suddenly an endangered species
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NFL quarterbacks had another tough Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Miami's Dan Marino, who became the first player to surpass
60,000 passing yards, is doubtful for Sunday's game against
Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   Marino injured his right, throwing shoulder in practice last
week and threw only three passes in the Dolphins' 31-30 victory at
New England. He was replaced by Damon Huard, who rallied the
Dolphins from a nine-point deficit in the final 13 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Marino had an MRI exam on his shoulder Monday, and doctors
discovered a bone spur in his lower neck. They advised him not to
practice until Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll just see what kind of strength Dan has throwing the
ball,'' Dolphins coach Jimmy Johnson said. ``If he isn't 100
percent, Huard will start. Dan's going to want to play even if he
has no arm. That doesn't mean he's the right one to win the game
with. I want the guy that's going to win the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Arizona's Jake Plummer is expected to miss four to six weeks
after suffering a broken ring finger on his right hand during a
24-10 loss to the Washington Redskins.
</P>
<P>
   Plummer, who never has missed a start in his three-year NFL
career, was injured when the finger got stuck in the face mask of
Redskins linebacker Shawn Bates on a sack.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals are off this week and host New England on Oct. 31.
</P>
<P>
   New York Jets coach Bill Parcells said Rick Mirer, benched
before his team's 16-13 loss to Indianapolis, will start against
the Raiders on Sunday. Backup Ray Lucas suffered a sprained left
ankle on the final play of his first NFL start and will miss three
to four weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Detroit quarterback Charlie Batch is expected to play against
Carolina on Sunday after his right arm was bruised.
</P>
<P>
   Banged-up millionaires
</P>
<P>
   Quarterbacks aren't the only players hurting. Buffalo Bills
receiver Eric Moulds will miss three to four weeks with a strained
hamstring. Minnesota running back Robert Smith could be sidelined
as long as six weeks with a hernia.
</P>
<P>
   Also, wide receivers Herman Moore (leg) of Detroit, Darnay Scott
(bruised ribs) of Cincinnati and Curtis Conway (sprained ankle) of
Chicago are doubtful this week.
</P>
<P>
   Bengals running back Corey Dillon is questionable with a
sprained ankle.
</P>
<P>
   George is back
</P>
<P>
   Vikings quarterback Jeff George will start Sunday's game against
San Francisco. George replaced struggling starter Randall
Cunningham for the second half of Minnesota's 25-23 loss at
Detroit. The loss dropped the Vikings to 2-4.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are all must-wins from here on out,'' George said. ``I
think you have to go into each game saying, `This is a must-win.'
If we want to accomplish the goals that we set out to accomplish,
every week is a must-win.''
</P>
<P>
   George rallied the Vikings from a 19-0 halftime deficit,
completing 10 of 12 passes for 214 yards and two touchdowns. He
threw both scores in a six-minute span during the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not quick-change artists, and I'm not either,'' Vikings
coach Dennis Green said. ``But we clearly weren't playing at a
level that is acceptable.''
</P>
<P>
   All is not well
</P>
<P>
   Vikings receiver Randy Moss, who finished with 10 catches for
125 yards and a touchdown, still was venting after the loss. After
running on three consecutive plays, Minnesota took a 23-22 lead on
Gary Anderson's 26-yard field goal with 1:40 left. It wasn't
enough, and Moss didn't like the conservative play-calling.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why stop?'' Moss said. ``I mean, if it's working.... It's not
my call. If I had a choice, I probably would have took the shot (at
the end zone). I mean, you got two All-Pros with a Jake Reed
healthy. Something was bound to happen good. The field goal put us
up, but I'm not big on the field goals. If you can get a touchdown,
get a touchdown.''
</P>
<P>
   Delaying a decision
</P>
<P>
   Denver coach Mike Shanahan said he won't decide until Wednesday
whether rookie Olandis Gary of Georgia or Derek Loville will start
at running back. Gary replaced the injured Loville in a 31-10
victory over Green Bay and rushed for 124 yards on 37 carries.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even when we had Terrell (Davis), we shuffled (running
backs),'' Shanahan said. ``You don't want to overwork a back. You
want to keep them fresh. When you give a guy 37 carries, that's a
lot of work.''
</P>
<P>
   Shanahan also declined to name second-year pro Brian Griese his
starting quarterback. Griese, who was benched after the team's 0-4
start, threw for 363 yards and two scores against the Packers. He
led Denver to its second victory in a row after replacing Bubby
Brister, out with a strained oblique muscle.
</P>
<P>
   Extra points
</P>
<P>
   Washington cornerback Champ Bailey, a rookie from Georgia,
became the youngest player in NFL history to return an interception
for a touchdown and to pick off three passes in one game. . . . New
Orleans coach Mike Ditka probably will draw a hefty fine from the
NFL for making an obscene gesture toward fans in a 24-21 loss to
Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Schlabach writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
