u i BC-INDONESIA-LEADER-BOS &LR;      10-18 1324
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDONESIA-LEADER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KEY TEST IN INDONESIA'S TRANSITION TO DEMOCRACY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By INDIRA A.R. LAKSHMANAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JAKARTA _ The world's fourth-most-populous nation chooses a new
president Wednesday, and for the first time since Indonesia gained
independence in 1945, no one knows in advance who the winner will
be.
</P>
<P>
   Indonesia is struggling to form a post-autocratic government
against an extraordinary backdrop of wheeling and dealing, shifting
alliances, and a total lack of party discipline _ a
rough-and-tumble process that is messy and imperfect but
undoubtedly more democratic than anything that came before.
</P>
<P>
   The members of parliament who will make the choice could produce
a result that reflects the public will, or one that tilts
dangerously against it. And until it's over and the public decides
whether it likes the result, Indonesia's transition to democracy
hangs in the balance.
</P>
<P>
   The race, for once, is a real contest _ a choice between a
candidate closely linked to the past and a main rival with a potent
political legacy who still symbolizes a break from the recent
regime. Polls show that Megawati Sukarnoputri, a daughter of the
country's founding president, commands 10 times the popular backing
of the 5 percent who support incumbent President B.J. Habibie. But
the people won't get to cast their votes directly.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the 700-member People's Consultative Assembly _ chosen
four months ago in Indonesia's first democratic elections in 44
years _ will select the next head of state. And with just one day
to go, the scene is more chaotic than the 1968 Democratic
convention in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   Parties are divided, alliances have collapsed, loyalty is for
sale, last-minute candidates have emerged, double-crossing is
rampant, the rules for selecting a winner are undecided, and by
Wednesday, anything could change.
</P>
<P>
   Whoever wins the job will face several enormous tasks. Not only
must the new president reform and kick-start an economy that
collapsed under the weight of corruption and bad debt, he or she
also will have to address public demands to bring former President
Suharto and his associates to account and establish the rule of law
_ all while appeasing a military accustomed to wielding ultimate
authority. It is not at all clear that any of the declared
candidates is up to the task.
</P>
<P>
   Whoever wins is likely to find the presidency far less powerful
than it used to be. The new parliament, armed with the right to
elect the nation's leader, is showing an unprecedented
assertiveness that has come to a head in debate over Habibie's
so-called ``accountability speech'' last Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The legally required address, a sort of state-of-the-union
report, was traditionally approved in a pro forma fashion by the
rubber-stamp parliament. But this time, lawmakers engaged in raging
debate all weekend, and could force Habibie to withdraw from the
race if they reject his report in the end.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this moment, every minute counts and everything is
changing,'' said Arief Budiman, professor of Indonesian studies at
the University of Melbourne. ``For now, we don't have a legitimate
government, because Habibie was never elected and everyone is
against him, more or less. . . . Habibie is part of the old regime
and a Suharto crony. He is only supported by people who want to
protect themselves from attack by the new civil society.''
</P>
<P>
   That may be the view of those who consider themselves reformers,
as a majority of the public apparently do, but their
representatives do not necessarily control the Assembly.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the beleaguered Habibie gave Indonesians something they
had never seen before _ a president literally begging lawmakers and
the public in a televised speech Sunday to ``open your hearts and
forgive the weaknesses I have shown.''
</P>
<P>
   Monday, Armed Forces chief General Wiranto, whom Habibie had
named as his running mate in a bid to secure the military's 38
votes in the Assembly, declined to enter the race unless ``the
people really need it,'' saying he must focus on insuring the
safety of the nation. That effectively freed military
representatives to support anyone, and weakens Habibie's chances.
But the tenacious Habibie vowed to ``continue the struggle until
the last minute. I don't want to say goodbye.''
</P>
<P>
   But many Indonesians are demanding that Habibie go. About 1,200
stockbrokers, lawyers, doctors, and other professionals rallied at
the Jakarta stock exchange Monday in the first major white-collar
protest to his 17-month tenure. More than 10,000 students and urban
poor took to the streets last Thursday to demand an end to his
rule, and 40,000 extra security personnel have been drafted to
maintain order in the capital. Clashes with riot police and
soldiers have left at least 200 people injured.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, about 2,000 Megawati supporters blocked a main traffic
circle, waving banners and dancing in a free-for-all that was more
carnival than protest. There were fire-eaters, a parade of buses,
and a chimpanzee dressed as Habibie. The mood was peaceful, but the
chanted slogan was ominous: ``Megawati or revolution.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Megawati won the most votes last June, taking 34
percent of the seats in the Assembly, by no means does she have the
race sewn up. Habibie's long-ruling Golkar party finished second
and controls 27 percent. In an alliance with conservative Muslim
parties, he could have the most votes.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Megawati's alliance with a reformist Muslim party
that finished third in June is in tatters after the ailing cleric
Abdurrahman Wahid declared himself a rival candidate. Smaller
Muslim parties have backed him, suggesting that religion could end
up a deciding factor in a country that has long divided religion
from state.
</P>
<P>
   There are also rampant allegations of vote-buying, with prices
quoted of between $250,000 and $500,000 for a single vote.
Independent political commentator Wimar Witoelar estimates that 30
to 50 percent of the 700 seats could be bought.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps even without bribery, party loyalty is a fiction. The
Megawati-Wahid coalition _ the largest in parliament _ has somehow
managed to lose the four key votes so far. In the race for
parliamentary speaker, the man it backed got only 58 votes, even
though the two parties control 185 seats.
</P>
<P>
   During a break at parliament, Kwik Kian Gie, deputy chairman of
Megawati's Indonesian Democratic Party of Struggle, acknowledged
that a secret ballot for president, ironically, could work against
democratic ideals by hiding from the public the votes cast by their
elected delegates.
</P>
<P>
   He also downplayed suggestions that Megawati might make a deal
to support a member of the ruling Golkar party or a military choice
for vice president in exchange for their backing for president.
</P>
<P>
   A deal for the Golkar party to support Megawati's choice for the
full assembly speaker collapsed two hours before the vote when
Megawati failed to appear for a meeting with Golkar chairman Akbar
Tandjung.
</P>
<P>
   Such overconfidence, or some say political naivete, has hobbled
Megawati. Many observers say she became arrogant after winning the
most votes last June, acting as if she had secured the presidency
already, and refusing to make deals with other parties. Still, she
is the single most popular candidate, and if she loses, the
``rakyat,'' or masses, have promised to revolt. Some military
leaders have said privately they will back her to ensure stability.
</P>
<P>
   Habibie's own party, meanwhile, is divided over whether to drop
him at the eleventh hour. ``It's an untenable situation to continue
to push for his nomination if his speech is rejected,'' Marzuki
Darusman, chairman of the Golkar party faction in parliament, said
in an interview. ``We're not foreclosing any possibility. We might
end up working with the majority party . . . We are in a position
of bargaining now.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
