<HEADER>
A0989 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w BC-STARR-SUCCESSOR-NYT &LR;      10-18 0697
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STARR-SUCCESSOR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW INDEPENDENT COUNSEL VOWS TO CONCLUDE INQUIRY OF PRESIDENT
</HEADLINE>
   (sw) 
 By DON VAN NATTA Jr.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Robert Ray, a career federal prosecutor, was sworn
in on Monday to replace the independent counsel, Kenneth Starr, and
he vowed to complete Starr's five-year-old, $47-million criminal
inquiry of President Clinton and Hillary Rodham Clinton in a
``prompt, responsible and cost-effective manner.''
</P>
<P>
   Appearing on the steps of the federal courthouse here after
taking the oath of office, Ray promised that the independent
counsel's office would be ``thorough and fair.'' He also saluted
Starr for his ``extraordinary service to the country at great
personal sacrifice over the past five years.''
</P>
<P>
   Ray succeeds Starr, who resigned on Monday after overseeing an
investigation that began in August 1994 with the Clintons'
Whitewater real estate deal and eventually led to Clinton's
impeachment by the House of Representatives over his affair with
Monica Lewinsky. Starr's tenure was marked by years of harsh
attacks by White House aides and supporters of the Clintons.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, those aides and supporters immediately extended those
attacks to Ray, calling him an ideologue unfit to conduct an
impartial inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   Even before Ray was sworn in, White House aides had begun
calling reporters to contend that Ray has a conflict of interest
because he had been hired as a federal prosecutor in early 1989 by
Rudolph Giuliani who was then U.S. attorney for the Southern
District of New York. Giuliani, now the mayor of New York City, is
considered the likely Republican candidate for the Senate seate in
New York, a seat likely to be contested on the Democratic side by
Hillary Rodham Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   James Carville, a Clinton confidant who declared ``war'' on
Starr in early 1998, accused Ray of being beholden to Giuliani even
though Ray actually began working for the the U.S. Attorney's
office in Manhattan in February 1989, several weeks after Giuliani
left office there..
</P>
<P>
   ``Ray got his first big break as a prosecutor from Rudy
Giuliani,'' Carville said on Monday. ``We question everything he
does _ every motive he has, every decision he makes, every word he
writes, everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Ray did not return telephone calls on Monday. He did not address
the allegations of the Clinton supporters after his swearing-in.
</P>
<P>
   Starr, in a resignation letter submitted to a three-member panel
of federal appellate judges on Monday, responded to some of his
critics by defending his work and the professionalism of his
office's career prosecutors. But he acknowledged that his
resignation had been prompted by the ``intense politicization'' of
his tenure. He said it would be best for someone else to lead the
independent counsel's office, which is still pursuing two
investigative matters, and to write a final report.
</P>
<P>
   ``To reduce the unfortunate personalization of the process, in
particular in the wake of the inherently divisive impeachment
proceedings, the wiser course, I believe, is for another individual
to head the investigation,'' Starr said.
</P>
<P>
   Ray inherits two investigative matters at the independent
counsel's office, lawyers say. Prosecutors are trying to determine
whether White House aides played any role in what a former White
House volunteer, Kathleen Willey, has said was an effort to
persuade her to deny that the president made a sexual advance to
her in the Oval Office.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecutors are also investigating the dismissals of White
House travel office employees in the early months of the Clinton
presidency to determine whether anyone involved in the matter
misled investigators about who had ordered the dismissals.
</P>
<P>
   Ray is a 39-year-old federal prosecutor who joined Starr's
office in April as senior litigation counsel. He worked on the
tax-evasion case against Webster L. Hubbell, a friend of the
Clintons and a former top Justice Department official.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers said Ray was instrumental in bringing the case to a
close. Hubbell pleaded guilty in June to a misdemeanor tax charge
and a felony charge of concealing legal work in a fradulent
Arkansas land deal.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
