<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-18 20:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0991 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-COMMENT-     10-18 1148
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-COMMENT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUNNING GAME WAS GROUND TO A HALT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ You will begin to hear whispers about
schemes now.
</P>
<P>
   It will begin Tuesday or Wednesday in the locker room of the New
England Patriots, as it has each year for the past half-dozen
around this time. To be honest, it began Sunday in some corners.
</P>
<P>
   You'll hear about inconsistent play-calling and predictability.
You will hear that the coaches aren't persistent enough with the
run. You'll hear offensive coordinator Ernie Zampese needs to be
more stubborn because you can't get anything going calling only 14
running plays, as the Patriots did in Sunday's disappointing,
last-second loss to the Miami Dolphins.
</P>
<P>
   You will hear many reasons to explain why the Patriots can't run
out for lunch, let alone run for a first down. Little of what you
hear whispered will involve the people most responsible for this
problem, because that is the age we live in.
</P>
<P>
   You will hear a lot of things said anonymously but little of
what you hear will center on the major reason the Patriots can't
run to the bathroom, let alone to the end zone. That reason has
nothing to do with schemes or coaches' decisions or stubborness or
emphasis or anything else but one thing. What it has to do with is
the five blocks of limestone standing at the line of scrimmage.
</P>
<P>
   ``The party line around here always has been that we've got to
run the ball, so you always say it, but at a certain point if you
always say it and then lead the league in pass attempts every year,
you have people within your own team wondering what we are,''
quarterback Drew Bledsoe admitted late last week, only days before
his team blew a 14-point lead to the Dolphins in large part because
it had to play like a team that was 14 points behind most of the
day.
</P>
<P>
   Why the Patriots did that was not because Zampese and Pete
Carroll don't understand the need to run. It is not because they
can't be stubborn because Carroll can be as stubborn as anyone.
Just ask Sam Gash and Willie Clay. No, they did what they did
Sunday _ which was throw the ball 36 times and run it just 14
despite having a 14-0 lead only minutes into the game _ because
their offensive line couldn't move the ball on the ground if they
put it in a Chevy Blazer.
</P>
<P>
   This is a familiar complaint. It has surfaced about this time of
year for a decade. It has been the Patriot coaches who have borne
the brunt of the blame for that failing, and it's time that stopped
before it gets a chance to start again because here are the facts.
</P>
<P>
   Since Bill Parcells first waddled into Foxborough and
transformed a loser into a winner, the Patriots have had two head
coaches, three offensive coordinators, three offensive line
coaches, and five running back coaches. They have had four
different backs serve as their leading rusher and will have a fifth
this season.
</P>
<P>
   While there have been an assortment of offensive linemen during
that time, since 1995 Bruce Armstrong, Todd Rucci, and Max Lane
have been starters most of the time. Since 1997, Zefross Moss has
been with them for nearly every snap. Until he left for free agency
in February, center Dave Wohlabaugh had been as well, although his
place now has been taken by rookie Damien Woody.
</P>
<P>
   Over that span the Patriots have averaged the following when
running the ball: 3.9 yards, 3.4 yards, 3.7 yards, 3.7 yards, and,
to date this year, 3.3 yards per carry. To quote the man who
started it all, Parcells himself, ``You are what you are,'' and
what these guys are are guys who can't run block.
</P>
<P>
   Some experts will tell you it's because most of them are too
lumbering to be able to pull or trap (with the exception of Rucci)
or because they lack the explosion to come off the ball and knock a
defense straight back. Others will tell you it's a mind-set they
don't possess because since Bledsoe arrived in 1993 so much of the
emphasis in New England has centered around protecting the
quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever it is, there has been one constant in this gridlock
since 1995: the faces of the interior linemen, who have found it
impossible to open a hole in a pair of old athletic socks, let
alone between a pair of defensive tackles.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong, Moss, Rucci, and Lane. The last three seasons,
whether it was Curtis Martin running or Robert Edwards running or
Terry Allen running, whether it was Larry Kennan calling the plays
or Zampese calling the plays, whether it was Paul Boudreau coaching
the offensive line or Fred Hoaglin coaching the offensive line or
Dante Scarnecchia coaching the offensive line, most of the five
blocks of limestone have been the same people and they have
produced a running game that has netted an average of around 1,460
yards a season.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996 (1,468) and 1997 (1,464) and 1998 (1,480) and as
projected for 1999 (1,536), it has been the same, so we can
conclude one of two things. One is that every head coach, offensive
coordinator, running back coach, line coach, and running back the
Patriots have had is an idiot incapable of understanding how to run
forward, or two, the men blocking can't perform this skill anywhere
near as well as they can pass block.
</P>
<P>
   The whisperers will try to convince you this week or next that
the former is true. The whisperers will be wrong.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots can't run because their line doesn't make holes
that stay open long enough for slender running backs like Allen to
fit through before they fill in like a collapsing sinkhole. It's as
simple as that.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly there are times when they are outmanned at the hole by
a defense that either guesses right or reads their formation.
Certainly there are times the bad guys make a play, as they are
paid to do, and life goes on. But you average about 3.4 yards a
carry long enough with the same blockers and it leads to an
inexorable conclusion.
</P>
<P>
   The numbers prove it and the faces prove it, which is why, when
Bledsoe was asked after Sunday's game, ``Do you feel like you're
getting into more of a throw-first-run-later approach?'' he
replied, ``What, that's different? We're a passing football team.
That's what we are. We do need to establish the run more than we
have but when, or if, that's going to happen I don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes he does.
</P>
<P>
   So do Zampese and Carroll.
</P>
<P>
   So do the Five Blocks of Limestone.
</P>
<P>
   It isn't going to happen.
</P>
<P>
   It's not any different than it was in 1997 or 1998. Not any
different than in 1993 or 1994 or 1995 or 1996 either.
</P>
<P>
   So the best thing they could do is admit it, throw 65 times a
game, and hope that teams become so petrified of that that one of
these Sundays they line up not with eight men in the box but with
eight men in the secondary.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots might not be able to run then either but at least
it would be a fair fight.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
