<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TAXBREAKS-HEALTHCARE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Proposal could backfire if `breaks' aren't significant
 &HT;    By Kevin Lamb
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The popular political strategy of using tax breaks
to help reduce the number of 44.3 million Americans without health
insurance could backfire if the breaks are not significant,
according to a National Coalition on Health Care report released
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The Lewin Group analyzed proposals in Congress and on the
presidential campaign trail, which are based on broadening the tax
exclusions that currently apply to money that employers spend on
employees' health insurance. It found no plan that would increase
the number of insured Americans by as much as 10 million.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal that has passed both houses of Congress would give
a 100 percent tax deduction on health-insurance costs for people
without access to employer-sponsored health plans.
</P>
<P>
   It would most help people who are paying for their own insurance
or who have incomes above $50,000, the report said. The coalition
said it would induce only 3.9 million currently uninsured people to
buy coverage, only about 200,000 of whom have annual incomes below
$15,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tax credits alone cannot solve the problem of the uninsured,
nor are they likely to contain the skyrocketing costs of health
care,'' said Dr. Henry E. Simmons, the coalition's president. ``If
Congress enacts tax credits absent other changes, we could end up
with even more people uninsured because of higher health-care
costs.''
</P>
<P>
   The coalition's recommendation would require employers to
convert their health-insurance expenditures to taxed wages, then
apply tax credits to individuals' purchases of their own coverage,
which would have a mandatory minimum benefits package.
</P>
<P>
   ``The net federal cost of such a plan, first proposed in the
early 1990s by the conservative Heritage Foundation ... would be
$55.3 billion (next year),'' the coalition said of the
paradoxically conservative approach to universal health coverage.
</P>
<P>
   Former presidents Ford, Carter and Bush are honorary co-chairmen
of the coalition, which comprises nearly 100 small businesses,
labor unions and consumer, physician, hospital and religious
groups.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Lamb writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
