<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-FINANCE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 (ATTN: Ariz., Wis.)  
 McCAIN OUTMANEUVERED IN VOTE ON CAMPAIGN FINANCE CHANGE  
(See also MCCAIN-MOLINARI, moved in `p' category) 
(th) 
 By ALISON MITCHELL    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Sen. John McCain tried to win a test vote on his
legislation to ban the large, unlimited donations to political
parties that have been proliferating over the past decade, but he
was outmaneuvered on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   In a confounding day in the Senate, McCain, the Arizona
Republican who is the lead sponsor of legislation to overhaul the
campaign finance system, made an unusual parliamentary proposal to
kill an amendment containing his own proposal to ban the donations,
known as soft money. He then urged his supporters to vote against
him as a way to send a signal that they support the soft money ban
and want it to stay alive.
</P>
<P>
   McCain characterized the strange maneuver as a way to
demonstrate how many senators support the effort to rein in the
influence of money on politics.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got at most 48 hours left on this legislation,'' he
said. ``We have not made a lot of progress. It's time we did, and I
believe that having the Senate on record on soft money is a very
defining vote.''
</P>
<P>
   But his effort to get senators on record was thwarted when not
just his supporters but also his opponents voted to keep the ban on
soft money alive, by a 92-1 vote. That made the vote meaningless.
</P>
<P>
   ``They threw the vote,'' complained Sen. Russell Feingold, the
Wisconsin Democrat who is McCain's co-sponsor. The opponents knew
they would have plenty of other opportunities to kill the bill.
</P>
<P>
   The gamesmanship was a sign of how slim the prospects are for
the Senate to follow the lead of the House and pass a bill this
year to overhaul the campaign finance law. The campaign finance
debate has simply degenerated into a procedural battle. Sen. Trent
Lott of Mississippi, the majority leader, is expected to pull the
legislation off the floor soon, perhaps as early as Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the Senate mustered a majority for comprehensive
legislation to overhaul the campaign finance law, but fell eight
votes short of the 60 needed to break a filibuster against the
bill. Although the House passed the comprehensive legislation in
September, McCain and Feingold scaled back their bill this year to
focus almost entirely on a ban on soft money.
</P>
<P>
   They dropped provisions that would have tightly regulated the
issue-advocacy commercials that are often thinly masked
advertisements attacking or supporting candidates.
</P>
<P>
   The two men said that by stripping down the bill they hoped to
win more supporters and then, through an amendment process on the
floor, build a bill that could gain the 60 votes needed to break a
filibuster.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-18-99 2058EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
