<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-18 21:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0998 &Cx1f; tad-z
b f BC-COMAIR-COX     10-18 0537
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMAIR-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Delta buys Comair for $1.8 billioni
 &HT;    By Timothy R. Gaffney
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CINCINNATI _ Delta Air Lines Inc. will buy Cincinnati-based
Comair Holdings Inc. in a $1.8 billion deal that unites the main
major and regional airlines serving Dayton, the companies announced
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta-based Delta will acquire Comair for $23.50 per common
share and operate the airline as a separate subsidiary, with its
headquarters remaining at Cincinnati-Northern Kentucky
International Airport. Delta already owned about 22 percent of
Comair's shares.
</P>
<P>
   No changes in Comair's services were announced. Dayton airport
spokesman John Sears said the acquisition is not expected to affect
Delta's or Comair's services.
</P>
<P>
   The change will not affect fares because they are mainly
influenced by market conditions, Pate said.
</P>
<P>
   Directors of both airlines unanimously approved the deal,
according to separate but nearly identical announcements by the
companies.
</P>
<P>
   Founded in 1977, Comair developed close ties with Delta in 1984
with a code-share marketing agreement through which Comair flies
customers from cities in the Midwest and Florida through both
Comair's and Delta's hubs in Cincinnati and Orlando.
</P>
<P>
   Leo F. Mullin, Delta president and chief executive, called
Comair ``a very successful regional airline with strong and
respected leadership and an outstanding record of financial and
operational performance.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the acquisition ``continues Delta's strategy to
strengthen its nationwide Delta Connection carrier network with an
emphasis on introducing regional jets.''
</P>
<P>
   Comair kicked off the regional jet movement 1993 as the first
airline to fly the 50-seat Canadair Regional Jet. Regional jets of
various makes and sizes are rapidly replacing turboprops throughout
the regional airline industry.
</P>
<P>
   Under terms of the agreement, a Delta subsidiary will make a
tender offer no later than Friday to purchase all outstanding
shares of common stock of Comair Holdings for $23.50 per share in
cash. Comair Holdings has outstanding 95.5 million shares of common
stock.
</P>
<P>
   Following the completion of the tender offer, which is subject
to customary conditions, the Delta subsidiary will merge into
Comair Holdings. When the merger becomes effective, each
outstanding share of Comair Holdings will be converted into the
right to receive $23.50 in cash. At that time, Comair Holdings and
Comair will become wholly owned subsidiaries of Delta.
</P>
<P>
   Separately, Delta reported third-quarter net income of $290
million, or $1.96 per diluted share, excluding gains from the sale
of investments and non-recurring charges. Net income was $327
million and $2.08 per share in the same period last year. Delta
said its operations were hurt by Hurricane Floyd, which forced
Delta to cancel more than 1,100 flights and reduced revenue by $20
million.
</P>
<P>
   Including gains from the sale of investments and non-recurring
charges, net income was $352 million and diluted earnings per share
were $2.38 for the quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Timothy R. Gaffney writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton,
Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
