u f BC-LUXURY-GOODS-ART-2TAK     10-18 1197
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LUXURY-GOODS-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SELECTIVE SHOPPING FOR PURVEYORS OF LUXURY GOODS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photos, NYT15 and NYT16, are being sent to NYT graphic
clients. Non-subscribers can purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By LESLIE KAUFMAN and CATHY HORYN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   That Calvin Klein Inc. is on the block should come as no
surprise. Many other fashion houses have been tempted by the
incredible prices that brand-name companies are receiving as they
are snapped up in a wave of luxury fever.
</P>
<P>
   Just last week, for example, the much-pursued Fendi finally sold
a majority stake in the business to a pair of suitors, the French
conglomerate LVMH-Moet Hennessey Louis Vuitton and the Italian
leather goods maker Prada SpA, at a price that valued the total
company near $1 billion. For Fendi, whose steamy reputation rests
mostly on the wild popularity of a single style of handbag and
whose net income last year (after the partners pulled their draw)
was estimated at well under $20 million, that was some deal.
</P>
<P>
   But if the designer Calvin Klein is counting on the same
impressive multiples that are going to his European cousins,
analysts suggest he may be disappointed. Barnard Arnault, LVMH's
chairman, has expressed interest in Calvin Klein, but he is cool in
his enthusiasm at best. The companies that today's high-end
acquirers have been going after are those with sterling reputations
in one arena _ shoes or jewelry, for example. Their strategy for
increasing sales is to attach that name to ancillary products like
sunglasses and porcelin _ a formula that has not always been
successful.
</P>
<P>
   American companies have a reputation for already being too loose
with their labels.
</P>
<P>
   Calvin Klein, for example, is most famous for transforming
cotton underwear into a daring personal style statement, but
through licenses the name is already on everything from sheets to
perfume to blues jeans; not a lot of new categories remain
available for bringing in new revenue.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are in the business of quality, creativity and legitimacy;
maybe for U.S. brands, this is the aspect that is still missing,''
said Arnault about the Europeans' discomfort with the large
American labels. ``You have fantastic brands, but they are the
creation of the last 20 years. American brands, they are the
fastest to build. They gain worldwide recognition in a few years,
but maybe for that reason they are more fragile.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides Arnault and his partners at Prada, the acquirers in the
luxury game include Gucci Group of Italy, backed by
Pinault-Printempts Redoute; Compagnie Financiere Richemont, the
owner of Cartier, Texas Pacific Group of Dallas, which recently
bought the Swiss shoe retailer Bally, and the Italian giant HdP,
which recently bought a stake in Valentino, an Italian fashion
house. Everyone seems to be largely shunning the Americans.
</P>
<P>
   American designers sense a bit of snobbism. Bill Blass made it
known more than a year ago that he was looking to sell his company,
one of the best-known names in the high-end fashion market in the
United States, but he still does not have a deal (he says one is
coming soon, however). Will there be a bid from LVMH or another
European Luxury group?
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never had an expression of interest from them, and it's
surprising, in my opinion.'' Unfortunately for would-be luxury
emperors, there are not many Fendi's left. ``It is not a frequent
phenomenon to have a brand that is so hot and is still small,''
Arnault acknowledged. And after the latest raft of deals, most of
the brands left that meet the snob test _ European, long lived,
well known but small _ are majority controlled by families who say
they have no intention of selling. Hermes International SA, the
maker of elaborately pattered silk scarves and ties, and Salvatore
Ferragamo, known for its comfortable dowdy pumps, are quietly on
many investors' wish lists, and both say they are not interested.
Nor is the Italian fashion retailer Stefanel, whose share price
jumped 14 percent one day earlier this month on rumors that LVMH
was preparing a bid. (Giuseppe Stefanel head of the family that
controls Stefanel, called the reports completely unfounded.)
</P>
<P>
   In the chase to make so few tightly held firms consider selling
out, investors are finding themselves in expensive contortions.
According to an executive involved in the Fendi sale, Gucci, which
had been the main competition of LVMH and Prada, quit bidding at
$700 million and walked away from the table. Yet for a month
afterward, the five Fendi sisters, who inherited ownership of the
company, were able to keep the talks going, ultimately convincing
LVMH and Prada executives to increase the valuation on the company
by $300 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``The partnership outbid itself four times,'' said the source.
</P>
<P>
   How can big companies expect to make back their money after
paying such high multiples?
</P>
<P>
   Gucci _ itself the target of an unsuccessful bid by LVMH _
provides an example of how a small business with a great name can
be transformed into a powerhouse. Five years ago the company, then
known for leather bags and snaffle-bit loafers and not much else,
was almost bankrupt on $200 million in annual sales. After a
takeover by new management and the sizzling designer Tom Ford,
Gucci re-established itself as a style maker. It increased sales to
$1 billion, largely by expanding the range of merchandise to
include ready-to-wear fashions and even perfumes. It also expanded
sales globally, by greatly increasing the company's retail presence
in the United States and Asia.
</P>
<P>
   Such a formula, of course, is far easier to describe than to
carry out. There are few similar success stories and many
disappointments. William Price, a founding partner of Texas Pacific
Group, put a bid in on Fendi and is still on the prowl _
acknowledges that such acquisitions do not always bloom as planned.
``I don't think I could cite one that has been an unmitigated
success,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Calvin Klein seems aware of the possible pitfalls of being
acquired and is exploring many options, including an alliance. But
a high price could be too tempting to turn down. (Klein declined to
comment.) Direct sales for Calvin Klein Inc. were $160 million last
year, which, by the Fendi valuation of 7.6 times direct sales of
$130 million, would make the American design house worth well over
$1 billion. But since revenues from total products under the Calvin
Klein label equaled about $2.5 billion, the brand may be too
exploited to earn such outstanding mutiples.
</P>
<P>
   Nowhere is the enthusiasm for conglomeration lower than at many
of the brands that have been acquired by LVMH, which has been at
this strategy longer than anyone else in the luxury goods world.
These units feel that LVMH is not as committed financially to
expanding their range and raising their profile as they had hoped.
`` Arnault is wonderful, but his pleasure and focus in life is
battling and fighting,'' said Christian Lacroix, a designer in the
LVMH stable for the last a decade. ``He loves much more the fight
than making or promoting a label once he has conquered it.''
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   Robert Duffy, president of Marc Jacobs, a design house that LVMH
bought four years ago, is similarly disappointed with LVMH's
commitment to invest growth money into the brand once it bought a
stake. Instead of acquiring new businesses, he said, ``It's my wish
that LVMH would invest the money here and grow this label.''
</P>
<P>
   The Fendi deal is full of quirks that may make it even more
difficult to manage than most would be. For example, although LVMH
and Prada together will own 51 percent of Fendi, it is unclear
which has primacy, and that could eventually lead to internal
fueding. Fendi, Vuitton and Prada are direct competitors on leather
goods; what happens if Fendi's growth comes at the expense of the
owners' own businesses?
</P>
<P>
   There is also the issue of whether after paying so much money
for Fendi, Prada will have enough money left over to help Fendi
along as promised. Prada, with sales under $800 million, had a drop
in net profit of nearly 27 percent last year as overhead ballooned.
Debt also jumped as the company borrowed heavily to finance the
recent investments in Church &AMP; Co., Helmut Lang and Jil Sanders.
(Though LVMH has also been on a buying spree, it has remained very
profitable.)
</P>
<P>
   For the Fendis there remains the issue of who will run the
company. For now the five Fendi sisters and their family are firmly
ensconced at the helm, but industry experts like Allen J. Ellinger,
a partner in MMG, a New York fashion management consulting firm,
think that real money in family businesses comes only when
``somebody starts to put structure into a company, and deal with
the margins.'' That is' code for replacing the family with a
professional cadre of mangers.
</P>
<P>
   ``You retain management only until something goes wrong,'' said
Massimo Ferragamo, chief executive of Ferragamo USA. ``It is why we
have no interest in selling.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
