<SLUG> BC-OHIO-TOBACCOSETTLE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tobacco settlement plan may shrink
 &HT;    By William Hershey
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLUMBUS, Ohio _ Gov. Bob Taft's plan for Ohio to spend $10.1
billion during 26 years from the national tobacco settlement could
shrink to an eight-year plan to spend about $3 billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's up in the air,'' said state Sen. Roy L. Ray, chairman
of the Senate Finance Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Ray's committee meets today and could vote to send a tobacco
spending plan to the full Senate. A substitute bill with the
eight-year plan was being circulated among senators Monday.
</P>
<P>
   While $10.1 billion is the amount Ohio is scheduled to get as a
result of the settlement between the states and the major tobacco
companies, some Senate Finance Committee members are worried about
making projections that go through the year 2025, said Ray,
R-Akron.
</P>
<P>
   State Sen. Richard Hottinger, R-Newark, a committee member, is
among them.
</P>
<P>
   ``His main concern is how do we know where we're going to be in
25 years,'' said Susan Wittstock, Hottinger's legislative
assistant. ``Priorities change. Different needs arise. How do we
know this plan is going to be the best for the state?''
</P>
<P>
   The eight-year, $3 billion plan would not decrease the amount of
money the state is scheduled to receive, but would leave it up to
future legislatures and governors to plan for spending the balance.
</P>
<P>
   Taft continues to support the 26-year plan recommended by the
task force he set up, said Scott Milburn, Taft's spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   The 26-year plan calls for putting nearly half the tobacco money
_ $4.5 billion _ in a trust fund to build and repair primary and
secondary school buildings.
</P>
<P>
   An eight-year schedule for spending the tobacco money would
upset a related Taft proposal, to spend $10.2 billion in state
money during 12 years for school buildings. The governor has
proposed that $2.4 billion of the tobacco money be used for school
buildings during those 12 years.
</P>
<P>
   Taft has used his school-repair plan as an example of his
commitment to education in a brief he filed with the Ohio Supreme
Court in the school funding case. Taft is trying to get the high
court to reverse a lower court decision that the school funding
system is unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
   While backing Taft's plan, Ray said it's important to note that
``as a practical matter'' no legislature is committed to a spending
plan that goes beyond the two-year term in which members serve.
</P>
<P>
   ``We appropriate every two years. That's the operative set of
circumstances. . . . We could have a 50-year plan, a 200-year plan.
It doesn't mean a hill of beans until the legislature in control
appropriates,'' Ray said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the school money, the tobacco task force
recommended spending the tobacco money on smoking cessation and
prevention, other health-related programs, law enforcement
technology and to help tobacco farmers and communities where
tobacco has been an important part of the economy.
</P>
<P>
   William Hershey writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
