<SLUG> BC-BUSH-MOLINARI-1STLEDE-TEX </SLUG>
 
MOLINARI JUMPS OFF BUSH BANDWAGON, JOINS McCAIN CAMPAIGN 
(EDS: Adds details from new Bush book) 
(For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
By RON HUTCHESON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A key early backer of Texas Gov. George W. Bush
defected to a rival presidential campaign on Monday, offering
another reminder that the race for the Republican nomination is far
from over.
</P>
<P>
   Former New York Rep. Guy Molinari, a name with considerable
clout in delegate-rich New York GOP circles, switched his
allegiance to Sen. John McCain of Arizona in the latest bump in a
series for what had been the smooth-running Bush campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Although Bush remains the clear front-runner in the GOP contest,
his efforts to set himself apart from the pack have alienated some
important factions within the party.
</P>
<P>
   First, Bush angered Republican lawmakers by accusing them of
trying to balance the federal budget ``on the backs of the poor.''
Then he seemed to go after social conservatives by saying that his
party sometimes seems obsessed with ``an image of America slouching
toward Gomorrah.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Bush's once-surging poll numbers, while still
impressive, have begun to level off.
</P>
<P>
   ``More and more, I wonder if George W. hasn't `Forrest Gumped'
his way into this,'' said New York pollster John Zogby, referring
to the movie character with an uncanny knack for turning up at the
right place at the right time. ``We're one inch from a real race.''
</P>
<P>
   Although no one suggests that Bush is in any immediate danger of
losing his front-runner status, there are enough uncertainties to
give his rivals hope. He is scheduled to participate in the first
of a series of presidential debates Dec. 2, giving the other
candidates a chance to exploit any gaffe.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's advisers are also bracing for a bruising ad campaign by
rival Steve Forbes, the only candidate who can match Bush's
campaign bankroll.
</P>
<P>
   In a sign of the concern in Bush's camp, the candidate's media
experts recently tested possible Forbes attack ads, as well as
Bush's likely response, on focus groups.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is McCain, who has emerged as Bush's closest rival in
some recent polls.
</P>
<P>
   Molinari, a leader in the effort to coax Bush into the race,
said he changed his mind after comparing the two candidates. The
former Republican congressman currently serves as Staten Island
borough president, a job that gives him clout in a heavily
Republican section of New York City.
</P>
<P>
   Molinari, who once called Bush ``the best candidate the
Republican Party can put forward,'' said he was stunned when Bush
criticized congressional Republicans. Molinari had lobbied
lawmakers to support the Texas governor.
</P>
<P>
   The Bush campaign responded to Molinari's defection with a terse
statement inviting him to reboard the Bush bandwagon ``when Gov.
Bush becomes the Republican presidential nominee.''
</P>
<P>
   Also on Monday, Bush aides said that new allegations about an
arrest for cocaine possession are ``completely false and untrue.''
</P>
<P>
   The charges, aired by anonymous sources, are contained in a new
biography, ``Fortunate Son: George W. Bush and The Making of an
American President,'' by former Texas freelance journalist J.H.
Hatfield.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's never been arrested for a drug possession offense,'' said
Scott McClellan, a Bush spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   The biography, citing unnamed sources, says that Bush was
arrested for cocaine possession in 1972 and further alleges that
former President Bush arranged with a friendly judge to have the
record expunged.
</P>
<P>
   Jean Becker, a spokeswoman for President Bush, said, ``It
absolutely did not happen.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Carol Vance, Harris County district attorney from
1966 to 1979, pointed out what he described as factual
inconsistencies in Hatfield's account _ including the contention
that the judge in question was ``a fellow Republican.''
</P>
<P>
   ``In 1972, there were no Republican district judges handling
criminal cases in Harris County,'' Vance said in a written
statement. He also said the law providing for expungement of
criminal records was not passed by the Texas Legislature until
1977.
</P>
<P>
   (Star-Telegram writers Jay Root and Jeff Guinn contributed to
this report. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World
Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
