<SLUG> BC-DELL-EARNINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DELL SHARES TUMBLE ON WARNING ABOUT RISING CHIP PRICES 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By LAWRENCE M. FISHER    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Shares of Dell Computer Corp. tumbled in after-hours
trading Monday after the company warned that rising memory chip
prices would hurt its third quarter earnings.
</P>
<P>
   Dell made the announcement after the market closed. Dell shares
had closed at $41.3125, down $1.50 in Nasdaq trading, but dropped
another $3.5625, to $37.75 in after-hours trading. Dell earnings
for the third-quarter, which ends this month, will be released on
November 11.
</P>
<P>
   Although Dell put a positive spin on the warning, emphasizing
the temporary nature of the DRAM shortage and reiterating the
company's positive outlook, analysts said the stock could easily
drag the whole technology sector down on Tuesday. Because the
market is sensitive to bad news right now, and Dell is considered a
bellwether, the reaction is likely to be disproportionate to the
news, they said.
</P>
<P>
   Prices for dynamic random access memory chips, known as DRAM,
have risen sharply in the past few weeks since the earthquake in
Taiwan disrupted production there. Hewlett-Packard Co. and Apple
Computer Inc., among others, had already said that the quake would
have an impact on product availability or on prices.
</P>
<P>
   Initially, Michael Dell, Dell's chairman and chief executive,
said the company would not be affected by the quake, and analysts
had said the company's size and long-term contracts might buffer it
from the impact. But Wednesday, the company said that the latest
memory prices had increased by as much as 25 percent, more than
they had expected.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are managing the memory situation carefully and are working
to offset the cost increases with efficiencies in other parts of
our business,'' Thomas J. Meredith, Dell's chief financial officer,
said in a statement. ``We are also taking actions to reduce overall
memory consumption, including advertising system configurations
with lower amounts of base memory,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Daniel Kunstler, an analyst with J.P. Morgan, said he estimated
that increased memory prices might trim Dell's earnings for the
quarter by 2 cents a share, or about 10 percent. Analysts had
expected the company to earn 20 cents.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is also the risk of some revenue getting deferred,
because as they point out, this is a temporary situation,'' he
said. ``A rational buyer wants lots of DRAM, so, do you pay up now,
to get all the memory you need, or just wait a couple of months,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   The memory chip situation is one instance in which Dell's much
vaunted business model may have worked against it. Dell builds each
computer to order and maintains minimal component inventories, so
it benefits during periods of rapid price declines for chips and
other key parts, as the industry has experienced for the past five
years.
</P>
<P>
   With a sudden steep price increase, such as the PC industry is
experiencing now, Dell has greater exposure than do vendors that
maintain larger inventories.
</P>
<P>
   Meredith said the company considers the effects of the
memory-cost issue to be a short-term matter, but that it will hurt
third-quarter operating margins. He pointed out that for the first
half of this year, Dell's sales grew by more than 40 percent,
double the industry rate. He said that current customer demand is
consistent with the growth pattern of the year's first half, and
reiterated that Dell's overall business and prospects for robust
growth remain strong.
</P>
<P>
   ``in fairness, DRAM pricing will come down again, and they are,
in that context, probably truthful in saying their long-term
outlook has not been altered,'' Kunstler said. ``But the market is
looking for reasons to go down, and Dell just gave it a new one.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
