<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RYAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REACTION BY THE FANS WAS UTTERLY INDEFENSIBLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   At least once a year I deliver my personal Sermon on the Mount
to those unfortunate individuals who do not have the great benefit
of organized sport in their lives. I condescendingly explain to
them that no matter how happy they think they are, or how fulfilled
they believe their lives to be, unless they know what it is like to
be filled with that delicious rush that only sport can bring, they
are missing something otherwise irreplaceable during their
existence on this earth.
</P>
<P>
   I firmly believe that. But along with the good things sport
brings into our lives, there is an undeniable dark side, which was
completely in evidence at Fenway Park Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   It is important to care. Appreciating sport for its own sake is
one thing, but investing deep emotion in the outcome of a
competition raises it all to a different level. At some point or
another, a true fan cares, and cares deeply, who wins or loses.
</P>
<P>
   That said, there is a limit. These are all games, and no matter
how steeped in history and tradition they are, and no matter how
much better a feeling it would be if your team wins rather than
loses, when it is all said and done, they remain games.
</P>
<P>
   I cannot rationalize for one millisecond the behavior of that
demented minority who took it upon themselves to disrupt Sunday
night's game by throwing things onto the field in the ninth inning
of the (deserved) Yankee victory over the Red Sox.
</P>
<P>
   On the Atrocity Scale of 1 to 10, it wasn't much more than a 2,
but it was bad enough that plate umpire Al Clark justifiably pulled
everyone off the field until order could be restored. Who cares
whether or not any potentially harmful objects really did land on
the field? (And at least one eyewitness of my acquaintance said a
hard something-or-other came whizzing by his ear.) They could have.
Ask Chris Chambliss and Mickey Rivers about the darts and bolts
thrown in their direction in this very park 25 years ago. Was Clark
supposed to wait until a bottle or battery or who-knows-what
actually struck Tim Tschida or Tino Martinez before acting?
</P>
<P>
   So, yes, there is a disturbing history here, and not just here,
but north of the border, as well. When sports passions are
inflamed, whether by officiating calls or noncalls, or by alleged
injustices of some sort, all bets are off. Thus we give you NFL
field judge Armen Terzian being skulled by a flying bottle in
Minneapolis during a 1975 playoff game; a massive riot in Montreal
when Maurice Richard was suspended by NHL commissioner Clarence
Campbell in 1955 for almost decapitating Boston's Hal Laycoe; and
Chargers equipment man Sid Brooks seriously injured by a Giants
Stadium iceball in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   And we're like a tot on training wheels behaviorally in this
country compared with the goings-on in the international arena. I
mean, we're not the ones with moats surrounding our soccer pitches,
are we? And ask any American who has ever played basketball there
about crowd behavior in such places as Italy and Greece, where
heating coins with a lighter and flinging them at both opposing
players and referees is often the evening's highlight.
</P>
<P>
   I say that nothing justifies any of this behavior, but not
everyone agrees. A woman called Monday afternoon to say she was
``outraged'' that I had criticized in print the Sunday night fan
behavior. ``If I were there,'' she said, ``I'd have thrown
something, too.''
</P>
<P>
   I was astounded. She was polite and she certainly sounded
cultured. What would compel her not only to harbor that
anti-intellectual desire but also to condemn me for not agreeing
with her?
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a frustrating evening,'' she explained. ``You wouldn't
understand if you're not a lifelong Red Sox fan.''
</P>
<P>
   No, ma'am, I'm not a lifelong Red Sox fan. I'm a lifelong sports
fan, and that's a much higher calling. I care about the Red Sox
(season ticket-holder), and I really like and admire this
particular team. I would find it far preferable for them to keep
winning for all the obvious professional and personal reasons. I am
a serious fan, and I'd be willing to bet that in the course of my
sports fandom I've punched more walls, shouted at more TV sets, and
had more despondent rides home from losing games than she could
possibly imagine. I know what it is to be a fan; believe me.
</P>
<P>
   She was understandably upset with the blown calls by Rick Reed
and Tim Tschida, and alluded to some sort of larger conspiracy
against her team. I asked her if she would have considered throwing
something at Nomar Garciaparra, Bret Saberhagen, or Jose Offerman,
all of whom made errors that led to runs. ``Oh, no,'' she replied.
``They're our boys, and we love them.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, you don't always love wisely in this life. Anyway, I've
overreacted to poor officiating, or what I thought was poor
officiating, as much as anybody, but as I get older I try to temper
that instinct by looking at the larger picture. My female protester
doesn't seem to understand that there is a huge difference between
clear self-inflicted wounds such as errors that lead to inexcusable
runs and very unfortunate missed calls, that, however aggravating,
still lead only to speculative situations. In both cases in
question, Mariano Rivera was still in control of the game, and was
likely to get himself out of trouble.
</P>
<P>
   We all know that a few booze-soaked slugs can spoil things for
thousands of people, but there is more in the Fenway air these days
than that. Red Sox fans have bought into their own folklore too
much, especially when the opponent is New York. You've got people
on the radio who should know better telling them that the umpires
are subconsciously favoring the New York team. You've got people
truly believing that larger forces are controlling the fate of the
Red Sox. And you've got people who maybe ought to read the front
page once in a while ready to inflict harm on people because they
don't like what's happening in a ballgame.
</P>
<P>
   It's really not that complicated. You watch, you yell, you go
home, you go to bed, you wake up, you read the paper to confirm
what you saw, you go to work, and you hash it out with someone.
Anything else is sick.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bob Ryan is a Globe columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-18-99 2117EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991018.0447 </DOCNO>
