<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-MEDICARE-870&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON PROPOSES A DISCOUNT PLAN TO TRIM COSTS OF MEDICARE 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By ROBERT PEAR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In a break from three decades of Medicare policy,
the Clinton administration asked Congress on Monday to steer
Medicare patients to certain doctors and hospitals that offer
discounts on the price of care they provide to people who are
elderly or disabled.
</P>
<P>
   Under legislation drafted by the administration and sent to
Congress, federal officials would notify beneficiaries of a list of
preferred doctors and hospitals that agree to offer ``discounted
rates'' to the government and to reduce the fees charged to
patients. The medical providers would attract more patients, making
up in volume for the lower charges.
</P>
<P>
   The White House and some Democrats, like Sen. Bob Graham of
Florida, say the proposed changes would save money and make
Medicare more competitive and efficient.
</P>
<P>
   But many Republicans oppose the idea, which has also provoked an
outcry from doctors and hospitals. Critics say the government would
emphasize price over quality and would steer Medicare patients to
mediocre doctors and hospitals that offered the biggest discounts.
</P>
<P>
   Under the president's proposal, doctors and hospitals that
wanted to be named as ``preferred providers'' would have to meet
new federal standards for the quality of care. But critics of the
proposal said that price would often be the dominant factor because
it was much easier to measure cost than quality.
</P>
<P>
   Since the creation of Medicare in 1965, beneficiaries have been
able to seek treatment from almost any licensed doctor or
accredited hospital. In its new legislative proposal, the
administration is asking Congress for broad new powers to pick and
choose providers who would coordinate the care of Medicare
patients. In some cases, under the proposal, certain services would
be provided only by the designated hospitals and doctors in
specific geographic regions.
</P>
<P>
   Here are other details of the administration's proposal:
</P>
<P>
   _ The federal government would designate specific hospitals
across the country as ``centers of excellence'' and would encourage
Medicare patients to use them for high-cost procedures like heart
surgery or hip replacement, provided the government saved money.
</P>
<P>
   _ The government would hire specialists to coordinate all the
care needed by Medicare patients for the treatment of particular
conditions like congestive heart failure, high blood pressure,
coronary artery disease, asthma and diabetes.
</P>
<P>
   _ Federal officials could use competitive bidding to obtain
discounts on medical equipment and other goods and services
purchased for Medicare beneficiaries. Medicare often pays more than
the retail price for common items like lancets and catheters.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton expressed interest in these proposals in June,
when he unveiled a comprehensive plan to redesign Medicare and add
prescription drug benefits.
</P>
<P>
   White House officials said the proposals would modernize
Medicare and save money, by using selected techniques of managed
care to control costs in the traditional fee-for-service Medicare
program, which still serves 84 percent of the 39 million
beneficiaries. Vice President Al Gore supports the administration's
Medicare plan, including these proposals, the White House said.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate Finance Committee and the House Ways and Means
Committee plan to vote this week on legislation to restore some
money cut from Medicare in 1997. White House officials said they
hoped that the committees would accept the president's proposals,
which could offset some of the cost of undoing cuts made in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Two members of the Senate Finance Committee, Graham and Sen.
John Chafee, R-R.I., support the president's proposal to revamp the
purchasing of goods and services in the traditional Medicare
program. A third member, Sen. Bob Kerrey, D-Neb., has expressed
support for some of the ideas.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Pete Stark, D-Calif., said that an experimental project in
Polk County, Fla., had shown that competitive bidding and similar
techniques could save money for Medicare without harming the
quality of care.
</P>
<P>
   But there is also strong criticism. Dr. Nicholas T. Kouchoukos,
president of the Society of Thoracic Surgeons, said heart surgeons
were ``extremely troubled'' by Clinton's proposal because they
feared that ``excellence would take a back seat to discounted
pricing.'' It is, he said, totally inappropriate to send elderly
patients to the ``lowest bidder'' when they need life-saving
surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Pollack, executive vice president of the American
Hospital Association, said Clinton's proposal could reduce access
to specialized services in areas where the local hospital did not
win a contract with Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials said that doctors and hospitals were
afraid of true competition because it meant that there would be
winners and losers.
</P>
<P>
   Some Republicans say they oppose Clinton's proposal simply
because he covets the modernization of Medicare as part of his
political legacy. Republicans said they did not want him to be able
to take credit for such changes in the program unless they got what
they wanted: fundamental overhaul of Medicare, putting the original
fee-for-service program into direct competition with private health
plans.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In March, 10 of the 17 members of a federal advisory commission
headed by Sen. John Breaux of Louisiana recommended that Medicare
compete directly with private health plans. To enhance such
competition, the panel said, Medicare officials should have more of
the purchasing tools available to private health plans, including
the ability to sign contracts with selected health care providers
who offer high-quality services and lower prices.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview on Monday night Breaux, a Democrat, said the
president's proposal, taken by itself, was ``like robbing Peter to
pay Paul.'' The government, he said, would cut payments to some
health care providers so it could redistribute the money to other
doctors and hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, Breaux said, ``I do not want to give the Health Care
Financing Administration more bureaucratic power, more regulatory
authority, at a time when it controls more than 80 percent of the
Medicare marketplace.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
