<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEWIS-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: CITY OF GHOSTS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Germany)  (mk) 
 By ANTHONY LEWIS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERLIN _ In most great cities, monuments to the past are an
unnoticed part of the landscape. In Berlin, the past _ the terrible
past _ is inescapable.
</P>
<P>
   Prominent in the skyline of the eastern part of the city is the
Moorish dome, topped by a Star of David, of the New Synagogue,
completed in 1866. It was an enormous building, seating 3,200 for
services: an indication of the size and position of the Jewish
community.
</P>
<P>
   Now all that remains are the facade and domes, beautifully
reconstructed, and a small museum of what used to be. A large
photograph shows the men of the congregation, prosperous-looking
burghers.
</P>
<P>
   In the southwest corner of the city is a large lake, the
Wannsee. On weekends dozens of sailboats race on it.
</P>
<P>
   On Jan. 20, 1942, 14 Nazi officials met in a villa on the
lakeshore to plan the carrying out of the Final Solution: the
extermination of the Jews. The chairman of the meeting was Reinhard
Heydrich.
</P>
<P>
   Today the villa is a memorial and educational center. Its
exhibits show how important the Jewish community was in Germany
from the mid-19th century _ how much it contributed to culture and
the economy. And then it shows how the Nazis harassed, humiliated
and finally murdered the Jews.
</P>
<P>
   In one room is the long table around which the Nazi officials
sat in 1942. You can imagine them jotting down notes, occasionally
recessing to stroll along the lake.
</P>
<P>
   ``Heydrich had expected that his concept would meet with
misgivings and objections from the ministerial departments,'' a
villa publication says, ``but he encountered only general agreement
and readiness to help in its execution. The discussions dealt
solely with details.''
</P>
<P>
   Many Jews, including Albert Einstein, lived in the neighborhood
around Bayerischer Platz in the first third of this century. They
were altogether integrated into the society, or so they thought.
</P>
<P>
   An extraordinary memorial designed by Renata Stih and Frieder
Schnock showed, on signs put high on light poles, what happened to
the Jews after 1933. On one side of a sign was an image _ of, say,
a cat. On the other was the text of a Nazi decree: Jews are
forbidden to have pets.
</P>
<P>
   The signs showed the gradual accumulation of anti-Semitic laws
that dehumanized an entire people: Jewish judges dismissed, then
public-school teachers, then civil servants, then actors, then
musicians, then doctors. Jews barred from theaters and concert
halls, forbidden to buy food except between 4 and 5 in the
afternoon. And finally, deportation and death.
</P>
<P>
   Most powerful of all is the new Jewish Museum building designed
by Daniel Libeskind. It is only a building; the exhibits are not
yet installed. But it is so remarkable that it is thronged with
visitors. They have to sign up for group tours, and there are now
40 tours a day, seven days a week.
</P>
<P>
   The outer walls of Libeskind's museum are covered in zinc,
pierced by slashes of window that might be lightning or a shattered
Star of David. Inside, the corridors and rooms are cut again and
again; bridges connect them. The unmistakable symbol is of Germany
and Judaism, linked and disconnected.
</P>
<P>
   Then, through a black door, one enters a dark angular tower. It
is an oppressive space, suffocating. As a symbol of the Holocaust,
I found it more powerful than museum images of the reality.
</P>
<P>
   The striking thing is that ordinary Germans in large numbers
visit these reminders of the Jewish past and Nazi savagery. And
newspapers, radio and television refer to the history in one way or
another day after day. Immediately after the war most Germans
seemed to wish the past away. Now they face it.
</P>
<P>
   History is everywhere here. Lord Foster, the British architect,
totally reconstructed the interior of the Reichstag _ but left bits
of the old interior walls, including Soviet soldiers' graffiti. At
the top he put a wonderful glass dome, with a circle of pictures
from history below it.
</P>
<P>
   Bits of the Berlin Wall have been preserved here and there as
mementoes, too. And a museum tells the story of the airlift that
saved West Berlin when the Soviet Union blockaded it in 1948-49.
Over 11 months the United States and its Allies flew in 2,325,000
tons of food, coal and other supplies. Republicans in Congress
supported President Truman in the great effort without
partisanship. But that was another country.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
