<HEADER>
A1016 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BBA-SOX-FANS-BOS &LR;      10-18 1051
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-SOX-FANS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW FRIENDLY FENWAY BECAME FRIGHTFUL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By THOMAS FARRAGHER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ As he braced against biting winds on Yawkey Way Monday,
Steve Busby tugged his Red Sox cap low over his eyes and took no
joy in firing a knockdown pitch at baseball fans behaving badly.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's bad for baseball,'' said Busby, 45, of Marblehead, Mass.
``And it's very bad for Boston. We're losers and we can't deal with
it. And it's reducing grown men _ lawyers, stockbrokers, and
accountants _ into children. I mean it's sad.''
</P>
<P>
   Measured against street riots and felonious deeds that have
shadowed sporting events for generations, Sunday night's shower of
debris from Fenway fans, forcing an eight-minute delay in the
bottom of the ninth, was somewhere between boorish and brutal.
</P>
<P>
   But fans, baseball officials, and students of sports psychology
said hideous umpiring, a legacy of losing, and a rivalry that
borders on hatred are toxic ingredients that have turned sections
of Friendly Fenway into Frightful Fenway this championship season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think some people have this sense of entitlement,'' said
Jose Masso, senior associate director of the Center for the Study
of Sport in Society at Northeastern University. ``They feel they
have this ticket that is expensive and hard to get and there are no
rules about their behavior.
</P>
<P>
   ``They can curse at the umpire, get personal with the players,
and even throw things. I'm sitting there thinking: This is now part
of our New England culture? This is something we find charming? I
was somewhat embarrassed.''
</P>
<P>
   If Sunday night's shower of bottles and cups, prompted by a
blown call at second base by umpire Tim Tschida, was unusual for
its ferocity, it was hardly unprecedented for a Red Sox-Yankees
matchup.
</P>
<P>
   In the late 1970s, the players in pinstripes literally feared
for their safety at Fenway. Chris Chambliss once took a dart in the
shoulder as he pulled into third base with a triple. Someone once
tossed 2-inch bolts at Mickey Rivers as he stood in center field.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, fanatical behavior is part of baseball history. In the
sixth inning of Game 7 of the 1934 series between the St. Louis
Cardinals and Detroit Tigers, St. Louis's Joe Medwick barreled into
Marv Owen at third. Commissioner Kenesaw Mountain Landis ordered
Medwick removed from the game after Tiger fans threw bottles,
fruit, and vegetables at him.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there is something about the first-ever postseason series
between two fabled franchises that has pushed the decibel level to
new extremes, sent veins popping in the necks of jeering Boston
fans, and added a razor-sharp edge to catcalls from the grandstand.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was with the Astros, some of the things that went on in
Shea Stadium were unbelievable. One of our players was supposedly
urinated on by a fan,'' said Jerry Trupiano, a Red Sox radio
broadcaster. ``But I've never seen anything like this Red
Sox-Yankee rivalry. Those who were throwing the bottles were just
the lunatic fringe.
</P>
<P>
   ``But there's a sense here that it's our turn. And there's a
level of frustration. I don't care if the fans yell or scream, but
keep it in the boundaries of good taste and let's not turn it into
a physical act.''
</P>
<P>
   But in a sport where bench-clearing brawls are not uncommon and
fans feel comfortable chanting obscenities in front of little boys
and bespectacled grandmothers, the boundaries of good taste are
moving targets.
</P>
<P>
   They said an expletive on CBS television last week, ``and you
can see people's naked butts on weekly TV, too. I'm not excusing
it, but that's the way everything else has evolved,'' said Lynn
Solomon, 32, of Yakima, Wash., who stood in line Monday for the
limited number of tickets sold for the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the beginning of the game, I was sitting in the grandstand
and there was a lot of good-natured bantering going on,'' Solomon
said. ``But by the end of the game when people had had their hearts
broken a couple of times and had a handful of beers, it was not
good-natured at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Thomas M. Menino called the behavior an embarrassment for
the city. ``I apologize to the baseball fans of America,'' Menino
said in a statement. ``That is not what Boston is about.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tonight's game will give us the opportunity to show the world
that we are not only the most loyal and supportive fans, but we are
courteous and sportsmanlike as well,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Red Sox spokesman Dick Bresciani said a small portion of the
team's fans were responsible for the outburst.
</P>
<P>
   ``Out of 34,000 fans, it doesn't take too many to create an ugly
scene,'' said Bresciani, adding that ballpark behavior has shifted.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't believe what I hear on radio and TV today,'' he said.
``The limits of appropriateness has changed. These kids hear these
words all the time and they chant it in all the ballparks. I know
it makes older people feel uncomfortable.''
</P>
<P>
   Len Zaichkowsky, a sports psychologist at Boston University,
said the same crowd mentality that would make otherwise rational
people behave irrationally, is at work in the growing sense of
frustration that has boiled over after Red Sox defeats amid
questionable umpiring.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the immediate frustration and the frustration that goes
back to the beginning of this century,'' Zaichkowsky said. ``People
know the history, and now we see the umpires really trying to take
it away from us and they become the enemy, too. There's sort of a
social contagion going on here, and it spills through the whole
crowd.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Masso: ``There's the frustration that's built up over all
these years added to the expectations that were raised in
overcoming Cleveland. There are a good number of fans out there who
are saying, `Doggone it. This is our year, and if people get in our
way, we're going to point them out and tell them they're the reason
we're not getting our just dues.''
</P>
<P>
   Matt Murphy, 26, of Peabody, needed no advanced degree in the
psychology of modern sports to summarize succinctly the behavior at
Fenway.
</P>
<P>
   ``Probably a combination of frustration, alcohol, and other
grown men around them doing the same thing,'' said Murphy outside
the park Monday afternoon. ``Nothing begets stupidity like
stupidity.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
