<SLUG> BC-FORD-EARNINGS-600&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. SALES HELP FORD DELIVER 11 PERCENT PROFIT GAIN IN QUARTER 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By KEITH BRADSHER    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   DEARBORN, Mich. _ Strong sales of sport utility vehicles, pickup
trucks and large cars in the United States gave Ford Motor Co.
better-than-expected earnings in the third quarter, even as the
company acknowledged severe problems in its European operations.
</P>
<P>
   Ford said Monday that it had earned $1.11 billion, or 90 cents a
share, up 11 percent from the third quarter last year, when it
earned $1 billion, or 80 cents a share. It beat analysts' profit
expectations of 85 cents a share.
</P>
<P>
   Ford's gain would have been even larger except for a one-time
charge of $125 million for retirement health care and life
insurance costs at an auto parts division, the company said.
</P>
<P>
   Investors focused Monday on the company's strong overall
earnings, bidding up Ford's stock in a weak market. Shares rose
$1.50, to $52.0625.
</P>
<P>
   Ford has profited, particularly in North America, by
discontinuing slow-selling, unprofitable car models and replacing
them with more lucrative models. Successful new models include the
Lincoln LS sports sedan, the Jaguar S-type sedan and the Ford
Excursion sport utility vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   W. Wayne Booker, Ford's vice chairman and chief financial
officer, acknowledged Monday in the bluntest terms used yet that
the company was having problems in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Ford's European operations lost $171 million in the third
quarter despite profits from its Volvo Cars and Jaguar divisions in
Europe, and despite the success there of the Ford Focus compact
sedan.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess it's an indication of the magnitude of the other
problems,'' that the European operations lost money despite those
three successes, Booker said at a news conference Monday at Ford's
headquarters here in a southwestern suburb of Detroit. Ford has
been losing market share in Europe as rival automakers,
particularly Volkswagen AG, have introduced more exciting car
designs.
</P>
<P>
   Ford lost $273 million in Europe in the third quarter of 1998,
but that included high costs for the introduction of the Focus. The
company said Monday that ``Ford does not expect to achieve its 1999
milestone for Europe to improve operating earnings year over
year.''
</P>
<P>
   The company also announced a management shake-up on Friday aimed
partly at improving results in Europe. The new structure will give
more autonomy to Ford's European operations, which have been run
mainly from here in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   Ford's South American automotive operations have also been
losing money, partly because of economic problems in Brazil but
also because Ford did not invest in new models and factories there
until recently. Ford lost $72 million in the third quarter,
compared with a $44 million loss a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, Ford earned $1 billion from North American
automotive operations in the quarter, despite setting aside $100
million for a continuing program of reducing white-collar
employment through voluntary-departure incentives. Ford, which did
not declare the $100 million as a one-time charge, had earned $896
million in the region a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Rod A. Lache, an auto analyst at Deutsche Bank Alex. Brown,
predicted that Ford would continue to do well at home while
struggling overseas. ``The North American earnings are going to
keep getting better and the rest are going to be nonfactors for
Ford as a whole,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Ford's cash reserves swelled to $25.7 billion, compared with
$22.9 billion a year earlier. Despite occasional criticisms from
institutional investors and Wall Street analysts, Ford has been
conserving cash to prepare for the next recession and for possible
mergers.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The auto parts subsidiary, Visteon Automotive Systems, which
Ford is expected to spin off soon, earned $155 million in the third
quarter excluding the one-time charge, which occurred when an
outside actuarial analysis of a Visteon division caused Ford to
conclude that it had been underestimating costs for retiree health
care and life insurance.
</P>
<P>
   Ford officials declined to identify the division, saying only
that it was small and that they did not believe other divisions had
similar problems. Visteon earned $148 million a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Ford Credit, the auto loans and leases division, earned $317
million in the third quarter, up from $272 million a year ago.
Hertz Corp., the car rental business in which Ford owns an 80
percent stake, earned $139 million, up from $119 million a year
earlier.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
