<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-18 21:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1029 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBO-OJEDA-LOYALTY-ART     10-18 0957
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-OJEDA-LOYALTY-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO-STEPPING WITH FATE, THEN COMING WAY, WAY BACK 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Md., Fla., Calif., N.J.)  (ART ADV: A photo is being sent. Non-subscribers can purchase by
calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By JAN HOFFMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It'S not that the man the fans called Bobby O. doesn't know from
comebacks. After all, in the 1986 World Series, he pitched Game
Three and the classic, Game Six, for the Mets, stonily willing them
to victory when they were on their knees. But though Bobby Ojeda
has played for the Red Sox, the Indians and the Yankees too, it
wasn't until his mother prodded him this weekend that he finally
watched some of the playoffs. That's because there are comebacks,
and then there is coming back, as in near-death freefalls.
</P>
<P>
   So to a grand new home, hidden in Rumson, N.J. On a sunny
October morning, his youngest girls are gamboling out back and
inside, candles have been lighted to calm the room. No newspapers.
They shake things up. Before, Bobby O. would read three a day.
</P>
<P>
   Before does not mean his 16-year career in baseball, but the
nightmare that essentially ended it. On a March night in 1993,
after a family barbecue in Florida with two of his fellow pitchers
from the Cleveland Indians, Bobby O., Steve Olin and Tim Crews
decided do a little fishing in Crews' motor boat. The boat crashed
into a dock. The autopsy said that Crews had had a little too much
to drink. Only Bobby O. survived, barely.
</P>
<P>
   It took Bobby O. six weeks to heal from his injuries, notably
the virtual scalping that, even after artful plastic surgery, left
him with a U-shaped scar looping across his forehead. The real
healing had not even begun.
</P>
<P>
   Stubborn fool. That summer, weeks after he fled to Sweden to
hide, followed by a stay at a Maryland psychiatric institution, he
made a comeback to honor his dead friends. When even the Orioles
fans welcomed him with a standing ovation, Ojeda, overcome, posted
a thank-you note on their scoreboard.
</P>
<P>
   At season's end, the Indians and Ojeda parted ways. He made it
through the 1994 spring training with the Yankees and began
pitching in the regular season. But it was obvious. After he got
the word, he sneaked away, got into his truck and drove his rage,
his guilt, the boozing and the ghosts home to New Jersey, to face
his family and himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't figure it out,'' says Bobby O., leaning back on a
couch. ``I was used to fighting and winning, but for the first time
in my life I couldn't fix it or make it go away or not happen, no
matter how hard I tried. That anger lasted, strong. I didn't make
sense for about three years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never played the victim, but I was mean and nasty, which is
way out of character.''
</P>
<P>
   In his grief and guilt about his friends' fatherless children,
he temporarily lost contact with his three children from his first
marriage. He endlessly berated his second wife and their young
daughter. ``I had strangers saying, `We're really glad you're
alive,' and even that would make me mad,'' he says. ``I didn't look
at a mirror for six months because I was terrified of who was in
there.''
</P>
<P>
   Now 41, Bobby O. looks as if he has stepped back into his skin
and likes the way it fits. His humor is self-deprecating. Raised in
California, his mother an interpreter for migrant workers, his
father an upholsterer, he wanted to be a professional ballplayer,
he said, because ``it was the only thing I was any good at.''
</P>
<P>
   He was good but not dazzling. He did have a great year in 1986,
after he left Boston and came to New York, where his loyalty
remains. ``All the Mets fans ask is that you give your best
effort,'' he says. ``If you try to pass the buck, they'll chew you
up.'' When he was lousy, he says, ``They knew I was really trying.
I was very average, but when the moon and the planets lined up in
'86, there I was, and it was a shock to me, too.''
</P>
<P>
   He adds: ``Boston? They're the proverbial bridesmaid and you're
just another groom. If you don't propose with a World Series title,
they'll hate you.'' As in: you stink as a baseball player, so you
stink as a person, ``and we hate your dog, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Bobby O. has always two-stepped with fate. He has flown planes,
still hikes and fishes in wildernesses worldwide and still rides a
Harley-Davidson. As a kid, he drove his minibike off a bridge.
During the 1988 pennant race, he almost lost a finger to a hedge
clipper.
</P>
<P>
   A lot of almosts. During those lost years, howling at his
staunch second wife, Ellen, he knew that if he could reach deep
enough, he might save himself from drowning.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball's salary, two more daughters, the amazing Ellen _ who,
12 years later, still jauntily calls him ``Baby'' _ building a new
home and mountain treks helped. These days, Bobby Ojeda, a
``professional Dad,'' can taste joy and gratitude.
</P>
<P>
   A decade ago, at his mother's behest, he and Ellen raised
$100,000 from Met fans for a group home on a California Indian
reservation. A month ago, Mom calls to say that, flush from a new
casino, the tribe built a Little League field and is dedicating it
to him. She knows how he is, but would he consider coming out?
</P>
<P>
   ``I said: `Are you kidding? You're talking to me, not Babe Ruth!
This is a highlight of my life! I'm there!''
</P>
<P>
   At the dedication, he sees Indian children in baseball uniforms
and a chief says, ``When no one was coming here, you helped us take
the first step. This is why we honor you.'' An elder waved burning
sage leaves, praying. Amid unfamiliar language, the former pitcher
heard the words, ``Bob Ojeda.'' In the retelling, Bobby O. looks
awestruck. ``It gave me the chills,'' he says, ``and I thought, `It
does not get better than this.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
