<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-18 21:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1034 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w BC-PUERTORICO-NAVY-ART-7     10-18 1028
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PUERTORICO-NAVY-ART-750&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PANEL RECOMMENDS NAVY BE ALLOWED TO USE PUERTO RICAN FIRING RANGE
FOR 5 YEARS
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo NYT17 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(sw) 
 By ELIZABETH BECKER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A presidential panel recommended on Monday that the
U.S. military be allowed to resume live firing exercises at a Navy
base in Puerto Rico but that the range be shut down in five years,
despite demands from the territory's governor that the base be
closed immediately and all bombing halted.
</P>
<P>
   Since April, when a Marine pilot killed a Puerto Rican guard in
a bombing accident on the base, which is on the island of Vieques,
Puerto Rican protesters have occupied the base and prevented any
target practice while the territory's politicians have argued that
the base was an unacceptable threat to the island's livelihood and
environment. The Navy has suspended all bombing pending a final
decision on the base.
</P>
<P>
   Anticipating criticism of Monday's recommendation, Secretary of
Defense William Cohen said in a written statement that Navy
officials and representatives from Puerto Rico should continue
searching for a compromise.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's clear from the panel's report there are serious concerns
among the residents of Vieques which need and deserve the careful
attention of the Navy and the Department of Defense,'' Cohen said
in the statement issued while he was traveling in the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
   The panel's recommendation was immediately criticized by Hillary
Rodham Clinton, a presumed candidate for senator from New York. She
endorsed the position of most Puerto Rican politicians in New York,
who have promised to make the closing of Vieques an issue in next
year's presidential and Senate elections.
</P>
<P>
   ``There should be an immediate and permanent end to the
bombing,'' Mrs. Clinton said on Monday. ``The use of live fire on
the island has put the people of Vieques at risk, degraded the
environment and hampered economic development.''
</P>
<P>
   Last month Mrs. Clinton angered several Hispanic leaders in New
York when she urged the president to withdraw his offer of clemency
to members of a Puerto Rican terrorist organization. And in
Monday's move, she was more in step with the Democratic Party
establishment.
</P>
<P>
   In a private conversation over the weekend, Vice President Al
Gore told a state senator from New York, Olga Mendez, that he also
favored shutting down the base, said an official with Gore's
presidential campaign. But a spokesman for Gore would say only that
the vice president was working for ``a resolution to this important
issue.''
</P>
<P>
   The Defense Department says that despite months of searching, it
has found no replacement for the base, which the secretary of the
Navy has called ``the only suitable training site.''.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the United States is to maintain military forces, it owes
its sailors, Marines, soldiers and airmen the best possible
training,'' the Navy secretary, Richard Danzig, said on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Danzig asked Congress to endorse the findings of the four-member
panel, which was headed by Francis Rush, principal deputy assistant
secretary of defense for force management policy. After a
congressional recommendation on the base, President Clinton will
make a final decision.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. government owns nearly two-thirds of the 33,000-acre
island of Vieques. Because the island is far from the major
commercial shipping and air routes, the Navy and Marines have
mounted exercises with live ammunition for amphibious assaults,
aerial bombing and aircraft carrier-based attacks.
</P>
<P>
   Pentagon officials said that as the only base for such exercises
on the East Coast, Vieques had been critical for training pilots,
sailors and Marines for every war since World War II, including the
recent Kosovo air campaign.
</P>
<P>
   In June Clinton appointed the four-member panel to resolve the
competing demands of the American military and the Puerto Rican
government.
</P>
<P>
   But the president tipped his own hand in a private letter he
wrote to his national security advisor, Sandy Berger, on July 26, a
White House official said. In it, the official said, the president
said he agreed with Ruben Berrios-Martinez, a Puerto Rican friend
of the president, who said that Vieques was being treated like ``a
colonial commonwealth.'' ``This is wrong,'' the president wrote.
``I think they don't want us there. That's the main point. The Navy
can find a way to work around it.''
</P>
<P>
   In its unanimous recommendation, the panel said it recognized
the need to hold the training but said the military should
substantially reduce the number of days it holds live-fire
operations and cut back by half the amount of ammunition used.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Lee Hamilton, head of the Woodrow Wilson International Center
for Scholars, was a member of the panel, along with retired a
Marine Corps general, Richard Neal, and a retired Navy vice
admiral, Diego Hernandez, a former commander of the Navy's Third
Fleet.
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton said on Monday that the issue was difficult because the
``Navy has not done a good job communicating to the Puerto Rican
community.''
</P>
<P>
   In nearly two months of testimony and travel to Puerto Rico,
Hamilton, a former Democratic representative from Indiana, said the
panel came to the conclusion that ``the Puerto Rican community is
very incensed by this and they all want it stopped immediately.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the strongest of those voices was Rep. Carlos
Romero-Barcelo, a Democrat and nonvoting delegate from Puerto Rico.
Romero-Barcelo told the special panel, ``We insist that the Navy
release its stranglehold on Vieques and that all property in
Vieques be returned to the government of Puerto Rico or the
municipality of Vieques.''
</P>
<P>
   Trying to make up for these lapses in communication, the Navy
has issued reports trying to counter arguments about environmental
degradation and showing that the death of the base guard in April
was the only civilian fatality in more than 50 years of live
ammunition training there.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
