<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   RITE AID OUSTS ITS CHIEF AND GETS A LOAN EXTENSION
</P>
<P>
   Directors of Rite Aid ousted the chief executive, Martin L.
Grass, and announced the company would restate $500 million in
pretax earnings since 1997 and would place control with four
independent board members.
</P>
<P>
   With those changes, the company said, its lead bankers agreed to
extend by one year $2.7 billion in loans and other debt that had
been due Oct. 29 and that Leonard Green &AMP; Partners, the Los Angeles
investment boutique, would invest $300 million.
</P>
<P>
   FINANCIAL SERVICES BILL IN LAST STAGE
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers in the Senate and House moved toward completing a bill
overhauling the nation's financial system but failed to satisfy
President Clinton's concerns about protecting consumers and
minorities. The issue, which would repeal the Glass-Steagal Act of
1933, has led to an intense lobbying campaign.
</P>
<P>
   CITIGROUP'S PROFITS TOP FORECASTS
</P>
<P>
   Citigroup reported that third-quarter profit more than tripled,
exceeding forecasts. Citigroup's stock rose $1.5625, to $43.6875.
Results at Bank of America and J.P. Morgan also topped analysts'
estimates.
</P>
<P>
   XEROX'S PROFIT AND SHARES SKID
</P>
<P>
   Xerox reported that its net income fell 11 percent, to 47 cents
a diluted share. Until Xerox warned on Oct. 8 that its results
would be dismal, analysts had expected earnings of 58 cents a
share. The company said that results for the fourth-quarter and the
first half of 2000 would also be sluggish. Xerox's shares, which
have fallen 44 percent since the warning, dropped $3.625 to
$23.8125.
</P>
<P>
   PROFIT AT FORD INCREASES 11 PERCENT
</P>
<P>
   Ford Motor reported an 11 percent profit rise, to 90 cents a
share, surpassing forecasts of 85 cents thanks to strong domestic
sales of sport utility vehicles, pickup trucks and large cars.
European operations had problems.
</P>
<P>
   DRUG COMPANIES' RESULTS ARE MIXED
</P>
<P>
   Warner-Lambert reported a 38 percent profit rise, matching
analysts' expectations, but a rival drug maker, American Home
Products, posted a $2.9 billion loss after setting aside $3.5
billion, mainly to pay for the settlement of litigation related to
its fen-phen diet drug.
</P>
<P>
   DELTA AND CONTINENTAL OUTPERFORM
</P>
<P>
   Two of the nation's largest airlines, Delta and Continental,
reported earnings that beat analysts' estimates, despite losing
millions of dollars to Hurricane Floyd. Delta also announced it
would pay $1.8 billion for outstanding shares of its regional
affiliate, Comair Holdings.
</P>
<P>
   LEVITT CALLS FOR WIDER DISCLOSURE
</P>
<P>
   Arthur Levitt, the SEC chairman, asked companies ``in the spirit
of fair play'' to let all investors take part in conference calls
about important information. He also criticized what he called a
``web of dysfunctional relationships'' among companies and
analysts, saying that brokerage firms often expect their analysts
``to act more like promoters and marketers than unbiased and
dispassionate analysts.''
</P>
<P>
   DELL SHARES TUMBLE ON CHIP WARNING
</P>
<P>
   Dell Computer shares tumbled $3.5625, to $37.75, in after-hours
trading after the company warned that rising memory chip prices
would hurt its third quarter earnings.
</P>
<P>
   FRANCE TELECOM IN $8 BILLION DEAL
</P>
<P>
   France Telecom, competing fiercely against its former partner,
Deutsche Telekom of Germany, agreed to pay $8 billion for a
controlling stake in a German mobile carrier.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-18-99 2140EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
