<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BANKS-BANKS </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 The Lure of Virtual Banks  &HT;     By Arthur M. Louis 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Internet-only banks have been going all-out lately to lure
customers with low fees and generous interest rates.
<P>
   If you feel that a bank must have marble floors, soaring pillars
and a ponderous stone facade to really be a bank, then perhaps the
online versions aren't for you.
</P>
<P>
   But if you already are comfortable dealing with virtual
financial institutions _ for example, if you have an account with a
stockbroker that operates strictly online _ then you might want to
give Internet-only banks a try. They offer some good deals.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've got lower overhead costs and better rates,'' notes
Robert Sterling, an analyst with Jupiter Communications in New
York. ``As a result, they are able to go after business more
aggressively than traditional banks.''
</P>
<P>
   Although they may be invisible, Internet-only banks are real
banks, with FDIC-insured checking and savings accounts. They let
you deposit and withdraw money, write checks and take out loans.
Most of them also let you pay most of your bills online.
</P>
<P>
   However, they can't meet all the banking needs of all consumers.
</P>
<P>
   If you need a safe-deposit box, you will have to continue to
maintain an account at a bricks-and-mortar bank. Nobody has figured
out how to store grandma's heirlooms in cyberspace.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, virtual banks don't have their own automated teller
machines _ though their customers can use ATMs maintained by other
financial institutions if they are willing to pay the standard fee
of $1 to $2 per transaction. (Some Internet-only banks _ among them
NetBank of Alpharetta, Ga. _ fully reimburse their customers for
ATM fees.)
</P>
<P>
   Virtual banks also can't accommodate you when you want to make
cash deposits or if you have special banking needs that require
prolonged, hands-on attention from a teller or branch manager.
</P>
<P>
   However, there is no good reason why you can't have more than
one bank account.
</P>
<P>
   Internet banking dates back about four years, but it has begun
to catch on only during the past year or so. About 4 percent of all
U.S. households do at least some of their banking on the Internet,
according to Jupiter Communications.
</P>
<P>
   The lion's share of Internet banking is done through online arms
of traditional banks, such as Bank of America and Wells Fargo.
</P>
<P>
   There are just about a half-dozen Internet-only banks, and their
name recognition isn't great yet. However, that could change
because their extremely low overhead allows them to offer highly
competitive checking, deposit and loan rates.
</P>
<P>
   Browse through the Internet bank Web sites, check out the deals,
select the bank that suits you best, and send in an application.
Most let you apply for an account online, though they then will
send you papers to fill out, sign and return.
</P>
<P>
   Once you establish an account, you will get a packet of checks,
if you open a checking account, and deposit slips and mailing
envelopes. While this may be the Internet Age, you still will have
to use snail mail to make deposits and transfer funds.
</P>
<P>
   Among the more prominent Internet-only banks are:
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; _Security First Network Bank &LR; , founded in 1995, is based in
Atlanta. It pays interest as high as 6 percent annually on checking
accounts and provides credit cards with a 3.9 percent introductory
interest rate for six months and 9.9 percent after that.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _WingspanBank.com &LR; , based in Delaware, opened for business in
the middle of this year. It offers three-month certificates of
deposit that pay an annual interest rate of 5.2 percent _ a full
percentage point above the national average.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _Net.Bank,  &LR; founded three years ago, doesn't charge fees on any
of its checking accounts, and it pays 3 percent annual interest on
even the tiniest checking balances.
</P>
<P>
   Net.Bank estimates that the average banking transaction on the
Internet costs it only 4 cents, compared with a typical cost of
$1.44 for a transaction done in person at a traditional bank.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are able to share much of that cost benefit with our
customers and still run a profitable banking operation,'' says D.R.
Grimes, Net.Bank's vice chairman and chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   Net.Bank is unusual among Internet-only banks because it is
entirely freestanding _ not owned by a larger financial
institution.
</P>
<P>
   WingspanBank.com, for example, is owned by Bank One Corp. of
Chicago, while Security First Network Bank is a subsidiary of the
Canadian Royal Bank Financial Group.
</P>
<P>
   Eric Hartz, Security's president, considers the affiliation with
a traditional bank helpful because it gives his bank credibility
among consumers. In addition, he says, Royal Bank provides Security
with ``knowledge of the industry and other synergistic benefits.''
</P>
<P>
   Apart from NetBank, there appear to be only two freestanding
Internet-only banks: CompuBank, based in Houston, and First
Internet Bank of Indiana, based in Indianapolis.
</P>
<P>
   Net.Bank went public in 1997, and it has more than 45,000
customers and revenues of around $30 million annually. It has
reported small profits in each of the latest five quarters.
</P>
<P>
   The other Internet-only banks don't publish any financial
details, either because they are privately held or because they are
subsidiaries of other institutions and therefore don't have to
break out their numbers.
</P>
<P>
   Whether an Internet bank is freestanding or a subsidiary
shouldn't make any practical difference to customers.
</P>
<P>
   What really matters is whether a customer can earn more on
deposits or save more on fees by using an Internet-only bank _
quite likely in most cases _ and whether the Internet-only bank
provides good service.
</P>
<P>
   Gomez Advisors (www.gomez.com), a Massachusetts firm that ranks
online financial institutions, publishes ratings of 58 banks that
do business online.
</P>
<P>
   The list includes both Internet-only banks and traditional banks
that let their customers do at least some of their banking online.
</P>
<P>
   The bank Web sites are scored on a scale from zero to 10
according to such criteria as ease of use, quality of customer
relations and quality of online resources.
</P>
<P>
   Gomez ranks Security First Network No.1 among all banks on the
Internet, giving it an overall score of 6.6. Net.Bank ranks third
at 6.13, CompuBank ninth at 5.75 and First Internet Bank of Indiana
10th at 5.69. WingspanBank.com, founded only a few months ago,
hasn't been rated yet.
</P>
<P>
   Among the traditional banks on the list, Wells Fargo ranks
second, Citibank fourth and Bank of America eighth.
</P>
<P>
   One useful feature of the Gomez site is a bulletin board where
customers sound off about their banks.
</P>
<P>
   A common theme is that it is hard to get satisfaction when
something goes wrong with your account. You can't walk down to the
nearest branch and grab the manager by the lapels.
</P>
<P>
   In one recent posting, a customer complained that he tried to
open an account with a virtual bank but that the bank lost $2,000
in money orders he sent as the initial deposit. Another customer
complained that his bank lets months go by without crediting him
with interest in his checking account.
</P>
<P>
   Bank executives say they are acutely aware of the potential for
service problems when bankers and customers never meet face to
face. They insist that they are doing all they can to prevent and
solve them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have asked our customer-service representatives to put
themselves in the customer's shoes,'' says Jeff Unkle, vice
president for corporate affairs with WingspanBank.com.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unlike a physical bank, we have 24-hour, seven-day access,
either by e-mail or you can pick up a phone and get a live person.
These people are going to work with you and make sure that whatever
the problem, it will be fixed in a way that is right for the
customer.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-18-99 2141EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991018.0462 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-18 21:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1040 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-MICROSOFT-MICROSOFT_S     10-18 0657
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-MICROSOFT </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Microsoft Hablara Espanol  By Tom Stein 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
Microsoft Corp. is trying to cash in on the latest Latin craze. No,
not salsa dancing: Spanish-language Internet portal sites.
<P>
   The software giant yesterday said it would join with Mexico's
largest phone company, Telefonos de Mexico (Telmex), to create a
new Web company that will deliver content and e-commerce services
to Spanish speakers across the Americas.
</P>
<P>
   The joint venture _ which will have offices in Argentina, Chile,
Colombia, Central America, Mexico, Venezuela and the United States
_ combines Microsoft's Internet software and services, notably its
Microsoft Network online service, with Telmex's telecommunications
infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
   The site will be called MSN Prodigy. It has no relationship to
the Prodigy online service. No launch date has been announced.
</P>
<P>
   Mauricio Santillan, vice president of Microsoft's Mexican
operations, said the portal will provide Spanish-speaking consumers
with Microsoft's Internet e-mail and instant messaging services, as
well as news and entertainment content and online search and
shopping capabilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many of the individual services we plan to offer are already
available to Spanish-speaking consumers,'' he said. ``But we plan
to offer these services in a more comprehensive and integrated
way.''
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft has its work cut out for it in Latin America. A slew
of Internet companies _ such as StarMedia Network, Yupi.com and
Quepasa.com, as well as Microsoft rivals America Online and Yahoo _
have already unveiled their own Spanish-language portals.
</P>
<P>
   ``The market is already saturated in terms of these general,
all-purpose Spanish-language sites,'' said Patrick Keane, an
analyst with Internet research firm Jupiter Communications. ``But
even though Microsoft is late to the game, you can never discount
them because of all the money and muscle they have.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Internet has been slow to catch on in Latin America.
Only 4.8 million Latinos, or 4 percent of all Internet users,
logged on last year, according to International Data Corp. And
Latin American e-commerce generated a paltry $167 million in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest obstacles in Latin America are high Internet access
costs and poor infrastructure. Only 1 one  &LR; in 10 Latinos has a
phone line, and fewer still own a computer.
</P>
<P>
   Those who have both a computer and a phone line must typically
pay about 10 times more than U.S. residents Americans &LR;   &LR; for
Internet access, largely due to shabby telecom networks in Latin
America.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft and others remain undeterred. They cite Latin
America's burgeoning population, which is almost double that of the
United States, as well as a drop in computer prices and increased
Internet access in public schools, as reasons for jumping into the
market. The number of Latinos using the Internet is expected to
grow to 19.1 million by 2003, according to IDC.
</P>
<P>
   Darlene Rios Drapkin, a business assistance manager at the
Spanish Speaking Unity Council in Oakland, said she is pleased to
see the rise of Spanish-language portals.
</P>
<P>
   ``These sites are useful to the community because they help
bridge the technological divide and let Latinos enter the
information age,'' she said. ``Up till now, there have mostly been
only English Web sites. That makes it more difficult for Spanish
speakers to get into computers.''
</P>
<P>
   Only about 3 percent of all Web pages are in Spanish, according
to StarMedia.
</P>
<P>
   But Rios Drapkin warned that the new Microsoft site may not
succeed if it focuses too heavily on online shopping features.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need Spanish sites that allow people to get more
informed,'' she said. ``I'm not sure Latinos are looking to engage
in e-commerce. For the most part, Latinos like the idea of personal
relationships and buying goods from people they know.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
