<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-18 21:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1042 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBN-METS-BRAVES-NYT &LR;      10-18 1140
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-BRAVES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEITER READY FOR HIS BIGGEST START  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By JUDY BATTISTA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Al Leiter looked perplexed and shook his head. The
pitcher who after each start remembers the nuance of almost every
pitch he throws, who can describe in minute detail the movement he
put on a ball, could not recall the only time he had pitched on
three days' rest.
</P>
<P>
   There is no doubt he will remember the second time.
</P>
<P>
   Leiter will start Game 6 of the National League Championship
Series on Tuesday night after having pitched last Friday in Game 3.
The Mets, down by 3-2 in the series after two astonishing come from
behind victories at Shea Stadium over the weekend, will be facing
Kevin Millwood and attempting to become the first team in baseball
history to rebound from an 0-3 start and win a four-of-seven-game
series.
</P>
<P>
   They are placing the ball in the hand of a pitcher who is known
to like extra rest.
</P>
<P>
   ``Guess what?'' said Manager Bobby Valentine. ``There was no
alternative.''
</P>
<P>
   There have been 116 best-of-seven series cpmbined in the League
Championship Series and the World Series and just 27 teams have won
four games in a row at any point in any series. The good news, if
you believe in this sort of karmic convergence, is that one of the
teams to do it was the 1969 Mets, who lost the first game of the
World Series and then beat Baltimore four in a row. They did that
after beating the Atlanta Braves in the League Championship Series.
</P>
<P>
   Only four teams have lost a series after being up 2-0, as the
Braves once were in this series. One of those teams was the 1996
Braves, who led the Yankees in the World Series 2-0, only to lose
the next four.
</P>
<P>
   But let the giddiness induced by the exhaustion of Sunday's
extra-innings spellbinder wear off and the fact remains that the
Mets have won just once at Turner Field in two seasons. Though
Leiter may have done just fine the last time he threw on short rest
_ it was April 17, 1994 while with Toronto when he went 6 2/3
innings against the Angels and allowed three runs on six hits with
four walks and eight strikeouts _ he was just 28 years old then and
he had just come out of spring training.
</P>
<P>
   Leiter has won some of the biggest games of the season for the
Mets. He stopped an eight-game losing streak by beating the Yankees
a day after three coaches were fired in June; he beat the Braves to
halt a seven-game dive last month that nearly cost the Mets a
playoff berth; he beat the Reds to secure the wild card spot two
weeks ago and he started the game in which the Mets clinched the
division series over the Diamondbacks nine days ago.
</P>
<P>
   But Leiter did not pitch one critical game, the final game of
the regular season against Pittsburgh, because Valentine had
reservations about using him with less rest than normal. Valentine
explained that when he had expanded the rotation to six pitchers
during the regular season, Leiter had told him he supported the
move because he felt better with extra rest.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, Valentine thought Leiter would have to pitch a lot
of innings against Pittsburgh. Of course, Leiter had thrown just
104 pitches, not an alarming amount, in the start before then, just
one more than he threw against Atlanta in Game 3 last Friday. No
matter. Valentine was persuaded by his coaches to bring Leiter back
for Game 6.
</P>
<P>
   Kenny Rogers, whose start this would have been, was not really
an option, Valentine said, because he did not feel confident using
Leiter out of the bullpen if Rogers got in trouble.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's going to empty the tank,'' Valentine said of Leiter. ``I
think it's a good situation. It's the right time to go on less
rest. The adrenaline will help you and there is no thought in the
back of his mind about his next start. This is a leave it all on
the table effort. You win and we play again and then he's rested
for the next time. It's one time when he can let it all hang out.''
</P>
<P>
   Leiter certainly didn't look the least bit tired after the team
arrived at its hotel in the early evening. An ebullient sort,
Leiter is a bundle of twitches and tugs on the mound and he
possesses the boundless energy of a kid at Little League. He does
not expect to know what he can do until he warms up before Game 6,
when he will determine just how much velocity his fastball has and
how much he will have to use his breaking pitches.
</P>
<P>
   He has scaled back his weightlifting in anticipation of this
start and he threw just 10 easy pitches in the bullpen during
Sunday's game, in case he was needed in relief. He knows he will
have to make adjustments to remain in a game against a team that
saw him so recently.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know what Chipper knows,'' Leiter said. ``I know what Brian
Jordan wants. There are probably a few innings where I will come up
with something different. I think the emotion of what the game
means will elevate me in other ways to feel 100 percent. And what's
100 percent? There's always something this time of year. The last
game, I threw five or six changeups, so even if the gun doesn't
show 90 miles per hour, I can still get hitters out. Let's face it,
every player should let it all hang out. You have four months to
rest.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mets have had eight winning streaks of four games or more
and in one of them _ where they won five in a row from the last
weekend of the season to the first game of the division series _
the Mets were essentially facing elimination every day. It was
during that stretch that Leiter pitched his gem, a complete game
two-hit shutout of the Reds in Cincinnati to clinch a Mets trip to
the post-season for the first time since 1988.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Piazza, who is almost certain to be the catcher despite a
host of nicks and bruises, has detected recently in Leiter a marked
increase in aggressiveness. After struggling for much of a season
that left him with a 13-12 record and a 4.23 earned run average,
Leiter has dropped his earned run average to 1.47 over his last
four starts.
</P>
<P>
   ``At times, I think he was pitching not to get hit,'' Piazza
said. ``You go through peaks and valleys when you become tentative
and you could see it. I don't know if it was nerves or
excitement.''
</P>
<P>
   When Leiter went home Friday night, after his error led to the
Atlanta's only run in a Mets loss that dropped them to 0-3 in the
series, he was not sure he'd have another start this season. ``I
was hoping,'' he said. Now, he has the biggest start. Again.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to believe something crazy is happening,'' he said.
``There's a lot of reasons we shouldn't be here and you wonder why
we're still here. We've achieved an awful lot to get to Game 6 and
that's comforting. But to say `We're this close to the World
Series' puts the slightest pressure on me and that doesn't help me
throw a nice slider to Gerald Williams.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
