<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CRAMMING-CRAMMING </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 PUC Charges Phone Firm With Cramming  &HT;     By Deborah Solomon 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
State consumer officials have charged a Louisiana phone company
with fraud, alleging the firm bilked Californians out of more than
$5.5 million through illegal charges placed on customers' monthly
phone bills.
<P>
   Telmatch Telecommunications, a long-distance carrier, is being
accused by officials at the state Public Utilities Commission of
``cramming'' _ a scam in which a company places fraudulent charges
on a customer's phone bill.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators with the PUC say Telmatch used a sweepstakes to
get as many as 135,000 Californians to sign up for a pricey calling
card service that included a $4.33 monthly fee.
</P>
<P>
   They want the company to return at least $5.5 million to
Californians who were billed by Telmatch and are asking the PUC to
bar the company from doing business in the state.
</P>
<P>
   PUC investigators, who began looking into allegations of fraud
after the commission was deluged with complaints from customers,
said this is one of the worst cases of cramming they have ever
seen.
</P>
<P>
   They said many customers were unaware they were being charged
for a calling card, and some racked up hundreds of dollars in bills
over time.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're really disturbed not only because of the high dollar
amounts involved, but the number of customers affected,'' said Bill
Schulte, head of the PUC's consumer services division.
</P>
<P>
   Attorneys for Telmatch insist the company did nothing wrong and
said all customers were informed about charges that would appear on
their monthly bills.
</P>
<P>
   David Brownstein, an attorney for Telmatch, said the company is
being attacked because it used a controversial sweepstakes method
to sign up customers. Complaints about sweepstakes marketing
prompted legislation earlier this year that bans using prize entry
forms to secure a written order for a service.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997 and 1998, Telmatch company  &LR; solicited customers by
getting them to enter a sweepstakes that offered a new car or
$25,000. Consumers filled out an entry form at fairs and shopping
malls and were entered into the drawing for a prize.
</P>
<P>
   But the forms also authorized Telmatch to send customers a
calling card that required customers make at least $4.06 per month
in calls. Even if customers did not use the card they were charged
the $4.06 minimum, plus a 27 cent monthly tax. The service also
included a one-time $4.96 activation fee.Calls made with the card
cost 25 cents per minute.
</P>
<P>
   The recurring charges were placed on a customer's monthly
Pacific Bell or GTE local phone bill by billing agents who were
collecting money for Telmatch. Those billing agents are Hold
Billing Services, Billing Concepts, USBI and ZPDI.
</P>
<P>
   PUC officials said most customers who were billed told
investigators they had never received or used a calling card and
many told the PUC they had never authorized a calling card service.
</P>
<P>
   Some said they had never filled out a sweepstakes entry form,
while others said they had entered a contest but did not know they
were authorizing a calling card service.
</P>
<P>
   ``These people were crammed,'' said Carol Dumond, an attorney at
the PUC who is leading the case against Telmatch. ``The sweepstakes
did not make it clear what people were signing up for. And when
they realized they were being billed, people who tried for months
to get those charges taken off their bills failed.''
</P>
<P>
   Dumond said Telmatch violated several state statutes, including
one that prohibits companies from signing customers to a service
without their consent. The commission staff has asked the PUC to
fine the company, force it to refund customers and revoke its
license to operate in the state.
</P>
<P>
   She pointed to Telmatch's records, which show that less than 1
percent of the income Telmatch collects comes from actual
long-distance calls. According to data presented to the PUC,
Telmatch collected an average of $206,035 in a single month, but
only $1,073 came from long-distance charges made using the card.
The rest of the money came from ``miscellaneous charges,''
including an average of $152,806 from the minimum use fee.
</P>
<P>
   Brownstein said that information data  &LR; is misleading because
many customers made calls with the card that amounted to less than
$4.06. Those calls are not included in the money collected for the
minimum use fee, he said.
</P>
<P>
   But after a series of hearings late last week, an administrative
law judge with the PUC issued an interim decision, saying, ``Good
cause exists to believe that a high portion of revenues ... result
from the unauthorized imposition of recurring monthly charges for a
calling card on California consumers' telephone bills.''
</P>
<P>
   Judge Joseph DeUlloa ordered the four billing companies to turn
over whatever funds they have collected for Telmatch. The money
would be kept in an escrow account and could be given back to
Californians if the PUC finds Telmatch guilty of cramming. The full
commission will vote on whether to approve DeUlloa's order at its
meeting Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Several customers who were billed by Telmatch said the
commission should force Telmatch to give refunds to consumers.
</P>
<P>
   Frank Mitchell, an official with the Los Angeles Board of
Education, said at least two Los Angeles schools, including an
elementary school, were charged for the calling card service two
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``We never authorized those charges,'' Mitchell said. ``It was
going on for a period of time and we were never reimbursed.''
</P>
<P>
   Other customers who filled out an entry form said the
sweepstakes box did not make it clear that they would have to pay
for a calling card. And once the charges started appearing,
customers said, it was hard getting them removed.
</P>
<P>
   Ivy Villegas-Borges, who lives in Hollister (San Benito County),
told investigators her husband entered to win a car at a swap meet
in San Jose but did not know there was any cost associated with it.
She said she had to call at least five different numbers to get the
charges removed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was disturbing that I had to spend a couple of hours taking
care of this problem,'' Villegas-Borges said.
</P>
<P>
   Brownstein said customers should have been aware of what the
sweepstakes entailed.
</P>
<P>
   ``After a customer signed up, before there was any billing, they
would receive a big packet of information via first-class mail that
clearly explained the charges and there was text saying if there's
a mistake, if you want out, here's an 800 number to call,''
Brownstein said. ``Anytime a consumer called the company and said
`I didn't know I signed up for service,' they got cancellations
without questions, without hassle.''
</P>
<P>
   Records filed with the PUC show that Telmatch's billing agents
have issued refunded to some customers who complained.
</P>
<P>
   One of the billing companies, Hold Billing Services, reported
collecting a total of $4,764,659 from Jan. 1, 1997, to April 22,
1999. During that same period, HBS issued refunds of $426,483 to
customers.
</P>
<P>
   Telmatch, which is still providing service in the state, has
since stopped billing its customers in California.
</P>
<P>
   This is not the first time Telmatch has run into problems.
</P>
<P>
   In February, Telmatch reached a settlement with North Carolina
over allegations of cramming related to the calling card program.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the settlement, Telmatch, which denied wrongdoing,
agreed to provide refunds to customers and change its marketing
practices so it's clear what consumers are agreeing to when they
sign up for a calling card program or other phone service.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
