<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONEYBAG-MONEYBAG </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 MONEYBAG/ARTHUR M. LOUIS  &HT;     Paying Tax on Market Gains 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
Q: I am a 16-year-old who has just received $1,000 to invest in the
stock market. Do minors have to pay taxes when they make money in
the stock market?
<P>
   A: Not necessarily. Whether you are a minor or a major, it
depends on how much money you earn.
</P>
<P>
   To take the simplest case first, let's assume that you have no
other income. In that case, says Internal Revenue Service spokesman
Jesse Weller, if your dividends and capital gains from stock
investments total no more than $700 for the year, then the income
is tax-free.
</P>
<P>
   If you can make more than $700 in one year on a $1,000
investment, then I would like you to manage my money.
</P>
<P>
   Things can become more complicated if you also earn money from,
say, a part-time job. This is known as earned income, as
distinguished from stock-market dividends and capital gains, which
are considered unearned income.
</P>
<P>
   If your earned and unearned income combined are greater than
$700, any portion of your unearned income that exceeds $250 would
be subject to tax.
</P>
<P>
   For more details, get a copy of IRS Publication 929, ``Tax Rules
for Children and Dependents.'' You can download it from the IRS Web
site at www.irs.gov, or order by telephone at (800) 829-3676.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; Taking IRA Distributions &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Q: I rolled over my traditional individual retirement account to a
Roth IRA in June 1998. Then early this year, I rolled half of the
Roth back into a traditional IRA. I reached age 701/2 on September
28. Does this mean I have to begin taking distributions from the
traditional IRA this year?
</P>
<P>
   A: The tax law requires you to begin taking distributions from
whatever traditional IRAs you hold by April of the year following
the year in which you reach age 701/2. Therefore, you don't have to
start taking distributions this year.
</P>
<P>
   As you may know, you are never required to take distributions
from a Roth IRA, no matter what your age. In fact, you can continue
to contribute to a Roth at age 701/2 and up.
</P>
<P>
   So, if you want to avoid taking distributions, you could roll
the balance of your traditional IRA into a Roth. You can do this
one more time under current tax rules. But if you try the switching
maneuver again after that, you may be subject to a tax penalty. I
say ``may'' because the IRS hasn't said what the rules will be
beyond 1999.
</P>
<P>
   You are one of many IRA holders who have switched back and forth
between Roths and traditional IRAs. This was particularly common
last year. The switchers were smart enough to realize that they
could save on taxes after the stock market took a sharp dip during
the late summer and early fall of 1998.
</P>
<P>
   That's because when they switched into Roths originally, they
were required to pay taxes on the value of the assets in their
traditional IRAs at that time. When the value of these assets
declined after the switch to the Roth, they were permitted to annul
the tax consequences of the switch by transferring the assets back
to traditional IRAs. If they then switched back to Roths again,
they were required to pay taxes only on the lower asset values
resulting from the stock-market decline.
</P>
<P>
   Switching to and fro became so hot and heavy last year that
financial institutions that sponsor IRAs raised Cain with the tax
authorities, complaining that the paperwork was overwhelming them.
The IRS then issued a temporary regulation restricting the number
of switches.
</P>
<P>
   We'll have to wait and see what they come up with next.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Tokyo Stock Quotes
</P>
<P>
   Q: How can I get quotes on Tokyo Stock Exchange stocks during
trading hours? Can it be done on the Internet?
</P>
<P>
   A: You can do it easily enough if you have access to the
proprietary terminal from Bloomberg News. Bloomberg also can tell
you just about anything else you need to know about investing, 24
hours a day, but you will have to pay upwards of $1,000 per month.
</P>
<P>
   A less-costly method, says Jim Bogin, portfolio manager of the
Matthews Japan Fund in San Francisco, is to go to the Yahoo Japan
Web page at www.yahoo.co.jp. However to proceed from there, you
will either have to know how to read Japanese characters or have
someone with you who can read them.
</P>
<P>
   By the way, the Japanese stock market is open from 5:30 p.m. to
11 p.m. Pacific Standard Time. Are you sure you want to stay up
that late?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Send questions about how to manage your money to
moneybag &LR; sfgate.com, or to Arthur M. Louis, Moneybag column, 901
Mission St., San Francisco, CA 94103.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
