<DOCNO> NYT19991018.0470 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-18 21:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1050 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-BRITISH-AEROSPACE-ART     10-18 1002
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRITISH-AEROSPACE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RIVALS' DEAL RAISES QUESTIONS ON FATE OF BRITISH AEROSPACE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Great Britain, Germany, France)  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By ALAN COWELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Ever since the end of the Cold War, Europe's fragmented
military industry has come to resemble a ponderous mating rite in
which the surprises came not so much from the urge to consolidate
as from the partners ticking the dance card.
</P>
<P>
   The newest, unexpected coupling came last week when
DaimlerChrysler AG of Germany and Aerospatiale Matra SA of France
agreed to merge. With annual sales of $22 billion, the cross-border
European behemoth would rank as the world's third-largest aerospace
company after Boeing Co. and Lockheed Martin Corp.
</P>
<P>
   The prospect of this new combination raised a tantalizing
question about the destiny of Europe's other military mammoth _
British Aerospace PLC, which, last January, sprang its own surprise
with a $12.7 billion takeover of British General Electric Co.'s
Marconi Electronics defense and missile business.(British General
Electric Co. is not linked to the U.S. company of the same name.)
</P>
<P>
   Simply put, the question was: Did the Franco-German deal leave
British Aerospace as the wallflower of European defense?
</P>
<P>
   Ask the company and the answer is simple enough. ``We don't
think we are isolated,'' said Mike Peters, a spokesman. ``This
further consolidates the industry in Europe and we welcome that. We
expect further moves in Europe.''
</P>
<P>
   Ask just about anyone else, though, and the responses are far
more complicated, reflecting the tangle of interests surrounding an
industry that, like the U.S. military business in the early 1990s,
is being pushed to consolidate by overcapacity and shrinking
markets.
</P>
<P>
   The European military business, moreover, is one in which
jealous governments have traditionally held sway as both political
masters and major customers. And it is laboring now under the
uneasy sense that its very fragmentation creates a huge obstacle to
the kind of military capability sought by those same governments to
build a military arm within the NATO alliance for the European
Union.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Kosovo conflict was a real wake-up call because it proved
that the fragmentation of the European industry was giving even
less capability than the spending would suggest,'' said John Dowdy,
a European aerospace and military specialist at the McKinsey
management consultancy here.
</P>
<P>
   British Aerospace, of course, would argue that it has been at
the forefront of efforts to draw Europe into a cohesive military
business. Its actions have not always been seen that way.
</P>
<P>
   Last January, when it announced its merger with Marconi,
creating an all-British leviathan with annual sales of more than
$20 billion, the deal scuppered negotiations with DaimlerChrysler
Aerospace to build a cross-border, European concern. And, in the
process, British Aerospace outbid a French contender, Thomson-CSF,
for Marconi.
</P>
<P>
   That, said Alex Ashbourne, a European military analyst with the
Center for European Reform, created ``fairly bad blood between the
U.K., France and Germany.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Ms. Ashbourne said, last week's shake-up in European
defense _ now essentially reduced to two big companies with sales
ranking them among the world's major players _ could well propel
British Aerospace to seek an American partner.
</P>
<P>
   That would mean, she said, that ``British Aerospace will bypass
some of the European consolidation to go trans-Atlantic.'' A likely
deal, she reckoned, was a combination of British Aerospace with
Boeing's McDonnell Douglas military aircraft division. British
Aerospace, said Peters, the company spokesman, already has joint
ventures with both Boeing and Lockheed, but he declined to comment
on talk of a merger, saying it was speculation.
</P>
<P>
   The European military industry is tangled in structure. ``It's
like a bowl of spaghetti,'' said Dowdy, the McKinsey analyst.
Companies are linked ``by program, by sector. All are related in
some way or other.''
</P>
<P>
   And Ms. Ashbourne said such are the existing ties between
various European contractors that British Aerospace ``can't really
afford'' to have the new Franco-German giant ``as an arch-enemy.''
</P>
<P>
   British Aerospace, for instance, is linked with Matra of France
in a sophisticated missiles project whose potential customers
include the four European air forces backing the Eurofighter
warplane _ Britain, Germany, Italy and Spain. And DaimlerChrysler
Aerospace of Germany, in turn, has a 43 percent stake in the
Eurofighter project.
</P>
<P>
   More troublesome still, British Aerospace builds the wings for
the European Airbus Industrie civilian airliner consortium in which
the newly created Franco-German aerospace giant now controls some
80 per cent, leaving British Aerospace with an uncomfortable
minority holding of 20 percent.
</P>
<P>
   And, to round the circle, Airbus is in ferocious competition
with Boeing, raising speculation that British Aerospace wants to
shed its stake in Airbus to make way for a trans-Atlantic deal with
Boeing focusing on military aircraft construction. That would
happen only after the Airbus consortium itself is reorganized as a
more conventional company _ a process that British Aerospace hopes
will accelerate as a result of last week's deal.
</P>
<P>
   For all the European defense contractors, the U.S. industry,
with its huge budgets and research projects, remains the ultimate
lure. U.S. military spending is double the entire European outlay
and U.S. military research is three times greater than the European
equivalent. British Aerospace has never made a secret of its desire
to deal with American companies from what it calls a position of
equality, as it made clear after the Marconi deal last January.
</P>
<P>
   Now, by some accounts, it is in a position to pursue U.S. or
European deals.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
