<HEADER>
A1057 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-FOREIGN-BRIEFS-NYT &LR;      10-18 0819
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOREIGN-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOREIGN NEWS IN BRIEF  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA: ZHIRINOVSKY CAN RUN
</P>
<P>
   The Central Election Commission ruled that candidates aligned
with the Russian nationalist Vladimir Zhirinovsky can take part in
the coming parliamentary elections. Zhirinovsky's Liberal
Democratic Party was disqualified after the commission ruled that
two leading party members had misrepresented their assets. To
satisfy the commission, Zhirinovsky formed a new bloc with two
minor parties and left some of his most contentious candidates off
the slate.
</P>
<P>
   FRANCE: MAYOR'S WIFE ON TRIAL
</P>
<P>
   The wife of the mayor of Paris went on trial on corruption
charges that have shaken City Hall and the members of President
Jacques Chirac's party, who run it. Xaviere Tiberi is charged with
receiving a bogus salary for writing a flimsy report on France's
relations with French-speaking nations for the government of the
Essonne region outside Paris. She has no expertise on the subject,
but was paid $35,000 for the 36-page report.
</P>
<P>
   ITALY: PREMIER PLEDGES CHANGES
</P>
<P>
   Seeking to bolster his center-left coalition and avert new
elections that could favor the opposition, Prime Minister Massimo
D'Alema pledged to make changes in his government. He was
responding to an appeal from the small Democrats Party, which asked
that D'Alema loosen his ties to a tiny and not always reliable
centrist faction and give the more ideologically compatible
Democrats a greater voice.
</P>
<P>
   SPAIN: CATALAN SQUEAKS BY
</P>
<P>
   Jordi Pujol, the Catalan nationalist who provides key support
for the minority government of Prime Minister Jose Maria Aznar,
narrowly won his sixth term as Catalan regional president. Pujol,
69, won the most seats, but the Socialist challenger, Pasqual
Maragall, a former mayor of Barcelona, got more votes. Aznar's
conservative Popular Party and the opposition Socialists both said
the results increased their chances in national elections due by
next year.
</P>
<P>
   CROATIA: EXTRADITION SUSPENDED
</P>
<P>
   Croatia suspended a Supreme Court decision allowing the
extradition of a Bosnian Croat to the war crimes tribunal in The
Hague, saying he was too sick for trial. Mladen Naletilic, 52, was
indicted on 17 counts of war crimes committed during the 1992-95
Bosnian war. Justice Minister Zvonimir Separovic said Naletilic's
extradition was postponed because of his circulatory problems.
</P>
<P>
   TURKEY: BARAK CEMENTS TIES
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Ehud Barak of Israel will visit Turkey next
Monday. The announced purpose is to inaugurate a housing complex
that Israelis have built for survivors of the earthquake that
devastated northwestern Turkey in August. It will also serve to
cement the growing friendship between Turkey and Israel.
</P>
<P>
   MIDDLE EAST
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL: MANDELA VISITS
</P>
<P>
   Nelson Mandela arrived on his first trip to Israel, a
conciliatory visit to a country that supported South Africa's
apartheid government. But now that Prime Minister Ehud Barak has
revived peace efforts, Mandela wants to show support, said a South
African rabbi with him.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL: 2ND RIGHTIST QUITS
</P>
<P>
   Hanan Porat, 55, who belonged to the two-man, far-right National
Union Party, followed its leader, Benny Begin, into retirement.
Porat, who spent 13 years in Parliament, said the legislature was
no longer an effective base for a pro-settlement advocate.
</P>
<P>
   THE AMERICAS
</P>
<P>
   CHILE: 4 OFFICERS IN PINOCHET PROTESTS
</P>
<P>
   The police arrested four military officers, including a colonel,
for taking part in protests marking the first anniversary of Gen.
Augusto Pinochet's arrest in London on a Spanish warrant. Military
officers are prohibited from getting involved in political affairs.
The officers were not identified.
</P>
<P>
   BRAZIL: BLAST KNOCKS OUT PHONES
</P>
<P>
   An explosion believed to have been caused by a bomb halted
telephone service for about 200,000 people in the southern state of
Rio Grande do Sul. Authorities said it was probably the work of
vandals.
</P>
<P>
   AFRICA
</P>
<P>
   BOTSWANA: PRESIDENT RE-ELECTED
</P>
<P>
   President Festus Mogae easily won re-election, leading the
ruling Botswana Democratic Party to its eighth election victory
since Botswana gained independence from Britain in 1966, officials
said. The governing party won enough seats _ 26 in the 40-seat
National Assembly _ to hold power for the next five years.
</P>
<P>
   NIGERIA: NEW CRACKDOWN
</P>
<P>
   The former heads of the Nigerian army and the police have been
arrested in a widening crackdown against members of the former
military government of Gen. Sani Abacha, a security official said.
The former army chief, Lt. Gen. Ishaya Bamaiyi, and the former
police inspector general, Ibrahim Coomassie, are under house
arrest, the official said. Their arrests follow the start of the
trial of Abacha's son for the murder of the wife of the late
opposition leader Moshood Abiola.
</P>
</TEXT>
