<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-18 22:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1059 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-BANKS-CONGRESS-NYT &LR;      10-18 0874
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BANKS-CONGRESS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAWMAKERS REJECT CLINTON CHANGES TO FINANCE-OVERHAUL BILL 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By STEPHEN LABATON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Lawmakers in the Senate and House Monday night
moved toward completion of a bill overhauling the nation's
financial system that failed to satisfy President Clinton's
concerns about adequately protecting consumers and minorities.
</P>
<P>
   The lawmakers were expected to work through the night on the
legislation in a joint House-Senate Conference Committee. While a
compromise between the Republicans and the White House was not out
of the question, the initial votes taken by early evening included
the rejection of an amendment, supported by Clinton's aides, that
would have strengthened the privacy rights of consumers.
</P>
<P>
   The amendments' defeat dimmed the prospects that Congress and
the White House would be able to reach an accommodation over the
measure
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials had said that Clinton would veto the
measure because it both failed to protect the privacy of consumers
of large financial conglomerates and it diluted the provisions of a
1977 law aimed at eradicating discrimination in lending.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation, different versions of which have already been
adopted by the House and the Senate, would repeal more than 60
years of laws that have restricted the cross-ownership of banks,
insurers and securities firms.
</P>
<P>
   For months Clinton has appeared to make the privacy and
discrimination issues a central policy focus of the debate over the
legislation. He has suggested that he viewed those issues as more
important than the issues that have driven the legislation and are
of greatest interest to the industry _ the repeal of the
Glass-Steagall Act of 1933 and other barriers to competition.
</P>
<P>
   In part, the administration's interest in the issues reflected
the view that Americans are more concerned with privacy and
discrimination than the nuances of bank regulation, even though
three powerful industries _ banks, securities and insurance _ have
lobbied heavily for the legislation, pouring more money into
lobbying and campaign contributions than at any time in modern
history.
</P>
<P>
   Monday evening the lawmakers defeated a measure, largely on
partisan lines, that was sponsored by Rep. Ed Markey, D- Mass.,
that would have permitted consumers to block their banks from
sharing private information with either affiliated companies like
insurers or brokerage houses or with third parties such as
telemarketers.
</P>
<P>
   Dozens of lobbyists from the financial services industry lined
the basement hallways of the Capitol building Monday afternoon as
the conference committee neared completion of its work. The
industry had uniformly lobbied against increasing the privacy
protections of consumers, maintaining that any barriers preventing
the affiliates of financial service conglomerates from sharing
customer information and marketing would defeat the purposes of
such combinatons.
</P>
<P>
   ``This amendment would place unworkable and inappropriate limits
on sharing of information between commonly owned affiliates,'' said
a letter sent to the lawmakers by trade groups for the securities,
insurance and banking industries. ``Our associations will find it
necessary to oppose any legislation'' that adopted such amendments,
adding that there were consumer benefits derived from affiliates
that shared customer information and were able to market more
services.
</P>
<P>
   Those contentions drew sharp criticism from the Democrats who
had supported the Markey proposal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've seen all the fat cat lobbyists in their $1,000 suits
outside looking very, very happy,'' said Rep. John Dingell, D-Mich.
``They're about to get everything they want.''
</P>
<P>
   In the end, the Markey measure failed on an 18-to-12 vote that
largely followed party lines.
</P>
<P>
   The vote suggested that partisan politics might play a stront,
and possibly fatal role in decideing the measure outcome.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the day, there was no sign of any significant
compromise by either the White House or the Republican leadership,
particularly in the Senate. But the lawmakers were not expected to
begin a series of important votes until late in the evening on the
Community Reinvestment Act of 1977, which prohibits discrimination
in lending. Those votes may ultimately determine the bill's fate.
</P>
<P>
   While the Community Reinvestment Act is not a significant issue
for most bankers, Sen. Phil Gramm has made it an issue in the
legislation. Gramm, the Texas Republican who heads the Senate
Banking Committee, has criticized the act for adding undue burdens
on many financial institutions.
</P>
<P>
   The measure before the conference committee was written by Gramm
and two other Republicans, Rep. Jim Leach of Iowa and Rep. Tom
Bliley of Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   For more than 85 percent of the nation's banks and savings
associations, it would decrease the number of times that their
lending records are reviewed to see if they have complied with the
Community Reinvestment Act _ to once every five years from once a
year.
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Gore, who has not generally spoken on the
legislation, issued a statement expressing his commitment ``to
insuring that CRA remains strong and is not weakened.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
