<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-18 22:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1062 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-TEXAS-COMPTROLLER-COX     10-18 0761
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-COMPTROLLER-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Rylander asked her agency's former chief lawyer to leave
 &HT;    By Mike Ward
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Two weeks after denying that an aide was
secretly tape-recording conversations, state Comptroller Carole
Keeton Rylander acknowledged Monday that her former chief lawyer
taped at least four conversations.
</P>
<P>
   Rylander asked Steven Koebele to leave after learning of the
secret recordings, her office said, and the tapes were all
destroyed.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats, who had been accused of playing dirty politics for
raising the issue, immediately denounced Rylander's turnabout.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Democratic Party Chairwoman Molly Beth Malcolm said
Monday's disclosure underscores ``a pattern of lies, deception and
a total disregard for the public's right to know what's going on in
government.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What we haven't seen are the tapes or transcripts or any of
the records we have requested under the law,'' she said. ``Carole
Keeton Rylander's credibility is so badly damaged now that it's
hard to believe anything she says.''
</P>
<P>
   Through her spokesman, Rylander made public 20 pages of
documents concerning the four conversations that Koebele taped
while he was general counsel, receipts for 35 tapes and two
recorders that he bought and a legal memo ruling that the tapes
could legally be discarded.
</P>
<P>
   The surprise admissions came after the Democratic Party two
weeks ago had sought copies of Koebele's tapes or transcripts under
Texas' open records law, charging that he abruptly resigned because
they caught him taping official conversations.
</P>
<P>
   After initially insisting ``the stories are not true,''
Rylander's spokesman, Mark Sanders, acknowledged Monday that the
taping was indeed the reason for Koebele's departure.
</P>
<P>
   ``The comptroller does not believe in and does not want any of
her employees tape-recording anything that should not be taped,''
Sanders said. ``Conversations should not have been taped.''
</P>
<P>
   Sanders said that in each of the four instances in which Koebele
recorded, the tapes were destroyed. In one instance, Sanders said,
he threw the tape away himself after Koebele gave it to him.
</P>
<P>
   Koebele was unavailable for comment.
</P>
<P>
   According to a confidential memo that Sanders said Koebele
wrote, one tape was of testimony last spring during sessions of the
Senate Finance Committee and the House Appropriations Committee.
</P>
<P>
   That tape was discarded in May after Koebele determined the
hearing was ``recorded by legislative staff and available on the
Internet,'' Sanders said.
</P>
<P>
   The memo states that Koebele also taped two phone conversations
_ one from a tipster about a ``very important and confidential
matter'' and the second from former Democratic state Rep. Hugo
Berlanga, now an Austin lobbyist. The Berlanga conversation was
taped, the memo says, ``to memorialize'' where Berlanga stood on an
amendment to a bill for which he was lobbying.
</P>
<P>
   Berlanga had gotten approval for the amendment by telling
legislative staffers that the comptroller's office agreed with it,
the memo says, even though ``no such agreement existed.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Berlanga would change his approval source depending upon
to whom he was talking,'' the memo states. ``Accordingly, the
general counsel taped a phone conversation between himself and Mr.
Berlanga to memorialize exactly where the approval resided.''
</P>
<P>
   Berlanga, in a statement released Monday, said he was not aware
his discussion with Koebele had been taped. The memo ``does not
accurately reflect my conversations,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   According to the memo, the fourth tape was made of a Sept. 17
meeting on an education initiative Rylander was launching.
Attending the meeting were staffers from her office and from the
offices of the governor, lieutenant governor, House speaker and
Texas Education Agency. Sanders said Koebele gave him the tape
after the meeting, and he discarded it. ``I didn't have any use for
it, and I thought it was improper. I'm not sure the others in the
meeting knew it was being taped,'' Sanders said.
</P>
<P>
   Sanders said Rylander's office initially denied the Democrats'
records request because they asked only for tapes or transcripts _
neither of which still exist.
</P>
<P>
   A subsequent request from the Democrats for related documents
about the tapings will be answered in coming days with the
documents Rylander made public Monday, Sanders said.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Ward writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
