u f BC-DELL-PROFITS-COX     10-18 0681
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DELL-PROFITS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Dell says higher memory prices will cut profits
 &HT;    By Jerry Mahoney
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Dell Computer Corp. warned analysts Monday that
another unexpected spike in memory chip prices may lower its
profits in its third quarter ending Oct. 29.
</P>
<P>
   In a conference call Monday after markets closed, the company
said suppliers of dynamic random access memory chips plan to raise
prices 25 percent on top of price hikes of more than 250 percent
earlier this year. DRAM chips are the most common type used in
computers.
</P>
<P>
   The latest increase will add about $75 to the cost of one-third
of the PCs Dell will ship this quarter, said Chief Financial
Officer Tom Meredith. ``With three weeks left, we can't really
manage our way around it without it affecting our (profit)
margins,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Dell shares closed down $1.50 to $41.31 1/4 in Nasdaq trading
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The memory-chip industry is cyclical, typically going from
periods of falling prices because of excess capacity to tight
supplies that prompt price increases.
</P>
<P>
   Prices for 124-megabyte modules ranged from $163 in October 1998
to $84 in July to $268 this month, according to Pathfinder
Research, a company that tracks the industry. The recent increase
is largely attributed to demand for more memory from consumers and
businesses rather than supply disruptions from the September
earthquake in Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
   While all PC makers will be affected by the latest increase,
Dell is likely to see its effects sooner because it has little
inventory of components, analysts said. While competitors such as
Compaq Computer Corp., Hewlett-Packard Inc. and IBM Corp. are still
moving toward Dell's low-inventory manufacturing system, they have
tens of thousands of finished machines in warehouses and on store
shelves.
</P>
<P>
   ``Compaq may have three or four weeks of inventory and then
Compaq has to deal with it,'' said Cody Acree of Frost Securities
in Dallas. ``Dell won't feel it worse, they'll feel it sooner.''
</P>
<P>
   Meredith and Dell said Monday's call didn't foreshadow a
disastrous third quarter for Dell. They, instead, conveyed
confidence in Dell's prospects, including for the fourth quarter.
``We're actually bullish there,'' Meredith said.
</P>
<P>
   The consensus of 28 analysts surveyed by First Call Corp. is
$0.20 a share for Dell's third quarter, whose results will be
reported Nov. 17. But that estimate is likely to come down today.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Dube of Wasserstein Pirella &AMP; Co. said he will take from
$0.02 to $0.05 off his estimate of $0.20 a share.
</P>
<P>
   Dell is part of the reason for the latest increase in DRAM
prices, he said. ``They have been rushing into the market, saying
'We will pay X, if you can get us X,' `` Dube said.
</P>
<P>
   Only 10 days ago, when Dell hosted its annual fall meeting with
Wall Street in Austin, Michael Dell indicated that the company
would be able to work its way through short-term supply disruptions
in a way that would not affect third-quarter earnings.
</P>
<P>
   But, he said, suppliers told the company last week that prices
would go up another 25 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The company's large enterprise customers are likely to absorb
the increases, Dell said, but consumers and small businesses may
respond by buying less memory or delaying purchases. That will slow
demand and, in time, should bring chip prices back down.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think memory vendors are probably pushing a little further
than this market, i.e. customers, are willing to bear,'' Dell said.
</P>
<P>
   Prices for other key components such as microprocessors from
Intel Corp. are expected to keep dropping and that will partially
cushion the DRAM spike. But PC makers probably will have to absorb
the rest because consumers and small businesses have become
accustomed to steadily declining prices.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think the PC market is in such a condition that
consumers have to pay more for anything,'' Acree said.
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Mahoney writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
