<HEADER>
A1064 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BBA-BOHLS-COLUMN-COX     10-18 0856
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-BOHLS-COLUMN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Blowhards are ruining a superb series
 &HT;    By Kirk Bohls
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ The results from Sunday night's game four of the
American League Championship Series are in, but you won't find all
of them in the box score.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Jose Offerman was never remotely tagged by Chuck
Knoblauch. Nomar Garciaparra was safe at first. And the Red Sox
fans are disgusting idiots.
</P>
<P>
   Not all of them. Not even a majority of them. But enough of them
_ dozens, according to the Boston media _ acted in such a
disgraceful, classless manner that the Yankees had to be taken off
the field for security reasons. Outraged Red Sox fans inexcusably
threw bottles, cans, magazines and all types of debris on the
field. Home plate umpire Al Clark made the correct decision _ one
of the few correct ones by the men in blue _ and the game was
stopped for eight minutes.
</P>
<P>
   I wish Clark had gone a step further and halted it for good.
Called it a forfeit and awarded the game to the Yankees. As
punishment? No, as precedent. Fans have to be taught a lesson
because it's obvious they won't learn it on their own.
</P>
<P>
   Did the umpires botch the two calls? Absolutely. But you'll find
no fan of instant replay here. Games are long enough already.
Sunday's Braves-Mets game lasted so long, it almost interfered with
February spring training. But I am in favor of umpire conferences
to get the critical calls right as they do in other sports. To
refuse to ask for help is the height of arrogance.
</P>
<P>
   But who would have guessed they'd be watching a baseball playoff
game and see an English soccer match break out?
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of atrocious umpiring, fan misbehavior is getting
totally and recklessly out of control. In Boston. In New York. In
Philadelphia, where they cheer the maiming of football players.
Fans know no restraint, no civility anymore. They think everyone's
fair game. One fan tried to grab Yankee right fielder Paul O'Neill
as he fielded a ball in the ninth inning Sunday. With the price of
admission comes the right to boo _ but not to commit mayhem.
</P>
<P>
   American fans jeer rabbit-eared Colin Montgomerie with profanity
at every turn at the Ryder Cup. Someone at Mile High Stadium hits
the Broncos' Dale Carter with a battery. A lunatic in Milwaukee
tries to play leapfrog with the Houston Astros' Bill Spiers. Mets
fans verbally rip Braves pitcher John Rocker, although he doesn't
do much to deter the verbal abuse.
</P>
<P>
   Taunting Chipper Jones by calling him ``Lar-ry, Lar-ry,'' his
given name, is good, clean, harmless fun. When Red Sox fans chant,
``Where's Roger?'' all night long, former Sox pitcher Clemens
deserves all the razzing he got. That's part of the legitimate
home-field advantage.
</P>
<P>
   But where does it end? Or does it? Is it going to take a serious
injury? Are we going to have to put huge barriers up separating the
fans from the players? Put in a moat? Do we put a cop in every
section? The Mets had to hire 500 extra, off-duty police officers
to patrol Shea Stadium. Add a $2 surcharge to every ticket for
security overhead? Make baseball players take the field wearing
helmets?
</P>
<P>
   Most fans are great. They give us the Lambeau Leap. They dress a
little weird in the Dawg Pound, but they're part of the color in a
too-often colorless NFL. The Cubs' bleacher creatures do nothing
more harmful than return visitors' home-run balls to the field. But
there are too many nut cases out there looking for an excuse to
swill beer and be destructive.
</P>
<P>
   The answer? Here's a few suggestions. Cut off all beer sales
before the seventh-inning stench. Or here's an idea: Don't sell
alcohol at all in stadiums, or is that a constitutional right?
Would sports die without the presence of alcohol? Eject offensive
fans who throw anything so much as wadded-up gum and revoke their
season tickets if they own such. Have ``real fans'' point out the
offenders who misbehave. Set up a mini-courthouse like the one in
Veterans Stadium in Philadelphia. Make the fines stiffer than their
drinks. Don't let television wag the dog any longer and schedule
more day games. Forfeit games when rowdy fans try to take over the
game.
</P>
<P>
   Yankees owner George Steinbrenner accused Red Sox Manager Jimy
Williams of inciting the crowd by arguing the call at first base.
Excuse me? Who incites more ill will than the Boss? What's Williams
supposed to do, take his licking and slink off? Sorry, George. He
has every right to crab at the umpires for blowing big calls the
same as Joe Torre does. If yelling at umps for wrong calls incited
riots, cantankerous Lou Piniella would have caused Seattle to tear
apart the old Kingdome long ago.
</P>
<P>
   Make no mistake about it. When unruly fans mistake ballparks for
a carnival sideshow and use players as targets, they threaten to
ruin one of the best-pitched, most dramatic baseball playoff series
since the 1986 World Series.
</P>
<P>
   Just think, Albert Belle isn't even playing.
</P>
<P>
   Kirk Bohls writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
