<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-TOURISM-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Successful promotions help state welcome more visitors
 &HT;    By Dave Doolittle
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Those people crowding into the Capitol and
stores in the San Marcos Outlet Mall are not just new residents to
Austin.
</P>
<P>
   Fueled by a strong economy, Texas has seen a steady increase in
tourism over the past five years. In Austin, the number of visitors
has risen to more than 16 million in 1998 from 14 million in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, venues such as the LBJ museum and the Lady Bird
Johnson Wildflower Center are enjoying increased attendance.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're seeing development in many different areas, with the new
airport, to roadways, to new restaurants, everything is continuing
to evolve,'' said Ric Luber, executive director of the Austin
Convention &AMP; Visitors Bureau. ``This not only benefits local
residents, but brings in out-of-town visitors as well.''
</P>
<P>
   Kevin McKinley and his wife, Stephanie, visiting Austin from
Baton Rouge, La., said they had been to Houston several times but
never to Austin.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were planning a trip to San Antonio and realized how close
Austin was,'' Kevin McKinley said. ``We're interested in seeing
some of the historical sights around Austin, like the Capitol
building and the University of Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   State officials say the increase in tourism generated more than
$34 billion for the Texas economy in 1998, while employing more
than 480,000 people statewide. It has grown to become the
third-largest industry in Texas, trailing only real estate and oil
and gas.
</P>
<P>
   ``The strong economy has made travel a possibility again,'' said
Stan Hodges of the Texas Department of Economic Development. ``By
1995, people had purchased items they couldn't before, like
refrigerators and cars, and then began to look at the feasibility
of travel.''
</P>
<P>
   State officials also started an advertising campaign with the
theme of ``Texas. It's like a whole other country.'' The television
and print ads, which give the state's 800 number and its Web site,
TravelTex.com., ran in all 50 states and contrasted Western images
with less well-known aspects of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``We tried to work with an image that was well-known around the
country, as well as showcase something like the different kinds of
music coming out of the state,'' Hodges said.
</P>
<P>
   Officials say that travel information requests from areas where
the ads ran were up 115 percent from the previous year and that
hits to the Web site increased during weeks the ads ran. Further
research shows that 71 percent of households that requested
information visited Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Texas will have spent an estimated $47 million between 1995 and
1999 trying to attract visitors from both the United States and
abroad, according to the Texas Department of Economic Development.
Tourists have spent more than $127 billion in the state since 1995,
with the totals increasing about $2 billion every year.
</P>
<P>
   Austin officials hope this trend continues.
</P>
<P>
   The city plans to bring in more visitors with the opening of the
Texas Historic Museum in 2001 and the opening of the Museum of
Art's new location at Fourth and Guadalupe streets, scheduled for
2002. The Museum of Art, which opened downtown in 1996, already has
close to 90,000 visitors a year.
</P>
<P>
   A survey done by an independent tourism research and consulting
company put the Alamo as the most visited attraction in Texas last
year. The outlet malls in San Marcos and the Capitol came in fourth
and fifth, respectively. Other Central Texas attractions that made
the top 30 include the Admiral Nimitz Museum in Fredericksburg, No.
25; Enchanted Rock, north of Fredericksburg, No. 26; and The LBJ
Library at the University of Texas, No. 28.
</P>
<P>
   In the coming years, state officials will be working to bring
more people to Texas. New print and television ads will focus on
wildlife and adventures, such as hiking and white-water rafting. In
addition, TravelTex.com will be highlighting activities such as
golf, theme parks and beaches.
</P>
<P>
   Texas is also trying to generate interest abroad. Last year, the
state had more than 1 million visitors from other countries. While
people from Mexico and Canada have historically made up the largest
portion of these visitors, the state will be running print ads in
countries where tourism has already shown to be strong, such as
Germany and Great Britain as well as Latin American countries.
</P>
<P>
   Austin will also be spending the next couple of years trying to
attract foreign travelers by inviting international meeting
planners to tour Austin and the Convention Center to show off the
city's potential for hosting meetings and conventions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd like people to see what a thriving center we are so
they'll bring their meetings here,'' said Gwen Spain, a spokeswoman
for the Austin Convention &AMP; Visitors Bureau.
</P>
<P>
   Dave Doolittle writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
