<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-18 22:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1069 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BBN-NLCS19-COX     10-18 1497
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-NLCS19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Braves appeared to be in cruise control before Mets won twice
 &HT;    By Curtis Bunn
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The Braves' National League Championship Series with
the New York Mets started a week ago at Turner Field as something
less than compelling. There was a little trash talk from both
sides, but nothing that hinted that it would ascend during an
enthralling weekend in Gotham into an epic matchup.
</P>
<P>
   If the first five games are an indication, tonight's Game 6 at
Turner Field promises head-shaking plots, subplots, excellence,
ineptitude, vulgarity and, most definitely, drama.
</P>
<P>
   Get plenty of rest because there's no telling when _ or how _
this one will end.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest surprise is that the series has yet to end. The Mets
continued to quiver at the mere sight of Turner Field, losing the
first two games here following a three-game sweep late in the
regular season. They returned home to fall behind 3-0. The Mets
were dead. Right? No team in baseball history had climbed out of
such a deep canyon. And yet, two out-and-out fascinating New York
victories later, we go into tonight not knowing what to expect.
</P>
<P>
   Let's relive the stimulating journey.
</P>
<P>
   _ Game 1: Oct. 12 at Turner Field
</P>
<P>
   Before 6,000 empty seats, the Braves executed a 4-2 victory on
the pitching of Greg Maddux that seemed to initiate burial
proceedings on the Mets. New York manager Bobby Valentine had
called his players ``ghosts'' after they rose from near elimination
to make the playoffs, but they seemed to be the same team that the
Braves backhanded in the regular season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Winning the first one makes it easier,'' said Braves catcher
Eddie Perez, whose home run in the sixth gave the Braves a 3-1
cushion.
</P>
<P>
   Perez's counterpart, Mike Piazza, played after missing two games
because of a bad reaction to a cortisone shot in his left thumb. He
swung the bat as if he was still in pain. But at least he had an
excuse. His teammates did not.
</P>
<P>
   It was encouraging to the Braves that John Rocker got the save.
The trash-talking originated on the Braves' side from Chipper
Jones, who told the Mets fans to switch to Yankee gear after the
Braves' last victory at Shea, and Rocker, who said he hated Mets
fans. He would soon find the feeling mutual.
</P>
<P>
   _ Game 2: Oct. 13 at Turner Field
</P>
<P>
   When Kenny Rogers realized he was in a playoff game, he turned
into the pitcher feared by doubting Mets fans. Ahead 2-0, he gave
up a pair of two-run home runs in the sixth inning. Ballgame.
</P>
<P>
   First Brian Jordan, then Perez, went deep, and the Braves'
pitchers shut it down for a 4-3 victory in front of plenty more
vacant seats. Afterward, Valentine pointed at himself as the
culprit, saying he should have taken out Rogers before Perez
unloaded.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was no reason to keep him in. It was absolutely the
wrong move,'' Valentine said.
</P>
<P>
   Dumb baseball was just as damaging to the Mets as Rogers' gopher
balls. Case in point: In the second inning, his team up 1-0,
shortstop Rey Ordonez inexplicably tried to bunt with runners on
first and third, no outs and the pitcher up next. Worse, he popped
out to first base.
</P>
<P>
   ``He did it on his own,'' Valentine said, trying hard to not
show his disgust. ``I was surprised.''
</P>
<P>
   Winning pitcher Kevin Millwood rated his stuff a C-minus, which
tells you either he's exceptionally hard on himself or that the
Mets' bats were made of concrete.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't do anything here,'' Edgardo Alfonzo said. ``I'm glad
to be going home.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Game 3: Friday at Shea Stadium
</P>
<P>
   There was not a seat to be had. The energy hung over the
building like a roof. Familiar baseball chants filled the air,
along with some nasty chants. During pregame introductions, the
fans berated every Braves player after his name was called, none
more so than Chipper Jones and Rocker, who doffed his cap.
</P>
<P>
   Throws by Rickey Henderson, not exactly known for his arm, from
left field gunned down Jones and sore-kneed Perez as they tried to
stretch singles into doubles. But that was about all Mets fans
could cheer as Tom Glavine threw darts on the black of the plate
and gave up nothing. His counterpart, Al Leiter was just as tough
on the mound.
</P>
<P>
   It was off the mound where Leiter had trouble. His throwing
error on a bunt led to an early 1-0 Braves' lead that held up when
Rocker closed matters.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guy can trash talk all he wants,'' Mets counterpart Turk
Wendell said, ``because he's backing it up.''
</P>
<P>
   No team has ever come back to win a post-season series after
losing the first three games. ``If we're thinking of the big
picture,'' Leiter said, ``that, 'Oh, my God, we have to win four in
a row,' we're not going to do that. We have to focus on the
smallest task at hand.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, that would be scoring a run.
</P>
<P>
   ``When was the last time a team won a game without scoring?''
Valentine said. ``I don't remember that one.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Game 4:
</P>
<P>
   Saturday at Shea Stadium
</P>
<P>
   The heretofore wild and raunchy crowd was decidedly tame. John
Smoltz, Mr. Series-Ender, was on the mound and the Mets hadn't
shown a glimpse of offense. Rocker and Jones still got the
business, but the fans were more wait-and-see than make-it-happen.
</P>
<P>
   Mets pitcher Rick Reed baffled hitters as long as Smoltz did,
and his effort inspired hope. John Olerud, who had been invisible,
showed up. He smoked a Smoltz pitch 405 feet for a bases-empty home
run in the sixth. Shea erupted.
</P>
<P>
   Two innings later, it was silent. Brian Jordan hit a home run
off Reed and Ryan Klesko followed suit for a 2-1 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Valentine pulled Reed, who said he thought as he headed for the
dugout ``the season was over.''
</P>
<P>
   Only, it was just beginning for the Mets.They worked the bases
loaded in the eighth with Olerud at the plate against Rocker, who
had not allowed him a hit in nine confrontations. Olerud hit a
bouncer up the middle that Ozzie Guillen got a glove on but did not
snare. Two runs scored to touch off a wild Mets celebration and a
3-2 victory.
</P>
<P>
   Headline in the next day's New York Post: ``Put A Cork In It,''
referring to the champagne the Braves expected to spray in victory.
</P>
<P>
   Lost in the hoopla was the fact that Valentine pulled Henderson
for Mora. The move incensed Henderson because it was not made
between innings and Henderson had to face the so-called indignity
of leaving his position.
</P>
<P>
   By the time the Mets poured into their clubhouse, Henderson was
showered, dressed and on his way out. That prompted Wendell to say
Henderson quit on the team.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Henderson took exception to that. He got an apology
from Valentine for not making the change earlier and then said
within earshot of a reporter, ``Tell Turk he can kiss my (butt). If
he's got something to say about it, tell him to meet me. I'll beat
his (butt).''
</P>
<P>
   Mets win a classic game and teammates feud. Just another day in
the big city.
</P>
<P>
   _ Game 5:
</P>
<P>
   Sunday at Shea Stadium
</P>
<P>
   The energy was back in the building. The game started on a
beautiful baseball day, first pitch at 4:11. By the time the last
at-bat was taken _ 5 hours, 46 minutes later, the longest playoff
game in history _ the teams had endured a consistent downpour and
used almost every player on the roster.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't remember most of the game,'' Valentine said.
</P>
<P>
   It was too much to remember. The Mets got two runs in the first
inning, the Braves two in the fourth. From there, it was mostly the
Braves blowing scoring opportunties. All told, they left an
NLCS-record 19 men on base.
</P>
<P>
   It was not until after the 14th-inning stretch _ the 15th, to be
exact _ that either side made a dent. Keith Lockhart doubled in a
run to put the Braves up 3-2.
</P>
<P>
   Shawon Dunston, leading off the Mets' 15th, battled reliever
Kevin McGlinchy by fouling off six full-count pitches before lining
a single to center.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tip your cap to him,'' Maddux said. ``A great at-bat.''
</P>
<P>
   McGlinchy, unable to find the plate, walked in the tying run
and, with the bases loaded, gave up Robin Ventura's first hit of
the series _ a blast over the wall in right-center that became a
single when Ventura was halted by his jubilant teammates between
first and second base. Final score: 7-3. No, make that 4-3.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's almost that 'Field of Dreams' thing, where the ball hits
the lights, everything explodes and it starts pouring,'' Mets
pitcher Orel Hershiser said. ``This is unbelievable.''
</P>
<P>
   Who has the advantage now? Chipper Jones said it might be in
someone else's hands.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe it's fate,'' he said, ``that this is the way it's meant
to be. We've been in positions before where we thought we should
win and we were either watching some other team in the World Series
or watching someone else's parade. If the baseball gods aren't on
your side, it ain't going to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Curtis Bunn writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
