<SLUG> BC-COLLINS-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: ONE HILLARY IS ENOUGH 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By GAIL COLLINS    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hillary Clinton has a new mortgage, thank heavens. The New York
Senate race doesn't need another controversy about the Clinton
family finances. Things are complicated enough right now, what with
the debate about elephant dung in the arts and the ongoing
investigation into exactly what Rudy Giuliani thinks about raising
the minimum wage.
</P>
<P>
   The Clintons defused the mortgage issue when they dropped the
idea of having a rich friend guarantee their loan. Now they're
going to pay 7.5 percent interest on a 30-year adjustable mortgage,
just as you or I would, should you or I ever suddenly get a yen to
own a $1.7 million, 11-room, fully loaded Colonial in an upscale
suburb. This is a pretty fancy pad for a Senate candidate.
Perfectly reasonable for a retiring president and first lady, but
Mrs. Clinton is planning on occupying two roles throughout the year
2000.
</P>
<P>
   Let's face it, that's one role too many.
</P>
<P>
   New York has more experience than most places in what happens
when a woman in politics fails to draw a clear line between her
identity as a candidate and her relationship to a politically
connected spouse.
</P>
<P>
   Geraldine Ferraro never seemed to grasp why it was a bad idea
for her to run for the Senate while serving as an officer in her
husband's real estate business. As a result, she wound up trying to
explain away the $340,000 a pornography publisher paid to lease
space in one of the family buildings. (Memorably, Ferraro said she
and her husband had been pursuing a strategy of ``raising the rent
in order to get them out.'')
</P>
<P>
   Jeanine Pirro, recently the New York Republican Party's Woman
Most Likely to Succeed, is trying to extricate herself from the
problems of her husband, Albert, who was indicted last spring for
tax evasion, despite his attempt to avoid prosecution by secretly
taping conversations with his accountant, who also happens to be
his brother. Ms. Pirro has attempted to portray herself as no more
sophisticated about family finances than Beaver Cleaver's mom, an
effort that might be easier if she were not Westchester district
attorney.
</P>
<P>
   We've learned at least one clear lesson from all this. If you're
a candidate for elected office, you can't rely on a spouse's money
or political muscle to propel your career, and then distance
yourself when it suits you. (``I don't make the money. I'm in
public service,'' said Ms. Pirro, who drove around in a Mercedes
that her husband is now charged with deducting as a business
expense.)
</P>
<P>
   Hillary Clinton crossed that line when her husband's top
fund-raiser agreed to guarantee the family mortgage. Now she's
unraveled that conflict. But she still wants to be able to travel
to Israel as first lady, tell the Jewish voters of New York what
she and the prime minister talked about, and then reserve the right
to distance herself if the administration takes a position on the
Mideast that's unpopular here. That's too many identities for the
public to juggle, and it would take a White House far more
coordinated than this one to keep things straight.
</P>
<P>
   If Mrs. Clinton wants to run for the Senate, she should cut her
first lady duties to the minimum. The line isn't as hard to draw as
it might seem. You stick to jobs with a low degree of public
interest and high potential for boredom. Feel free to host dinners
for visiting dignitaries, especially those from countries not
widely represented in the New York electorate. Skip the trips
abroad. Keep a low profile at Christmas-tree-lighting time.
</P>
<P>
   It's surprising how often the nation has managed to get along
without a first lady. Thomas Jefferson and Andrew Jackson made the
Top Ten Presidents list as widowers. James Monroe presided over the
Era of Good Feeling while his wife stayed in her room, sulking
because she'd been forced to move to Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly half of our chief executives have governed without the
assistance of the kind of on-the-go helpmeet we've been primed to
expect as part of the presidential package. Some of the absent
first ladies were ill, others kept to themselves out of shyness or
depression.
</P>
<P>
   Americans saw very little of Ida McKinley, a rather gloomy
invalid who was subject to fits. When Mrs. McKinley had a spell
during White House dinners, her husband covered her head with a
napkin. Chances are, the president's guests weren't all that
disappointed when he arrived at the table alone.
</P>
<P>
   The Clintons' challenge is a bit more upbeat: Downsize Hillary's
Washington role to a cameo appearance, and find some furniture to
put in all those rooms in Chappaqua.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-18-99 2211EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991018.0489 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-18 22:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1074 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-ALBRIGHT-AFRICA-1STLD     10-18 1449
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALBRIGHT-AFRICA-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-550&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALBRIGHT BRINGS MESSAGE OF PEACE AND AID TO RAVAGED SIERRA LEONE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (EDS: Adds new 16th, 17th grafs. Picks up previous, ... Albright's
visit ...)  (ART ADV: A map is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling
1-888-603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(th) 
 By NORIMITSU ONISHI    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   FREETOWN, Sierra Leone _ Secretary of State Madeleine Albright
cuddled a 3-year-old girl whose arm had been hacked off by rebels,
then met with rebel leaders responsible for thousands of such
mutilations in this country's eight-year civil war, urging them
Monday to stick to a fragile peace agreement.
</P>
<P>
   On the first day of a weeklong visit to Africa, Albright said
that to insure lasting peace in this small West African nation, it
was critical that the rebel leader, Foday Sankoh, take part in the
effort. Sankoh was imprisoned and sentenced to death, but he was
later freed and will occupy a high government position under a
peace deal that granted amnesty to the rebel fighters.
</P>
<P>
   Albright pointedly avoided being photographed with Sankoh _
meeting him behind closed doors and providing no photo
opportunities _ and emphasized the importance of eventually
punishing war criminals.
</P>
<P>
   The United States helped broker the peace deal, signed in July
in Lome, Togo, between the government of President Ahmad Tejan
Kabbah and Sankoh's Revolutionary United Front. But the agreement
has been criticized by human rights groups as too lenient to those
responsible for some of the worst atrocities seen in Africa.
</P>
<P>
   At a camp housing 516 men, women and children _ run by Doctors
Without Borders, the international relief organization that was
awarded the Nobel Peace Prize last week _ Albright walked around a
courtyard on red earth baked hard by a burning sun.
</P>
<P>
   She met long lines of people, most of whose arms had been
chopped off by machete-wielding rebels. ``It's hard to reach out a
hand to shake hands with somebody and know they do not have a
hand,'' she said later.
</P>
<P>
   Albright picked up a 3-year-old girl named Mamuna, who was
dressed in a red jumper and whose right arm had been taken off at
the elbow.
</P>
<P>
   Mutari Jalo, who was missing his right arm and who was acting as
the camp's informal chairman, told her, ``We know the government of
America will help us to alleviate our suffering.''
</P>
<P>
   In her remarks Monday, Albright said, ``Ultimately, the only way
that reconciliation really can come is if people have a sense that
justice has been done and those who have perpetrated the terrible
crimes are punished individually.''
</P>
<P>
   But she emphasized that peace must first become entrenched in
Sierra Leone, where carrying out the peace accord has been delayed
by bickering among rebel leaders and where 45,000 fighters have yet
to disarm. Sankoh has just returned from visiting a rebel
stronghold to encourage his men to disarm.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sankoh is delivering the right message,'' Albright said at a
news conference before meeting with him, ``and I hope very much he
will continue to intensify his efforts to insure full adherence to
the Lome accord. The atrocities must end, and abductees must be
released. The peace must be sustained.''
</P>
<P>
   Here in Sierra Leone's capital, she met Monday with Kabbah and
pledged $55 million in aid _ the only aid announcement made so far
on her trip. Most of it is for food, education and efforts to
control the illegal traffic in diamonds, which fueled the civil war
and has drawn in neighboring Liberia and Burkina Faso at various
points.
</P>
<P>
   She also promised $65 million in debt forgiveness, conditioned
on Sierra Leone's agreement to carry out an International Monetary
Fund economic program.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Part of the American interest in helping Sierra Leone is related
to the Clinton administration's effort to find ways to distinguish
between legitimate diamond sales and those that finance strife in
Africa.
</P>
<P>
   The rebels in Sierra Leone, as well as those in Angola and
Congo, have used diamond sales to prolong their conflicts. The war
in Sierra Leone appears to have drawn more attention from the
United States because of the nature of the atrocities against
civilians.
</P>
<P>
   Albright's visit to Africa is also viewed by the administration
as an answer to criticism that Washington was prepared to intervene
on humanitarian grounds in Kosovo and more recently to give some
support in East Timor but has not shown such interest in Africa.
</P>
<P>
   Of all the conflicts in Africa, the situation in Sierra Leone
appeared to be one in which a visit from Albright could shine the
brightest spotlight, administration officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Albright's visit to Africa, her third as secretary of state,
began with a brief stop in Guinea. After her visit to Sierra Leone,
Albright arrived on Monday night in Mali, whose successful
transition from dictatorship to democracy has made it a model in an
unstable region. She was headed next to Nigeria, which recently
ended nearly 16 years of military rule.
</P>
<P>
   She is also to visit Tanzania and Kenya, in East Africa, where
the American embassies were bombed in 1998. On Thursday in
Tanzania, she will attend the state funeral for Julius Nyerere,
that country's founding father.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, at the American ambassador's residence here, which
overlooks the green hills and blue bays of this seaside town,
Albright met with Sankoh and another rebel leader, Johnny Paul
Koroma.
</P>
<P>
   Her visit came two weeks after Sankoh's return to Sierra Leone.
His extended stay in Togo, after the peace agreement was signed
there in July, delayed carrying it out. The rebels were supposed to
start disarming in August, and the process is finally expected to
start this week.
</P>
<P>
   Since his return, Sankoh has said that people must forget the
past and move on. He has yet to visit the war amputees' camp, which
has become an obligatory stop for visiting dignitaries, including
U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, Koroma, who led another faction, paid a
surprise visit to the camp and, breaking down in tears, pleaded for
forgiveness. The amputees _ who like most ordinary Sierra Leoneans
have expressed grudging support for the peace deal _ jeered at him.
</P>
<P>
   Under the peace agreement, Sankoh will become the chairman of a
commission overseeing the country's mineral resources, with the
rank of vice president. Several of his men will occupy other
government positions in a power-sharing arrangement.
</P>
<P>
   Sankoh, a cashiered army corporal and former commercial
photographer, began the civil war in 1991, saying that the
country's corrupt rulers had enriched themselves on diamonds while
leaving Sierra Leone one of the poorest countries in the world. He
attracted recruits in rural areas and for many years was rarely
seen as he waged war from the bush.
</P>
<P>
   But over the years, his message of economic exploitation was
lost and his fighters became known for the atrocities they
committed.
</P>
<P>
   After Kabbah was elected president in 1996, the rebels began
slicing off civilians' hands _ in retribution, the rebels often
said, for having voted for Kabbah by putting a thumbprint next to
his name on the ballot.
</P>
<P>
   The number of deaths during the war is thought to be in the tens
of thousands and the number of amputations in the thousands, but
there are no accurate figures.
</P>
<P>
   Albright's visit to Africa is her first since President
Clinton's 12-day trip in March 1998. His visit _ with his pledge of
more American interest in the continent, his talk of an African
renaissance and a commitment to integrate African nations in the
international community _ drew enormous attention to Africa.
</P>
<P>
   But since then, many Africans and American critics of policy
toward Africa have said the United States has failed to follow
through.
</P>
<P>
   As the United States and the rest of the West quickly spent
billions of dollars in conflicts in Kosovo and East Timor, many of
the critics have pointed out that Western countries have done
comparatively little to intervene in civil wars in Sierra Leone,
Congo, Angola and Sudan and in the war between Ethiopia and Eritrea
_ all extremely lethal conflicts.
</P>
<P>
   ``The U.S. has played a leading role in the international
community in assisting the peace process in Sierra Leone,'' the New
York-based Human Rights Watch wrote in a letter to Albright last
week.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, the letter continued, the commitment to justice shown to
Sierra Leone falls far short of that shown in Kosovo and East
Timor, ``even though the atrocities committed in Sierra Leone match
or surpass anything seen in these crises.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
