<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-18 22:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1076 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-FLEE-BAILEY-COX     10-18 0986
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLEE-BAILEY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bailey presses legal, ethics battles over right to keep
attorney's fees
 &HT;    By Jenny Staletovich
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ORLANDO, Fla. _ Once a legal giant whose client roster read like
a civics lesson _ he counted Patty Hearst, Sam Sheppard and the
Boston Strangler among his best known besides himself_ F. Lee
Bailey is mired these days in battles over how he earns his legal
fees.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, while he fought a contempt charge over a $2 million
fee in a federal case here, the Florida Bar filed a seven-count
complaint of ethics violations in Tallahassee.
</P>
<P>
   And still, Bailey remains unfazed by the assaults, arguing that
federal prosecutors in Orlando are going after what's rightfully
his while the Bar is ``cranking up again,'' as if it exists to
annoy him. Both cases stem from Bailey obtaining multimillion
dollar fees from clients who were ultimately convicted and had to
surrender mansions, boats and millions in cash and stock obtained
through their crimes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once (a judge) looks, he will see there was no breach of
ethics,'' Bailey said of the Bar complaint. As for the Orlando
case, he said, ``every nickel is right in there.''
</P>
<P>
   The Orlando case stems from Bailey's representation of
infomercial king William J. McCorkle, who bilked hundreds in a
get-rich-quick scheme that involved buying foreclosed property. The
former stripper and his wife were sentenced last year to 24 years
in prison and ordered to forfeit $10.6 million in assets, including
$7.1 million in Cayman Islands accounts.
</P>
<P>
   When Bailey turned over all but $2 million, which he said
covered his legal fee, the government threatened to hold him in
contempt and send him to jail. Again.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, Bailey spent 44 days in jail after refusing to give up
stock valued at $17 million he said he earned representing a French
drug dealer in Gainesville. That case, in turn, prompted the
lengthy Bar complaint.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, Bailey's attorney, Richard Lubin, argued that because
Bailey had already spent the McCorkle money, he could neither be
held in contempt or be forced to repay it.
</P>
<P>
   While it may not sound logical, Lubin said the law does not
allow the government to order an attorney to substitute other
assets for the money in question.
</P>
<P>
   Puzzled, U.S. Magistrate Judge James Glazebrook asked a
question: If a bank robber used tainted money stained with the
bank's dye to pay his attorney, why can't the government demand
back an equal amount?
</P>
<P>
   ``I say it has to be the very same dollar bill, or traceable,''
Lubin argued. ``If the red dye money (from the bank robbery) came
to me and I bought a car and you could trace the car and I refused
to turn the car over, then you could hold me in contempt,'' he
said. But if no trace is made, the money cannot be returned.
</P>
<P>
   Lubin's first witness was a former IRS agent who traced Bailey's
legitimate spending from the Cayman accounts. Bailey said he also
plans to testify.
</P>
<P>
   Lubin also warned that the Bailey conflict points to a larger
issue involving the Sixth Amendment's guarantee of a citizen's
right to legal counsel.
</P>
<P>
   ``What it's ultimately going to mean is just a court-appointed
system,'' he said afterward of government attempts to seize
attorney fees. ``It's a serious issue. There's not enough money now
for public defenders. Court-appointed attorneys are incapable of
functioning on a competent level with the amount they get paid.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Bailey: ``The government is trying to drive every private
practitioner out, and they'll have no one to beat up but public
defenders.''
</P>
<P>
   But Assistant U.S. Attorney Marie DeMarco has argued Bailey knew
the money was illegally obtained and Monday said his keeping the
money was the same as stealing it from the government.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you steal the money, you have to pay it back. It's really
that simple,'' she said. ``In this case we have a lawyer who did
know from the very beginning ... that the money was obtained
through fraud ... and he sent it (to the Cayman Islands) for the
purposes of avoiding seizure. We have a lawyer in the exact same
position as the lawyer who takes the red dye money.''
</P>
<P>
   DeMarco pointed out the McCorkle case parallels Bailey's other
contentious battle _ the 1994 Gainesville case involving drug
dealer Claude Duboc _ and submitted transcripts of hearings as
evidence of his behavior.
</P>
<P>
   In that case. Bailey and federal prosecutors agreed that he
would hold $3 million in pharmaceutical stock to cover his fee and
maintain Duboc's property until the government, which had seized
it, sold it. When the stock skyrocketed to $17 million after the
company made a break-through in the treatment of AIDS, the
government demanded it back.
</P>
<P>
   In May a federal appeals court upheld the government's right to
the money and Bailey dropped the fight. But he is still arguing for
fees in federal claims court in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   In its complaint, the Bar alleged Bailey used the money for
personal and business expenses not connected to the case, mingled
the money with his own, misappropriated at least $309,861 and
continued to misuse the money even after the court ordered him to
stop. Bar investigators also said Bailey lied under oath,
improperly communicated with the judge, repeated confidential
communication with his client and should have realized the obvious
conflict his taking the money created between his and his Duboc's
interests.
</P>
<P>
   Florida Supreme Court justices will now assign the complaint to
a judge, probably in Fort Myers, for a hearing. The judge would
recommend sanctions _ or no punishment _ to the Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the McCorkle case continues today and is expected to
wrap up Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Jenny Staletovich writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm
Beach, Fla. E-mail: jennystaletovich(AT)pbpost.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
