<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-18 22:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1077 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-NISSAN-CUTBACK-1STLD-     10-18 1296
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NISSAN-CUTBACK-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAJOR OVERHAUL AT NISSAN WILL INCLUDE DEEP CUTS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS to replace 5th and 6th grafs with new grafs containing
corrected information on job losses in U.S. Rewrites 2nd graf
following 2nd optional trim to be more precise.)  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By STEPHANIE STROM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ Hobbled by years of losses and high debts, Nissan Motor
Co. surprised Japan and the auto industry Monday with details of a
radical overhaul plan that will make unexpectedly deep cuts at the
company, Japan's No. 3 automaker, and reverberate more broadly
through the economy.
</P>
<P>
   Under the three-year plan, presented by Nissan's aggressive new
chief operating officer, Carlos Ghosn, three plants will be closed
and 21,000 jobs eliminated, most of them in Japan. Nissan will also
halve its supplier base and close 10 percent of its dealerships,
with the objective of returning to profitability in the next fiscal
year, starting April 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``I understand that a lot of people at Nissan will feel like
orphans in this plan,'' Ghosn said at a briefing for reporters and
securities analysts, where the details were released. ``But we have
no choice, and the fact that we have no choice is the strength of
our plan.''
</P>
<P>
   He was echoed by Yoshikazu Hanawa, Nissan's president. ``There
is no other alternative for us,'' Hanawa said. ``In order for us to
survive, we must implement this revival plan.''
</P>
<P>
   Jason Vines, a Nissan spokesman, said that 1,400 jobs in the
United States would be eliminated through attrition and the sale of
divisions as part of the 21,000-person reduction in employment.
</P>
<P>
   Nissan plans to sell a 530-employee forklift division in
Illinois and a 380-person computer operations unit, he said, adding
that the remaining 490 jobs would disappear through attrition among
Nissan's 11,000 American employees, with no layoffs planned.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The scope of the plan took securities analysts and executives
from other car companies by surprise, although its general
parameters were well known.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as the numbers are concerned, it's even better than
expected,'' said Koji Endo, an analyst at Schroders Japan Ltd.,
speaking presumably of Nissan's aim of a return to profitability.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In some respects, the plan is like other corporate
reorganizations in Japan these days, but the magnitude of Nissan's
cuts makes it likely that its effects will be felt more strongly
than most others. About 500 parts and materials suppliers, for
instance, will lose Nissan's business, and the communities affected
by plant closings, still a rarity in Japan, could feel the most
acute impact.
</P>
<P>
   Nissan also plans to sell most of the shares it holds in
companies that have been linked through loans and
cross-shareholding, reducing its obligations to them as well as the
impact of stock-market fluctuations on its balance sheet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Very few of those companies we consider as indispensable,''
Ghosn said. ``Over the next three years, a lot of these companies
will be out of the reach of Nissan.''
</P>
<P>
   How those businesses and communities respond to the challenge
created by Nissan Monday may in turn help shape the future of other
Japanese businesses. In the same way that closing three of Nissan's
plants is aimed at improving the productivity of its remaining
factories, a supplier forced to become more competitive might be
expected to become a healthier business.
</P>
<P>
   Ghosn and Hanawa acknowledged that their plan is nothing until
it is executed. ``Ninety-five percent of the work remains,'' Hanawa
said. ``It is not going to be an easy process. It will be a very
difficult one.''
</P>
<P>
   It will also be costly to Nissan. The company will take a 200
billion yen accounting charge, or about $1.9 billion, to cover the
costs of the restructuring in the current fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
   Ghosn said the year's losses would be much larger than the 60
billion yen the company had forecast in May. In addition, Nissan's
liabilities will swell this year as changes in accounting rules
force it to include previously unrecognized pension and other
costs.
</P>
<P>
   The financial pain will not be limited to Nissan, either.
Renault SA, the French carmaker that purchased a 36.8 percent stake
in Nissan in March and installed Ghosn and several other foreign
executives to help lead a turnaround, said Monday that it would
take a $317 million accounting charge related to its Japanese
partner's restructuring.
</P>
<P>
   But the plan's costs in human terms and in corporate pride are
expected to be even greater. Traditional labor practices and tough
labor laws make layoffs as they are known in the United States
virtually impossible. ``The plan is roughly what the doctor
ordered,'' said Jay Woodworth, an independent automotive analyst.
``Now I hope Mr. Ghosn has all his ducks in a row, and in
particular has Nissan's labor union on board.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, while the rest of his speech was straightforward, Ghosn
finessed the part on job reductions, using the same cautious
language employed by Japanese executives forced to broach that
uncomfortable subject. He said Nissan, which has a global work
force of around 148,000, plans to prune its work force through
attrition, the increased use of part-time employees, spinoffs and
``early retirement,'' a euphemism in Japan for layoffs sweetened by
generous severance packages.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Endo of Schroders said he had spoken with the chairman of the
company's union not long ago, who told him the union would be
unhappy with any job cuts of more than 3,000. While it is almost
unheard of for Japanese unions to strike, their cooperation is
considered critical to the plan's success.
</P>
<P>
   Ghosn and Hanawa played down such concerns Monday. ``Already in
the past we have had reallocations of personnel,'' Hanawa said.
``This won't be a first-time experience.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In other respects, the plan was blunt and direct. ``The key
facts and figures about Nissan point to a reality: Nissan is in bad
shape,'' Ghosn said.
</P>
<P>
   The Japanese automaker's market share has dropped to 4.9 percent
worldwide from 6.6 percent in 1991. It has turned a profit in only
one of the last seven years, and its debts, excluding potential
liabilities related to leasing cars, are estimated at $12.6 billion
by the close of this fiscal year, at the end of March 2000.
</P>
<P>
   The restructuring plan presents a litany of cuts that go beyond
plants and workers: Purchasing costs, which now eat up 58 percent
of Nissan's net sales, will be cut 20 percent. Platforms, the
backbone of a vehicle, will be reduced to 14 from the current 24 by
2002, and to 12 by 2004, and Renault and Nissan will produce some
cars on the same platforms.
</P>
<P>
   But Ghosn made it clear that the plan was not only about cutting
back and casting away, but also about creating new,
more-exciting-looking vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   ``Product development will be at the heart of Nissan's
revival,'' he said. In one sign of Ghosn's commitment, the design
team in Japan is being removed from the engineering group and
placed under the oversight of Patrick Pelata, the French head of
product development, in hopes of insuring that Nissan's future
models will have greater consumer appeal.
</P>
<P>
   Nissan's plan was announced after the stock market closed here.
Earlier, its shares tumbled 7.1 percent to 637 yen, or $6.06. Later
in New York, Nissan's American depository receipts closed unchanged
on NASDAQ at $12.875. Renault shares fell a little more than 2
percent in Paris to 49.9 euros, or $54.10.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-18-99 2214EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
