<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-PASSER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HAROLD PASSER, NIXON ADVISER AND FORECASTER OF THE ECONOMY, DIES AT
77  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.H., Minn., N.C., Me., Mass.)   By WOLFGANG SAXON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Harold Clarence Passer, an economic forecaster for business and
the government, including the Nixon White House, died on Oct. 8 at
his home in Portsmouth, N.H., where he retired in 1983. He was 77.
</P>
<P>
   Passer served as assistant secretary of commerce for economic
affairs from 1969 to 1973. At the time, he sat on the President's
Council of Economic Advisers and regularly appeared at news
conferences about the country's economic health and prospects.
</P>
<P>
   Before and after his years in Washington, he worked as an
economic analyst for the Eastman Kodak Co. in Rochester and was the
company's assistant treasurer.
</P>
<P>
   Harold Passer was born in Lakefield, Minn. He graduated summa
cum laude in 1943 from Harvard University, where he earned an
master's degee in economics in 1948 and a doctorate in the subject
in 1950. He taught economics at Harvard before joining Eastman
Kodak in 1952.
</P>
<P>
   Passer also lectured at the University of Rochester and Cornell
University. He served as chairman of the New York State Council of
Economic Education in the 1970s and earlier as a consultant to the
Federal Reserve Board.
</P>
<P>
   He wrote many articles and a book, ``The Electrical
Manufacturers'' (1953). Passer is survived by his wife of 32 years,
Astrid Louise Anderson Passer; a stepdaughter, Christine Thurber
Streeter of Portland, Maine; a stepson, Dr. David C. Thurber Jr. of
Raleigh, N.C.; and a sister, Carolyn Passer of Faribault, Minn. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-18-99 2214EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991018.0494 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-18 22:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1080 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-FLA-IRENE-DAMAGE-COX     10-18 1578
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLA-IRENE-DAMAGE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Irene still doing damage
 &HT;    By Thomas R. Collins, Sally D. Swartz and Jim Reeder
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT PIERCE, Fla. _ A major raw sewage spill Monday afternoon
suddenly eclipsed power outages and flooding on the list of
Hurricane Irene-related problems.
</P>
<P>
   In an incident officials say was likely caused by a tremendous
increase in stormwater that surged into Fort Pierce Utility
Authority plumbing, a 36-inch pipe burst, causing untreated sewage
to spill out onto the authority's plant grounds and pour into the
Indian River at the rate of about 625,000 gallons an hour. By 8
p.m. Monday, between three million and six million gallons of
sewage had drained into the river, said Fort Pierce Utilities
Authority director of operations Tom Richards.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not sure exactly what occurred but it's pretty big,'' he
said of the spill.
</P>
<P>
   He said the authority notified the St. Lucie Health Department
and the state Department of Environmental Protection. Boaters and
others on the river were warned to steer clear of the plant on
Seaway Drive.
</P>
<P>
   The burst pipe was 15 years old, ``We never would have expected
it to fail,'' he said. ``I would expect a pipe like that to last 50
years.''
</P>
<P>
   Usually, about five million to six million gallons a day flow
through the pipe, but with Irene's rains that rose to 15 million
gallons a day, Richards said, adding he suspected the increased
flow at least partly caused the break.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems like it's too much of a coincidence to say that it's
not related,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The massive spill capped a day which saw Treasure Coast
residents cleaning up flooded homes, while government workers
repaired damage to public buildings in both counties.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 17,000 St. Lucie County and 4,000 Martin County residents
still had no electricity at noon Monday, but Florida Power &AMP; Light
Co. officials expected to have service restored to most or all
areas by late Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   Eight to 10 inches of rain from the storm were reported in
Martin County. Emergency officials reported gusts up to 92 mph on
Jupiter Island during the storm and sustained hurricane force wind
of 75 mph in various parts of the county.
</P>
<P>
   Damage assessments are still underway. Federal, state and local
officials were out in the field Monday and may have a preliminary
estimate of the damage today, St. Lucie's Emergency Management
Director Jack Southard said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got a very preliminary figure for wind damage only of
$140,000 to $155,000,'' Southard said. ``More reports are coming in
and there's flood damage on top of that.''
</P>
<P>
   County Administrator Doug Anderson said he drove around Saturday
and saw extensive flooding in Lakewood Park and Indian River
Estates. Houses near Bell Avenue and South 25th Street were also
flooded
</P>
<P>
   ``We saw a lot of trees toppled because the ground was so wet,
carports and screen rooms damaged,'' Anderson said.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson plans a helicopter flight with officials from the
Federal Emergency Management Agency to assess the damage today.
</P>
<P>
   And taxpayers will be paying for Irene's blow in additional
areas:
</P>
<P>
   _ The toll for the South Florida Water Management District will
top $5 million, according to spokeswoman Ann Overton. That includes
$2.5 million in damage to district buildings, $2.3 million in
damage to canals, and about $127,000 spent per day on extra staff
to deal with the storm.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Florida Department of Transportation will spend at least
$1 million to repair damage to state roads in South Florida,
according to spokeswoman Barbara Kelleher. That includes a $150,000
repair job for the interchange at Interstate 95 and Indiantown
road, which suffered heavy erosion.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Army Corps of Engineers begins today to release water
from swolen Lake Okeechobee, now at 17.47 feet, about 8 1/2 inches
higher than normal for this time of year. An estimated 2.9 billion
gallons daily will be dumped in the Caloosahatchee River to the
west of the lake.
</P>
<P>
   Corps workers wakened Col. Joe Miller, the Corps' chief for the
state of Florida, at 3 a.m. Saturday for permission to open the St.
Lucie gates wider. ``We were afraid the structure would be damaged
if we didn't,'' Griffin said.
</P>
<P>
   Local runoff still is pouring through the St. Lucie canal
spillway into the St. Lucie River at a rate of 1.9 billion gallons
a day, and that amount probably will remain about the same when the
Corps decides to release water from lake, Corps spokeswoman
Jacquelyn Griffin said. That decision could come as early as today,
but the Corps will stay in close touch with Martin County officials
so flooded areas downstream aren't further damaged.
</P>
<P>
   Some areas in Martin and St. Lucie counties were slow to drain
because fallen trees blocked creeks and feeder canals, water
district spokesman Paul Millar said. A breach in a reservoir dike
at Riverland Groves Monday sent grove runoff into the C-23 canal,
which runs along the Martin-St. Lucie county line into the St.
Lucie River, Millar said.
</P>
<P>
   Irene's winds damaged several St. Lucie County buildings,
including libraries, the County Administration Building and
warehouses. Most seriously damaged were the courthouse and the
Legal Arts Building in downtown Fort Pierce.
</P>
<P>
   Air-conditioning equipment on the courthouse roof was damaged by
the wind and inoperable Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The roof came off the Legal Arts Building and it's
uninhabitable,'' St. Lucie Administrator Anderson said. ``We have
to find new offices for the Guardian Ad Litem program and new
storage space for the court records that got wet.''
</P>
<P>
   Circuit Judge Dwight Geiger postponed jury selection until this
morning because of the lack of air conditioning.
</P>
<P>
   More than 1,000 street signs throughout the county are missing,
blown away or their poles broken by the storm.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson hopes to have a damage figure by tonight's County
Commission meeting so he can ask permission to transfer money from
reserves to pay for repairs.
</P>
<P>
   In Martin County, a section of County Road 609 in the
southwestern part of the county washed out in the storm and some
unpaved roads were impassable for low-riding vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   The roof of the new Blake Library on Monterey Road in Stuart was
damaged and a maintenance building nearby at Witham Field had major
damage.
</P>
<P>
   The Martin County Chapter of the American Red Cross reported
about 40 homes received mostly minor damage from wind or water,
Executive Director Mary Shaw said.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Cross is offering assistance with food, temporary
shelter and clothing for those affected by the storm and has vans
touring neighborhoods offering bottled water.
</P>
<P>
   Martin County Health Department officials are advising residents
to boil drinking water if their wells were submerged or if their
water company lost power. No contamination to any water supplies
was reported.
</P>
<P>
   Schools in Martin County opened on time Monday, but only after
maintenance crews spent the weekend mopping up and making repairs
at several schools.
</P>
<P>
   At Hobe Sound Elementary, the carpet in the media center had to
be replaced and four classrooms had at least 3 inches of standing
water in them, said Jerry Smith, director of facilities for the
district.
</P>
<P>
   Power was knocked out at South Fork High School until 2 a.m.
Monday, and sewer lines were replaced at Martin County High.
</P>
<P>
   Across the county, water seeped in through doorways and windows.
``We took a lot of water intrusion at just about every site,''
Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   Damage at St. Lucie County schools was relatively minor,
although one school, Woodlands Academy, remained without power
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   C.A. Moore Elementary required fascia repairs, and Port St.
Lucie Elementary was without electricity until about 6 p.m. Sunday.
Other schools reported roof leaks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think overall we're OK,'' said Senior Project Manager Andrew
Favata.
</P>
<P>
   A fish kill off Hutchinson Island in St. Lucie County discovered
Monday was blamed on winds from Irene that caused a drop in the
water's oxygen levels. As many as 20,000 mullet were found floating
in Big Mud Creek off the Indian River, near FPL's St. Lucie Nuclear
Power Plant.
</P>
<P>
   The creek includes a large back bay where fine silt settles on
the bottom, Department of Environmental Protection biologist Doug
Strom said. Decaying material on the bottom was stirred up by
strong eastern winds that robbed oxygen from the water.
</P>
<P>
   ``This same thing has occurred at this site a couple of times in
the last few years,'' Strom said.
</P>
<P>
   Oxygen levels in the water are returning to normal, Strom said
Monday
</P>
<P>
   In Okeechobee County, where about 60 percent of the residences
are mobile homes, the wind was the main problem, said Gene O'Neill,
the county's director of emergency management. The wind was
sustained at 40 to 45 mph and blew in gusts of 55 to 60 mph in the
county, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had some mobile homes that had some damage from carports,
screen rooms and partial roofs blown off,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neill said the county had shelters on standby that could have
opened them in 15 minutes, but ``didn't feel it was necessary'' to
open them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We stand by our decision,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas R. Collins, Sally D. Swartz and Jim Reeder write for the
Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach, Fla. Molly Hennessy-Fiske, Jill
Taylor, Lady Hereford and Trebor Banstetter contributed to this
story.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
