<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OHIO-CELESTE-SENATE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ted Celeste may make Senate run
 &HT;    By William Hershey
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLUMBUS, Ohio _ Ohio Democrats could find a familiar name on
the ballot when they go to the polls next March to pick a U.S.
Senate candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Ted Celeste, younger brother of former two-term Gov. Richard F.
Celeste, said Monday that he is ``taking a look'' at the race.
</P>
<P>
   He doesn't have much time before the Jan. 7 filing deadline but
said, ``I am trying to give it as serious consideration as I can.''
</P>
<P>
   One Democrat, Richard Cordray of suburban Columbus, an
unsuccessful candidate for Ohio attorney general last year, entered
the Senate race last week. A second candidate, Marvin McMickle,
pastor of a Baptist church in Cleveland, is expected to announce
later this month.
</P>
<P>
   Celeste, 54, who recently stepped down as chairman of the Ohio
State University board of trustees, is president of a real estate
company in Grandview Heights, a Columbus suburb. While he has never
ran for elective office, he has run several statewide campaigns
from behind the scenes.
</P>
<P>
   He said that he has discussed the Senate race with his older
brother, now U.S. ambassador to India.
</P>
<P>
   He said his brother told him that a statewide race against an
incumbent _ Republican Sen. Mike DeWine _ would be an ``uphill
battle'' and require him to raise a lot of money.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Celeste was on the statewide ballot four times from 1974
to 1986 _ three times for governor and once for lieutenant
governor. Richard Celeste left office at the end of 1990 after his
second term.
</P>
<P>
   The Celeste name would be an advantage, said state Sen. Rhine
McLin, D-Dayton, who succeeded her father, the late C. J. McLin, in
the Ohio House before going on to the state Senate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's put it like this,'' McLin said. ``Half the politics in
Ohio is a name game.''
</P>
<P>
   William Hershey writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
