<SLUG> BC-PHOTO-BUDGET-NYT </SLUG>
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving Monday, 10/18/99. Photo
clients will automatically receive these photos via AP's
PhotoExpress or may download them from either the Wieck Photo
Database in Dallas at 972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at
305-448-8411. Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling
(888) 603-1036 or 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   Editors:
</P>
<P>
   We will continue to provide coverage this evening of Game 5 of
the Americal League Championship Series between the New York
Yankees and the Boston Red Sox. Should the Yankees win, post-game
photos will move within the hour after the game ends.
</P>
<P>
   Coverage will include photos not only from the New York Times
photographers but from our partner, the Boston Globe.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT39) BOSTON -- Oct. 18, 1999 -- BBA-YANKS-BOSOX-3, 10-18 --
Boston Red Sox pitcher Kent Mercker during the first inning against
the New York Yankees on Monday at Fenway park in Game 5 of the
Americal League Championship Series. (Barton Silverman/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT38) BOSTON -- Oct. 18, 1999 -- BBA-YANKS-BOSOX-2, 10-18 --
Yankees shortstop Derek Jeter (2) is congratulated by his teammates
after his two-run homer in the first inning on Monday at Fenway
park against the Boston Red Sox in Game 5 of the Americal League
Championship Series. (Barton Silverman/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT37) OKLAHOMA CITY -- Oct. 18, 1999 -- TRAVEL-OKLAHOMA-HNS,
10-18 -- Water taxis on a milelong canal are among several new
surprises while visiting Oklahoma City. ``The biggest (tourism)
problem for Oklahoma City isn't 'misconception,''' said Doug
Stafford of the Oklahoma City Convention and Visitors Bureau. ``It
is 'no conception.' People think about Oklahoma, and they think
Cowboys, Indians and prairie.'' (Syd Kearney/Houston Chronicle
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT36) STAFFORD, Texas -- Oct. 18, 1999 -- DSP-CHIPS-HNS, 10-18
-- Greg Delagi, a Texas Instruments vice president in charge of DSP
technology, holds some products which include the chip. DSP is
considered by Texas Instruments to be the processor that will take
consumers closer to the technology-rich world of ``Star Trek,''
with such products as portable universal translators. One of the
benefits of DSP is that apart from being a fast chip, it
specializes in turning analog signals - such as sound or light -
into digital information that can then be manipulated.(John
Everett/Houston Chronicle Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT35) HOUSTON -- Oct. 18, 1999 -- FOOD-STAMPS-HNS, 10-18 --
Maria Diaz, a mother of two who is expecting a third child, said a
delay in getting food stamps meant she and her children had to eat
less. Diaz works full time weekdays cleaning rooms at a hotel, but
the $850 she brings home each month doesn't put enough food on the
table. Diaz tops a list of poor mothers in Houston who are suing
the Texas Department of Human Services for illegal foot-dragging in
the processing of food stamp claims. (Carlos Antonio Rios/Houston
Chronicle Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT34) RUMSON, N.J. -- Oct. 18, 1999 -- BBO-OJEDA-LOYALTY,
10-18 -- Bobby Ojeda during an interview last week. Though Ojeda
has played for the Mets, Red Sox, the Indians and the Yankees too,
it wasn't until this mother prodded him this weekend that he
finally watched some of the playoff games. That's because there are
comebacks, and then there is coming back, as in Ojeda's life. (Dith
Pran/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT33) WEST ORANGE, N.J. -- Oct. 18, 1999 -- WEB-CAMPAIGNING,
10-18 -- Lynn Reed, a Web consultant to the Bill Bradley
presidential campaign, in her office at the campaign's headquarters
going through photos in a folder. The modern campaign headquarters
is no longer a rented storefront decorated with bumper stickers,
bunting and empty soda cans. In creasingly it has an annex open any
hour of the day or night, at an address starting with www. (Frank
C. Dougherty/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT32) ATLANTA -- Oct. 18, 1999 -- xxx, 10-18 -- Bobby
Valentine during a news conference on Monday. ``I've been in long
games, but not in games where every pitch meant so much from the
fourth inning on,'' said Valentine about Sunday's 4-3, 15-inning
victory in Game 5 of the NL Championship Series. Game 6 is Tuesday.
(G. Paul Burnett/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT31) BOSTON -- Oct. 18, 1999 -- BBA-YANKS-BOSOX-1, 10-18 --
Sandy Alderson, supervisor of Major League umpires speaks to
reporters just prior to Game 5. Game 5 of the American League
Championship Series at Fenway Park. Umpires have been criticized in
the past week for blown calls during the AL Championship Series,
most of them in favor of the New York Yankees. (John
Tlumacki/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT30) BOSTON -- Oct. 18, 1999 -- BBA-YANKS-BOSOX-9, 10-18 --
Boston Red Sox manager Jimy Williams, right, takes the ball from
pitcher Kent Mercker after Mercker loaded the bases in the fourth
inning during Game 5 of the American League Championship Series
against the New York Yankees on Monday at Fenway Park. Mercker was
relieved by Derek Lowe. (Chang W. Lee/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT29) BOSTON -- Oct. 18, 1999 -- BBA-YANKS-BOSOX-8, 10-18 --
New York Yankees pitcher Orlando ``El Duque'' Hernandez during the
first inning in Game 5 of the American League Championship Series
against the Boston Red Sox at Fenway Park on Monday. (Chang W.
Lee/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT27) UNDATED -- Oct. 18, 1999 -- SEASON-FASHION-2, 10-18 --
From left, a different take on glamour by Michael Kors. The colors
say ``Palm Beach''; Miuccia Prada's new low-slung skirt, in
ostrich, with a slinky but ladylike blouse; an organdy skirt
printed with lipstick tubes from Prada. (Marilynn K. Yee, Corina
Lecca/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT26) UNDATED -- Oct. 18, 1999 -- SEASON-FASHION-1, 10-18 --
From left, Marc Jacobs' trench coat for Louis Vuitton printed with
monogrammed logos; Ralph Lauren's gingham skirt, with leotard,
caught the wave of bigger volume; from Oscar de la Renta, a
polished-looking shirtwaist dress in rinsed denim, a trend for
spring. (Dan and Corina Lecca/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT25) BOSTON -- Oct. 18, 1999 -- BBA-YANKS-BOSOX-7, 10-18 --
Boston Red Sox pitcher Kent Mercker walks back to the mound as
Yankees second baseman Chuck Knoblauch rounds third on Derek
Jeter's first inning, two-run homerun on Monday in Game 5 of the
American League Championship Series against the New York Yankees at
Fenway Park. (John Tlumacki/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT24) BOSTON -- Oct. 18, 1999 -- BBA-YANKS-BOSOX-6, 10-18 --
Boston Red Sox fans show their feelings as field umpire Rick Reed
stands in the outfield during Game 5 of the American League
Championship Series against the New York Yankees on Monday at
Fenway Park. Umpires have been criticized in the past week for
blown calls during the series, most of them in favor of the
Yankees. (Jim Davis/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT23) BOSTON -- Oct. 18, 1999 -- BBA-YANKS-BOSOX-5, 10-18 --
Red Sox manager Jimmy Williams, center, talks to his pitcher Kent
Mercker after giving up a two-run homer to New York Yankees
shortstop Derek Jeter in the first inning at Fenway Park on Monday
in Game 5 of the American League Championship Series. Cather Jason
Varitek looks on at right. (Barry Chin/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT22) BOSTON -- Oct. 18, 1999 -- BBA-YANKS-BOSOX-4, 10-18 --
Yankees principle owner George Steinbrenner is bundled up from the
cold as he watches Game 5 of the American League Championship
Series between the New York Yankees and Boston Red Sox on Monday at
Fenway Park. (Barry Chin/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT21) BOSTON -- Oct. 18, 1999 -- BBA-YANKS-BOSOX-RUTH, 10-18
-- Julia Ruth Stevens, dauther of baseball legend Babe Ruth,
prepares to throw the ceremonial first pitch in Game 5 of the
American League Championship Series between the New York Yankees
and Boston Red Sox on Monday at Fenway Park. (Barton Sivlerman/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) NEW YORK -- Oct. 18, 1999 -- KISSINGER-TEACH, 10-18 --
Henry Kissinger, right, the former secretary of State and national
security advisor under President Nixon during a class at the
Eleanor Roosevelt Middle School in the Manhattan neighborhood of
Washington Heights on Monday. Kissinger is one of dozens of
celebrities visiting classrooms around the country this week to
celebrate the 10th anniversary of Teach for America, the nonprofit
group that places recent college graduates in poor and struggling
school districts. (Jack Manning/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) WASHINGTON -- Oct. 18, 1999 -- SPEND-CONGRESS, 10-18 --
House Majority Leader Dick Armey, R-Texas, is followed by reporters
after commenting on the House leadership's reaction to President
Clinton's veto on foreign aid appropriations on Monday. Clinton and
Congress moved closer to a showdown on Monday over the federal
budget following the veto. Clinton invited congressional leaders to
a meeting at the White House on Tuesday to discuss their
differences. (Paul Hosefros/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) VIEQUES, Puerto Rico -- Oct. 18, 1999 --
PUERTORICO-NAVY-2, 10-18 -- The Puerto Rican flag flies over an
encampment set up by protesters in August just over the hill where
remnants of armored vehicles, used during target practice by the US
Navy, litter the landscape on the island off eastern Puerto Rico. A
Presidential panel recommended on Monday that the United States
military be allowed to resume live firing exercises on Vieques but
ordered the range shut down in five years. The recommendation was
made despite demands from the territory's governor that the base be
closed immediately and all bombing halted. (Photo by Mike
Williams/Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) VIEQUES, Puerto Rico -- Oct. 18, 1999 --
PUERTORICO-NAVY-1, 10-18 -- Ruben Berrios, a member of the Puerto
Rican Senate and head of the Puerto Rican Independence Party, looks
at spent ammunition found on the bombing range in Vieques, off
eastern Puerto Rico, in August. A Presidential panel recommended on
Monday that the United States military be allowed to resume live
firing exercises on Vieques but ordered the range shut down in five
years. The recommendation was made despite demands from the
territory's governor that the base be closed immediately and all
bombing halted. (Photo by Mike Williams/Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) TOKYO -- Oct. 18, 1999 -- LUXURY-GOODS-2, 10-18 -- A
Tokyo shopper walks past the new Hermes shop in the Ginza district
in Tokyo last month. Hermes International S.A., the maker of
elaborately pattered silk scarves and ties, and Salvatore
Ferragamo, known for its comfortable dowdy pumps, are on many
investors wish lists. But both say they are not interested. (Stuart
Isett/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) NEW YORK -- Oct. 18, 1999 -- LUXURY-GOODS, 10-18 --
Bernard Arnault, head of LMVH, in his Midtown office. It may seem
strange in climate where brand name recognition is paramount that
ambitious investors like Arnault would snatch some lesser known
firm more readily then household names like Calvin Klein or Bill
Blass. But that is just what is happening as companies like LMVH
are searching for company's with sterling reputations that have not
been widely exploited in ancillary products like perfumes or
handbags and underwear. (Chester Higgins Jr./New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) WASHINGTON -- Oct. 18, 1999 -- , 10-18 -- Vice President
Al Gore, right, points to Bill Cosby after Cosby playfully pocketed
the $20,000 check won by jazz pianist Eric Lewis, center, in the
Thelonious Monk annual competition at the Kennedy Center Sunday
night. The finalists' competition on Sunday night wa n't just
surprisingly good; it was also indicative of where jazz piano is
now. (Justin Lane/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) NORTH TOP SAIL BEACH, N.C. -- Oct. 18, 1999 --
HURRICANE-IRENE, 10-18 -- Dennis Lucas stands atop a stairway on
Monday that use to lead to the beach. Between Hurricane Floyd in
September, and Irene on Sunday, much of North Top Sail beach has
been eroded. Irene, a relatively weak but very wet hurricane, was
blamed for at least 15 deaths in Cuba, the Bahamas and Florida last
week before brushing flood-weary North Carolina over the weekend.
(Mark Courtney/Wilmington Star-News)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) WELLESLEY, Mass. -- Oct. 17, 1999 -- BOSTON-BRAVES-BOS,
10-18 --''I've followed them ever since they left town,'' says
Philip Cahill, 76, of Wellesley, who grew up across the street from
Braves Field, now the site of Boston University's Nickerson Field.
``If there's a Braves game and a Red Sox game on TV, I'll watch the
Braves.'' While in Boston, the franchise won 10 pennants, one World
Series (1914), and was followed by fiercely loyal fans like Cahill
who grew accustomed to pulling for the underdog. (Tom
Landers/Boston Globe Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) MADISON, Wisc. -- Oct. 18, 1999 --
SCI-LEOPOLD-CONSERVATION-3, 10-18 -- Remnants from ecologist Aldo
Leopold's work: unused bird bands and notes about tagged birds
written on his stationery. In the field of conservation, Leopold is
a titan. Currently his ideas are being scrutinized afresh. A recent
conference was convened by the Wisconsin Academy of Sciences, Arts
and Letters to examine his legacy and its relevance for the future.
(Andy Manis/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) MADISON, Wisc. -- Oct. 18, 1999 --
SCI-LEOPOLD-CONSERVATION-2, 10-18 -- A former chicken coop known as
``The Shack,'' bought in 1935 by Aldo Leopold. It was at ``The
Shack,'' in south-central Wisconsin, about an hour's drive north of
Madison, that Leopold, one of the half-dozen most influential
thinkers of the last 150 years on the relationship of human beings
to the rest of nature, gleaned many of his insights and sharpened
his ideas. (Andy Manis/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) MADISON, Wisc. -- Oct. 18, 1999 --
SCI-LEOPOLD-CONSERVATION-1-B&AMP;W, 10-18 -- The conservationist Aldo
Leopold in 1940 on the property in south-central Wisconsin where he
developed his ideas on the relationship of human beings to the rest
of nature. In the field of conservation, Leopold is a titan.
Currently his ideas are being scrutinized afresh. A recent
conference was convened by the Wisconsin Academy of Sciences, Arts
and Letters to examine his legacy and its relevance for the future.
(Robert McCabe/Aldo Leopold Foundation/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) NEW YORK -- Oct. 18, 1999 -- SCI-IRONMAN-4, 10-18 -- Bob
Spina Jr., left, an attorney, with colleagues. Spina, training for
a triathalon, is up by 5 a.m. and out the door before his wife and
three daughters are awake. He gets in a 15-mile run, a 60-mile bike
ride or a 2.4-mile swim swim before most of his neighbors are
putting the filters in their coffee makers. (Aaron Lee Fineman/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) MASSAPEQUA, N.Y. -- Oct. 18, 1999 -- SCI-IRONMAN-3, 10-18
-- Bob Spina Jr., right, repairs a wheel on his bike during his
daily 60-mile morning ride. Spina, training for a triathalon, is up
by 5 a.m. and out the door before his wife and three daughters are
awake. He gets in a 15-mile run, a 60-mile bike ride or a 2.4-mile
swim swim before most of his neighbors are putting the filters in
their coffee makers. (Aaron Lee Fineman/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) MASSAPEQUA, N.Y. -- Oct. 18, 1999 -- SCI-IRONMAN-2, 10-18
-- Bob Spina, right, Jr. during his daily 15-mile run. Spina,
training for a triathalon, is up by 5 a.m. and out the door before
his wife and three daughters are awake. He gets in a 15-mile run, a
60-mile bike ride or his swim before most of his neighbors are
putting the filters in their coffee makers. (Aaron Lee Fineman/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) MASSAPEQUA, N.Y. -- Oct. 18, 1999 -- SCI-IRONMAN-1, 10-18
-- Bob Spina Jr. prepares for his daily 2.4-mile swim. Spina,
training for a triathalon, is up by 5 a.m., and out the door before
his wife and three daughters are awake. He gets in a 15-mile run, a
60-mile bike ride or his swim before most of his neighbors are
putting the filters in their coffee makers. (Aaron Lee Fineman/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) GOMA, Congo -- Oct. 18, 1999 -- SCI-RELIEF-CHILDREN,
10-18 -- Dr. Karen Olness, co-author of a manual to help relief
workers care for children who are victims of disasters, treating
two Rwandan orphans at a hospital in Goma in 1994. Although
disasters - from hurricanes to earthquakes to political unrest -
can be devastating for anyone, they can be particularly hard on
children. But the special health needs of these youngest victims
often go unmet, experts say. (Courtesy of Dr. Karen Olness/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) NEW YORK -- Oct. 18, 1999 -- SCI-AIDS-MORNING-AFTER,
10-18 -- Dr. Gabriel Torres with a patient in his Manhattan medical
office. Frustrated by the continued spread of HIV, a growing number
of AIDS doctors are trying out a kind of morning-after treatment:
an experimental application of drugs meant to abort infection in a
person who was recently exposed to the virus through unsafe sex.
Torres has been using an experimental treatment for people who
believe they have just been exposed to the AIDS virus. (Marilynn K.
Yee/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) MELBOURNE, Australia -- -- Oct. 18, 1999 --
SCI-CATHEDRAL-ASTRONOMY-2 Science and religion blend as sunbeams
enter the Shrine of Remembrance in Melbourne. Beams of sunlight
that fall past religious art and marble columns not only inspired
the faithful but provided astronomers with information about the
Sun, the Earth and their celestial relationship. (Harvard
University Press/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) PALERMO, Italy -- Oct. 18, 1999 --
SCI-CATHEDRAL-ASTRONOMY-1, 10-18 -- The meridian line at the Dumo
of Palermo. While the Roman Catholic Church condemned Galileo, new
research shows that centuries of oversimplifications have concealed
how hard Rome worked to amass astronomical tools, measurements,
tests and lore. (Harvard University Press/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
