<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BANKS-EARNINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CITIGROUP REPORTS BIG REBOUND IN PROFIT FOR 3RD QUARTER 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By PATRICK McGEEHAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Citigroup, the nation's largest financial services
company, said Monday that its third-quarter profit had more than
tripled as its banking and trading businesses rebounded from a weak
performance a year earlier, when global financial turmoil hurt big
banks and securities firms.
</P>
<P>
   A combination of rising revenue and sharp cost-cutting helped
improve results for virtually every segment of Citigroup's
far-flung operations, from making consumer loans to trading bonds
through its Salomon Smith Barney investment-banking unit. At the
rate it has been going in 1999, Citigroup would end the year with
nearly $10 billion in annual profit.
</P>
<P>
   Excluding $15 million in restructuring charges, Citigroup earned
$2.45 billion, or 70 cents a diluted share, compared with $729
million, or 20 cents a share, in the third quarter of 1998. The
results were about even with those for the second quarter of this
year and slightly higher than analysts had expected.
</P>
<P>
   Of 22 analysts surveyed by First Call/Thomson Financial, the
average estimate was 68 cents a share. Citigroup's stock rose
$1.562, to $43.6875.
</P>
<P>
   Two other major banks, Bank of America and J.P. Morgan &AMP; Co.,
also reported net income Monday that exceeded analysts' estimates.
Bank of New York Co. reported record earnings that were inflated by
a large gain on the sale of a business.
</P>
<P>
   Bank of America, based in Charlotte, N.C., earned $2.15 billion,
or $1.23 a diluted share, up from $893 million, or 50 cents a
share, excluding merger-related charges. That total exceeded
analysts' expectations of $1.21 a share, according to First Call.
Bank of America's shares rose $1.375, to $49.5625.
</P>
<P>
   J.P. Morgan posted a bigger surprise, reporting net income of
$442 million, or $2.22 a diluted share, up from $156 million, or 75
cents a share, in the third quarter of 1998. Its stock jumped
$7.3125, to $113.
</P>
<P>
   Bank of New York reported net income of $773 million, or $1.02 a
share, but that total included a gain of $573 million, or 75 cents
a share, from the sale of a business-financing unit. A big increase
in the bank's provision for loan losses ate into the bank's
operating profit for the quarter. It set aside $90 million to cover
bad loans, up 500 percent from $15 million in the second quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts had expected Bank of New York to earn 42 cents a share.
Its stock gained 43.75 cents, to $34.3125.
</P>
<P>
   ``These numbers indicate the health of the banking industry,''
said Diane Glossman, an analyst at Lehman Brothers Holdings Inc.
``Bank earnings continue to be quite robust and credit quality is
still quite pristine.''
</P>
<P>
   The generally strong performances by the banks demonstrated how
much healthier the market remained last quarter for financial
services tailored for consumers than those aimed at investors and
corporate customers. Citigroup and other multinational banks
reported smaller declines overall from the second to third quarters
than did their counterparts on Wall Street, whose fortunes are tied
more tightly to the ups and downs of the stock and bond markets.
</P>
<P>
   ``First and foremost, the consumer businesses are really driving
earnings momentum'' at Citigroup, said Judah Kraushaar, an analyst
at Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co. ``This company embodies the concept of
diversification.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Citigroup is involved in more sectors of the financial
services industry than any other U.S. company. Along with its
commercial and investment banks, it is a major player in insurance
through its Travelers unit.
</P>
<P>
   Sanford Weill, one of the company's two chairmen and chief
executive officers, said he was happy to hear that lawmakers in
Washington were progressing toward passage of a bill that would
reform Depression-era rules that separate the banking, insurance
and brokerage industries. The merger of Citicorp and Travelers that
created Citigroup might have to be restructured if long-anticipated
changes in those laws are not approved this year.
</P>
<P>
   Kraushaar said he thinks Citigroup will hold off on making any
more acquisitions until the legislative issues are sorted out. But
once they are, he said, the company could start spending some of
the cash it has been building up. He estimated that Citigroup has
about $7 billion more than required by regulators. That excess
capital could be spent on acquisitions or to buy back stock, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Weill and John Reed, the company's other chairman and chief
executive officer, described last quarter in unexciting terms,
suggesting that the company is humming along after a period of
post-merger turbulence.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were able to make those gains without having to take major
risks in some of our businesses,'' said the famously risk-averse
Weill. ``All of this was done without overleveraging our balance
sheet.''
</P>
<P>
   In particular, he pointed to the shrinkage of the highly
volatile bond-trading operation Travelers inherited when it bought
the Salomon Brothers investment bank before merging with Citicorp.
Weill said that the capital committed to that trading unit, known
as global arbitrage, had declined by more than 90 percent, to $7
billion from $100 billion. He declined to comment on published
reports that some traders in the unit may leave to start one or
more hedge funds and that CitiGroup is considering investing in the
funds.
</P>
<P>
   Bond arbitrage, making huge bets on small discrepancies in the
prices of various bonds, was responsible for the bulk of the loss
of $1.3 billion that Salomon Smith Barney incurred in the third
quarter of 1998 when investors stampeded out of emerging markets
after Russia defaulted on its debt. Overall last quarter, the
corporate and investment banking division, which includes Salomon
Smith Barney, earned $1.15 billion. That compared with a loss of
$221 million a year earlier and a gain of $1.26 billion in the
second quarter of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Citigroup's global consumer businesses, including lending and
insurance, had income of $1.12 billion, up 38 percent from $806
million a year before. Claims for damage caused by Hurricane Floyd
cut into profit for the personal-lines insurance business but
profit from commercial lines of insurance rose 44 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said the Travelers management has instilled a
cost-cutting discipline that has Citigroup on track to surpass its
stated goal of reducing annual expenses by $2 billion by the end of
this year. The company's return on equity, a key measure of
profitability, was 21.9 percent, exceeding the company's target of
20 percent on average.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
