<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAIL-AMERICA'S-CUP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOP AMERICANS FIND SAILING SMOOTH IN AMERICA'S CUP QUALIFYING
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By JOHN SHAW   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUCKLAND, New Zealand _ The top three skippers in the United
States' bid to recapture the America's Cup won all five of the
races they sailed Monday as the four-month, eight-nation campaign
for the cup began here.
</P>
<P>
   Two other Americans gained one victory between them in four
starts, with two of the defeats inflicted by rival U.S. boats.
</P>
<P>
   But facing a marathon program of up to 400 races to qualify for
a showdown next February with the current Cup holder, New Zealand,
the winning crews declined to read much into their initial
successes.
</P>
<P>
   Bright morning sunshine and light breezes welcomed crews from
seven nations to the 3-mile course off Rangitoto Island, an ancient
volcano in Hauraki Gulf 15 miles north of this port city.
</P>
<P>
   But afternoon rain squalls, swept by freshening 11-knot gales
sent many of the 150 spectator boats home early, and one crewman,
Simone de Mare, of the Italian yacht Luna Rossa, was tipped
overboard while struggling to control a wayward spinnaker. He was
pulled aboard unhurt.
</P>
<P>
   Ten one-on-one races, each of them four legs covering 12 miles,
were sailed on this first day of the four-month regatta.
</P>
<P>
   These grueling qualifying stages comprise what is known as the
Louis Vuitton Cup.
</P>
<P>
   The New Zealand defender, which defeated the United States off
San Diego in 1995, followed events at a discreet distance, cruising
one of its black-hulled yachts within sight of the challenge
racers.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Yacht Club, which held the Cup from 1851 to 1983,
began its second attempt to regain it with two victories Monday.
Its skipper, Ed Baird, led his craft, Young America, in comfortable
victories against modest opposition from San Francisco's America
True and then the Spanish entrant, Bravo Espana.
</P>
<P>
   The rival San Francisco yachts, America One and America True,
clashed Monday as well. America True, skippered by Dawn Riley, the
first woman to head an America's Cup syndicate, lost by 3 minutes
45 seconds in an afternoon event, after sailing more strongly in
the morning race and losing by only 37 seconds to the New York
Yacht Club.
</P>
<P>
   Abracadabra, entered by the Waikiki Yacht Club, and skippered by
John Kolius, defeated the Swiss entry, optimistically named Be
Happy, by 10 minutes. However, earlier, after some apparent winch
problems, the Hawaiian yacht lost by 40 seconds to Nippon Challenge
of Japan.
</P>
<P>
   The senior American skipper here, veteran Dennis Conner, began
his eighth Cup campaign with a cliff hanger, edging the lightly
rated French opponent, Sixth Sense, by only 9 seconds. The French
made a last-leg spinnaker rush at Conner's San Diego-based Stars
and Stripes.
</P>
<P>
   The official summary of the day _ issued by ocean race experts
advising the events sponsor _ declared that ``due to extremely
tricky and changeable conditions, it is unreasonable to draw any
serious conclusions'' from Monday's races.
</P>
<P>
   However, the three undefeated Americans, the Japanese, with one
victory, and Italians, with two wins, started impressively Monday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
