<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COKE-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING: CAMPAIGN IS PREPARED FOR LAUNCH AT COCA-COLA  
(DW) 
 STUART ELLIOTT AND CONSTANCE L. HAYS  
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ill., Ga.)   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Coca-Cola Co., the maker of the world's
best-known brand, will soon be exhorting consumers to take what
amounts to a magical mystery tour of the mouth by enjoying the
``unique taste sensation'' and ``sparkle on your tongue'' of its
flagship product.
</P>
<P>
   Starting early next year, the company will promote its
best-selling brand _ known as Coca-Cola Classic in North America
and Coca-Cola elsewhere _ in more emotional, elemental ways
intended to resonate with consumers who tell market researchers
they value attributes like authenticity and optimism and have been
eschewing colas in favor of beverages like water, juices and
flavored teas.
</P>
<P>
   The overhaul of the flagship brand's advertising, marketing,
promotions and graphics, which amounts to a re-introduction of the
venerable soft drink, will end campaigns that have carried the
theme ``Always Coca-Cola'' since 1993. The changes will also
involve a revamping of Coca-Cola's relationship with its myriad
agencies around the world as the task of providing strategy for
sales pitches is centralized at the company and the duties for
creating ads for the flagship brand are narrowed to a shorter list
of shops. &QR;
</P>
<P>
   Charles S. Frenette, chief marketing officer at Coca-Cola in
Atlanta, outlined the new magic-tinged methods of selling Coke in a
90-minute interview Monday at the company's New York office in
midtown Manhattan. While he described as premature discussion of
details like the new brand theme, he discussed generally a sweeping
overhaul of how Coca-Cola will be sold, from redesigning employee
uniforms to increasing the availability of modern versions of
Coke's traditional contoured bottle.
</P>
<P>
   Frenette's talk of ``fireworks on the tongue'' and ``a little
magic'' generated by quaffing what he acknowledged was ``just a
soft drink'' sounded like phrases lifted from the pages of the
Harry Potter books. Coca-Cola could use such sorcery to enliven
sales of its flagship brand, which have been inching forward
worldwide but more slowly than during the 1970s and 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coca-Cola Classic has held its own through the '90s,'' said
Gary Hemphill, vice president at the Beverage Marketing Corp., a
research, data and consulting company in New York. ``But they
always want to do better.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Coca-Cola has gotten big by thinking small,'' he added,
``emphasizing broad-based marketing themes and focusing locally.
It's Coke's challenge to connect better with consumers.''
</P>
<P>
   The new campaigns for Coca-Cola will cover the United States and
overseas markets, where Coke sales have been disappointing in the
last year, hampered by economic crises and retail price increases.
</P>
<P>
   The reason ``Always'' is not forever is that although it
``served us extremely well,'' Frenette said, it was perhaps more
about ``Coca-Cola the institution'' than ``Coca-Cola the brand.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The strategy we're embarking upon is one of reconnecting with
consumers today,'' he added, by offering them ``an invitation to
view life through the optimistic lens that Coke provides.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're finding people looking for touchstones,'' he added,
``that are real and dependable and genuine.''
</P>
<P>
   Drinking a Coke is ``just a simple moment of refreshment,''
Frenette said. ``We don't make the moment, the consumer does; we
just add a little magic.''
</P>
<P>
   The new campaigns will be centered on a ``core proposition,'' a
strategic statement developed by Coca-Cola and shared with the
agencies: ``Only the unique sensory experience of an ice-cold
Coca-Cola brings a magical delight to the real moments of my
life.''
</P>
<P>
   Clearly the executives have spent considerable time thinking
about that. Frenette described Coca-Cola as offering ``enjoyment
inextricably linked to the power of the secret formula'' and
discussed how ``it awakens all of your senses.''
</P>
<P>
   The chief method to convey those intangibles will be to focus on
the contoured green-tinted glass bottle, the only Coca-Cola
container until the 1950's. The bottle _ originally six and a half
ounces, now eight _ has appeared recently on Coca-Cola labels,
signs and ads and inspired a successful line of 20-ounce contoured
plastic bottles.
</P>
<P>
   Now the smaller bottle _ with the word ``Coca-Cola'' embossed in
glass again _ will play an even more prominent role to help prod
sales. The company plans tactics from samplings in malls to
contests to installing ice chests at convenience stores. Even so,
Frenette said its role would be mainly promotional, adding that he
expected American consumers to keep buying Coke in cans and plastic
bottles.
</P>
<P>
   ``That bottle is a metaphor for Coca-Cola, a metaphor of what's
inside,'' said Frenette, who took over as the marketing chief 18
months ago from Sergio Zyman. ``When that bottle is in your hand,
it says something.''
</P>
<P>
   One analyst who follows Coca-Cola, Emanuel Goldman at Merrill
Lynch, praised the initiative because, he said, Coke in smaller
containers tastes better: ``By the time you're down to the lower
part of the 64-ounce bottle, you've lost the fizz. They're trying
to remind people the name of the game is refreshment.''
</P>
<P>
   Another reminder will be the new graphics, produced by Lipson
Alport Glass &AMP; Associates in Northbrook, Ill., along with an
in-house team at Coca-Cola. The graphics show the brand's name in
larger type under the word ``Enjoy,'' which has been identified
with Coke for decades. There is also a glass bottle tipped to one
side, its metal cap off and the contents fizzing up and out. The
familiar red disk logo, in one design, is topped with crushed ice.
</P>
<P>
   That emphasis on chilled Coca-Cola evokes the major investments
that bottlers have made, at the company's urging, in refrigerator
cases and other equipment. For instance, one bottler, Coca-Cola
Enterprises, announced a $5.2 billion investment plan last summer,
much of which was for such equipment.
</P>
<P>
   The exhortation to ``enjoy'' Coke comes as its primary
competitor, Pepsi-Cola _ sold by the Pepsi-Cola Company unit of
Pepsico Inc. _ urges consumers to taste ``the joy of cola.'' The
current Pepsi-Cola campaign, by the BBDO New York unit of BBDO
Worldwide, part of the Omnicom Group, is centered on an upbeat
jingle infused with a perception of bubbly fun.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not `The joy of cola' but the enjoyment of life,''
Frenette said. ``We're pretty confident we can stand on our own.'' &QR;
</P>
<P>
   As for the agency relationships, Frenette played down reports of
a shake-up in creative responsibilities. Rather, he described a
process that would be streamlined to place ``more focus'' on a
short list of shops that have been considered first for Coca-Cola
work in various countries.
</P>
<P>
   He listed: the Leo Burnett Co. unit of Leo Group; D'Arcy Masius
Benton &AMP; Bowles Communications, part of MacManus Group; Doner; Edge
Creative, the lead creative agency in the United States;
McCann-Erickson Worldwide Advertising, part of the McCann-Erickson
World Group unit of the Interpublic Group of Companies; Publicis,
part of Publicis SA, and Wieden &AMP; Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The difference is that they'll all be working off a common
strategy,'' Frenette said. ``And the winners are the ones who do
the best work.''
</P>
<P>
   With earnings shortfalls a problem, the company does not expect
to significantly increase its marketing budget to pay for the new
campaigns, Frenette said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
