<HEADER>
A1123 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BBN-NLCS-HNS &LR;      10-18 0676
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-NLCS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CARLTON THOMPSON  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
ATLANTA _ The move Atlanta Braves manager Bobby Cox didn't make at
the end of Sunday's wild Game 5 says all you need to know about his
level of confidence.
<TEXT>
<P>
   However, the way the New York Mets seem to respond in desperate
situations suggests Cox might be holding his feet just close enough
to the fire to get burned.
</P>
<P>
   Cox chose to stick with rookie reliever Kevin McGlinchy at the
end of Game 5 of the National League Championship Series, which
ended with Robin Ventura's game-winning ``grand single.''
</P>
<P>
   With the Braves still on top in the NLCS, Cox felt his best
course of action was to take his chances at Turner Field with Kevin
Millwood, who is scheduled to start tonight's game.
</P>
<P>
   Millwood and Game 3 starter Tom Glavine were available to pitch
the 15th inning Sunday. And either almost certainly would have been
a better option than McGlinchy.
</P>
<P>
   But of course, that's hindsight. What lies ahead for the Braves
is a suddenly serious challenge from a Mets team that refuses to
die.
</P>
<P>
   Down 3-0 in the best-of-seven series after Friday's game, the
Mets have momentum on their side as they bid to become the first
team to overcome a three-game deficit in a postseason series.
</P>
<P>
   Coincidentally, the Braves were down three games to San Diego in
the 1998 NLCS before losing in six games.
</P>
<P>
   While some teams might crack under this type of pressure, the
Mets seem to welcome the win-or-go-home challenge.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're kind of getting used to it,'' manager Bobby Valentine
said. ``It seems like we've been doing this for a couple of weeks
now.''
</P>
<P>
   To hold up their end of the Subway Series _ a possibility that
seemed derailed just a few days ago _ the Mets will have to work
their magic for a couple more days.
</P>
<P>
   New York has lost seven of eight games at Turner Field this
season, including Games 1 and 2 of the NLCS.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're still in the driver's seat,'' Braves reliever Russ
Springer said. ``It comes down to us winning one game. Obviously,
we'd rather do it in Game 6 than in Game 7, so we'll come out
scrapping. In a game (as long as Sunday's), whoever wins it has a
big win, and whoever loses it has a big loss, and it's magnified in
the playoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   Some wonder if the nature of Sunday's loss was so demoralizing
that the Braves won't be able to bounce back. Shortstop Walt Weiss
begs to differ.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's pretty easy to turn the page on one game when you play
every day for eight months,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   It would be a lot easier if the Braves had any semblance of an
offense. They left 19 runners on base in Sunday's 15-inning
marathon and are hitting .211 in the series. Four of the five games
have been decided by a run, and the other was a two-run victory by
the Braves.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, the lack of offense puts increased pressure on the
pitchers, who are forced to work with minimal margin for error.
That can be a difficult task for a pitcher, even one who has the
word ``Braves'' embroidered across the front of his jersey.
</P>
<P>
   Despite a terrific team ERA of 1.82 in the NLCS, the Braves
haven't been able to put the Mets away. Tonight, Millwood will get
a chance to deliver the knockout blow some thought he should have
been given an opportunity to give Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm excited,'' Millwood said. ``This is the place everyone
wants to be, pitching in a game like this. I'm pumped. Everyone
wants to do it in the postseason. If you're not pumped now, there's
something wrong with you.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the Braves have an advantage because they are home and
because Millwood will be pitching on five days' rest. Mets starter
Al Leiter will be working on three days' rest, something he hasn't
done since 1995, by his recollection.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm looking forward to it,'' he said. ``Why not? I've got four
months to rest. Any time there is a chance that your ballclub is
going home if you lose, you have to put on a good performance.''
</P>
<P>
   Somehow, some way, the Mets always seem to do just that.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
