<SLUG> BC-BBN-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METS CAN'T SAVE 3 RUNS VENTURA LOST
</HEADLINE>
  (With BBN-METS-BRAVES, BBN-COLUMN) 
 (nk) 
 By GEORGE VECSEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The more he thought about it, the more Robin Ventura
decided he would have liked that grand slam home run.
</P>
<P>
   He relayed that sentiment to Todd Pratt on the team charter
flight Monday, as the Mets flew down here, more or less on their
own steam, to see if they could terrorize the Braves any further
Tuesday night in the sixth game of this suddenly extended series.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had it all down,'' Pratt said. ``He was gonna do the Kirk
Gibson.''
</P>
<P>
   Ventura, playing with a knee just aching for some remedial
surgery, finally figured out that he could have emulated the
sore-legged hobble of Gibson, who hit the dramatic game-winning
homer in the 1988 World Series.
</P>
<P>
   Ventura never got the chance, however, after whacking the ball
over the fence with the bases loaded Sunday night, because Pratt
turned back from second base and initiated an emotional mosh pit,
with Ventura at the bottom of the scrum.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was busting on me,'' Pratt recalled. ``He was saying that I
was the only one who could do the home run trot.''
</P>
<P>
   The plot thickens. It was Pratt, you see, who hit the home run
to win the previous series with Arizona. Pratt made all the
highlight films with his dramatic gestures and low-gear rumble as
he passed first base. He has a tape of it back home. There will
never be a tape of Ventura chugging around the bases, gamely
dragging his sore leg behind him, because Pratt intercepted him.
</P>
<P>
   As it turns out, Pratt did not consciously choose to disrupt a
grand slam home run. He had tied the game with a bases-loaded walk
off Kevin McGlinchy while sporting this huge almost disconcerting
smile on his face. (``It was weird,'' Pratt said. ``I knew he had
to throw me strikes. I knew I'd tie the game.'') Then Pratt never
saw Ventura's shot go over the fence.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw the trajectory, and I thought it was a gapper,'' Pratt
explained Monday. ``I knew I had to touch second and the game was
over, and then I used the base as a sprinter's block and I ran to
Robin.''
</P>
<P>
   What's three runs between friends? Now, who wants to be the
designated worrywart to fret that the Mets may just have set off
some bad vibrations by their giddy little celebration in the swamp
of Flushing Meadow? Instead of a four-run victory, the Mets had a
4-3 triumph in 15 classic innings, enough to propel them down here
for the sixth game.
</P>
<P>
   I had not thought through the implications of those three
squandered runs. There were too many other things to think about on
that manic night, with the Mets winning one of the most epic games
in franchise history. Five hours into the game, in a steady
drizzle, there were still more Mets fans in Shea than there were in
arid Turner Field for the first and second games of this series.
</P>
<P>
   Here in the land where foo'ball is king, I ran into a baseball
buff who was clearly preoccupied with the rashness of the Mets'
celebration. The Lenny 4 gleaming from his forehead was a subtle
clue that he was a Mets fan.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know, I know, you can't carry over those runs to the next
game, I mean, not officially,'' said the fan, who identified
himself as Dave From Inman Park, originally from Long Island. ``But
I can just see it if the series goes seven. I can see Glavine on
the mound, smirking and saying, `Oh, so you can afford to just toss
away three runs, huh?'
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm afraid of what could happen in the future,'' added the
brooding Mets fan. ``His kid is going to go to junior high school
and some wise guy is going to say, `Hey, I thought your old man hit
a grand slam to win a famous playoff game for the Mets. It says
here in the record book that he only hit a single.'''
</P>
<P>
   Bobby Valentine, the Mets' manager, noted that Ventura has ``a
knack for grand slams,'' 13 in his career, and that it is too bad
the Sunday shot will not count.
</P>
<P>
   ``He  &UR; did  &LR;  hit it,'' Valentine said Monday. ``I hope there's an
asterisk.''
</P>
<P>
   There will be no asterisk. Ventura had seemed to motion to Pratt
to keep running before the hugfest got out of hand. And Ventura
assured reporters that he was fine with the loss of the grand slam,
but he did quip that he might feel differently after we all cleared
out of the clubhouse and he had time to think about it.
</P>
<P>
   By Monday, Ventura was busting on Pratt, the banter between
athletes who have suddenly done something remarkable, who have
prolonged their season and just might have more to say and do.
</P>
<P>
   Now they are down here, in the land where fans deliver a banal
tomahawk chop, a gesture borrowed from a university in another
state, for goodness' sakes. The record book may never identify that
Robin Ventura hit one over the wall in the 15th inning on Sunday.
But the Mets know he did. And so do the Braves.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
