<SLUG> BC-RITEAID-SHAKEUP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHIEF IS OUSTED AT RITE AID AND EARNINGS ARE RESTATED 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Pa.)  (mk) 
 By RICHARD A. OPPEL Jr.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Directors of Rite Aid Corp. stepped in Monday in an effort to
stem a series of disasters at the nation's third-largest drugstore
chain, ousting Martin Grass, the chief executive, announcing that
the company will restate $500 million in pretax earnings since
1997, and placing control with four independent board members.
</P>
<P>
   With those changes, the company said that its lead bankers had
agreed to extend by one year $2.7 billion in loans and other debt
that had been due on Oct. 29. It said that Leonard Green &AMP;
Partners, the Los Angeles investment boutique, had agreed to invest
$300 million in new preferred stock that can be converted into
common shares worth 9.7 percent of the company.
</P>
<P>
   While the restatement will wipe out most of the company's pretax
earnings for the last three fiscal years, the moves, taken as a
whole, are good news for investors, some analysts said. They said
the heavy-handed management of Grass, along with a series of
problems this year, had badly damaged the company's credibility
with investors. And while Wall Street had been expecting a serious
earnings restatement, it had not been clear until Monday night that
the banks would roll their loans over.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Rite Aid have dropped 80 percent this year as the
company badly missed earnings expectations, said it would have to
restate earnings, and was charged last month by the Florida
attorney general with illegally overcharging uninsured pharmacy
customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the end of the Grass dynasty,'' said Mark Husson, a
drugstore analyst at Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co. ``The directors and the
banks must have been very upset and frustrated and lacked
confidence in current management's ability to control this
business.''
</P>
<P>
   While the earnings restatement is severe, Husson said, investors
should be relieved that the banks agreed to the extension, and he
said the stock could rise in trading Tuesday from its close Monday
of $9.625. But he noted that the company did not say what interest
rate the banks would charge, and he said it might be some time
before investors and analysts are able to sort out Rite Aid's true
financial picture. The big restatements ``make you wonder what the
underlying earnings power of this company is,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In an announcement Monday night, Rite Aid said its president and
chief operating officer, Timothy Noonan, had been appointed interim
chief executive. But the company also said that the board had
created an executive committee of four outside directors: Gerald
Tsai, the former Fidelity mutual fund manager; Preston Robert
Tisch, the co-chairman of Loews Corp.; Leonard Stern, the chairman
of Hartz Group, and Nancy Lieberman, a partner at the law firm
Skadden, Arps, Slate, Meagher &AMP; Flom.
</P>
<P>
   The company, based in Camp Hill, Pa., also said it had not been
able to find a permanent replacement for its former chief financial
officer, Frank Bergonzi, who said in June that he would resign. And
the company said it would delay the filing of its quarterly 10-Q
statement with the SEC, which had been expected Monday, but that
the document would show no ``material differences'' with
projections the company made on Oct. 11, when it said it expected a
second-quarter loss of $67.9 million, or 26 cents a share.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Grass, the son of company founder Alex Grass, nor Noonan
could be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   A company spokeswoman, Sarah Datz, said the executive committee
was formed to act for the full board between meetings and that it
would oversee the search for a permanent chief executive. She said
the earnings restatement came in response to issues raised in the
SEC review but said the company has not been told by the agency
that any legal action was expected. She also declined to say
whether the loan rollover was contingent on the departure of Grass.
</P>
<P>
   A secretary for Leonard Green, founding partner of Leonard Green
&AMP; Partners, said Green had no comment on the matter beyond a
written statement, in which he said his investment ``reflects the
confidence we have in Rite Aid's core business.''
</P>
<P>
   Green will join the directors' executive committee after his
investment closes, the company said. The preferred stock he will
receive will pay an 8 percent pay-in-kind dividend _ meaning
dividends will come in the form of more preferred stock. But in
what may be a good sign for investors, Green agreed to the
conversion price of $11, about 14.3 percent above Monday's closing
price.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
