<HEADLINE>
HACKETT'S HACKLES RAISED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The search for answers following USC's two-game
losing streak has left USC coach Paul Hackett speechless. Almost.
</P>
<P>
   ``The talking's over. There's nothing to say,'' Hackett said.
``Until we go out and do something, I have nothing to say.''
</P>
<P>
   The self-imposed gag order didn't last long, but it's clear
Hackett is frustrated over the Trojans' inability to play a
complete game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm all of out of tricks,'' Hackett said. ``We've got to go
out and play. I don't know whether the first-half or second-half
team will show up.''
</P>
<P>
   Hackett is disturbed that USC has blown fourth-quarter leads to
Oregon and Notre Dame, and a third-quarter lead to Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought we learned our lesson (last year) against Cal,''
Hackett said of USC blowing a 21-point lead.
</P>
<P>
   Hackett also chose not to talk about Saturday's opponent,
Stanford (4-2, 4-0), which is atop the Pacific-10 Conference
standings.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't worry about anybody,'' Hackett said. ``We can't win a
game. We're .500.''
</P>
<P>
   His anger was not just restricted to how the Trojans (3-3, 1-2)
will play this week. Asked how his team's injured players were
recovering from the Notre Dame game, Hackett said: ``I have no idea
and I don't care. Whoever's ready to play will play.''
</P>
<P>
   Free safety David Gibson echoed Hackett's belief that words no
longer suffice when talking about the Trojans' performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the talking's been done. It's all lip service,'' Gibson
said. ``Everyone just has to take it as a man and perform. We pride
ourselves on playing great defense and didn't step forward (against
Notre Dame).''
</P>
<P>
   Road kill: Wide receiver R. Jay Soward said USC's main problem
is figuring out how to win on the road.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to learn how to like getting on airplanes and
winning in other people's houses,'' Soward said.
</P>
<P>
   As unrealistic as it sounds, Soward is talking about USC's Rose
Bowl hopes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stanford is the only team undefeated,'' he said. ``It can be a
nine-way tie for the championship.''
</P>
<P>
   Rough result: So was the 25-24 loss to Notre Dame the toughest
of Hackett's career? ``It's right up there,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Double jeopardy: For the first time since Hackett became head
coach, USC has lost back-to-back games.
</P>
<P>
   Club 100: USC has had two receivers with 100-or-more yards
receiving the past two games. Windrell Hayes (115) and Kareem Kelly
(100) surpassed the century mark against Arizona; Hayes (107) and
R. Jay Soward (101) did it against Notre Dame.
</P>
<P>
   What's the rush? USC is averaging 2.9 yards per carry, which is
on pace to be the Trojans' lowest average since the 1991 season,
when the average-per-carry was 2.66 yards.
</P>
<P>
   USC's all-time low in yards-per-carry since records were kept
was 2.51 in 1949.
</P>
<P>
   Cal game time: USC's game at Cal on Oct. 30 will kick off at
3:30 p.m. and be televised locally on Channel 9 (KCAL-TV).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
