<SLUG> BC-BBN-TV-SPORTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TV SPORTS: FOR MORGAN, SO MUCH TO SAY AND SO LITTLE TIME
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By RICHARD SANDOMIR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   One of Joe Morgan's frustrations as a baseball analyst for NBC
and ESPN is the lack of sufficient time to say everything that is
on his mind. Part of that stems from Morgan's failure to be a
chatterbox seeking to hog every free moment for himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always feel the game is more important than my comments,''
he said Monday from his hotel in Atlanta, where he and Bob Costas
will call Game 6 of the National League Championship Series on
Tuesday night. ``If a guy is ready to hit the ball, it's more
important than what I have to say. If I talk during a home run,
that's the biggest sin I can commit.''
</P>
<P>
   Morgan's education as a broadcaster entered the master's phase
during his years as the Cincinnati Reds' second baseman, discussing
how a pitcher cocked his curveball with Johnny Bench or how a
hitter dropped his shoulder with Pete Rose.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every play contains something unique,'' he said. But he rarely
says it all. ``It's hard to say everything, because I'd be
preaching at you.''
</P>
<P>
   So here's a chance for Morgan to amplify and illuminate some of
his insights during Sunday's epic Game 5 of the Mets-Braves series.
</P>
<P>
   Mets first baseman John Olerud holds runners by starting off the
bag, then scampering back for a pickoff throw: ``It started with
Chuck Tanner, when he was managing the Pirates. When I played, he
moved Willie Stargell off the bag to stand in front of me and block
my view of the pitcher. I complained that he can't move around the
way he did, that you have to stand still in front of me. The Mets
take that correct approach, then Olerud broke to the bag. A good
base stealer should eat that up and take off. If the pitcher throws
to Olerud, he has to hit a moving target whose momentum is moving
toward first when he throws to second. But yesterday, with the game
on the line, Olerud held runners on.''
</P>
<P>
   Mets reliever Dennis Cook appears in the seventh inning, throws
two pitches to complete a walk that was credited to Turk Wendell.
``I played baseball for 20-plus years, and the term was always, `He
has to pitch to a batter.' So it's a 2-0 count, he comes in, and
the walk goes to Wendell. He doesn't have a line. He was 0-0-0. If
he came in with a 1-0 count and walks the guy, it's his walk.
That's the confusion. The umpires were confused. I rode in today
with one of the umpires, Ed Montague, and he said, `We all had to
think about it.''' (Cook was credited with facing one batter, then
was removed.)
</P>
<P>
   The Mets' Shawon Dunston fouls off half a dozen pitches with a
3-2 count in the 15th inning and then singles off the loser, Kevin
McGlinchy: ``Guys like Tony Gwynn keep fouling off pitches until
you make a mistake. The greatest I ever saw at that was Rico Carty,
the best at getting two strikes and fouling pitches off until he
got a good pitch. When he got it, he grunted. Carew and Brett could
do it. Normal hitters don't do it. I don't know if Dunston intended
to do it, but he did. Dunston's at-bat was the key one in the game,
forgetting Olerud and Ventura's home runs. Dunston's at-bat led off
the inning.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mets' pitching coach, Dave Wallace, confers with reliever
Octavio Dotel in the 15th; on the air, Morgan says it is to warn
Dotel that Keith Lockhart is a good fastball hitter. ``The Braves
had three good fastball hitters _ Gerald Williams, Lockhart and
Chipper Jones. They can hit anybody's fastball and Dotel only has
one pitch. So the matchup wasn't good for the Mets. Dotel had no
choice but to throw him a fastball, so Wallace was there only to
tell him where to throw it.'' Dotel did not heed the lesson well
enough; Lockhart slashed a fastball for a triple.
</P>
<P>
   Regarding Game 6, Morgan is bullish on the Mets.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this point, the Mets' offense is better than the Braves',''
he said. ``The Mets can put up numbers, with Henderson's speed, and
Alfonzo, Olerud, Piazza and Ventura who can drive in runs. They
have a better offense, but the Braves' pitching is better. But you
look at the Braves' lineup, and you wonder how they're going to
generate runs. The Mets are capable of stringing together eight
hits in a row. I don't think the Braves can hit three in a row.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Sunday's Game 5 was memorable for more than its 5-hour-46-minute
length. The game held a vise grip on viewing in the New York
market.
</P>
<P>
   It began on NBC's Channel 4 with a 16.1 local Nielsen rating
from 4:15 to 4:30 p.m., concluded from 9:30 to 10 p.m. with a 36.9
rating, and was seen by 52 percent of the local television
households watching TV at the time.
</P>
<P>
   That kind of single-minded focus on one program is rarely seen
except in mega-events. Last January, Fox-owned Channel 5 averaged a
38.4 local rating for the Super Bowl, and grabbed 56 percent of the
homes with their TV sets on.
</P>
<P>
   While the Mets were beating Atlanta, the prime-time competition
was almost in hiding. In those final 15 minutes, the Yankees-Red
Sox game on Channel 5 rated a 4.1; a Farrah Fawcett movie, ``Silk
Hope,'' on Channel 2 had a 4.7 rating and ``Snoops,'' on Channel 7,
a 5.4.
</P>
<P>
   The two playoff games overlapped for two and a half hours, and
the Mets' telecast overwhelmed the Yankees'. But during that time,
they controlled 53 percent to 63 percent of the local market's TV
sets in use.
</P>
<P>
   Once the Mets won, the Yankee game leaped locally to a 22.7
rating from 10 to 10:30 p.m., and rose to a 27.0 in its final
half-hour, from 11 to 11:30 p.m.
</P>
</TEXT>
