<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: THE FACE OF BASEBALL  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: Adds Mora's age, corrects spelling of his home town in
Venezuela.)  By WILLIAM RHODEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Who is Melvin Mora?
</P>
<P>
   Mora is the Met who made his way out to left field on Saturday
with the uncomfortable mission of having to tell Rickey Henderson
that he had to come out of the game. This was the top of the eighth
inning in Game 4 of the National League playoffs last Saturday
night, a full house at Shea Stadium, another tight game. Usually
the switch _ Mora was replacing Henderson for defensive purposes _
would have been made between innings, in the privacy of the Mets
dugout. But Bobby Valentine, the Mets manager, said he had
forgotten. So he sent the quiet, mild-mannered Mora to break the
news.
</P>
<P>
   Mora, thanks to Valentine, was well schooled in this kind of
humiliation. A similar experience happened to him last April, at
the end of a successful spring training. Mora thought he had made
the Mets' 25 player roster. He had outperformed his nearest
competitor _ hitting, fielding and exhibiting the proper attitude.
Finally after seven years in the minors, Mora, 27, was going North
to open the '99 season as a major leaguer.
</P>
<P>
   His bags were already on the bus as the team prepared to head to
Texas for the last exhibition game. That's when Mora got the news:
He had not made the roster and would be demoted. The Mets _ i.e.,
Bobby Valentine _ forgot to tell him, just as he'd forgot to tell
Henderson Saturday. Mora's bags had to be retrieved off the truck
headed to the airport.
</P>
<P>
   Mora was crushed. When someone asked him to describe his
emotions, Mora said ``I feel like I want to go to a bridge and jump
off.''
</P>
<P>
   So on Saturday, he broke the news to Henderson and watched him
leave the field angry, embarrassed. Mora understood. But he also
remembered how he'd kept his own spirits up when he was demoted in
the spring. ``I wasn't angry, I was sad,'' he said. ``But I told
myself I don't make decisions; I have to accept whatever they say
and continue to work. Now I have the opportunity to show everyone
that I can play, because if you can play in the playoffs, you can
play in the regular season.''
</P>
<P>
   Six months after the spring training disappointment, Mora is the
leader of an undercard of unsung Mets players who have propelled
the team from 0-3 series deficit to an unlikely Game 6 against
Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   The quest for respect began on Oct. 3, in the last game of the
regular season, when Mora, a rookie with just five hits to his name
this season, reached on a one-out single in the ninth inning. When
fellow Venezuelan Edgardo Alfonzo singled, Mora sped around second
and dived headfirst into third as the crowd went wild. Moments
later he raced home with the winning run on a wild pitch. The Mets
defeated Pittsburgh and earned the right to play Cincinnati for the
wild-card berth.
</P>
<P>
   Last Friday, Mora made his third start of the season as part of
Valentine's lineup shakeup. He kept a close game close when he
threw a perfect strike to Mike Piazza to nail Bret Boone at the
plate. On Saturday, after replacing Henderson, Mora executed a
daring baseball play when he initiated a double steal with Roger
Cedeno on second, Mora on first and John Rocker on the mound. Mora
remembered being on third base in Atlanta and faking like he was
straying home, and saw how nervous it made Rocker.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told Roger we have to put pressure on this guy,'' Mora
recalled. ``With a man at second base he's going to throw a lot of
pitches in the dirt; a man on third base is a different story _ he
has to throw strikes.''
</P>
<P>
   They executed the double steal, and then a John Olerud smash
grazed off Ozzie Guillen's glove and allowed both runners to score.
In a critical juncture of the game on Sunday, Mora may have saved
the game for the Mets when, in a heavy drizzle, he cut off a
hard-hit ball before it reached the right field wall, then fired
the wet ball to Alfonzo, who fired to Mike Piazza, who applied the
tag.
</P>
<P>
   Who is Melvin Mora? Mora is the face of baseball.
</P>
<P>
   Born in Agua Negra, Venezuela, Mora came out of the Houston
Astros' academy in Valencia, but was overshadowed by other players
regarded as better major league prospects. Houston kept him on one
of their minor league clubs for six years. When the Astros did not
invite him to major league camp in 1997 Mora thought about quitting
baseball. Instead of doing that or going back to Triple A, Mora
went to the Chinese Professional Baseball League in Taiwan, though
he left a month and a half later.
</P>
<P>
   Back in the United States, Mora contacted Edgar Alfonzo,
Edgardo's brother, a coach with the Mets' Class A affiliate in Port
St. Lucie. Alfonzo put Mora in contact with Jim Duquette, the Mets
assistant general manager of player personnel. Duquette offered
Mora a utility role with the Mets A team in St. Lucie.
</P>
<P>
   Now, in what seems like a lifetime later, he's headed for Game 6
in Atlanta. Even as he does, he embodies for some the indomitable
spirit of the minor leagues. Bobby Floyd, the minor league field
coordinator, saw Mora when he returned from Taiwan and again when
he returned to AAA after failing to make the 25-plater roster this
spring.
</P>
<P>
   ``Melvin never quit,'' Floyd said Monday from Melbourne, Fla.
``It's like a fighter that keeps getting knocked down; he gets back
up and you just he will never let go until everybody _ everybody _
says `no we don't want you.' It's that wanting to go out there and
do it one more time, giving it all you've got and being able to say
to yourself when its all over and done that you gave it every shot
you could.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-18-99 2320EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
