<SLUG> BC-BBA-NLCS-ADVANCE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRAVES ARE BACK AT HOME AND CONFIDENT FOR GAME 6
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The Atlanta Braves are not ready to panic.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Mets coming to town after winning two in a row is
not viewed with the same dread and despair as Sherman marching in
with the Union Army 135 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves still have good reason to feel confident about a
return to the World Series for the fifth time in this decade. They
still lead the National League Championship Series three games to
two when it resumes tonight at Turner Field.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still feel good about our chances,'' Braves pitcher Greg
Maddux said. ``We've been down this road before.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mets might have at least halted the Braves' momentum by
winning the past two games at Shea Stadium, including the 15-inning
4-3 thriller Sunday. But other factors favor the Braves.
</P>
<P>
   First of all, the final two games are at Turner Field. The
Braves, unlike most playoff teams, might have trouble selling out
their place during the postseason, but they still play well there.
They went 56-25 at Turner Field during the season, including 5-1
against the Mets. They swept three from the Mets at home Sept.
21-23.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no mystery we haven't done well in Atlanta,'' Mets
center fielder Darryl Hamilton said. ``The one thing we have going
for us is everybody expects us to lose because no team has ever
come back from being down 3-0 in a series. I'm sure we still feel a
little pressure, but I'm sure those guys don't want to be the first
team to lose after being up 3-0.''
</P>
<P>
   Second, the Braves still have their pitching rotation intact.
Manager Bobby Cox resisted the temptation to use Game 6 starter
Kevin Millwood or Game 7 starter Tom Glavine in relief during
Sunday's 15-inning affair.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves didn't win the game, but Millwood will be fully
rested for tonight's game, as will Glavine if Game 7 is needed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm excited,'' said Millwood, who beat the Mets in Game 2
Wednesday. ``This is the place that everybody wants to be in,
pitching in a game like this. I'm pumped.''
</P>
<P>
   Mets manager Bobby Valentine has to improvise to get his
rotation back in order. He will start Al Leiter on three days rest
tonight and Rick Reed tomorrow, also on three days. They normally
get four days off between starts during the regular season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm looking forward to it,'' Leiter said. ``Why not? I've got
four months to rest.''
</P>
<P>
   Catcher Mike Piazza probably needs four months off right now
after two collisions at home plate in three games at Shea Stadium.
Piazza suffered a slight concussion in Game 3 when Bret Boone
crashed into him trying to score on a sacrifice fly. He also had to
leave Game 5 in the 14th inning when Keith Lockhart slammed into
him trying to score from first on a double.
</P>
<P>
   Piazza suffered a strained left forearm, basically the same spot
where Braves first baseman Ryan Klesko whacked him with his
backswing earlier in the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm banged up,'' Piazza said. ``But I'll go out there and do
whatever I can.''
</P>
<P>
   Both sides are well-aware no team in major-league history has
come back from three games down to win a best-of-seven series. The
Braves flirted with doing that last year when they lost three in a
row to the San Diego Padres in the NLCS, then won the next two.
Their hopes died, though, when they returned to Turner Field and
lost Game 6.
</P>
<P>
   But they realize now the Mets are dangerous, no matter how much
the Braves dominated them during the regular season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any team, you give them a chance to win,'' Cox said. ``Nobody
is going to give up once you've gotten this far. Nobody is. Every
team should be the same way.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-18-99 2325EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
