<HEADLINE>
TEXAS NOT IN AWE OF NEBRASKA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIMMY BURCH 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Texas coaches and players spent yesterday
expressing concern about Nebraska's option game but confidence in
their ability to extend a two-game winning streak against the
unbeaten Cornhuskers.
</P>
<P>
   Since the Big 12 began playing football in 1996, No. 18 Texas
(5-2, 2-1) is the only league school with a winning record against
No. 3 Nebraska (6-0, 3-0) heading into a 2:30 p.m. meeting Saturday
at Royal-Memorial Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The Longhorns are 2-0 against the Cornhuskers, prevailing both
times as double-digit underdogs. Texas won the 1996 league title
game, 37-27, in St. Louis and pulled a 20-16 upset last season in
Lincoln, Neb., ending the Cornhuskers' 47-game home winning streak.
</P>
<P>
   Texas finds itself in familiar territory again this week. The
Longhorns are 91/2-point underdogs. But they don't feel like it,
said wide receiver Ryan Nunez.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no doubt in my mind we can win. They're beatable,''
Nunez said. ``Take that logo off their helmets and they're just
another team. That's something Coach \RMack\S Brown has mentioned
and it's so true.''
</P>
<P>
   The key to Texas' success, said defensive end Cedric Woodard, is
viewing Nebraska with respect, not awe. Other teams, said Woodard,
tend to be intimidated by the Cornhuskers' 25-4 record against
league foes.
</P>
<P>
   Because half of those losses came against the Longhorns, Woodard
said: ``We realize we can play with them. They're just regular
players, like we are. You have to think that they are men, like we
are men. If you look at it like that, it's not as bad.''
</P>
<P>
   What is bad, from a Texas perspective, is finding a way to slow
an option-based attack that ranks seventh nationally in scoring
offense (39 points per game). Nebraksa also is third in total
defense, allowing 230.8 yards and 9.7 points per game. But it is
the Cornhuskers' option game that presents the greatest challenge,
said Brown.
</P>
<P>
   ``The defense needs to penetrate and create havoc,'' Brown said.
``That's how you stop the option. If you don't stop their option,
you'll never see a pass. You need to make them two-dimensional. If
you don't, the game is over and you were never in it.''
</P>
<P>
   In the Longhorns' lone contest this season against an option
attack, Texas surrendered 209 rushing yards in an 18-13 victory
over Rice. Brown said his team did not create penetration or havoc
``until the fourth quarter'' against the Owls and must
significantly step up the timetable against Nebraska.
</P>
<P>
   As for the team's two-game winning streak against the
Cornhuskers, Brown said: ``It gives our team some confidence. But
usually, the best team wins on Saturday.'' \Nsubheds:Briefly
</P>
<P>
   The ESPN Game Day crew (Chris Fowler, Lee Corso and Kirk
Herbstreit) will be in Austin for Saturday's game, marking the
show's first visit to Royal-Memorial Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Kickoff for the Longhorns' Oct. 30 game at Iowa State has been
moved to 11:30 a.m. so the game can be shown as a Big 12 syndicated
telecast on KXTX/Ch. 39.
</P>
<P>
   Reserve tailback Victor Ike (ankle) remains questionable for
Saturday's game. Brown said three other players who have been
nursing ankle injuries (offensive tackle Leonard Davis and
linebackers De'Andre Lewis and Aaron Babino) are ``the best they've
been all season'' in terms of physical conditioning after last
week's open date.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
