<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-UCLA-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UCLA LOOKS TO IMPROVE SECONDARY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Hoping to seal his porous secondary, UCLA coach
Bob Toledo said Monday that redshirt freshman Lovell Houston, a
huge talent with no experience, will compete for strong safety Eric
Whitfield's starting job.
</P>
<P>
   Whitfield, a fifth-year senior, has missed tackles and blown
coverages in several games, including Saturday's 17-0 loss to Cal.
The Bears had five plays accounting for 184 yards, and Toledo said
Whitfield was involved _ or not involved _ in four.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the most experienced guy, but there comes a point when
you look at somebody else if guys don't play better,'' Toledo said.
</P>
<P>
   Houston, a former Parade All-American who picked UCLA over
Florida State, has been injured numerous times since his arrival
last fall. He recently switched from cornerback to safety and has
less game experience than some true freshmen. The Bruins aren't
sure he's ready, but they're desperate.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to try to force-feed him,'' Toledo said. ``If he
can't do it in practice, he won't start. But we're going to give
him the opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   That's not all: The situation isn't as dire at weakside
linebacker, but true freshman Marcus Reese could supplant starter
Ryan Nece with an impressive week of practice.
</P>
<P>
   Nece was UCLA's No.2 tackler last year and earned
honorable-mention All-Pac-10 honors. But he lacks Reese's speed,
and against Oregon State's aerial attack _ the Beavers lead the
Pac-10 in passing with 327 yards per game _ athleticism is
essential.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not that Nece has played that poorly, but we need to get
(Reese) in more,'' Toledo said.
</P>
<P>
   Bell update: It appears senior cornerback Jason Bell will
redshirt because of post-surgery pain in his right heel. He hasn't
played since the Ohio State game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just going to ride out the year and see what happens,'' he
said. ``But each game, (redshirting) gets closer.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he could return in a week or two, Bell said: ``Not
unless something miraculous occurs.... I'm walking with less pain,
but right now, running is a no.''
</P>
<P>
   Stat of the week: In its last three games, UCLA has been
outscored 43-6 in the fourth quarter, with four turnovers and a
blocked field goal.
</P>
<P>
   Injury update: Tailback DeShaun Foster (sprained ankle) won't
play Saturday on Oregon State's artificial turf. Foster, who has
three carries in the last three games, might return for Arizona on
Oct. 30.
</P>
<P>
   ``The (OSU) turf grabs your cleats, and he doesn't need anything
grabbing his cleats,'' Toledo said.
</P>
<P>
   Linebacker Ali Abdul Azziz (sprained shoulder) is doubtful.
Billy Pieper will replace Azziz as the No. 2 outside linebacker
behind Tony White.
</P>
<P>
   Tight ends Bryan Fletcher (strained groin) and Mike Seidman
(sprained shoulder) are questionable.
</P>
<P>
   Receiver Freddie Mitchell, tailback Jermaine Lewis and Whitfield
did not practice Monday because of an upper-respiratory infection.
</P>
<P>
   Odds and ends: After his Sunday film session _ yes, it looked as
bad on tape as it did in person _ Toledo did not name players of
the game. He also delayed naming captains until later this week.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins weren't fazed by the Hector Mines earthquake Saturday
morning. ``My room shook for quite a while,'' fullback Durell Price
said, ``but I didn't budge. I was in Sylmar for the Northridge
quake. This was nothing compared to that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
