<HEADER>
A1252 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBA-UMPIRES-NYT &LR;      10-18 1219
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-UMPIRES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KIND OF BLUE: UMPS UNWITTINGLY BECOME THE STORY
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Bill Buckner is headlined in history, obscuring
previous mistakes by the Boston Red Sox before his error ended Game
6 of the 1986 World Series. And similarly, what Boston fans will
remember years from now is not that the gritty Red Sox really did
not play well against the Yankees in the 1999 American League
Championship Series, but that they were victimized by umpires.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's bad enough that we've got to beat the Yankees,'' one fan
was bemoaning while filing out of Fenway Park after Game 4 on
Sunday night. ``But the umps are sticking it to us, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Twice in the first four games, umpires committed blunders on
calls from which the Yankees benefited, and their subsequent
admissions of error will not reduce the disgust of the Red Sox or
their fans. Like the first in a row of falling dominoes, that rage
led to fans throwing bottles and other debris on the field in the
ninth inning of the Yankees' 9-2 victory Sunday, the Yankees being
ordered off the field by umpires, and a brief and nasty
confrontation between Yankees personnel and two members of the Red
Sox security detail.
</P>
<P>
   Sandy Alderson, the executive vice president of Major League
Baseball, said that Kevin Hallinan, baseball's top security
officer, arrived here from New York on Monday to oversee operations
for Game 5.
</P>
<P>
   But the most substantive discussions on how the umpires could
improve will take place in the off-season, Alderson said. He
mentioned the possibility that umpires will view videotape as part
of their training, review procedures and positioning for common
calls and discuss the protocol for consulting on decisions.
</P>
<P>
   Alderson dodged a question about whether he thinks there is a
place in baseball for video replay, but he mentioned that instant
replay in baseball, because of ``its texture,'' might be unwieldy.
Alderson did not rule out that the use of instant replay would be
discussed, and he mentioned how the umpires' mistakes in the
post-season were indelible.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball fans here will always recall Larry Barnett's decision
that Ed Armbrister of Cincinnati did not interfere with catcher
Carlton Fisk of Boston while bunting at a critical juncture of the
1975 World Series, and fans everywhere will never forget the
mistaken safe call by Don Denkinger at first base in Game 6 of the
1985 World Series, which led to Kansas City eventually defeating
St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   And if Boston loses this series, Red Sox fans, who are blessed _
or cursed _ with exceptional retention, will always remember the
umpires' errors, more so than Boston's failure to hit with runners
in scoring position in Games 1 or 2, or the 11 errors made by the
Red Sox in the first four games of the series.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees were winning, 3-2, in the bottom of the eighth
inning of Game 4. Boston's Jose Offerman was on first base with one
out, and Mariano Rivera was pitching. John Valentin hit a roller to
second baseman Chuck Knoblauch, who rushed in, gloved the ball and
attempted to tag Offerman.
</P>
<P>
   Knoblauch swiped his glove at Offerman, and then flipped to
first to retire Valentin. But Tim Tschida, the umpire at second
base, ruled that Knoblauch had tagged Offerman, meaning an
inning-ending double play. The Red Sox runner, the first-base coach
Dave Jauss and Manager Jimy Williams all argued the call.
</P>
<P>
   Tschida later viewed videotape of the play and saw what millions
around the country had seen: Knoblauch's glove missing Offerman's
right side by a substantial margin. There was no question. ``I
didn't make the right call,'' Tschida acknowledged.
</P>
<P>
   When asked if he had sought input from another umpire, Tschida
said that even Williams had told him he understood that no other
umpire could be consulted on the play because no other umpire was
in position to make the call. But Monday, Williams had an entirely
different interpretation of his conversation with Tschida.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to ask somebody around here for help, just to make
sure you get the call right,''' Williams recalled saying to
Tschida. ``Because that's all I've ever been told by other umpires
in situations where they changed a decision against a club I was
managing.''
</P>
<P>
   Nobody will ever know what would have happened if Tschida had
called the play correctly and Offerman had been ruled safe. At
best, the Red Sox would have faced a difficult situation, two outs
and a runner at second and a need for a clutch hit. Nomar
Garciaparra, the American League batting champion, was scheduled to
hit and the Yankees might have pitched around him and then Rivera
would have been pitching to Mike Stanley.
</P>
<P>
   Rivera has not blown a save in three months, so it would be hard
to assume Stanley would have tied the score. But Williams would
have liked to take his chances; he would have liked the players to
have full control over the outcome.
</P>
<P>
   What gnawed at Williams, the Red Sox and their fans is that, for
the second time in five days, an umpire's call robbed them of an
opportunity. In the 11th inning of Game 1, Knoblauch dropped a
throw at second base, but the second-base umpire Rick Reed called
the runner out _ saying that Knoblauch lost the ball as he began a
double-play attempt.
</P>
<P>
   So instead of having runners at first and second and nobody out
with the heart of their lineup coming up in a tie game, the Red Sox
rally was sabotaged.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody makes mistakes,'' Williams said. ``I probably made
more than anybody in here. But I try to 0ilize our coaches the best
I can to help us in a game situation. So to me, that's trying to be
a team to win a game as a unit. To me, as umpires, you're trying to
officiate a game properly as a unit so it's fair for both sides.''
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees scored six runs in the top of the ninth inning of
Game 4, all but finishing the Red Sox. Garciaparra led off the
bottom of the ninth and grounded to third, and it appeared he had
beaten Scott Brosius' throw from third. But the umpire Dale Scott
called him out, and Williams exploded.
</P>
<P>
   After arguing at length, he threw his cap _ an act for which he
was ejected _ and kicked the dirt, the fans yelling all the while.
A fan launched a water bottle from the stands on the first-base
side, and soon there were many items airborne. Later, the Yankees'
principal owner, George Steinbrenner, said Williams had incited the
fans.
</P>
<P>
   Williams' response Monday: ``When Georgie Porgie speaks, I don't
listen. I didn't incite the fans. The situation incited the fans.''
</P>
<P>
   Alderson said he did not believe Williams had incited the fans,
adding that as a manager, Williams often has a responsibility to
his team and the fans to express his displeasure with a call.
</P>
<P>
   When the assault of debris intensified, the Yankees were waved
off the field by Al Clark, the home-plate umpire. As the Yankees
descended into their dugout, some exchanged words with fans behind
the visitors' dugout. Several Yankees said that Steve Corcoran, the
head of security for the Red Sox, began screaming obscenities at
them and telling them to get in the dugout. Ultimately, teammates
restrained pitcher Jeff Nelson from going after Corcoran and
another security guard, and Manager Joe Torre criticized Corcoran
after the game.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-18-99 2336EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
