<SLUG> BC-NY-CARDINAL-HOSPITAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CARDINAL O`CONNOR READMITTED TO HOSPITAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Cardinal John O'Connor, who has been undergoing
radiation treatments for a brain tumor, was readmitted to the
hospital Monday at the request of his doctors, the cardinal's
spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   O'Connor, 79, the archbishop of New York, entered Memorial
Sloan-Kettering Cancer Center in Manhattan at 3 p.m., said Joseph
Zwilling, his spokesman. O'Connor was expected to stay at least one
night.
</P>
<P>
   ``The cardinal is experiencing fatigue from the therapy, which
is normal,'' Zwilling said. ``But given his age and the relatively
high dosages of radiation he is receiving, his doctors wanted to
make sure he is recovering normally.'' They also want to insure
that the cardinal is not becoming dehydrated because of the
therapy, Zwilling said.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether the cardinal had lost any weight, Zwilling said,
``I'm not sure.'' He added, ``People who have seen him say he may
have gained weight.''
</P>
<P>
   The cardinal canceled his appearance at a 5:30 p.m. Mass Monday
welcoming the relics of St. Therese of Lisieux to St. Patrick's
Cathedral. On Sunday, for the second week in a row, he canceled his
celebration of the 10:15 a.m. Mass at the cathedral.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement Sunday, he apologized for his absence. ``So much
for my promises,'' the cardinal wrote. ``I'll be back when I'll be
back.''
</P>
<P>
   After the cardinal had been hospitalized for 10 days, a
spokesman said on Sept. 4 that doctors had removed a small tumor
from his brain and that ``no other areas of the body were
affected.'' The announcement said O'Connor would undergo radiation
therapy for ``the next several weeks.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
