<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-18 23:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1257 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-CAMPAIGN-FINANCE     10-18 0503
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-CAMPAIGN-FINANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: ANOTHER CAMPAIGN FINANCE FIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Tuesday, Oct. 19:
</P>
<P>
   After months of delays, the Senate has finally begun its debate
on campaign finance. A surprise gambit last night by Sen. John
McCain to get a test vote on his bill, co-sponsored by Russell
Feingold of Wisconsin, was blocked by defenders of the current
system. Another attempt is due today. Now is the time for Trent
Lott, the majority leader, to fulfill a promise to allow votes on
the main bill and also on amendments that might expand the support
for reform.
</P>
<P>
   But there were reports last night that Lott would attempt today
to drop campaign finance reform from the agenda after two initial
test votes and go on to the subject of partial-birth abortion. Any
such effort would betray his pledge to McCain earlier in the year
for five full days of debate. If Lott tries to short-circuit the
process, McCain has no obligation to keep his promise not to
reintroduce campaign reform this year. The best result would be for
all pro-reform senators to demand that the Senate continue on this
critical subject.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Mitch McConnell actually performed a service with his
extraordinary personal attack last Friday on McCain, a fellow
Republican who had the temerity to suggest that money corrupts the
system. To McConnell, the truckloads of cash for party coffers from
gambling, tobacco, health insurance and oil and gas interests are
just ``participation'' in politics. McConnell also complained on
``Meet the Press'' that this page had editorialized 114 times on
this subject since the beginning of 1997.
</P>
<P>
   But as McCain has shown, persistence is necessary to any cleanup
of influence peddling in Congress. Even so, Democrats and
Republicans who favor reform are not fully unified. McCain angered
Democrats by not informing them that he would be moving abruptly
yesterday for a procedural vote on his own bill. But he acted out
of a reasonable fear that McConnell and Lott would try to prevent
the promised vote on a soft-money ban.
</P>
<P>
   Underlying the maneuvers is the emergence of at least 53
senators favoring a basic ban on ``soft money'' donations to
political parties, the unlimited contributions from corporations,
unions and rich individuals that the parties use on behalf of
candidates in circumvention of the law. That support can grow only
if Lott fulfills his promise to allow a full debate, with
opportunities by Republicans and Democrats to offer amendments.
</P>
<P>
   We continue to support the basic objective of McCain and
Feingold to push for a simple soft-money ban, omitting for now the
separate provision that would regulate fund-raising by independent
groups. That measure has the best chance of gathering strength this
week. Thanks to McConnell's overplaying his hand, every senator
must ask whether his or her constituents really want a system that
is bought and paid for by wealthy outside interests. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-18-99 2346EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991018.0522 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-18 23:47 </DATE_TIME>
