<SLUG> BC-EDIT-STARR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: MR. STARR CUTS OUT 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Tuesday, Oct. 19:
</P>
<P>
   Common sense and the rule of law both dictate that any
independent counsel charged with investigating a president has a
civic obligation to make a final report to the nation on his or her
findings. Kenneth Starr is skittering away from that obligation
even though the taxpayers, after the expenditure of $47 million,
have every right to expect him to be the government's most
knowledgeable official on the Monica Lewinsky scandal, Whitewater
and related matters. Starr, who accepted the job of independent
counsel in 1994, likes to blame the White House for damaging his
reputation. But no one in the Clinton administration can fairly be
blamed for his failure to stay the course.
</P>
<P>
   It was Starr's decision to hand off his duties to Robert Ray, an
aggressive racketeering and gang prosecutor, who joined the
independent counsel's office five months ago. President Clinton's
allies complained Monday that Ray overlapped briefly with Hillary
Rodham Clinton's likely opponent for Senate, Rudolph Giuliani, at
the U.S. Attorney's office in Manhattan, and the new counsel needs
to be forthcoming on any questions of conflict of interest. Ray
says he intends to move the investigation forward in a ``prompt,
responsible and cost-effective manner.'' Those are reassuring
words. But they cannot disguise the fact that the public is being
cheated of a final summary of the evidence drafted, vouched for and
signed by Starr and backed by his five years of research.
</P>
<P>
   Starr may feel that any report from him would be tainted by the
perception that he has pursued a vendetta against Mr. and Mrs.
Clinton. But copping out on his duty is not the answer to that
problem. Having led the nation on a tumultuous journey punctuated
by the impeachment of a sitting president, Starr was obliged to
spend a few more months deciding on any final indictments and
delivering his professional conclusions about the quality of the
evidence on all aspects of his sprawling inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   Kenneth Starr took over as a former federal jurist with a
reputation for sound judgment. Monday, by leaving before his job
was done, he further diminished a reputation damaged for the most
part by his own legal and public-relations decisions.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
