<HEADER>
A1265 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-BUSH-COLOMBIA-COX     10-18 0640
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-COLOMBIA-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    More foreign leaders making Austin stop as Bush lead grows
 &HT;    By Ken Herman
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ The president of Colombia wants $3.5 billion in
foreign aid to boost a faltering economy that has his nation
reeling. So he's coming to see Gov. George W. Bush today.
</P>
<P>
   The world _ with its problems and leaders _ is finding its way
to Austin to meet the man who might be president. So far this year,
leaders from 22 nations have made the pilgrimage to Austin.
</P>
<P>
   Some are dignitaries who would be interested in the governor no
matter who held the office. But others are folks interested in
getting a handle on the leading candidate for the White House.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would say so,'' said Achilles Paparsenos, spokesman for the
Greek Embassy, when asked whether Bush's international profile has
soared with his poll numbers. ``Many Greeks follow the American
campaign very closely. And this will multiply when the campaign
gets into high gear.''
</P>
<P>
   Alexander Philon, the Greek ambassador to the United States,
made the trek to Austin to meet Bush in January.
</P>
<P>
   Today's private meeting at the Governor's Mansion was requested
by Colombian President Andres Pastrana as part of his effort to
make his case for foreign aid.
</P>
<P>
   Claudia Morales, spokeswoman for the Colombian Embassy in
Washington, said Pastrana is trying to meet with all of the major
presidential candidates.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it is important for President Pastrana to meet (Bush)
just to explain, as he has been doing here in Washington and will
be doing in Europe, what is the real situation in Colombia, and to
explain why it would be attractive to invest in Colombia,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Morales said Pastrana also wants to meet with Vice President Al
Gore and former U.S. Sen. Bill Bradley, contenders for the
Democratic presidential nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Colombia is looking for help with an economy in deep recession.
Last week, workers staged a one-day nationwide strike to protest
Pastrana's economic plan, which includes a call for a freeze on
public-sector wages and cuts in social services programs.
</P>
<P>
   The nation recently secured a $2.7 billion loan from the
International Monetary Fund and is seeking increased aid from the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   Also last week, Colombian officials, acting on indictments from
a Miami federal grand jury, arrested 31 people targeted as major
drug traffickers in a nation that provides much of the U.S. supply
of heroin and cocaine.
</P>
<P>
   Campaign spokeswoman Mindy Tucker said Bush welcomes the
increasing attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is currently the front-runner and, from our perspective, it
is important for somebody who might be president of the United
States to begin establishing personal relationships that could be
key to conducting foreign policy later,'' Tucker said.
</P>
<P>
   But visits by foreign dignitaries also may be due to Bush's
being governor of the second-largest state in the country.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, whose foreign policy experience is limited to dealings
with Mexico and meetings with campaign advisers trying to get him
up to speed, has met this year with officials from Australia,
Brunei, Costa Rica, Germany, Greece, Ireland, Israel, Japan, South
Korea, Laos, Lithuania, Luxembourg, Malaysia, Mexico, Myanmar, New
Zealand, the Philippines, Slovenia, South Africa, Taiwan, the
United Kingdom and Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, as Bush was laying the groundwork for the
presidential campaign, his international visitors included
officials from Argentina, Austria, China, Cyprus, the Czech
Republic, France, Ireland, Israel, Italy, Mexico, New Zealand,
Slovenia, Turkey, the United Arab Emirates, the United Kingdom and
Venezuela.Ken Herman writes for the Austin American-Statesman,
Austin, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
